<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0001 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1939 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-RETAIL-SLUMP-HNS &LR;      12-16 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RETAIL-SLUMP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The pulse of the golf industry, relentlessly pumping dollar signs
through the veins of the sport for the past five years, skipped a
beat in 1998.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Golf clubs. Everything from Callaway's oversized drivers to
heavy-metal fairway woods to irons with satellite-dish sweet spots.
Every one of them sold poorly this year compared to the retail
surge from 1992 to 1997. Retailers in Houston and everywhere else
felt the cooldown.
</P>
<P>
   So is the golf boom that has enveloped everybody from the
country club to the inner city waning? Are there lean times
forthcoming? Have golf manufacturers glutted the market with their
techno-products? Has everybody in the world bought a Big Bertha and
realized that it doesn't go obsolete in two years?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the game is that golfers do not go on strike.
Unlike the NBA, there are no owners to lock out the players. Unlike
baseball's 1994 World Series, the Masters will not be wiped out
this year. Titleist will not have to juice up its golf ball to the
point that even topped shots travel home-run length just to get
fans interested again.
</P>
<P>
   In short, some of the foremost authorities in the game believe
golf is enduring a brief downturn _ a correction, to use a
stock-market term. And it is expected to run its course rather
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf-club sales in the U.S. still are very, very healthy,''
says Ely Callaway, founder of Callaway Golf, which produces the Big
Bertha and Warbird lines of woods and is the world's leader in the
industry. ``The interest in the game, I think, is higher than ever.
And so the future looks good. It's not an out-of-character thing to
see dips in the cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a backlash against us, except among the
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway is far and away the sales leader in the golf-club
market. The Carlsbad, Calif.-based company did $843 million in
business in 1997. That was up from $679 million in '96. Those
figures were unheardof in the golf business previously.
</P>
<P>
   Sales figures for 1998 are expected to be slightly below those
of the previous year, and Callaway's stock price has plummeted from
a high of almost $34 this year to $10.50 at Tuesday's close. But
Callaway still will have greater sales than its four nearest
competitors combined.
</P>
<P>
   When Callaway laid off 700 employees last month, it sent shock
waves through the golf and business communities. Not that cutbacks
are unusual in any business. Lynx went bankrupt and was absorbed by
another company. There have been cutbacks at TaylorMade, Zevo and
others. Everybody is feeling the pinch caused by a downturn in
sales and an increase in costs. Reductions in the work force are
the result.
</P>
<P>
   But when the industry leader must restructure, it's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are saying that we're down _ and we're saying
we're down, too,'' total sales will not have fallen far from the
firm's previous peak year, Callaway says. ``No other golf-club
manufacturer has ever been within $300 million of that total.
That's not bad for a down year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the rest of corporate America, our downturn is
nothing. Boeing is laying off 50,000 workers. Exxon is merging, and
that will eliminate about 9,000 jobs. You can't read about any
business without hearing about belts being tightened.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Jack Nicklaus. His Golden Bear line of golf equipment
was no different than the rest of the industry this year, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like everybody else, we got murdered this year,''
Nicklaus says. ``Our inventory is backlogged, just like all other
golf-equipment people. And we're having to do a lot of conserving
to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's like everything else. It'll go through this cycle and
make its way back up. It's the old story: You can't keep bringing
out a new model of club every six months. The average player is
saying, `Why am I buying five or six different clubs for the same
shot?' It's a tough business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Callaway. They said titanium was the only way to go,
and now they've got stainless steel back in their inventory. But
Callaway is a good company, and they'll be back, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Callaway isn't abandoning its philosophy that titanium
is better and bigger is better.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company's new Steelhead fairway woods were labeled as
a departure from its Big Bertha meal ticket, Callaway says the
Steelheads were meant to replace and improve upon the Warbirds.
And, in fact, new advertising that hits the racks in magazines this
week will remind golfers that the Steelhead actually has a larger
clubhead than the Warbirds did.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at the Steelhead and think it's a smaller
replacement of the Warbird,'' Callaway says. ``Some of our
competitors are going on a design trend of shallower faces and
smaller clubheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our opinion that bigger is still better. We're not
getting any smaller. Our competitors are. That's fine. Let 'em go.
We like that. We led the way into Titanium woods with the Great Big
Bertha. But, contrary to what Cobra and some other companies
believe, steel is not dead. We've never said it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing being said by all our competitors now,
that smaller heads and slightly smaller heads are the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying that's not the way to go _ if you want to go
Callaway. That's just a difference of opinion. Steelhead is the
replacement for the Big Bertha Warbird, and it's a slightly bigger
clubhead. We've done a bum job getting that word out. But you'll
see by the end of January that the message we need to get out will
be entirely cleared up.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway Golf's 1998 wasn't impacted strictly by the soft market
for golf clubs. The company had to wage another fight as well.
</P>
<P>
   With roughly 30 percent of its business overseas (and most of
that in Japan), when the bottom fell out of the Asian economy,
Callaway took a major hit. People just stopped buying luxury items,
and golf clubs are high on that list.
</P>
<P>
   And design costs have jumped radically. There is a reason
Callaway has been the market leader in golf clubs for years. It
spends a lot of money on design research trying to stay ahead of
the competition. And, of course, there are production costs.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is saturation in the market. It's difficult for
any company to market a state-of-the-art product for $350 and then,
a year or two later, come back and say that product now is
obsolete, so you need a new $350 product. What's next, a metal
tennis racket on the tee box?
</P>
<P>
   ``The reasons are pretty well known,'' Callaway says. ``There
was a slowdown at retail in golf equipment, at all price levels.
And by slowdown, we're guessing 10 percent. And we've found in our
case that our competitors have cut prices or pushed sales of
closeouts more than we can ever remember. That affects sales
somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then another big reason for the downturn has been the
financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, which was something that
nobody could predict. When you have a big business over there, you
suffer. Most of the other companies didn't have as much to lose in
Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Callaway's layoffs were in manufacturing. Four
vice presidents and a number of managers also had to hit the
highway. In all of their cases, it had nothing to do with their
performance and everything to do with the outside factors.
</P>
<P>
   But Callaway Golf is far from struggling. In fact, its salvation
may end up being a venture into the competitive world of golf
balls. The company is investing $150 million in creation and
development of a Callaway golf ball.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is sure whether the golf ball will rejuvenate Callaway or
not. The golf-ball market is a $2 billion-a-year business. There's
no denying people use a lot more balls than they do clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' Nicklaus predicted. ``The difference
is that they are the established leader in the equipment business.
They won't have that distinction in the ball market. That goes to
Spalding or Titleist or whoever. But the ball business is going to
be a tough one for them to get into.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway is taking the plunge into the ball market fully aware
that it won't be easy. But by next Christmas, you probably will be
able to put a dozen Callaway balls in somebody's stocking.
</P>
<P>
   But the main focus of Callaway Golf, according to the man
running it, won't change from clubs to balls. The two areas will
coexist. But club design and manufacturing will remain a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's any doubt about it,'' Callaway says.
``We're going to have new and improved products. Steelhead sales
have been terrific, and that's going to continue to be important
for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a whole different direction for the golf-club
industry. But there will be no mystery about which way Callaway is
going. We have something up our sleeves. We can't say when it's
going to drop out of our sleeves. But Callaway will come up with a
superior product and take advantage of the higher-priced metal-wood
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready for a metal tennis racket on the tee box?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
