<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S MORTON MAKES HIS MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chad Morton can recount a variety of roles he has
played at USC, and rarely with much satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   When he first arrived, Morton was primarily known as former
Trojans wide receiver Johnnie Morton's little brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bad hearing you're Johnnie's little brother, but a
lot of people thought I was only here because of my brother,''
Morton said. And usually, the emphasis was on little. Morton is
5-foot-8 and 185 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Morton became the team's defensive specialist.
He bounced between defensive back and free safety, with some spot
tailback duties. Sometimes, Morton could be difficult to locate at
practice, because he worked with the offense and defense on the
same day.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it was a pretty unsatisfying experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough. Even though I got a scholarship, I felt
like I was a walk-on, like I didn't really belong,'' Morton said.
``I didn't feel I was part of the Trojan family yet. I was on the
side and trying to get in. I felt that for my last couple years.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton finally found his niche this season as USC's full-time
tailback. He is just 33 yards shy of gaining 1,000 yards, something
no Trojan has done since Delon Washington in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime during the Sun Bowl, Morton figures to smash the
1,000-yard mark against Texas Christian University. In Morton's
mind, it will be one more accomplishment to show that he has
arrived and that he fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year was my coming-out party,'' Morton said. ``Now, I'm
starting to understand what the Trojan family is like. I didn't
feel like I was part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Morton is small for his position and has overcome
several injuries this season, there are no lingering questions of
whether he truly belongs in the backfield. He's proven his worth by
gaining 967 yards rushing with an average of 5.1 per carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pound for pound, he might be the best player I've ever
coached,'' USC running backs coach Hue Jackson said. ``He meant as
much to the offense as Chris (Claiborne) meant to our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   As he's become more comfortable with his role with the team,
Morton has become a more secure player. In the past, he might push
himself too hard in practice, worried that another player would
take his job.
</P>
<P>
   When he was bothered by a sore back or sprained ankle earlier in
the season, he would not hesitate to let coaches know he needed
rest, in order to increase his chances of being available for
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm in a position where I have a lot of confidence in
myself,'' Morton said. ``If I'm not feeling up to practicing, I
won't hesitate to tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   The best example occurred before USC's game with Stanford last
month. Although Morton's ankle bothered him, there was some
pressure to get him to practice. Morton held his ground, however,
and did not practice. He did play in the game, and gained a
game-high 87 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big deal for me,'' Morton said. ``My ankle was
sore. Either I could practice during the week and stay injured or I
could not practice but play in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said Morton probably will never be able
to carry the ball 20-25 times a game, but said Morton can still
influence a game enough even with just 15 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the contribution he makes to the team in all areas,''
Hackett said. ``There's the leadership and his being captain, then
there's that spin move.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``spin move'' was the juke Morton made against Notre Dame
at the line of scrimmage that turned an apparent no-gain into a
21-yard run which set up the Trojans' touchdown in the 10-0
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything doesn't have to be perfect for Chad to make a
play,'' Jackson said. ``When things weren't exactly the way you
wanted, he could squirt out and make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton also made a big play in practice that week. He became
extremely upset at the end of one session, when the linemen decided
not to do wind sprints because they earned a reward by winning a
team contest the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Morton was bothered that the linemen would choose practices
during Notre Dame week to rest, instead of waiting until the
less-significant bowl practices began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just made me so mad. It just hurt,'' Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   Morton's feelings were not ignored. The next day, the line came
back and ran wind sprints.
</P>
<P>
   His competitive spirit causes him to faithfully check the
Pacific-10 stats every week, keeping tabs on how he matched up with
the league's other top running backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll read the thing for about an hour,'' Morton said. ``If I'm
not No.1, I'm just down. I'll be in a bad mood for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted being ``deeply disappointed'' when he was not
selected to the All-Pacific-10 Conference first or second teams.
Morton was named honorable mention, behind Arizona State's J.R.
Redmond, Arizona's Trung Canidate, Oregon's Reuben Droughns and
Washington State's Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely using this as motivation for next year,''
Morton said. ``I'm not really respected throughout the league. It
really hurt. All that hard work and dedication didn't really get
noticed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
