<HEADER>
A1957 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETH     12-16 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS FALL IN LINE, MAKING IMPEACHMENT A NEAR CERTAINTY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede graf for updating and rewriting; subs 30th graf for new
quote by Tom DeLay about prospects for impeachment)  (htv) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton returned to Washington Tuesday
night facing the near certainty that the House of Representatives
would vote to impeach him later this week unless he can find some
extraordinary means to reverse the Republican tide running against
him.
</P>
<P>
   The almost insurmountable problems facing the president became
clear Tuesday as several previously undeclared Republicans
announced that they would vote in favor impeachment on one or more
of the four counts against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The blows came one by one by one throughout the day, as if
choreographed. And on Tuesday it was not the Republicans considered
longshots by the White House who proclaimed their intention to vote
against the president. Rather, the White House lost Republicans who
were considered as possible opponents of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The hemorrhaging of support left the White House pondering
several desperate and unappealing options Tuesday night. All had
their proponents in the White House and in Clinton's circle of
outside advisers. But none of these advisers expressed confidence
that any words or actions by the president could reverse the
momentum at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the situation was still in flux Tuesday evening,
but the president was planning to meet with Rep. Christopher Shays
of Connecticut and other undecided Republicans individually in an
attempt to craft a tough censure option including a fine and an
admission of wrongdoing to keep the last Republicans from
defecting.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats said it would be difficult to persuade Clinton
to make a confession of perjury and other offenses that Republicans
are demanding. Clinton has insisted in public that he did not lie
under oath and does not believe he committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   White House advisers also said the president is weighing an
appeal to the public in a televised address, not to sway Republican
votes but to awaken the public to the stakes and to paint the
impeachment drive as a partisan effort to undo the result of two
national elections. Such a speech would most likely be delivered
only after it was clear that Clinton did not have the votes to
defeat an impeachment resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was also studying two new proposals for an
alternative punishment short of impeachment, one from former Sen.
Bob Dole, the other from Rep. Michael N. Castle, Republican of
Delaware. Both require forthright admissions of wrongdoing by the
president; Castle's proposal also would have Clinton pay a $2
million fine to help cover the cost of the Monica Lewinsky
investigation that formed the basis of the four impeachment
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging announcement for Clinton came from
Representative Jack Quinn of New York, who for weeks had said that
he would oppose impeachment. On Tuesday he said he had changed his
mind after studying the evidence against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I learn about the serious details of perjury and
obstruction of justice, the more I am concerned about the
President's failure to tell the truth under oath,'' Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican announcements Tuesday, the mathematical
possibilities of avoiding impeachment became as unlikely as drawing
an inside card to a royal flush. To prevent 218 votes' being cast
to impeach the president, he would need to win over nearly all the
18 undecided Republicans and hold the support of almost every
Democrat who is wavering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to happen to change the dynamic,'' said one
Democrat. ``The math gets tough from here on out. You've got to
walk this back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Campbell, a California Republican who came out against
Clinton on Tuesday, said, ``It is my judgment that the president
will be impeached by the House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Shays, one of the last undecided Republican House members, is
scheduled to meet with Clinton at the White House on Wednesday.
Shays, a respected moderate, has said that he wants the president
to admit that he lied under oath and accept the legal consequences
of his acts.
</P>
<P>
   Shays is seen as the envoy of the dwindling band of undecided
moderate Republicans who are seeking some final admission from the
president before deciding on their impeachment votes. The White
House beseeched him to bring other undecided Republicans with him
for a session of presidential persuasion, but an official close to
Shays said, ``We're trying. We don't know the result. Chris is very
pessimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   With the time before the decisive House impeachment vote now
counted in hours, White House officials, in public at least,
continued to hold out hope that the tide could somehow turn in the
president's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it over? Definitely not,'' said Paul Begala, presidential
counselor. ``No vote is certain until it is cast.''
</P>
<P>
   But private assessments were decidedly gloomy, alternating
between anger and a sense of foreboding about Thursday's
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll lose,'' one senior adviser to the president
said. ``The real blow was Quinn. He's a very moderate Republican
who was always friendly to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser, who insisted on anonymity, said that no one at
the White House, from the president on down, had a strategy for
winning the impeachment fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just at a loss for what it is you do,'' this adviser
said of the president. ``He took the advice to give a speech last
week and it didn't do him any good. He can't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   The adviser continued glumly, ``My biggest fear is that there
will be a din for resignation after the vote. How do we stop
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Republicans who declared themselves Tuesday were the
ones who had been expected to be Clinton's allies either because
they came from districts in the northeast that had voted for
Clinton, or because they sometimes cross party lines in their
voting. Four of them came from New York, the state that had been
expected to be a Clinton stronghold: Quinn, Michael P. Forbes, John
M. McHugh and Sue W. Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes had signaled to colleagues for weeks that he was going to
support the president. But on Tuesday he said he would vote to
impeach him on all four articles against him. ``I don't think there
is anything more that the president or the White House can do on
this issue,'' he said as he announced his position at a Capitol
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Campbell, a Stanford University law professor, was
another disappointment for the White House. He is a Republican who
has worked closely with Democrats on campaign finance overhaul and
he had opposed Newt Gingrich as Speaker when he faced his own
ethics controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell had been talking to two Cabinet officers for weeks
seeking some answers from the president that could sway him. But on
Tuesday, in an office crammed with television cameras and with his
voice occasionally trembling, Campbell said he had decided to vote
in favor impeachment based on Clinton's testimony before a federal
grand jury last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my belief that the president did not tell the truth on
several occasions before the federal criminal grand jury,'' he
said, ``having had seven months' advance notice, with his attorney
by his side, being able to stop the questioning at any point.''
</P>
<P>
   He said those lies also carried a fundamental cost in the world
of politics, where business is done with a handshake. ``If he would
not tell the truth under those circumstances, I do not know when I
can trust that he will tell the truth when it is to his political
advantage not to,'' he said. ``And that, in my judgment, seriously
incapacitates him in his abilities to carry out the duties of
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The others who came out for impeachment on Tuesday included:
Nancy L. Johnson of Connecticut, E. Clay Shaw, Jr. of Florida, Fred
Upton of Michigan, Gil Gutknecht of Minnesota, Jim McCrery of
Louisiana, Roy Blunt of Missouri and Anne M. Northup of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who is the majority whip, has been driving
the impeachment in the House. He said on Tuesday night that he did
not have the 218 voteds needed for impeachment, but added ``The
momentum is certainly going that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have 206 votes in the 105th Congress and there is
one independent who votes with them. They are counting on losing
only three to six Democrats in the impeachment vote. That means
that to prevail by just one vote, Clinton needs to draw 14 to 17
Republicans to his side. So far just four have said they are
supporting him or leaning toward supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be the last optimist at the White House,'' said one
senior presidential aide, ``but I'm not ready to say it's over in
the House. I still believe a majority of Congress opposes
impeachment and would welcome an opportunity to vote their
consciences.''
</P>
<P>
   This official said once again that Clinton had no intention of
resigning, even if the House votes to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Members of the public have consistently said they would prefer
that Clinton finish his term. According to the latest New York
Times/CBS News Poll 69 percent of respondents continue to say it
would be better for the country if Clinton remained in office,
while only 28 percent say he should resign, according to the latest
New York Times/CBS News Poll. That sentiment has held steady since
September when the question was first asked.
</P>
<P>
   But public sentiment for resignation jumps when a different,
hypothetical question is asked about possible resignation if a vote
by the House sends articles of impeachment to the Senate for a
trial. In that situation, 40 percent say it would be better for the
country for Clinton to resign, while 56 percent oppose resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reacted favorably to the censure options offered
by Dole and Castle as a means for members of Congress to condemn
the president's behavior without provoking a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's proposal, made in an op-ed article in Tuesday's New York
Times, calls for the House to complete its vote on impeachment.
Regardless of the House action, the Senate and House would
immediately draft a strong joint resolution of censure
incorporating the charges against Clinton _ perjury, obstruction of
justice and abuse of power. The bill could also include a financial
penalty. Clinton would have to accept the censure resolution at a
public signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Castle said that he was seeking a solution that would respond to
the majority of the public that abhors the president's actions but
does not want to see him removed from office. His proposal would
repeat the charges against Clinton and affirm that he remains
liable to criminal prosecution after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Castle said that he believed the Senate was unlikely to vote to
convict Clinton and eject him from office. ``Would not the country
be better served if we took action now _ in the next 48 hours _ to
bring this matter to the same conclusion that is likely to occur
even after months of a Senate trial?'' Castle said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official, speaking not for attribution, said that
Clinton would be reluctant to sign anything that forces him to
confess to serious crimes and constitutional offenses. But if the
House votes to impeach, Clinton might consider such a step to spare
himself and the nation the agony of a protracted Senate trial, the
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As the stream of previously undeclared Republicans announced
their intentions to vote for impeachment, at least two
rank-and-file Republicans reserved judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've announced I won't announce,'' said Rep. Jim Greenwood of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, the newly-elected chairman of the
House Republican campaign committee, at first ignored questions
from reporters as he walked to a leadership meeting on the Capitol
Tuesday. Finally, he snapped, ``The committee report isn't even
printed yet. I'd like to read that before I make up my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the House Judiciary Committee's summary
report of the articles of impeachment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
