<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SCHOOL FACED PLAYOFF DILEMMA: FORFEIT OR HAZARDOUS ROADS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Friday, the Stanton Buffaloes, the defending state champions,
awoke to fast-falling snow. The small community between Midland and
Big Spring on Interstate 20 had been primed to leave for
Stephenville, about 200 miles or a four-hour drive away, where the
Buffaloes were to take on Celina in the Class 2A state semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:37 Friday morning, the National Weather Service in Midland
issued a winter weather advisory. At 9 a.m., the advisory was
upgraded to a heavy snow warning from Midland stretching close to
Abilene along I-20.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffaloes were scheduled to leave Stanton around 10 a.m.
heading for Abilene on I-20 for the 7:30 p.m. game. Heavy snow
continued to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``My office is a half-mile from the highway,'' Stanton coach
Mark Cotton said. ``You couldn't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   From here, what's really hard to see is why Stanton would be
allowed to travel to play a game in such treacherous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Stanton superintendent Jim White said he called
Celina superintendent Ken Burks to warn him of incoming inclement
weather. At 9 a.m. on Friday, White phoned Burks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them it's snowing pretty bad,'' White said. ``In the
meantime, I called the UIL to see what our options were. They told
me both teams had to agree to change once we accepted a date and
location.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outside looking in, maybe the UIL should have the
ability to step in or at least consult a third party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him (Burks) we wanted to play on Saturday in the middle
of the afternoon,'' White said ``He wanted to talk to his coach
about it. They called back and said they want to play tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotton found himself with little choice: forfeit or battle the
weather. Five school buses prepared to leave. White settled some
nerves when the Stanton sheriff's department gave him a forecast
that said the snow was dissipating around Coahoma, about 30 miles
away. He was unaware of the National Weather Service's expanded
snow warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him (White) if you can't put buses on the road then we
won't play the game. We would be completely agreeable to that,''
Burks said. ``We would like to play the game, but we think of the
safety of the students first and foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Celina coach G.A. Moore said the final say was up to
Stanton. However, White and Cotton didn't get that impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to (postpone the game),'' said Cotton, whose team
lost, 9-0, on a miserably cold and windy night. ``I'm not saying we
would have won the football game on a dry field. My deal was the
safety. The only time I talked to coach Moore was when we had 4
inches of snow on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Celina officials told Cotton that Saturday's forecast called for
worse weather. Ironically, Saturday was a spectacular fall day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what he (Celina's Burks) felt pressure to do was go
along with what his coach wanted to do,'' White said. ``He said,
`Are you telling me then you cannot make it there?' I said, `No, if
we start out I would expect to make it there. I am worried about
the kids in these travel conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the (Celina) superintendent had some compassion, but I
think he had some uncertainty to how much he could trust me since
he didn't know me.''
</P>
<P>
   At about 10:50 a.m., the buses pulled out of Stanton. In
Midland, city officials had already closed Loop 250 and off-duty
officers were called in.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 130 miles, five Stanton buses rumbled through snow
storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a situation with our band buses,'' White said. ``An
18-wheeler tried to pass them. It knocked off their side-view
mirror. If I'm ever again in that situation, I will say, `Sorry, we
will not be there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cotton also said the football team buses had a close call,
swerving to avoid sideswiping another 18-wheel truck.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, including a stop for lunch, lasted six hours, still in
plenty of time for normal pregame rituals, Cotton said. His team
was ready to play, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we would have beaten them on a clear day, but I
sure would have liked to have tried,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, Midland had a snowfall of 9.75 inches,
according to the National Weather Service. The Buffaloes lost the
game, the majority of their fans never left Stanton and the team
eventually made it home safely.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains, when does playing a game _ even a state
semifinal _ override the safety of students?
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Caplan writes about high school sports for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7371. E-mail:
sportszone(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's high
school site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
