<HEADLINE>
MILLS LOOKS BACK ON INJURY AND IS THANKFUL THINGS DIDN'T GET WORSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veteran receiver Ernie Mills walked into the locker room earlier
this week and was besieged with questions regarding the problems
with the Cowboys, who have lost three consecutive games since Mills
suffered a perforated small intestine Nov. 22 against Seattle. The
injury sidelined him for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mills had no answers _ partly because he's not the type to
criticize his teammates and partly because the Cowboys' problems
were the least of his concerns the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mills was injured when he caught a short pass from Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman and was hit by Seattle's Fred Thomas.
Others have suffered a similar injury from being in car wreck and
having the steering wheel smash into their stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt pain like that in my life,'' Mills said. ``There
was so much going through my mind while I was in the hospital.
Football wasn't one of them. It was just life in itself. The first
thing was, Will I be able to be healthy again? Will I survive? Will
I live? That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills remembers little about the incident, though he somehow
still stretched for the first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody told me I did that,'' Mills said. ``That's just
instinct. The pain initially was like getting the wind knocked out
of you. I was gasping for air. When I got to the sideline, I was
really gasping for air. Once I got my breath back in the locker
room at halftime, I started feeling the pain and it wouldn't go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills spent a sometimes rough two weeks in the hospital after
surgery Nov. 23. The good news is that Mills, a six-year veteran,
will be able to return to the field next season _ although he has
lost 15 pounds and won't be able to start working out again until
his wounds heal, which should be about six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He also said there is a good chance he will be on the sideline
for Sunday's crucial matchup with the Eagles. He wants to offer any
help he can to his teammates _ particularly the receivers, who had
come to rely on his in-depth knowledge of Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey's offense from their days in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also sorely miss his big-play ability. His absence
is one reason for the drop in offensive production the past two
games. Mills was the second-leading receiver with 28 passes for 479
yards and had a team-leading four touchdown receptions before the
injury. More important, he was a target Aikman trusted to make a
play when he needed one.
A BLOSSOMING STAR?
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is impressed by what he has seen from former Country Day
star Patrick Jeffers, who has stepped up to play since the injury
to Mills four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, only Michael Irvin has caught more passes than
Jeffers' 13. No receiver has scored more touchdowns than Jeffers'
two. And he has led the Cowboys in receptions the past two games
with eight. There is even speculation that he could replace Billy
Davis as a starter opposite Irvin down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has become a big-play guy for us,'' Gailey said. ``I knew
was a solid receiver. He is one of those guys that has stepped
forward to pick up some of the slack. He will have to continue to
do that for us.''
LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys held their first draft meeting Monday to help scouts
get ready for college all-star games during the holidays. Areas of
need include a big-play wide receiver, offensive guard/center,
linebacker, pass rush end and cornerback. Considering that the
Cowboys can get an offensive lineman or defensive end in free
agency, a wide receiver, linebacker or cornerback appear to be more
likely options as possible first-round picks. Also don't rule out
the possibility that in the off-season the Cowboys will sign former
Texas A&AMP;M star Quentin Coryatt to play middle linebacker.
INSIDE THE LOCKER ROOM
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Falcons coach Dan Reeves, who had quadruple bypass
surgery Monday, is in his prayers. But Gailey said it has not
caused him to re-evaluate his own health. Gailey said he doesn't
work out and doesn't particularly watch what he eats. He said he
gives thanks for his health, but said his biggest concern is
winning football games, not worrying about his health. ... Speaking
of health, the official name for the injury to Cowboys cornerback
Deion Sanders' left great toe is not a sprained toe or turf toe,
but a hyperdorsal flexion of the first metatarsophalangeal joint,
says Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer. Now say that three times in a row.
YARD MARKERS: How far do the Cowboys have to go?
</P>
<P>
   First and long
</P>
<P>
   Standout defensive tackle Leon Lett has recorded 44 tackles,
including four sacks and leads the team in tackles for losses with
seven and quarterback pressures with 17. Lett's numbers are good
but it's generally thought at Valley Ranch that his impact would be
even better if players around him were better.
</P>
<P>
   Second and short
</P>
<P>
   Safety Darren Woodson, who leads the team in tackles with 123,
has topped the 100-tackle plateau for the fifth consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth Down
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for cornerback Kevin Smith, who apparently is going
to be replaced by Kevin Mathis in the starting lineup, to be going
anywhere soon. Smith is signed through 2003 and was given a signing
bonus of $4.7 million last spring to restructure his deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
