<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE FANS CAN GET VIRTUAL REVENGE THIS WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attention Kansas State football fans: Your shot at revenge
against Texas A&AMP;M is available this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats battle the Aggies in a rematch of their Big 12
Conference championship game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But a warning to K-State fans: Don't start packing the purple RV
yet; this rematch is one step on the way to the ``virtual''
national football championship, which is being waged online through
Jan. 4. CBS SportsLine and The FANSOnly Network are featuring the
Virtual Championship Series (www.fansonly.com/virtual), a simulated
16-team playoff to determine the online college football national
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Why a virtual champion? ``Because,'' as the FANSOnly Network
states, ``we've all had enough of this BCS nonsense and want a real
playoff at long last.''
</P>
<P>
   FANSOnly seeded the top 15 teams in the latest Bowl Championship
Series standings and the highest-ranked team in The Associated
Press that didn't make the BCS cut. The teams were in a
single-elimination tournament, utilizing 3-in-1 Football, a
text-based computer simulation game created by Lance Haffner of
Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The champion will be crowned Jan. 4 in the Virtual Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's Virtual Cotton Bowl, A&AMP;M and Kansas State battle
for a spot in the semifinals. In the first round, A&AMP;M defeated
Nebraska, 13-10, on Russell Bynum's late 55-yard field goal. In
last weekend's first round, Kansas State defeated Georgia Tech,
38-17, in the Virtual Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The games are played based on statistical comparisons. The
FANSOnly site provides options to view the comparisons. The
computer simulation comes up with a game recap and an extended box
score. Mike Kahn, CBS SportsLine executive editor, provides expert
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   All they need are virtual nachos and hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   RECRUITING HELP: The recruiting season is here, which means
decisions for recruits, parents and coaches. The Athletic Network
(athletenetwork.com), produced by Marc Isenberg and Rich Rhoads,
has produced a companion survival guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Real Athletes Guide: How to Succeed in Sports, School &AMP;
Life'', is a 208-page book available on Athlete Network. It can
also be ordered on Amazon's online bookstore (www.amazon.com) by a
toll-free number, (800) 356-9315.
</P>
<P>
   The book answers questions about eligibility for NCAA, National
Association of Intercollegiate Athletics and junior-college
athletes, the availability of scholarships and what to watch out
for during recruiting periods.
</P>
<P>
   The Athlete Network site also features diaries from several
athletes on different levels of competition.
</P>
<P>
   EASY LISTENING: Broadcast.com of Dallas features hundreds of
sports cybercasts, and one of its more interesting has to be its
69th annual Pop Warner football championships
(www.broadcast.com/sports/football/popwarner).
</P>
<P>
   Poll of the week: In a recent CNN/SI.com poll, 36 percent of
12,362 respondents are ``making whoopee'' in response to the
question: How are you spending time usually devoted to the NBA?
Thirty-three percent are watching more college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
