<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' HULL RETURNS TO FORM, ZINGS BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Brett Hull returned to form in more ways than one last
night.
</P>
<P>
   The gregarious Stars winger, who signed as a free agent in the
summer, came back from a six-game layoff after recovering from a
strained groin muscle to score two goals and help lead the Stars to
a 7-3 victory against the team he left, the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Hull had faced the Blues, where he had
been a captain and averaged 51 goals a season for 10 years. It was
also the organization that engaged him in rocky contract talks that
led Hull to seek a new home.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old winger said his anxiety showed last night. ``I
was very nervous; I wanted to get it out of the way,'' he said. ``I
couldn't sleep in the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was through, however, Hull was his old self, cutting up
with the news media and flashing the ``Brett Hull'' smile that
showed he is having fun again.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he had thought he would immediately return to
the top line, playing beside Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen, as he
did, Hull replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a double-edged sword. If I say no, you'll say I'm
lying. If I say yes, you'll say I'm a cocky \Rplayer\S. So I think
I'll just leave that one alone.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the Lehtinen-Modano-Hull line will work, he
replied: ``How can it not work? You've got one of the most talented
players in the league in the middle \RModano\S, you've got the top
defensive forward \RLehtinen\S and you've got me picking up the
scraps. I think it'll work. Those two will carry me all year.''
</P>
<P>
   And when asked about his second-period breakaway on old friend
Grant Fuhr, the Blues goalie who had just entered the game to
replace starter Jamie McLennan, Hull replied: ``We had a good
chuckle afterward. I told him it didn't count because he was
cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Read between the lines, and the message that Hull delivered was
that he continues to become more a part of the Stars, who are
17-5-5 with the victory, good for an NHL-leading 39 points. The
Stars also ran their unbeaten streak to a season-high six games
(4-0-2), while the Blues (9-10-7) saw their winless streak stretch
to a season-worst six games (0-4-2).
</P>
<P>
   Two injuries have sidelined Hull in eight of the Stars' 27
games, and he has only now started to play as a regular on the
right wing after an early-season experiment on the left side. In
the past three games Hull has played in which he has been healthy
and playing the right side, he has four goals and three assists for
seven points.
</P>
<P>
   Having him back ``really gives us a deeper top six,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``He takes everybody's focus away from
our other players. He's a distraction to the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't need that distraction early as they jumped to a
2-0 lead 10 minutes into the game on goals by Derian Hatcher and
Pat Verbeek. The Blues, who played Monday night in Denver and are
missing Pierre Turgeon (broken hand), Geoff Courtnall
(post-concussion syndrome) and Tony Twist (finger laceration), were
swimming upstream most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blues scored twice in a 34-second span thanks to a slash
by goalie Ed Belfour, and that provided St. Louis with momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Hull made it 3-2 after one period with a power-play deflection
42 seconds before intermission. And the Blues again tied things
when Pascal Rheaume undressed Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk 5
minutes, 7 seconds into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Stars opened up. Brian Skrudland scored his
third goal in the past six games _ a goal that proved to be the
game-winner _ after a great setup pass by linemate Guy Carbonneau.
Hull sandwiched his breakaway goal between two Joe Nieuwendyk
goals, and the Stars had their biggest offensive output of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Hull had two goals, Nieuwendyk two goals (breaking a nine-game
goal drought), Jamie Langenbrunner had two assists and Tony Hrkac
added two assists. All four lines scored _ an important fact
considering that Hitchcock switched two of his lines to accommodate
the return of Hull. Langenbrunner moved to the left wing on a line
with Nieuwendyk and Grant Marshall, and Mike Keane moved onto a
line with Verbeek and Hrkac.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I liked was that all four lines looked like they had some
real strong identity,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that identity was sticking up for the new kid on the
block when he wanted to show up his old pals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit special for him, and I think our players
recognized that,'' Hitchcock said of Hull facing the Blues for the
first time. ``That was a good thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
