<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-WISCONSIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FALLS SHORT AGAINST WISCONSIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas had a shot at defeating its second consecutive
Top 25 opponent last night _ just not enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns made just one field goal in the last four minutes
against defense-minded Wisconsin, which survived William Clay's
desperation 3-point shot at overtime to spoil Texas' upset bid,
65-62.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising No. 23 Badgers (10-1) have won eight consecutive
games, seven on either neutral or hostile courts. Included is a
63-56 victory at then-No.16 Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're a Top 10, Top 15 team,'' said Texas coach Rick
Barnes, whose 2-6 team defeated No. 25 Utah on Saturday. ``But if
I'm saying that about them, I think I'm kind of telling you we're
pretty close. They're a little more experienced than we are right
now. They made some plays you have to make to win games like this,
and that was the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns led by eight early in the second half. They were
up 40-35 when the game apparently turned.
</P>
<P>
   As the teams came back downcourt after Hennssy Auriantal's
3-pointer cut the lead to 40-35, volatile junior Gabe Muoneke
punched Auriantal in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Though the officials did not see it and Wisconsin's leading
scorer Sean Mason (21 points) said it had no real effect, Badgers
coach Dick Bennett said he used the incident to fire up his team _
which took the lead for good at 58-56 on Mason's two free throws at
2:36.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches are hams,'' Bennett said. ``They'll use anything to
charge the troops. I was surprised there weren't more faceoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes pulled Muoneke, but the player returned in a couple of
minutes. Barnes said, however, the play hurt the Longhorns, and he
threatened to suspend Muoneke if such an incident ever happened
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No player of mine is going to play like that,'' Barnes said.
``It's not right. I apologized to the \RWisconsin\S players because
I wouldn't want that to happen to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabe has got to be more mature than that. If it gets to where
I'm going to have to set him down and suspend him for a game \RI
will\S if that's what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke later apologized and echoed Barnes' pledge that there
would be no repeat.
</P>
<P>
   But what really hurt Texas was that after Chico Vazquez followed
a miss by Chris Mihm at 4:07 to put UT ahead 54-52, the Longhorns
didn't make another basket until Ivan Wagner drove the lane to
bring Texas to 64-59 with 27.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Bothered by fouls most of the night, Kris Clack scored just
seven points. Clay led with 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't let anything come easy to us,'' Vazquez said.
</P>
<P>
   But they almost did. After Wagner's drive, Wisconsin's Ty
Calderwood made only one of two free throws, then fouled Clay on an
attempted 3-pointer. Clay made all three free throws, and Badgers
freshman Charlie Wills missed a pair with 16.3 seconds left to open
the door for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clay got a partial look after an inbounds play with five seconds
left, following an errant 3-pointer by Mihm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shot off-balance and it went too far to the right,'' Clay
said. ``But those are the kinds of shots I shoot every day after
practice. I feel like I ought to hit those.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
