<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BROWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN'S IN TOWN FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The $105 million contract begins with the
30-something starts right-hander Kevin Brown is projected to make
this season, the 100-or-so wins he's expected to secure over the
next seven years and the multiple world championships his arrival
to the Los Angeles Dodgers could signify.
</P>
<P>
   And the $105 million is for another portion of Brown's game that
is equally, if not more, essential to the deal. It's for his
between-games demeanor and his professionalism that the Dodgers
hope rubs off on the rest of the pitching staff, particularly the
younger players.
</P>
<P>
   After being introduced at a news conference Tuesday at Dodger
Stadium, Brown was reminded of a performance last spring training
when he came off the mound in a rather nasty mood after not
pitching well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a game,'' Brown, 33, said. ``Sure, spring training is
spring training, but you have to set the tone. Whenever I walk on
the field I expect to do my best, but I also expect to win. You
have to have that drive and desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training, mid-July or the postseason holds little
relevance for the nomadic Brown, who will pitch for his fifth team
in six years. People speak of his personality being about winning
and teaching others along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who pitched in the past two World Series for the Florida
Marlins and the San Diego Padres, isn't only charged with
maintaining his domination on the mound _ he's 51-26 with a
league-low 2.33 ERA in the past three seasons _ but also with
molding a young staff.
</P>
<P>
   In leading the Padres to the National League championship in
October, Brown got major credit for the maturation and success of
San Diego starters Joey Hamilton, Andy Ashby and Sterling
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Come spring training in Dodgertown in February, Brown's pupils
are expected to be Chan Ho Park, Ismael Valdes, Carlos Perez and
Darren Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have a major, positive impact on the (staff),''
Dodgers GM Kevin Malone said. ``He knows how to win. He knows how
to prepare mentally, physically. This is the ultimate warrior. This
guy does not accept losing. I think when you have that sort of
pitcher on your staff it's contagious in a positive way. It
motivates, it encourages and it helps teach. His personality will
transcend his affect of taking the ball every fifth day.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why the Dodgers were willing to add a seventh year for
Brown _ who will be 40 when his contract expires _ just six months
after balking at a seventh year to keep catcher Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers president Bob Graziano said Brown's addition upgrades
the Dodgers in a way the retention of Piazza would not. Brown is an
acquisition, whereas Piazza would have kept the Dodgers status quo
and not given them flexibility in the free-agent market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also relayed the results of an examination conducted by
Dodgers team physician Dr. Frank Jobe on Brown's right arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elbow looked pristine and clear and Dr. Jobe said his arm
was in such condition he could pitch for another 10 years,'' Malone
said. ``One of the objectives when I came here was to try and find
a leader. I thought we were fortunate to acquire Todd Hundley, who
is a leader, and the acquisition of Kevin Brown, it changes the
personality of the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson wasn't in attendance because he
was on a fishing trip. But Brown was accompanied by his wife,
Candace, who was making her first trip to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   She offered insight into Brown's personality in regards to his
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lot more frustrated when he makes a mistake,'' Candace
Brown said. ``He can throw a bad pitch and win, and be frustrated
by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Brown, who lives in Macon, Ga., said he would be
pitching for the Atlanta Braves because of the proximity to the
home he's building. It would allow him to spend more time with
Candace and their two sons, Ridge, 7, and Grayson, 3.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves never expressed interest, so Brown and his wife
made a list of negatives for each ballclub, and its city, involved
in the sweepstakes. When it came to Los Angeles, the time change
and travel distance were glaring problems.
</P>
<P>
   So the Dodgers countered the concerns with a plane, which the
organization will charter 12 times a year for Brown's family to fly
to L.A., or any other city the Dodgers are playing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This solution makes them, basically, a Midwest team by cutting
three or four hours of travel time off for my family,'' said Brown,
who added he planned on buying a house in Los Angeles. ``I was
impressed with their commitment to family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
