<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-FOCUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE-WIDE COULD BE THE CHARM FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The absence of Ernie Mills has compromised the
Cowboys' ability in their four-wide-receiver formations. The
alternative is to use more three-wide-receiver formations. On
statistics alone, that is not a bad alternative for coach Chan
Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   In this formation, quarterback Troy Aikman is 38-of-59 passing
for 596 yards, with seven completions of 25 yards or longer. His
passer rating of with three receivers on the field is 109.1, second
to the Seattle Seahawks' John Friesz (112.8). Cowboys backup Jason
Garrett has been similarly efficient passing out of the three-wide
formation, with a passer rating of 103.8.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the Cowboys' team passer rating of 107.3 is tops in
the NFL. Rounding out the top five are the Minnesota Vikings
(102.4), San Francisco 49ers (99.9), Denver Broncos (96.9) and
Pittsburgh Steelers (95.8). It is no small coincidence that all but
Pittsburgh rank among the top 10 teams in passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's important that all of our guys play well,''
said wide receivers coach Dwain Painter, who was unaware of the
Cowboys' three-wide efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles, the Cowboys' opponent Sunday, have been
successful stopping the pass. They rank fourth in that category,
allowing 178.2 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have the seventh-ranked passing offense in the
league, although they have traditionally struggled to pass against
the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and company will try to attack the Eagles with a
receiving unit that is banged up. Mills is out for the season.
Michael Irvin has a sore lower back, although he is expected to
play. Billy Davis (35 receptions, 631 yards, three touchdowns) and
Patrick Jeffers (14 for 257, two TDs) have most often been the
players joining Irvin in the three-wide set, although Jeff Ogden (8
for 63), and Eric Bjornson (12 for 163, 1 TD) will rotate in at
times in the formation.
</P>
<P>
   Painter said the Eagles usually try to defense the
three-wide-receiver set mostly with three formations. By using a
four-man front, Eagles defensive coordinator Emmitt Thomas can put
four players in underneath zone coverage and three in deep
coverage, or he can keep five players in underneath zone coverage
and two for deep help. If the Eagles blitz when the Cowboys use a
three-wide-receiver set, Thomas can send five at Aikman, keep five
in underneath zone coverage and keep a safety back.
</P>
<P>
   The key to combating this strategy, Painter said, is to keep
Aikman out of harm's way and to give the wide receivers an option
when running routes so that they can adjust to the defensive
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to protect the quarterback, and our receivers have
to run coordinated routes,'' Painter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
