<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE SHUTTLE RETURNS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The space shuttle Endeavour swooped out
of a clear, starry sky late on Tuesday, bringing home six
astronauts who laid the cornerstone for the international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``One flawless mission completed and a new era in space
exploration just begun,'' a NASA commentator, James Hartsfield,
said in Houston as the shuttle's landing gear touched the pavement
at 10:53 p.m. at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The return of five Americans and one Russian capped a 12-day
flight in which they assembled and outfitted the first two sections
of a $60 billion research outpost for 16 nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a beautiful landing,'' a flight controller in
Houston, Scott Horowitz, radioed the crew after Endeavour had
rolled to a stop. ``Thanks a lot for an awesome job starting our
space station adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great to be home after such an exciting mission,'' Col.
Robert Cabana of the Marine Corps, the mission commander, radioed
back.
</P>
<P>
   After years of controversy and delays, a Russian-built
propulsion cylinder and an American connecting hub now orbit the
planet in a permanent embrace.
</P>
<P>
   The propulsion module named Zarya, for the Russian word for
dawn, and the connecting hub called Unity towered seven stories out
of the open shuttle cargo bay while a pair of astronauts worked on
the stack in space walks on three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept pinching ourselves and saying, `It can't be
real,''' Cabana said earlier in the week. Endeavour's mission was
first envisioned in 1984 when President Ronald Reagan announced
that the National Aeronautics and Space Administration would build
a space station.
</P>
<P>
   More than 21 hours in the void of space made Col. Jerry Ross of
the Air Force the most experienced American space walker and put
his partner, Dr. James Newman, in third place.
</P>
<P>
   But the time they spent outside was just a tiny fraction of the
entire construction effort that will be needed. NASA estimates that
159 more space walks will be needed as the space station takes
shape over the next five years. Eventually, it will cover an area
almost as big as two football fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 0119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
