<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-LOCKOUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' ANSTEY CHASTISES PEERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mavericks forward Chris Anstey has a serious beef with
those responsible for the NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Anstey said the players should be back on the court
playing the game they say they love and quit trying to earn enough
money to purchase a Third World country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference if you make $10 million a year or if you
make $9 million a year?'' Anstey said. ``How much difference does
it make to your lifestyle? It's going to be more than most people
see in a lifetime anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``These \RNBA\S guys spend more money in a week than a lot of
people do in two or three years. Everyone should just be thankful
for what they've got and play the game they love.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie last season, Anstey earned $713,900, and this season
he was scheduled to make $985,200. But he and his peers missed
their third paycheck yesterday because of the owners' lockout,
which has reached 169 days after players and owners were able to
agree on a new collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   NBA players are assured of missing at least two more paychecks.
And with the union and owners toeing the hard line in negotiations,
the entire 1998-99 season might be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Last season the average NBA player salary was $2.6 million.
Anstey said he can't explain to basketball fans why _ with the
players earning that kind of money _ they're not at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish someone would explain it to me,'' Anstey said. ``I
played my first three years of professional basketball in Australia
and my total salary was $150,000, and I was happy with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm making less than half the average salary, and I
couldn't be happier with what I'm making. I never thought I'd make
this much in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Anstey purchased a $600,000 home in Australia this year. He said
he was hoping to pay it off soon, but the lockout is costing him
$82,100 per pay period.
</P>
<P>
   As for his NBA co-workers, Anstey had stern advice. Stop being
greedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who makes a million bucks has got to be pretty happy,''
Anstey said. ``If you walk up to somebody who's working an office
job and say, `I'm making a million dollars to play sports,' I can
guarantee they'll say, `I wish I could do that, too.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the highest-paid basketball league in the world, and
we're arguing about how much we're earning. I've got no problem
with my salary, so, as far as I'm concerned, the lockout shouldn't
even be happening.''
OPEN THOSE BOOKS
Forward Kurt Thomas said NBA fans shouldn't focus only on the money
the players are making. He said the owners are making money, too.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas pointed to the six-year, $126 million contract
Minnesota's Kevin Garnett signed last season, and the $33.1 million
the Chicago Bulls paid Michael Jordan last season as evidence that
the owners are making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can pay a man $126 million over six years and another
man $33 million in one year ... I don't want to hear that,'' Thomas
said. ``If they can pay us $2.6 million a year, what are they
making off us?
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is a business. Look at the luxury boxes. The owners
are making billions of dollars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 0130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
