<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CORNERBACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS CORNERBACKS GETTING HEALTHIER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cornerback Kevin Smith's return to health does
not guarantee his return to the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, still nursing a sore back, will play in the Cowboys'
nickel defense Sunday against the Philadelphia Eagles, coach Chan
Gailey said. But Smith's role as a reserve might not change when he
is totally healthy, Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will evaluate that when the time comes,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to reverse a three-game losing streak, Gailey also
indicated yesterday that more personnel changes might be coming,
``primarily on offense.'' But he was less forthcoming about those
moves than he was about the possible switch at one cornerback spot.
</P>
<P>
   If Deion Sanders is healthy, he and Kevin Mathis will be the
starting cornerbacks. If Sanders cannot play, Charlie Williams will
make his fourth consecutive start.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has one interception this year. Before hurting his back in
the first half Nov. 26 against the Minnesota Vikings, Smith had
been beaten for eight touchdown passes, including six of 35 yards
or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he would not cause a fuss if he doesn't get his
starting job back. But he expressed disappointment about Gailey's
assessment of the position that Mathis has manned the last two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was playing all right before I got hurt,'' Smith
said. ``I know we haven't won a game since I've been out. Hey, they
want me to play this week. That's got to say something about
whether I'm needed or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he would not worry about starting until he was
totally healthy. He added that, ``we're trying to win. We're
scrapping and scrapping for a win in whatever way we can.''
</P>
<P>
   In Smith's absence, Mathis allowed an 89-yard touchdown pass in
New Orleans, but rebounded on Sunday. He helped limit Kansas City
Chiefs wide receiver Andre Rison to one catch for 11 yards. Mathis
also broke up three passes.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Mathis will start against Philadelphia, and he
expects Sanders will take his customary spot at the other
cornerback position. Sanders has been inactive the past three games
with a sprained left big toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is pointing toward Deion getting in the ballgame
this week,'' Gailey said.
INJURY UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   As he walked to the team meeting room to conduct his weekly
press briefing, Gailey ran into Michael Irvin in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you feelin'?'' asked Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing a little better than I was \RMonday\S,'' Irvin
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, his backside sore after taking a hard hit Sunday against
the Chiefs, was still moving slowly yesterday. But Gailey said he
expects Irvin to play against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey also expected Chris Warren (groin injury) to play. But he
was not sure about tight end David LaFleur (sprained knee).
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a real question,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayward Clay could be asked to make his second start to replace
LaFleur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
