<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR BROWN TO EARN HIS MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adding up the time and effort involved in posing
with a Los Angeles Dodgers cap and jersey, saying nice things about
Fox management and coming off bright, witty and grateful at his
introductory news conference, I'd say Kevin Brown earned $49.46 of
his $105 million Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what's he got to do to earn the rest of it?
</P>
<P>
   It's not an easy question to answer, since there's no formula
for converting on-field success into front-office revenue and since
the baseball economy is likely to go through even more changes
during the seven years of Brown's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Brown himself didn't have an answer, saying no more than ``I've
got to do what I've done in the past'' and that any player ``has to
expect a championship (or) you don't belong on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Scott Boras didn't have an answer, cautioning that no
single player can guarantee a team a World Series championship
while noting that Brown helped underdog Florida and San Diego to
the Series in 1996 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   And Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone didn't have an answer,
although he did cite Brown's durability and predict he'll improve
with age.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone might have cut closest to the truth of the matter
whether his prediction comes true or not.
</P>
<P>
   Because when you think about it, Brown will have to do even more
in the next seven years than he's done in the past seven years to
make the Dodgers look back in 2005 and say it was money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   His contract is the first nine-figure deal in baseball and his
$15 million salary makes him the highest-paid player in baseball by
a sensational margin of $1.7 million a season. For that money, he
ought to be inarguably the most valuable player in the sport at
this moment and maybe a Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Is he? Will he be? Let's do the math.
</P>
<P>
   Assume Brown repeats his past seven seasons, which began with a
21-win year with Texas in 1992 and included a National League-low
1.89 ERA for Florida in '96 and a '97 no-hitter as well as the '97
and '98 pennants.
</P>
<P>
   That's no sure thing, considering that pitchers normally decline
in their mid-30s, but we're giving him the benefit of the doubt at
least until Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   If he repeats the past seven years, he'll win 114 games for the
Dodgers, he'll help them to go to two World Series and win one,
he'll go to four All-Star Games and he'll pitch a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he then retires _ he'll be 40 years old _ his career
accomplishments will stack up like this.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have 253 wins (ranking in the top 40 of all time, in the
neighborhood of Carl Hubbell, Bob Gibson and Jack Morris).
</P>
<P>
   He'll have a .604 winning percentage (ranking in the top 75,
about equal to Preacher Roe, Dave McNally and Tom Seaver).
</P>
<P>
   He'll have eight All-Star appearances (up there with the
leaders, in the company of Don Drysdale, Jim Bunning and Juan
Marichal).
</P>
<P>
   He'll have four World Series appearances and two championship
rings.
</P>
<P>
   And _ here's the bad news _ he'll have earned zero (0) Cy Young
Awards and recorded zero (0) winning decisions in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   That's a mixed bag. With a couple of gaping holes in the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The question isn't whether any baseball player deserves $15
million a year (though that's a valid one too).
</P>
<P>
   The question isn't whether a starting pitcher, who appears only
once every five days, deserves as much money as a hitter, who
appears every day. (Mike Piazza batted about 620 times in 1998.
Brown faced about 1,040 batters. Unless you place an unusual
emphasis on defense, how can you argue that the everyday player has
more influence than the pitcher?)
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether this is the player or pitcher who
deserves the biggest bucks. To say ``yes'' is a stretch as long as
Greg Maddux, Randy Johnson and Roger Clemens _ to say nothing of
Mark McGwire _ are out there.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see what the Dodgers like about Brown and why they
decided to bet $105 million on his future. His no-nonsense demeanor
makes him the kind of player they've notably lacked during most of
their solid decade without a postseason victory. His performance at
age 31, 32 and 33, if you believe his agent's research, suggests
he'll age as gracefully as Seaver, Don Sutton, Nolan Ryan, Gaylord
Perry and Steve Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   But in their desire for Kirk Gibson-like inspiration, the
Dodgers are counting on a pitcher who happens to have never won a
World Series game; Brown was outdueled twice by Cleveland's Chad
Ogea while battling the flu in '97, and done in once by San Diego's
bullpen and once by New York's choppy ground balls in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I didn't have the horseshoes turned the right way in
the World Series,'' Brown said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   For the biggest money in baseball history, he'd better find a
way to change that.
</P>
<P>
   This is the question that will hang over Brown well into the
next century: What's he got to do to earn $105 million?
</P>
<P>
   And this is the daunting answer: He's got to do even more than
he's done so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
