<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEARIN HAS SOME REGRETS IN LEAVING CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jeff Kearin said his decision to leave Cal State
Northridge gave him a sick feeling, but in order to advance in the
profession he couldn't pass up the opportunity with UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could he pass up the chance to work with former USC head
coach John Robinson again.
</P>
<P>
   ``My four years at Northridge were the most formative of my
coaching career,'' said Kearin, who will coach tight ends and
special teams at UNLV. ``I'm sick to leave. It's done for
professional development. We did some really great things at
Northridge, but I had to do this for professional development.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, who made $39,700 annually at CSUN, said his contract
with the Runnin' Rebels was much higher. He said added perks _ no
state taxes in Nevada and a staff car _ make the deal even more
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sell shoes for John Robinson,'' said Kearin, who served
under Robinson for four years at USC. ``It was hard because I had
autonomy at Northridge. (CSUN coach) Ron (Ponciano) gave me my
areas and I ran with them. There was a comfort zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin was the assistant head coach and coached special teams
and quarterbacks at CSUN. He said he would return to Northridge
today to tell the players of his decision and to clean out his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the timing with the recruiting season, Kearin said he
will head onto the road immediately. He expects to move to Las
Vegas after the New Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2008 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     12-16 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARING GIFTS FOR OLYMPICS SHAMES ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, allow me to introduce our contestants. Trust me _ they
will ALL leave with lovely parting gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Faisal Fahd Abdul Aziz of Saudi Arabia is a member of the
International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Princess Anne is another, as is Princess Nora von
Liechtenstein, the only lady on the IOC named after a country. Or
is it vice versa?
</P>
<P>
   There are generals and doctors. There are octogenarians and
politicians. They have Prince Albert any way you want him.
</P>
<P>
   They are not all rich. But judging from the news emanating out
of Salt Lake City, they are working on it.
</P>
<P>
   There are 115 members of the IOC, and suffice to say that Motel
6 need not bother leaving the light on for them. They just awarded
the 2002 Winter Olympics to Salt Lake City, the 2004 Summer Games
to Athens, and they're all going to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   No, wait. That was the Atlanta bid.
</P>
<P>
   As a historical footnote, please be advised that offering
college scholarships was one of the claims also leveled at the
committee that snatched and shmoozed away the 1996 games for
Atlanta. Organizer Billy Payne emphatically denies that his people
ever swapped tuition payments at a Georgia college for votes.
</P>
<P>
   But who are we going to believe? Marc Hodler of Switzerland, a
respected senior executive on the IOC who has served on the
committee for 35 years? Or a man who convinced visiting IOC
dignitaries that the average summer temperature in Atlanta was 72
degrees?
</P>
<P>
   Just when the organizers in Salt Lake City thought last week
that the reports about tuition bribes would go away, Hodler spoke
out in Lausanne, Switzerland, surfing from TV crew to TV crew,
telling them all that swapping favors for votes is an IOC way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler seemed to confirm the existence of ``agents'' _ middlemen
among the electorate _ who regularly solicit fees of $3 million to
$5 million to deliver site-selection votes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of Olympic scandal began in Utah as a simple
leak _ a stolen letter, passed to a Salt Lake TV station. The
letter referred to a $10,000 tuition payment in 1996 that was being
made by Salt Lake Olympic bidders to Sonia Essomba, daughter of a
now-deceased IOC member from Cameroon. In all, 13 people, including
six relatives of IOC members, allegedly received tuition payments.
</P>
<P>
   The initial response of the Salt Lake Olympic Committee (SLOC)
was that it had done nothing wrong. Hodler himself tried to defuse
the guilt by saying Salt Lake ``is not the villain. It's the
victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodler's point is that the vote agents ``put cities in awkward
positions.'' By the time the Olympic votes are ready to be taken,
bid cities are so far down the financial bobsled run that they'll
agree to anything.
</P>
<P>
   And let me get this straight. In good, clean Utah, this makes it
right?
</P>
<P>
   Awkward corners or not, somebody in former bid organizer Tom
Welch's inner circle had to see the obvious unethical nature of the
tuition payments and free medical care that were being doled out.
But no one said anything.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever does when the Olympics are involved, it seems. The
Games are still too prestigious, too coveted an honor, for any city
to tear down the curtain.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get the Olympic Games, be advised. The IOC
doesn't want cubic zirconium. It wants your best hotel, your
longest limo and, apparently, your best root-canal man.
</P>
<P>
   If you see a limousine, flanked by siren escorts, traveling the
streets during an Olympic Games, chances are it's not Carl Lewis or
Alberto Tomba. It's an IOC member, or maybe an IOC member's wife,
returning from a shopping expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, tsk-tsk, it's terrible. It's scandalous. The Olympic
Movement can't let things like the bribery reports in Salt Lake
City happen.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch, the head of the IOC, said all that
himself last week, as he was slapping a gag order on Hodler.
</P>
<P>
   They have rules, Samaranch said. But the IOC rules governing
gifts, legal or otherwise, are all directed at the bidding cities _
not the IOC members. According to Andrew Jennings, noted author and
Samaranch Achilles' heel, no IOC blueblood has ever publicly been
admonished for accepting a gift, no matter what size or karat.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City a victim? Sure. And I'll bet it's 72 degrees in
the middle of February, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
