 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Dec. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH (Moved in ``w'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE (Washington) _ Republican and Democratic senators
said Tuesday that it appeared increasingly unlikely that President
Clinton could avoid a trial in the Senate if the House votes this
week to impeach him. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLASSROOM (New York) _ Not since communism fell and
rendered Cold War-era textbooks passe have social studies and
civics teachers faced a target that has shifted as rapidly as the
Lewinsky matter _ a subject whose enormity could not possibly have
been anticipated by the course materials that they selected at the
beginning of the school year. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RULES (Washington) _ A primer on the rules, and how
Democrats might try to foil them to get censure. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LOBBY (Washington) _ Why the business lobby isn't
lobbying. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-VOICES (St. Louis) _ Talking to people about the
impeachment issue. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON-MOOD (Jerusalem) _ Clinton was a puzzle during
this trip, even to some of his aides. He was clearly concerned
about the impeachment vote, occasionally checking on his position
in calls to chief-of-staff, John Podesta, or one of his
congressional experts, Steve Ricchetti. But when forced by
reporters to address the matter, he seemed almost indifferent, and
gave sullen answers that risked tipping away the fence-sitters
whose support he needs. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CHILDREN (Jerusalem) _ The Israelis are furious as
Clinton seems to equate children of Palestinian prisoners with
children of Israelis killed by Palestinians. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-MOURNING (Bulawayo, Zimbabwe) _ Across Africa, as
the AIDS epidemic has gnawed through people like a conqueror worm,
the number of the dying is so great that it is changing the culture
of death itself. There are 5,500 AIDS-related funerals every day in
Africa, according to the United Nations. On a continent where death
has always been a communal rather than a private matter, poverty
and emotional exhaustion are taking their toll. The poorest go
unshrouded into a common pit. Thousands of graves are left with no
markers grander than the favorite cup and spoon of the deceased,
smashed in loving memory of them. And people in all walks of life
shamefacedly confess that they no longer have the money or energy
to mourn as they feel African tradition demands. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-MARKETPLACE (Los Angeles) _ The biotechnology industry
is facing a financial reckoning. Investors, disappointed by the
financial returns the industry has provided so far, are growing
more reluctant to provide the huge amounts of money young companies
need to develop, test and sell new drugs. The result is that many
small biotechnology companies are cutting back on research. Some
are falling by the wayside or being acquired by bigger companies.
By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WIEDEN-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ One of America's most creative
agencies, Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, is seeking to raise the profiles of the
larger offices beyond its headquarters in Portland, Ore. As part of
those ambitious efforts, the agency's New York office has been
assigned a big, important task: leading the pitch for the creative
portion of the Miller Lite beer account. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PEONY (Paris) _ Peter Sellars's ``Peony Pavilion'' comes
to Paris. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd on the impeachment
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich writes about impeachement.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-RACE (New York) _ The negotiations have often been
heated, with both sides pointing fingers and hurling profanity.
Egos have been bruised, and enormous amounts of money and pride
have been sacrificed. But while it sounds like any other labor war
in America, one dynamic separates the National Basketball
Association from other disputes _ the issue of race. The players
union is 85 percent black and has begun to question whether it is
being treated with respect by an ownership that is 100 percent
white. Any number of players have already concluded they are not
being taken seriously and seem angry enough to sacrifice a season
to prove a point. By Selena Roberts and Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column the NFL
vagabonds _ the owners who keep moving their teams. By George
Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' copy) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ During most of December, and most
definitively during the Cena della Vigilia, the ritual dinner of
the vigil on Christmas Eve, my childhood home in Buffalo, N.Y.,
could have been beamed to Sicily without a single Sicilian noticing
anything peculiar about it. Alfred Portale of Gotham Bar &AMP; Grill
recreates his Sicilian Christmas Eve feast.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE (Undated) _ First, the aroma beckons. The intense
scent drawing you in is unmistakably that of rich chocolate, but
you detect exotic hints of clove, coffee, orange peel, even cedar.
The bar is dark and shiny, scored into sections. It breaks cleanly,
with a definite snap. At this point you don't even need to taste it
to know you're dealing with extremely fine chocolate. A look at how
to truly appreciate chocolate; what makes the really good stuff
worlds away from Hershey's. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
