<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS &LR;      12-16 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The Astros left baseball's winter meetings
Tuesday in the same position they arrived in _ without Roger
Clemens.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So did every other club interested in dealing for the five-time
Cy Young Award winner, who has demanded a trade from the Toronto
Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   After a gathering of baseball management failed to produce a
resolution, Toronto general manager Gord Ash and his 20-member
contingent checked out of the Opryland Hotel still holding Clemens
with no immediate deal in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. spoke with one of Clemens'
agents, Randy Hendricks, on Tuesday. McLane said that based on the
travel schedules of the parties involved, further talks aren't
expected until the beginning of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is in California playing in a golf tournament, and his
agents, Randy and Alan Hendricks, are in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something that once seemed imminent, hour-to-hour, has been
pushed back a week,'' McLane said. ``We're parking this and letting
them get back to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash had set a self-imposed deadline of seven to 10 days when
Clemens demanded on Dec. 2 to be dealt to a bona fide contender or
closer to his Houston home. Interest in the 36-year-old pitcher has
steadily dropped since it became known he desired an extravagant
new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience has been the longer things go, the least likely
you are to be successful,'' McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' complicated contract has been mostly to blame in
holding up negotiations with potential suitors. Many clubs are
reluctant to pursue Clemens because of their having to trade
top-line players, then spend free-agent money for him. When the
Hendrickses spoke with McLane last weekend, they proposed a $27.4
million, one-year extension that would give Clemens $43.5 million
over the next three seasons _ a $14.5 million average that would
nearly equal the record $15 million Kevin Brown received over the
weekend from the Los Angeles Dodgers (seven years, $105 million).
</P>
<P>
   The Hendrickses' proposal also included a fourth-year vesting
option worth an additional $15 million and a $12 million signing
bonus to be spread over the life of the contract, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the Astros were ``shocked ... just stunned'' at the
financial demands of Clemens' agents, Astros general manager Gerry
Hunsicker called a news conference Sunday to announce the club was
pulling out of the Rocket sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   McLane revived the Astros' interest in obtaining Clemens by
submitting an undisclosed counteroffer the next day. McLane added
he has received no indication from the Hendricks brothers if the
club's latest offer is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty well set, unless they come back with something
that economically makes sense,'' McLane said in regard to the
club's current pitching rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clemens' agents agree on a deal, the Astros would then
have to come up with an acceptable pool of players for Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if we make a deal with Randy Hendricks and then Toronto
wants talent that we can't give up? We still wouldn't do it,''
McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   McLane also took the opportunity Tuesday to clear matters
regarding any dissension in the Astros' front office. Sunday's
announcement by Hunsicker caused a series of heated exchanges
between the general manager and Randy Hendricks, who said McLane
hadn't written off the possibility of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Gerry took it very personal. That's what we all
would do,'' McLane said. ``We've learned from that experience and
are prepared to work closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, Baltimore and the New York Yankees remain involved in
the Clemens derby, while the Colorado Rockies acknowledged Clemens
has little interest in pitching regularly at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're absolutely out of it,'' Rockies manager Jim
Leyland said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers, also considered a front-runner for Clemens,
had an offer rejected Monday that included 20-game winner Rick
Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work and work and work, and you hope your work pays off,''
Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said. ``I really felt we had
the upper hand. Now, I feel like things have changed again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
