</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-72DOLPHINS-HNS &LR;      12-16 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-72DOLPHINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Dick Anderson, who played on the only NFL team with a
perfect record, looked forward to this being a special week of
reunion and reminiscence and of reasserting the disputed claim of
the 1972 Miami Dolphins as the greatest club in football history.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The current Dolphins are preparing to make a stand Monday night
against the Denver Broncos, who could have matched the 14-0
regular-season run of Anderson's team.
</P>
<P>
   But Denver's quest was thwarted by the New York Giants, who won
20-16 on Sunday. So nobody is hyperventilating any more about the
Broncos coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electricity would have been flowing all week,'' Anderson
said, a tinge of regret in his voice. ``The excitement would have
been greater than some playoff games.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame fullback Larry Csonka had called Dolphins coach
Jimmy Johnson to ask if he and some 1972 teammates could join him
on the sidelines Monday night. Johnson granted permission,
welcoming the '72 karma.
</P>
<P>
   Don Shula, who coached the '72 Dolphins to their 17-0 overall
record, had summoned the alumni to a banquet today at ``The Perfect
Season'' room of his Miami steakhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the Giants, that confab was canceled. So was a
Nike television commercial featuring Shula and three of the stars
of that '72 team: Csonka, Bob Griese and Mercury Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Shula was as shocked as Nike by New York's giant upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think the Giants had a chance to beat Denver,'' he
said. ``I was just hoping the Dolphins could do the job and stop
them next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Griese had said: ``If the Dolphins don't stop Denver, I
don't know who will.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris was cheering for the Broncos to beat the Giants, not just
to get his commercial aired but to see ``poetic justice'' _ an
opportunity for the present-day Dolphins to preserve the glory of
their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   He longed for a repeat of 1985, when the Chicago Bears came here
12-0 and were knocked off 38-24 by a team still being coached by
Shula.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson, Shula and most of the other '72 Dolphins are happy
the Broncos were stopped before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   And the '98 Dolphins are equally happy. Relieved, you might say.
</P>
<P>
   Some had grumbled that they could do without Griese and cohorts
making comments that added to their burden. Forget '72. These
Dolphins are trying to make this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kiick, halfback for the '72 team (back when ``halfback'' was
a position), empathized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the Giants won and there won't be a distraction for
this team,'' Kiick said. ``I know it would have been a distraction,
with all the hype during the week and a lot of us old guys hanging
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Morris was right about the Giants' victory having its
downside. Now, the '72 Dolphins are denied the limelight that would
have shined on them. National media had planned to descend on South
Florida and write volumes about these gridiron perfectionists of
the past.
</P>
<P>
   There's cruel irony here, because far from diminishing the
Dolphins' accomplishment, the Broncos' loss enhances it.
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who attended Sunday's Miami-New
York Jets game, observed: ``This is something that happens every
quarter century or half century. You have to root for people who
are doing the extraordinary, but the Broncos' losing shows you also
have to recognize this league is really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The '72 Dolphins are more deserving than ever of tribute. But as
Shula, 66, has sourly noted from time to time, it's a team forever
denied its due.
</P>
<P>
   Shula's famous iron jaw practically quivers when football
historians postulate that the Pittsburgh Steelers of the later
1970s superseded his team as the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, NFL Films president Steve Sabol set out to
discern the greatest team of all time. After interviewing numerous
players and coaches, reviewing game film and cramming data into a
computer, he selected the 1978 Steelers and '72 Dolphins as his
fantasy finalists.
</P>
<P>
   In his computerized championship game, Pittsburgh won 21-20.
Shula, the winningest coach in NFL history, was incensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing anybody could possibly have done to come out
on top of us,'' he insisted. ``We didn't make mistakes. We
dominated in time of possession, in touchdowns. We went 32-2 over
two seasons and won two Super Bowls.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1973 Dolphins, with Csonka having his finest year, may have
been even stronger than the youthful '72s.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say the '73 team was better,'' Kiick said. ``I
don't know. They were both pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Better than was realized at the time. Being a 1966 expansion
team from the defunct American Football League, the Dolphins of the
'70s had no tradition and little credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Buoniconti, their Pro Bowl middle linebacker who is now a
Miami lawyer, said, ``A lot of people think we were a fluke. They
don't speak of our team with the same reverence they show for the
Steelers or Packers or Cowboys. We have never been paid the homage
we deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics point out that Miami's 1972 schedule included only two
winning teams, both of which were an unimposing 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins even entered the Super Bowl as underdogs. But they
won 14-7, with the Washington Redskins scoring only because of an
ill-conceived pass by Miami kicker Garo Yepremian on a botched
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   What's too often overlooked are the myriad reasons why the
Dolphins always won. They were wonderfully balanced, with
exceptional depth (pioneering the 3-4 and nickel defenses),
pulverizing power (Csonka) and game-breaking speed (Hall of Fame
receiver Paul Warfield and a running back fast enough to be
nicknamed Mercury).
</P>
<P>
   Their versatility allowed them to prevail on any surface, in any
weather. They landed 10 players in the Pro Bowl following the '72
season.
</P>
<P>
   They passed sparingly (259 times for the season), because Csonka
and Morris each rushed for more than 1,000 yards, with Kiick
contributing 521.
</P>
<P>
   Griese, a Hall of Fame quarterback, submerged his ego to let the
methodical running game flourish. He missed two-thirds of the
season with a broken ankle, but 38-year-old Earl Morrall, plucked
by Shula from the waiver wire, filled in magnificently, averaging
9.1 yards per pass.
</P>
<P>
   While their No-Name Defense by its very definition lacked the
flamboyant assassins of Pittsburgh's Steel Curtain, it was no less
effective. It was the stingiest in the NFL, allowing 235.5 yards
per game, and it intercepted 26 passes. It limited Joe Namath to
151 yards passing and O.J. Simpson to 45 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was short on speed, but coordinator Bill
Arnsparger's zone alignments proved impervious to the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnsparger was brilliant,'' said Anderson, who played free
safety. ``He put us in the right situation all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins might not have been the most talented team ever,
but as Hall of Fame guard Larry Little observed, ``We knew what it
took to win games. The players today are a lot bigger and more
athletic, but we could have played with 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful any team now could have as much will to win as the
1970s Dolphins. Guard Bob Kuechenberg played the '73 season with a
broken arm. Defensive tackle Manny Fernandez played in '74 with his
left shoulder so badly torn, it had to be strapped together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning was more important to us than anything else,''
Fernandez said. ``I wasn't worried about injuries cutting short a
$6 million career. With the salary I was making, I could make as
much outside of football.''
</P>
<P>
   In that era before free agency, football teams were family
units, and the Dolphins were closely knit, though sometimes at odds
with the driven and hard-driving Shula, who scheduled as many as
four practices in a day.
</P>
<P>
   The players grudgingly accepted his regimen in order to be the
best-prepared team in the league. And they appreciated Shula's
lighter side. Csonka referred to Shula as ``a madman,'' but he
dared to put an alligator in the coach's shower stall, knowing
there would be no recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins' biggest scare in their undefeated season came in
the third game, when the Minnesota Vikings led 14-6 in the fourth
quarter. Miami rallied with a 51-yard field goal by the native
Cypriot Yepremian (``I keecked a touchdown,'' he would say) and a
scoring pass from Griese to tight end Jim Mandich.
</P>
<P>
   But as committed as the Dolphins were to winning every game, it
took years for them to fathom the significance of their 17-0
perfecto.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we thought the only thing that mattered was
winning the Super Bowl,'' Kiick said. ``In 1985, coach Shula called
me up to tell me about beating the Bears and keeping them from
being undefeated, and I said, `So what?'''
</P>
<P>
   Kiick said Csonka ``lost interest in football for several years
after he retired. He didn't want to have anything to do with it.
But when the Bears were trying to beat our record, he got
interested again.''
</P>
<P>
   Interested enough to deliver an impassioned pre-game speech to
the Dolphins, challenging them to protect a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, vice president of a cellular-phone company located
here, said he ``didn't think too much about our record for a couple
of years after it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it wasn't until the Dallas Cowboys in 1991 snapped
Washington's string at 11-0 that the significance of '72 struck
him. That's when he first uncorked a bottle of champagne and shared
it with his neighbor, Buoniconti.
</P>
<P>
   Every year since, the bubbly has come out when the last
undefeated NFL team gets blemished.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem unsportsmanlike to celebrate someone's downfall. But
the Dolphins' shameless display is a male rebonding and a
reaffirmation of their collective worth, a validation of a
sweat-wringing, blood-draining, unified effort that never waned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams today get beat by a bad team, and they say they weren't
up for the game,'' Kiick said. ``We got up for 17 games. At the
time, it wasn't considered that big an achievement. But every year
that passes, it's more unbelievable. I don't think it will ever be
done again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
