<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2025 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     12-16 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE REFUSES TO SELL ITSELF ON WORLD OLYMPIC STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle is one arrogant little city. What else can
local champions of an effort to bring the 2012 Summer Olympics to
this splendid region be thinking this week?
</P>
<P>
   The Emerald City is out of contention. Forget about it now _
unless a wildly unlikely 11th-hour rescue operation unfolds before
Dec. 31. That is the deadline set by the United States Olympic
Committee for American cities to get in or out of the 2012 bid
process.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Seattle City Council killed the 2012 initiative
when it voted 8-1 to not enter the bid process.
</P>
<P>
   What Atlanta could do to haul in the 1996 Summer Games, Seattle
will not.
</P>
<P>
   What Salt Lake City did to win the 2002 Winter Games, Seattle
won't.
</P>
<P>
   If that is arrogance, maybe that's not such a terrible thing,
although the 2012 Olympic bid champions will no doubt see the City
Council as an isolationist, quasi-xenophobic collection of
Northwesterners who should be doomed to a lifelong diet of salmon
and microbrews.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that would be perfectly terrific to most Seattle
natives, and even to some of its many newcomers, which would mean
anyone who moved here after the maiden voyage of the Kalakala.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, Seattle was at least a front-runner among USOC and
International Olympic Committee officials, although no polls or
votes would make that public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle is an envied city. It is one of the five cities in the
U.S. where if you asked people where they would live, if they could
live anywhere, Seattle would be one of them,'' USOC spokesman Mike
Moran told the P-I Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle is also an international city. It has attracted many
events and is an enviable place to hold sporting events, no
question about it,'' Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have been getting consistent signals that there was a
hostility toward the prospect of the Olympics coming there, and the
USOC is rooted in the strict requirement that we will only go where
we are welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the USOC, there are eight other American
cities/regions still alive for the 2012 bid. With China now a
strong candidate to bring the 2008 Summer Olympics to Asia, it
increases the likelihood that the IOC would return the Games to
North America in 2012.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Seattle bid proponents like Kathy Scanlan or Bob Walsh
are a little extra bitter or funereal over the death-penalty doled
out Monday, it is probably because they viewed Seattle as the
likely beneficiary of a long, hard, expensive bid campaign and
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when the 2012 Olympics are awarded in three years, and
if it goes to San Francisco or Baltimore/Washington or Houston or
New York or one three other U.S. cities, then Seattle will have to
live with the quirky and admirable trait of civic arrogance, which
surely it can do.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Denver, which threw back its Olympic bid to the USOC in
the early 1970s and now yearns for another shot, Seattle will
probably never look back.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it soon will have no alternative. Thursday, the Seattle
bid committee's executive board is scheduled to meet. It will more
than likely vote to disband, ending four years of fund raising,
four years of politicking by Walsh, the promoter who brought the
Goodwill Games to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh's vision for an even greater Seattle through an Olympic
extravaganza was rebuked by a City Council that heard nothing more
loud or more resounding than the protests of irate citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's crying around here,'' City Council member Peter
Steinbreuck said Tuesday, adding that the council looked forward to
getting back to the business of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic torch never caught on the attention it would have
needed. The bid committee did not have an inspired local leader.
They didn't work well with the council,'' Steinbreuck said, making
it clear that head-butting and suspicion between the bid committee
and council was an issue from the start of the non-process.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbreuck admitted that beyond the awesome financial
obligations now required of a local government by the USOC in order
to become a bid city, there were other, more parochial issues on
the minds of the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Olympics came here, Seattle would never be the same. It
would have the spotlight on it again. It would just add to our
growth problems,'' Steinbreuck said. ``It would draw more people
here, and we are already dealing with housing and transportation
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is a little far-fetched to think that every
Olympic visitor would fall so immediately, so deeply in love with
Seattle that he or she would evacuate homes from Biloxi or Beijing
to set up residence under the Space Needle.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, in addition to the natural and warranted suspicion
about the costs, liabilities and human resources associated with an
undertaking as mammoth as the Olympic Games, there seems to be
messed up in this council's decision an overwhelming _ and not
entirely healthy _ dose of hostility toward the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people over there laughing about killing the
Olympics,'' one bid insider said in disgust, failing to understand
why Seattle would choose not to flaunt itself in front of a global
audience for an Olympic fortnight in exchange for what he says
could be 10 years of residual benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Ongoing tourism, conventions, government subsidies for education
and transportation, and if you can believe this, potential profit
are being sacrificed in this knee-jerk and premature end of the
Olympic discussion.
</P>
<P>
   If it can be faulted for anything, the bid committee _ with
officials like Mayor Paul Schell and County Executive Ron Simms on
board _ could not get the word out loud enough on these positive
Olympic factors to combat the bevy of full-throated nay-sayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor feels it is very unfortunate that we have shut this
discussion off in the city when there is strong support in the
region,'' Cliff Traisman, the city's director of intergovernmental
relations, said Tuesday. ``The mayor is very frustrated that there
can't be regional debate. This was all contingent on a public
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the central issue about why this Olympic bid
was never going to see the light of day in King County or
Washington state: Not with the such intense backlash in the wake of
two stadium votes that were at best flawed or flops.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the Mariners' new stadium is being built despite
the fact the public mandate was for it not to be built. And
remember that Seahawks owner Paul Allen underwrote the costs of a
statewide referendum on the Kingdome _ something some advocates of
democracy say smacks of buying an election.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such tumultuous manipulations on the part of
local and state officials in their efforts to give public funding
to Seattle's sports teams, it is easier to understand why some
citizens _ elected or otherwise _ are steadfastly, unerringly
denying this Olympic bid to take a single, trespassing step onto
Seattle's hallowed environs.
</P>
<P>
   Hostility, arrogance, call it what you want. The Olympics
themselves are truly one of the most awesome and inspiring events,
the way the world comes together, the way the athletes soar.
</P>
<P>
   It's just not going to be happening in our backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 0156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
