A2043 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-MITCHELL-NYT &LR;      12-16 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MITCHELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL CLEARS OLYMPIC SPRINTER OF DOPING OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By PAUL GAINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Mitchell, the Olympic sprinter suspended last summer
because of a positive drug test, has been cleared by a panel of the
United States Track and Field Association.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of testimony in a Chicago airport hotel, a
three-member panel of the association's doping hearing board ruled
that Mitchell did not commit a doping offense in connection with an
out-of-competition test last April.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, reached on Monday, should clear the way for
Mitchell, a three-time Olympian, to compete sometime early in the
new year, if the International Amateur Athletic Federation upholds
the findings. If it rejects the findings, the federation can ban
him for up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   The IAAF suspended the 32-year-old sprinter in July after the
analysis of a urine sample taken in April. That analysis revealed
an elevated level of testosterone to epitestosterone level, growth
hormones that are widely believed to enhance performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy with the results and I am looking forward to
putting the events of the last six months behind me,'' Mitchell
said in a prepared statement issued by his lawyer, Suja Thomas. ``I
look forward to competing again as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said Mitchell was obviously elated at the news but
cautious in his reaction because the IAAF must sanction his
reinstatement before he sets foot on the track.
</P>
<P>
   A similar process took place with the American distance runner
Mary Slaney, who was suspended for a positive test during the 1996
Olympic trials. Two years later her case is still unresolved, but
she is allowed to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing on Mitchell had been postponed from Nov. 14 when
Thomas asked for more time to prepare for cross-examination of a
new witness.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared and confident, Mitchell was reported to have been
delighted to be able to finally tell his side of the story, though
neither he nor his attorney will reveal the nature of their
successful argument.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell earned a gold medal as a member of the 400-meter relay
team that set a world record in the Barcelona Summer Olympics in
1992. He also won a bronze medal in the 100 meters there. In the
Goodwill Games in New York last summer, he again won gold on the
U.S. 400-meter relay team.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer panel members _ a judge, a lawyer and a former
track world record-holder _ were unanimous in their decision. Now
they must present a written explanation of their decision to the
USATF and to the IAAF within 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in Seville, Spain, Istvan Gyulai, the IAAF general
secretary, was reluctant to comment on the case until the IAAF had
received the written judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Once the report is received at IAAF headquarters in Monte Carlo,
the council will judge whether it should go to arbitration or
whether it accepts the American decision outright.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell case had been particularly embarrassing to the
USATF because the sprinter is the chairman of the association's
athlete's advisory committee and has always spoken out against drug
use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0049 </DOCNO>
