<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FELL-OBIT-NYT &LR;      12-16 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELL-OBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN FELL, 74, ACTOR KNOWN FOR TV ROLE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
   Norman Fell, a television and film actor best known for his role
as the crotchety landlord Stanley Roper on the sitcom ``Three's
Company,'' died on Monday at the Motion Picture and Television
Fund's retirement home in Woodland Hills, Calif. He was 74.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said Carol Pfannkuche, a spokeswoman for
the fund.
</P>
<P>
   In ABC's ``Three's Company,'' which made its debut in 1977, Fell
and Audra Lindley played Stanley and Helen Roper, landlords to two
attractive female roommates. The young women, played by Joyce
DeWitt and Suzanne Somers, decide for financial reasons to share
their apartment with an attractive male, played by John Ritter.
Nosy and uptight, Roper spends a good deal of time meddling in his
neighbors' affairs, while enduring the constant putdowns of his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Fell and Ms. Lindley left the sitcom to star in ``The
Ropers,'' a spinoff that lasted one season. Fell's peevish
expression and hangdog eyes were distinctive, and the role earned
him considerable recognition into his later years, often to his
exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   Fell also appeared in 35 movies, including ``Catch-22'' and,
somewhat presciently, ``The Graduate,'' in which he played the
landlord who throws Dustin Hoffman out of a rooming house.
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared in the television series ``Dan August,'' a
detective drama starring Burt Reynolds that ran from 1970 to 1975,
eventually winning roles with Reynolds in the films ``Paternity''
and ``The End.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Philadelphia, Fell graduated from Temple University with
a bachelor's degree in drama.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, during which he served as an Air Force tail
gunner in the Pacific, he studied acting, struggling to win small
parts in stage and television productions like ``Twelve Angry Men''
in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   He made his first regular television appearances in the
short-lived comedy ``Joe and Mabel,'' which was broadcast in 1956,
and in the role of Detective Meyer in the 1961-62 drama ``87th
Precinct,'' based on the Ed McBain mystery novels.
</P>
<P>
   Fell is survived by two daughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUNY-CURRICULUM-NY     12-16 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUNY-CURRICULUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNY BOARD TO REQUIRE CORE COURSES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over complaints that they were ramming through a
policy that had never been publicly discussed, trustees of the
State University of New York on Tuesday approved a new core
curriculum for about 150,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   While many other universities allow their students wide latitude
in choosing what classes they take, SUNY's board saw a firmly
defined core curriculum as a cornerstone to its efforts to raise
standards and enhance SUNY's prestige.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will elevate the value of the State University degree,
and that our graduates will possess the skills and know-how they
need,'' said SUNY's chairman, Thomas F. Egan.
</P>
<P>
   The curriculum approved by the trustees, in a 10-3 vote,
requires that all freshmen starting in the fall of 2000 at the 29
undergraduate SUNY campuses take 10 individual courses, including
mathematics, natural science, social sciences, American history,
Western civilization and foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   Some trustees had reservations about specific requirements, like
foreign languages. Others asked why the curriculum included some
broad fields, like the sciences, but was specific in calling for
American history and Western civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have concerns for academic freedom,'' said Louis T.
Howard, a trustee. ``Why in these two areas are we so specific? Why
not Franco-American history?''
</P>
<P>
   Randy A. Daniels, one of the trustees who was co-chairman of the
board's subcommittee that shaped the policy, argued that American
history was a must. ``We are all Americans and we should all be
knowledgeable about our own history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest complaint was the board's hurry to pass the
proposal without campus discussion, which some critics viewed as an
effort to put the policy in place before people could attack it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are dealing with something that is going to affect
everyone in the university community, there should be some time
spent discussing it,'' said Celine Traylor, the sole student
trustee, who called for the vote to be delayed and was one of the
three trustees who voted no.
</P>
<P>
   Paul R. Perez, a trustee and co-chairman of the curriculum
subcommittee, said that the topic had been publicly discussed since
1995. But presidents of several SUNY colleges said that they had
not seen the specific proposal until Tuesday, when they arrived at
the board meeting. And some trustees said they had not seen copies
until late last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only got mine faxed Friday afternoon,'' said Edward S.
Nelson, another trustee who voted against the proposal. ``It looks
to me like this is a rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan, the board chairman, tried to reassure Nelson and others,
saying that there would be plenty of time for discussion and
changes before the policy takes effect in 2000. He said that the
policy would be discussed with the college presidents in January,
and that amendments were possible.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY's provost, Peter D. Salins, also tried to reassure critics,
saying there was room for faculties and presidents to set their own
requirements within the framework. ``I don't see it as a
straitjacket,'' he said. ``I see it as having a great deal of
flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arnold B. Gardner, the third trustee to oppose the measure,
called it ``a milestone in increasing the intrusion by the central
office'' into campus affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to act so quickly except to claim the
ground and then act to defend it,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
