<HEADER>
A2050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-HONDURAS-COLUMN-N     12-16 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-HONDURAS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: U.S. STALLS FLIGHTS TO AID HONDURAN VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A big yellow truck rumbled down the drab streets of
Long Island City, Queens, before heaving to a halt outside a
warehouse. Luis Riera gave it a weary glance from inside the drafty
space that has been his home lately. All around him, boxes of food,
medicine and clothing were piled high like building blocks, all
donations intended to rebuild Honduras, his native land, which was
battered seven weeks ago by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of this largess did not make him happy. Nor did the
arrival of the truck, which was ready to be loaded with more boxes,
if only they had a way to reach Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be different if we had a way to transport this to
Honduras,'' said Riera, a volunteer who oversees the warehouse.
``Right now we have a list of places where we could collect more
donations, but we can't. There's no more room to move in and out.
Without transportation, we are delayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar snags have been reported in Los Angeles, Miami and
elsewhere as tons of donations await shipment to Central America.
In New Jersey alone, some 20,000 pounds of relief supplies sit in
warehouse limbo. Much of the aid has to be sent by boat, a slower
process made more difficult by what Honduran consular officials
said was a seasonal scarcity of cargo containers.
</P>
<P>
   The officials had hoped that National Guard planes would be made
available to airlift the boxes. But it appears that those plans
were sidetracked when American forces were put on alert because of
the potential need for forces in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials in New York state offered us transport planes from
the National Guard,'' said Octavio Pineda, the Honduran consul in
New York. ``The problem is they need federal authorization to leave
American air space. They never were authorized. Then the situation
with Iraq happened and all the planes were put on hold. Since then,
we have not had any communication.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, the United States had no problem flying nearly
anything it wanted to Honduras, which was then considered a friend
and ally in Central America. At the time, Honduras was an
intelligence and command post for the contra war being waged
against Nicaragua's Sandinista government. The presence of
thousands of American-supported contra troops and their base camps
embarrassed Honduran officials, who were reduced to taking a
face-saving cue from that old ``Hogan's Heroes'' stalwart, Sgt.
Schultz. ``Contras? CIA? I know nothing! Nothing!''
</P>
<P>
   Now the contras are history, and democracy has come to
Nicaragua. And the promise of cargo planes that could have ferried
relief supplies vanished once the president of Iraq, Saddam Hussein
_ himself once a friend of sorts to the United States _ started
playing his usual shell game with weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Two spokesmen for the Defense Department could not explain why
the cargo flights to Honduras had not been authorized. Instead,
they punted the question on Monday to New York state National Guard
officials, a puzzling move, since state officials cannot
unilaterally authorize the flights.
</P>
<P>
   This has frustrated New York state officials, who said they were
still willing to supply several cargo planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been asking from the beginning, but it has not been
approved,'' said one state official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``We're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has pledged hundreds of millions of dollars
in aid to Honduras. It has also suspended the country's obligations
to make foreign debt payments for two years and provided
helicopters and engineers to help rebuild roads and bridges. But
Hondurans and their supporters here wonder why the tons of goods
they collected _ with the generous help of state and city officials
_ can't get to their homeland in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
   Edward James Olmos, the actor, visited Honduras for UNICEF soon
after the hurricane, and he said the devastation he witnessed
underscored the need for as much help as possible. He said that in
Los Angeles alone there were 20 50-foot containers packed with
supplies sitting in a factory, and he worried that they might have
been collected in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might just be easier to buy things locally in Honduras or
Mexico than it would be to wait for help to be flown in,'' he said.
``They need everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Honduran consular officials said that some commercial airlines
had helped move supplies, but that much more of them had had to be
sent by boat. They said their office had been forced to scramble to
find enough cash and cargo containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the point of losing hope,'' said Julio Cesar
Enamorado, the vice consul. ``We cannot keep food and clothing in
warehouses while our people are dying of hunger. We decided we are
going to cover the cost of containers until we get free planes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, volunteers still show up to pack and stack
boxes of donations. On Saturday, Sandra Monge stood before a tower
of boxes, each one filled with toys and decorated with jolly Santas
and messages of Feliz Navidad. She was collecting money from
friends and family to send the toys by boat, which means they
probably won't arrive by Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets there by Three Kings Day, that's good enough,'' Ms.
Monge said of the Jan. 6 holiday. ``I like kids, so this is the
most important shipment to me. They don't understand what is
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Children understand friendship. So what if in their fickleness
they jump from one best buddy to another _ who doesn't? Just ask
some of the volunteers toiling at the warehouse on Saturday.
Outside, the skies were a cloudy gray. It was a fitting backdrop
for the volunteers, who were swamped with boxes. Among themselves,
they were learning how it felt to have fair-weather friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
