<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kelso: Do your worst to win our card contest
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ How's this for a couple of nuts?
</P>
<P>
   The nut on the left is Robert Burns, 54, the art director of the
'70s cult horror classic ``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre.'' Burns is
the guy who created the gooey special effects for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The nut on the right in this Christmas card is the World's
Largest Pecan, not an actual pecan but a 1,000-pound concrete pecan
that sits in the square in Seguin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Burns moved from South Austin to Seguin, a town of
21,373 people and lots of pecans about 50 miles south of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Burns' first artistic act after moving to Seguin was to visit
the town square last week and have this picture taken for his
Christmas card.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to wonder what the locals were thinking when they saw
this happening. I imagine the conversation went something like
this: ``Hey, Midge. Looks like another nutbag from Austin has moved
into town. There's some idiot over by the pecan getting his picture
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns went to some trouble to get this picture taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it on the first day that big cold front blew through,
and it was just colder than (provide your own noun),'' Burns said.
``I was just standing out there making a fool of myself next to
that pecan in front of the whole city.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the good news. This picture has provided the inspiration
for John Kelso's Extremely Stupid Christmas Card Contest. If you
have a Christmas card that is anywhere near as silly as this one,
please send a copy of it to me to P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767,
and you could become famous.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have a Christmas card that shows you giving your cat a
bubble bath. Maybe you've got a Christmas card of Aunt Nelda
accidentally electrocuting herself while putting on that
glitter-covered, battery-powered sweat shirt that plays ``Silent
Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe you have a Christmas card of you and mom on
vacation in Florida, holding up a large, dead fish.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have anything that creative? If so, get jolly and send it
to me. The silliest Christmas cards will be printed in The Austin
American-Statesman newspaper along with your name and explanation
(alibi?).
</P>
<P>
   Burns is going to be hard to beat, though, because he is a
veteran of putting out stupid Christmas cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I've sent out a lot of goofy cards,'' he said smugly.
``The first one I ever did was the one I did with those rubber
stamps. I've done all kinds of them through the years. Now it's
expected of me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas card done with a rubber stamp was a postcard Burns
sent to his friends that showed the globe with some little round,
smiling green peas sitting on top.
</P>
<P>
   The caption? ``Peas on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that makes Burns' most recent stupid Christmas
card so perfect is the outfit he has on for the occasion. That
plaid jacket Burns is wearing in the picture is louder than Texas
Monthly publisher Mike Levy. Where did Burns get those clothes?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is around the house. ``I have outfits for all
occasions,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns picked the World's Largest Pecan for his Christmas card
because it is a centerpiece in Seguin, a major pecan-growing town.
``It's featured on all their brochures,'' Burns said. ``Seguin is
mighty proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowning touch of this card is the message on the right
side: ``Come share the excitement.'' Makes you want to pack the
kids in the car and take off for Seguin, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The inscription on the plaque of the World's Largest Pecan tells
visitors that 16th century Spanish explorer Cabeza de Vaca traveled
on the Guadalupe River, which runs through Seguin, and that the
river used to be known way back when as ``The River of Nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Burns has moved to Seguin, there is more truth to the
name than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Christmas card that can top this, and I'm sure
some of y'all have, get it to me and we'll share it with the world.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
