<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slicker Than Nixon
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ President Richard Milhous Nixon was standing a few
feet in front of me, sweating and twitching, on Sunday evening,
Nov. 11, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have got to know whether or not their president is a
crook,'' he said. ``Well, I'm not a crook.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, unlike President William Jefferson Clinton, was a lousy
liar.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon looked shifty and sounded shifty during that press
conference and throughout his political career. His body language
was out of sync with his words.
</P>
<P>
   Where Nixon was clumsy, Clinton is slick. Clinton is an actor, a
con man and a master manipulator. He has been accurately described
as someone who could teach Machiavelli lessons in the art of
deceit.
</P>
<P>
   Like all good grifters, Clinton tells people what they want to
hear, plays on their emotions, draws them into his web and uses
them for his gain.
</P>
<P>
   If Nixon had half of Clinton's guile, he likely would be warmly
ensconced in history books as a great president. Surely, Clinton
could make those incriminating Oval Office tapes disappear just as
easily as the Rose law firm billing records.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had a genius for masterminding foreign policy resolutions
that brought long-term benefits to this nation. Clinton has a
genius for adopting and changing positions based on effervescent
public opinion polls. His career is littered with friends, allies
and policy positions dropped in a heartbeat when they threatened
his public approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers gave me a Richard Nixon watch that included the
instantly famous ``I'm not a crook'' remark. It still runs. Nixon's
eyes shift back and forth with each tick.
</P>
<P>
   Today there's a Bill Clinton watch. It shows his nose growing
longer and longer with each tick. Also now on sale is a takeoff on
the ``Tickle me, Elmo'' dolls called ``Fondle me, Bubba.'' They
play back remarks such as ``I'll bomb Baghdad, I'll bomb France, if
you'll remove my underpants,'' or ``Hey, baby, I've got some
Astroturf in the back of my El Camino.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers also can buy a knockoff of Russian nesting dolls that
include the figures of Paula, Gennifer, Monica and Kathleen.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors flock daily to White House to catch a glimpse of the
``Bill and Monica'' room.
</P>
<P>
   First Clinton turned America's revered People's House into a
hot-sheet flop house to raise campaign funds and then he turned it
into a bawdy-house joke. True to his nature, he lied about it.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, in my estimation, was a crook. He committed high crimes
and misdemeanors. He ``violated the trust of the American people,
lessened their esteem for the office of president and dishonored
the office which they have entrusted to him,'' which is the censure
resolution congressional Democrats want to apply to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon deserved to be impeached in the House, tried in Senate and
removed from office. Fortunately, Nixon took the advice of powerful
Republicans who told him it was time to go.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's partisan apologists keep reminding us that there is no
equivalency in the crimes committed by Nixon and Clinton. They are
right. But so what?
</P>
<P>
   All crimes are not equivalent. If all criminals except the very
worst were released, there would be only one person in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Preachers, pundits and more than 150 U.S. newspapers have called
on Clinton to resign. But Clinton will never resign unless the
leaders of his party tell him to go. Even then, he might not do it.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that Congress will force Clinton's removal even if
it comes to a trial in the Senate. That's fine with me.
</P>
<P>
   But American voters must come to grips with the fact that they
have twice been slickered by an immoral con man. They must make
sure it never happens again.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is a senior editor for The Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas. E-Mail: RNeth(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
