<HEADER>
A2257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-     12-16 1632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-TAKE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard about the discovery of stone bullets in the
Mediterranean Sea that were used in a battle 2,000 years ago. What
kind of weapon was used to fire such things? How big were the
bullets?
</P>
<P>
   A: Researchers say the projectiles were fired by catapults,
which worked on the same principle as slingshots, but on a larger
scale. Just before the battle for control of the Mediterranean
world began on Sept. 2, 31 B.C., the fleets of Octavian, fighting
against those of Marc Antony and Cleopatra, faced one another in
long parallel lines and launched thousands of stone balls. While
larger stone-throwing catapults were used on land, smaller ones
were used on the naval vessels because of their weight. The balls,
found and photographed on the sea floor in the battle zone, are
estimated to be between 4 and 6 inches in diameter and to weigh
between 3.3 and 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that there is an immediate need for an influx of cash
before construction can begin on the proposed World War II monument
in Washington. It would be helpful to know where to send donations.
Can you tell us?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call 1-800-639-4992 for information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During the House Judiciary Committee hearings, members often
used the phrase ``strike the last word.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a parliamentary tactic to extend debate time during the
amending process. The ``last word'' refers to the last word of the
pending amendment or bill. Motions to strike the last word actually
are nonsense amendments, or more technically, pro forma amendments
(amendments in form only).
</P>
<P>
   House members recognize that these motions to strike the last
word are used strictly to extend debate. They're not meant
literally to strike out the last word.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. The House most often amends bills under the
``five-minute rule,'' which allots five minutes for the mover of an
amendment to explain it, and five minutes for an opponent. This
time can be extended only by unanimous consent, which is not always
forthcoming. With a total of only 10 minutes per amendment under
the regular order, the two principal members debating an amendment
often use up all the time and have none left to yield to other
members who wish to participate in the debate. However, members can
get five minutes of their own if they offer an amendment _ so
that's what they do. They move to strike the last word of the
pending amendment. They then are recognized for five minutes, which
they use not to discuss the merits of striking the last word of the
pending amendment, but instead to discuss its substantive content.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I keep seeing mention that there's one independent in the
House of Representatives. But the person is never identified. Who
is it? What is his or her voting record like?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rep. Bernard Sanders, just re-elected to his fifth term from
Vermont, is the only independent in Congress. He usually votes with
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Donna Shalala, secretary of health and human services, was
named by the Sara Lee Corp. among women who are exceptional. I
recall that Shalala, commenting about Vietnam veterans, once was
criticized for saying ``They are not our best and brightest.'' What
was the context?
</P>
<P>
   A: The remark, made in April 1995, created a brief stir, fueled
by syndicated conservative commentator Rush Limbaugh and others.
Shalala, appearing on CNN's ``Capital Gang,'' was commenting about
a new book, ``In Retrospect: The Tragedy and Lessons of Vietnam,''
by Robert S. McNamara, secretary of defense in the Kennedy and
Johnson administrations.
</P>
<P>
   When it first was reported that Shalala had said ``the best and
the brightest sons'' did not go to Vietnam, Limbaugh and others
pounced, saying she was disparaging the men who fought there, with
Limbaugh adding that she ``should be forced to apologize for and
maybe even resign over'' the comment. Avis LaVelle, her
spokeswoman, said Shalala was misunderstood, and what she meant was
that ``the best and the brightest's sons'' were able to avoid
serving in the war.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Shalala, then-Veterans Affairs Secretary Jesse
Brown, a Vietnam veteran, wrote: ``I understand what you were
saying _ it is mainly the poorer kids of this country who have
traditionally fought our wars.'' Shalala also wrote to six
veterans' organizations, saying: ``I did not, and would never,
disparage or denigrate those who served our nation so valiantly.
The point I was making is that the burden of fighting the war fell
disproportionately on poor and middle-income families, and that the
sons of the so-called best and the brightest were rarely called.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't Joe DiMaggio have a brother who also played
professional baseball? Is he still living? Can you tell us
something about him and his baseball career?
</P>
<P>
   A: Three DiMaggio brothers _ Vince, born Sept. 6, 1912; Joe,
Nov. 25, 1914; and Dom, Feb. 12, 1917 _ played professional
baseball. While Joe, the Yankee Clipper, was the most celebrated,
Dom and Vince each played in more than 1,000 Major League games.
Two other DiMaggio brothers didn't go into pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   Vince (Vincent Paul) died in 1986 after a bout with stomach
cancer. He played 10 seasons in the National League as an
outfielder with the Boston Braves. He also played with the
Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, Philadelphia Phillies and New
York Giants. He had a career batting average of .249 with 125 home
runs and 584 runs batted in. He also had at one time the dubious
distinction of holding the Major League record for strikeouts with
134 in 1938 for the Braves. He retired from baseball in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   At last report, Dom (Dominic Paul) was splitting his time
between New England and his waterfront home in Florida. He broke in
with the Boston Red Sox in 1940, four years after brother Joe made
his debut with the New York Yankees. In 1949, Dom set a Red Sox
record for the longest hitting streak by a rookie: 34 games. He
retired from baseball in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the popular vote totals in the 1996 presidential
race between Bob Dole and Bill Clinton? What were the Electoral
College vote totals? How many states did each of them win?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clinton got 47,401,185 votes (49.25 percent of the total);
Dole got 39,197,469 (40.73 percent). Electoral College: Clinton
379; Dole 159. States: Clinton 31 and the District of Columbia;
Dole 19.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give us an update on the Thompson sextuplets, the
first born to an African-American couple in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jacqueline and LindenThompson of Washington became the
parents of the nation's first black sextuplets May 8, 1997. One,
Allison Nicole, was stillborn, but the other five _ Octavio
Daniela, Stella Kimberly, Emily Elizabeth, Richard Linden and
Ann-Marie Amanda _ are doing well. Even though the one daughter
died, the family still refers to their babies as ``sextuplets.''
</P>
<P>
   The babies were virtually ignored by outsiders for six months,
until a published report contrasted their circumstances to the
attention poured on white septuplets born in November 1997 to Bobbi
and Kenny McCaughey in Iowa. After that, the Thompsons began
receiving donations too, including free day care, a Chevrolet van,
a lifetime supply of diapers, free toys until they are 15, and free
dental care. In December 1997, Howard University and the National
Political Congress of Black Women announced full four-year
scholarships for the babies.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Thompsons moved from their apartment to a
six-bedroom home purchased by the Freddie Mac Foundation for
$210,000. Renovations costing $100,000 were covered by the
corporation and the donated services of several Washington
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Donations are still being accepted: The Thompson Family Fund,
c/o The Village Helpers Group, Attention: Deborah E. Reid, 1620 E.
12th St., 3-C, Brooklyn, NY 11229.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some months ago, I read about a cruise ship with cabins that
could be purchased like a condominium. What's that all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 958-foot vessel, called The World of ResidenSea, is the
brainchild of Knut Kloster Jr., whose father founded Norwegian
Caribbean Line, which later became Norwegian Cruise Line. It's
scheduled to be completed in early 2001, according to Christie's
Great Estates, marketing agent for the vessel in the Americas.
Condo-style suites and apartments range from $792,000 to more than
$3.6 million; annual maintenance fees range up to $302,600.
</P>
<P>
   While the concept resembles a floating condo, residents won't
really own their homes like condo owners do, according to a report
in Business Week. While documents are structured to resemble condo
agreements, residents actually would be buying a 50-year lease, the
magazine added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has any TV show other than ``The White Shadow'' won an Emmy
for its pilot?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. It's not ``exceptionally unusual,'' says Louise Danton,
archivist for the Television Academy of Arts and Sciences. But ``it
doesn't happen often,'' either. Last year, for example, an Emmy for
directing for a drama series was awarded to Mark Tinker for the
pilot of ``Brooklyn South,'' and two choreographers, Marguerite
Dericks and Peggy Holmes, won for choreography for the pilot of
``Fame.'' And there were pilot winners in previous years, too,
Danton said. You can find more information on the Television
Academy's Web site: www.emmys.org
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
