<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 09:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-     12-16 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-TAKE2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: PART TWO OF TWO TAKES.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is a nonreactive pan? I tried to make a lemon tart in a
regular pan and it didn't turn out right.
</P>
<P>
   A: What you need is a glass baking dish or a metal pan coated
with enamel, says nutritionist Connie Crawley of the University of
Georgia Cooperative Extension Service. Most other baking pans are
aluminum, and those tend to react with acidic foods, she adds. The
glass or enamel-coated wares are widely available, and the brand
doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've always enjoyed reading ``The Night Before Christmas'' at
this time of year. How old is this beloved poem? Can you tell me
anything about its author, Clement C. Moore?
</P>
<P>
   A: The popular ballad goes by several names, ``An Account of a
Visit From St. Nicholas,'' ``A Visit From St. Nicholas,'' and
simply by its first line, ``'Twas the Night Before Christmas.''
According to tradition, Clement Clarke Moore wrote the poem in 1822
as a Christmas present for his children. It was first published
anonymously on Dec. 23, 1823, in the Troy (N.Y.) Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was born in New York in 1799; he died in 1863. He was a
biblical scholar who taught Greek and Oriental literature in the
Episcopal seminaries of New York from 1821 to 1850. There's some
dispute about the authorship of the holiday favorite; some people
have attributed it to Henry Livingston Jr., a New York land
surveyor who also composed poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Stolen art during World War II has been in the news lately.
I've been told that the French hid a large part of the Louvre's
collection so successfully that it was never found by invading
armies. Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was the declared intent of the German Nazis to take home a
long list of French masterpieces for a special new imperial museum.
The French reacted to that threat, and to the possibility of German
bombings of the Louvre and other museums, by taking their cherished
contents and secreting them around the countryside. Hector
Feliciano's book ``The Lost Museum: The Nazi Conspiracy to Steal
the World's Greatest Works of Art'' examines the subject of
artworks missing or lost in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did Sen. Max Cleland get hurt in Vietnam? I've heard
several theories.
</P>
<P>
   A: Cleland (D-Ga.), who served in the Army from 1965 to 1968,
explained the incident in his own words in the November issue of
George magazine, which paid tribute to 20 Vietnam veterans serving
in Congress. This is what he said, in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was awake long before dawn on April 8, 1968. My tour of
Vietnam was almost over. . . . I volunteered for one more mission,
my last. My unit was sent to relieve the Marines in Khe Sanh. After
we landed at the base, the team unloaded our equipment from the
chopper. I called to the pilot that I was getting out. . . . I
jumped to the ground, ran in a crouch until I got clear of the
spinning helicopter blades, turned around, and watched the chopper
lift. Then I saw the grenade. . . . It must be mine, I thought.
Grenades had fallen off my web gear before. Shifting the M-16 to my
left hand and holding it behind me, I bent down to pick up the
grenade. A blinding explosion threw me backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleland, a captain, lost both legs and an arm. He was awarded a
Silver Star and a Bronze Star. Before being elected to the Senate,
he served as Georgia's secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will be the time and azimuth of sunrise and sunset on
the winter solstice? What will be the elevation of the sun at noon
Dec. 21?
</P>
<P>
   A: The winter solstice occurs at 8:56 p.m. EST on Dec. 22, says
astronomer David Dundee at Fernbank Science Center in Atlanta. The
maximum elevation of the sun that day will be 33 degrees above the
horizon in the South. Sunrise will be at 7:39 that morning, sunset
at 5:33 that evening. For non-astronomers, the azimuth is an
angular measurement used to locate an object such as the moon or a
star. It's measured clockwise around the horizon from the north, or
south, to the object or the object's vertical circle with the
horizon. Dundee says the sun will rise at 118 degrees and set at
242 degrees; 90 degrees is east, zero degrees is north.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' recently featured the Rockefeller family.
What was the relationship between the Rockefeller who died on the
Titanic and John D. Rockefeller Sr.? Also, can you list John Sr.'s
descendants?
</P>
<P>
   A: Titanic's passenger list shows no Rockefeller aboard. You may
be thinking about millionaire John Jacob Astor or department store
owner Isidor Straus, both of whom were lost in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   John Davison Rockefeller was the American businessman who made a
fortune in the petroleum industry and later became famous for his
philanthropy. Born in 1839, he died in 1937 in Ormond Beach, Fla.
His only son, John D. Rockefeller Jr. (1874-1960), continued his
father's philanthropic work. John D. Jr. had five sons: John D.
III, chairman of the Rockefeller Foundation 1952-71; Nelson,
governor of New York from late 1958 to 1973 and vice president from
1974 to '77; Laurance, a noted conservationist; Winthrop, governor
of Arkansas from 1967 to '71; and David, CEO of Chase Manhattan
Bank from 1969 to '80. John D. IV, by the way, was governor of West
Virginia from 1977 to '85 and has been a U.S. senator from West
Virginia since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a picture of an old American flag with 15 stripes. I
thought the stripes represented the 13 original colonies. Can you
explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: On June 14, 1777, the Continental Congress resolved that the
U.S. flag would have 13 alternating red and white stripes
representing, as you say, the 13 original colonies. By 1794, two
new states had joined the Union, so Congress decided to add two
stripes (and two stars), with the 15-stripe version to be used
after May 1, 1795. By 1817 five more states had come into the
Union, but Congress didn't want the flag to have 20 stripes (and 20
stars) because it would be too cluttered. Peter Wendover, a House
member from New York, proposed a flag with 13 stripes, with a star
for each state. Congress accepted the idea, and April 4, 1818, it
set the number of stripes at 13 again.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend saw a report on CBS News recently concerning a new
drug to treat osteoporosis.Testing of the drug was a part of Sen.
John Glenn's regimen on his recent space voyage. Do you have any
information? My father is severely afflicted with this debilitating
disease.
</P>
<P>
   A: CBS News correspondent John Roberts was reporting on A1x1-11,
a drug that works by mimicking hormones produced by the parathyroid
glands. Those hormones help regulate the ongoing process of
renewing bone. The drug stimulates new bone growth and restores
lost bone mass, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   While drugs such as estrogen slow the breakdown process, A1x1-11
puts the rebuilding process into overdrive, rapidly increasing
density and strength, Roberts said. It appears that A1x1-11 is a
promising new way to attack osteoporosis without the cancer risks
associated with estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   When Glenn returned to space in October, he tested how the new
drug might prevent the bone loss astronauts suffer in zero gravity.
``Potentially, if we can work it out correctly, parathyroid hormone
would be the first of the agents that actually cures the disease of
osteoporosis in the spine,'' Dr. Robert Lindsay of the National
Osteoporosis Foundation told CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw where in September,Sen. Sen. Strom Thurmond became only
the second senator ever to cast 15,000 votes. Who was the first?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was 81-year-old Sen. Robert Byrd (D-W.Va.). He remains
about 140 votes ahead of Thurmond (R-S.C.), who is 96. When
Thurmond hit the 15,000-vote mark, his comment was this: ``I'm
speechless. The quality of the people in this body (the Senate) is
just outstanding, and I wish all of them stay here till they cast
15,000 votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it safe to drink Diet Coke after the expiration date? My
husband says the Nutrasweet in it changes chemically after a
certain time, and it shouldn't be consumed. I say it just loses
some of its fizz. Who is right?
</P>
<P>
   A: If this is a bet, your husband wins, because he's at least
partially correct. The loss of carbonation doesn't figure into it.
The expiration date on diet drinks is mainly to prevent you from
drinking something sweetened with aspartame _ the active ingredient
in Nutrasweet and Equal _ that is no longer sweet, said nutrition
expert Connie Crawley of the University of Georgia Cooperative
Extension Service. When it's stored over time in liquid, aspartame
tends to become unstable and less sweet. This is especially true
when temperatures are high and drinks are stored in a hot warehouse
or kept for long periods in a metal delivery truck. Technically
there's indeed a chemical change, Crawley said, but she added that
she knows of no danger or problem other than ``a poor-tasting
product.''
</P>
<P>
   As always with food concerns, you might want to follow the old
saying: If in doubt, throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
