 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 413 - December 16, 1998   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 413 -- Dec. 16, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. MUCH ADO ABOUT GWYNETH PALTROW Why has Gwyneth Paltrow
reigned as America's It Girl for the last three years? Some might
attribute it to her undeniable style. Others might say it's her
ability to shine in small, unpredictable films, including ``Emma''
and ``Sliding Doors.'' Find out what writer Merle Ginsberg
discovered about Paltrow, who now stars in ``Shakespeare in Love''
in this Q&AMP;A interview. From WWD. 1,500 words + photos.
________________________________________________________ 2. ROCK
'N' GREED The Rolling Stones are charging up to $300 a ticket for
their upcoming arena tour - a gesture that has made them the new
poster boys for the runaway greed that is infecting the music
industry and changing its very fabric. By Steve Morse. From The
Boston Globe. 2,000 words. 3. A YOUNG TAKE ON OLD MEN Kirk Jones,
first-time feature-film writer and director, did not set out to
make a movie about old men. But when you come up with two lead
actors whose combined age is over 150 years, you have not made the
ordinary narcissistic about-my-life First Film. His comedy,
``Waking Ned Devine,'' was a quiet hit at Cannes earlier this year.
It is about an Irish wake -- but really about the human condition,
with the emphasis on geriatric imperatives. By M.R. Montgomery.
From The Boston Globe. 1,400 words. 4. BRENDA BLETHYNB FINDS HER
'VOICE' Brenda Blethyn seemed to come out of nowhere in 1996 to win
an Oscar nomination for her riveting performance in ``Secrets and
Lies.'' In fact, she had been working steadily in England as a
popular star of stage, screen and TV. Blethyn shows a very
different but no less remarkable side in ``Litle Voice,'' playing
the boozy, fast-talking mother of a strangely gifted daughter.
Blethyn had worked for 10 years in an office before turning to
acting. ``I didn't think acting was a reasonable profession,'' she
says. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,100 words. 5. JOHN TRAVOLTA'S
'CIVIL' WAR FOR RESPECT If ``A Civil Action'' wins John Travolta
the Oscar that many are predicting, it will cap his remarkable
comeback. Now he is rich, famous, happily married and the father of
an adored son. In this interview he talks about the new film, the
challenge of playing a cynical, detached, arrogant and insensitive
lawyer in his most serious film in years, why he candidly admits he
would love to win an Oscar for the role and how he views his
controversial Scientology religion. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words
+ photo. 6. MAYA ANGELOU : A NEW ROAD LEADS 'DOWN IN THE DELTA'
Maya Angelou earned fame as a poet, but she's also a playwright,
teacher, mother, actress and civil-rights advocate - and now a film
director. Making her improbable debut at age 70, Angelou has
directed ``Down in the Delta,'' a subtle family drama which is
earning glowing reviews. In this interview she talks about the new
film, why she chose to direct a story written by someone else, why
she wanted to direct a film now and why, aging aside, she's still
enthralled by every opportunity for new experiences. By Ian
Spelling. 1,400 words + photo. 7. HAS GUS VAN SANT GONE PSYCHO?
When the director of ``Drugstore Cowboy'' and ``My Own Private
Idaho'' announced his shot-by-shot remake of the Hitchcock classic
thriller ``Psycho,'' cinephiles screamed sellout. But it may be Gus
Van Sant's most experimental film yet. By R.J. Smith. From The New
York Times Magazine. Full-length (3,000 words) + edited article
available.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
DODGING THE DETECTORS Engineers in Britain who have spent the past
two years developing a hand-held device to detect illicit TV sets
will soon be overtaken by changing technology. While their detector
is great at spotting the radio frequencies emitted by the
cathode-ray tubes used in conventional sets, it is blind to the new
flat-panel displays. By Barry Fox. From New Scientist magazine.
(N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand.) 400 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
BURT BEHIND BARS It seems a long time ago that Burt Reynolds was
associated mainly with stories about a messy divorce, financial
entanglements and allegations of failing health. In this interview
Reynolds talks about his renewed career, past hits, why he doesn't
consider himself to be engaged in a comeback and why he owes his
entire career to two people : Actress Joanne Woodward and a
literature teacher named Watson Duncan. By Jean Oppenheimer. 1,400
words + photo. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
33.1.47.42.18.81
</P>
