<P>
   &UR; A MAGGOT FOR THE PROSECUTION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JESSICA SNYDER SACHS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Insects can help solve murders, but their testimony is being
attacked in the courts. Forensic entomologists say their science
offers the most reliable way of determining the time of death at a
crime scene, short of an eyewitness. Insects populate the human
corpse _ or any carcass _ in predictable waves over the course of
weeks. An entomologist must then knit together the arrival and
departure of several kinds of insects that visit the body in a more
or less orderly succession. Jessica Snyder Sachs, a former editor
of Science Digest who is based in the Atlanta area, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-A-MAGGOT'S-TESTIMONY-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DRUGS AND BUGS ON YOUR BUCK &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By PATRICIA GADSBY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A recent study at the University of California at San Francisco
cultured 113 examples of cash. Most grew harmless organisms, but 18
percent of coins and 7 percent of notes had some less friendly
bacteria on them, including the odd colony of Escherichia coli and
the potential pathogen S. aureus. So Mom was right when she would
yell, ``Don't put that in your mouth. You don't know where it's
been.'' Patricia Gadsby, a contributing editor of Discover
magazine, reports on how bugs, drugs and grime hitch a ride on the
back of every buck.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-DIRTY-MONEY-SCIENCE-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROBING THE PAST &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHY A. SVITIL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see a time machine, go to room 2677 on the second
floor of the geology building at UCLA. Once you pass into the inner
sanctum, you are faced with a 5-foot-tall, 20-foot-wide piece of
equipment housed in stainless steel. This is the time machine. This
device, however, will not accept human passengers. What goes inside
is a flake of rock. By analyzing the atoms in the rock, this
machine can take you back to the time when the Himalayas arose, or
when life appeared on Earth. Kathy A. Svitil, an associate editor
at Discover magazine, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-UNLOCKING-EARTH'S-HISTORY-NYTSF. Sent to category
codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GIFT OF GAB &LR;  &QL; 
