<HEADER>
A2388 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIRTY-MONEY-SCIENCE-N     12-16 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRTY-MONEY-SCIENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGS AND BUGS ON YOUR BUCK  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: FOUR COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight
delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) at NO EXTRA
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.)  
 &HT;    
 By PATRICIA GADSBY  
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Saint Paul and your mother have always agreed about one thing:
Money is dirty. The peevish apostle worried about what lucre does
to the soul, while your mom worried about what money might do to
your body. Don't put it in your mouth, she'd say, you don't know
where it's been.
</P>
<P>
   You don't, but you can just imagine. Money is used for every
type of commerce, from buying milk at the corner store to
trafficking in sex and drugs. All this trade is rough on money.
</P>
<P>
   Even though paper bills (actually a rugged mix of 75 percent
cotton, 25 percent linen) are made to take abuse (4,000 folds in
each direction), the average U.S. dollar lasts a mere 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Moms the world over have done a fine job of convincing us money
is full of disgusting germs. Oddly, though, studies of bacteria on
money are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972 a study in the Journal of the American Medical
Association cultured bacteria from 200 coins and bills and found
objectionable ones like fecal bacteria and Staphylococcus aureus on
13 percent of coins and 42 percent of notes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 a study published in Infections in Medicine found 3
percent of coins and 11 percent of bills growing bacteria, but only
benign ones, and decided ``our country seems to have cleaned up its
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Both studies used money collected in hospitals. Rigorous
scrubbing by doctors and nurses could leave their hands _ and money
_ exceptionally clean. Maybe differing hygienic practices account
for the studies' disparity.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a study at the University of California at
San Francisco cultured 113 examples of ``real life'' cash. Most
grew harmless organisms, but 18 percent of coins and 7 percent of
notes had some less friendly bacteria on them, including the odd
colony of Escherichia coli and the potential pathogen S. aureus.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, these organisms usually spell trouble only if they
somehow breach the skin in large numbers. You're not likely to get
sick from the few bugs your hands encounter on a coin.
</P>
<P>
   What will be obvious by now is that anything that gets on hands
can get on money. And hands are hardly germ-free.
</P>
<P>
   In general, though, skin resists being colonized or invaded by
foreign bacteria. Its horny outer layer forms an efficient barrier,
its surface is too dry or too acidic for many nonresident species,
and its surface oils contain antimicrobials.
</P>
<P>
   In the mouth, saliva _ our natural mouthwash _ contains
germ-killing enzymes and the antibody immunoglobulin A. Any microbe
that makes it past the skin or the mouth's pink lining must contend
with the body's immune system. And any microbe that's swallowed
faces the acid test of the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   If money has a dirty little secret, it's not bugs but drugs. For
the past decade, there have been sporadic reports that U.S.
currency is hopelessly contaminated with cocaine. Is our money
snowed under?
</P>
<P>
   A study conducted at the Houston Advanced Research Center in
Texas and the Argonne National Laboratory in Illinois examined
currency in Miami, Chicago and Houston and found an overall 70 to
80 percent contamination rate, with single dollar bills more
commonly contaminated than higher denominations.
</P>
<P>
   A recent look at money circulating in northern Illinois,
published this May in the Journal of Forensic Sciences, found even
higher rates: close to 93 percent of the sample, and 100 percent of
$20 bills, tested positive for cocaine. ``In fact, most Americans
handle small amounts of cocaine every day, not as packets sold by
drug dealers but on the dollar bills that line their pockets,''
concluded this study.
</P>
<P>
   How has moola become so amazingly infested with cocaine?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the reason you traffic in drugs is to get money,'' comes
the deadpan reply from a spokesman for the Drug Enforcement
Administration who has worked undercover in narcotics and asked not
to be identified by name. ``When drugs come into the country,
traffickers are going to cut the dope with any number of chemicals.
Open the bags, mix in the cut, repackage in smaller bags, sell to
people who sell on the streets. All the time money's changing
hands. It's hard to keep money and drugs apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that can't be the whole story,'' adds Tom Jourdan, chief
of the materials and devices unit at the Federal Bureau of
Investigation Laboratory in Washington. The going theory, held by
Jourdan and others, is that one bill brushed through a counting
machine in a bank could contaminate a whole stack.
</P>
<P>
   Something in paper money seems to be binding to cocaine almost
like a biological receptor, and Jourdan thinks that something is
ink: ``I've wiped an old bill on white paper, and ink comes off.
The green pigment never really dries, and drugs of abuse get stuck
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine dissolves in almost anything _ water, alcohol, fat. And
it sticks quite nicely to skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean your grandmother in the Midwest is going to be
contaminated by a bill handled by a drug dealer in Chicago?'' asks
David Kidwell, a chemist at the Naval Research Laboratory in
Washington. ``Not very likely. If money's freshly dusted with
cocaine, it will get on you, of course. But once money's been
handled and passed through machines, it's too deeply embedded.''
</P>
<P>
   Simulation studies at Argonne and a ``real life'' test at
Creighton University in Omaha, Nebraska, apparently bear him out.
For the Creighton study, bank tellers were swabbed after a
four-hour shift handling cash. Although cocaine was found on the
cash (even in rural Nebraska), none was transferred to the tellers'
hands.
</P>
<P>
   So money isn't exactly squeaky clean. But it isn't exactly going
to do us in, either. If there's a lesson here, it's that money
reflects whatever activity, and mischief, human hands get up to _
and the activity and occasional mischief of all the microscopic
organisms along for the ride on our skin.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Patricia Gadsby is a contributing editor of Discover
Magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC; 
