<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNLOCKING-EARTH'S-HISTORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBING THE PAST  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: THREE COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight
delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) at NO EXTRA
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.)  
 &HT;    
 By KATHY A. SVITIL  
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   If you want to see a time machine, go to room 2677 on the second
floor of the geology building at UCLA. Once you pass into the inner
sanctum, you are faced with a 5-foot-tall, 20-foot-wide piece of
equipment housed in stainless steel. This is the time machine.
</P>
<P>
   This device, however, will not accept human passengers. What
goes inside is a flake of rock. By analyzing the atoms in the rock,
this machine can take you back to the time when the Himalayas
arose, or when life appeared on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The official name of this place is the National Science
Foundation/Keck Foundation National Ion Microprobe Facility. The
name of the machine is the Cameca 1270.
</P>
<P>
   There are other ion microprobes, but the one at UCLA is by far
the best. They all work by sorting and counting isotopes.
</P>
<P>
   If you remember basic chemistry, you'll recall that isotopes are
the various forms an element can take. Once created, many isotopes
are stable.
</P>
<P>
   Carbon 12 and carbon 13, for example, can be found in our solar
system in the same ratio that they were in when the solar system
formed some 4.5 billion years ago. Living things prefer carbon 12
to carbon 13, so the minerals and fossils that have contained life
always have more, relative to nonliving things, of the lighter
isotope.
</P>
<P>
   Not all isotopes are stable, though. Some will release particles
and metamorphose into entirely different elements, and they do so
at a predictable rate. Some break down after just fractions of a
second; others in quadrillions of years. Isotopes can thus act as
clocks, each working on its own timescale.
</P>
<P>
   But decoding the history written in isotopes is not simple,
because it is sometimes inscribed on mineral crystals only a few
thousandths of an inch across, buried inside younger rock. To
detect them, you need an ion microprobe _ ideally, UCLA's ion
microprobe.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA machine is the brainchild of isotopic chemist Mark
Harrison. It analyzes isotopes by liberating them from the rock
that holds them captive.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers embed the target flake in a one-inch block of resin
and fire a beam of charged atoms, or ions, at the block. When the
beam strikes the sample, some of its momentum is transferred to the
atoms on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them will have enough energy imparted to them that
they'll ionize,'' Harrison says.
</P>
<P>
   These new ions form a cloud, which the microprobe can corral in
a 10,000-volt electric field. The ions can then be sorted by their
charge and by their mass as they pass through a giant magnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heavier ions take a wider path through the magnet because the
magnet is unable to deflect them as much,'' Harrison says.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the ions crash into a detector at the end of the
machine in an orderly ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can just count them,'' Harrison says.
</P>
<P>
   With its four-ton magnet, the Cameca 1270 can distinguish
between molecules that differ in mass by just one part in 8,000,
and analyze specks of mineral less than four-millionths of an inch
across. That sort of precision has led to some exciting
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   For example, geologist Stephen Mojzsis and his Scripps
Institution of Oceanography colleague Gustaf Arrhenius used the
microprobe to look at the ratio of carbon 13 to carbon 12 in
3.85-billion-year-old sedimentary rocks from an island on the
southwest coast of Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   (The oldest previously known sign of life was
3.45-billion-year-old fossils of microbes.)
</P>
<P>
   If Earth had been lifeless 3.85 billion years ago, the crystals
in the rock should have had the same ratio found throughout the
lifeless solar system. But the proportion was actually off by a few
percent _ ``Far and away above anything that is inorganic,''
Mojzsis says.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, scientists have begun to wonder if life also left its
mark on Mars. In 1996, NASA scientists announced that they had
found microscopic fossils and other signs of biological activity in
a Martian meteorite that had landed in Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Leshin, a cosmochemist at UCLA, decided to use the
microprobe to analyze the tiny globules of carbonate inside the
meteorite where these supposed signs of life were. The type of
oxygen isotope that a carbonate incorporates into its structure
depends greatly on temperature.
</P>
<P>
   A carbonate that forms at a relatively cool temperature will be
enriched in oxygen 18 compared with carbonates that form at warmer
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   In NASA's meteorite, Leshin found that the ratio of oxygen 18 to
oxygen 16 varied wildly between different carbonate globules.
Several scenarios could explain the ratios _ none of them very
friendly to life.
</P>
<P>
   Leshin's results now stand as a major question mark to the claim
for life on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The Cameca 1270's sharp focus recently allowed Harrison to put a
new date on the birth of the Himalayas. Scientists had long
believed that the mountain range was built some 19 to 25 million
years ago. Harrison got hold of garnets that had formed in the
intense pressures of the primary fault in the Himalayas. Inside the
garnets were tiny crystals rich in the element thorium, which
decays into lead 208 with clocklike regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Using the ion microprobe, Harrison was able to measure the
thorium and lead in the crystals and was surprised to discover that
they were only 4 to 8 million years old. The Himalayas actually
arose over 10 million years more recently than anyone had thought.
</P>
<P>
   As researchers continue to explore the Cameca 1270's powers,
Harrison believes that the only limit they will encounter won't be
the machine's technical capabilities but the inherent limits in the
isotopes themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get to smaller and smaller domains _ to see
behavior, to see gradients, to see signals that we haven't had
access to before. But because we are looking at such small domains,
with relatively few atoms, we are beginning to run into the
statistical limits of our chronometers,'' Harrison says. ``It's not
a problem now, but in a few years we'll have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ( Kathy A. Svitil is an associate editor at Discover
magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
