<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Dec. 16, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-REPORTER (Undated) _ Journalist Philip True remains
missing after a false alarm that he had been found by a Mexican
Army helicopter. True, 50, is the Mexico City correspondent for the
San Antonio Express-News. Robert Rivard, the editor of the
newspaper, said the Mexican government would resume the search
Wednesday. By The San Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-AFTERMATH (Tipitapa, Nicaragua) _ Residents of this town
still recovering from Hurricane Mitch now spend time in line,
waiting for donations of food and other basic items. Recently, the
Red Cross handed out sacks of rice and oats, along with cooking
oil, a few plastic dishes, toothpaste, toilet paper and soap. By
TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SNOWBIRDS-TEXAS (San Benito, Texas) _ For decades, retired
Canadians and Northeasterners have preferred Miami Beach and
Tucson, Ariz., to Texas' lesser developed Rio Grande Valley. But
Texas tourism boosters are hoping to change that. And one big draw
for the snowbirds is that the valley is cheaper. By JAMES
PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIC-HOME (Rotterdam, N.Y.) _ If you look in the telephone
directory you'll find a listing for Jan P. Mabee. The phone will
ring inside a white farm house he built in 1670. Scott Haefner, the
town historian who lives in and is caretaker of the historic Mabee
house, keeps the Mabee name in the telephone book. By BOB
GARDINIER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STARBUCKS-EXPANDS (San Francisco) _ News that coffee giant
Starbucks is going to buy San Francisco-based Pasqua Coffee has
left a bitter aftertaste in the mouths of many local coffee
connoisseurs. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-ENTERTAINING (Albany, N.Y.) _ The holidays are a festive
time often shared with friends, family, neighbors and colleagues.
One of the most convenient ways to accommodate everybody is to host
an open house. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader wants to know if she should
cut back and fertilize her 20-foot sweet olive. A Q&AMP;A. By KATHY
HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-BOOKS (Undated) _ Snowy nights and Jedi knights. Ancient
heroes and new heroines. Tales retold, reprinted, recited. Cupid
shooting, hamsters counting, dolls dancing. New children's books on
a wild variety of subjects pour into stores this time of year,
enticing, beckoning, pleading. To help guide holiday shoppers
through the maze, we have selected some standouts from hundreds of
newly published works. By JANE P. MARSHALL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOOKSHELF (Undated) _ Looking for a last-minute holiday
gift? Among dozens of new books, some volumes are bound to appeal
to the traveler in your life. A roundup of gift books for young
children. By HARRY SHATTUCK and SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GIFTS (Undated) _ Ten gift ideas for the traveler _ from
gadgets to games, binoculars to magazines. By HARRY SHATTUCK and
SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-BAKING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Although time seems shorter than
an elf during the holidays, some folks are unable to let the season
pass without baking cookies. For those who must bake, here are a
few tips to make the process easier. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS (Undated) _ For interested bystanders who wish to
send any tokens of appreciation or esteem, hint, hint, the address
is Giants Stadium, East Rutherford, N.J., 07073. Cards from the
1972 Miami Dolphins would be nice. Cases of champagne would be
nicer. Not that the New York Giants need any help to get on a good
buzz. Their shocking 20-16 victory against the Denver Broncos was
legally intoxicating. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEADWATERS-FOREST (San Francisco) _ Powerful forces are arrayed
to block a plan to protect thousands of acres of wildlife habitat
in Northern California. This is the moment to look past the banner
waving and the shouting, to assess how much the plan would actually
accomplish for the sake of the environment, and to measure how much
would be lost if the opponents succeed in destroying this effort.
By JOHN CAMPBELL.
</P>
</TEXT>
