<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-EXPERIMENTAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION PROTESTS FAA COMPUTER TEST ON LIVE TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is gambling with safety by
testing a new computer system for controllers on live traffic
before it has been certified, the union representing technicians
who install, repair, and maintain much of the nation's air-traffic
control equipment alleged Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, a new mainframe computer was tested at the New
York en route center, which controls all high-altitude traffic in
southeastern New York, New Jersey, eastern Pennsylvania, and out
into the Atlantic Ocean, without undergoing the battery of safety
and human performance evaluations the FAA usually requires for new
systems, executives of the Professional Airways Systems Specialists
charged.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials acknowledged making the tests, but portrayed the
union's objections as more related to labor issues than safety.
</P>
<P>
   The union insisted its only concern was for safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the agency feels pressured. . .to field a new system
very quickly,'' Tom Brantley, vice president of PASS, said Tuesday,
noting the many ongoing problems with the FAA's antiquated computer
system. ``They turned it on this weekend and used it on live
traffic but they haven't declared it operational and we haven't
certified it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new computer will replace the aging host, or primary,
computer used in the New York Center. The FAA expects the new
system to be operational there Dec. 28. The new computer will also
replace the aging host computer at the Boston Center, in Nashua,
N.H., which has had numerous computer problems this year. The new
system is scheduled to begin operating there on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   There are 21 so-called en route centers around the country.
Centers in Los Angeles, Minneapolis, and Oakland are also expected
to get the new computer early next year. PASS officials said if
there are major glitches in the new computer, they may not be
discovered until it is operating in many of the en route centers
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   An FAA spokesman in Washington said officials are meeting
regularly with PASS to negotiate a settlement to the issues the
union has raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the current contract, we are required to negotiate any
changes in working conditions, and the new computer system is a
change in working conditions,'' said FAA spokesman William A.
Shumann. ``At the same time, we are simultaneously and separately
negotiating a new contract with PASS.''
</P>
<P>
   Brantley, however, said the issue is one of safety, not labor
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried very hard to keep anything to do with contract
negotiations from spilling over into the (air-traffic control)
modernization area,'' he said. ``That is one of the reasons why we
have liaisons on these work groups to informally address issues as
they come up. To be honest, there are labor issues here that we
have not brought up. They put in a new system without negotiating,
which is an unfair labor practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, before a new system is introduced, it undergoes human
performance and safety evaluations, which can result in design and
operating changes. For example, the replacement system for
controllers who work airplanes in the congested airspaces around
major airports underwent such a review, and 98 changes _ more than
50 of them requested by PASS _ are currently being instituted. It
is unclear if the changes will affect the installation of that
system, scheduled for March 1999 at Washington's Ronald Reagan
National Airport.
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues the union identified regarding the new
comptuer is there is no audible alarm if a failure occurs. As a
result, the FAA has hooked up a modem to ring a telephone if the
system fails. That jury-rigged solution, PASS contends, could
result in false alarms if a wrong number is dialed, or someone not
familiar with the importance of the telephone, picking it up.
</P>
<P>
   Brantley said he would be reluctant to fly through New York
airspace if the new system is continued to be used without its
first being tested off-line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The existing host computer, as obsolete as it is, I know it
works,'' he said. ``Odds are, if this new system fails, they will
go to the back up and nothing (bad) would happen. The odds are with
them, the odds are pretty good that you will come out okay. But
most of us don't like to gamble when we fly.''
</P>
<P>
   The replacement computers, which will cost about $85 million
systemwide, will not be maintained by PASS technicians. Instead,
the FAA has contracted with IBM to maintain them.
</P>
<P>
   PASS must still certify the new computers.
</P>
<P>
   Mike DePalma, the New York Center local president of the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association, said testing the new
host computer went fine this weekend with no glitches. He said
controllers desperately need the new computer in order to begin
training on a replacement of the radar display system they use.
</P>
<P>
   He was distressed, however, that PASS representatives will not
be maintaining the new computer system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work traffic and I worked a sector recently and the radar
failed. A technician was there in 30 seconds,'' DePalma said. ``If
the agency is planning on contracting out this work, I don't want
to be sitting here waiting an hour for a technician to arrive.
Contracting out the work is dangerous and reckless.''
</P>
</TEXT>
