<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2468 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WOMEN-BOS &LR;      12-16 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON CHIDES FEMINISTS FOR CLINTON SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Asserting that their ``inconsistency is amazing,''
House Speaker-elect Robert L. Livingston told a group of feminist
leaders Tuesday they are undermining the women's rights movement by
opposing impeachment and being ``strident'' in support of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that feminism is championing this particular
cause?'' Livingston asked a group that included feminist icons
Betty Friedan and Eleanor Smeal. ``If (former GOP Senator) Bob
Packwood had been caught in similar circumstances with a young
intern under his control, you would have had his head.''
</P>
<P>
   When the women angrily denied they have a double standard for
Democrats and said impeachment is too strong a punishment for
Clinton, Livingston declared that President Nixon faced
impeachment, and resigned, for a lesser offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Nixon's crime was covering up a crime he did not
commit,'' Livingston said. ``Clinton is covering up a crime he did
commit, and that is a large difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary exchange occurred in an impromptu session in
Livingston's Capitol Hill office. The women's rights leaders
requested, and unexpectedly got, the meeting after they held a news
conference decrying this week's expected impeachment votes as a
Republican attempt to undo the will of women, who
disproportionately voted for Clinton in 1996 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to think you do not represent all women in your very
strident views on behalf of the president,'' Livingston told the 20
women seated in his office, as he stood behind his desk.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker-elect related how his mother, divorced and left with
two young children, worked as a secretary in New Orleans in the
long days before Friedan's ``Feminine Mystique'' was published.
``She never ran the office, but she raised us and nurtured us and
got the job done,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother has better feminist credentials than half of the
people in this room,'' he added, ``and she believes Clinton ought
to be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, many of the women said they were shocked and
upset at what they viewed as Livingston's confrontational style and
condescending remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a founder of the women's movement, I would say that he was
very insulting,'' Friedan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His tone was disrespectful,'' said Smeal, president of the
Feminist Majority Foundation, ``and we're troubled and saddened by
his response.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston flatly rejected the women's appeal that the House
consider a censure resolution as a substitute for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our belief is censure is not envisioned by the Constitution in
the US House,'' said Livingston, adding that he intends to vote for
``two, and possibly more'' articles of impeachment. ``Censure will
be an option in the Senate. Censure is a penalty. Expulsion is a
penalty. Those are issues the Senate will have to determine after
we vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker-elect stopped short of calling for Clinton's
resignation, as some of his GOP colleagues have done, but he called
Vice President Al Gore ``fully capable'' of stepping in if Clinton
steps down.
</P>
<P>
   During their news conference, which included activists in labor
unions and civil rights groups as well as leaders of the National
Organization for Women and the National Women's Political Caucus,
the women said a Senate trial would create turmoil in Congress and
block progress on issues important to women, such as education,
child care, and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that after a majority of women said in exit polls
in November that they don't want this to happen, a Congress that is
12 percent female reverses the election of a president who stands
with women and stands for their issues,'' Smeal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are suddenly born-again on sexual harassment after
they have voted again and again against women's rights, from
abortion to pay equity,'' Smeal added. ``We are not fooled by their
hypocritical actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's rights groups have been called hypocritical for having
little to say about Paula Jones's sexual harassment lawsuit against
Clinton when they were very vocal in calling on Packwood to step
down in 1995 when allegations of sexual misconduct were made
against him. During the fall campaigns, several Democratic women
candidates who rode a feminist tide in 1992 in the wake of sexual
harassment allegations against Supreme Court nominee Clarence
Thomas had to answer for defending the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your inconsistency is amazing,'' Livingston told the women.
``You stand by the condemnation of Bob Packwood but not the
president? By championing his cause, the cause of feminism and the
integrity of your movement is severely jeopardized.''
</P>
<P>
   Feminist leaders say they abhor the president's behavior with
former intern Monica S. Lewinsky, but they don't believe that
either his sexual misconduct or his misleading the public about it
are impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if he did what he's alleged to have done, what is the big
deal?'' Friedan asked. ``It's not a matter of public concern. To
have our will overthrown by a bunch of dirty old white men, trying
to use sexual issues wrongly ... this is a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedan said she was ``seriously considering'' calling a women's
protest march on Washington if the House votes to impeach Clinton.
Tuesday, the feminist activists staged their own mini-march on
Capitol Hill, traveling from House office to House office, first
seeing Livingston, then Representative Maxine Waters, a California
Democrat, and finally Democratic Minority Leader Richard Gephardt
of Missouri. Most of the time, they were followed by press cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he would provide a ``short list'' of undecided
Republicans and urged the women to personally press the case for
censure with them. ``You are doing the very right thing,'' Gephardt
told them.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the personal visits, the women said, was because
it was so hard to reach members over the jammed Capitol Hill phone
lines. They said the majority of Americans were telling lawmakers
what the polls have long showed: They don't want Clinton impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston responded that he was not elected by the polls, but
by people who expect him to use his judgment. ``I like the guy, I
think he's nice,'' Livingston said of Clinton, ``but I believe what
he said in his deposition and before the grand jury is perjury, and
perjury is a felony, punishable by five years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies, when the history books are written, you will have to
tell your grandchildren why you were defending a president who
lied,'' Livingston said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 1117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
