A2483 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-APPLE-SFCHRON &LR;      12-16 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Apple Preps Laptop Version of iMac  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple Computer is readying a low-cost laptop version of its
popular iMac in an all-out bid for consumer sales, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The new portable _reportedly called WebMate _ is translucent
plastic, like its desktop forebear, and comes with a lightning-fast
microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   One insider described several prototypes of the lightweight
portable, including a ``spiffy'' curved model with 300 MHz
processor, built-in modem, Ethernet connections and universal
serial bus for connecting to printers, scanners and other devices.
Although a price has not been set, it is expected to be competitive
with the inexpensive $1,500 laptopson the market, one source said.
</P>
<P>
   The WebMate is due in the first half of 1999 but could be sneak
previewed at next month's Macworld Expo computer trade show at
Moscone Center, sources said. (During a speech to educators
yesterday in Seattle, interim Apple CEO Steve Jobs said a new
consumer portable will be shown later in the year, not at
Macworld.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an aggressive attempt by Apple to drive a stake in the
ground for the consumer market,'' said Matthew Rothenberg, content
director at MacWEEK.com in San Francisco, which has been tracking
Apple's new products. ``The iMac has kicked ass in the desktop
consumer market, and Apple intends to do the same with its new
laptop.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple sold 278,000 of its curvy aquamarine iMac machines in the
six weeks following its August debut, and industry observers
estimate that as many as 800,000 units will ship this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some are calling WebMate, code-named P1, the technologic
successor to the defunct eMate, a four-pound, $600 clamshell-shaped
computer that was well received by students and educators but
discontinued as part of Apple's cost-cutting measures. Unlike the
eMate, which used Apple's Newton operating system, WebMate is
expected to run the Macintosh operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The new notebook would round out Apple's personal computer line.
The PowerMac and PowerBook anchor the company's business offerings,
while the iMac is a desktop PC for consumers. All three models have
sold well, triggering a financial turnaround that has vaulted Apple
from fiscal despair to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Apple is tinkering with a ``palmtop'' computer
project that would resurrect elements of the ill-fated Newton
MessagePad, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   That project, called MacMate, would come with either the Mac OS
or much-rumored Mac OS Lite _ a graphical-user interface designed
for palmtop devices _ and provide wireless connections to the
WebMate, iMac, PowerBook and other Macs. It reportedly would
include software for connecting to both Mac and Windows machines.
</P>
<P>
   MacMate, which probably will not debut until late 1999,
allegedly was spotted at a meeting of the Hong Kong Newton Users
Group earlier this year. Oracle CEO Larry Ellison, an Apple board
member, has publicly hinted about an upcoming $500 handheld Mac.
MacMate is the likeliest candidate to fulfill that description,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has maintained the semblance of a handheld project despite
shutting down its Newton division in February. At the time, the
company said it was ``committed'' to a Mac-based portable,
beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Apple also could conceivably strike a deal to develop a hybrid
of 3Com Corp.'s popular PalmPilot device, or sign a co-marketing
agreement with 3Com, sources said. In a recent interview in
Fortune, Jobs said Apple attempted to acquire 3Com's Palm Computing
division.
</P>
<P>
   The new consumer Macintosh models are expected to help stoke a
remarkable comeback at Apple by further boosting its lot in the
home market. Until recently, it had squandered market share with
consumers because, as Jobs has repeatedly said, the company didn't
build sufficiently compelling products.
</P>
<P>
   The number of consumers who bought Macs plunged to 4.3 percent
last year from 11.2 percent in 1995, according to ZD Market
Intelligence. That total, however, is on the upswing with iMac
sales, said analyst Matt Sargent.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company _ which hemorrhaged $1.8 billion in 1995,
1996 and part of last year _ has now registered four-straight
money-making quarters and is expected to finish in the black for
its first quarter, ending December 25.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has relied on a streamlined product strategy and
aggressive cost cutting to reverse its flagging fortunes. The iMac
has been a runaway hit, topping the best-seller list at computer
superstores, according to ZD Market Intelligence in La Jolla (San
Diego County).
</P>
<P>
   An Apple spokeswoman declined to comment on the rumored
machines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-09-98 2145EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
