<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK SMALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're working up a gearhead's gift list, think small. There
are a lot of cute little tech devices on the market in time for
Christmas. These lightweight gadgets will fit nicely in a stocking
or a shirt pocket, while being powerful enough to tempt many
business travelers to leave the laptop at home.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Electronics has freshened up an old favorite, the Rex
shirt-pocket databank. I wrote about the original version about a
year ago, when it accompanied me to the Comdex computer show in Las
Vegas. With a Rex, I had all my phone numbers, e-mail addresses,
and appointments stored in a device about as thick as three credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Rex was touted as an alternative to the larger and more
expensive 3Com Palm Pilot. But the Palm Pilot lets you punch in new
information by touching the screen with a pen. To add new names or
memos to the Rex, you had to plug it into a full-fledged computer.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Rex Pro features a clever system for scheduling new
appointments or typing in contact data. You just use the six tiny
buttons along the right edge of the device.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing the data input button on the Rex Pro opens a menu of
tasks. Say you want a reminder to call somebody. Click the ``To
Do'' command, which opens yet another menu. Click ``Call.'' Still
another menu appears, and so on. If the person you want to call is
already in the Rex address book, it takes just a few clicks to
create your appointment. The Rex even beeps to remind you.
</P>
<P>
   What if the name isn't in the address book? With the old Rex,
you'd be out of luck. But the new version can display a menu of
letters and numbers, and will let you type in new data.
</P>
<P>
   The Rex Pro lists for $239, but CompUSA sells it on the Net for
$199.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the Rex was a reliable gadget, but I had my doubts about
another trinket that recently slid over my transom. I think it was
the suction cup that worried me. It's tucked away on the underside
of the JVC HC-E100 Portable E-Mail Device, and it brought back
memories of computing in the Jurassic era.
</P>
<P>
   Before RJ-11 phone jacks became commonplace, people connected
computers to phone lines with acoustic couplers _ big rubber
suction cups that you wrapped around the mouthpiece and earpiece of
a standard telephone. The portable kind, long used by journalists,
were heavy, bulky, and unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   So why is somebody making a device that uses an acoustic coupler
to check e-mail? Because it'll work with practically any phone on
earth. And because JVC uses one that's simple and lightweight. Just
dial an 800 number to reach the PocketMail e-mail service, then
press the JVC device against the phone receiver. Your e-mail is
quickly loaded into a box slightly larger than a Walkman. If you
can stand the cramped keyboard, you can pound out a reply.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the JVC e-mail device against the phone is clumsy, but
unless you've got hundreds of messages, you'll be done in a couple
of minutes. For maximum speed, you can download only the title of
each message. Then you can look them over and dial up again to get
just the messages that matter. The devices even send faxes, for 25
cents per page inside the United States and $1 everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't try the JVC device with a cell phone. PocketScience
says it'll work with analog phones, but not the new digital ones,
including PCS phones. They're working on upgraded software to solve
that problem.
</P>
<P>
   PocketMail provides you with an e-mail account, but the service
can also check three outside mailboxes, including your company
e-mail box or even your America Online account. But for some odd
reason, PocketMail only checks these other mailboxes once an hour,
rather than doing it whenever the customer dials in. So if someone
sends you mail one minute after PocketMail's hourly update, you'll
wait 59 minutes to see it. Anybody willing to wait that long
doesn't need PocketMail.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is an impressive gadget _ and cheap. At the
PocketMail site (http://www.pocketmail.com) you can order the JVC
e-mail device for $100. Then you pay $99.95 a year or $9.95 a month
for a PocketMail e-mail account. Then you can place it under the
Christmas tree and win the eternal gratitude of some poor
laptop-lugger who hasn't walked upright through an airport since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-10-98 1322EST &QL;
</P>
