<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2495 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-FOR-KID     12-16 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-FOR-KIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR IBM, YOU'RE NEVER TOO YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would you pay $2,300 for a home computer, when you can easily
buy two for that price?
</P>
<P>
   The computer is made by IBM Corp, not some maker of cut-rate
clones. It's got an Intel microprocessor, a big hard drive and lots
of memory. And not only does the system include a color monitor,
IBM throws in a computer desk and chair, ergonomically designed for
comfort and easy operation.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like a deal? Okay, but there is a catch. The IBM Young
Explorer computer isn't for Mom or Dad or even Big Sister. This
pricey new computer was designed in cooperation with Little Tykes
Co., the popular maker of toy furniture for toddlers, and is
intended for children aged 4 through 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Young Explorer isn't a family computer _ it's a kid's
computer, with every feature tailored to a preschooler's idea of
comfort. IBM says it's the first machine of its kind, created for
use in day care centers. But when hundreds of parents began asking
where they could buy one to use at home, IBM executive Michele
Riggs decided it was time to take a gamble, and begin selling Young
Explorer at retail.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs thinks Young Explorer is the product many American
children and their parents have been waiting for. ``We are
responsible for insuring that our kids have the right tools so they
can learn for the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs herself is a mother of two. Her official title _ ``market
segment manager for moms and dads with kids at home'' _ shows how
far IBM has moved from its blue-suited Fortune 500 past in an
effort to tap the massive consumer technology market.
</P>
<P>
   The Young Explorer isn't your typical desktop computer. Indeed,
it's an entire desk. A 14-inch color monitor peeks out of a tough
plastic housing, and the keyboard is a part of the desk itself.
Unlike standard keyboards that can easily be ruined by spilled milk
and cookie crumbs, the Young Explorer uses a membrane-type keyboard
permanently sealed under thick plastic.
</P>
<P>
   The tough but friendly design was tailored to the needs of Young
Explorer's original target market _ schools and day care centers,
where the machines would regularly receive harsh treatment from
dozens of very low-tech children. Field testing even led IBM and
Little Tykes to modify the plastic seat, when they found that
toddlers view computing as a social activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it a bench so it can accomodate two kids,'' Riggs
said. And instead of a modem for dialing onto the Internet, each
unit comes with a built-in Ethernet adapter, for connection to a
school's internal computer network.
</P>
<P>
   The Young Explorer has been available since April to schools and
day care centers, but IBM executives soon got word that teachers
and kids weren't the only ones who liked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we rolled this product out, we were getting unbelievable
calls from parents saying, `We want this product. I'll write you a
check right now.' '' The same thing happened this fall, when a
Young Explorer unit was exhibited for two weeks at the Oklahoma
State Fair.
</P>
<P>
   IBM decided to begin selling the Young Explorer at retail this
week. ``We are responding to our customers,'' said Riggs.
</P>
<P>
   But it is far too early to know whether all the tirekickers will
really break out their checkbooks for computer, which is available
by mail order directly from IBM and from Little Tykes.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based children's software expert Cathy Miranker
thinks the Young Explorer is fine for schools and day care centers.
But she's skeptical about its value in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you happen to have septuplets or something, you probably
want some special computer equipment,'' said Miranker, author of
Great Software for Kids and Parents, part of the popular ``For
Dummies'' book series. ``But I don't see any pressing need for this
kind of equipment, other than its physical charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Miranker said that most households could make do with a cheaper
standard computer equipped with a special kiddie keyboard and
mouse. ``Kids are very adaptable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Miranker fears that parents who have just parted
with $2,300 may try to get their money's worth by encouraging small
children to spend too much time on the machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm opposed to their parking their kids in front of the
computer the same way parents park their kids in front of the TV,''
Miranker said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Riggs said she doesn't want that to happen either.
``Nothing, absolutely nothing, should be used as a babysitting
tool,'' she warned. The Young Explorer isn't supposed to be a
substitute for ``Rugrats'' reruns, but a high-tech head start for
curious kids and ambitious parents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-10-98 1319EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
