<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Changing Default Font In Word 97  
 By David Einstein   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  Is there some way to change the default setting for
Word 97 from Times New Roman 10 to Times New Roman 12? I am getting
tired of reformatting my letters after they are done.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  I don't know why Microsoft uses 10-point type as the
default in Word. It's too small on the screen, and it's too small
when you print it out. Anyway, there's an easy remedy to the
situation. Go into the Format menu in Word and choose Font. Select
the font you want (in this case, Times New Roman 12), and click on
the Default button at the bottom of the window. From that point on,
all new documents will default to your chosen font.
</P>
<P>
   Copying to Another Drive
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to copy all the files from my old hard drive on
a Windows 95 computer to my new computer, which has Windows 98. I
am trying to avoid having to reinstall all my applications on the
new computer. Is there a smart way to do this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It can be done, but not easily. You'll need a program such as
DriveCopy from PowerQuest ($30), which can copy the contents of one
hard drive to another. And you'll have to remove the hard drive
from the new computer and connect it to the old one, which entails
opening up both cases and messing with cables and power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I don't think it's possible to copy applications without
also copying the operating system, which means you'd be
transferring Windows 95 to your new hard drive. You could then use
the Windows 98 disc that came with your new computer to upgrade the
hard drive to Windows 98. But that seems like an awful lot of work
just to transfer your applications and documents.
</P>
<P>
   The more practical approach is simply to reinstall your
applications on the new computer and copy your document files from
the old computer to the new one using a floppy disk or a Zip drive.
</P>
<P>
   Refurbished Computers
</P>
<P>
   Q: I occasionally see ads for refurbished/reconditioned
computers from major vendors. These often are near top-of-the-line
models, selling for a significant discount. Often, warranties are
provided. Are these PCs likely to be good deals, or are there
pitfalls a consumer should know about?
</P>
<P>
   A: Assuming that you can get the specifications you want _ chip
speed, memory, hard drive capacity, etc. _ a used or refurbished
computer can be a great deal. The components most susceptible to
failure are the hard drive and the CD-ROM drive, and the monitor
also could be a problem, especially if it's a few years old. But if
you get a warranty on those parts, there's little risk.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing to consider is expandability. If you think you
might want to add a new video or sound card, make sure the computer
has enough PCI expansion slots.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the issue of software. A good vendor will include
Windows 98 and a bundle of programs such as Microsoft Works, so you
won't have to fork over big bucks for a new set of applications.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the Question
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there some way that I can print out the address book in
the Netscape e-mail program? A copy would be handy to have while
traveling.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're in luck. The latest upgrade of Netscape Communicator,
version 4.5, lets you do just that. With your address book open,
choose Select All from the Edit menu. Then choose Export from the
file menu. You can save the list in the Netscape format or in
formats that can be printed from a word processor or spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AOL UPDATE: &LR;  A couple of weeks ago, I outlined a way to control
cookies using AOL 4.0. There's a catch, however _ you also must
have Internet Explorer 5.0 on your PC. AOL has a built-in version
of IE, which doesn't let you block cookies. But if you also have IE
5.0 installed, the AOL program will utilize some of the options of
the latest Microsoft browser _ including cookie control. You can
download the Beta of IE 5 for free from www.microsoft.com/ie.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to get around AOL's cookie conundrum is to use any
version of IE or Netscape Navigator instead of AOL's browser. After
connecting to AOL, simply start your other browser (after adjusting
its settings for cookie control).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Here's a cool way to get on the Web fast from the Windows 98
desktop. Right-click on any blank area of your taskbar (that's the
bar that runs along the bottom of the screen). Point to Toolbars
and choose Address. An address space will be displayed on the
taskbar every time Windows is running. Type an Internet address
into the space, hit Enter, and the Internet Explorer browser will
open automatically.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
