<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-PRODUCTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING GIFTS _ AND SOME SECURITY _ ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This Christmas, you could probably do all your shopping from
home. The Internet gold rush has driven thousands of merchants onto
the Web, selling everything from jewelry to automobiles. Now the
big problem is finding what you want, and a trustworthy merchant to
buy it from.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most secure place for electronic shopping is the
America Online computer network. AOL runs its own shopping mall,
open only to subscribers to the service. Many of the merchants
doing business on AOL are well-known outfits like Walt Disney Co.,
L.L. Bean and Macy's. Many also run major shopping sites on the
public Internet, so you needn't be an AOL subscriber to deal with
them. But as the saying goes, membership has its privileges.
</P>
<P>
   AOL pledges total safety and satisfaction to customers who
purchase merchandise at its on-line mall. All merchants must use
the latest digital security systems to make sure customer data
can't be swiped by hackers. The threat of having one's credit card
number intercepted by data thieves has been wildly exaggerated. But
to reassure customers, AOL promises to reimburse shoppers if their
credit card data falls into the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, all stores at the AOL site must respect their
customers' privacy and guarantee their satisfaction. AOL itself
promises to reimburse customers if the guarantee isn't met by the
merchant .
</P>
<P>
   About 14 million people are AOL members. What about the rest of
us? We can find similar on-line shopping centers at the popular
portal sites. These sites began life as search engines, listing
millions of interesting Internet pages. Now, in order to attract a
constant stream of traffic, they offer many other services,
including listings of retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these are companies that have paid for a spot on, say,
the Yahoo shopping site. Unlike AOL, Yahoo offers virtually no
assurance that one of its stores is a good place to shop. ``There's
not a universal set of protections that apply to every single
store,'' said Yahoo director of brand management Karen Edwards. The
company will offer refunds to disgruntled shoppers on a
case-by-case basis, and spokesman Tim Brady said that Yahoo will
rid itself of bad apples. So far, he added, it hasn't been
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Excite Web site offers somewhat more consumer protection
through its Certified Merchants program. These are on-line stores
that have to meet fairly rigorous customer service standards. But
not every store listed at the Excite shopping mall is certified,
and it took a little hunting to find a list of the certified
merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Most uncertified stores are run by honest merchants, so don't
write them off. Preston Gralla , author of ``The Complete Idiot's
Guide to Online Shopping,'' says you can take steps to protect
yourself. ``Check for warranty and return policies,'' he urges.
Responsible merchants will generally display them prominently at
the site. ``If there's no warranty and return policy posted, I
wouldn't shop at the site.''
</P>
<P>
   Also beware of sites that don't display the address and phone
number of the company. ``If a site isn't willing to post that kind
of information, I wouldn't want to do business with them,'' said
Gralla.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Internet credit card theft is highly unlikely,
reputable firms will use a secure transaction system for extra
protection. Your browser will display a message when you connect to
a secured shopping area on the `Net, and the ``http'' at the
beginning of the Web address will turn into ``https.`` If this
doesn't happen, shop elsewhere. These days, the Internet has plenty
of alternatives to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-09-98 1413EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
