<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE15-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Sites ready to indulge taste for the offbeat 
By Bill Husted  
c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The trouble with the Internet these days is that it's
so danged practical.
</P>
<P>
   If you're heading for a picnic on Saturday, you can check out
the weather at the Weather Channel at http://www.weather.com. Then
you can drop in at
</P>
<P>
   http://members.xoom.com/KountryCook/sofryck.htm to get a recipe
for the fried chicken you want to bring.
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good, but the real fun of the Web used to be
exploring pages that were totally useless but loads of fun. There
are only so many chuckles in a forecast that tells you it'll be
partly cloudy on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   So today, we'll take a break from the real world and check out
some sites that are just plain fun.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with a site that may actually be useful. It's called
Roadside America and calls itself a guide to offbeat vacation
attractions. You'll find the home page at
http://www.roadsideamerica.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've visited the page, you'll know things your friends
and co-workers do not. For instance, you'll discover on the east
side of Baltimore, in the restaurant known as Hausner's, ``there is
a huge ball of string in one of the off-rooms. Visitors to the
restaurant can't see the ball of string unless they go in search of
the restroom and make a wrong turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, in case you ever visit the little town of Norton, Kan., the
page will tell you about a ``picture gallery in the First State
Bank, with pictures of all the men who have run for president and
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that we have your next vacation planned, let's give you
reason to celebrate. If you love holidays and find Christmas,
Hanukkah and New Year's Eve aren't enough to fill your appetite,
then there is good news for you.
</P>
<P>
   Set your browser for
</P>
<P>
   http://www.jpmorgan.com/cgi-bin/HolidayCalendar and you'll find
yourself at the J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. page devoted to holidays around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Just take any date and use the pull-down menu to set the Web
page to find the holidays for that date. You'll learn, for
instance, that tomorrow (Dec. 14) is a Russian holiday,
Constitution Day. You can also use the pull-down menus to look at
holidays specific to other countries. That way you can learn that,
in Botswana, Dec. 26, is Boxing Day.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want to waste some time, and find some surprises,
try WebCrawler Web Roulette. Just go to
http://www.webcrawler.com/cgi-bin/random and you'll be presented
with links to 10 Web pages selected at random. (Parents should keep
in mind the pages are randomly selected and the possibility exists
of being presented with material of an adult nature).
</P>
<P>
   Next let's take a look at a page called Stupid People, Crime and
Current Events at http://www.mindspring.com/(tilde)iam392/. It is
very much as it sounds, a collection of news stories about crimes
committed by stupid people. For instance, you'll learn about the
Nevada robber who let a convenience store clerk make one phone call
during a hold-up, then seemed surprised when police showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you really don't have a life at all, you may be
interested in a page devoted to people who collect the toys given
away at fast-food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the page at
http://www.netcore.ca/(tilde)gkillops/toys.html. If you have a
pantry full of Batman glasses, you'll feel right at home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-14-98 1012EST &QL;
</P>
