<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's a Web site in which Fido can delight
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've checked your Christmas list not twice but at least half a
dozen times. You think you've covered all the people you want to
buy presents for and also the ones you have to buy presents for.
</P>
<P>
   But is it possible that you've overlooked the most deserving
friend of all? The individual whose steadfast love and support has
never wavered _ not once _ no matter what? Even if he did drool
over your cashmere jacket or chew the claw feet off an heirloom
table, Christmas is a good time to return some of that
unconditional love your pooch shows you all year.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you could go to a canine Toys ``R'' Us and bring home
something plastic. But what about whipping up some doggie treats in
the kitchen to show you really care? It's fun and easier than you
think.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet offers at least one excellent site with an
abundance of recipes and information about homemade doggie treats.
At http://pages.prodigy.com
</P>
<P>
   /pomathon/pomtreat.htm, you'll find a host of surprisingly easy
and tasty-sounding recipes for treats using bacon, beef, cheese,
chicken, garlic, liver, nuts, vegetables and whole grains. There
also are recipes for party mix, and if you've ever wondered what
those treats are that trainers use to get dogs to do whatever they
want, there's a recipe there for dog handler show bait, too.
</P>
<P>
   Another site to check out ``when store-bought just isn't good
enough'' is
http://ionet.net/(tilde)rkcathey/goldenbone/dogbisc.htm, which
contains a rather festive recipe for peanut butter dog biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   DOG TREAT
</P>
<P>
   Idgie's Peanut
</P>
<P>
   Butter Dog Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 32
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peanut butter (sugar free; smooth or chunky)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a mixing bowl, combine wheat and
soy flours, baking powder and salt. In a separate bowl, whisk
together peanut butter and milk until well-combined and smooth.
Fold peanut butter mixture into dry ingredients and mix well to a
soft dough. Turn out dough onto lightly floured surface; knead
lightly. Roll dough out to 3/8 inch thick and into a 9-by-12-inch
rectangle; cut into 1 1/2-by-2-inch pieces. Place 1/2 inch apart on
ungreased baking sheets. Bake 15 minutes or until lightly browned.
Store cooled biscuits in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Per biscuit: 77 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 55), 7 grams carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 109 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber. DOG TREAT
</P>
<P>
   Bacon Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 34
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   5 cups whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons vegetable oil or bacon fat
</P>
<P>
   Pinch onion powder or garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In large bowl, mix flour, milk,
eggs, oil, onion or garlic powder, salt and water. Pinch off pieces
of the dough and roll into 2-inch balls. Place on greased cookie
sheet. Bake for 35 to 40 minutes. Cool and store in an airtight
container. _ From the Humane Society of Santa Clara County, Santa
Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Per biscuit: 104 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 43), 13 grams carbohydrates, 13 milligrams
cholesterol, 78 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DOG TREAT
</P>
<P>
   Fido's Favorite Cheese-Flavored Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 42 large (3 1/2-to-4-inch bone-shaped) or 72 small
biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons chicken- or beef-flavored instant bouillon
granules
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (1 cup) shredded cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 cups flour (all-purpose or whole wheat)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease cookie sheets. In large
bowl, combine rolled oats, margarine and boiling water; let stand
10 minutes. Stir in cornmeal, sugar, bouillon, milk, cheese and
egg; mix well. Add flour 1 cup at a time, mixing well after each
addition to form a stiff dough.
</P>
<P>
   On a floured surface, knead in remaining flour until dough is
smooth and no longer sticky, 3 to 4 minutes. Roll or pat out dough
to 1/2-inch thickness. Cut with bone-shaped cookie cutter. Place 1
inch apart on greased cookie sheets. Bake for 35 to 45 minutes or
until golden brown. Cool completely. Store loosely covered. _ From
Pillsbury Classic Cookbooks 142, December 1992
</P>
<P>
   Per large biscuit: 69 calories, 2 grams protein, 3 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 37), 9 grams carbohydrates, 8
milligrams cholesterol, 45 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
