<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savannah reader sings praises of Hummingbird Cake
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Michael Rocchins of Savannah(Ga.) requested a
Hummingbird Cake recipe, we didn't have to go any further than the
archives to find it. A perennial favorite, it was last published
here in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rocchins said he had tried to find the recipe for two years,
since his mother passed away. She made the cake at Christmastime,
he said, and now he intends to make it, too.
</P>
<P>
   This spice cake with pineapple has nuts baked into it and is
topped with a cream cheese frosting. Pecan halves in a circle on
top make a pretty finishing touch.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Hummingbird Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 23-28 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3large eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce can crushed pineapple, undrained
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4cups mashed bananas
</P>
<P>
   Cream Cheese Frosting (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   16pecan halves for garnish, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour three 9-inch cake
pans; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Sift into a bowl the flour, baking soda, salt, sugar and
cinnamon. Add eggs and oil, stirring until dry ingredients are
moistened. (Do not beat.) Stir in vanilla, pineapple, pecans and
bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into prepared pans and bake for 23 to 28 minutes or
until a wooden pick inserted in center comes out clean. Cool in
pans for 10 minutes; remove from pans and let cool completely on
wire racks.
</P>
<P>
   Spread frosting between layers and on top and sides. Refrigerate
up to three days, or freeze up to three months. Garnish, if
desired, with pecan halves.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving, with Cream Cheese Frosting: 591 calories, 6 grams
protein, 29 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 44), 81 grams
carbohydrates, 75 milligrams cholesterol, 264 milligrams sodium, 1
gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Cream Cheese Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for a three-layer cake
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce package cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   116-ounce package confectioners' sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Beat butter and cream cheese at medium speed with an electric
mixer until creamy. Gradually add confectioners' sugar, beating
until mixture is light and fluffy. Stir in vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leslie Booth of Fayetteville(Ga.) is looking for a recipe for
restaurant-quality chicken wing sauce _ something with more to it
than Tabasco sauce and butter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  We got no responses when Caryn Hanrahan (e-mail) asked last
summer for a recipe for a cold salad with black-eyed peas and
pineapple. So we're trying again, because we agree with her that it
sounds good to serve on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
