<HEADER>
A2525 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MOVIES-COMPUTERS-     12-16 1951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MOVIES-COMPUTERS-2TAKES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING PERSONAL WITH THE COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``I honestly think you ought to calm down; take a stress
pill and think things over.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   That is, as cult-film enthusiasts know, one of the most
memorable lines uttered by HAL 9000, the computer that goes berserk
in Stanley Kubrick's 1968 head-trip classic, ``2001: A Space
Odyssey.'' ``Calm down,'' HAL says in that distinctive disembodied
voice, a sort of mellow whine with a malevolent bite. ``Take a
stress pill,'' the dysfunctional computer advises, shortly before
suffering a system breakdown and threatening the mere humans who
brought him into operation one fine day in January 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Poor HAL and his compatriot computers, forever typecast as the
evil menace wreaking danger and destruction. In films ranging from
``Desk Set'' in 1957 to ``The Net'' in 1995, computers have been
characterized on the big screen as dark, sometimes apocalyptic
forces that instill paranoia and fear. Created and operated by
stereotypical programmers portrayed as emotionless bureaucrats,
misfits, or nerds, these huge machines are going to make us lose
our jobs, lose our wars, lose our freedom, lose our very
identities. The message has been clear: Pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, that is. The computer has a new screen image _
perky, trim, and so user-friendly you can snuggle up with it in
bed. In ``You've Got Mail,'' the romantic comedy starring Tom Hanks
and Meg Ryan that opens Friday, the laptop computer is more than
just a benign communication tool. It comforts lonely hearts; it
brings unlikely lovers together; it makes folks who live small but
meaningful lives feel significant in the cosmos. It's the yenta of
the 21st century, an unparalleled matchmaker, a silicon chip with a
heart of gold. And the people who use it aren't calculating
scientists or adolescent hackers: They're America's sweethearts,
ordinary sorts harboring that &QC; timeless dream that their soul mate
is out there, maybe just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The blinking red eye of HAL has segued to the teary hazel eyes
of the adorable Meg Ryan, typing away on the keyboard and praying
for Mr. Right.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a good thing. ``Over the years, the computer has
played the heavy and the villain, but increasingly, we're going to
see the computer as less and less the evil bad guy,'' says
Christopher Morgan, a computer consultant and author of ``The
Official Computer Bowl Trivia Book.'' ``Over the last two decades,
people's impression of computers has changed, and certainly the
personal computer had a role in that. The mystique went away. The
idea that the computer was going to harm us has melted. Now, people
don't think twice about their computers doing good or evil. They're
just an integral part of life, like a car. I can't imagine a movie
about an evil car.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that long ago, it would have been hard to imagine a
children's movie about a friendly computer (HAL the debugged Love
Bug?), but that scenario doesn't seem too far-fetched today.
</P>
<P>
   As the technology has evolved and infiltrated everyday life, so
has the computer's screen image. In fact, the doomsday films of the
last few decades _ and even a few years ago _ seem hilarious today,
even to those without an engineer's sense of humor. It's hard not
to snicker when world leaders with grim faces and trim haircuts are
called in to oversee computer-generated crises in such films as
``Colossus: The Forbin Project'' (1970) and ``WarGames'' (1983).
After all, today President Clinton wants a computer in every
classroom and greets browsers cheerfully on the White House Web
site. HAL, we hardly knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail,'' then, brings the computer image full circle
in more ways than one. Back in 1957, an ``electronic brain'' called
EMMY terrified office workers in ``Desk Set,'' a screwball comedy
starring Spencer Tracy and Katharine Hepburn. The computer itself _
a laughably inauthentic wall of steel and flashing lights, complete
with a Teletype machine _ was a thin plot device to get the
Hepburn-Tracy chemistry thing going. She runs a research office at
a television network, and he has been hired to improve office
efficiency. The researchers are convinced the computer is going to
make their jobs obsolete; they do all end up with pink slips, but
only as a result of a computer error made by the payroll
department. The important thing is that the stars get to battle
wits and acknowledge their attraction by the time the credits roll.
Boy gets girl, despite the computer.
</P>
<P>
   That will-they-ever-get-together theme is central to ``Mail,''
though the computer is now the conduit for love rather than the
obstacle. (Coincidentally, Henry and Phoebe Ephron wrote ``Desk
Set''; four decades later, their daughters, Nora and Delia Ephron,
penned the script for ``Mail,'' which Nora Ephron directed; see
accompanying story.) The male romantic lead has evolved, however.
In his usual frumpy fashion, Tracy played an eccentric MIT
graduate, a kind of antisocial character whose socks don't match
and who seems to idle away the time solving differential equations.
By contrast, Tom Hanks in ``Mail'' is, well, Tom Hanks, the
fresh-scrubbed hero who guided Apollo 13 back to earth safely.
</P>
<P>
   In its lighthearted, gentle way, ``Desk Set'' started the
tradition of the computer geek on-screen. The Space Age engineers
in ``2001'' are inscrutable, even when interrogated by HAL. (``What
are you doing, Dave?'') In ``Colossus,'' electronics wizard Charles
Forbin describes himself as ``an impartial, emotionless machine, a
paragon of reason.'' The college students in a 1970 Disney comedy
called ``The Computer Wore Tennis Shoes'' are lovable losers; in
the hit ``WarGames,'' an astonishingly young Matthew Broderick fits
all the criteria of the stereotypical hacker _ a brainy
underachiever who is estranged from his parents and has difficulty
communicating with his peers. Two programmers in ``WarGames'' are
quintessential geeks: One is a nasal-voiced nerd in a plaid shirt,
and the other is a volatile nutcase wearing a smily-face T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The stereotype gets even more absurd in ``The Net,'' which casts
Sandra Bullock against type as a lonely software engineer who has
no friends, rarely leaves the house, and hasn't taken a vacation in
years. When evil computer mavericks steal her identity, she has
nowhere to turn. The film, which came out just around the time the
World Wide Web was emerging as the great new frontier for
nontechnical types, paints in the kind of paranoid shades that
colored movies during the Cold War. In this case, however, the
enemy isn't the abstract notion of communism: It's simply the
computer. In ``The Net,'' the computer isn't going to blow up the
world with one quick blast; it's going to do it slowly, eliminating
us one by one, erasing our identities as well as our humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock is up against evil manipulators who use the technology
maliciously; the people, not the machines themselves, are the
psychopaths who pull the trigger. But in films made during the Cold
War, computers are sentient things with the ability to learn and to
act on their own. In ``2001'' and ``WarGames,'' they can also play
a good game of chess, which shows what most people thought
computers could do in previous decades _ that is, play games and
destroy the universe.
</P>
<P>
   That fear stemmed from the belief that computers really were
electronic brains with the ability to think. For all its spacy
choreography, ``2001'' offers an astute psychological study of HAL,
who becomes maniacal only after his feelings get hurt. When he's
disconnected, he reverts to childhood in that creepy, classic
``death scene,'' singing ``Daisy'' as he remembers his youth.
Likewise, the computer in ``Colossus'' begins to act on its own and
establishes contact with its counterpart in the former Soviet
Union. The two machines communicate via neon messages scrolling
across a marquee; the machine orders military-style executions,
takes over the global defense system, and threatens to launch World
War III. Not bad for a big box with flashing lights. The looming
threat is that man will become a slave to the machine: ``Obey me
and live, or disobey me and die,'' the computer commands eerily.
</P>
<P>
   The apocalypse is also the underlying threat in ``WarGames,''
which starts out as a sort of ``Ferris Bueller's Day at the Video
Arcade'' and turns into a military thriller. After Broderick's
character inadvertently finds a ``back door'' into the Defense
Department's computer system, the machine starts acting on its own,
simulating an international conflict that could end in nuclear
destruction. Broderick's computer geek joins forces with a mad
scientist played by John Wood, whose darting eyes and nervous tics
make him seem a human version of HAL 9000.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but yesterday's madmen and misfits are today's millionaires.
In ``You've Got Mail,'' Tom Hanks is a perfectly sane, perfectly
handsome fellow who uses his personal computer to reach out and
e-mail his on-line buddy. Oh, he also happens to be a filthy-rich
scion of a bookselling empire, but in the film, that's just a
little plot device to get the two cyberpals together. Hanks's
character, Joe Fox, is opening a superstore around the corner from
Ryan's children's bookstore, appropriately called the Shop Around
the Corner (a nod to the title of the 1940 Ernst Lubitsch comedy
that ``You've Got Mail'' remakes). The two feud like competitors:
He represents big business swallowing up the mom-and-pop shops, and
she is a link to a simpler past, where human contact mattered. In
the meantime, Ryan and Hanks are doing a little flirting dance in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The computer here is just a part of everyday life, as routine
as, say, a toaster oven. The machine isn't evil; the people who use
it are regular folks. The film, a sort of cyberversion of
``Sleepless in Seattle,'' even has in-jokes about the computer
industry: A batty character played by Jean Stapleton announces that
she is rich, explaining, ``I bought Intel at $6.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this isn't the first movie that presents computers as
benign: The machines in such film and television series as ``Star
Trek,'' ``Star Wars,'' ``Lost in Space,'' and ``The Jetsons''
certainly did more good than harm. But in ``Mail,'' the computer
actually brings people together, a fact that isn't lost on folks
who have been preaching about the potential of technology for
decades. ``I'm so pleased to see this type of movie come out,''
says computer consultant Morgan. ``I've been proselytizing about
computers for years, and now they've hit critical mass. They're a
very important part of society, and they're going to revolutionize
the way we live over the next 100 or 200 years. It's about time
movies started to reflect that.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, ``You've Got Mail'' does just that. In the film, both
Hanks and Ryan are avid customers of America Online, the Internet
service provider and communication service that has 14 million
members. Whatever their differences in the flesh world _ he's the
corporate monolith swallowing up the competition, she is the
competition _ the romantic leads open windows to each other's souls
in the cyberworld. The computer is no longer the heavy; it's a
humanizing tool that enables two strangers who might unknowingly
pass each other at Starbucks to actually sit down over a tall decaf
latte.
</P>
<P>
   Without giving away the ending, let's just say computers are no
longer the evil menace. In fact, the movie asks: How were we ever
human without them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-14-98 1332EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
