A2526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-DAZZLERS17-COX     12-16 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DAZZLERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four metro area chefs offer culinary delights that capture the
special mood of the holidays
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The cards are in the mail, the garland is on the
mantel, the ornaments are dangling from the tree and the presents
are disguised in red and green wrap.
</P>
<P>
   You've thought of everything for a festive holiday _ except the
feast. You want to dazzle, but after all the other preparations,
you're feeling a little frazzled.
</P>
<P>
   Focus.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Thanksgiving, when an entire menu is set in stone, down
to the cranberries ground in grandmother's antique food mill, you
have more flexibility with the Christmas spread. So why not choose
one dish to pour your culinary heart into, and simply assemble the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   For the crowd coming Christmas Eve, follow the Italian tradition
and serve up some succulent seafood pasta offered by Lenny Trovato,
chef of Trovato's in Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas Eve is the biggest night for Italians,'' said
Trovato, who grew up in Brooklyn in a brownstone that was home to a
large family. ``There would be about 40 of us crammed onto four
floors, the steps outside, wherever we could find a seat. We would
start at 4 in the afternoon and eat until it was time to go to
midnight Mass.''
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas morn, give in to indulgence with a fancy French
toast crowned with seasonal toppings made ahead of time. Harvest
chef Justin Ward shared recipes for kumquat marmalade and cranberry
syrup, as served at his Atlanta restaurant throughout the holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta cookbook author Ray Overton swears by beef tenderloin
with an assortment of condiments, whether for a party buffet or a
sit-down meal. And Edible Art chef Deborah Berry says no Southern
dessert table is complete without a red velvet cake.
</P>
<P>
   Choose one of these stars for the spotlight and pick up a few
prepared or easy-to-assemble dishes _ fruit salad, oven-roasted
potatoes, poundcake _ to fill out the stage. You're sure to impress
without all the stress.
</P>
<P>
   Seafood Mariciare
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Trovato of Trovato's in Roswell offers this seafood
extravaganza as a Christmas Eve crowd pleaser. For appetizers, try
crab meat seasoned with salt, pepper and lemon on crackers, a clam
dip or shrimp _ peel-and-eat, fried or scampi. To complete the
meal, add a simple green salad and fresh bakery bread. Pick up some
cookies or a cheesecake to finish. Pair the entree with pinot
grigio.
</P>
<P>
   Red Velvet Double Chocolate Mousse Torte
</P>
<P>
   Red Velvet Cake is a Christmas tradition in the South. Edible
Art's Deborah Berry and her pastry chef, Rossi Kemp, have taken it
to a new level. Instead of cream cheese filling and frosting, you
have mousse and ganache. Pair with a pie, poundcake or some cookies
from a local bakery, set out nuts and fresh fruits and you'll have
a smashing dessert spread. Serve with hot coffee and liqueurs.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Toast
</P>
<P>
   Justin Ward at Harvest restaurant in Virginia-Highland offers
this seasonal ``Holiday Toast'' with kumquat marmalade and
cranberry syrup as a sweet starter to the big day. Serve with your
favorite sidekick _ bacon, sausage, ham _ and a fruit salad. Smoked
salmon, capers and cream cheese with bagels can be added for a big
crowd. Serve with coffee, juice, Bloody Marys and mimosas.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Tenderloin of Beef With Three Condiments
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author Ray Overton says there are few things easier or
more impressive than beef tenderloin. For a meal, slice thickly;
for a crowd, go thin. He offers a spinach and roasted red pepper
dip, a honey mustard and a lemon and black olive gremolata as
condiments. Round out the meal with oven-roasted potatoes, glazed
carrots and rolls and serve a merlot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
