<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-DAZZLERS-RECIPES     12-16 2807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DAZZLERS-RECIPES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipes for holiday dazzlers
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's time to indulge. And what better way, after
hitting the malls and decking the halls, than with delectables.
Here are four to choose from, each sure to convince guests you are
a culinary genius. We asked four area chefs to offer recipes that
would capture the special mood of the holidays. Doing one thing
really well will tell your family and friends they are special and
will spare you the maddening multi-tasking. Have guests bring
dishes to fill out the rest of the table, or go with prepared
foods. With a succulent tenderloin, sensational seafood, a seasonal
french toast or sweeter-than-sin red velvet cake, celebration is
all but guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Tenderloin of Beef With Three Condiments
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes Marinating time: 6 hours-overnight
Cooking time: 30-35 minutes Standing time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author Ray Overton says folks needn't be intimidated by
beef tenderloin. It's ideal for a party buffet or as a centerpiece
for a sit-down meal. And it's very easy to prepare, especially if
you purchase one already trimmed of fat. (Try ordering one from a
butcher.) If you really want to get a head start, put the meat and
a marinade in a zip-top bag several days in advance and keep in the
freezer until the night before you plan to serve it. Then move to
the refrigerator until you are ready to cook. You also can make
these condiments up to a week ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   Tenderloin:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, crushed with 1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarse-grained Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 (5- to 6-pound) beef tenderloin, trimmed of all visible fat
</P>
<P>
   Kale, fresh herbs, baby vegetables, cherry tomatoes and/or
mushrooms for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl whisk together the rosemary, ginger, garlic
crushed with salt, black pepper, Dijon mustard, lemon juice, sherry
and olive oil. Place the tenderloin in a heavy-duty zip-top bag.
Pour the marinade over the meat. Seal the bag and place in the
refrigerator, turning occasionally, for 6 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Remove the
tenderloin from the marinade and place on a foil-lined baking sheet
with sides, such a jellyroll pan or roasting pan. Tuck the tail or
thinner end of the tenderloin under the rest of the meat so that it
will cook more evenly. Place the meat in the preheated oven and
roast for 20 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees and cook the meat
for 10-15 minutes more or until a meat thermometer inserted into
the thickest part of the tenderloin registers 120 degrees for rare.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the oven and let the meat sit for 20 minutes before
slicing. Slice the meat thinly and place on a serving platter lined
with the kale and garnishes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with the condiments on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 382 calories, 48 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), less than 1 gram carbohydrates,
143 milligrams cholesterol, 326 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCES FOR MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Spinach and Roasted Red Pepper Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours or overnight
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce package frozen chopped spinach, thawed and squeezed
very dry
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brine-packed green peppercorns, drained and
slightly crushed (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup capers, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   6 cornichons, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 roasted red pepper, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1 16-ounce container sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarse-grained Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl combine the chopped spinach, tarragon, green
peppercorns, capers, cornichons, roasted red pepper, shallots,
horseradish, sour cream, Dijon mustard, lemon juice and salt and
pepper to taste. Cover and chill for 2 hours or overnight. Store in
the refrigerator for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Per 2-tablespoon serving: 91 calories, 2 grams protein, 7 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 70), 5 grams carbohydrates, 15
milligrams cholesterol, 171 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Honey Mustard Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours or overnight
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup orange blossom or clover honey
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup coarse-grained Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl mix together the honey, mustard and rosemary.
Cover and chill for at least 2 hours or overnight. Store in the
refrigerator for up to 1 week.
</P>
<P>
   Per 2-tablespoon serving: 40 calories, 1 gram protein, 1 gram
fat (percent calories from fat, 12), 9 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 105 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Lemon and Black Olive Gremolata
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours to overnight
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated lemon zest, no white attached (10 lemons or more)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pitted Greek black olives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped walnuts, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl combine the lemon zest, basil, parsley, garlic,
black olives, Parmesan cheese, walnuts, olive oil, and salt and
pepper to taste. Cover and chill for at least 2 hours or overnight.
Can keep in the refrigerator for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Per 2-tablespoon serving: 40 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 92), less than 1 gram
carbohydrates, 1 milligram cholesterol, 55 milligrams sodium, less
than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Red Velvet Double Chocolate Mousse Torte
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 1 hour, 30 minutes Chilling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes Cooling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Edible Art chef Deborah Berry loves red velvet cake, something
her pastry chef, being a Northerner, doesn't quite understand.
``Why do you want to eat cake with all that red food coloring?''
muses Rossi Kemp. But he collaborated with Berry and agrees the
stunning version they came up with is delicious. The torte shown on
Page H1 features two layers of cake with one thick layer of mousse.
This recipe calls for the more traditional three layers, with
thinner layers of mousse, but you can build it any way you want.
And you may be used to working with softer frostings or whipped
cream when it comes to piping. The mousse will be stiff, so a
professional tip will work best. Of course, piping is optional. If
you have some of the mousse left over, simply spoon it into a cup
with some fresh berries. As tempting as it may be to set this out
all evening, it's best to keep it chilled until 15 to 20 minutes
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Red Velvet Cake:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces red liquid food coloring
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   5 cups sifted cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Citrus White Chocolate Mousse:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces good-quality white chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1 1 1/4-ounce package unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange juice concentrate
</P>
<P>
   3 cups heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   Dark Chocolate Ganache:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 tablespoons citrus-flavored brandy, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Dark chocolate shavings or curls (optional for garnish)
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour
three 9-inch round cake pans and set aside. Beat shortening at
medium speed of electric mixer until fluffy; gradually add sugar,
beating well. Add eggs, one at a time, beating until blended after
each addition. Stir in food coloring and vanilla, blending well. In
a medium mixing bowl, combine flour, salt and cocoa; set aside. In
a large mixing bowl or 8-cup liquid measuring cup, combine
buttermilk, vinegar and soda. (Mixture will bubble.)
</P>
<P>
   Add flour mixture to shortening mixture alternately with
buttermilk mixture, beginning and ending with flour mixture. Beat
at low speed after each addition. Beat at low speed for 2 minutes
after last addition. Pour batter into prepared pans. Place in oven
and bake for about 30 minutes. Do not overbake. Cool in pans on
wire racks about 10 minutes. Remove from pans, and cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   For the Citrus White Chocolate Mousse: In a heavy medium
saucepan, melt white chocolate over very low heat, being careful
not to burn. Place the white chocolate in a large mixing bowl and
set aside. In a small bowl, combine the gelatin and orange juice
concentrate and set aside. In the large bowl of an electric mixer,
whip heavy cream at medium speed until it forms medium peaks. Place
the small bowl of gelatin and orange juice over a saucepan of
barely simmering water to dissolve gelatin. Fold the whipped cream
and gelatin mixture alternately into the white chocolate, beginning
and ending with the whipped cream. Work quickly, being careful not
to break the whipped cream. Let the mousse chill at least 2 hours
before using.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dark Chocolate Ganache: Heat whipping cream in small
saucepan over low heat, being careful not to scorch. Add chocolate
and stir until completely melted; add brandy. Remove from heat and
set aside until ready to use. As it cools, the ganache will thicken
slightly to a glaze consistency.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble torte: Reserve some white chocolate mousse for
decoration. Spread most of the white chocolate mousse between
layers of cake. Put cake on serving platter. Pour ganache over cake
and let chocolate run down the sides. Let sit for about 5 minutes.
Spoon the reserved white chocolate mousse into a piping bag with
large star tip. Pipe rosettes on top of torte and garnish with dark
chocolate curls or shavings. Serve immediately or keep chilled
until about 15 to 20 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 794 calories, 9 grams protein, 48 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 54), 89 grams carbohydrates, 153
milligrams cholesterol, 329 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Seafood Mariciare
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Yep. That's right. This recipe calls for two sticks of butter
and four cups of cream. Come on. It's Christmas. You can cut the
butter in half if you like, or at least trade some of it for more
olive oil. You also have leeway with the seafood you include. Don't
like squid? Leave it out. Don't want to cook the lobster? Get it
already steamed (many of the larger grocery stores will do that for
you) or omit it. Add a green salad and some crusty bread for
dipping into the sauce, and you'll have one memorable meal, thanks
to Lenny Trovato of Trovato's in Roswell. The Italian-American from
Brooklyn carries on his family's tradition of a Christmas Eve
seafood feast at his home here in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound (2 sticks) butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, diced
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 1 1/4-pounds fresh lobsters, cooked, meat removed and shells
discarded
</P>
<P>
   1 pound shrimp, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   24 littleneck clams
</P>
<P>
   24 mussels
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound cleaned squid, sliced crosswise into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   4 cups marinara (see below; or your favorite tomato sauce)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped basil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fettuccine, cooked
</P>
<P>
   Lemon slices and parsley sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In a very large Dutch oven, add butter and oil over medium-high
heat. When butter has melted, add onions and garlic and cook,
stirring frequently, until just beginning to brown. Add lobster,
shrimp, scallops, clams, mussels and squid and cook for 2-3
minutes. Add white wine and simmer for 2 minutes. Add tomato sauce,
cream, basil and parsley. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to
medium and simmer until shellfish opens, stirring occasionally.
Season with salt and pepper to taste. Serve over pasta. Garnish
with sliced lemon and parsley sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 1,086 calories, 49 grams protein, 67 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 72 grams carbohydrates, 387
milligrams cholesterol, 1,235 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE FOR MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Marinara
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 28-ounce cans whole plum tomatoes with juice, very coarsely
chopped or broken by hand
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh Italian parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh basil, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of oregano
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of red pepper flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pour olive oil in a medium saucepan and heat over medium-high
heat. Add the onion and garlic and cook, stirring constantly, until
almost brown. Add red wine and cook until liquid reduces by half.
Add tomatoes, bring to a boil, reduce heat to low and simmer 1
hour. Add the parsley, basil, oregano, red pepper flakes, salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4-cup serving: 38 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 5 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 162 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber. MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Toast
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 20
minutes
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of this dish is that the festive, seasonal sauces can
be made a few days ahead of time. It's a great way to use kumquats,
which you've probably seen in the produce section but might not
have known how to use. They look like miniature, oblong oranges.
And Justin Ward of Harvest restaurant in Virginia-Highland adds a
special touch by cutting the bread in perfect circles with a
biscuit cutter. You can take it a step further and use cookie
cutters in Christmas shapes.
</P>
<P>
   1 large loaf fresh bakery bread, such as a Tuscan loaf or
country white
</P>
<P>
   4 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   5 whole eggs
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Pinch allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Using a 2-inch biscuit cutter or a cookie cutter, cut out 12
pieces of bread (no crust) and set aside. In a large mixing bowl,
combine the milk, eggs, nutmeg, allspice, vanilla and sugar. Heat
butter in a medium skillet over medium heat. Quickly dunk a bread
piece in the batter, then place in skillet. Cook for about 3
minutes, then flip and cook for another 3 minutes. (You should be
able to cook about 3 pieces of bread at a time.) Cook until firm
and batter no longer oozes from the bread when pressed with
spatula. Serve with Kumquat Marmalade and Cranberry Syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 350 calories, 14 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 35 grams carbohydrates, 223
milligrams cholesterol, 380 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Kumquat Marmalade
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cup sliced, seeded kumquats, about 1 pint
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Combine the kumquats, water, orange juice and sugar in a medium
saucepan over medium heat. Stir until sugar dissolves, then reduce
heat and simmer until the liquid is reduced by two-thirds, about 50
minutes. Serve immediately or store in airtight container in
refrigerator for up to 1 week.
</P>
<P>
   Per 2-tablespoon serving: 33 calories, less than 1 gram protein,
no fat, 8 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium,
1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Syrup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces fresh cranberries
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Combine cranberries, water and sugar in medium saucepan. Simmer
until liquid is reduced by half, about 35 minutes. Remove from heat
and add maple syrup. Serve immediately or store in airtight
container in refrigerator for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Per 2-tablespoon serving: 69 calories, less than 1 gram protein,
no fat, 18 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 2 milligrams
sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
