<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     12-16 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Noteworthy ale stands elegantly above the rest
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At the two Sherlock's Beer &AMP; Wine Warehouses in
Marietta, Ga., you could have chosen from 300 or more bottled beers
this year. At any one time, upwards of 50 were in stock. ``And
that's not counting the suitcase beers,'' says Harry Gregory, beer
manager at the Marietta store.
</P>
<P>
   He means the 12-packs, usually Budweiser but also Miller and
Coors, that young males swing into their pickups like luggage.
</P>
<P>
   A similar plenitude could be found at Jax in Sandy Springs, Ga.,
Tower in Atlanta, Green's in Atlanta and elsewhere. But if beer's
beer, why so many?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that 300, although large for any one store,
doesn't begin to encompass the variety of beer in the world. Not
all are particularly good; some are pretty dreadful. But if some
are mediocre, others are excellent and a few are superlative.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's first Beer of the Year award
recognizes one superlative beer among many. The criteria were
happily subjective: Which was the most noteworthy addition to the
local scene? Of which could it be said, ``None other compares?''
</P>
<P>
   Arguments could be made for several. Sierra Nevada's Summerfest
Lager was an example of a pioneer in West Coast ales showing the
industry giants how well an American lager can be made. From Canada
came the silky-smooth McAuslan oatmeal stout. A masterstroke from
one of North America's best female brewers, Ellen Brousnal, it
takes its place among the world's premier stouts.
</P>
<P>
   But one stood clearly apart _ Tuppers' Hop Pocket Ale. More
aromatic and assertive than even Anchor Liberty Ale, Tuppers' Hop
Pocket achieves an elegance rare in an ale. A friend put it best as
we sat over an audacious pale ale at an Atlanta brewpub. ``The
difference between these beers and Tuppers','' she said, ``is that
with these, the hops hit you first and that's it. With Tuppers',
there's so much more complexity. And you realize it at the
finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Poured properly into the glass, it will rise to an immense,
rocky crown, the Cascade and Mount Hood hops giving off an aroma at
once citrusy and spicy (it's dry-hopped during a secondary
fermentation of up to three weeks). The foretaste is firm and
malty, the middle assertive, the finish dry and long.
</P>
<P>
   As remarkable as the beer is, the story of its creation is even
more so. Bob and Ellie Tupper have spent the nearly 30 years of
their marriage compiling notes on the great beers of the world.
They are not professional brewers (he teaches history at a prep
school in Maryland, and she is an editor for the American Society
for Microbiology), but they have carefully cataloged some 7,000
beers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was one they had not encountered _ an ale that was
assertive in the Pacific Northwest style but with some of the
roundness of a great lager. They conceived it in their imagination
and then talked their friend Jerry Bailey, founder of Old Dominion
in Ashburn, Va., into brewing it. For Tupper, the Mount Hood hops
are a key, imparting herbal notes in addition to the familiar
citrusy character of Cascades. But so, too, is the secondary
fermentation of three weeks _ unusually long for an ale.
</P>
<P>
   Hop Pocket quickly acquired a following in Northern Virginia and
the District of Columbia since its introduction in 1994, and last
year it won the gold medal for pale ales at the Great American Beer
Festival in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   If any beer could have denied Hop Pocket recognition in Atlanta
this year, it would have been its own sibling. Tuppers' Hop Pocket
Pils is brewed to a different style altogether, but is no less
distinctive. It might, in fact, be more so. With the renaissance of
American brewing 20 years ago, well-crafted pale ales are not
uncommon. A distinctive pilsener is another matter, hard to brew
and harder to find. In the United States, there might not be more
than half a dozen that compare with the best in Germany or the
Czech Republic. This is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to brew a North Bavarian pilsener, and I think we
went through it eight times before we got it right,'' Tupper says.
Ironically, the domestically grown Mount Hood hops, used in
conjunction with Saaz hops, again made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either a German immigrant or it's a German pils with an
American accent,'' Tupper says. ``When we went back to Germany this
summer, we carried a six-pack of the Pils with us, and were
surprised. It was a bigger beer than all but a few of the German
pilseners.''
</P>
<P>
   At 40 International Bitterness Units, the Pils has a presence
you'll find in few pilseners. But for folks not accustomed to
hoppiness in the range of 60 International Bitterness Units, it's
more accessible than Hop Pocket Ale.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the quaffer is not the only beneficiary. Half
the proceeds from the sales of Tuppers' Hop Pocket _ ale or pils _
goes to programs to help the needy. A few months ago, Tupper called
the Journal-Constitution to ask a question: Could someone suggest
local charities to which he and his wife might contribute?
</P>
<P>
   Public-spiritedness does not a great beer make. But it's one
more reason why, among 300 beers on the market, Hop Pocket stands
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Michaeal Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
