<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perky `Madeline' takes slight series and turns it into
full-length fun
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Madeline'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   Madeline (Hatty Jones) fools a band of kidnappers. She has an
appendectomy. She falls into the Seine. She's very brave. This
blithe film version of the beloved kids' books unreels like a
colorful object lesson in the art of being perky. And there's
nothing wrong with that. Richly appointed for such a slight series
of anecdotes, the movie co-stars Oscar-winner Frances McDormand as
Miss Clavel, the nun who oversees orphaned Madeline and 11 other
little girls, and Oscar-nominee Nigel Hawthorne as a stern landlord
who intends to sell the girls' home out from under them. The colors
are lively, the Parisian scenery is grand; little girls will love
the movie. You won't mind. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
