<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BAKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS FOR MAKING PERFECT HOLIDAY COOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROTH FANTASIA  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Although time seems shorter than an elf during
the holidays, some folks are unable to let the season pass without
baking cookies. Bakeries and specialty stores simply can't:
</P>
<P>
   Duplicate grandma's recipe for butter cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the children occupied for an afternoon decorating sugar
cookies and gingerbread men.
</P>
<P>
   Put love and tenderness into every bite.
</P>
<P>
   So, for those who must bake, here are a few tips to make the
process easier:
</P>
<P>
   _ Have at least four cookie sheets, two sets of measuring cups
and two sets of measuring spoons on hand. With enough basic
equipment, the cookie sheets will have time to cool properly
between batches and you won't have to be washing and drying
measures for every kind of cookie.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sift baking soda before measuring to break up any clumps that
may throw off the measure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chop chocolate bars into small pieces (a food processor makes
fast work of this) before heating to make melting faster and the
results smoother.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chocolate that has a grayish, powdery or oily coating on the
outside has ``bloomed,'' meaning it has melted just enough for some
of the sugar crystals to separate, an occurrence usually caused by
storing chocolate in areas where temperatures and humidity are not
stable. Don't worry, bloom doesn't harm the chocolate; it is still
delicious. Take care, however, when melting bloomed chocolate as it
can separate more easily than chocolate that has been stored
properly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beat older, room temperature egg whites to make the smoothest
meringues. Adding 1/8 teaspoon cream of tartar for each egg white
used will stabilize the whites enough to prevent them from drying
out by overbeating. (Or, use 1 teaspoon cream of tartar for each
cup of egg whites).
</P>
<P>
   _ When measuring flour, pay close attention to the method called
for in the recipe. The ``dip and sweep'' method means to dip the
measuring cup into a bin of flour and then level off the top using
a knife. If the recipe calls for flour to be ``lightly spooned into
the cup,'' spoon the flour into the measuring cup and then level
the top with a knife. ``Sifted'' flour means to sift the flour
directly into the measuring cup, without shaking the cup, and then
level the top with a knife. Spooning uses less flour than the dip
and sweep method and sifting uses less flour that either of the
other two. If the recipe doesn't specify how to measure the flour,
use the spooning method.
</P>
<P>
   _ Liquid food coloring can be mixed with egg yolk and painted on
cookies before baking to add color.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toasting nuts adds flavor to cookies and other baked goods. To
toast most nuts, spread on a baking sheet and toast in a 350 oven
for about 10 minutes, or until golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, allow cookie sheets to cool between uses so the raw
cookies don't begin to cook before you place them in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Rose's Christmas Cookies,'' by Rose Levy Berenbaum
(William Morrow, 1990); ``CookWise,'' by Shirley O. Corriher
(William Morrow, 1997); and ``Desperation Dinners!'' by Alicia Ross
and Beverly Mills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
