<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-ENTERTAINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE HOLIDAYS, CONSIDER AN OPEN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The holidays are a festive time often shared with
friends, family, neighbors and colleagues. One of the most
convenient ways to accommodate everybody is to host an open house.
</P>
<P>
   At an open house, guests are invited to stop by for a short
visit and refreshments during certain hours, according to the
rewritten and updated ``Amy Vanderbilt Complete Book of Etiquette''
by Nancy Tuckerman and Nancy Dunnan. It is very much like a large
cocktail party, although liquor is not necessarily served,
according to the Vanderbilt book.
</P>
<P>
   Grown or well-behaved children may be included in invitations to
their parents. If you are not sure if you can take your child or
children, ask the host or hostess first.
</P>
<P>
   Guests are expected to stay about a half-hour or 45 minutes,
long enough to greet the host and hostess, wish everyone a happy
holiday and have a bite to eat. The invitation should state both
the beginning and ending hours, and there is generally no need to
RSVP.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore it's best to be well prepared but keep the food
simple, as guests are basically there for conversation.
</P>
<P>
   If you are doing your own cooking, make it relatively
stress-free by preparing as much as possible ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   Platters of small sandwiches, cookies and cupcakes, mixed nuts,
cheese and crackers and crudites, along with a punch or eggnog, are
common fare. If planning on a soup, serve one that can be drunk
from a cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely want to serve bite-sized food, so people can
eat it in one or two bites and hold their drink at the same time,''
advised Liz Mazzone, a caterer in Scotia, N.Y.. ``Whatever you
serve, make sure it doesn't crumble easily or stain, or you'll hate
yourself the day after.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Baker, director of Sales for the Glen Sanders, said that
open houses are mingling parties, so you'll also want to pass hors
d'oeuvres, punch, champagne, especially to those who are trapped in
group conversations and can't make it to the bar, punch or buffet
tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't set your table so that people can walk around it,
locate a variety of edibles in various places around the dining,
living and family rooms,'' Baker said. ``You may want to serve four
or five cheeses and four to six types of hors d'oeuvres. If your
party crosses over into dinner time, you might want to serve two
hot dinner-like items, such as a pasta or chicken dish and a baked
ham or turkey, so guests can make a mini-sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mistake people make when hosting an open house is,
they think they are only going to be hosting 30 people at a time
the result of scheduling some guests early and others later,
according to Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's always a time in the middle of the open house
where everybody is there at once,'' she said. ``So make sure you
are ready with everything for that kind of rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Plan your party list and invitations at least a month to eight
weeks in advance, followed by the menu and decorations. The
decorations provide holiday mood and pizzazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas is the one time that you should overdecorate,''
stressed floral designer Rudy Grant, co-owner of Experience and
Creative Design Ltd. in Schenectady, N.Y. ``It's expected. Don't
hold back. Go to extremes and overdo. Decorate doors, mantels,
windows, tables and so-on. Use a tree in as many rooms as you can
and something dramatic at the entrance and in the foyer to set the
party and decorating tone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to do this is either by theme or color scheme,'' Grant
said. ``If you don't do it this way, your decorations will jump out
at you in an odd mismatched way. Next, you want to add a lot of
candles and soft lighting to set a calm, relaxed mood that's always
right for entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Alan Boehmer, interior designer and stylist for
Coming Home, the home products division of Lands' End in
Dodgeville, Wis., you can avoid a disjointed look by decorating
your home and property in uniform colors and materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start with the walkway and front door, as those are the first
things, that your guests will see,'' Boehmer said. ``Try
incorporating nontraditional colors into your holiday decor, which
can give it a fresh feel without dramatically changing the
traditional style.''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a lot of room or wherewithal for decorating,
decide on one focal point and make it the most beautiful and
eye-catching piece and build around it, Boehmer said. The buffet
table should be one of the main focal points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might wish to decorate your buffet table with a small
table-top tree that's simple decorated with plaid ribbon and
berries,'' Boehmer said. ``You can also weave a holiday plaid
ribbon through a row of Granny Smith apples, which adds several
spots of nice color in a runner-like fashion. You may even wish to
add a few votive candles in and around the apples.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baker said that the table should be very festive with lots of
interest, such as evergreens, ribbon and Christmas ornaments for
lots of glitz and color.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try making several tiers for displaying food,'' Baker said.
``You can do this by stacking several boxes and covering them with
fabric and other decorations, but careful to leave room for the
various dishes you plan to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Grant said a mixed arrangement of fresh and dried flowers
makes a strong statement, as well as bowls of fresh fruit and
ornaments for accent and color.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional standbys include cornucopias filled with ornaments
or fruits and vegetables, dried hydrangeas, a vase of fresh
poppies, poinsettia plants in various sizes and colors,
pomegranates or a bowl of clove-studded or ribbon-tied lemons,
limes and oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said if eating utensils are going to be used, place them
in small individually decorated Christmas stockings, so that your
guests can keep the stocking as a party favor or holiday gift.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning on the addition of holiday music, keep it
low enough so that guests can talk without shouting over it.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the party glow should be lots of candles in various
sizes that are placed in safe areas so they don't ruin a surface by
dripping or igniting something. You should also be careful to not
overpower your guests with overly fragrant candles and potpourri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about buying soft pink bulbs for your electrical lights,
particularly for areas where guests may gather,'' Boehmer said.
``The pink hue gives off a pleasing warm glow to people's skin and
a relaxed, intimate feel to the get-together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
