<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD FAVORITE IS BACK ON THE MENU AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeing our recent schedule of meals for senior citizens reminded
Gladys Nolden of Bedford, Texas, that she hadn't seen a recipe for
chicken tetrazzini in years.
</P>
<P>
   This old favorite has lost a following as we've moved on to
leaner, less rich fare. But here's a version from the new ``Betty
Crocker's Best-Loved Recipes'' (MacMillan, $35.95). And if you want
it lean, there's a low-fat variation included.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY TETRAZZINI
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   7-ounce package spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken or turkey broth
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half or milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cut-up cooked turkey or chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced ripe olives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Cheddar cheese (4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   See Note for a lower-fat version.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Cook and drain spaghetti as directed
on package.
</P>
<P>
   Mix broth, half-and-half, flour, margarine, salt and pepper in
3-quart saucepan. Heat to boiling over medium heat, stirring
constantly. Boil and stir 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in spaghetti, turkey, olives and almonds. Spread in
ungreased 2-quart casserole. Sprinkle with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake uncovered for 25-30 minutes, or until hot and bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 618 calories, 37 grams fat, 30
grams carbohydrates, 32 grams protein, 101 milligrams cholesterol,
844 milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To reduce fat and calories, substitute 2 teaspoons chicken
bouillon granules and 4 cups evaporated skim milk for the chicken
broth and half-and-half. Then, decrease flour to 1/4 cup, the
margarine to 2 tablespoons and the almonds to 1/4 cup. Top with
reduced-fat Cheddar cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 506 calories, 15 grams fat, 50
grams carbohydrates, 41 grams protein, 67 milligrams cholesterol,
791 milligrams sodium, 27 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   In time for Christmas: Several readers sent in the requested
recipe for brandied cranberries. We didn't get it in time for
Thanksgiving, but it'll be just as great for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   BRANDIED CRANBERRIES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh cranberries
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   Wash and clean cranberries. Place in shallow baking pan.
Sprinkle with 2 cups sugar. Bake at 350 degrees for 30 minutes,
stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven. Stir in brandy and 1/4 cup sugar. Chill.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 264 calories, 0 fat, 63 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite from Luby's: And for all of you who've asked over the
years, we finally got the recipe for Luby's salmon croquettes. The
size of this recipe would make it perfect for a church supper.
</P>
<P>
   LUBY'S SALMON CROQUETTES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 18
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds canned pink salmon (bones and skin removed)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds cooked haddock or cod
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds potatoes, boiled and shredded or diced
</P>
<P>
   1 jumbo white onion, peeled and shredded
</P>
<P>
   2 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound crushed saltine crackers
</P>
<P>
   Breading:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/8 pounds crushed saltine crackers
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil, for deep frying
</P>
<P>
   Place canned salmon and juice in large mixing bowl. Discard any
bones and skin. Press salmon flat against pan and check for
remaining bones.
</P>
<P>
   Flake haddock or cod and add to salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Add the potatoes and onions.
</P>
<P>
   Add the eggs, paprika and crackers; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Mold into 4 1/2-ounce portions.
</P>
<P>
   Dust croquettes in flour.
</P>
<P>
   Whip eggs and buttermilk with a fork until well-blended. Dip the
flour-dusted croquettes in the buttermilk mixture. Place the
croquettes into crackers and fluff crackers around the salmon.
Avoid pressing the crumbs into the croquettes.
</P>
<P>
   Deep-fry at 300 degrees for 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 377 calories, 14 grams fat, 45
grams carbohydrates, 18 grams protein, 63 milligrams cholesterol,
683 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
