u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-16 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PLANTS LIKE NORTHERN EXPOSURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a sweet olive about 20 feet tall. Should I cut it back
and fertilize? I want to plant night-blooming jasmine. How should I
care for them? The north side of my house is 100 percent shade.
Tell me what plants I can put in.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sweet olive (``Osmanthus fragrans'') flowers off and on
during late fall, winter and early spring, and likes a moist,
fertile soil and partial sun or bright shade. I would prune after
flowering and after danger of frost. If it has been some time since
fertilization and the plant could use a boost, you could then apply
a slow-release, balanced fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Night-blooming jessamine (``Cestrum nocturnum'') prefers sun or
partial sun and a well-draining, organically enriched soil. Mulch
the root area well during winter. This shrub is inclined to be
rangy or irregular in form, even when pruned heavily in late
winter. In order to encourage a bushier habit, you'll need to nip
it back more frequently. Of course, you could rest the lanky limbs
on some type of support. The blossoms, which become so fragrant at
night, typically appear midsummer into fall.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what height is best for your northside plantings.
From your drawing, it looks as if the area is not in heavy shade.
Easy-care plant suggestions include the dwarf yaupon, a rounded,
dense shrub with small leaves. This plant takes full sun to bright
shade and tolerates various soils. Fertilize in late winter/early
spring to encourage bushiness. Mature height is about 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese mahonia (``Mahonia fortunei'') is an attractive
evergreen good for shade or filtered sunlight. The yellow flowers
are followed by blue berries that are food for the birds.
Pest-resistant, the Chinese mahonia likes an organically enriched
soil that drains well. Mature height is about 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangeas like a northern exposure. They flower best with some
sun but will bloom in shade, especially bright shade. They are
deciduous, but our winters are so short, they're not long without
leaves. I like the variegated lacecap hydrangeas for foliage as
well as floral interest. Mature height is in the 4-foot range.
</P>
<P>
   Giant liriope is about the easiest evergreen out there. It takes
sun or shade. This big form of liriope so often used to border beds
or paths has a nice form. There is a variegated variety, too.
Summer flowers are lavender. Mature height is 2 1/2 to 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a year-old hydrangea that will not grow or bloom. The
tips of the leaves are brown. What must I do?
</P>
<P>
   A: This was a tough year for all plants, especially newly
planted ones. The drought slowed or stopped growth. Hydrangeas
required frequent watering during the wretched summer months just
to stay alive, then they got too much with 10-inch rains. Such
moisture fluctuations and other environmental extremes will cause
leaf margins to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Mulch your hydrangea for the winter. It will lose its leaves
during the cool weather, but do not prune until after it flowers
next May.
</P>
<P>
   Your shrub will do best in a well-draining, organically enriched
soil. If your soil lacks organic matter, you can use compost as a
mulch to gradually improve conditions. Replenish as needed. You can
give the shrub a slow-release, balanced fertilizer in early spring.
Shrubs that are healthy and growing well in an organically enriched
soil will require little or no supplemental fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   Keep soil moist but not soggy. Pay special attention to watering
during the summer. Again, mulch will help by conserving soil
moisture and keeping roots warm in winter and cooler in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We would like to know when to prune our Confederate rose.
</P>
<P>
   A: I would prune it in early spring, after danger of frost.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do I plant my daffodil bulbs?
</P>
<P>
   A: Plant daffodils in late October-December in well-draining
beds of loose soil enriched with humus. Sun or partial sun is best.
Place one tablespoon of bone meal (or superphosphate if squirrels
dig in your beds) in each bulb hole, add a little soil or an inch
layer of sand, then set the bulb on the sand and cover with soil.
There should be about 2 inches of soil above the shoulder of the
bulb. Fertilize with superphosphate or bone meal when the foliage
pops through the soil and following the bloom period. Water in
well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
