<HEADLINE>
REJECTED BY VOTERS, OUTGOING LEGISLATORS STILL COUNT IN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several Republican House members rejected by the
voters in the November elections have said they will cast their
votes with a clean conscience on whether to impeach President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Their pronouncements, however, are tempered by the complications
of their status as lame-ducks: Some may favor impeachment even
though their earlier support of Clinton's removal may have been a
factor in their rejection by their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Their situation recalls a question often taken up in civics
classes: Who are these representatives representing? Their own
conscience? Their district? Only those members of their district
who supported them?
</P>
<P>
   Before the November elections ``there was the nagging concern''
among the representatives ``that you would get fired if you got too
far away from your constituents,'' said John R. Hibbing, political
science professor at the University of Georgia. After the
elections, ``everything changes because now you've been fired.''
</P>
<P>
   These departing Republicans are among 38 lame-duck House members
who are not returning to office in January for a variety of
reasons. And while these House members feel there is nothing wrong
with deciding the fate of the president after the voters have
spoken, others said it raises an ethical red flag.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding whether or not Clinton's conduct in the Monica S.
Lewinsky affair rises to the level of high crimes and misdemeanors
is a tricky question that requires ``profound personal judgment,''
said Bruce Ackerman, professor of constitutional law at Yale
University, who testified before the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a clear-cut question, which is exactly why it is
profoundly illegitimate for people who have been repudiated by the
electorate to make the deciding judgment on Clinton's fate, which
is what it might amount to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the mind of Representative Vince Snowbarger, Republican
of Kansas, what the voters say is neither clear nor decisive for
him. When he became one of the first House members to call on
Clinton to resign, for instance, public opinion was mixed and calls
coming into his office now are evenly split.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this figures in some subtle way, but ultimately I'm the
one who has to live with the consequences of the vote,'' he said.
``I have to uphold my responsibility. Congress will be in real
trouble in determining what's right and wrong by seeing what the
polls are rather than by looking at the law and the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote is expected to be close.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show six in 10 Americans oppose impeachment while support
for the president's removal from office is growing, mostly among
moderate House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientists say the question of whether a
representative is a trustee of the public will or simply a vehicle
for its expression is a question all members routinely grapple
with, especially on votes where they part ways with popular
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   House members are supposed to more closely reflect public
opinion, which makes itself felt at election time every two years,
noted Charles S. Bullock III, professor of political science at the
University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, which was originally elected not by the populace but
by state legislatures, is supposed to be stocked with people who
can more easily take the best interests of the country into account
because they only have to worry about reelection every six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House was supposed to be very sensitive to public opinion,
while as someone once said, the Senate is supposed to be the saucer
that cooled the cup of tea,'' said Hibbing.
</P>
<P>
   That someone was George Washington. Hibbing added that the
impeachment proceedings may see a reversal of those roles.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republicans who were voted out of office but who are
expected to vote to impeach the president are Representative Mike
Pappas, Republican of New Jersey, who lost his reelection bid in
part because Democrats blasted him for singing, ``Twinkle, twinkle,
Kenneth Starr, now we see how brave you are,'' on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Jon D. Fox of Pennsylvania also supported
impeachment, which ``had a lot to do with why he lost,'' said press
secretary Tony Swanick.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Rick White of Washington was rejected from office when
his opponent, Jay Inslee, became the first Democrat in the nation
to run pro-Clinton, anti-impeachment ads.
</P>
<P>
   These Republicans are among the lame-duck members working to
fullfill their last major political obligation. They were evicted
from their Capitol Hill offices by House rules earlier this month
and are working out of a basement room in the Rayburn House office
building that also serves as a banquet room.
</P>
<P>
   There are cubicles equipped with voice mail, access to a
computer, fax and phone, but no separate quarters for these members
as they sort through the most weighty vote of their careers.
</P>
</TEXT>
