<HEADLINE>
THINK CONVENIENCE WHEN LOOKING FOR LAST-MINUTE GIFTS FOR TRAVELERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
and SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are 10 terrific holiday gift ideas for the traveler:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fill a stocking or a shoe box with practical accessories _
disposable camera, folding rain poncho, crush-proof hat,
travel-size toiletries, batteries, hard-shell eyeglasses case, tiny
flashlight, compact umbrella, pocketknife, travel alarm, insect
repellent and sunscreen, luggage tags, pocket translator,
pocket-size journal, roll of postcard stamps (but remember that
U.S. postage increases in 1999).
</P>
<P>
   _ In conjunction with Cirrus Air Technologies, developer of the
popular EarPlanes, Travel Smart now offers FootPlanes, therapeutic
socks designed to relieve leg discomfort due to swelling
experienced by many air travelers. A special knit gently massages
legs to improve circulation as you flex your ankle. FootPlanes come
in several men's and women's sizes; cost is $16.99. Disposable
EarPlanes help avoid ear discomfort aloft and are available for
about $5. Many specialty and department stores stock the products,
or call 800-327-6151 or access www.earplanes.com to learn more.
Other innovative Travel Smart products include a padded organizer
pouch, outdoor field organizer and padded notebook organizer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ever forgotten to retrieve a credit card from a hotel clerk or
restaurant cashier? An unusual gift for the security-conscious
traveler is Kopel's Beeping Wallet, whichbeeps every 20 seconds
while a credit card is out of its usual place. Inside each wallet
is a replaceable watch battery with a three-year warranty; a
microchip triggers the beeps. In look, size and price ($20-$35,
depending on which of 10 styles preferred), these are the same as
traditional wallets. They're available at many stores or can be
ordered by calling 800-988-6255 or by looking on the Internet at
www.beepingwallet.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ From the urban backpack to the hard-sided trunk, durable
luggage is on any traveler's holiday wish list. Wheeled bags are
the way to go: Check out the Voyager ($124.95) from JanSport; this
handsome and rugged duffel bag boasts wheels, a hard bottom and
7,700 cubic inches of space and weighs less than 6 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether they face an interminable wait at an airport or a
cross-country ride in the back seat of the parents' sedan, youthful
travelers _ and adults who never grow old _ will appreciate the
gift of a small electronic game. Our favorite is the new hand-held
Monopoly Game ($24.99) by Hasbro. It's the same
wheeling-and-dealing game you remember as a kid, only better thanks
to interactive, talking opponents. Other Hasbro hand-helds include
Candyland ($19.99), Battleship ($14.99) and Yahtzee ($13.99). They
are available at many retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The serious trekker and the vacation walker will relish a
walking stick or a compass, and these handy items come in a variety
of style and prices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Binoculars are useful on almost any trip. Think small and
portable, unless you're buying for a serious birder. We like the
Lightweight Ruby Travel Binoculars from Travelsmith. Look at the
new 6x16 version; it'slightweight, will fit in your pocket and
costs $79. Call 800-950-1600 or access www.travelsmith.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ The quality, depth and practical value of magazines geared to
the traveler have grown in recent years. Most subscriptions are
easily affordable, and they make gifts that last all year. Among
magazines to consider: Travel Holiday (303-603-1464), Conde Nast
Traveler (800-777-0700), Travel &AMP; Leisure (800-888-8728), National
Geographic Traveler (800-647-5463), Business Traveler International
(800-726-1243), Arthur Frommer's Budget Travel Magazine
(800-829-9121), Best Fares Travel Discount Magazine (800-880-1234),
Islands (800-284-7958), Trips (510-834-3433), Porthole
(800-776-7678) and Cruise Travel (P. O. Box 342, Mt. Morris,
Illinois 61054-0342).
</P>
<P>
   _ Automobile-club membership is another valuable resource for
frequent travelers. In addition to dispensing travel planning
information, many such clubs offer discounts at hotels, restaurants
and attractions. Best of all, most clubs provide emergency road
service, which makes this gift particularly attractive. Look at
AAA, Allstate Travel Club and Montgomery Ward Auto Club.
</P>
<P>
   _ While you can't sell your frequent-flyer miles, many airlines
allow you to make a gift of them. The recipient must be enrolled in
the program as well; contact individual airline programs for
details. Consider, too, that some airlines, travel agencies and
other travel-service providers will issue gift certificates in
varying denominations. And for that special senior in your life,
you may want to splurge and purchase a coupon book (usually good
for four or eight flights) that allows travel at bargain prices.
Consult airlines or a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
