<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN DRAMA WILL LACK HEROES, SCHOLARS AGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever its outcome, the intensely partisan impeachment process
unfolding in Washington doesn't offer a very appealing snapshot of
American politics at the end of the 20th Century. And historians
say the picture is unlikely to improve with age.
</P>
<P>
   Some maintain that President Clinton will go down as a
bottom-rung leader, a victim of his own failings who dragged the
Oval Office down with him. Others argue that congressional
Republicans will be cast as the villains, as die-hard ideologues
who fueled voter cynicism and ultimately hurt their own party.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the political and cultural scholars interviewed
Tuesday agreed on this much, however: None of the principals seem
likely to emerge with enhanced personal reputations or as having
created a lasting, positive legacy for the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one thing, sadly, that I think there's agreement
on,'' said Doris Kearns Goodwin, a Pulitzer Prize-winning
historian. ``It's hard to see how anyone in this sad tale is going
to come out looking well.''
</P>
<P>
   All of those interviewed this week, as the full House of
Representatives prepared for its own entry into the history books,
emphasized the difficulty of forecasting how current events will be
depicted in the future. Moreover, they stressed that pivotal scenes
of the impeachment drama _ like the final House vote or how the
Senate responds _ still have not been written, and will prove
critical to any eventual assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the historians said many major conclusions, some obvious
and others more subtle, already appear clear even without the
perspective of hindsight.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed, for example, that the partisanship exhibited during
the impeachment debate will go down as among the most fervent,
rancorous, and personal in modern times. Nearly all said the GOP
has been the more rigid and ideological party, but they added that
the Democrats' nearly unwavering unity also has demonstrated the
magnetic power of party allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Such partisan orthodoxy is particularly striking, several
political scientists said, as it comes against the backdrop of
steadily waning party affiliation among American voters. ``It will
certainly be seen, I think, as yet another key bit of evidence of
the disconnect between the people and those they send to Washington
to represent them,'' said Irwin Hargrove, a political historian at
Vanderbilt University.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars on both sides of the ideological divide _ those who
argued that the impeachment effort was wrong-headed and those who
said Clinton had brought it on himself _ alike underscored the
harsh personal edge to the Republican thrusts against the
president. The historians believe that as events are unsorted by
scholars in future years, two principal reasons will be cited for
such emotional rancor in a debate that should, in theory, be
grounded in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I believe it's genuine that the majority of
Republicans. . .take family values and personal values extremely
seriously,'' said Alfred Rubin, a professor of international law at
the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University. ``So
I think they're genuinely offended, and it shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Sketching on a far bigger canvas, those interviewed said the
animosity between the Republicans and the president will almost
surely be viewed as the natural tensions that accompany the turning
from one chapter of US history to the next. In this case, Clinton
stands for the generational transition from the 1960s, while the
GOP conservatives bristle at what they view as an era of
ever-loosening moral standards _ a trend the president epitomizes,
in their view.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the disdain people have for Clinton is a disdain for
the 1960s, so much of what we're seeing is a backlash,'' said
Douglas Brinkley, director of the Eisenhower Center for American
Studies at New Orleans University. ``I think quite a lot will be
written in the history books about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Robert Dallek, a history professor at Boston University
and a biographer of Lyndon Baynes Johnson: ``This is another round
in the nation's culture wars. The Republicans are incensed because
they essentially see Clinton ... as the embodiment of the
counterculture's thumbing of its nose at accepted wisdoms and
institutions of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Several academics said the cavernous split between the two
parties _ and divisiveness of the impeachment drive _ also might be
explained partly by a coincidence of history: that Clinton moved
into the Oval Office just as the Soviet empire fell. The presence
of an overarching national enemy or goal, the historians said, had
long mitigated differences and tensions between the Republicans and
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Cold War were still on, we wouldn't have this crisis;
I'm certain that's how this will be seen,'' said Dallek.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Republicans ultimately succeed in ousting
Clinton, they already have ensured some important, unflattering
opening paragraphs about him in history books. Similarly, they have
already deprived him of what he hoped would be an essential part of
his legacy: that of a skilled politician who opened a ``third way''
for his party, a Democratic center that would outlast him and for
which he would receive enduring credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to run for office ... saying he's a Clinton
Democrat, a new Democrat,'' said Brinkley. Even though he has
presided over a booming economy and ushered in significant changes
like welfare reform, Brinkley added, ``the bottom line is that
he'll be known as a semi-amiable rake who will rate near the bottom
of American presidents of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the historians agreed Clinton's personal behavior
would inevitably taint his legacy, many said he would get
considerable credit in areas such as civil rights and the economy.
Some also flatly blamed the Republicans for precipitating a
constitutional crisis, and predicted future scholars would
emphasize that aspect when they chronicled proceedings in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think history will record this as a very strange episode,
very curious,'' said James McGregor Burns, the presidential
historian and Williams College professor. ``It will be judged, not
exactly as an effort to defeat or violate a decision of the last
election, but ... as a very partisan act. ... The reasons, whether
moral, ideological, or political, are something historians will
explore for some time and at some length.''
</P>
<P>
   The profound discontent about Clinton's behavior, coupled with
the lopsided disapproval of the GOP impeachment drive, also appear
certain to increase cynicism about politics during a period when
most analysts believe it's already at a historic high.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder where the bottom is and when we will reach
it,'' said Elmer Cornwell, an expert in presidential history at
Brown University. ``And you have to be concerned about whether we
will have a viable, vigorous democratic system left when we reach
the bottom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
