<HEADER>
A2777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOARD-GAMES-BOS &LR;      12-16 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOARD-GAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD GAMES? NO DICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Board games line an entire wall of the Toys R Us store in
Dorchester, Mass., but they draw so few customers at any given time
that young visitors could hold a tricycle race down the aisle
without much risk of hitting anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Someone would surely get hurt in the two adjoining rows of
games, though. They're filled with Christmas shoppers snapping up
cartridges for their Game Boys and PlayStations, jamming their
carts with electronic gadgets and computer games.
</P>
<P>
   Those scenes are repeated every day in toy stores across
America, and they provide far more than just a snapshot of the
nation's technological revolution. They mark the little-noted
closing of an era, the irreversible fading of a Norman Rockwell
scene in which mom and dad sit around the kitchen table with their
kids on a rainy Sunday afternoon, moving pieces and chatting
happily away.
</P>
<P>
   And, as dice rapidly give way to mice, analysts say the trend
simultaneously reflects and accelerates profound changes in our
country's culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, we're seeing the end of the board game as we
all grew up to know it . . . (it) was part of family life for many,
many generations,'' said Michael Brody, a child psychiatrist based
in Washington, D.C., who studies the role of games in behavior and
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effects are unfortunate,'' added Brody. While noting that
other influences in children's lives also play integral parts in
their upbringing, he listed several areas in which he was troubled
by the move toward less personal contact in game-playing: ``the
acceleration of the disintegration of the family unit, the
lessening of parents' influence, and the loss of socialization
benefits that came with board games and the interaction that was
required to play them.''
</P>
<P>
   Other specialists in child and social development said too
little research has been done on the effect on such skills as
conversation, dealing with competition with a sibling, or abiding
by rules to make judgments as pessimistic or conclusive as Brody's.
Some said, for instance, that another reason for the waning
popularity of board games is an increase in after-school sports
activities, which also teach competitive and social skills. Others
argued that children are participating in different, but not
necessarily worse, interactions when they play computer games with
each other or even trade e-mail on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nearly all those interviewed agreed the steady increase
in the use of computer games, particularly ones kids play on their
own, fuels a fundamental societal shift away from an emphasis on
community-based values and behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of a bigger picture of what I call the
post-modern family,''' said David Elkind, the author of ``Ties That
Stress: The New Family Ambivalence'' and a child psychologist at
Tufts University. ``People used to worry about socialization; now
they worry about self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   The specialists and consumers also agreed, and lamented, that
the trend away from board games is a manifestation of the growth of
two-earner families, more divorce, more day care, more movement
among jobs and cities, and other factors that can place strains on
family and community ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no more sitting around after dinner with everybody,
family and friends, around the game board. That's the crux of the
whole thing,'' Chris Ireland, a fire-alarm technician, said as he
entered the Toys R Us store in Dorchester. ``My wife and I both
work, so who has time for it?''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they did have time, it's not at all certain how many
eager young players most parents could corral, or for how long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get bored with board games,'' said Leila Duncan, a
10-year-old whose sentiments seem to typify many of her generation.
``I mean, with Monopoly and the other games, it's just luck and all
you can do is buy property and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   With computer and video games, on the other hand, ``It's more
fun and more interesting because you can do more than one thing at
once. They're more interactive and, really, you can play without
somebody else at the other end. They're just better.''
</P>
<P>
   While the move from kitchen table to computer desk is clear,
precise statistics on toy sales are hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island-based Hasbro Inc., which owns nearly all the major
brands of board games, considers such figures proprietary and will
not reveal even generic information. The same is true of major US
marketers Toys R Us and Kay-Bee Toys.
</P>
<P>
   But NPD Group, a research company in Port Washington, N.Y., that
tracks the toy industry, estimates retail sales of board games have
fallen from about $450 million in January through September of
1996, to $430 million during the same period of 1997, to $380
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The video game industry, meanwhile, ``has been going through the
roof,'' said Mary Ann Porreca, an NPD official. She said retail
sales of hand-held and stationary video and computer games have
soared from $1.6 billion to $2.2 billion to nearly $3 billion in
the January-September periods of 1996 through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to continue this way for the foreseeable future . .
. because people don't play family games anymore.,'' she added.
``You just don't hear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, no board game has taken off and maintained a big
audience since Trivial Pursuit and Pictionary were introduced in
the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even as its high-tech offerings proliferate, Hasbro's
marketing indicates its concern about the future of its board
games. It has been promoting Scrabble extensively as a learning
device in schools, for example, and it has been running television
commercials this holiday season advocating once-a-week ``family
game nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Annicelli, the associate editor of Playthings Magazine, a
toy-trade publication, said board games today are played
overwhelmingly by children too young for computers, or just getting
started on them, and by adults who were brought up without the
faster-moving, multi-graphic new technology. Nearly everyone
in-between, he said, spends the bulk of their gaming hours with
hand-held units, CD-roms, and in cyberspace _ sometimes playing
video versions of longtime board favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're working against,'' said John Williams, the
executive director of the National Scrabble Association. ``They
might not like to hear it, but I've told Hasbro and everybody else
that 25 years from now, many people will only be introduced to
Scrabble on-line and not at the board at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its other implications, the seemingly inexorable
dominance of computers in leisure activities struck some analysts,
particularly those most comfortable with the new technologies, as a
phenomenon with considerable benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Jenkins, director of the comparative media studies program
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, argued there is a
flip side to kids being deprived of socialization when they use
one-person games or communicate on the Internet. For the many
children whose parents aren't home, who don't know their neighbors,
or whose outside activities are restricted for safety reasons, he
said, computer games offer unprecedented opportunities for
entertainment, learning, and establishing relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Jenkins agreed the extraordinary popularity of
computer games is abetted by and reflects fundamental changes in
family and social structure. He said people are ``moving away from
playing games in immediate environments and toward playing games in
environments not bound by the vagaries of geography.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wondered whether the weekly family games of Parcheesi of
yore have been romanticized over the decades. Almost all, however,
recalled their time at the game board fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad, I guess,'' sighed Veronica Wall, the mother of
boys ages 3 and 6. ``They're really just interested mainly in the
video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no going back,'' Wall added as she put a Land
Before Time computer game into her shopping cart at the Dorchester
toy store. ``We're going into a new era.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
