<HEADER>
A2786 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-16 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNUAL CHRISTMAS DANCE SHOW AN ACT OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He got the dancing bug early in life, influenced by his artistic
parents, both of whom were opera singers. When he was as young as
5, the Rev. Robert VerEecke was a big fan of swing dancing.
</P>
<P>
   But back then, in the late 1950s, dancing ``wasn't considered
manly enough,'' for boys, said VerEecke, a Jesuit priest and pastor
of St. Ignatius Loyola parish on the campus of Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   So VerEecke did not take his first ballet class until he was 21
and a young seminarian preparing for the priesthood. ``It was an
epiphany,'' VerEecke said. His Jesuit superiors encouraged the
talented young dancer and, as a result, VerEecke has woven his
passion into his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   This is a busy time for VerEecke because it is when his most
ambitious artistic work is unveiled on stage. For the past 18
years, ``A Dancer's Christmas'' has drawn rave reviews from
audiences and critics alike as a beautiful spiritual alternative to
more secular Christmas shows.
</P>
<P>
   The show, being performed this weekend and next at BC's Robsham
Theater Arts Complex, does not garner anywhere near the kind of
attention that the ``Nutcracker'' or other Christmas works do, but
it draws a loyal following and attracts top dancers.
</P>
<P>
   For VerEecke, who also is Jesuit-artist-in-residence at BC, ``A
Dancer's Christmas'' is as much a labor of love as it is an
artistic endeavor. It is, he makes clear, a serious religious work
that uses music and dance to tell the Nativity story.
</P>
<P>
   But VerEecke also wanted to make it fun, which is why the final
act features contemporary and familiar Christmas carols. This year
VerEecke gave the opening act a new twist. He retells the Nativity
story but from the perspective of an older Mary recalling the life
and death of her son.
</P>
<P>
   And the first act juxtaposes on the same stage the tableau of
Jesus's birth _ Mary and the young baby surrounded by angels and
shepherds _ with that of his death _ Mary holding her son's corpse
after it has been taken from the cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas is not just the story of the birth of this baby,''
said VerEecke in an interview over lunch at BC recently. ``It's
about this tremendous mystery of birth leading to death and then
resurrection. It's all connected and I wanted to try to make that
come across.''
</P>
<P>
   VerEecke debuted ``A Dancer's Christmas'' in 1980 with 10
dancers staging one performance in a chapel on campus in front of
about 50 people. The show has evolved into a staple of the
Christmas season for thousands of people. VerEecke says the show
draws many people who attend year after year.
</P>
<P>
   The show also features some of the most talented performers in
the dance world. Andrew LeBeau, of the famous Peter Taylor Dance
Company in New York, is performing in ``A Dancer's Christmas'' for
the third time.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to dance in it when he was a student at the Boston
Conservatory of Music but could not because of commitments to other
shows. ``But the first time I could do it back in 1994 I fell in
love with it,'' says LeBeau, 31, who appears in ``A Dancer's
Christmas'' courtesy of Paul Taylor. ``I never was really a
particularly religious person. So for me, at a time when people are
thinking about religion, it helps make the season complete for me.
It's a foot in the door. And it's a beautiful story.''
</P>
<P>
   VerEecke notes that the idea of a Jesuit working as a dance
choreographer is perfectly natural given the historical role the
order has played in promoting dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 16th and 17th century Europe dance was a required part of
the curriculum in Jesuit universities,'' VerEecke said. ``Some of
the early dance manuscripts we have were written by Jesuits. The
Jesuits very much believe in using whatever is necessary or popular
to communicate the Gospel story.''
</P>
<P>
   At St. Ignatius, VerEecke has made music an integral part of the
church, which has helped boost the parish's popularity. VerEecke
would like to see dance incorporated into the Liturgy, something,
he says, the Roman Catholic Church views with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our tradition there seems to have been this split between
the body and the spirit,'' he says. ``But prayer and worship
doesn't just go on in your head. Jesus himself, as a good Jewish
person, must have danced as part of his religious celebrations.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Dancer's Christmas'' VerEecke hopes to convey the
possibility of triggering a spiritual response through dance. ``I
hope they are moved by the beauty of the dancing and the singing
and that it may provide some deeper spiritual insight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The religious right has begun weighing in on President
Clinton's impeachment process. Last week, the Christian Coalition
brought more than 250,000 petitions to Congress urging lawmakers to
remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tate, executive director of the coalition, told reporters
Thursday that the petitions ``allowed citizens to address this most
important issue in a timely way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tate, a strong supporter of Clinton's ouster, said the president
should be forced out of office because Tate believes he perjured
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition began circulating the petition in October. Copies
were sent to every member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   --A group of evangelical Christian scholars recently passed a
resolution reasserting their belief that the Bible ``teaches that
homosexual conduct is always an abomination.''
</P>
<P>
   But the group denounced the national media for
``unsubstantiated, untruthful and hateful accusations'' about
evangelical Christians following the murder of gay student Matthew
Shepard in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We abhor the terrible sin of doing intentional physical harm
to another human being for no reason other than hate,'' the
Evangelical Theological Society said in a statement passed last
month during the society's meeting in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But, the statement added, ``We equally abhor using the rhetoric
of hate to prejudice the power of civil government against the open
and complete proclamation of moral standards revealed in God's Holy
Word _ including both God's love for sinners as well as his
judgment of sin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
