A2787 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     12-16 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE HOLIDAY COOKS STUCK A FORK IN TURKEY TRADITION?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting here on high center between Thanksgiving turkey and
Christmas goose, I can't help but wonder how much longer we can
expect to enjoy those holiday meals.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience and common sense have muscled their way into our
celebrations. Suddenly, people are thinking that because they don't
know how to cook a goose, or because turkey can take from daylight
to dusk to prepare and then end up drier than dust, we shouldn't
use them as our festive centerpieces anymore. We need change.
</P>
<P>
   I fear it is too late to save the Christmas goose. I really
don't know anyone who has goose for Christmas. I watched the ``Two
Fat Ladies'' cook one on PBS one time, but gastronomically
speaking, I've never had a goose.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a lot of families savor turkey twice each year: once on
Thanksgiving, again on Christmas. That would be acceptable, but the
holidays are too close together. We can't space them out more,
because we have to start shopping for Christmas the day after
Thanksgiving. It's the national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   It's too much turkey, but without the turkey I wouldn't get the
oyster dressing I enjoy. There is, I am relatively certain, a
regulation that requires oyster dressing be made only with roasted
turkey. And if you have oyster dressing for one holiday, you must
have corn bread dressing for the other.
</P>
<P>
   The law is the law.
</P>
<P>
   Some exceptions have been made for deep-fried turkey and
turducken.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies part of our problem. Look at what we're doing
to a simple turkey just to make it seem like something else: Place
it on a hook and lower it into boiling peanut oil.
</P>
<P>
   It tastes great, but you could burn down the neighborhood if you
accidentally spilled all that grease. Even if you don't spill it,
where are you going to dump it? You don't want to end up as the
Exxon Valdez of your cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   And turduckens ... they are wonderful, as well. I had my first
this season, and it was certainly different. A chicken stuffed in a
duck, stuffed in a turkey; all boned. It made the carving a cinch.
</P>
<P>
   It did not, however, work well with white bread and mayonnaise
for after-dinner sandwiches. Without the sandwich, there is no need
to have the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote about the turduckens a while back, asserting that the
triple-stuffed birds migrated here from Louisiana about 10 years
ago. I was wrong. Frank Heick, a staffer at ``The Philadelphia
Daily News,'' informed me that George Washington had a similar dish
at Mount Vernon. Washington was not Cajun.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he didn't get to be the father of our country by
being ordinary, either. His dish was special: It was a turkey
stuffed with a duck, stuffed with a capon, stuffed with a squab,
stuffed with a quail. All were boned.
</P>
<P>
   The dish was placed in a large cube of partially baked pastry
along with 7 pounds of butter and cooked all day.
</P>
<P>
   George was apparently not health-conscious.
</P>
<P>
   I have since found that this kind of dish went on well before
Washington. A friend sent me several recipes for stuffed camel _ a
meal often prepared by Bedouins for a wedding feast.
</P>
<P>
   One of the recipes called for one medium camel, one lamb
(large), 20 whole chickens (medium), 60 eggs, and assorted measures
of rice, pine nuts, almonds, pistachio nuts and 110 gallons of
water. Salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   If we can't cook our goose, I doubt we'll do a camel, but we are
beginning to look at bison, wild boar, venison and pheasant as
alternatives. GoodHeart Brand Specialty Meats in San Antonio said
it had ``zero'' requests for turkey this year. Instead, the gourmet
game meat company shipped out capons, quail and pheasant.
</P>
<P>
   It's all fine enough, but capons aren't prepared much
differently from turkeys. Quail and pheasant are wonderful, but the
meat is delicate and can be overcooked in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetarians are already striking out against meat at Christmas
with what they call ``Tofurkey,'' a seasoned, stuffed roast made of
tofu. You can find the nearest retail outlet by calling 1 (888)
TOFURKY. A percentage from the sale of each Tofurkey goes to
support the efforts of ``The Farm Sanctuary's Turkey Adoption
Program.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not making this up.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should just go along with Calvin Trillin, the
misguided New York-based writer who mistakenly promotes Kansas City
barbecue over all others. He says spaghetti carbonara should be the
ideal Thanksgiving meal. He fantasizes that the Pilgrims were
served the pasta dish by the Indians, who picked up the recipe from
Christopher Columbus, whom they called ``the big Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, spaghetti would be easier, and the kids would like
it. It does not, however, slice very easily nor make good
sandwiches. Nor does it go well with oyster dressing.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
