<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOWBIRDS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAP PRICES DRAW SNOWBIRDS TO SOUTH TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Canada) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BENITO, Texas _ A warm south wind ruffled towering palm
trees as Bart and Ann Vanderlans sat on the shady side of their new
travel trailer. The brutal Canadian winters and their country's
lingering currency crisis were distant memories as they quickly
settled into retirement life at the sprawling, 1,515-space Fun N
Sun &UR;  &LR; R.V. Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Vanderlans, 60, who retired in September after 22 years as
a Toronto bus driver, and his wife selected the Rio Grande Valley
over Florida for their first extended winter vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the weather, we like the prices, we like the people.
The people in the stores are awfully friendly,'' 56-year-old Ann
Vanderlans observed as she sat in a lawn chair in shorts and a
sleeveless top. ``This beats the snow. I'll take it any time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sentiment tourism officials in the Valley _ and in the
state capital _ are hoping will translate into more Canadian
tourists. Even though the Canadian dollar has sunk to historic lows
_ now worth just 65 cents in this country _ Texas last year saw a
modest 3 percent rise in Canadian visitors.
</P>
<P>
   To lure more Canadians this winter, the Texas Department of
Economic Development launched its first international promotion in
October. The department held news conferences in major Canadian
cities and is running ads on television and in six major regional
newspapers. It is also offering a free coupon book called
``Buckaroo Bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   For Texas, the benefits of increased tourism are considerable.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley alone, an estimated 120,000 so-called Winter
Texans took up residence in more than 800 trailer parks and other
forms of housing during the winter of 1997. The visitors were
mostly Midwestern retirees from Illinois, Iowa, Michigan and
Minnesota; 7 percent were Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Winter Texans have become a &UR;  &LR; bonanza to an impoverished border
region whose agricultural economy is periodically decimated by
droughts and freezes, and a commercial sector often flattened by
abrupt devaluations of the Mexican peso. But each fall, the Valley
can count on an infusion of law-abiding, affluent retirees who not
only fill cash registers but also swell the ranks of volunteers at
hospitals, schools and nonprofit agencies by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   University researchers who survey and study the Winter Texans
estimate the retirees spent $319 million on food, rent, gas, cars,
homes and entertainment in the four-county Valley last year. A full
30 percent, or 36,000, said they had served as volunteers in the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting the Winter Texan season to be strong,
including the Canadians,'' predicts Cheryl La Berge, vice president
of the Harlingen Chamber of Commerce. ``If they go south, they have
to go somewhere, and the Valley is a very appealing destination.
Quite honestly, their dollar will go farther than most places in
the American South.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't get an argument from the Vanderlans or their Canadian
friend Jannie Van Schagen, who has spent the last seven winters at
Fun N Sun and invited the Vanderlans down for brief visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find Florida very commercial, and the Valley isn't. The
best way to put it is they're too stuck-up. You don't seem to fit
in particularly well there,'' Van Schagen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one important thing _ it's cheaper here.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a state income tax, low rent and housing costs
compared to Arizona and Florida, bargain prices for fruits and
vegetables grown in Valley groves and fields, and the proximity to
shopping in Mexico all help reduce living expenses for retirees on
a fixed income.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Vern Vincent, who directs the Center for Tourism
Research at the University of Texas-Pan American at Edinburg, notes
that the number of Winter Texans has increased in the Valley an
average of 24 percent over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is phenomenal growth,'' Vincent said. ``We have no reason
to think it's going to be anything but continued growth. You've got
more retirees, and they have better health and more financial
resources than they've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent said growth could only be stymied if Valley recreational
vehicle parks run out of space, noting that the average occupancy
was 97 percent and a fourth of the parks were completely full
during the last survey in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend Vincent and fellow researchers found is that
Winter Texans are spreading out from the trailer parks, with a full
25 percent in 1997 either staying in motels, renting houses or
apartments, buying condominiums or staying with friends. That was a
10 percent increase from the previous survey in 1995, Vincent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about it, they contribute. They give far
more than they take away,'' Vincent said of the northern visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, state tourism managers say they have been kept busy
answering Canadian responses to the advertising and coupon book
campaign launched in October. Texas Department of Economic
Development figures show 15 percent of some 509,000 Internet
requests for the Texas State Travel guide (between Oct. 1 and Nov.
5) were from Canadians, and Canadians made 62 percent of the 16,000
calls to the state's toll-free information line.
</P>
<P>
   And more than 15,000 Canadians were mailed the ``Buckaroo
Bucks'' coupon book, which provides discount rates at hotels and
motels, restaurants and state parks across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberley Baker, U.S. and Canada project coordinator at the
development agency, said the Canadian campaign is making its mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be effective, just because of the
response we've seen so far on our toll-free line and some of the
comments we're getting on the Web site,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian marketing firm, TravMark Group Inc., was hired three
years ago by state officials to help promote Texas tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalyn Hunter, communications manager for the Toronto firm,
noted that 278,900 Canadian tourists of all kinds, including
retirees, came to Texas in 1997. That is second only to Mexico in
the number of international visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the diversity Texas offers is something great for
Canadians. There's so much in one state to see,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many vacation options in Texas, whether you're a
senior wanting a long stay on the Gulf Coast or more adventurous
and want to go river-rafting in the Big Bend, or someone who wants
to do a big city and go to Houston and Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians interviewed had seen Texas' advertising campaign
and called Austin for the travel guide and coupon book. But they
said they decided to winter in South Texas at the urging of friends
or acquaintances who had visited before.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Beauregard, a 57-year-old retired schoolteacher from
Montreal, and his wife, Claudette, who is 56, arrived in the Valley
on Nov. 27 in their small motor home. They towed a compact car and
had a pair of bicycles on roof racks.
</P>
<P>
   They had never heard of Harlingen, but consulting the tour book,
they picked out the Sunshine RV park at random. ``I looked at the
name of the campground, and it was just a feeling,'' recalled
Claudette.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a quick look at the park, they decided to stay
until April. ``I saw the palm trees, and it was clean. So we
stopped here and stayed here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Beauregards have made monthlong visits to Key West and Key
Largo during previous winter trips, but last winter they happened
to meet a woman at a ski resort near their Montreal home who
extolled the charms and low prices of South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she had a lot of fun,'' Benoit said with a laugh as
he lay next to the resort's hot tub, ``so we are trying to have a
lot of fun, too.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
