<P>
   BANK-Y2K BUG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Year 2000 computer bug bit Bank One
Texas a little early. And it all happened because the bank was
trying to make sure that it would not have computer problems with
the new millennium. The bank confirmed this week that it had
accidentally mailed out notices to 2,013 Texas customers saying
they had bounced checks. The notices were generated because Bank
One wanted to make sure that its computers were Year 2000
compliant, meaning that they could recognize the difference between
1900 and 2000. The notices carried a post-2000 date. By DAN PILLER.
Story will move in ``f'' financial category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-SUITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The long, costly legal battle over expanded
service at Dallas' Love Field is making it tough for Legend
Airlines to get its business off the ground. Legend President Allan
McArtor, who wants to offer long-haul service from Love, says the
company is not facing a cash crunch. But a Legend source who asked
not to be identified said the company has been carefully conserving
its cash since October, when a state judge issued an initial ruling
against the long-haul service from Love. By DAN REED AND MAX B.
BAKER. Story will move in ``f'' financial category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
