<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2796 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-HANUKKAH-BOS     12-16 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-HANUKKAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWS CONCERNED BY HANUKKAH'S COMMERCIALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Laurie Bloom's 8-year-old daughter wanted a new menorah for
Hanukkah, the Newton, Mass. mother made sure not to go anywhere
near the Mickey Mouse versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just going a little too far for me,'' said Bloom.
Instead, her daughter chose a much more traditional _ and staid _
Hanukkah candelabrum made from pewter. ``It's beautiful and
definitely not kitschy,'' she said. ``No Mickey for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Jews around the world celebrate Hanukkah, Mickey and
other cash-ins are harder to avoid, as the festival has become a
merchandising bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Although the holiday is not as religiously important as Yom
Kippur or Rosh Hashana, Jews worry that the meaning of Hanukkah is
falling victim to rampant commercialization surrounding Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   This year Disney has licensed not one but five different Mickey
menorahs _ not to mention three Winnie the Pooh designs, all
ranging in price from $70 to $90.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Curious George musical water ball, which shows
the famed fictional primate lighting Hanukkah candles. Wind up the
ball and it plays the classic Hanukkah tune, ``Maoz Tsur,'' or
``Rock of Ages.'' Go to any of the 81 Starbucks coffee shops in New
England and find Hanukkah goodies, including a Hanukkah travel mug.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, Jews flock to stores, flip through catalogs,
and surf the Internet to stock up on gifts and decorations for the
eight-day festival of lights, which celebrates the victory of a
small band of Jews over a massive Greek army in the second century
B.C.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a California-based company is even offering Jews a
chance to order dog biscuits shaped like a dreidel, a four-sided
Hanukkah top. Drive down some streets and you'll see homes
decorated with outdoor blue and white Hanukkah lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we've made Hanukkah into the Jewish Christmas
with all the whistles and bells,'' said Ilene Springer, who lives
in Brookline and has two children. ``But Hanukkah isn't Christmas.
It's supposed to celebrate freedom of religion, not the freedom, it
seems to me, to go crazy at the mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, say it is hard to stay out of the mall,
especially when Jewish children see their Christian friends getting
Christmas gifts or writing wish lists to Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Hanukkah's importance in America has been inflated,
there is a growing backlash among some Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Temple Emanuel in Newton, for example, the largest Conservative
congregation in New England, is going against the tide and
deliberately downplaying the holiday by not scheduling any special
Hanukkah celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   And many parents are trying to tone down the materialism by
giving gifts to their children on only one night as opposed to all
eight nights, as other parents do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of stuff,'' said Marla Choslovsky, who has two
children. ``My daughter's birthday was in October and she still
hasn't even opened all those gifts yet. She doesn't need more
stuff. So we're going to give her tickets to the ballet and our son
tickets to a hockey game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom not only gives her children only one gift, but makes sure
it's a Judaica item, such as a menorah or a yarmulke, the
traditional skullcap for men and boys. ``When other kids call them
up and say they got Nintendo, I want my kids to say they got a
menorah,'' Bloom says.
</P>
<P>
   Some families also are taking the money they would use to buy
presents and giving it to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Yosef I. Abramaowitz of Newton gives each of his two daughters a
dollar bill for each day of Hanukkah, to put in envelopes from
charities. Then, he tells them what the charities are about and
lets them decide where to donate the money.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Jews who are merchants acknowledge that Hanukkah may
have been overinflated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for business, but is it getting a little too much?''
said Avohom Levine, manager of the Israel Book Shop, a large
Judaica store in Brookline, Mass. ``Maybe. Ten years ago we maybe
sold 10 different kinds of dreidels. Now we have about 40. It is
the single biggest Jewish holiday in terms of gift giving.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewish religious leaders are split on the issue. Many decry what
they consider to be commercialism and pressure to keep up with the
Christmas rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain irony to what has happened with Hanukkah,''
said Rabbi Andrew Warmflash, spiritual director of Temple Emanuel
in in Newton. ``We celebrate the victory of the Maccabees and their
refusal to assimilate into the dominant Hellenistic culture. And
now we are sort of mimicking the dominant culture by making it this
big commercial enterprise. We're making Hanukkah exactly what it
was not intended to be.
</P>
<P>
   But other rabbis believe elevating Hanukkah into a major
celebration fits in with the message of the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to publicize the miracle of Hanukkah and how
the weak overcame the mighty,'' said Rabbi William Hamilton of
Congregation Kehillath Israel in Brookline. ``We don't light these
candelabras on the Boston Common or in front of the State House
because we're trying to get equal time with Christmas. We do that
to publicly proclaim that Jews have survived and preserved their
identity through the ages in spite of whatever odds they have
faced.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine notes that many of his customers are in interfaith
marriages and are buying Jewish gifts to ``make sure that their
kids do not forget about their tradition. This could be seen as a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Jonathan E. Kraus, spiritual leader of Beth El Temple
Center in Belmont, Mass., believes there should be a balance to
Hanukkah celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of trying to resist Hanukkah, perhaps we could make
sure that if it is going to be enlarged in scope that we observe it
in the right way, rather than succumbing to commercialization,''
Kraus said. ``Use it to emphasize the notion of charity and
justice. Use it as a time to reflect on ways we respond to the
pressures of assimilation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
