<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARDINAL-ANNIVERSARY-     12-16 1454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDINAL-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW AT 76: PORVRAIT OF A LEADER TRANSFORMED 
</HEADLINE>
\   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When he came to Boston more than 14 years ago, Cardinal
Bernard Law wasted little time making his hard line position on one
of the nation's most explosive issues perfectly clear.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public appearance inside Holy Cross Cathedral
before hundreds of bishops and a small army of journalists, Law
called abortion the ``primordial evil of our day.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a memorable line that foreshadowed the strident and very
public broadsides Law frequently launched during his early years as
leader of the fourth largest archdiocese in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   As he celebrates 25 years as a bishop in the Roman Catholic
Church, Law recently reflected on the successes, disappointments
and challenges of his tenure as the eighth archbishop of the
Archdiocese of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, those who know him, say Law, 67, is a different
leader now than he was in his earlier years here.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they said, Law came across as an agressive and stern
moralist using church teachings to scold and lecture everyone from
former Gov. Michael Fukakis to then Lieutenant Gov. Paul Cellucci
to leaders of the Boston public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1986, he chided Dukakis for speaking to an abortion
rights rally in Boston saying, through a spokesman, that he was
``less than pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in 1991, Law said Cellucci should not be allowed to speak
at Hudson Catholic High School, Cellucci's alma mater, because the
then lieutenant governor supported a woman's right to an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, as he has emerged as one of the nation's
most prominent and influential Catholic churchmen, Law, has toned
down the volume of his rhetoric, say some colleagues and others qho
have worked with the prelate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there has been a sort of mellowing,'' said the
Reverend Walter H. Cuenin, pastor of Our Lady Help of Christians, a
large parish in Newton.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Law has wavered one bit on issues he has
frequently been outspoken about, ranging from abortion to the death
penalty to US policy on Cuba. But, observers say, Law is less prone
to engage in public battles than he was when he came to Boston as a
fairly unknown archbishiop from a diocese of less than 50,000 in
southern Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the head of over 2 millikn Roman Catholics in the
archdiocese tends to work on more issues behind the scenes than in
front of the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Law acknowledges that _ perhaps _ his style, but not his
position, has changed. ``If that's the case, it isn't the case by
design or strategy,'' said Law, in an interview inside(the
cardinal's sprawling Brighton residence. ``It might be the case by
age. It might be the fact that when I was the new kid on the block
people tended to cover what I had to say more often than they do
now. I think what I've been saying has been quite consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Law adds, ``I don't think it's my job to be a culture
cop. My job is to teach about the Lord, about the church and about
how we should live our lives as Catholics as convincingly as I can.
If you have that as your prime focus, you're not going to leave
that to respond to every blip that comes across your radar screen.
If something is particularly obnoxious, then I'll try and react but
I think others should be doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, observers say, Law has become a savvy politician with a
keen talent for cultivating relationships with people in key
positions, even with those he sometimes tangles with.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he worked with US Rep. Joseph Kennedy to secure
federal funding for hepatitis vaccinations for poor people in the
Boston area. Law also made a visit to the State House to asj
Cellucci for National Guard planes to ferry supplies to Honduras,
which was ravaged last month by Hurricane Mitch. Neither of these
two episodes made the news, but they are good examples of how Law
can make t`ings happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things that you do effectively you're not going to be
able to do all the time in the public arena,'' Law said. ``You have
to network in order to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Phelan, executive vice president of the giant real estate
firm, Meredith and Grew, and one of the many movers and shakers in
Boston that Law can call upon, saqs: ``I think his Rolodex would
challenge anybody's in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Law also has used this archdiocese, which is considered one of
the key Catholic communities in America, as a springboard to become
a well-known and highly-regarded international spokesman,
particularly on issues affecting Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   He has played a vital role in strenghtening the Catholic church
in Cuba, traveling regularly to one of the world's last Communist
strongholds, enjoying a close friendship with Cardinal Jaime Ortega
of Havana and regularly sending money and medical supplies to the
island nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt Cardinal Law is a respected leader in the
Catholic Church,'' said Rev. Thomas Reese, an expert on church
hierarchy and editor of America, a Jesuit magazine.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, in fact, there has been speculation(that Law
could be headed for the Vatican, not necessarily as pope _ most
Vatican insiders say fear of granting too much power to the United
States leaves little chance of an American pope anytime soon _ but
as head of a pontifical agency. 
</P>
<P>
   At the same time as his international prestige has grown, Law's
critics say he has failed to pay sufficient attention to problems
at home, such as the declining number of priests end growing number
of Catholics who feel alienated from the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as keyed in to local affairs as other bishops of
Boston perhaps have been,'' said Thomas H. O'Connor, emeritus
professor history at Boston College and author of ``Boston
Catholics: A History of the Church and Its People.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than 14 years at the seat of power, Law remains an
enigma to many Catholics, a churchman who can adroitly articulate
and defend thm church's position on welfare reform, for example,
but a pastor who has not really made a strong personal connection
with his flock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's been very open to talking with Catholics
who disagree with some of the church's practices,'' said Dot
Landry, of North Reading, and a former local leader of Call to
Action, a national church reform group that advocates, among other
things, married and women priests.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Landry said, Law did not respond to an invitation
to attend Call to Action New England's annual conference. Law has
said repeatedly that there is little room for discussion on church
teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know him say Law can come across to strangers as
somewhat aloof, that's just one side of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In public, the official side of him is very formal and less
personally revealing,'' Cuenin said. ``But when you get to know him
as a person you realize he is a warm, compassionate !nd friendly
man.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, observers say, it would be impossible to have much
of a rapport in an archdiocese of Boston's size.
</P>
<P>
   And Law's defenders say he has not ignored critical issues such
as the falling numbers of priestw. Indeed, earlier this year Law
said he expected to close 40 to parishes by the year 2006, in part,
because of the shrinking supply of priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's conscious of the realities he faces,'' O'Connor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps where Law has had the biggest impact locally is on
parlaying his clout and his networking skills into tangible
results, whether it be raising money to build AIDS hospices,
working with black clergy on youth programs or improving relations
with Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Law is one of the best connected leaders in Boston who can count
among his friends people like Jack Connors, the public relations
guru, Thomas Flatley, the real estate developer and Peter Lynch,
the investment wizard at Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the cardinal calls, I take it right away,'' said Phelan,
who helped chair a party Law hosted last spring that raised several
hundred thousand dollars for archdiocesan programs. ``He could
easily be running any number of Fortune 500 companies. He's tough
to say no to.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Connors said, Law has drawn from the strong
tradition of charity among Jews to convince some Catholic civic and
business leaders to become more generous in providing financial aid
to the archdiocese. One well-known local businessman, for instance,
recently gave Law $50,000 to provide relief to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has grown into the job and became a very powerful person,
but he understands how to use that power for good,'' said Connors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
