A2814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-16 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING LEAVES COLUMNIST SUBDUED, RESPECTFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have decided to perform a service for the schoolchildren of
Massachusetts. I have taken the much-dreaded Massachusetts
Comprehensive Assessment System (MCAS) test.
</P>
<P>
   But first _ what exactly is the MCAS? A full-employment scheme
for PhD-wielding education ``experts''? Yes. A ludricrous, $20
million boondoggle ``revealing'' that lily-white suburbs like
Harvard, Medfield, and Wayland, primarily populated by lawyers,
junior executives, and Globe staffers, have good schools? Yes. A
subject of mindless chatter for shiftless soccer moms, lacking for
conversation topics now that Louise Woodward has crawled back under
her rock? Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   But just as important, it is one more stick for lazy teachers
and apathetic parents to beat kids over the heads with. Because
that's really what the headlines are screaming, isn't it? ``You
dummies! You're so stupid! When I was your age blah blah blah . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, take heart, young people. I know you've been frittering
your lives away playing video games like Crusader: No Remorse. And
I've seen you stare slack-jawed at Dave Matthews music videos, and
ogling Adam Sandler and Neve Campbell movies. But who am I to
criticize? As it happens, I'm no smarter than you.
</P>
<P>
   What's the MCAS like? Think: ``Jeopardy!'' from hell. It's
divided into three parts _ English, Math, and Science and
Technology _ combining multiple-choice questions with short- and
long-form essay responses. I chose to take the 10th-grade test in
Math and Science and Technology. I skipped the English test,
figuring I'd ace it. What's more, I couldn't bear to read that
turgid excerpt from the wrong Tom Wolfe, which was printed in the
Globe a few days ago, one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Schoolchildren had 17 45-minute blocks to take the test, or, um,
let's see . . . about 12 hours, right? I took a little bit less
time, partly to minimize the damage to my weekend, and partly to
avoid penning long essays on such subjects as the chemical
transformation of moistened steel wool, on which I can safely plead
total, complete, and utter ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of questions invoking the median and the mean
_ is there a difference? _ I thought I performed creditably on the
Math. I got 24 out of 27 right on the multiple choice, half of the
short-answer questions, and again half of the open-response, i.e.
essay questions. When Question 39 invited me to peruse the attached
trigonometric tables, I scrawled ``NO CREDIT'' across the page and
switched on the last few moments of the Patriots debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Science and Technology promised to be another kettle of fish.
When the Globe printed a sample question about the eukaryotic cell,
whatever that is, that put me on guard. But yet again, I thought I
acquitted myself with honor. I answered 22 of 29 multiple-choice
questions correctly, even the one that alluded to ``TIF computing
systems,'' a term that _ are you listening, Mr. Silber? _ doesn't
exist. (If you enter the phrase into FOLDOC, the Free Online
Dictionary of Computing, you get ``no match.'' Could they have
meant TIFF, tagged image file format? Or does TIF refer to what the
Chambers Dictionary of Science and Technology calls T.I.F. _
telephone interface factor? But that doesn't make sense . . .)
</P>
<P>
   I answered fewer than half of the Science and Technology essay
questions. I could handle the physics of the tennis ball, but when
confronted with questions about semi-permeable membranes and the
mutant DNA strand actttgac _ hey, have pity, already!
</P>
<P>
   How did I do? Jeffrey Nellhaus, the Department of Education's
director of standards, delivered the bad news. In Math, I got a
246, rendering me ``proficient.'' Proficient?! Twenty-four out of
27 on the multiple choice, and you're calling me proficient? I have
a college degree! ``Multiple-choice tests tend to overestimate what
people can do,'' Nellhaus told me. ``I think now we have a truer
picture of your math ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise in Science and Technology, Nellhaus told me that I
``just hit the cut point for proficient'' with a score of 248.
``Not bad,'' he continued, sensing the damage to my normally
healthy sense of self-esteem. ``I think you did very well for
someone who's been away from these ideas for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Like my intellectual peers, I think I'll go drown my sorrows in
``The Waterboy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
