<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MAHONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY MOTHER, MYSELF _ AND LILLIAN HELLMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHFIELD, Mass. _ When Rosemary Mahoney was 17, in the summer
of 1978, she worked as housekeeper and cook for the writer Lillian
Hellman whom she had admired for ``her bravery, her strength and
her intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she says now, ``what I thought I saw in her, I already had
in my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney, now 37 and a writer herself, has written a memoir of
that summer on Martha's Vineyard, ``A Likely Story,'' published
last month by Doubleday. But, reflecting the fact that it is her
mother who possessed those qualities of bravery, strength and
intelligence, ``A Likely Story'' became, in large part, an account
of the role which her mother, Nona Rohan Mahoney, played in her
growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really wanted to write about,'' Mahoney said, ``was
being 17.'' And while the summer with Hellman provided ``the
catalyst for writing about what was happening to me,'' Mahoney
said, ``my mother became a big part of the story as well.''
</P>
<P>
   It was actually Mrs. Mahoney who urged her daughter to write to
Hellman about working for her on the Vineyard. Rosemary, then a
student at St. Paul's School, had expressed her admiration for
Hellman _ and her complete uninterest in working behind the counter
at a local Howard Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite all the resentment which Mahoney felt towards
Hellman as the summer staggered from one humiliation to another, it
was a comment which Hellman made, Mahoney recalls _ that allowed
her to express for the first time, and to an outsider, her deep
feelings about her mother.
</P>
<P>
   One noontime, Hellman surprised Mahoney by asking if she'd like
to have lunch with her. And as they worked together in the kitchen,
Hellman _ for the first and only time that summer _ asked Mahoney
about her family.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney told her about her mother being a widow, crippled with
polio, and raising seven children _ but not that she was an
alcoholic, a shaming fact that Mahoney had desparately kept hidden
from feiends and classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brave woman,'' Hellman said. ``She must be very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The words, and the sincerity with which she spoke them,
``glittered in the air before me like a small gift,'' Mahoney
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is,'' Mahoney told Hellman. And, she recalls, ``I knew it
was true. She was stronger than anyone I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both Rosemary Mahoney and her mother had a rose-tinted
expectation of what the summer would be. ``I thought they'd be
rocking in chairs on the porch, talking about books,'' Mrs. Mahoney
said. And Rosemary, concurring, added ``I guess I thought we'd be
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out that way. Rosemary Mahoney admits she was
``woefully unsuited'' for the housekeeping job and had absolutely
no idea of how to prepare the gourmet meals that Hellman expected.
Not only didn't she know how to make sorrel soup, one summer day,
but she didn't even know what sorrel was _ or what sorrel would
look like growing in Hellman's garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were stubborn,'' Mrs. Mahoney said, ``and so was she.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it was,'' her daughter agreed, ``a contest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hellman which the schoolgirl Mahoney had admired from
reading her memoirs, ``An Unfinished Woman'' and ``Pentimento,''
turned out to be vain and acerbic and a mean-spirited employer. And
the summer, one of continued humiliation when she was sent on
errands _ or attempted, unsuccessfully, to cash her paycheck, which
Hellman had made out to ``cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, in one humiliating incident, Mahoney recalls being sent to
ask writer John Hersey's cook for help when she spoiled botched a
batch of cookies being prepared for an afternoon tea-time visit
from Carly Simon and James Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't grow up in the country, did you,'' Hellman says
offhandedly one day. Mahoney actually had, with woods and fields
behind the house in Milton. ``You don't seem to recognize
vegetables,'' Hellman says by way of explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney recalls that ``ridiculous postulation infuriating her
more than anything else Hellman had said all summer,'' and asks
what hadn't she recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mint, for one,'' Hellman says.
</P>
<P>
   And Mahoney, ``mind furiously scrambling for a defense,''
replied, ``Mint isn't a vegetable.'' And Hellman crumples her
napkin, crushes her cigarette, in her eyes what Mahoney saw as ``a
studied expression of amused boredom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney has been criticized for writing harshly and judgmentally
about a American literary icon. She could have been equally harsh
and judgmental about her mother, now 75.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mahoney, society editor of the Boston Post when she was in
her 30s, before leaving to raise a family, had been a social
drinker. ``The cocktail parties made it legitimate,'' she said. The
serious drinking started after her husband died when Rosemary, the
youngest of her seven children, was 7. ``Then, the only guests at
my cocktail parties were the alcohol and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But she stopped drinking years ago. ``I just grew out of it,''
she said. ``I never went to AA or anything like that.'' And
Rosemary Mahoney, spending a morning in Marshfield with her mother,
adds, ``I think I stopped worrying about your drinking about 15
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things I feel proud about my mother for,''
Rosemary Mahoney said, ``that she's willing to talk about it. That
takes courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Mahoney recalls a Chicago Tribune reporter who
interviewed her a few weeks ago, following the publication of ``A
Likely Story.'' She told Mahoney that its didn't seem ``nice'' for
her to have written so bluntly about her mother's drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ashamed,'' Rosemary Mahoney said she told the
interviewer. ``And she's not ashamed,''
</P>
<P>
   But back in 1978 and the years before that when Rosemary Mahoney
was growing up in Milton, in a houseful of older brothers and
sisters, she was so ashamed of her mother that she would jump
quickly into the car when her mother picked her up at school,
rather than let her classmates see her drunk.
</P>
<P>
   And fearful. She remembers times _ long before she had a
driver's license _ when she would slide over and take the wheel of
the car away from her mother as she drifted into a drunken stupor.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney graduated from Harvard in 1983 and is now 37, with two
previous books in her credits, ``The Early Arrival of Dreams,'' an
account of a year teaching English at a provincial college in China
which was a New York Times notable book in 1990, and ``Whoredom in
Kimmage,'' a gritty study of the changing role of Irish women which
was a National Book Critics Circle finalist in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And on a late-fall morning earlier this month, Rosemary Mahoney
has driven up to Marshfield from her apartment just off the
Providence, R.I. waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Marshfield holds memories of happy summers, and also of the very
protective feeling Rosemary Mahoney had for her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming was the only athletic activity Mrs. Mahoney was able to
continue after being crippled by polio. As both she and Rosemary
recall, she would wade thigh-deep into the ocean, then call for
someone to come take her crutches.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Mahoney had made sure all the children could swim
because of her inability to rescue them _ and dressed them all in
red swimsuits ``so I could look out and count them'' _ Rosemary
would stand on the beach while her mother was swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling,'' Rosemary Mahoney said to her mother as she
talked about those days, ``was not only that you couldn't save me,
but that you'd drown and I couldn't save you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
