<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-16 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISDOM MIXED WITH CARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Five years have passed since Leo Williams left General
Electric Co., but the Boston financial services executive has not
forgotten the advice he received from his mentor at GE.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was working as a mechanical engineer in the Wisconsin
division when he decided he wanted to become a manager. He
mentioned his goals to James Shepard, general manager of GE's
global X-ray tubes and detectors business, and Shepard suggested he
go to business school. That meeting proved to be a turning point in
Williams' career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim helped me make the best moves within the company, and
within my own objectives, which was to move from engineering into
management,'' said Williams, 37, president of Williams &AMP; Associates
Investments in Boston. ``He was a black man, a senior manager who
took an interest in me. I looked up to him. We bonded. By the time
I left in 1993, he had been promoted to general manager.''
</P>
<P>
   How important are mentors? ``They are definitely critical to
professional success,'' says Ann Bartels, a professor of labor
economics and human resources at Columbia University's School of
Business.
</P>
<P>
   Bartels is among several researchers at Columbia University and
Korn/Ferry, a worldwide executive search firm, who took part in a
1998 study of the professional lives of 280 minority achievers
whose annual salaries range from $100,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   When Bartels interviewed the respondents, she was struck by the
fact that 50 percent had had a mentor, or a series of mentors, who
played a significant role in their work lives. Seventy-percent had
informal mentors, while 20 percent said they had formal mentors who
were assigned to them by employers. Additionally, a majority spoke
of role models who had encouraged achievement in childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each case, mentors actively advocated for the promotion of
the executive,'' said Bartels. ``They introduced the executive to
important formal and informal networks; they helped explain the
informal rules of the organization, the unwritten rules no one ever
tells you about. They also provided important advice about career
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the respondents, 161 were African-American, 63 were Asian, 43
were Hispanic, and 13 belonged to other nonwhite racial categories.
Seventy-six percent were men; 24 percent were women.
</P>
<P>
   All were employed by a Fortune 500 company or a financial
institution among the top 200 in the country as measured by assets.
Moreover, all had high-ranking positions: 24 percent were general
managers, 19 percent were financial service or accounting
executives, and 16 percent were marketing or sales executives.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, 42, of Montclair, N.J., the GE mentor, said common
interests and a common background helped him forge a relationship
with Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leo and I went to Princeton. I graduated in 1978. He graduated
a few years later, but we were both part of the National Society of
Black Engineers,'' he recalled. ``I would come back to the campus
and give talks, which is how we met. We became friends. I worked in
aerospace at GE; he was in a different division, but we kept in
touch. Then, our paths crossed in GE's medical division.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point that Williams realized he wanted to become
a manager and was interested in the marketing and financial end of
the business. ``Based on what he had decided he wanted to do,''
said Shepard, ``I felt he should pursue the MBA even though he was
a good engineer. So, for him, the question became: What should I
do? Leave engineering to pursue a business career?''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Williams enrolled at Wharton Business School, but
remained at GE, which sent him overseas during a summer break to
work in a global division.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, in a large company there are different paths
and it can be difficult to determine which one to take,'' said
Shepard. ``Leo was an engineer in entry-level manufacturing and
could have continued in engineering, but he also could have
remained in manufacturing or gone into marketing. At that time, it
was unusual to switch from engineering to business and it really
required that he go and get an MBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartels, who included Williams in the Columbia
University-Korn/Ferry study, said the participants shared many
other characteristics. ``The majority were not from the middle
class, but were from two-parent, blue-collar families and, in 67
percent of the cases, both parents worked,'' said Bartels.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Miller, a managing director at the Stamford, Conn.,
office of Korn/Ferry, said the company got involved with the
research because many of its clients were looking for ways to
train, recruit, and retain minority executives.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, was surprised by some of the findings. ``Ninety
percent said they were better off financially today than they were
three years ago,'' said Miller. ``But the real surprise was that
about 50 percent said they would change companies for a greater
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them, the most important reasons to stay with a company
were that their talents and abilities were being utilized, they had
respect and authority, a supportive work environment, and that
there was a clear link between performance appraisals and career
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   A common thread among all the executives, Miller said, ``was
they all had developed successful strategies for dealing with
discrimination and their own career goals and advancement.''
</P>
<P>
   When faced with discriminatory actions by peers or midlevel
supervisors, they analyzed the situation and then developed a plan
for dealing with it. ``They also spoke directly to the person
involved in order to correct the situation,'' said Miller. ``Some
waited until the incident had passed, and then spoke separately and
individually to the person involved.''
</P>
<P>
   While others might have become embittered, these professionals
saw such incidents as an opportunity to learn how things were done
at the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The tendency to develop a plan and stick to it, attention to
detail, and the ability to discuss business issues with authority
while showing respect for other kinds of expertise and perspectives
were all instrumental in helping them achieve their career goals,
said Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, whose family is from Jamaica, grew up in New York
City, where he attended local public schools. His mother was an
elementary teacher who rose to assistant principal. His father was
an insurance inspector.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school and in junior high school, there were teachers
I looked up to, but I also looked up to my parents,'' said
Williams. ``In business, there were many different mentors along
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   (Diane Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
