<SLUG> BC-MITCH-AFTERMATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY CONTINUES TO STRUGGLE IN AFTERMATH OF HURRICANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIPITAPA, Nicaragua _ German Castro's neighbors are gone, having
escaped to refugee centers in nearby schools. Just a block closer
to Lake Managua, not a house remains.
</P>
<P>
   But Castro, his home flooded, his business destroyed by a
hurricane named Mitch, is sticking it out.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, with patience, determination and a little help from
cousins in San Francisco, figures to regain his livelihood and
rebuild the family home in Tipitapa for his seven children and
young grandson.
</P>
<P>
   With the city on the shores of Lake Managua and the Tipitapa
River, both swollen by torrential rain, there was no stopping the
flooding when the hurricane hit in late October. The Red Cross
estimates that 9,000 Tipitapa residents lost their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, which stalled over Central America for days, killed
more than 9,000 people and left as many as 2 million others
homeless in Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months later, the river still rushes through town.
Children use it as a swimming spot despite potential health
hazards. A block from Castro's house, the water is still
shoulder-high inside many homes.
</P>
<P>
   Residents now spend time in line, waiting for donations of food
and other basic items. Recently, the Red Cross handed out sacks of
rice and oats, along with cooking oil, a few plastic dishes,
toothpaste, toilet paper and soap. People haul the goods away on
city buses or in wheelbarrows, back to their shattered homes or
temporary shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The Castros were luckier than most because their home survived.
Nevertheless, the kitchen and bedrooms were flooded, and the shop
where Castro sold soft drinks and snacks, his main livelihood, was
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these conditions, Castro, whose wife of 35 years died
last year, making him sole caretaker for their children aged 12 to
25, didn't want to leave his home. With such a large family, moving
to a shelter would have been difficult, and leaving his home and
belongings unprotected would have been dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The Castros have found ways to adapt. Family members moved their
beds into a wide hallway where they sleep side-by-side. One
daughter, though, found the conditions too dangerous for her
3-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   So Doris Castro, 23, and her son moved to a friend's house in
another part of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many diseases down there. I don't want my boy to
get sick,'' she said of the flood zone surrounding her father's
home. ``There's cholera, dengue, and the water's polluted. There
are millions of mosquitoes.''
</P>
<P>
   German Castro wonders where he will find the money to repair his
little shop and to whom he will sell Pepsis now that the
neighborhood is nearly empty. Still, with the help of his older
children, he hopes to keep the family fed and healthy and to
rebuild their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be father and mother to these kids now,'' Castro
said.
</P>
<P>
   His spirits were lifted two weeks ago when he received $150 from
two cousins in San Francisco, though with nine mouths to feed, it
won't last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's first-cousin, Laura Perez, said she wished she could do
more for her family in Nicaragua. On a recent afternoon, she
slipped into the chapel at St. Luke's Hospital in San Francisco
where the medical secretary prayed for her relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Perez grew up in Nicaragua but has been back only twice since
she moved to the United States in 1979. She has seen the damage of
Mitch only through news reports and her relatives' accounts.
</P>
<P>
   As Christmas approaches, German Castro has a wish list of things
he hopes his cousin can provide or maybe pray for: a pair of rubber
boots, a fishing pole to catch food for the family and someone to
call a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell her to send me a new wife in a package from San
Francisco,'' he joked wistfully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
