<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-PERNELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITAKER SIGNS ON TO MAKE COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than a year layoff following a suspension for twice
testing positive for drugs and alcohol, Pernell Whitaker will come
back to boxing with a bang Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Intense negotiations between promoters Don King and Dino Duva,
as well as executives at HBO, led to an agreement Tuesday for
Whitaker to meet International Boxing Federation welterweight
champion Felix Trinidad Feb. 20 on HBO, with the winner fighting
No. 1 contender Vincent Pettway, also on HBO, later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither fighter has yet signed, sources familiar with
the negotiation said, ``It's 90 percent done. What remains is not
significant, although in boxing, you always worry about these
things even after the contracts are signed.''
</P>
<P>
   The belief is that King has decided following his successful
negotiation with HBO for the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis
heavyweight title unification match that this is the time for him
to reacquaint himself with HBO, the largest cable outlet for boxing
_ and the most lucrative. King saw a 13-year relationship with HBO
disintegrate seven years ago in a power struggle when he tried to
force Time Warner executives not to use analyst Larry Merchant on
Mike Tyson telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   HBO and King had already agreed on a contract extension for
Tyson, but when the network backed Merchant, King took his fighter
to cable rival Showtime. Although King retains a connection with
Showtime, that relationship has cooled since King lost control of
Tyson last year. Tyson continues to fight for Showtime and in fact
signed a contract extension recently that will commence with his
Jan. 16 comeback fight vs. Frans Botha. But King no longer controls
him and appears to be trying to angle his top fighters into more
lucrative HBO contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker has not fought since winning a 12-round decision over
Andrei Pestriaev at Foxwoods Oct. 17, 1997. Following that bout,
Whitaker tested positive for an illegal substance and was
suspended. That suspension was later overturned, and Whitaker, once
hailed as the world's finest fighter, pound for pound, was set to
fight then World Boxing Association welterweight champion Ike
Quartey earlier this year. But he tested positive a second time
after agreeing to random testing as part of the deal to have the
suspension lifted. The fight was canceled, and Whitaker (41-2-1)
was suspended until September.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time world champion will be 35 next month and has not
looked sharp for nearly two years, so the Trinidad match is a
crossroads fight for him. If he wins, he would get Pettway and then
a likely rematch with Oscar De La Hoya, who defeated him in a
surprisingly close fight April 12.
</P>
<P>
   If Trinidad (33-0) wins, he would get Pettway as well as a
likely relationship with HBO but no immediate shot at De La Hoya.
That's because King does not want to negotiate such a match with
rival promoter Bob Arum without first having Trinidad in a near
parity situation with De La Hoya, HBO's most popular fighter. To do
that, King thinks, he must at least get him two of the three major
welterweight titles by matching him next fall with WBA champion
James Page, whom King also controls.
</P>
<P>
   That would also be a lucrative HBO fight. Beyond that, it would
allow King to enter into contract negotiations for a megabucks
unification match with De La Hoya on HBO in 2000 with Trinidad at
least controlling the majority of the titles at stake.
</P>
<P>
   But for any of that to happen, Trinidad first will have to get
by a wily old man named Pernell Whitaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
