<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RAT PACK; SPIN'S TOPS; WHO'S OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he's been dead seven months, we still aren't quite
ready to bury Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, there were news stories about the release of the
40-year confidential file the FBI kept on the entertainer,
especially in regards to his friendships with underworld figures.
Elaborate displays bearing stacks of his classic CDs still adorn
most record stores, and hardly a week goes by without some Sinatra
chestnut _ his scintillating duet with Ella Fitzgerald on ``The
Lady Is a Tramp,'' or such films as ``From Here to Eternity'' or
``Guys and Dolls'' _ flickering across our television screens. But
just as much attention has been paid to the man as well as the
artist. A few months ago, an academic conference on Sinatra was
held, and Pete Hamill, in his book, ``Why Sinatra Matters,'' said
the entertainer, through his ambitions, loves, and fears,
``indirectly changed the way all of us lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes American Heritage, and Max Rudin's ruminations on the
Rat Pack, the Sinatra-led group of entertainers _ Dean Martin,
Sammy Davis Jr., Peter Lawford, and Joey Bishop _ who turned Las
Vegas into a personal playground onstage and off in the late 1950s
and early 1960s. Rudin rehashes much of what is already known about
height of Sinatra's so-called ``Hat'' years: his infamous temper,
the Kennedy connection, and the Pack's often unbelievably boorish
behavior. But he also makes a convincing case for a method behind
all that ring-a-ding-ding madness. Sinatra, a proponent of civil
rights long before it became popular or fashionable, was presenting
in his multicultural Rat Pack, a ``giddy version of multiethnic
American democracy,'' where race and ethnicity were not only
featured, but flaunted. Comic bits that now seem offensive, such as
Martin picking up Davis and saying, ``I'm proud to accept this
award from the NAACP,'' had quite the edge at the time. The Rat
Pack thumbed its nose at the great racial divide by implying
relations had so improved we could joke about our differences. In
his way, Sinatra, Rudin writes, was ``teaching a lesson in American
possibilities.'' Not bad for a guy from Hoboken who often referred
to himself as ``just a saloon singer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This being December and all, we're up to our elbows in year-end
lists _ the best movies, the best sports moments, the best
explanations for what exactly constitutes a sexual relationship.
Spin has its annual Year in Music issue, featuring the 20 best
albums and 20 best singles. Anyone who heard Lauryn Hill's stunning
solo debut should not be surprised that her CD, ``The Miseducation
of Lauryn Hill,'' was selected best album of 1998. Writes Craig
Seymour of the record the 23-year-old wrote and produced, ``From
spirituals to Stevie Wonder to dancehall, Hill harvested the
history of black music for an idiosyncratic brew _ sing-song
melodies, edgy productions, enviable rhyme skills, back-to-church
vocals _ that definitely played to the people, but also challenged
them to meet her ambitions halfway.'' Seymour calls Hill, also
named Artist of the Year, ``one of the woefully few career artists
to emerge this year'' _ which says a lot, but also damns her with
faint praise when you consider this was also the year of such vapid
pretty-boy groups as Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables on the list: Garbage's sorely overlooked
sophomore effort, ``Version 2.0,'' (No. 9); ``Celebrity Skin,'' the
Hole album few us ever expected to see, let alone enjoy (No. 11);
and Fatboy Slim's cracking good ``You've Come A Long Way, Baby.''
Speaking of Fatboy Slim, also known as Norman Cook, his ``The
Rockefeller Skank'' clocks in as the mag's best single. Some may
argue that there were better singles this year, but really was
there anything more infectious than that ``Check it out now, the
funk soul brothers'' riff? And hey, does anyone remember the days
when singles were truly singles, and you could even buy them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere on Spin's list is George Michael, whose had quite the
naughty, if less than commercially successful, year. Back in April,
Michael was arrested for public lewdness after he played a game of
``I'll-show-you-mine-if-you-show-me-yours'' with an undercover cop
in a Los Angeles park. Since then he's finally come clean about his
sexuality (not that it should have been a surprise to anyone), and
has released a greatest-hits CD that has been largely ignored
stateside. Now, the singer who spent most of his career avoiding
comments about his sexuality is talking, talking, talking about his
sex life like there's no tomorrow, this time in Britain's cheeky Q.
Michael speaks frankly about his late lover, Brazilian designer
Anselmo Feleppa, who died of an AIDS-related brain hemorrhage in
1993, as well as of his current boyfriend, Kenny Goss, the most
patient partner this side of Hillary Clinton. He's rather
unrepentant about his arrest _ ``I've always liked having sex in
places I shouldn't have. I did it because I couldn't resist a free
lunch,'' Michael says. And he admits that having to come out
because of his arrest wasn't exactly the way he wanted to deal
publicly with his homosexuality. ``Running naked up and down Oxford
Street singing `I Am What I Am' would have been a more dignified
way to come out.'' Which is exactly why Michael should have come
out years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 1438EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
