<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY'S RETURNS SIZZLE, SALES FIZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of Fidelity Investments' biggest mutual funds are putting
up sizzling performance numbers this year. Peter Lynch's familiar
face is all over television, the financial pages, and business
magazines in maybe Fidelity's biggest ad blitz ever.
</P>
<P>
   And the sales of it most important product, its stock funds?
They're down right puny.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of strong investment gains and a big marketing push,
the world's largest mutual fund company finds itself looking up at
a host of smaller competitors who are taking far more new dollars
into their stock funds from investors.
</P>
<P>
   The gap is startling.
</P>
<P>
   According to Financial Research Corp., a Boston consulting firm,
Fidelity's equity funds through October recorded $2.7 billion in
net sales, or new money invested excluding redemptions and
transfers among Fidelity funds. Archrival Vanguard Group took in an
extraordinary $28.5 billion over the same period, FRC says, a
tribute to investors' growing commitment to Vanguard's specialty,
funds designed to track market indexes. In all, 10 fund complexes
took in more new equity dollars than Fidelity, including
Massachusetts Financial Services and Putnam Investments, which both
outsold Fidelity 3 to 1. Fidelity also trailed Vanguard in
fixed-income sales more than 2 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity would not comment for this column. But the FRC numbers
indicate that October was a particularly ugly month for the
Boston-based giant. Roughly $2.3 billion flowed out of the Fidelity
equity funds during the month at a time when Vanguard and MFS both
added $1.2 billion, FRC estimates. Fidelity previously said it was
having a better November, with about $3 billion coming into its
equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost like the Grand Canyon: It is kind of
breath-taking to see the difference between equity sales (at
Fidelity) this year vs. Vanguard,'' says James Lowell, editor of
Fidelity Investor, a newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Fidelity lagging?
</P>
<P>
   In part it has to do with investors' jitters about the market
and their resulting ``flight to safety,'' or low-risk investments.
For example, US money market funds took in far more cash than stock
funds through November. That is the first time money market funds,
which hold relatively safe government and corporate bonds, have
outsold equity funds since 1990. Fidelity has taken roughly $22
billion into its money market funds this year; last year the
company saw a net outflow from money funds.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity also has a problem that none of its rivals have: A
company with one of the best brand names in the world ironically
finds itself with virtually no brand names on the shelf to sell.
That oddity is a result of its decision to close some of its
biggest and best-selling funds to new investors. After years of
maintaining the big funds were manageable despite their increasing
heft, Fidelity changed direction last year, closing its flagship
Magellan. This year it has closed Growth &AMP; Income, Contrafund, and
Low-Priced Stock, all well-known and top-selling funds.
</P>
<P>
   Existing investors and those who had the funds in their 401k
retirement menus could continue to put money into them, but sales
have fallen off dramatically. Fidelity had only one fund _ the
top-performing Dividend Growth _ among the top 10 selling equity
funds, according to FRC. Two of Fidelity's best-selling equity
funds are index funds, long the province of Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't hear Dividend Growth and think of Fidelity,''
says Lowell. ``When you hear Magellan and Contrafund you think of
Fidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity slow sales come at a time that it is enjoying terrific
performance numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Big funds like Magellan, Growth &AMP; Income, Retirement Growth,
Large Cap Stock, Blue Chip Growth, and Advisor Equity Growth are
beating the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, the Holy Grail for
managers who actively pick stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, Fidelity's US equity funds are ranked number one by
return among the 10 largest fund families this year, according to
Kanon Bloch Carre, a Boston consulting firm. Fidelity's funds were
up 17.41 percent through November compared with number two
Vanguard, which was up 15.25 percent, says Kanon Bloch.
</P>
<P>
   After its highly publicized performance problems in 1996 and
early 1997, Fidelity has turned its results around by making a huge
bet on big-capitalization stocks. Fully 80 percent of Fidelity's
equity assets are in big-cap stocks, and many of the funds own many
of the same stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, the newsletter editor, believes Fidelity's sales
problems indicate just how much the world has changed for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fidelity used to be a name you could take to the bank,'' he
said. ``Today they have to earn their stripes, just like any other
fund company. They are earning their stripes, which I find
ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not enough investors are noticing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
