<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAL FEARLESSLY SEARCHES FOR ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After winning three Grammy awards for his graceful,
adult-soul music, the artist known as Seal is getting back on the
road for a much-awaited tour. He's played only one show so far this
year _ appropriately enough at the Gentleman's Quarterly awards in
New York _ but he was to play his second Wednesday in Boston as
part of KISS-108's Jingle Ball with Cher, Bryan Adams, Joe
McIntyre, and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fortunate,'' Seal said Tuesday during a rehearsal at
Avalon. ``The thing I enjoy most about performing live is the
connection with the audience. That's too euphoric to describe. But
the other thing is that I get a chance to work with such great
musicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Seal, who plans a full-scale tour in March, has a new, all-star
band with former Bruce Springsteen/Sting keyboardist David
Sancious, ace studio guitarist Michael Landau (who rarely tours),
and drummer Brian Blades, who last toured with Joni Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, his six-piece group ran through ``Human Beings,'' his
new single. The sumptuous sound flooded the room, while the
London-born Seal (whose real name is Sealhenry Samuel) sang ``It is
only love, I feel, that will give us peace of heart,'' before
adding, ``Tell me, is it death you fear?'' and ``We're mere human
beings, we die.''
</P>
<P>
   That's strong stuff by today's radio standards, but Seal is an
intensely spiritual man whose new album, ``Human Being,'' is about
his personal search for answers _ again, an uncommon theme in the
pop world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to respect life,'' says Seal, 35. ``We can't live in
an irresponsible way, as in the case of the two rappers, Tupac and
Notorious B.I.G., who had disrespect for life. If you play with
fire, you will die that way. We're not indestructible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the song is also saying that death is as much a part of
life as being born. We shouldn't spend a whole life fighting it. We
should embrace it as an integral part of life, rather than fearing
it as this void that will take us away.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album grapples with such issues as loss of faith and
loss of love (Seal has had a couple of romances go awry, including
a much-publicized one with supermodel Tyra Banks), but the ultimate
tone of his dreamily alluring album is quite positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me about the lyrics and what space I was in
when I wrote the songs,'' says Seal, sipping a cup of tea
backstage. ``They're just another chapter in my journal. I'm trying
to walk unafraid and be completely open.''
</P>
<P>
   For inspiration, Seal sees the West Coast-based Guru Singh, but
doesn't want people reading too much into that. ``He's a friend,''
Seal says. ``Some people have shrinks, some go to confession, some
stay at home and pray. For me, he's a guy you go to unload on.''
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Seal has unloaded a lot of hits, topped by
``Kiss from a Rose'' (from the ``Batman'' soundtrack), which in
1995 won record of the year, song of the year, and best male pop
vocal performance. He also scored a hit with a version of Steve
Miller's ``Fly Like an Eagle'' for the ``Space Jam'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   While Seal is known for his soundtrack successes, he is much
more personal in his sleekly understated solo albums, which have
been produced by ex-Buggle Trevor Horn.
</P>
<P>
   The new album requires some extra listening, but rewards the
effort. ``A lot of people say it's an introspective record,'' says
Seal. ``But in terms of content, I think it's fearless. I don't
mean in breaking musical barriers, but I'm striving constantly to
be more open and address certain issues in my soul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
