<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-BURNHAM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFTING THE VEIL OFF A RECLUSIVE GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ Shortly after being tapped to become chief
executive of Raytheon Co., Daniel P. Burnham gathered senior
managers in the company's sunny cafeteria and offered to answer
questions about himself and his plans for the defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Of the several hundred people seated in rows at that meeting
July 1, no one spoke up. Such gatherings, after all, had been rare.
Following an uncomfortable silence, Burnham told the meeting,
``That's OK, you'll get used to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was clear: Raytheon's new top officer aims to foster
a more open culture at an institution known for its Pentagon-style
secrecy under Dennis J. Picard, who formally turned over the title
of chief executive on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham's ascension comes at a crucial time for Lexington-based
Raytheon. He is just the fifth leader in its 76-year history, and
the first outsider brought in to take its helm. He takes over
following an acquisition spree last year that elevated the company
to the top tier of the defense industry, facing off with giants
Boeing Co. and Lockheed Martin Corp. Now, it's his job to ensure
Raytheon's growth amid tight military spending in a consolidated
defense industry.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Burnham must capitalize on the empire that Picard
built.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, 52, a midwesterner with an MBA and a penchant for fast
cars, intends to decentralize decision-making, reduce the company's
bureaucracy, and put Raytheon's 115,000 employees through a
quality-control training program. Another 14,000 defense workers
are scheduled to be laid off in coming months, a reduction Burnham
says is needed to improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, a productivity expert, took similar steps at his
previous job, heading the aerospace units of AlliedSignal Inc. in
southern California. But at Raytheon, Burnham's initiatives may run
contrary to the hands-on management style of Picard, an engineer
more comfortable with aircraft-weight memorandums than with Wall
Street analysts. At least, company insiders expect more focus on
financial analysis.
</P>
<P>
   One telling sign: behind Burnham's desk sit two sleek computer
screens displaying the latest stock quotes and headlines from
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned the technical side under one CEO and I'm going to
learn a hell of a lot of the financial side from another CEO,''
says William Swanson, chief of Raytheon's big defense business.
Warren Rudman, the retired New Hampshire senator who sits on
Raytheon's board, says Burnham's focus on new management techniques
will be a good fit for the newly bulked-up company. ``He's probably
right for the time,'' Rudman says.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last week, Burnham and Picard noted the outgoing
chief executive had already begun some of the reforms, which they
say could save Raytheon as much as $1 billion over the next several
years.
</P>
<P>
   Picard agrees he has been tight-lipped to employees and to Wall
Street analysts about Raytheon's plans. But he attributes his stern
reputation to securities trading rules he says gagged him.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he asks, ``What's better, building a $20 billion
company or being nice to the Street?''
</P>
<P>
   Burnham inherits a complex legacy at Raytheon, whose 15,000
employees in Massachusetts at the end of 1997 trailed only Bell
Atlantic Corp. and Stop &AMP; Shop Supermarket Co. among the Bay
State's largest employers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after becoming CEO in 1991, Picard tried to diversify
Raytheon into more civilian industries such as home appliances and
construction services to shield it from defense cutbacks. But he
switched course as military spending cuts following the end of the
Cold War prompted consolidation in the defense industry. Picard
says the company had to leap into the top echelon or be swamped by
competitors. In 1997, Raytheon spent $12.5 billion to buy large
defense units from Texas Instruments Inc. and Hughes Electronic
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The purchases will give Raytheon record revenue of about $20
billion this year, but they brought total debt to nearly $10
billion, putting pressure on earnings. To handle the integration of
the disparate units in California, Texas, and Arizona, board
members asked Picard to stay on as chief executive through 2000 or
so.
</P>
<P>
   Picard, now 66, says he declined because he had already stayed a
year longer than planned and had promised family members he would
step down to spend more time with his eight grandchildren. ``If I
was younger I would have accepted it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Raytheon named Burnham president and chief operating
officer last June and scheduled his appointment to become chief
executive this month. Sometime in 1999, Picard plans to turn over
the chairman's title as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the top job, Burnham will oversee a defense business _ which
represents about 75 percent of Raytheon's sales _ striving to win
Navy contracts worth billions of dollars to develop electronic gear
for destroyers and aircraft carriers. He also intends to improve
profits at the company's laggard engineering and construction unit,
which faces reduced demand for its power plant projects in Asia and
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts think Burnham's goals are realistic, but note the
company depends heavily on limited Pentagon budgets. ``I think
they're shrewd, but obviously they have to win the contracts that
are coming up,'' says Credit Suisse First Boston Corp. analyst
Peter Aseritis. He rates Raytheon a `buy' and expects shares to
rise to between $65 to $70 by 2000; Raytheon Class B shares closed
at 53 13/16 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham says the management transition is going smoothly and
that employees speak their minds more now than when he first
arrived. ``I can't shut them up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While Burnham grew up in a Detroit suburb, he has significiant
New England roots. His parents moved there from the Boston area
during World War II, and his father was a manager at General Motors
Corp. The younger Burnham graduated from the University of New
Hampshire in 1970 with a master's degree in business
administration. After a three-month Army stint, he went to work as
a budget analyst for a division of RCA Computer Services, in
Marlborough. But within a year, he was laid off, he recalls, an
experience he says ``was as disruptive as a death in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Broke, he was forced to move with his pregnant wife into the
home of his parents who had just retired to Atkinson, N.H. He
turned down the next job he was offered, with a local bank because
it seemed too dull.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my parents were going to kill me,'' he recalls.
Instead Burnham went to work for Carborundum Co., a maker of
abrasive materials, becoming its controller at age 28. He joined
AlliedSignal Inc. in 1982 and by 1991 was named to head its large
aerospace division based in Torrance, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, the units faced a dramatic downturn in
military orders and he oversaw the layoffs of more than 10,000
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked into a situation that was collapsing at a fast rate,
and he had to create a consensus and make some fast decisions,''
recalls Joe Leonard, a Burnham appointee at AlliedSignal. But he
also brought in many new managers, aiming to find new markets for
the company's aviation components.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to 1997, annual sales grew 42 percent to $6.4 billion
and profits rose 130 percent to $515 million, according to a book
that describes Burnham's experience, ``Every Business is a Growth
Business,'' by consultant Ram Charan and Noel M. Tichy, a professor
at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Boston over the summer, Burnham and his wife _ who now
have four grown children _ have rented an apartment in the
Financial District and are in the process of buying a Beacon Hill
townhouse. Burnham also brought his turbocharged Porsche from
California but regrets he doesn't have time to attend the
performance-driving courses he enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   At Raytheon, employees expect him to launch growth campaigns
similar to his initiatives at AlliedSignal. Along with the ongoing
Raytheon layoffs, Burnham replaced the company's top human
resources executive with General Electric Co. veteran Dennis
Donovan and named new legal and communications officers. Another
new vice president will be named this week, says Burnham, who adds
that he thinks the changes aren't so significant given Raytheon's
size.
</P>
<P>
   But on the shop floor, line employees say managers lately seem
more willing to discuss performance goals and attribute the changes
to Burnham. ``With Picard it was a like news blackout all the time.
You never knew where you stood,'' says Bill Guthrie, a Raytheon
electrician. Refering to Burnham, he says: ``It's amazing how
rapidly things can change.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon says increased communication with employees was taking
place before Burnham's arrival but only now is apparent to workers.
Picard himself says contact with line workers during the last six
months was ``a void'' because the company hadn't yet reorganized
following last year's multibillion-dollar acquisitions. ``We didn't
have anything to tell them,'' Picard says.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham also faces questions about just what obligations the
company took on in 1995, when state lawmakers granted its request
for large reductions in taxes and utility bills in exchange for
keeping its payroll and property holdings at certain levels in the
state. Picard told lawmakers those cuts were needed to keep its
missile plants in the state competitive. But in October, Raytheon
said it would lay off 1,200 in the state and close a large plant in
Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   The decision angered previous allies like Waltham Mayor Bill
Stanley, who now says he feels used for having testified on
Raytheon's behalf. Burnham says that's unfair because the tax cuts
improved the economic climate overall and says the company can
avoid further layoffs by improved productivity.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Picard says he will stay on the board, if asked,
after he steps down as chairman next year. Meanwhile, he plans to
continue living in Concord and to write a book, for which his
working title is ``Pragmatic Management.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a book about how it happens in real life, versus what you
learn in universities,'' where many business management tomes are
written, Picard says.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to spend more time fishing for striped bass and
tuna off Cape Cod, in a 37-foot boat equipped with the latest in
Raytheon-built radar, fish-finders, and night-vision gear. Picard
says he looks forward to passing along, even from retirement, his
famously blunt reviews of the devices' performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to pity my Raytheon Marine people,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
