<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO IMPEACH, OR NOT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's just one little old lady of 82, in her activist sneakers,
with her homemade sign, standing on the sunny side of Harvard
Square. She stood outside the Coop with her petition for three
hours, till her feet got cold and she quit.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Iten Fales did not go home empty-handed Monday
afternoon. ``People were queueing up to sign my petition. It was
exhilarating. I got 300 signatures against this impeachment
business. There were men with suits and briefcases, lots of women
of every size and color and origin. There was one alcoholic who
signed. It was very interesting to see. When people smiled at my
sign, you could see they would sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sign said ``Clinton Stay, Starr Go Away'' on one side, and
``Clinton Stay, No Impeaching'' on the other. Mrs. Fales took her
stand in Harvard Square for two reasons. ``I saw a photograph in
the paper of a lady in southern California carrying a sign that
said `Impeachment ASAP'.''
</P>
<P>
   The other reason? ``I was born in Berlin, and lived through the
collapse of the Weimar Republic. I saw Germany disintegrate under
Hitler, and I know the signs. I am very sensitive to the beginnings
of dictatorship.'' She believes the Republican leaders in Congress
are plotting to overthrow the elected president in a conspiracy
with Kenneth Starr. ``I can see and smell the signs of an embyronic
takeover of our government.''
</P>
<P>
   Iten Fales is not a woman to be taken lightly. ``I've been
married twice, have four children, nine grandchildren, two
great-grandchildren. I've lived in Cambridge for 30 years. My
husband is an archeologist, who's dug in Cyprus; he's a Harvard
man. My husband, who is a cradle Republican, stood with me and
collected signatures. He even sent a $1,000 check to the Democratic
National Committee for the first time in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   This elderly couple gathering signatures in Cambridge is part of
the 60-percent-plus majority against impeachment. But most of the
intensity in the debate is on the other side, which is why the vote
in the US House Thursday or Friday is too close to predict and may
well go against Clinton. This governmental crisis, triggered by a
partisan four-year investigation of the presidency that cost
$40-plus million, now threatens to cost us a president and all his
policies to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment drive, greased by right-wing Republican
congressional insiders, snuck up on the nation during Christmas
season. ``Jingle Bells, Ken Starr sells, Henry Hyde is on his way;
oh, what fun it is to ride all the way with Tom DeLay.'' And here
we are impeaching Bill; happy holidays, everyone!
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``It's not about ---- '' crowd: ``It's not
about sex, it's about (perjury, lying, misleading, trimming, not
being sufficiently repentant, etc., choose one or more).'' There's
the ``I'd be for censure if only Clinton would (admit he lied, wore
a different necktie, crossed-his-heart-and-hoped-to-die, held his
breath to the count of 30, etc.)
</P>
<P>
   There's not one vote for impeachment from the Commonwealth's 10
congressmen, all Democrats. But four New England Republicans, two
from Connecticut and two from New Hampshire, where the Manchester
Union Leader calls the tune, have come out for impeachment, joining
the chorus of GOP impeachers who insist this is a matter of
principle. Whenever I hear one party on Capitol Hill insist that an
issue is a matter of principle, I duck.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a Sun Belt rebellion from start to finish. With
nine of the 10 Republican congressional leaders from the South or
West, this struggle has been not only partisan and ideological, but
personal and geographical. The Republican House members, knuckled
by their right-wing leaders, decided to go with the anti-Clinton
flow, apparently fearful that they'd have trouble raising money or
evading primary challenges from conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans like Chuck Bass in New Hampshire and Nancy
Johnson in Connecticut may find that this vote will bring them down
November after next. Because the vote to impeach may become the
largest political mass suicide of the 20th century for Republicans
looking over their shoulder instead of two years into the future.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market last tanked bigtime on Aug. 31 of this year,
dumping 512 points off the Dow Jones Industrials, wiping out in one
trading day the paper gains of a full year. Fasten your 401(k) seat
belts for Thursday and Friday and next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A House vote to put Clinton on trial in the Senate for what he
did with a young woman and what he said about it afterward puts the
country in a terrible bind.
</P>
<P>
   A weakened, emasculated presidency imperils the world economy,
not just ours. War is never far over the horizon in the Middle
East. Are we supposed to take comfort in the belief that Saddam
Hussein will show more restraint than the Republican members of
Congress?
</P>
<P>
   The chorus for resignation resonates from the right, despite a
2-1 division in the citizenry against impeachment. Solid Midwestern
Republicans like Gerald Ford and Bob Dole say no, don't go there,
but the House is melting down.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich's final stab at Clinton is this drift into the
impeachment Twilight Zone. Speaker-to-be Bob Livingston let
majority whip Tom ``The Hammer'' DeLay of Texas hijack the process.
Over the cliff they go, risking the House, the Senate, and the next
presidential campaign on their furious folly.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
