A2856 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-16 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICINE, LAW AT ODDS IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happens when the ethical canons of law and medicine
collide?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Superior Court Judge Peter M. Lauriat must decide in
the case of Eric Brown, a 30-year-old Boston man facing trial for a
double murder in the city's South End.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's attorney wants his client to stop taking antipsychotic
drugs in order to allow a jury to see him in the throes of paranoid
schizophrenia, the mental condition he was in when he allegedly
gunned down Athos Oliveira, 30, and Thomas Meyer, 38, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's psychiatrist objects to a legal strategy designed to
intentionally worsen her patient's already tenuous mental health.
</P>
<P>
   In a pretrial hearing concluded Tuesday, both the lawyer and the
doctor claimed to have Eric Brown's interests at heart; the problem
is that those distinct interests are very much in conflict. Bernard
Grossberg's obligation is to provide his client with a ``zealous
defense.'' Dr. Inguenn Hodgson's responsibility to her patient is
to ``first, do no harm.''
</P>
<P>
   He cannot do his job if she insists upon doing hers.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's is only the most recent murder case to demonstrate that
a criminal courtroom is the wrong venue to deal with mental
illness, no matter how violently expressed.
</P>
<P>
   From John Salvi, the abortion avenger, to Theodore Kaczynski,
the Unabomber, to Russell Weston Jr., the deranged gunman who shot
and killed two police officers in the US Capitol last summer, the
judicial system finds itself ill-equipped to deal with horrific
acts perpetrated by men who belong in psych wards, not cell blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Paranoid schizophrenics present a particular challenge to a
lawyer trying to mount an insanity defense. One characteristic of
the condition is the ability to plot and scheme, even while in the
grip of paranoid delusions. Given the misconceptions about mental
illness, it is not surprising that juries often interpret evidence
of rational planning as confirmation that a defendant is a faker,
his insanity plea nothing more than a staged act of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the Supreme Judicial Court reinforced our
ignorance about schizophrenia in 1983 when it set aside the murder
conviction of a defendant who claimed that his right to a fair
trial had been compromised by the refusal of the trial judge to
allow the jury to see him in an unmedicated state.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case where an insanity defense is raised, the jury are
(sic) likely to assess the weight of the various pieces of evidence
before them with reference to the defendant's demeanor. Further, if
the defendant appears calm and controlled at trial, the jury may
well discount any testimony that the defendant lacked, at the time
of the crime, substantial capacity either to appreciate the
wrongfulness of his conduct or to conform his conduct to the
requirements of the law,'' the court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to present expert testimony describing the effect
of medication on the defendant is not an adequate substitute. At
best, such testimony would serve only to mitigate the unfair
prejudice which may accrue to the defendant as a consequence of his
controlled outward appearance. It cannot compensate for the
positive value to the defendant's case of his own demeanor in an
unmedicated condition.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, hearing that a defendant is mentally ill from
his doctors pales next to actually seeing him have a psychotic
episode at the defense table.
</P>
<P>
   What would that look like exactly? Would a videotape of an
unmedicated Eric Brown show him responding to voices heard only by
himself? Would he behave erratically or sit silently?
</P>
<P>
   What would happen after Brown had been psychotic enough to be
captured on videotape? Grossberg said the plan would be to resume
his medication. But would stability return, in turn?
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark _ and Achilles' heel _ of psychiatry is the
unwillingness of its practitioners to say, ``We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Rosmarin, a psychiatrist called by the defense
Tuesday, brought himself to the brink of such humility but was
unable to cross the threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Dr. Rosmarin's testimony was laced with qualifiers
about the consequences of destabalizing a mentally ill man, with
the effects variously described as ``speculative,'' ``relative,''
``potential,'' ``hopeful,'' ``probable,'' ``anecdotal,'' and
``inferential.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Brown's psychiatrist at Bridgewater (Mass.) State Hospital
is a woman of considerably fewer words. This whole idea, she
rightly noted, is simply ``unethical.''
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
