<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYDESSERTS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   YOL GALIK'S PEANUT BUTTER MOUSSE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla wafer crust:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups vanilla wafer crumbs (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fine-ground dry roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Peanut butter mousse:
</P>
<P>
   3 (8-ounce) packages cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creamy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce container frozen nondairy whipped topping, thawed
</P>
<P>
   3 (0.6-ounce) Reese's Peanut Butter Cups, each sliced crosswise
into about 6 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Note: To make crumbs, process vanilla wafers in a food processor
fitted with the metal blade. Or, place in a plastic bag, remove air
and seal. Hit with a heavy object such as a rolling pin until fine
crumbs form.
</P>
<P>
   Crust: Combine all ingredients. Press into bottom of a 9-inch
springform pan. Chill 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Filling: Meanwhile, with an electric mixer on medium to high
speed, beat the cream cheese and peanut butter. With mixer on low
speed, carefully beat in the sugar a bit at a time. Increase mixer
speed to high and add vanilla, cinnamon and butter, scraping bowl
as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Fold in the whipped topping until well-combined and creamy. Pour
into pan. Refrigerate overnight. Before serving, garnish with
peanut butter cup slices laid on their sides.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 746 calories, 62 grams fat, 38
grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 119 milligrams cholesterol,
314 milligrams sodium, 75 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS CRANBERRY GALETTE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar, preferably superfine, divided
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups fresh or frozen cranberries, picked over
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup walnuts, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Pie-crust dough for a 14-inch free-form tart
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   At least 1 1/2 hours and no more than 24 hours ahead of baking,
place the superfine sugar (reserving 1 teaspoon for the border) and
the light brown sugar in a medium bowl and use your fingertips to
combine them and rub out lumps of brown sugar. Cut each cranberry
in half and add the halves to the sugar mixture. Stir the mixture
well and set it aside for 1 hour at room temperature or,
preferably, overnight in the refrigerator. Stir the cranberry
mixture well, then stir in the walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees at least 20 minutes before
baking. Roll the pastry into a circle roughly 18 inches in diameter
on a floured pastry cloth or two sheets of lightly floured plastic
wrap. Using an expandable flan ring, or using a sharp knife and a
cardboard template as a guide, cut out a 16-inch circle. If the
dough has softened, slip it (still on the cloth or plastic wrap)
onto a baking sheet and refrigerate it for about 30 minutes,
covered, until firm, before lining the pan. The pastry is too large
to slip your hands under and support adequately. When rolled (and
chilled, if necessary), transfer to a 12-to-14-inch flat, round
heavy steel pizza pan or an inverted baking sheet, preferably
black. To transfer it to the pan, roll it loosely over the rolling
pin or dust it lightly with flour and fold in quarters, then unfold
on pan. Leave the overhang.
</P>
<P>
   Scatter the cranberry mixture evenly over the dough, covering a
13-inch area and leaving a 1 1/2-inch border. Fold the overhanging
border of dough over the outer edge of the cranberries, using your
fingers to pleat it loosely at even intervals. Brush this border
with a little milk or water and sprinkle on the reserved sugar.
(This will give the border a crunchy texture.) Cut a 10-inch round
of foil and place it gently over the cranberries, leaving the crust
uncovered. Bake the galette for 30 minutes. If not using a black
pan, plan to bake the galette directly on the oven floor;
alternatively, set an oven rack at the lowest level and place a
baking stone or cookie sheet on it before preheating.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 minutes, cover the tart with a second round of foil
large enough to cover the filling and the crust border and continue
baking for about 10 minutes more, or until the bottom crust is
golden brown. (Slip a small, angled metal spatula or flexible knife
under the edge of the tart, lifting it slightly, to check
doneness.)
</P>
<P>
   Cool the tart on the pan on a rack for about 20 minutes or until
warm. Dust with confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 431 calories, 18 grams fat, 65
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 5 milligrams cholesterol, 190
milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rose Levy Beranbaum's ``Pie and Pastry Bible'' (Scribner, $35)
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
