<HEADLINE>
RIDING AT THE SPEED OF LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If voice, data, and Internet traffic is like water spewing out
of a garden hose, imagine 10 to 30 times more water coming out of
the hose.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore Networks Inc. wants to build a new type of high-volume
nozzle that directs the gusher as well as the meters needed to
measure it.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last 10 years, fiber-optic glass cables have widely
replaced bulky copper wires to accommodate long distance voice and
data communications. And with the growth of the Internet,
telecommunications carriers have built extensive glass fiber
networks that carry pulses of light to handle the load.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, fiber-optic lines carried data at the rate of 10
billion bits a second. However, a new technology, known as dense
wavelength division multiplexing, promises to significantly
increase the volume of data transmitted on a single glass wire.
</P>
<P>
   The multiplexing equipment, used by carriers, acts like a prism
by splitting a beam of light into 10 to 30 streams. That enables
one fiber-optic cable to move data at the rate of 100 billion to
300 billion bits of information a second. The result is a mammoth
increase in traffic without digging up streets or stringing new
cables on telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing and managing this high speed flow of data is the
mission of Sycamore and several other companies. They want to build
the routing and measuring equipment required to funnel these
voluminous light streams to corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Company founder and chairman Desh Deshpande and president Daniel
Smith estimate there's a $20 billion annual market for the new
generation of optical networking equipment. Customers include local
and long distance telephone companies along with other independent
carriers, Internet service providers, and cable television service
companies.
</P>
<P>
   These customers, in turn, would sell optical networking services
to corporate customers and consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
