<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S JUST WHAT THEY EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes the success of a season is defined late in the
proceedings, in the harsh reality of football in December when the
stakes are high and the energy level low, sapped after a full
regular season and three weeks of playoff competition.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it comes earlier than that. Much earlier. Like in
August, before practice begins.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams know their fate, know that playing for championships
is merely a goal, not a wish.
</P>
<P>
   At the Division 1-AA level, Georgia Southern knew. ``The goal of
this team since August has been to win the national championship,''
said coach Paul Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Simple statement, without a hint of boastfulness. That's what
happens when you are at a program which has produced four national
championships, dating back to the marvelous days of Erk Russell,
who compiled an 83-22-1 record and won three national titles in an
eight-year span from 1981-89.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four days away from its final game of 1998, Georgia
Southern is approaching the summit one more time. Fourteen games
have turned into 14 wins. Only the University of Massachusetts
stands in the way of a perfect Eagle landing.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose link to Russell is stronger than that of the two
coaches who followed Russell when he stepped aside following his
third national championship in 1989, knows the bar has been set
high enough that a loss will wash out much of the joy of the
season. ``We've not accomplished the final goal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia Southern, the story probably begins in 1981 when
Russell, a longtime Georgia assistant, revived the football program
after a 40-year hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, the Eagles had a national championship. Johnson, a
member of that staff before moving to the Division 1-A level at
Hawaii, remembrs the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of the state got involved,'' he said by phone from
his office in Statesboro, Ga. &UR;  &LR; ``It was just a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years following Russell's retirement, the excitement
faded. The Eagles faded into the also-ran pack. When Johnson
returned two years ago, he knew he had to rebuild once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were real young a year ago,'' said Johnson, who has
reestablished a link with Russell that had been missing for nearly
a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says he has watched UMass on tape and assumes nothing.
``You don't get to where you are without being good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he sees in UMass a lot of what he saw at Georgia
Southern in 1985 _ a sense of excitement and enthusiasm that comes
with new experiences.
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia Southern, the experiences also have been pleasant,
especially in the playoffs. The Eagles rolled over Colgate and
Connecticut before trouncing Western Illinois, 42-14, in last
weekend's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   With quarterback Greg Hill and fullback Adrian Peterson, the
Eagles offense has produced at a championship pace for most of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thinks he knows what UMass's strategy will be. ``It's
simple,'' he said. ``They're going to try and hold the ball.
``Obviously, they have done a pretty good job of that or they
wouldn't still be here. They beat two outstanding teams on the
road, and you have to be pretty good to have done that in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern is pretty good as well. The Eagles, whose only
losing season since 1981 came two years ago, now have a chance to
match Russell's 15-0 record of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Russell feels they are back to where they once were. ``For a
while, I think we were letting everything slip away,'' Russell told
the Atlanta Constitution this week. ``But it is suddenly all back.
I feel like I'm a real part of things around here and I've felt
like that forever. But that's particularly true now that the
program is in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   All that's missing is for the Eagles to get their hands on
another national championship trophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
