<HEADER>
A2871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-BOOKS-2TAKES-HNS     12-16 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BOOKS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLIDAY GUIDE TO NEW BOOKS FOR CHILDREN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over e in Coppelia) 
 
By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snowy nights and Jedi knights. Ancient heroes and new heroines.
Tales retold, reprinted, recited. Cupid shooting, hamsters
counting, dolls dancing.
</P>
<P>
   New children's books on a wild variety of subjects pour into
stores this time of year, enticing, beckoning, pleading. They stuff
shelves along with thousands of old books waiting to be uncovered
or rediscovered.
</P>
<P>
   But the new ones are a challenge _ not tried and true like Pooh.
</P>
<P>
   To help guide holiday shoppers through the maze, we have
selected these books from hundreds of newly published works. A
couple _ ``Miss Spider's ABC'' and ``10 Minutes Till Bedtime'' _
are the latest from popular authors who have, once again, lived up
to their creative past.
</P>
<P>
   Others scatter off in many directions, like children at recess.
Each one is for giving _ to newborns (the perfect time to begin a
library), to X-Generation ``Star Wars'' freaks who will probably
find minute errors in the fact-filled books, to great-grandmas who
no longer see the tiny print of their beloved Jane Austen or P.D.
James but who will glow at bright art and short yet wise stories.
</P>
<P>
   Each is gloriously special.
</P>
<P>
   The best holiday present is hugs and kisses and reading
together.
</P>
<P>
   The second best is a book.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``10 Minutes Till Bedtime'' by Peggy Rathmann (Putnam,
$16.99).
</P>
<P>
   We never learn the name of the little boy, but we know he has a
very unusual hamster. Via the Internet, the hamster offers a
10-minute bedtime tour centered around the child. The tour is for
hamsters only and boasts free snacks and clean restrooms; families
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   When Dad announces, ``10 minutes till bedtime,'' the tour _ with
hamsters on motorcycles, in tour buses and in motor homes _ begins
and stays with the little boy in fuzzy green slippers through his
whole bedtime routine.
</P>
<P>
   Rathmann, who won the 1996 Caldecott Medal for ``Officer Buckle
and Gloria,'' offers the cutest, most charming counting book to
come along in a long time. Well, maybe it's not a counting book at
all. Maybe it's about imagination. Maybe it's about what pets
really do when we aren't watching.
</P>
<P>
   The book has hundreds of hamsters, one dad, one little boy, 10
numbers and three words. A work of genius and an utter delight.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Snow'' by Uri Shulevitz (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $16).
</P>
<P>
   This utterly enchanting story by the much-awarded Shulevitz
tells what happens to a gray city and one little child when a
snowflake falls. The wonderful art dances with color and shape. The
story is about the power of color, of a child and of believing.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Sitting Ducks'' by Michael Bedard (Putnam &AMP; Grosset,
$15.99).
</P>
<P>
   This is a silly, wonderful story about a duck factory run by
alligators _ alligators who eat ducks. One day an egg rolls off the
conveyor belt, a duck hops out, and a worker-alligator sneaks him
home in a lunch bucket.
</P>
<P>
   They become unlikely friends, and the alligator decides not to
fatten and eat the duck as originally planned. The duck, being a
curious duck, goes on an adventure and finds ... well, we won't
tell you. What he was trying to find was Ducktown.
</P>
<P>
   The illustrations are better than anything on Saturday morning
television. You end up loving the ducks and the alligators. Perhaps
there is a lesson here.
</P>
<P>
   Nah, probably not. Just a clever and charming story with a happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   But beware _ this will become a child's favorite to be read over
and over and over.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My Name Is Georgia'' by Jeanette Winter (Harcourt Brace,
$16).
</P>
<P>
   ``My Name Is Georgia'' tells, for 6- to 10-year-olds, the story
of Georgia O'Keeffe, her childhood and her yearning for sky.
Illustrations mimic, in a respectful and enchantingly childlike
way, O'Keeffe's art.
</P>
<P>
   Winter shows and tells children about what inspired O'Keeffe and
about the legacy she left for us all. In a broader sense, the book
is about following dreams and touching others with art.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Miss Spider's ABC'' by David Kirk (Scholastic, $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   Miss Spider is back, this time with the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   Insects from A to Z are coming to Miss Spider's birthday
surprise party. Kirk, toymaker turned best-selling children's book
writer and artist, has no surprises here. His insects are as lively
and brilliantly colorful as usual. The publishers recommend this
book for ages 4 through 7.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A World of Words: An ABC of Quotations'' by Tobi Tobias,
illustrated by Peter Malone (Lothrop, Lee &AMP; Shepard, $16).
</P>
<P>
   Tobias and Malone ingeniously use quotations from literature to
spell out the alphabet. Example: C is for circus, and the quote is,
``when god decided to invent everything he took one breath bigger
than a circustent and everything began'' by e.e. cummings. Quotes
are by Emily Dickinson, William Shakespeare, Carl Sandburg,
Langston Hughes, J.R.R. Tolkien and others. The paintings mix
whimsy with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   This is a special book for young and old.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Boshblobberbosh'' by J. Patrick Lewis, illustrated by Gary
Kelley (Harcourt Brace, $18).
</P>
<P>
   One of the quotations in the Tobi Tobias book is from Edward
Lear (``The Owl and the Pussy-Cat''), who inspired Lewis' clever
``Boshblobberbosh.'' Whenever Lear was at a loss for a word, he
made one up. He made up words like ``jumblies,'' ``fizzgiggious
fish,'' ``oblong oysters'' and ``quangle wangle.'' The word
``bosh'' means ``nonsense''; Lear invented worlds of bosh.
</P>
<P>
   Lear's magical words inspired Lewis and artist Kelley. Author
Lewis made up the word ``boshblobberbosh'' for his unusual poetry
book, a tribute to Lear.
</P>
<P>
   While the poems are not Lear, they are Learlike and fun to read.
The book, beautifully designed and printed, also contains a bit of
history and background on each poem. For all ages.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``To Every Thing There Is a Season'' by Leo and Diane Dillon
(Blue Sky/Scholastic, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the prettiest books of the season. Leo and Diane
Dillon, much-honored with Caldecotts and other children's book
awards, take the ancient verses of Ecclesiastes and pair them with
stunning artwork representing 16 cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian wall murals express ``A time to be born, a time to
die.'' A Chinese fishing scene illustrates ``A time to keep and a
time to cast away.'' Australian traditional aboriginal bark paints
were mimicked (gouache on bark paper) for ``A time to keep silence
and a time to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson here is more than just the singing Biblical phrases.
The Dillons celebrate life, diversity and the universal human
condition. The cover is magnificent. For all ages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Coppelia'' told by Margot Fonteyn, paintings by Steve
Johnson and Lou Fancher (Harcourt Brace, $17).
</P>
<P>
   Fonteyn, one of the most influential ballerinas of the 20th
century, wrote a version of the classic ``Coppelia'' shortly before
her death in 1991. The ballerina did the job with heart and
empathy. She knows the human doll as few others can know her
because she danced the role. She knows about creating beauty as did
Dr. Coppelius, the dollmaker.
</P>
<P>
   But the beauty of this book isn't in the retelling of the famous
story, a ballet (and two operas) based on a story of E.T.A.
Hoffmann and first performed in 1870.
</P>
<P>
   The illustrations are breathtaking. They are oil, acrylic and
fabric on canvas and create the mood of a rich old European
painting.
</P>
<P>
   For all ages but especially for the young dancers in the family.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shake Rag: From the Life of Elvis Presley'' by Amy
Littlesugar, illustrated by Floyd Cooper (Philomel, $16.99).
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's magic has touched another story.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year-old boy's daddy loses his job and moves his family
near Shake Rag, where mostly black people live. The little boy, who
loves his old guitar, plays songs he heard on Memphis blues radio
stations and mimics music swirling in the streets in his
neighborhood. He catches on fast. He loves the music and can sing
it as well as his neighbors can.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, in a Memphis recording studio, that music
comes pouring out of him. It is, writes, Littlesugar, ``the sound
of a brand-new day.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy is Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The 20th Century Children's Book Treasury'' edited by Janet
Schulman (Knopf, $40).
</P>
<P>
   Schulman has done a commendable job of selecting 44 beloved
children's books for this treasure.
</P>
<P>
   There's enough bedtime reading in here for months. For parents
who want to understand her choices, Schulmann explains her reasons.
A color code indicates recommended ages. This is a wonderful
bargain and a great gift, a whole library in one _ Seuss, Amelia
Bedelia, Babar and Tigger, old books and new.
</P>
<P>
   But the book is heavy. So the youngster needs strong fingers and
wrists and a reading voice from someone older.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Apollo &AMP; Daphne: Masterpieces of Mythology'' by Antonia
Barber (Getty Museum, $16.95). The story of Apollo and Daphne, you
recall, is about the Greek god who, stung by Cupid's gold-tipped
arrow, fell hopelessly for the water nymph Daphne. Apollo had
insulted Cupid, and Cupid, being a young brat, sought to give him
pain. Ah, love.
</P>
<P>
   This myth and others are illustrated with beautiful great-master
works of art from the National Gallery in London, the Louvre and
other collections. The book ends with a list of the Roman names for
the Greek gods and the family tree of the gods, of the children of
earth and sea and of the children of Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   The retelling is direct and respectful in this beautiful book
for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Life of Jesus: In Masterpieces of Art'' by Mary Pope
Osborne (Viking, $17.99).
</P>
<P>
   As with Apollo &AMP; Daphne, masterpieces from around the world
illustrate ``The Life of Jesus.'' ``I tried to be as clear and
direct as possible, without sacrificing the wonder and passion of
the story,'' Osborne writes. Most of the paintings were done in the
15th and 16th centuries. Osborne chose them for their beauty and
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Gregory the Great, she says, wrote, ``Painting can do for
the illiterate what writing does for those who can read.'' In this
book is the best of both.
</P>
<P>
   This is a beautifully produced book for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Star Wars: The Visual Dictionary'' by David West Reynolds
(DK, $19.95). ``Star Wars: Incredible Cross-sections'' by David
West Reynolds (DK, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 you will (1) get sick and tired of hearing about Star
Wars, or (2) pant for more. But you will not feel ambivalent about
the subject. The eagerly awaited ``Star Wars: Episode One _ The
Phantom Menace'' is scheduled to open in theaters May 21.
</P>
<P>
   If someone on your list falls into category 2, buy one or both
of the new ``Star Wars'' books. They are amazingly detailed.
Frankly, it's amazing that anybody would go so overboard about a
movie. The cross section book is 32 pages of Star Destroyers,
Sandcrawlers, Jabba's Sail Barge and more. Death Star folds out
into a four-page spread. It's full of minute characters and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Where did all this come from? Certainly George Lucas didn't plan
the upper laser cannon mount or the primary sensor array in the
T-65 X-wing.
</P>
<P>
   The dictionary is called the ultimate guide to ``Star Wars''
characters and creatures. Most fascinating is the list of how the
books were actually researched and executed. Reynolds is an
archaeologist who ``approaches the world of ''Star Wars`` like
ancient Rome or Egypt, considering it a culture from another time
and place to explore.''
</P>
<P>
   We see inside a Stormtrooper's helmet. Biographies detail
Boushh, Logray, Interrogator Droid and even the gross ones like
rancor monster and ephant mon.
</P>
<P>
   Yoda does deserve more than one page. For ``Star Wars'' fans of
all ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women of Hope: African Americans Who Made a Difference'' by
Joyce Hansen (Scholastic, $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the most beautiful books of the year. It is based
on a series of posters created by Bread and Roses, the cultural
project of 1199 National Health and Human Services Employees Union,
AFL-CIO, in New York. The union, with the hope of nourishing the
hearts and minds of members and their families and to honor courage
and creativity in women of color, ended up inspiring a nation.
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white posters are elegant in their simplicity.
They pack a wallop. So does the book.
</P>
<P>
   The book tells a one-page story of each woman, and on the facing
page reproduces the poster photo, some new images, some old. The
women are Ida Wells-Barnett, Fannie Lou Hamer, Mae Jemison, Ella J.
Baker, Ruby Dee, Maya Angelou, Toni Morrison, Marian Wright
Edelman, Alice Walker, Alexa Canady, Septima Clark and the Delany
Sisters.
</P>
<P>
   These women paved the way for a better future, and that makes us
proud.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Meet My Staff'' by Patricia Marx, illustrated by Roz Chast
(Harper Collins, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   Most readers will take this book personally. It is about you,
and me, and the person next door, and your teacher, and ``my
staff.'' But the author claims the book is about Walter. And young
Walter's staff. Sure it is.
</P>
<P>
   Walter's staff includes Miss Peck, who is in charge of kissing
Aunt Winnie, ``which is something I would rather not do,'' he
explains. And that's how the book goes. The cat practices the
piano, Delores De-cruster cuts the crust off Walter's bread. Sir
Yes ... well, you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   We all need 'em, have 'em, and suffer when they take the day
off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
