<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'78 UMASS TEAM KNEW THE FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ Two significant events in the history of
University of Massachusetts football occurred on this date. The
latter came last season, when the school named former Brown coach
Mark Whipple to head its beleaguered program.
</P>
<P>
   The former came 20 years ago, when the Minutemen played Florida
A&AMP;M in the first NCAA Division 1-AA national championship game
ever.
</P>
<P>
   How coincidental that on the 20th anniversary of the biggest
game in UMass football history, the Whipple-led 1998 Minutemen
depart Wednesday for Chattanooga, Tenn., in preparation for the
school's second 1-AA championship game _ a showdown against
undefeated Georgia Southern Saturday at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to call us the greatest team in school history,
but I think you can say that about this team now,'' said Kevin
Sullivan, a defensive back on the 1978 team, which finished 9-4
after losing to FAMU, 35-28, in Wichita Falls, Texas. ``I think we
were similar in the fact that both could score at will and both had
great defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, both knocked off previously unbeaten teams en route to
the final. The 1978 team defeated heavily favored Nevada-Reno,
44-21, in Reno in the semifinals (back then, the tournament
consisted of two rounds rather than today's four).
</P>
<P>
   This year's squad knocked off previously unbeaten Lehigh, 27-21,
at Warren McGuirk Stadium in the second round, earning UMass's
first home playoff victory ever.
</P>
<P>
   And as if that weren't enough of a coincidence, both teams were
headed by first-year coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Pickett, who coached the '78 team after serving seven years
as an assistant under Dick MacPherson, says his scenario was much
different from that of Whipple. MacPherson had taken the program to
the Division 2 playoffs in 1977. ``Mac didn't actually leave the
cupboard empty,'' said Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple, whose 11-3 team set a school record for victories in a
season, was appointed after UMass lost nine games for the first
time this century.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking differences between the two teams was
their talent pools. The 1978 Minutemen consisted predominantly of
in-state players.
</P>
<P>
   In their Nov. 16 contest against New Hampshire, 20 of 22
Minutemen starters hailed from Massachusetts (both the offense and
defense had one starter from New York).
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Minutemen are typical of many of the better teams in
the Northeast _ their talent pool covers many states. The starting
lineup for last week's semifinal victory over Northwestern (La.)
State included three offensive starters and five defensive starters
from the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly the biggest difference between the teams is style of
play. The 1978 Minutemen were run-oriented. They set a school
record with 3,000 rushing yards. They relied on ball control and
aggressive defense to stymie the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were not a lot of zone defenses back then; everything
was strictly man-to-man,'' said Pickett. ``Back then, we had
defensive objective charts like four shutouts in a year and no
(yielding a) play of more than 20 yards. Back then, those
objectives were reasonable. You couldn't do that today.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1978 team registered one shutout _ a 27-0 decision over
Boston College in the regular-season finale. It held five other
opponents to 8 points or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the 1998 team has come to a shutout was a 23-13 win
over Rhode Island. Its forte has been Whipple's wide-open passing
attack, which scores in bunches. These Minutemen have scored 40
points or more five times, something the 1978 team did only twice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, members of the 1978 team see similarities. ``We both had
a few losses early and a loss late and then we excelled in the
playoffs,'' said Bruce Kimball, former UMass offensive lineman and
member of the Washington Redskins' Super Bowl XVIII team. ``I've
seen their running back, Marcel Shipp, and he's outstanding. He
reminds me of the guy we had, Dennis Dent.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the game itself, members of the 1978 team hope this
year's squad has better fortune. Pickett's defense played much of
the game without three starters. Sullivan broke his ankle in the
first quarter. He spent much of the day watching a gusty wind wreak
havoc with the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were punts that were sailing backwards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop placekicker Sandro Vitiello from booting a pair
of 20-yard field goals in the first half, the second of which gave
UMass a 6-0 lead. But Florida A&AMP;M, playing without leading rusher
Ike Williams, had a pair of rushing touchdowns in the second
quarter to take a 14-6 halftime advantage.
</P>
<P>
   A 29-yard field goal by Vitiello and two touchdowns by Cliff
Pedrow put the Minutemen ahead, 22-21, with 8:26 left in the game.
Then FAMU converted a UMass fumble into a 29-yard touchdown run by
Mike Solomon. He caught a 2-point conversion pass to put the
Rattlers ahead, 29-22.
</P>
<P>
   UMass punted the ball back to FAMU after stalling on three
downs, and the Rattlers took advantage again as Solomon scored on a
20-yard run for a 35-22 advantage. UMass scored the game's final
touchdown on a last-second 34-yard pass from Mike McEvilly to Chris
Kurtz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to win,'' said Kimball, ``but we missed some
scoring opportunities early and we settled for field goals rather
than move the ball inside the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan hopes to gather members of the 1978 team to watch
Saturday's game on television. As dominant as the program was back
then, he can't believe it took another 20 years for the Minutemen
to reach the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would be right back there the next year with all
the talent we had,'' he said. ``I'd say to this year's team, `Make
the best of it while you can.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
