<SLUG> BC-STARTUP-AGAIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOVATORS TAKE A DETOUR FROM LIFE ON EASY STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you made a fortune by selling the company you cofounded and
helped build. With leisure time and new wealth on your hands, you
sink a few bucks into some promising young companies where you sit
on the board. And best of all, you now have plenty of time to spend
with the family.
</P>
<P>
   Idyllic for some, but the change in lifestyle left millionaires
Gururaj ``Desh'' Deshpande and Daniel Smith restless.
</P>
<P>
   What was left to do?
</P>
<P>
   Start over again.
</P>
<P>
   Both were leaders of Cascade Communications Corp. of Westford,
Mass., a telecommunications equipment maker that was one of the
most successful technology companies in New England during the
1990s. It grew to $500 million in annual sales and had 900 workers.
In 1997, six years after establishing Cascade, they sold it for
$3.7 billion to Ascend Communications Inc. of Alameda, Calif. They
split more than $150 million in Ascend stock.
</P>
<P>
   The duo represent a breed of incurable entrepreneurs _ too young
and too restless to retire with the riches; too independent to work
for the new bosses. Deshpande and Smith say they love the start-up
life and couldn't resist the chance to build another successful
company. And in an unusual twist, they ended up together again in
the entrepreneurial trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a month after the Ascend deal closed, Deshpande, chairman
of Cascade and one of its four founders, took a vacation to his
native India and started sprinkling some of his new wealth into
several companies.
</P>
<P>
   In February _ barely seven months out of Cascade _ he launched
Sycamore Networks Inc. in Tewksbury, Mass., another
telecommunications start-up. Last month Smith, who stayed 15 months
with the merged Ascend/Cascade, joined Sycamore as president and
chief executive. Deshpande is chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recruited him over a sandwich and an ice cream cone _ and he
paid for both,'' recalls Deshpande, 48, referring to a lunch near
Smith's summer home in Watch Hill, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 49, enjoyed cheering his kids on at soccer games and
overseeing some of their school activities, but he says the slower
pace left him wanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to build things _ I can't walk past a construction site
without stopping to figure out how the building is put together,''
comments Smith, who says he puts in 13-hour days at Sycamore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Desh and I talked, it was the challenge of building
something very new. We had made enough money. That was not our
primary motivation'' with Sycamore, adds Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore, which was started without a business plan, got $5
million right away, half from Deshpande and half from Matrix
Partners, a Waltham, Mass. venture capital firm that had financed
Cascade. Much of the company's subsequent financing came from
Matrix and North Bridge Venture Partners of Waltham, two venture
firms known for backing early-stage telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The start-up's aim is to build a new generation of
telecommunications equipment that uses waves of light to deliver
huge amounts of voice, data, and Internet traffic through
fiber-optic cable to business and residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   The young company's core technology comes from Richard Barry and
Eric Swanson, two research scientists at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratories, who developed a way
of testing an all-optical network for data communications. They
were persuaded by Deshpande to leave the lab and risk their futures
in a startup. At Sycamore, Barry is director of ``optics
architecture'' and Swanson is chief scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Sycamore has grown to 50 employees and drawn a total
of more than $20 million in investments. Aside from Deshpande's and
Smith's funding, money also came from Chi Shue another cofounder of
Cascade, who rose to vice president of software and systems
engineering at Ascend's switching division in Westford, Mass. He is
now Sycamore's vice president of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trio at Sycamore is probably the most experienced
management team of any start-up we have done,'' says Paul Ferri of
Matrix Partners. ``They want to be leaders at the beginning of the
technology curve while others are developing products that are more
straightforward extensions of existing technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Deshpande, who holds a doctorate degree in data
communications from Queens University in Canada, and Smith, an
engineer and Harvard Business School graduate, acknowledge they
each questioned whether they had the energy to start another
company. Each had plenty of job offers after selling Cascade.
</P>
<P>
   After all, very few successful entrepreneurs still have the same
hunger and passion to start all over.
</P>
<P>
   For Deshpande, to begin again meant personally arranging for
office furniture, workspace cubicles, computers, and fax machines.
Six-day work weeks sometimes blended into a nightlife of cell phone
conversations from home.
</P>
<P>
   But Deshpande's and Smith's success with Cascade also made it
easier to attract people and money for Sycamore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to brag, but it took 15 minutes on the phone to
get venture funding and we've got very talented engineers
approaching us,'' says Deshpande, noting that Sycamore is the sixth
start-up to spin out of Cascade.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Smith: ``You give up power when you leave a big company and
to start over takes an emotional maturity. There are no trappings
of a big office.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few entrepreneurs are as successful the second or third
time around.
</P>
<P>
   William Poduska, a founder of Prime Computer, succeeded with
Apollo Computer, which was acquired by Hewlett-Packard Co. But he
later failed with Stardent Computer Inc. of Concord, Mass. And
Henry Burkhardt III, prospered handsomely as a cofounder of Data
General Corp. only to see his next company, Kendall Square Research
Corp. of Waltham, fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started Cascade, people thought we were eccentric, and
frankly, you have to be a bit crazy to start again,'' says
Deshpande. ``But Dan and I work very well together and the
opportunity in optical computing is what really excites us.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its promise, Sycamore must still reach certain
milestones commonly expected of telecommunications start-ups:
completing development of a first product in 15 months; getting a
product onto the market six to nine months later, before
competitors arrive; and achieving profitability about a year later,
followed by either an initial public offering or selling out to a
bigger company.
</P>
<P>
   Still, things are advancing much more quickly for Deshpande and
Smith the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-month-old Sycamore will have its first product developed for
customer testing next spring. By comparison, Cascade took a year to
get its venture capital funding and a second year to get its first
product out the door, notes Deshpande.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore's tight time schedule means grueling 12- to 15-hour
days for nearly all Sycamore employees during the first year. And
so far, Deshpande says, there has been no shortage of engineering
applicants, looking to strike it rich and get in on the ground
floor of emerging technology.
</P>
<P>
   And while both have complementary skills, each has strengths
gained at Cascade that carry over to Sycamore. Smith, the chief
salesman, drives the business. Deshpande is the strategist and
technology guru.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan and Desh are a killer team because they complement each
other. Desh can figure out markets, navigate around problems, knows
more about the details of a product than anyone else. Dan is the
street fighter, the team leader and the best manager under fire of
anyone I ever worked with,'' says Kurt Melden, a Cascade cofounder
who is now chief technical officer of Redstone Communications Inc.
of Westford. ``Together again, they will do very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
