<SLUG> BC-BBO-FISK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUEEZE PLAY FOR FISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``The only thing that will keep Carlton Fisk out of the
Baseball Hall of Fame would be a traffic jam on the road to
Cooperstown.''(unitals) &QL; 
_ Boston Globe, April 2, 1993 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a certain wisecracking baseball writer with a Boston
address wrote this about the Chicago White Sox catcher.
</P>
<P>
   While the prospect of Fisk joining baseball's elite is a given,
so, too, is the notion that there might be several obstacles to him
being included in the Class of 1999. The onetime Red Sox star is
traveling the same path as Nolan Ryan, George Brett, and Robin
Yount, also first-time candidates. Support for holdovers Tony Perez
(321 votes in last year's balloting), Jim Rice (203), and Gary
Carter (200) could also block the way.
</P>
<P>
   History tells us nothing is automatic. Since 1936, only 26
players have been elected on the first ballot by members of the
Baseball Writers Association of America. The last was Mike Schmidt
of the Philadelphia Phillies in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Having said all that, it remains clear that the Class of '99
will be considered lacking if Fisk is not a first-ballot selection.
As much as Ryan, Yount, and Brett, he has become a legend. He
lasted 24 years at a killer position, and he wound up with 376
homers and 1,330 RBIs, plus 10 All-Star Game appearances and the
records for homers by a catcher (351) and games behind the plate
(2,226).
</P>
<P>
   But his credentials transcend raw numbers. In the 1975 World
Series, he provided one of the most indelible moments in baseball
history. His 12th-inning home run that gave the Red Sox a 7-6
victory over the Cincinnati Reds in Game 6 _ and his dance down the
first base line as he implored the shot down the left-field line to
stay fair _ remains a staple in Boston lore.
</P>
<P>
   For this quintessential New Englander _ born in Bellows Falls,
Vt., raised in Charlestown, N.H., the embodiment of flinty,
hardworking Yankee values _ that stood as the signature moment from
his 10-plus years with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But that tenure ended on a decidedly sour note. Five years
later, during contentious contract negotiations, Fisk became a free
agent when general manager Haywood Sullivan committed a contract
blunder that ranks just behind the sale of Babe Ruth as the biggest
in Red Sox history. After getting assurances it wasn't necessary,
Sullivan failed to send Fisk a contract by the deadline of Dec. 20,
1980. Fisk was susequently declared a free agent on the grounds
that the option year on his contract called for a new salary offer
before the deadline and the Red Sox had not made one. Sullivan's
initial offer to Fisk was $210,000. The White Sox snapped him up
for five years at $700,000 annually, and he spent the remaining 13
years of his career in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter where he went, New England was always home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around since 1942,'' said Red Sox great Johnny
Pesky. ``And I played on a great team in 1946. You've got to put
Fisk among the list of greats who have ever played around here _
Williams, Yaz, Doerr, DiMaggio, Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some great catchers to come along over the
years _ Gabby Hartnett, Bill Dickey, Johnny Bench, and Yogi Berra.
Fisk has got to be in that group. He never should have left here.
But I'm happy he's still got a chance to be in the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability Fisk showed as a skinny 6-foot-2-inch kid was
special, and it didn't surprise Pesky or anyone else in the Red Sox
organization that he became a fixture at Fenway Park. In 1972, Fisk
not only won a Gold Glove as the best defensive catcher in the
American League but was named Rookie of the Year. He finished in
the top 10 in the Most Valuable Player balloting four times and
played in two League Championship Series (1975, '83), and of
course, the aforementioned World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that Carlton Fisk belongs in the Hall of
Fame,'' said former Red Sox batterymate Dennis Eckersley, recently
retired after 24 seasons. ``I don't think even Johnny Bench could
match what Pudge could do. It's hard to explain. But I'd say
offensively, Fisk put it together better than any other catcher at
that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to have the kind of career he had at his age is
something; the numbers he put up. He was 33 when he left Boston.
But he had some great years after he became 33. Who knows what he
would have done if he hadn't left Boston?''
</P>
<P>
   We do have a clue. In 13 seasons against Boston, Fisk hit .308
(119 for 386) with 27 home runs and 68 RBIs. In 1987, he became
only the third catcher with 300 career homers, 1,000 runs scored,
and 1,000 RBIs. He had eight 20-homer and two 100-RBI seasons _ all
while serving as a masterful handler of pitching staffs.
</P>
<P>
   What also set Fisk apart in his Red Sox days, Pesky reminds, was
his unmistakable leadership, the ability to drive not only himself
but those around him. Behind the dish, Fisk took command. He
smothered nearly every errant pitch. He made catching foul balls an
art. True, his trips to the mound seemed endless, as did his
propensity for hitting foul balls down the left-field line. But he
got results.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was at the plate,'' said Pesky, ``he never backed off.
Maybe that's why he went after every ball. Maybe that is why he hit
1,000 foul-ball home runs. He wasn't always a pull hitter. But as
he got bigger and stronger, he became quick inside _ almost as
quick as DiMaggio, although Joe straightened out quite a few
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk played in 1,078 games for Boston, batting .280 _ .011 above
his career average. He represented Boston seven times in the
All-Star Game, missing the 1974 showcase because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, there was that epic homer in the '75 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still see the shot he hit,'' said Pesky, a Red Sox coach
in 1975. ``It wasn't a cheap shot. It was a pea. People kept
yelling, `Stay fair, stay fair!' I looked over at Pudge, and he was
pushing his hands towards right field while trying to steer the
ball fair at the same time. If the screen hadn't been there, the
ball would have gone to Kenmore Square.''
</P>
<P>
   After an injury-plagued stretch early in his career, Fisk became
a paragon of durability and longevity because of his monster
pregame and postgame workouts. They encapsulated the demands he
placed on himself, a commitment to excellence that also manifested
itself in a lack of tolerance with with those above him who
disagreed with his views.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether he'll wear a Red Sox or White
Sox cap in Cooperstown. But it's beyond dispute that he belongs
there. Now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
