<HEADLINE>
IN FINLAND, US HOCKEY PUT ON ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canada won the tournament, but US coach Julie Sasner likes what
she saw over in Finland nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team played well,'' said Sasner Tuesday by telephone after
the US beat Finland, 3-2, to clinch second place in the round-robin
Three Nations Cup, with only Wednesday's statistically meaningless
game between Canada and Finland remaining. ``I think we
accomplished our goal of being able to blend in some of the rookies
with the veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in this Three Nations Cup, the US beat Canada for the
first time in an international hockey tournament; two months later
the Americans would defeat their northern neighbors and fierce
rivals, 3-1, for the Olympic gold medal. But these are new teams _
just over half of each are Olympians _ and this first competition
since Nagano signaled the beginning of a new cycle for all three
medal-winning squads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've closed that Olympic book, and now we're starting
fresh,'' said Sasner, who will hand the reins back to Olympic coach
Ben Smith for the World Championships next March. ``This is a new
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, its Olympic triumph has taken the target off the backs of
the Canadians, perennial world champions, and transferred it to the
Americans. ``Everybody's out to beat us now,'' said Sasner.
</P>
<P>
   Canada did just that in this tournament, though not by much. In
their first game, the US fell, 2-1, while on Monday the Americans
lost, 4-3, in a sudden death shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both losses to Canada were disappointing,'' Sasner said, ``but
more so because of the result than the way the team played. Our
second game against Canada was just a great hockey game. It's too
bad either team had to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In that game, typical of the drama when these teams meet, the US
went ahead early when Karyn Bye scored her second goal of the
tournament just 5:33 into the first period, and built its lead to
2-0 at 16:07 in the first on a slapshot by Shelley Looney. Canada
responded with three unanswered goals to go ahead, 3-2, at 4:32 of
the third period. Sue Merz converted on a power play about six
minutes later to tie the game at 3-3, and when neither team scored
in the 10-minute overtime period it went to a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Several newcomers stood out for the US, among them left winger
Krissy Wendell, a 17-year-old from Minnesota; Natalie Darwitz, a
15-year-old from the same state; and defenseman Kelly Halcisak, a
Michigan 16-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But Sasner was also impressed with the gold medalists. ``They
really showed the younger players what it takes,'' she said.
``They're not ready to just kick back and rest on the laurels of
the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for the rest of the teams coming to Finland
early next year for the World Championships, a title Canada still
holds and the US desperately wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are bigger wars ahead,'' Sasner said, looking ahead to
March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blizzard stay popular
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New England Blizzard has already lost five home games this
year, equalling its 17-5 home mark of last season, but fans don't
seem to be deterred. With attendance averaging 7,945, the 2-9 squad
is drawing only slightly fewer fans than this time a year ago and
is still luring almost 4,000 more spectators per game than the
league average. The Blizzard is 1-5 since losing top scorer Carolyn
(Jones) Young to a torn ACL. Young is scheduled to undergo surgery
Jan. 4 and will be out for the season . . . Elsewhere in the ABL,
34-year-old Teresa Edwards is still going strong: the four-time
Olympian is just nine points away from becoming the first ABL
player in league history to reach the 2,000 milestone. Her 20.8
points per game for the Philadelphia Rage leads the league this
season . . . It's a hat trick for the Harvard women's ice hockey
team, which boasts ECAC player (A.J. Mleczko), rookie (Angela
Ruggiero) and goaltender (Crystal Springer) of the week. On a
seven-game winning streak, the Crimson (10-1-0 and ranked No. 1 in
the nation) have not allowed a goal in the last 168:39 of action
and have outscored their opposition 49-7. Their only loss of the
year came Nov. 15 to Brown, 4-2 . . . For the second year in a row,
Cindy Parlow of North Carolina has been named the top women's
college hockey player. The Tar Heels forward becomes only the
second two-time recipient of the Hermann Award. Mia Hamm was the
other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
