u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-SMITH-BOS &LR;      12-16 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-SMITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBBY SMITH A SINGULAR SENSATION IN TWO SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When University of Vermont freshman Libby Smith was in high
school in Essex Junction, Vt., she was juggling three sports and
excelling at all of them.
</P>
<P>
   She was a basketball player who as a senior was named USA Today
Vermont Player of the Year, was a two-time all-state soccer player,
and won the Vermont Girls' High School State Championship in golf
as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Now Smith, 18, has narrowed the juggling _ she only plays two
sports competitively _ but is still excelling.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in her collegiate debut with the basketball team,
she scored 23 points, including the game-winning basket in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   She's been named America East Rookie of the Week twice,
including this week; has started all seven games with UVM, and
leads the conference in three-point percentage (44 percent).
</P>
<P>
   All this comes after her fall season with the men's golf team,
where she shot an average of 81 and was the Vermont medalist at the
New England Intercollegiate Golf Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a special kid,'' said basketball coach Keith Cieplicki.
``As a coach you get certain players you call once-in-a-lifetime
players, and that's what she is. She has a very strong mind and
will, but a very kind way. It's a really neat mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Cieplicki said he recruited the 5-foot-9 point guard after her
team at Essex won four straight state championships and amassed a
93-3 record. He also faced her team when he was a coach at
Burlington High.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just someone that knows how to win,'' he said. ``I felt
she was a key to our future.''
</P>
<P>
   But someone else at the school had his eye on Smith, too. That
was Mike Gilligan, the men's golf coach. The school has no women's
golf team, but he was sure Smith was good enough to play with the
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been reading about her for years, because she had been one
of the better amateur golfers in the state,'' Gilligan said. ``So
we had a kind of combined recruiting effort for her.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the first priority at UVM was to get Smith
to sign on for basketball, for which she was offered a full
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had to put in my two cents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan, who has been golf coach for six years, said he could
offer Smith a shot at the men's team, but that was about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her I had never had women on the golf team, and that
she would be allowed to try out with the men, and if she scored
well, she'd make the team,'' he said. ``But I'd keep her on the
roster no matter what she scored. Well, not only did she score
well, but she started out at No. 5, and is now No. 2 on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she was torn between the two sports when looking at
colleges, and was tempted by the University of Hartford, which has
a women's golf team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision, but academically, it didn't work
out,'' said Smith, an engineering major.
</P>
<P>
   As far as juggling the two sports, Smith said the two seasons
did overlap, and there were preseason basketball practices going on
while the golf season was winding down.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I did have to balance the two,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Which she did quite well, said Gilligan.
</P>
<P>
   After the America East golf championships in Portland, he said,
Smith had a sandwich and a nap on the three-hour ride back. When
the van arrived at the UVM campus in Burlington, Smith hopped out
and was on her way to the first day of tryouts for the basketball
team. She ran _ OK, she won _ the team's two-mile mandatory run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was after walking 18 holes and carrying her bag, and
riding back for three hours,'' Gilligan said. ``She never even told
me she had to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Smith understates that she has to play from the men's
tees, which are farther back than the women's tees.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've always played from the mens' tees _ it presented more
of a challenge to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cieplicki said he had no problem with Smith being a two-sport
athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encourage players to do as many different things that they
enjoy,'' he said. ``I discourage specialization. I think this has
been great for Libby and a model for her teammates, I think it adds
a lot in respect for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is earning plenty of respect on the court, too.
</P>
<P>
   She has scored in double figures in five of the team's seven
games, averages 36 minutes per game, ranks first on the team in
assists (4.57 per game), and second in free-throw percentage
(.818).
</P>
<P>
   The team is 5-2, and hopes to make it back to the NCAA
tournament, as it did in 1992, '93, and '94. Junior co-captain
Karalyn Church (6-foot-0) is the reigning America East Player of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she's been playing basketball ``ever since I could
dribble,'' and started playing golf when she was 7 years old, but
``wasn't serious about it until I was 11.'' That's when Smith and
her older brother played virtually all summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has a summer home in northern Vermont, and it's a
mile-and-a-half away from the course, so we'd just hang out all
day,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to join the boys' team in high school, since there
weren't enough girls to form a girls' team. But she did compete
individually in the state tournaments, which she won in 1995. Smith
also was named New England High School Girls' Golf Champion her
freshman and sophomore years.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she's grown to take it as a given that she has to
prove herself on the boys' and men's teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of had to make a name for myself, but it's not like
the boys were mean,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the returning players were pretty skeptical, but she's
like one of the guys now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan said he especially took delight when the team played
other schools for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to see the opposing teams get to know her,'' he said.
``They say `the word is that there's a pretty good player at UVM,
and it's a woman.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled with a chuckle that at the Intercollegiate
championships at New Seabury, a player on another team told his
coach that if he got beat by a woman, he'd sell his clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I was sure to match her with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith beat the man _ whom Gilligan diplomatically declined to
name _ by six strokes. No word on whether he sold his clubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
