<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADWATERS-FOREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVE THE HEADWATERS FOREST PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The last chance to preserve the Headwaters
Forest and protect thousands of additional acres of wildlife
habitat in Northern California is about to move into the final
phases of implementation.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? Powerful forces are arrayed to block the plan the
Clinton and Wilson administrations have developed for protecting
these old-growth redwoods, no matter what the cost for the
environment would be.
</P>
<P>
   This is the moment for Californians and the rest of the nation
to look past the banner-waving and the shouting, to assess how much
the Headwaters plan would actually accomplish for the sake of the
environment, and to measure how much would be lost if the opponents
succeed in destroying this effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Headwaters plan will preserve in perpetuity the largest
remaining privately owned tract of old-growth redwoods on Earth. It
goes far beyond existing law to provide unprecedented levels of
habitat conservation on 210,000 other acres owned by the Pacific
Lumber Co.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, one-fourth of our company's entire existing ownership
will be dedicated to preservation. That means permanent protection
not only for 7,500 acres in and surrounding virgin old-growth in
the Headwaters and Elk Head Springs forests, but also all of the
8,000 acres in the so-called ``lesser cathedrals'' of old growth
trees. In addition, we will place 30,000 acres in riparian buffer
zones and set aside nearly 10,000 acres to mitigate landslide
risks.
</P>
<P>
   No other timber company in the nation has to operate under the
restrictions we have adopted under the plan to protect coho and
chinook salmon, steelhead trout, and other aquatic resources. Since
logging would largely be limited to previously harvested areas that
have little or no habitat value for the marbled murrelet, state and
federal wildlife experts have affirmed that enactment of the plan
will ensure the long-term conservation of these birds.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the plan will put an end to more than a
decade of confrontation and turmoil on California's North Coast. It
will restore stability and security to the lives of the 1,600 men
and women who work for Pacific Lumber, and their families. It will
help to lay the foundation for the region's future prosperity. And
it will accomplish all this while securing the objective that
environmentalists have pursued since 1985 _ Headwaters will be
saved.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the Headwaters plan is broadly based and bipartisan.
It has the support of President Clinton and Gov. Pete Wilson, Vice
President Al Gore, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt and California Secretary for Resources Doug Wheeler. Both
Congress and the state Legislature have approved the funding to
acquire Headwaters and the other lands designated for permanent
preservation.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the same small band of activists who have claimed for
more than 10 years that they want to save Headwaters are now doing
everything they can to prevent it. When the Legislature voted in
August to approve the funds to save the ancient redwoods, this is
the group that denounced the effort, shouting from the balcony.
They have put their own followers' lives at risk in a reckless
campaign that their own instructional materials say is intended
simply to create chaos. And when the federal government last month
sent its top wildlife scientists to take public testimony on the
Headwaters plan, these activists rose and pointedly turned their
backs on the process, making a mockery of a serious environmental
review.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if they succeed? The funding to save Headwaters
will be withdrawn permanently if the plan has not been adopted by
March 1. The plan itself will collapse and there is nothing to take
its place. Since it has taken three years of delicate negotiations
to carry the effort to save Headwaters this far, there is no way
that the scores of scientists and political leaders who have
committed so much of their time and expertise to the development of
the plan could ever be reassembled to start over again.
</P>
<P>
   If the opposition succeeds, all of the provisions of the plan
that currently go far beyond existing law will be lost. That means
there will be far less land that will be required to be preserved
or protected. The Department of the Interior, for example, has
already pointed out that the Endangered Species Act will not
provide nearly as much protection as the Headwaters plan. Moreover,
the plan would conserve habitat for approximately 30 species that
are not currently listed; without the plan, they will receive no
protection under the state or federal endangered species acts.
</P>
<P>
   Without the plan, salvage logging in Headwaters, Elk Head
Springs, and the other virgin old growth forests can proceed. The
courts have already affirmed Pacific Lumber's authority to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Streamside protections will likewise revert to existing law _
which means that far less land will have to be set aside. The
Headwaters plan in some instances triples the level of protection
that would otherwise be required. And under the plan, Pacific
Lumber has committed to stormproofing 50 miles of roads in its
forests every year _ another provision that goes beyond any
statutory responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The people who are fighting to stop the Headwaters plan offer no
alternative. If they succeed, the future will only bring more years
of conflict and chaos. And defeat of the plan would leave Pacific
Lumber with little alternative except to proceed with a
constitutional takings lawsuit against the state and the federal
government that could wind up costing taxpayers hundreds of
millions of dollars more than implementing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   With so much to gain if the plan is adopted _ and so much to
lose if it is not _ it makes no sense for the environment, for the
economy, or for the public interest to throw away our last, best
chance to save Headwaters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Campbell is president and chief executive of the Pacific
Lumber Co. in Scotia, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
