<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS RUNNING INTO YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We would have the right to expect that since they got whipped in
St. Louis Sunday, the Patriots might be dragging, sagging, and just
plain listless.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if they are, they better got over it fast, because Mr.
Uptempo is coming to town, and he'll do a number on them Sunday in
Foxborough if they are not ready to run with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one who makes San Francisco so tough to defend,'' said the
New Orleans Saints' highly regarded defensive coordinator, Zavan
Yaralian, ``is Steve Young. Young is the guy. He makes them play
the game faster than any other team. The way they set the pace of
the game to play faster is different than any other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Young and the 49ers do not come to town bearing gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are refreshed,'' said coach Steve Mariucci the morning
after his team whacked the Detroit Lions, 35-13, Monday night in
San Francisco. ``We did a good job in that game and we want to keep
playing well right into the playoffs. I wanted to play a physical
game against Detroit, so we rested the team the two days before the
game and they responded. We beat them on the line of scrimmage on
both sides of the ball. We shut down their running game (Barry
Sanders). On offense, we spread the ball around to our receivers.
Steve did a good job. He ran more than usual. They gave it to him
and he took it. He's playing at a very high level right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Young is the most accurate passer in NFL history and has the
numbers to prove it. His 97.0 pass efficiency rating is the best
ever, 5 points above that of the man in second place, his 49ers
predecessor, Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young has great vision,'' said Yaralian, who must try to stop
Young twice every year. ``He sees the field as well as anyone. And
because he can scramble so well, he can buy more time for receivers
to get open by moving out of the pocket and making plays. Then, if
there is no one open, he can run. His running ability limits what a
defense can do against him. If you are playing man-to-man coverage
and he sees it and you have your defensive backs covering with
their backs to the line of scrimmage, he'll take off and make big
plays in the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Young has thrown a league-high 32 touchdown passes in directing
the NFL's No. 3 scoring offense, which averages more than 30 points
per game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two key questions for local NFL fans these days seem to be:
</P>
<P>
   (1) After owner Bob Kraft takes the Patriots to Connecticut, can
Boston get another team?
</P>
<P>
   Here is the official answer from the league: ``The location of
our teams is decided on a three-quarters vote of the teams in the
league. If another NFL team wanted to play in Boston, it would
require the approval of 75 percent of the teams in the league. This
is true whether the Patriots are playing in Foxborough or Hartford.
It would require a three-quarters vote of the teams in the league
for a second team to play in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation: Another team can come to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   (2) Will Patriots games that aren't sellouts in Hartford be
televised in the Boston market?
</P>
<P>
   The league response: ``The issue of the Patriots' games being
televised in Boston has not been discussed in detail by the league
at this point. There are several issues, including the fact that we
probably are talking about something which probably will not take
effect until the 2002 season.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation: The decision has not been made. However,
Jonathan Kraft of the Patriots said on WEEI Radio in Boston Tuesday
that his family wants the games televised in Boston, and that being
the case, the presence of his father, Bob, on the owners'
television committee would seem to ensure that the games will be
televised here.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
