<HEADER>
A2958 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ZOMBIES-NYTSF     12-16 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ZOMBIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 How the Dead Live: Stories.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Alvin Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   229 pp. St. Paul:
</P>
<P>
   Graywolf Press. Paper, $14.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; ZOMBIES
</P>
<P>
   BY PAul Baumann
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This you call living? That retort springs to mind after one puts
down the poet and novelist Alvin Greenberg's latest collection of
short stories. In ``How the Dead Live,'' Greenberg's subject is the
existential dread that seems to permeate life in the Minneapolis-
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul area, and he covers it with all the knowingness but
none of the whimsy that his fellow Minnesotan, Garrison Keillor,
brings to Lake Wobegon. Greenberg's storytelling can be mannered
and self-conscious, but if there is something a little too flat in
his spare style, something a little too pat in the anomie and
disconnectedness that buffet his characters, there is still real
life in these pages.
</P>
<P>
   A discerning ear, a wicked tongue and a sharp dramatic and
visual sense are evident throughout the collection. Greenberg can
put you into predicaments that are at once familiar yet alien:
behind the wheel with a man suffering from such severe prostate
pain that it obliterates every other sensation; in the training
room with a professional baseball player who is literally on his
last leg; in a house where clouds of dust from a construction
project, like Vesuvius's ash settling on Pompeii, entomb all signs
of human life.
</P>
<P>
   Such uncanny moments bring a sense of mystery as well as comedy.
In ``Gruber in Traffic,'' the protagonist, suddenly haunted by the
fact of death, is unnerved by the sight of an Orthodox rabbi
driving a Jaguar. In ``No Loose Ends,'' a divorced couple --
Greenberg's men and women circle warily like Beckett characters on
a Midwestern ash heap -- exchange venomous recriminations in
late-night phone calls that often require decoding:
</P>
<P>
   ``What Henry meant . . . was that if you expect the worst of
people, then, indeed, they probably will live up to your
expectations. . . . What Malvina meant . . . was wreathed in the
poison gas aura of sarcasm, as befits the battlefield. Aware of the
lethal hazards of modern warfare, however, Henry was . . . safely
ensconced behind the gas mask of irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to know is: Can anything of value --
civilization, for example -- survive the conditions of such a
no-man's-and no-woman's land as this?''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's wit and ability to bring a character quickly to life
are perhaps best exhibited in ``Scholars and Lovers.'' The story's
narrator teaches in a college humanities department, and his
deadpan descriptions of students and colleagues are pitch perfect.
The reversals Greenberg deftly plants and expertly sets off before
the eyes of the unsuspecting reader are a succession of wry
epiphanies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them involve the enigmatic Weinstein, a brilliant member
of the ``Adult Scholar'' program whose presence in the narrator's
class reawakens his passion for teaching but prompts an unwelcome
revelation. Weinstein seems to be a descendant, albeit a too
philosophically freighted one, of Nabokov's Pnin. Known as ``old
hat-and-gloves,'' the student with the heavy accent is notorious
for standing when addressing his professors and for never taking
off his coat or gloves. ``My heart leaps when he climbs slowly out
of his desk in my classroom and rises bulkily to his feet,'' the
professor confesses, ``fur hat, black woolen coat, leather gloves
and all, and I will go to the wall for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein, like the aimless freeway night rider Joey Ampersand
in the story ``FREE-43,'' is a singular creation. You want more of
him. But Greenberg is stingy. An elusive confrontation between
professor and sagelike student brings ``Scholars and Lovers'' to a
merely cryptic conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these stories peter out in a similar way. Too many
characters are sacrificed to an assumed faith in life's futility.
With his acute ear for the emptiness of so much of modern American
aspiration, Greenberg captures the truncated words and lives of a
society deprived of spiritual oxygen. One wishes he were better at
lifting up this world of mundane conflict and uncertainty, turning
it 90 or 180 degrees and allowing us to see things we never knew
existed, or only dimly perceived.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Paul Baumann is executive editor of Commonweal magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
