<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2959 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BLOOD-NYTSF     12-16 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BLOOD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BLOOD
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Epic History of Medicine and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   By Douglas Starr.
</P>
<P>
   441 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; RED GOLD
</P>
<P>
   BY DEBORAH BLUM
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ON Sept. 1, 1939, a young British physician named Janet Vaughan
received a much-dreaded telegram: ``Start bleeding.'' Vaughan had
been working frantically to establish a blood supply system in
London, racing against the possibility of war with Germany. The
city had no blood supplies and barely any place to put them if it
had. Vaughan's group was setting up refrigerators, anywhere -- in
empty hospital wings, in the back room of a bar. A year later, when
the bombing of London was under way, delivery drivers were
careering around the city at night. Vaughan and her colleagues had
been bleeding in earnest: doctors used almost 70,000 pints of
blood. As Douglas Starr shows in his fine book, ``Blood: An Epic
History of Medicine and Commerce,'' the destruction of war, and the
demands it made, greatly accelerated medicine's ability to use
blood well. The desperate scramble by services like Janet Vaughan's
led straight to the take-it-for-granted use of blood and blood
products.
</P>
<P>
   It's a difficult notion to convey in these post-Vietnam,
``Saving Private Ryan'' days, that there could be a silver lining
to the darkness of war. And Starr's book does not, in any sense,
favor combat. His description of the carnage of the battlefield is
unflinchingly grim; there's an especially bitter recounting of
Americans fighting in the Pacific, where in some battles 60 percent
of the medical personnel present were killed trying to help, or
just get near, dying soldiers. But it's that horror that shows why
researchers drove the science so hard, drove the technology, rushed
through ways to package blood, process it, preserve it, deliver it
by any means possible. Vaughan told of finding a small girl so
badly burned in a bomb-lighted fire that she couldn't find a vein.
There in the darkness, she remembered a research article that
theorized that one could transfuse through bone marrow. She punched
her biggest needle into the child's breastbone and it worked. The
technique was adopted at sea: ``You see, on a rocking boat getting
into a vein is very likely to be difficult, whereas you could hope
to get into a sternum.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is just an extended war story. Starr begins his
history of blood as a mystery, back when physicians had no idea,
really, what this warm, red liquid was. They regarded it as a
semimystical substance and practiced the kind of semimystical
medicine that encourages one to rejoice in the fortune of being
born much later. In the 17th century, for instance, personality was
considered literally to flow through the veins, and transfusion a
possible means of improving character in both people and animals.
At one point, trying to alter a wife beater's behavior, a doctor
dosed him with the blood of a mild-mannered calf. The idea of blood
as necessary to health had no credence; most doctors believed that
they could cure illness by letting the ``bad'' blood drip away.
George Washington, as the author reminds us, died in late 1799
after two straight days of being bled in response to a streplike
infection.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the notion of replacing lost blood -- and, equally
important, of using typed and tested blood -- didn't catch on until
this century, and then not really until the 1930's. Starr, who is
co-director of the graduate program in science journalism at Boston
University, tells this story graphically and well. The writing is
straight-ahead, calm amid the goriest events. He's done a
tremendous amount of research too, and deftly uses anecdotes and
personalities to enliven potentially dry descriptions, like the
separation of blood into its myriad components. By the war's end, a
whole industry is taking shape and, equally important, as Vaughan
and her counterparts in the laboratory persist, as they demystify
blood, they drive a cultural shift. Blood itself begins to seem
less essentially human, merely a formula. As perception changes --
as blood becomes industrial chemistry -- so does the way in which
it is handled. Starr compares blood to oil: a necessary and
profitable product that starts belonging less to researchers and
more to a sometimes motley collection of entrepreneurs and a
territorial collection of blood bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The story of blood illustrates more than one of the real
paradoxes of medicine. Practice balances on a perilously imperfect
point, between detachment and compassion. Blood is, indeed, a
remarkable formula; understanding that, in the most clinical way,
is what allows us to use it and market it effectively. Starr, in
fact, insists that there's a logical parallel between the blood
industry and the oil industry; indeed, some people have actually
called blood ``red gold.'' Still, the comparison makes it only
partway home. The early physicians had a point: blood, unlike oil,
is the stuff of life. The failure to recognize or at least honor
that difference led to a tragic miscalculation on our watch: the
failure of the blood industry after the rise of the AIDS epidemic
to protect its products, and so all the people who receive them,
from infection. In France, as became clear in a continuing national
scandal, officials knew that blood supplies could kill, and chose,
in a cost-benefit analysis, to let it happen anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Starr methodically takes apart the French bureaucrats who found
the deaths of others so acceptable an answer. He does an even
better job of showing how contamination of clotting agents ripped
apart the American community of hemophiliacs. He writes not only of
betrayal but of the demoralizing sense of shared guilt, perfectly
illustrated in this quotation from the mother of a child infected
with AIDS through the injections of clotting factor: ``Today, I got
up to shower and dress and while brushing my hair looked in the
mirror and saw for the umpteenth time the person who injected the
lethal dosage into the veins of my hemophiliac son.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a haunting image, and this is so sad and so intense a piece
of recent history that the somewhat tentative final chapter that
follows -- where are we going, what have we learned -- comes as an
anticlimax. ``We have to be careful how we use it'' is a thought
that had occurred to me about blood before I read several hundred
pages on the topic. I didn't finish this book with confidence in
the safety of the blood supply. We have reliable procedures for
handling for blood, but not for insuring reliable caretakers; the
next chapter in the history of blood will doubtless contain its own
measure of heroics and of arrogance. Those ancient mystics had a
point: the story of blood is still the story of human nature.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Blum, a professor of journalism at the University of
Wisconsin, Madison, is the author of ``Sex on the Brain'' and ``The
Monkey Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
