<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FAIRWAYS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 FORBIDDEN FAIRWAYS:
<TEXT>
<P>
   African Americans and the Game of Golf.
</P>
<P>
   By Calvin H. Sinnette.
</P>
<P>
   216 pp. Chelsea, Mich.: Sleeping Bear Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; MEMBERS ONLY
</P>
<P>
   BY CLIFTON BROWN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While many African-Americans have loved golf for generations,
the sport has not always returned that love. Calvin H. Sinnette
shows that in ``Forbidden Fairways,'' a straightforward and
informative book that describes the exploits of many courageous,
innovative and determined individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The book's jacket cover depicts Bill Spiller, a legendary black
golfer during the 1940's and 50's, sitting forlornly on a bench at
the 1952 San Diego Open, head in his hand, dejection on his face,
after being excluded from the tournament because of the
Professional Golfers' Association's color bar. Yet, as Sinnette
notes, many blacks have overcome great odds to make important
contributions to golf's history. After diligent research and
hundreds of interviews, he chronicles triumphs and tragedies to
give a revealing look at men and women who simply longed for a fair
shake on fairways that were forbidden to them.
</P>
<P>
   Sinnette -- giving credit to black newspapers for providing
critical references, because mainstream newspapers seldom published
information about minority exploits in golf -- begins with the
sport's all-too-little-known African-American trailblazers. George
Grant, a dentist from Boston, designed the first golf tee
registered by the United States Patent Office, in 1899. John
Shippen was the first black American to play in the United States
Open, in 1896, even though some competitors threatened to withdraw.
Dewey Brown, who learned the game as a caddie, became a renowned
club designer and teacher during the 1920's and 30's. Around the
same time, Joseph Bartholomew, a noted architect, designed and
built more than a half-dozen golf courses in the New Orleans area.
Because he was black, Bartholomew was not allowed to play on the
courses he built. ``Finally fed up with the prejudice that was
preventing African-Americans from playing the game,'' Sinnette
writes, ``Bartholomew constructed a seven-hole course for black
golfers on property he owned in nearby Harahan, La. It was
separate, but -- even with his superb skills -- he could not make
it equal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980's and early 90's, country clubs with affluent
white members that barred blacks and other ethnic groups became
increasingly popular. The first documented country club owned by
blacks was the nine-hole Shady Rest Golf and Country Club in Scotch
Plains, N.J. It was originally a white-owned club called the
Westfield Country Club, but when Westfield's members decided to
expand to an 18-hole course, they sold the club to a group of black
investors. Shady Rest survived from 1921 until 1963, when it became
a public facility and changed its name to the Scotch Hills Country
Club. As of 1998, Sinnette could find only four black-owned golf
courses in existence, the oldest being the Clearview Golf Course in
East Canton, Ohio, owned by William Powell, the father of Renee
Powell, who played on the Ladies' Professional Golf Association
Tour for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks who dreamed of careers in professional golf were rebuffed
during the 40's and 50's. The best black golfers played primarily
in events sponsored by the United Golf Association and other black
organizations. The P.G.A. did not delete its infamous ``Caucasian
race'' clause until 1961. Talented golfers like Spiller, Ted Rhodes
and Charlie Sifford were barred from most P.G.A. Tour events for
years, but their legal and moral battles, as well as their ability
on the golf course, helped pave the way for others, like Lee Elder,
Calvin Peete and, of course, Tiger Woods. And in a chapter devoted
to women's golf, Sinnette, a retired pediatrician, tells of the
accomplishments of Ann Gregory, who won many U.G.A. events and who
became the first black woman to play in the United States Women's
Amateur, in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample room for more books on African-Americans in golf.
However, ``Forbidden Fairways'' required passion and persistence,
and Sinnette has done a significant service in bringing attention
to achievements and struggles that are an important part of golf's
history.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Brown is a sports reporter for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
