<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2961 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CHARACTER-NYT     12-16 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHARACTER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE CORROSION OF CHARACTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   Personal Consequences of Work in the New Capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Sennett.
</P>
<P>
   176 pp. New York: W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; YOU CALL THIS PROGRESS?
</P>
<P>
   BY ALAN EHRENHALT
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of the more unusual events in recent American politics was
the sudden appearance and rapid disappearance of the Angry American
Worker. For a few noisy weeks in the spring of 1996 he was the star
of the Presidential campaign -- a decent, hard-working citizen who
had been rudely downsized out of a job and was casting about for
someone to blame. Candidates in both parties struggled for
effective ways to offer him sympathy, and promised him governmental
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Then, almost as quickly as he had entered, the Angry American
Worker left the stage. By the time of the fall campaign between
Bill Clinton and Bob Dole, he had ceased to be a topic of
discussion altogether. Nor has he emerged very often since. In the
thousands of campaigns waged this year for state, local and
national office, I know of none that centered on the issue of the
displaced worker's plight.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a simple explanation for this sequence of
events. It is that the booming national economy of the mid-1990's
took care of the problem. At a time when unemployment is just over
4 percent and good new jobs are being created in ample numbers, the
50 million or so jobs that have disappeared over the past two
decades need not preoccupy any of us very long. Even the poster
child of early 1996 -- the middle-aged white-collar employee
downsized onto the street after a career of consummate corporate
loyalty -- becomes whole again once he finds new work somewhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the majority of mainstream economists will tell
you. It is not what Richard Sennett believes. A sociologist at New
York University and the London School of Economics, Sennett is the
author of several provocative books on work, family and social
class. He thinks the wrenching changes of late-20th-century
capitalism are having subtle but profound consequences that will
endure far into the next century. ``Many more are hurt,'' he warns,
``than cry out.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sennett is an unusual writer. He has always brought to
his topics a combination of broad historical and literary learning
and a reporter's willingness to walk into a store or factory,
strike up a conversation and write down what he hears. In ``The
Corrosion of Character,'' he reports on his regular visits to a
bakery in Boston, a bar in Manhattan and a self-help club of
middle-aged I.B.M. castoffs in upstate New York, interspersing his
observations with excursions into Marx, Diderot, 17th-century
mathematics and Virgil's ``Georgics.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument may take an occasional detour, but the ultimate
point is always clear: the working conditions of modern capitalism
are eating away at loyalty, commitment and the kind of long-term
thinking that used to make even the most routine work a central
ingredient in orderly human life.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston bakery where 25 years ago Sennett interviewed
sweating Greek-Americans grumpy about the conditions but proud of
themselves and their product, he returned to find a collection of
interchangeable transients pressing buttons to produce loaves of
bread they never saw or touched. They do not consider themselves
bakers; they do not plan to stay in the job more than a few months,
even if they could; most of them have no idea what they will be
doing in a year, let alone where they will be in a decade. They are
not angry, or alienated -- they lack the necessary emotional
investment for that. They are merely indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   The disaffectedness of Sennett's bakers differs only by degree
from that of the workers he meets at higher levels of the economic
ladder. Rico, the son of a janitor who lived for his children's
future, has achieved almost everything the father dreamed about. He
is a consultant to computer companies, with a good income and a
spacious house in the New York suburbs. But his working life has
been no picnic. He has moved four times in 14 years, been downsized
out of a job by virtue of a corporate merger, and patched his
career back together as an independent operator whose professional
relationships are, in their way, as transient and unstable as those
in the bakery. He has no more idea where he will be in 10 years
than the bakers do.
</P>
<P>
   Rico tells Sennett that he feels the decline of loyalty and its
depressing result all around him, not just in the business world
but in the culture and in his family life. ``You can't imagine how
stupid I feel,'' he says, ``when I talk to my kids about
commitment. It's an abstract virtue to them; they don't see it
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   THE downsized I.B.M. executives Sennett talks to at the River
Winds Cafe, in a town in New York's Hudson Valley, seem at first to
be making a peaceful adjustment to the earthquake that hit them.
Perhaps these were some of the Angry American Workers of early
1996, but they are mellower now, wistful rather than bitter about
the fact that they spend their afternoons in a cafe rather than in
a cubicle at Big Blue. But anyone who wishes to count this as
progress might still be well advised to ponder Sennett's account of
the consequences. The I.B.M. exiles have not only accepted
responsibility for their fate, they have turned inward in general,
expending energy on self-awareness that used to be devoted to
school boards, local government and other forms of public
participation. ``They aren't afraid of holding up their heads in
the community,'' Sennett reports. ``They've just lost interest in
civic affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it is a bleak picture. But Sennett leaves the reader
with a tantalizing morsel of optimism. He believes that
end-of-century Americans, denied the satisfactions of order and
rootedness in the workplace, will finally begin to rebuild them
from scratch in the rest of their lives. ``One of the unintended
consequences of modern capitalism,'' he writes, ``is that it has
strengthened the value of place, aroused a longing for community .
. . for some other scene of attachment and depth.'' The reader must
fill in for himself where this will happen -- on neighborhood
streets, in schools, perhaps most of all in the trenches of family
relationships. But one reaches the end of this book convinced, with
Sennett, that the reaction is bound to come.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ehrenhalt is the executive editor of Governing magazine and
the author of ``The Lost City'' and ``The United States of
Ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
