<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2962 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SIN-NYTSF     12-16 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE SIN EATER
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Alice Thomas Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   192 pp. Wakefield, R.I.:
</P>
<P>
   Moyer Bell. $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; AS HE LAY DYING
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVID FINKLE
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FIRST pressing reason to read ``The Sin Eater'': the appearance
in it of a sheep called Virginia Woolf. Of an animal that moves
through the action with oblivious purpose, the omniscient narrator
observes, ``The sheep had been named because of the facial
resemblance, which was very marked.''
</P>
<P>
   If more persuasion is needed to hook readers into Alice Thomas
Ellis's sly novel of (bad) manners, perhaps the best way to put it
is that the book's bipeds walk around as if outfitted in spiked
armor. It's Ellis's conviction that the idiosyncratic attitudes by
which people live render connections between them impossible. Their
pricking interactions inevitably have comic or sad repercussions --
more likely, both.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Wales, where Ellis's previous novels and memoir take
place, the book examines a contentious family that's fetched up for
a long weekend in a house outside the village of Llanelys to see
whether the ailing patriarch, identified only as the Captain, is
going to die. The sulfurous deathwatch is attended by the Captain's
three children, Henry, Michael and Ermyn; his sons' wives, Rose and
Angela; and Edward, a journalist friend. Tending to their needs, or
spitefully holding out on them, are the housekeeper, Phyllis; her
son, Jack; and grandson, Gomer.
</P>
<P>
   As the discontented relatives and retainers go about their busy
but superficially uneventful schedules -- shopping, cooking,
napping, attending a picnic, participating in an annual cricket
match -- it's Rose and Ermyn whom Ellis observes most closely.
Rose, a Roman Catholic and therefore deemed inferior to the family
into which she has married, runs the household with sour
efficiency. Her every thought is wry. When, for instance, Angela
and Michael arrive, she is ``gratified to see they both wore silly
hats.'' Ermyn, entering adulthood, is so unsure of her ability to
manage anything that she responds most readily to inanimate
objects. ``It seemed foolish to envy a train, but its determination
was astounding,'' she muses on the trip home.
</P>
<P>
   In a book where, to paraphrase Nichols and May, there's
proximity but little relating, Rose and Ermyn do join up for a
venture into town, but, typically, they're at cross-purposes.
Later, Ermyn -- hiding the Bible between the pages of Country Life
because she fears her religious interests are ``very poor form'' --
contemplates a conversion to Catholicism. ``You'd never get in past
the people falling over themselves to get out,'' Rose snaps.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ellis is so taken with Rose and Ermyn, the other players
in this juicy blend of Anton Chekhov and Ivy Compton-Burnett get
less page time. That, though, is part of Ellis's unknowability
thesis. It's what allows her to hint at shenanigans rather than
announce them obstreperously. When the others disappear into
literal and symbolic bushes, Ellis is provoking speculation on what
they've been up to. Rose is lusted after -- and knows it -- by the
gormless Gomer, but with whom else is he dallying? What's going on
between boozy Edward and self-impressed Angela? When Phyllis
tinkers under the hood of Michael's car, what is she planning?
</P>
<P>
   Choosing to leave answers to the imagination is Ellis's way of
saying that imagination is all we have in our efforts to comprehend
one another. We're too detached, she suggests, for anything else to
work. Letting our suppositions fill in the blanks doesn't, however,
excuse her from the novel's one drawback -- the sketchiness with
which the men are depicted. Perhaps Ellis feels that she
understands her own sex but is reluctant to portray men any more
than is absolutely necessary. Unfortunately (fortunately?), she's
so skillful at making a reader want more that it's noticeable when
she's been casual about characters prowling the fringes.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis takes her title from a Welsh custom whereby the ingestion
of funeral meats represents ridding the deceased of his sins.
Though ``The Sin Eater'' may be about dealing with poisonous
natures, it lends itself all the same to being gobbled up whole.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David Finkle writes frequently about books and theater. He has
just completed a family memoir.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
