<HEADER>
A2963 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NEWHOUSE-NYTS     12-16 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NEWHOUSE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 CITIZEN NEWHOUSE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Portrait of a Media Merchant.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Felsenthal.
</P>
<P>
   512 pp. New York: Seven Stories Press. $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; KING OF ALL MEDIA
</P>
<P>
   BY TOM GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of what her publisher labels an ``unauthorized
investigative biography'' of S. I. Newhouse Jr. and his influential
publishing family, Carol Felsenthal devotes 22 chunky paragraphs to
Tina Brown's stepping down from The New Yorker, the flagship
magazine of the Newhouse collection. The chapter, called ``The
Queen of Buzz Buzzes Off,'' is short on fresh insights. This is not
surprising given that a blunderbuss endnote for the episode lists
more than 50 articles, mostly from the three New York City dailies,
which covered Brown's resignation with the thoroughness generally
accorded a sudden change of leadership in a medium-sized European
country.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by her endnotes, Felsenthal has read just about
everything ever written about this very private family. Like other
Newhouse biographers before her, she did not get to interview any
of the immediate family members, who famously shun publicity. So
Felsenthal, whose earlier book on Katharine Graham of The
Washington Post received some good reviews (and some withering ones
as well), faced a formidable task: to pierce a shield of privacy.
She interviewed more than 400 people, a remarkable number, which
only shows that an author can interview a lot of people and still
not come up with the story. She talked to many of Si Newhouse's
high school classmates, some of his former colleagues and employees
(many of whom were dismissed or left with a grievance) and his
former wife, Jane Franke, who generously concludes, ``I think it
was the blind leading the blind in our marriage and our
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizen Newhouse'' was initially signed with Viking, but new
management there took the unusual step of canceling the book when
it was done -- a decision that was itself the subject of news
articles and gossip columns. Felsenthal said that once she turned
in the manuscript, Phyllis Grann, president of Penguin Putnam Inc.,
parent of Viking, told her she couldn't publish it because too many
people mentioned in it were friends. (Until earlier this year, the
Newhouses owned Random House.) It is equally conceivable that Grann
turned down the manuscript because it was deficient and was too
polite to say this. No other publisher came forward until Seven
Stories Press volunteered. Felsenthal's agent, Philippa Brophy,
represents Gary Webb, whose controversial ``Dark Alliance: The CIA,
the Contras, and the Crack Cocaine Explosion'' is also published by
Seven Stories. According to her notes, Webb is a source for
Felsenthal's assessment of The Cleveland Plain Dealer, one of many
Newhouse newspapers, which she calls ``perhaps the most
relentlessly reviled paper in the country.'' (I have read many
lists ranking newspapers as good or bad or up or down, but never as
reviled.) She then quotes Webb: ``Of all the newspapers I've worked
for, that is the most bizarre operation, where the business side
essentially runs the newspaper.'' This is annoyingly unfair. If she
tried to determine whether the business side ran the paper, it
doesn't show. And she fails to mention that Webb left more than a
decade ago, a period during which that paper and most Newhouse
papers have improved significantly.
</P>
<P>
   What this book is, then, is a rather dull hatchet job. The
contradictions of the Newhouse family, which through its various
publications, including Vogue and Vanity Fair, has done so much to
promote the culture of celebrity while remaining intensely private,
remain unexplained. Felsenthal suggests that Si Newhouse's younger
brother, Donald, is the real force behind the company's success,
but supplies incomplete evidence. She describes little of the
interplay between the brothers except to note that they dine once a
week with their families at the same East Side restaurant and that
they like each other. Si Newhouse and his brother, like their
father before them, are rich and shrewd. Just how shrewd and how
rich are not knowable. Unlike most families in their business, they
have not taken their company public. In this book, Si Newhouse, in
particular, comes across as opaque, hard-working, introverted and
addicted to celebrity employees, some of whom he dismisses on whim.
This is an oft-told tale. How the quirky figure Felsenthal portrays
has been able to build such an influential enterprise remains
unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   An afterthought: publishing moguls often make fascinating
subjects for biographies, but perhaps it is time to retire the
honorific Citizen in the title. Let this book be the last of its
kind.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goldstein is the dean of the Columbia University Graduate
School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
