<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2964 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-IRIS-1000&AMP;ADD     12-16 2029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-IRIS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ELEGY FOR IRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By John Bayley.
</P>
<P>
   275 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press. $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; IRIS AND JOHN
</P>
<P>
   BY MARY GORDON
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   John Bayley, the distinguished literary critic, author of books
on Shakespeare and Tolstoy, has been married for more than 40 years
to Iris Murdoch, the eminent novelist and philosopher. Now Murdoch
has been stricken with Alzheimer's disease and Bayley has the sole
care of her. His caretaking is an act of heroic love, but every now
and again he loses his composure. He speaks of ``the horrid wish,
almost a compulsion at some moments, to show the other how bad
things are. Force her to share the knowledge, relieve what seems my
isolation. I make a savage comment today about the grimness of our
outlook. Iris looks relieved and intelligent. She says, 'But I love
you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   These heartbreaking sentences exemplify an important part of the
greatness of ``Elegy for Iris.'' It is a greatness that must be
seen simultaneously in literary and moral terms, for the moral
trustworthiness of Bayley's voice is inextricably connected to its
rightness of tone. Bayley is indeed engaged in a continuing act of
heroic love, but the heroism plays itself out in a register that is
unfamiliar to contemporary audiences, particularly American ones.
Its dominant notes are humility, modesty, patience and humor. The
heroism is all the more admirable for its reluctance to acknowledge
that heroism might be defined in such terms.
</P>
<P>
   It may be surprising to speak to the pleasures of a book that
recounts a tragedy, but Bayley has been throughout his life a
determined searcher, in a particularly English way, for life's
pleasures. His descriptions of these are in themselves a cause for
joy. He speaks of the roses in his failed garden: ``They had
tissuelike petals and smelled of wine. The white petals looked as
transparent as ice.'' The book is full of humor: he tells us that
he is grateful that he and Iris were spared ``the media-haunted
kitchens of today.'' He chronicles, with a quiet relish, the
pleasures of a successful and enjoyable marriage in which two
singular souls found a happiness as luminous as any we have heard
of in the annals of marriage (a genre not noted for appealing
models). For John Bayley and Iris Murdoch, marriage was much
concerned with the preservation of individual solitude. Bayley's
aphorisms about marriage have the formal satisfaction of La
Rochefoucauld's, substituting self-reflective generosity for
knowing bitterness: ``Inside marriage, one ceases to be observant
because observation has become so automatic, its object at once
absorbing and taken for granted''; ``To feel oneself held and
cherished and accompanied, and yet to be alone. To be closely and
physically entwined, and yet feel solitude's friendly presence, as
warm and undesolating as contiguity itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rivers and pictures were our holiday ideals,'' Bayley says,
and we enter the story of Iris Murdoch's decline at a moment by a
river. This is not the mighty Mississippi or the romantic Danube.
It's a poky little river near Oxford, where the couple have taken
dips on hot days for nearly half a century. The scene of their
final bathe in this river is as masterly as a moment of Chekhov:
</P>
<P>
   ``In her shabby old one-piece swimsuit . . . she was an awkward
and anxious figure, her socks trailing round her ankles. She was
obstinate about not taking these off, and I gave up the struggle. A
pleasure barge chugged slowly past, an elegant girl in a bikini
sunning herself on the deck, a young man in white shorts at the
steering wheel. . . . We must have presented a comic spectacle --
an elderly man struggling to remove the garments from an old lady,
still with white skin and incongruously fair hair. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in the water, Iris cheered up a bit. It was almost too
warm, hardly refreshing. But its old brown slow-flowing
deliciousness remained, and we smiled happily at each other as we
paddled quietly to and fro. Waterlily leaves, with an occasional
fat yellow flower, rocked gently at the passage of a pleasure boat.
Small bright blue dragonflies hovered motionless above them. The
water was deep, and cooler as we moved out from the bank, but we
did not go out far. Looking down, I could see her muddy feet, still
in their socks, moving in the brown depths.'' Anyone who has cared
for an Alzheimer's patient will be struck by the detail of the
socks. A balked willfulness about routines of life like bathing and
dressing can become characteristic, and can darken the morning of
the most cheerful caretaker. The details of this river swim are
metaphoric for Bayley and Murdoch's life together: the ``brown
slow-flowing deliciousness,'' the ``occasional fat yellow flower,''
the ``small bright blue dragonflies,'' the depths noted but not
explored, the glamorous world glimpsed from the corner of the eye.
The sources of Bayley and Murdoch's bond are not those of
conventional heterosexual romance, ending up at the altar; what
they both seemed to be after was submersion in a pool that would
allow them a dependable refreshment and also the occasional glimpse
of brilliance. It is possible to say they married for privacy and
comfort, but to say that is to ignore the mystery and complexity of
their union.
</P>
<P>
   John Bayley fell in love with Iris Murdoch when he was in his
late 20's and she was in her early 30's; she passed his window on a
bicycle. ``I indulged the momentary fantasy that nothing had ever
happened to her; that she was simply bicycling about, waiting for
me to arrive. She was not a woman with a past or an unknown
present.'' This almost mystical vision, in which Murdoch appears as
timeless as God, foreshadows the timelessness that is the curse of
the victim of Alzheimer's, in which past and future are collapsed
into a moment that is a mix of blankness and anxiety. Bayley
suggests that the comparative lack of anguish with which he can
experience his wife's condition is explicable by its echoes in his
past perception of her. Always she was, for him, a person for whom
identity was not important; she was always protean, hidden; he
rejoiced in her unknowableness. The impermeability of her mind now
is, for him, only another type of something he has always known.
</P>
<P>
   Radical privacy, sealing compartments of her life off from each
other, was always a condition of Iris Murdoch's selfhood, and
anyone who married her had to deal with that. From the beginning,
she had friendships that she kept from Bayley, and love affairs
that he was meant to understand had nothing to do with him. There
are some hints that this was not always easy, but Bayley rose to
the challenge. ``In early days, I always thought it would be vulgar
-- as well as not my place -- to give any indications of jealousy,
but she knew when it was there, and she soothed it just by being
the self she always was with me, which I soon knew to be wholly and
entirely different from any way that she was with other people.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-IRIS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: other people.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bayley did desire Iris Murdoch, but it was a desire both simpler
and more complex than the kind we are used to hearing about. Its
source was the body, but its satisfactions contained intimations of
a kind of pastoral comedy in which the true Eden is a return to
childhood. When they first embrace after a dance in which Iris
appears ridiculous to him in a flame-colored brocade, falling down
the stairs by way of entrance, we are told that ``she seemed to be
giving way to some deep need of which she had been wholly
unconscious: the need to throw away not only the maneuvers and
rivalries of intellect but also the emotional fears and
fascinations, the power struggles and surrenders of adult loving.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bayley tells us ``I think one reason we fell in love, and
got on so well, is that both of us have always been naive and
innocent, at some deep healing level.'' Bayley asserts that Murdoch
has always been free of professional competitiveness and
ambitiousness; her having forgotten that she has written books is
an extension of the modest self-forgetfulness that marked her as a
writer. Neither of them seemed interested in any sort of
fashionableness; they dressed badly and lived in domestic chaos in
a crumbling house. They were remarkably free of the demands of the
outside world; they pleased themselves and each other.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is no one else but him in her world, and his days are
shaped by caring for her. That he can see this as a great hardship
but not a martyrdom is a triumph not only of goodness but also of
the imagination. The greatest anguish for someone who loves an
Alzheimer's patient is the sense that the beloved is no longer
there, but Bayley uses his luminous and supple mind to prevent that
anguish; he insists upon the continuity between their past and
their present. The couple who spent hours in front of a Piero
fresco now devote their mornings to watching ``Teletubbies'';
nevertheless, they share an act of visual apprehension. He is quite
aware of the cruel irony that their marriage, which was marked by a
desire to return to the innocence of childhood, condemns them to
the radical simplicity of childhood because Murdoch is no longer
capable of anything else. Bayley suggests that their marriage was
not most importantly a marriage of true minds, but a marriage of
domestic closeness, of shared routines, shared jokes, rituals,
songs, of physical proximity and the dependability of seeing each
other regularly. They still have all that, in terrible spades.
</P>
<P>
   BayleY is neither a fool nor a deceiver, of himself or of us. He
does not forget the loss, or the fact that the main victim is his
wife, not himself. ``All this sounds quite merry, but in fact, most
days are for her a kind of despair,'' he writes. He recounts a
harrowing bus trip from Gatwick Airport to Oxford, during which
Murdoch panics, harassing the bus driver and her fellow passengers.
Bayley arrives home desperate, sick with flu, knowing they won't
make such a trip again. He is adamant about resisting the invasive
help of the welfare state, but I wanted to beg him to call on his
beloved friends, to whom he and his wife have given so much for so
many years, to suggest to him the limits of a stiff upper lip and
the tonic effects of an afternoon off.
</P>
<P>
   But such practical considerations seem almost to defile the
sacred enclosure of the Bayley-Murdoch marriage, of which Murdoch's
illness is, after all, only the latest chapter. ``Elegy for Iris,''
a title with its own rather dark double meanings, is a celebration
of the mystery of human connection, which marriage metonymically
enacts. Bayley wanted Murdoch in his life; he treasured her as a
benevolent, constant, and finally incomprehensible presence. He
still rejoices in her presence beside him in the marriage bed; he
is still able to swim in the river of his desire: ``It is
wonderfully peaceful to sit in bed with Iris reassuringly asleep
and gently snoring. Half asleep again myself, I have a feeling of
floating down the river, and watching all the rubbish from the
house and from our lives -- the good as well as the bad -- sinking
slowly down through the dark water until it is lost in the depths.
Iris is floating or swimming quietly beside me. Weeds and larger
leaves sway and stretch themselves beneath the surface. Blue
dragonflies dart and hover to and fro by the riverbank. And
suddenly, a kingfisher flashes past.''
</P>
<P>
   Santayana said that everything in nature is lyrical in its ideal
essence, comic in its existence and tragic in its fate. In its
evocation of the lyrical, the comic and the tragic, this splendid
book enlarges our imagination of the range and possibilities of
love.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Mary Gordon's latest books are ``Spending,'' a novel, and ``The
Shadow Man,'' a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
