<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2965 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BORBA-NYTSF     12-16 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BORBA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 QUINCAS BORBA
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Joaquim Maria Machado de Assis.
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Gregory Rabassa.
</P>
<P>
   290 pp. New York: Oxford University Press. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE EMPEROR'S NEW DOG
</P>
<P>
   BY JONATHAN KEATES
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Until the end of the 19th century, almost every novelist or
dramatist felt honor bound to respect the canons of traditional
storytelling. Plots carried no obvious suggestion of alternative
beginnings or endings. Events occurred in chronological sequence
and the omniscient author, while entitled to direct reaction to the
narrative, was not expected to interfere drastically with its
progress or behave too waywardly in developing characters. Now and
then a writer might feel bold enough to kick over the traces.
George Eliot abruptly halted the majestic progress of
``Middlemarch'' to examine a flaw in her technique as narrator. At
a crucial moment in one of his comedies the Italian dramatist Carlo
Goldoni inserted an astonishing address by the heroine to the
audience, telling us what she might have said if her creator could
have been bothered to observe correct dramatic protocol.
</P>
<P>
   With Joaquim Maria Machado de Assis, however, whose novel
``Quincas Borba'' was first published in 1891, we arrive at a
genuine subversive, bent on overturning convention but always with
an air of leisurely nonchalance. Steeped in the work of
contemporary French and British novelists, he nevertheless rejected
the missionary realism of Zola or a Trollopean matter-of-factness
in favor of an authenticity based, with conscious irony, on
emphasizing contrivance. Truth to life in ``Quincas Borba'' depends
not on incidental details of calling cards, carriages or newspapers
but on the author's continuing presence as ringmaster and stage
manager, constantly reminding us of his power to dissipate or
rearrange the universe he created.
</P>
<P>
   This deliberate air of transience is partly induced by Machado's
own world of late-19th-century Brazil, poised to become a republic
after 70 years as an empire ruled by a branch of the royal family
of Portugal. Machado had long ago perceived the inherent frailties
of the imperial charade, sustained by halfhearted attempts at
constitutional democracy in a nation that still relied extensively
on slave labor. The ultimate madness of his hero, Rubiao de
Alvarenga, is emblematic of the country's dubious political
destiny, while the man himself, according to one authoritative
reading of the novel, is Brazil's last Emperor, Pedro II.
</P>
<P>
   Such an interpretation matters less perhaps for the ordinary
reader than the book's links with its predecessor among Machado's
works, ``The Posthumous Memoirs of Bras Cubas,'' whose principal
character, the eccentric philosopher Quincas Borba, here provides
us with a deliberately misleading title. After a lingering illness
Borba dies, leaving vast wealth -- ``slaves, bonds, stocks in the
Bank of Brazil . . . jewelry, coins, books'' -- which he himself
acquired at the last minute after years of shabby penury, to a
genuinely grieving Rubiao. The sole proviso is that the heir must
look after the dead man's dog (also named Quincas Borba) and in the
fullness of time bury the animal with sufficient decorum.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few predictable elements in the novel is the danger
lurking beneath the allure of Rubiao's surprise inheritance. An
innocent and a dreamer, he drifts from the provinces to Rio de
Janeiro in search of sophistication and the chance to snub those
who earlier mocked his stubborn loyalty to Borba and his canine
alter ego. Meeting Cristiano and Sofia Palha, a brace of plausible
social climbers not unlike Dickens's Mr. and Mrs. Veneering, he is
shamelessly exploited by the greedy husband, while the wife, having
coaxed him into a liaison, flings him aside when he appears most
vulnerable. By now Rubiao starts to go mad, having his beard
trimmed to resemble Napoleon III's and then convincing himself that
he is indeed the Emperor.
</P>
<P>
   Through the clarity of Gregory Rabassa's spirited translation,
such plot elements may seem simple enough, but the author is
constantly trying to detach us from the mere exercise of threading
together a sequential narrative. What in fact happens here occurs
not within the story itself but on a foreground created by
Machado's determination to sabotage the resources used effectively
by earlier novelists. Scarcely a chapter goes by without the
accompanying sense of its creator as critic, not just of other
writers but of the expectant reader besides. Interrupting a
significant episode in which Rubiao is being duped by a wily
political journalist, Machado pauses to consider whether or not he
should make use of the habit of using chapter headings to summarize
contents. He decides not to, but mocks the reader's desire for
explanations before taking up the story once more, apparently
because ``I don't know if all of the next chapter could be
contained in a title.''
</P>
<P>
   Characters become handy vehicles for this speculative approach
to putting a novel together. In a passage reminiscent of Alice's
conversation with the flowers in ``Through the Looking Glass,''
Sofia Palha, uncertain whether to reject Rubiao, projects her
doubts onto a pair of roses, both of which supply her with an
answer of sorts. And Machado seizes the chance to meditate on the
psychological collusion of human beings with inanimate objects:
``The expression, 'Talking to his buttons,' which looks like a
simple metaphor for 'Talking to himself,' is a phrase with a real
and direct meaning. The buttons operate synchronically with us,
forming a kind of senate, handy and cheap, that always votes in
favor of our motions.''
</P>
<P>
   In this new edition of ``Quincas Borba,'' interpretative
guidance by David T. Haberly and Celso Favaretto consoles us
somewhat for the mistrust of readers implied in Machado's endless
shifts of direction. Both commentators maintain that it is not hard
to grasp the book's fascination, whether as a political allegory, a
drama of solitude amid multitudes, a critique of Brazil's failure
to reconcile the imperatives of past and present or a celebration
of skepticism. Features like these brought Machado his earliest
constituency of English-speaking readers when ``Bras Cubas'' was
translated in 1952. For some its sequel, ``Quincas Borba,''
consolidates the triumph of a Latin American proto-modernist. For
others the author's interventionist tactics, amounting at times to
a peevish, high-handed impatience with the task in front of him,
may offer discouragement to the normally pleasing experience of
hailing an undiscovered masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Keates's books include ``Henry Purcell: A Life'' and
``Soon to Be a Major Motion Picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
