<HEADER>
A2969 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BLUFF-1000&AMP;AD     12-16 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BLUFF-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BLIND MAN'S BLUFF
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Untold Story of American Submarine Espionage.
</P>
<P>
   By Sherry Sontag and Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 352 pp. New York: Public Affairs. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE SONAR WAR
</P>
<P>
   BY TIMOTHY NAFTALI
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, two ballistic missile submarines, one Soviet and one
American, died similar deaths. In each case an unexpected explosion
set off a series of catastrophic events culminating in a dramatic
plunge to depths where submarines collapse from bow to stern like
accordions. Entombed in these blocks of steel were 200 men.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cold War ended less than a decade ago, it is
farther away from us emotionally than World War II. There is
something about the carnage and moral certainties of that war that
makes it accessible even to the notoriously ahistorical Generation
X. But the Cold War, with the notable exception of the morality
play of Vietnam, seems in retrospect a time of contingency plans
and unrealized fears, now gratefully dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   Yet every day for over 40 years, young Russians and Americans
went to very difficult jobs not knowing whether that day would be
their last. It is fashionable now to play down the fears of the
statesmen, to describe as manipulative or insincere presidential or
Kremlin statements of concern. But what is beyond doubt is the fear
that the individual sailor, pilot or spy periodically felt in doing
his duty.
</P>
<P>
   In deftly exploring the lives of engineers and sailors who spied
on Soviet power from the depths of the world's oceans, Sherry
Sontag and Christopher Drew have produced an evocative and
important look at the Cold War. ``Blind Man's Bluff: The Untold
Story of American Submarine Espionage'' is also satisfying to read,
at times hurtling forward with the speed of a Polaris submarine.
The use of submarines to plumb Soviet intentions and capabilities
involved some of the most secret, or blackest, American projects of
the Cold War. Sontag, who has covered government and international
affairs for The National Law Journal, and Drew, who is a reporter
at The New York Times, cultivated veteran submariners who talked
for the first time about spying. With the help of Annette Lawrence
Drew and of an intrepid Russian colleague, they tracked down Soviet
counterparts where appropriate, and set the sea stories into a
wider Cold War context.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is a compelling study of magnificent men and spying
machines. Take the case of Capt. James E. Bradley Jr., a diesel
submariner with World War II service. One of the frustrating truths
of the Cold War was that it was always extremely difficult to
figure out what the Russians intended to do. Unlike General
Eisenhower in World War II, President Dwight D. Eisenhower and his
successors were rarely presented by their intelligence chiefs with
the high-level strategic chatter of their adversary. The Russians
took better care with their codes and ciphers than the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who by 1966 was director of undersea warfare for the
Office of Naval Intelligence, came up with an ingenious partial
solution: why not bug transmissions that the Russians would assume
could not be bugged? Recalling the signs ``Cable Crossing. Do Not
Anchor Cables'' from childhood days on the Mississippi, Bradley
assumed that Russian shores would have similar warnings posted for
underwater telephone cables. In 1971, with its periscope up, the
nuclear submarine Halibut secretly traced the Siberian coastline
and confirmed Bradley's hunch. After divers attached the largest
telephone tap ever made to a cable on the floor of the Sea of
Okhotsk, a stream of useful information about Soviet naval
deployments and military exercises flowed to Washington. Had the
Russians ever prepared for a first nuclear strike, this tap would
have provided critical warning. Code-named ``Ivy Bells,'' this
source would remain active for a decade, one of the greatest
intelligence hauls of the Cold War, until an American, Ronald
Pelton, sold the secret to the Russians in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The authors also provide simple stories of individual courage,
beginning with a thrilling episode from the first days of Cold War
submarine spying. The diesel submarine was about as inhospitable a
place to work as one could imagine. Smelly and moist, these
120-foot long canisters were often buffeted by waves. And they were
vulnerable. If they didn't regularly approach the surface to pull
fresh air in through a snorkel, their batteries would lose their
charge while the crew suffocated from carbon dioxide in the air.
With fear growing in 1949 that the Soviet Union would soon deploy
its versions of U-boats in the open seas, the Navy sent submarines
close to Soviet ports to follow such vessels or listen to their
communications. As Sontag and Drew tell it, crews on the Tusk and
the Cochino, with newly trained spooks aboard, learned that year
that even in the Cold War the greatest adversary could be the sea.
</P>
<P>
   On-board nuclear reactors would eventually scrub submarines of
the pervasive ``Eau de Diesel'' and allow them to sail underwater
for months at a time, but this progress reduced neither the tension
nor the dangers of underwater spying. By the mid-60's, the arms
race extended into the seas. Not only were the Russians deploying
nuclear tipped ballistic missiles on submarines, but the French and
the superpowers were using the ocean as a firing range to test new
missiles. Among the new American fleet of nuclear submarines were
spy boats with specially designed hulls to permit deep-water
investigations, to detect strategic Soviet junk and when necessary
to violate Soviet territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
   The twin submarine disasters of 1968 provided a test of the new
American approach to the deep. That year the Russians lost a Golf
class diesel submarine in the Pacific, while the American nuclear
attack submarine Scorpion disappeared on its way back to Norfolk,
Va. In a mark of the sophistication of the naval spy game by that
time, neither the White House nor the Kremlin blamed the other for
the unexplained disappearance of a ballistic missile submarine.
Unlike the United States, however, Moscow had no way of finding its
sailors. Soviet submariners were trained to send signals from
predetermined points along a tight path from the motherland to
their firing positions off the American coast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BLUFF-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: coast.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Russian sub's failure to send its position triggered a
desperate search by a dozen Soviet ships. But Moscow lacked the
underwater technology to investigate the ocean floor for her dead.
Five years earlier, the loss of 129 men on the American nuclear
submarine Thresher had inspired the Navy to promote a serious
deep-water program to investigate wrecks. In 1968 this program
grabbed the attention of the White House by finding the Scorpion
11,000 feet below the surface, and by locating the Soviet sub 1,700
miles northwest of Hawaii, with its complement of cipher machines
and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   This hunt seemed to capture the spirit of the entire Cold War.
Not only did technological prowess permit Americans to set new
standards for the Russians to match, but it also led to costly
American overreaching. Learning of the Navy's achievement, the
C.I.A. persuaded the White House to finance a joint venture with
Howard Hughes to recover the Soviet submarine from the Pacific
floor. Warned that the submarine was too fragile and would break
apart under the stresses of a climb to the surface, the C.I.A. went
ahead anyway -- and 90 percent of the Soviet sub sheared away as it
was lifted by the Hughes-designed ship Glomar Explorer in 1974. The
C.I.A. found only six Russian corpses in the portion brought to the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   So was all this courage and innovation worth it? The authors are
careful not to offer grand theories. However, they suggest that
espionage played a significant role. It reduced uncertainties and
increased confidence that neither superpower was bent on blowing up
the world. But it also increased the tension of the Cold War, the
need to follow enemy submarines closely, to enter hostile waters
and to push old ships beyond their limits. The Russians did not
rely as much as the Americans on this highly technological spying,
but they enjoyed equally dramatic results. From 1967 until the
mid-80's, an American Navy officer, John Walker, and some members
of his family gave the Russians the keys to copying our submarine
technology and to following changes in our naval doctrine. As
Soviet ships got quieter, their payloads more dangerous and their
use wiser, the need for American spying increased. Until the very
last days of the Cold War, in the rarefied world of undersea chess,
ignorance seemed the greatest danger. With their book, Sontag and
Drew introduce us to one of the least known and most harrowing
battlefields of the superpower conflict.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Naftali, director of the program on contemporary
political history at the University of Virginia's Miller Center of
Public Affairs, is a co-author of ``One Hell of a Gamble:
Khrushchev, Castro and Kennedy, 1958-1964.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
