NYT-12-16-98 1516EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2971 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     12-16 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY SCOTT VEALE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNIVERSAL DONOR
</P>
<P>
   By Craig Nova.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, $13. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles doctor, trying to save his lover after she is
bitten by a snake she is studying, is forced to track down a
psychopathic criminal who shares her rare blood type. Part love
story, part thriller, this novel explores ``highly emotional
conflicts without resorting to either sentimentality or cliche,''
Scott Bradfield wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CRYSTAL FRONTIER:
</P>
<P>
   A Novel in Nine Stories
</P>
<P>
   By Carlos Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Alfred Mac Adam.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a series of tales centering on a powerful tycoon and his
family, the prolific Mexican author explores the troubled relations
between his native country and the United States. Last year our
reviewer, Jay Parini, found the stories uneven but said that at
their best they display ``acute observation'' and a fine ``sense of
satire.'' Eccentric Neighborhoods, by Rosario Ferre (Plume,
$12.95), is a sweeping novel about the shifting fortunes of two
upper-crust families in Puerto Rico, one representing the nation's
agrarian past and the other its industrial future. ``The author's
voice is bright and vital,'' Mark Childress wrote here earlier this
year. ``The magic in Ferre's fiction arises from the intertwined
experiences of human beings, carrying the story of 20th-century
Puerto Rico in the arc of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MRS. KEPPEL AND HER DAUGHTER
</P>
<P>
   By Diana Souhami.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Griffin, $14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This chronicle of adultery, homosexuality and intrigue among the
British aristocracy focuses on Alice Keppel, the winsome mistress
of Queen Victoria's eldest son, both as Prince of Wales and as King
Edward VII, and her daughter, Violet, whose heart was broken when
her affair with the writer Vita Sackville-West hit the skids. The
result is a ``fascinating, richly textured story,'' Kennedy Fraser
wrote in the Book Review last year. In The Queen: A Biography of
Elizabeth II, by Ben Pimlott (Wiley, $18.95), a professor of
politics and contemporary history at the University of London
argues that the Queen's dutiful, passive reign is in keeping with
Britain's sense of itself and its history. In 1997 our reviewer,
Andrew Sullivan, called this a ``superbly judicious biography''
with ``a wry awareness of the paradox of a populist monarchy being
at the center of a constitutional democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TRUEST PLEASURE
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Algonquin, $11.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In this historical novel, set in rural North Carolina early in
the century, a religious woman tells of her difficult marriage to
an industrious, practical-minded man, and their conflicting views
of salvation and devotion. '' 'The Truest Pleasure' is a quietly
audacious book,'' Richard Bausch wrote in these pages in 1995. ``It
contains characters and situations that aren't easy to forget.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MAN WHO ATE EVERYTHING:
</P>
<P>
   And Other Gastronomic Feats, Disputes, and Pleasurable Pursuits
</P>
<P>
   By Jeffrey Steingarten.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage, $14. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In these obsessively omnivorous essays, the food critic for
Vogue describes his far-flung gastronomic adventures, stopping
along the way with morsels of culinary advice and medical and
scientific digressions. ``Steingarten writes with marvelous ease
and clarity and humor,'' Alexander Chancellor said here last year.
``His facts are fascinating and so are his recipes.'' Olives: The
Life and Lore of a Noble Fruit, by Mort Rosenblum (North Point,
$15), is a journalist's freewheeling homage to Athena's gift to
mankind, crammed with history, recipes and health tips. This is an
``edifying new book,'' Christopher Lehmann-Haupt wrote in The New
York Times in 1996. ``Pit by pit, his savory details add up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIREWALL:
</P>
<P>
   The Iran-Contra Conspiracy and Cover-Up
</P>
<P>
   By Lawrence E. Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, $18. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel in the Iran-contra affair answers his
many critics, charging that Congress, conservative judges and,
above all, Reagan Administration officials prevented him from
meting out justice. ``Walsh's book is a useful record of the
scandal and its aftermath,'' John B. Judis wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUN DANCER
</P>
<P>
   By David London.
</P>
<P>
   University of Nebraska, $14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This first novel is about a bloody confrontation between Federal
agents and Indian protesters in the Black Hills of South Dakota.
The result is an ``unflinching look at the conflicts among the
Sioux, and . . . the pervasive cynicism and slow-burn despair that
accompany a history of frustrated attempts to set right several
generations of wrongs,'' Scott Martelle said in these pages in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOONSHINE:
</P>
<P>
   A Life in Pursuit of White Liquor
</P>
<P>
   By Alec Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry Mind, $12.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This profile of a brave and cunning Federal agent named Garland
Bunting is also a history of bootlegging, which these days mostly
exploits alcoholics among the rural poor. In 1985 our reviewer, Bob
Lancaster, found the author's ``reporting style so sharp and
economical that the prose fairly crackles.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AUTOBIOGRAPHY OF FOUDINI M. CAT
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Fromberg Schaeffer.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett, $10.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A precocious housecat recounts his life and times, from his
abandonment as a kitten to his adoption by a couple he named Warm
and Pest. ``This entertaining cat's-eye view of life . . . can be
recommended even to those who are less than entranced by felines,''
Kimberly B. Marlowe wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
