<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-RACE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 RACE MEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Hazel V. Carby.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 228 pp. Cambridge, Mass.:
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University Press. $24.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; COLOR VISION
</P>
<P>
   BY JONATHAN RIEDER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the motion picture ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' the black
detective played by Danny Glover shouts to his white partner in his
arms (Mel Gibson): ``You're not dead until I tell you. Now
breathe!'' To which Gibson replies: ``Did anyone ever tell you, you
really are a beautiful man? Give us a kiss before they come.''
</P>
<P>
   This is only one of the moments that catch Hazel V. Carby's
fancy in ``Race Men,'' her provocative and exasperating look at
depictions of black masculinity in novels, jazz, film and
photography. Ranging from the Caribbean writer C. L. R. James's
search for heroic black manhood to the efforts of the folklorists
John and Alan Lomax to fabricate Leadbelly's primitivism, the book
chronicles the deforming power of ``the gaze,'' as Carby might put
it. Her concern is with acts of symbolic violence -- by whites
against blacks, but also by men of all hues against women. They are
a form of soul murder, she argues, in which the image turns on the
imagined. Even images that don't seem virulent may be backhanded
compliments, as when the glorification of blacks as superior
sensualists serves to deprive them of rationality. Looks can kill,
sometimes with kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to necromancy than to science, this sort of cultural
decoding is notoriously dicey, especially if you think a handful of
texts can be made to give up the secrets of a culture. Moreover,
Carby's interpretations are often far-fetched. Her notion that
Miles Davis's sidemen symbolize both a phallus and the breasts from
which he sucked creative inspiration seems a bit much. She is at
her best when she curbs the excess fanciness and keeps close enough
to her targets to illuminate them in all their subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   Her detailed examination of a series of modernist photographs of
Paul Robeson by Nickolas Muray in the 1920's illuminates the
murderous power of the glance. To stare at Robeson's naked body in
the light of Carby's commentary makes for a wretched poignancy.
This ``homoerotic'' rendering of Robeson made him a hapless
plaything of the photographer's lust. Here, the look is a leer; the
eye is invited to follow the placement of the body toward the
genital triangle. White reviewers of Robeson's spirituals who
hungered for primal ``authenticity'' offered a similar
constriction. They sifted out of the spirituals the veiled urging
to ``steal away'' to freedom. Fetishism, reshaping the object in
jarring ways, is always selfish; it stripped Robeson of his
prideful dignity, his political core, his sense of himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just whites who are conjurers. Black men too have
worked their symbolic mischief, on themselves and on black women.
Carby takes her lead from Phillip Brian Harper's comment, ``All
debates over and claims to 'authentic' African-American identity
are largely animated by a profound anxiety about the status
specifically of African-American masculinity.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ever wondered what's the deal with Cornel West's suits
(or his cuffs), it may be neither stylistic affection nor
affectation. To Carby, the suit betokens his link to W. E. B. Du
Bois and the shared cult of manhood both men's clothes ``embody'';
it secures critical intelligence ``as irrevocably and
conservatively masculine.''
</P>
<P>
   This dynamic of manhood underlies the entire structure of jazz,
Carby argues in her chapter on Miles Davis. Davis was a shameless
misogynist who beat women and called them bitches. Even Davis's
music sounds ``patriarchal and phallic'' to Carby. All these men
musically pleasuring one another with their equipment is also
``homoerotic.'' But Carby hears a gentler manhood in the magical
symbiosis achieved by Davis, John Coltrane and Bill Evans on the
album ``Kind of Blue'' (1959). Their ``refusal to resolve the
tension through any single climax'' represents nothing less than a
``democratic sensibility'' and a ``revolutionary mode of being.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how the refusal of climax gets to define democracy.
In any case, the heavy, old-school Freudian-style reductionism that
reappears throughout ``Race Men'' raises a contradiction that
intensifies as the book moves toward the present. Even as Carby,
who teaches African and African-American studies and American
studies at Yale University, applauds the lingering foreplay of
``Kind of Blue,'' she herself marches to the ideological end point.
In such moments she seems not to be communing with the images so
much as using them to score her points. There is a similar tension
between the flashes of insight and the lifeless jargon into which
she presses them. We are in a universe of ``subject positions,''
``hegemony of a racialized social formation'' and ``inscribed''
bodies, in which an individual ``genders his narrative'' and has
``privileged a discourse.''
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't want to be too fussy about unlovely writing. A lot
of academics write like this; it's post-modern Muzak. It's also why
so much criticism sounds like a cross between Sid Caesar shtick and
Monty Python parody. But in Carby's case, this speaking in tongues
is frustrating because it betrays her imaginative, boldly
distinctive voice; her beloved ideal of jazz, with its image of
free play and artful spontaneity; and her feminist ideal of
intimacy, in this case with her own data.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-RACE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: data.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This distancing language matches an ideological distance from
American culture. Much has changed since the days of the old
defamatory images, but Carby sees many continuities. In a
patronizing aside to Tiger Woods, Michael Jordan and Danny Glover,
she warns them that they risk the same symbolic capture Robeson
suffered. Actually, it's too late for Glover, she says; his
crossover roles signify ``the exploitative and oppressive nature''
of white dream work. White liberal men in Hollywood use Glover to
expel ``the alien black presence'' and to heal, symbolically, white
men damaged by post-modern life. The affection between Glover and
Gibson -- and the famous embrace that closes ``Lethal Weapon 2'' --
represents not humanizing intimacy but the director's fascination
with homoeroticism.
</P>
<P>
   This verdict strikes me about as wrong as it could be. By airily
removing herself to the cosmic narratives of Huck and Jim, Carby
leaps over more recent and relevant buddy pairs who affirm loyal
partnership while also making way for women, blacks, Jews and
Latinos -- Starsky and Hutch, Crockett and Tubbs, Cagney and Lacey,
Bobby and Sipowicz, Chris and Rita in the original ``Silk
Stalkings.'' ``Lethal Weapon 2'' reverses the old racial
iconography in other ways. The white Riggs (Gibson) is the
dangerous primitive, the defiant Dionysian, while the black
Murtaugh (Glover) is enveloped in caution and domesticity. When his
daughter appears in a condom ad, he's the consummate Dad, foolish
and befuddled -- which is to say the black man gets a crack at
normality. As their racial banter indicates, such universalism
doesn't come at the price of blackness, any more than Oprah
Winfrey's or Michael Jordan's white fans stop seeing them as black.
</P>
<P>
   Carby's interpretation of masculine intimacy is no less
heavy-handed. She ignores the vernacular codes of male feeling for
cartoonish representations of masculinity; once again, it's as if
she has internalized male anxiety and sees every moment of men's
connection as homoerotic. But Riggs and Murtaugh do not favor the
talky confessionalism of feminist men; they express intimacy in
their own way. Sex can serve as a metaphor for love rather than
vice versa: Gibson's insouciant ``Give us a kiss'' may not mean
what it says, but it says what it means, precisely: ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta represent,'' goes the pop tune, and it's true, one
can't help it. That's also true for the people who try to fathom
other people's images. For some time now, the cultural left has
been going around in a funk, deconstructing everything in sight,
wavering between scolding a culture that seems hostile to
liberation and conducting a promiscuous search for signs of
resistance to that culture's dominating symbols. But in all this
rage for representation, the left has often committed soul murder
too, projecting disappointment onto the objects of its gaze,
representing itself rather than the complex reality of a vibrantly
imperfect culture. Given that liberals won the imagery wars on the
racial and sexual front, there is an irony here. Maybe culture just
isn't that important. And maybe it's better to direct the rage not
for, but against, the suffering and inequality that cultural
triumph has been unable to arrest.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Rieder, chairman of the sociology department at Barnard
College, is a co-editor of Common Quest: The Magazine of
Black-Jewish Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
