<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GATHER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE LORD WILL GATHER ME IN
<TEXT>
<P>
   My Journey to Jewish Orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   By David Klinghoffer.
</P>
<P>
   260 pp. New York: The Free Press. $24.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; OLD-TIME RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   BY MARK SILK
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Midway through this arresting spiritual autobiography, an
Orthodox rabbi tells the author: ``It sounds like you've been
searching for what you consider to be religious truth. That's not
the way it happens to most converts.''
</P>
<P>
   To non-Jews, the remark may seem surprising. What could be more
likely to result in religious conversion than the quest for
religious truth? But traditional Judaism is less a system of belief
than a way of living, an orthopraxy that tends to convert people
for emotional rather than intellectual reasons. David Klinghoffer,
who edits the Books, Arts, and Manners section of National Review,
is an exception. For him, the heart of the matter is: Is Judaism
true? All else is secondary.
</P>
<P>
   From an early age, Klinghoffer displayed a religious
sensibility. The adopted child of a well-to-do Los Angeles dentist
and his wife, he took Judaism a good deal more seriously than was
customary in the Reform Jewish milieu in which he was raised. As an
adolescent, he experimented with tefillin -- the leather-strapped
boxes that traditional Jews don in obedience to Deuteronomy 6:8
(``and thou shalt bind them for a sign upon thine hand, and they
shall be as frontlets between thine eyes''). He began to be
troubled that his circumcision was not ritually correct, and sought
to remedy the situation by immersing himself in a bathtub and, in
line with Orthodox teaching, drawing a drop of blood from the tip
of his penis with a straight razor. There are two more
re-circumcisions -- first by a Conservative, then by an Orthodox,
mohel -- before he is satisfied that he truly is a Jew.
Klinghoffer's spiritual journey winds through undergraduate years
at Brown University, a summer at the Jewish Theological Seminary, a
passionate love affair with a Roman Catholic woman and the
discovery of his birth mother -- a Swedish Christian who picked out
Jewish parents for her son. The son comes across as an agreeable
young man, open about his shortcomings, modest about his spiritual
accomplishments, un-self-righteous.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he pulls many punches. He has no kind words for the
liberal Judaism of his youth, describing the Reform movement as ``a
thing entirely of this world.'' He cuts Conservative Judaism a
little more slack, but still writes it off as ``untenable.'' A
Jewish pluralist he is not. He is fixed on molding himself to
divine truth, and, as he sees it, that means adopting the belief
that God handed down both the Pentateuch and all rabbinical law
(the ``oral Torah'') to Moses on Mount Sinai. As David Weiss
Halivni has shown, this fundamentalistic account of tradition arose
relatively late in Jewish history, but since the Middle Ages it has
been embraced ever more fervently by Orthodox rabbinical authority.
To say that it rejects modern scholarly understandings of the
composition of the Bible and the Talmud is to say the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Klinghoffer reasons that if the God of the Hebrew Bible is
incapable of guaranteeing the purity of revelation then He is not
the Almighty God He claims to be, and is in fact no God at all.
That God might permit corruptions of the tradition, like other
forms of evil, is intolerable, as is the view that extrabiblical
Jewish law is the result not of direct revelation but of scriptural
exegesis by fallible human beings.
</P>
<P>
   If Klinghoffer's adherence to the inerrancy of Torah is
traditional, his unconcern for Jewry as such is distinctive. He has
nothing to say about the Holocaust or the state of Israel. He
attacks Jewish tribalism, including the self-satisfied subculture
of some birthright Orthodox, and takes a poke at Irving Kristol and
William Safire for advocating Jewish education without subscribing
to Jewish truth. That the covenant was made with the entire Jewish
tribe doesn't seem to concern him. Jewish survival should be solely
a function of belief. With his convert's zeal, David Klinghoffer
has issued a prophetic challenge. Whether he will be honored for it
in his adopted house is an interesting question.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Mark Silk, director of the Center for the Study of Religion in
Public Life at Trinity College, Hartford, is editor of the magazine
Religion in the News.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
