 BREAKFAST ON PLUTO
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Patrick McCabe.
</P>
<P>
   202 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Harper Flamingo. $22.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; A COMEDY OF TERRORS
</P>
<P>
   BY COURTNEY WEAVER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McCabe firmly established himself as a master of the
literary macabre in 1993 with the lurid and brilliant novel ``The
Butcher Boy,'' which escorted us through the mind and world of the
child-murderer Francie Brady in claustrophobic 1960's Ireland. So
when I read the blandly hopeful prelude to his new novel,
``Breakfast on Pluto'' (which was short-listed for Britain's Booker
Prize this year), my immediate thought was: Uh-oh. ``The war
over,'' McCabe ironically writes of the recent Good Friday
agreement in Northern Ireland, ``now perhaps we too can take --
however tentatively -- those first few steps which may end unease
and see us there; home, belonging and at peace.'' For in McCabe's
world, hope is only the flip side of horror, a red herring to lull
you into a kaleidoscopic land riddled with brutality and comedy.
</P>
<P>
   It makes perfect sense that the protagonist of ``Breakfast on
Pluto'' is not an I.R.A. guerrilla, or a war-weary priest, or any
other well-plundered stereotype of literary Northern Ireland.
Rather, this is the tale of Patrick (Pussy) Braden, an effusively
cheerful transvestite who gallivants from his Irish border village
of Tyreelin to swinging-70's London, in search of his ``Sergeant
Rock or Captain Yum Yum Be-My-Girl-For-Ever!'' Abandoned as a baby
by his teen-age mother, unacknowledged by his father, the village
priest, Puss wages a personal campaign of vengeance that takes his
own mental health prisoner, while he's listlessly looking for love
in all the wrong places. Set against the backdrop of a London
paralyzed by I.R.A. bombs, ``Breakfast on Pluto'' is a wretchedly
uplifting story within a story, with Puss as ringmaster, gaily
writing his memoirs for his psychiatrist as he dips in and out of
sanity.
</P>
<P>
   London in the early 70's was more Patrick McCabe-ian than he
could have made up. It was a sinister, garish city in the heady
throes of glam rock and skyrocketing inflation, and the bombing
campaign waged by the I.R.A. insured that in 1974 cars and pubs
exploded almost daily, it seemed, while department stores were
routinely evacuated. In Northern Ireland, ``13 people had been shot
dead by British Army paratroopers,'' Puss recounts with some
regret, yet ``I sat . . . in the darkened square, shamefully not
thinking about the dead victims or their relatives but what
combination of my luscious goodies I should go and try on first!''
Puss is ``much too preoccupied with my own personal revolution to
be bothered with anything so trivial'' as Irish Republicanism, yet
his internal world is filled with the rage of bombing victims and
terrorized London denizens. Friends and lovers are murdered,
guerrilla soldiers torture and maim, while Puss, refusing to take
any of it seriously, announces, ``It's Bombing Night and I haven't
got a thing to wear.''
</P>
<P>
   It is McCabe's particular brand of humor that Puss is arrested
not for prostitution, a trade he successfully plies in London's
West End, but for planting bombs. ``So to all intents and purposes
you were living as a woman now?'' the psychiatrist asks him later.
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Well, I didn't have any yucky briefs if that's what you
mean, my sweet!' said Puss and chuckled in her chuckly way, her
head as light as air. . . . 'I'd dance for them and husky-coo until
they could take no more. And other times----.'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Other times?'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Why I'd be a right old whore!' . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Then dropped my eyelids and sexy-whispered: 'Before I became a
bomber, of course!'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard not to laugh -- because he took it so serious!
Which he had to -- as indeed I ought to -- after all, people lost
their limbs and eyes!
</P>
<P>
   ``But I couldn't, Pussy as a bomber -- I simply had to clutch my
sides!''
</P>
<P>
   As a character, Puss Braden has great propensity to become
another kind of stereotype -- the campy gay boy on whom to project
silly dreams and adventures worthy of Screen Parade, which he so
avidly reads. And yet McCabe, whose dexterity with marginalized
kooks was brought into high relief with ``The Butcher Boy,'' lends
so much cheerful optimism to Puss that one can't help feeling a
wrenching sense of empathy. In another failed attempt at finding a
``Home-Loving Man,'' Puss remembers: ``When I look back on it, I
really have to hand it to Silks. To listen to him you would have
thought he was the sort of person who started drenching the place
with tears anytime anything remotely upsetting came on the cinema
screen, for whom the abuse of a dumb animal was a tragedy of
awesome proportions.'' Silks, it turns out, was a john intent on
strangling Puss to death, and very nearly succeeded. Nevertheless,
``just because you get a kick out of strangling people doesn't mean
that another side of you can't be humane and kind and sensitive --
perhaps even more so indeed,'' Puss observes wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the victim of Puss's vengeance is his guilty priest
father, still living in the Irish border village; as the
psychiatrist points out, ``there appears to be no similar
generosity of spirit evident'' when it comes to Puss's treatment of
his father. Puss dreams of burning him alive, but before leaving
for London, in one of the novel's funnier moments, he boldly enters
the church intent on confrontation. ``Just then the door of the
confession box opened and in I went. . . . He drew the shutter
back. 'Hello, Daddy,' I said as I knelt down in the dark and you
can imagine the shock I get when it wasn't him. . . . 'What are you
doing here?' I said. 'I work here,' he says, as I began to realize
just what an idiot I'd made of myself!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-PLUTO-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: myself!'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1955 in the heavily Republican border town of Clones in
the Irish Republic, McCabe is an avid musician and former
schoolteacher whose creative coming of age in the 1970's couldn't
have avoided being affected by the political storm in the North.
``Breakfast on Pluto'' falls in a logical progression from ``The
Butcher Boy'' (whose 13-year-old narrator must have given the
parents of McCabe's former students some food for thought) and
``The Dead School'' (1995), which is about two Dublin
schoolteachers caught in a psychological maelstrom of drugs, music
and youth culture. ``Breakfast on Pluto'' (the title refers to a
bit of musical frippery by Don Partridge, high on the British
charts in 1969) embodies the kinetic frenzy of its predecessors
through the eyes of a new kind of Irish enfant terrible -- a
sentimental yet ironic 19-year-old transvestite with a temper.
</P>
<P>
   The Troubles in Northern Ireland have pricked scores of literary
imaginations throughout the years, and will no doubt continue to do
so. McCabe's latest may be the most successful book yet to be born
out of the violence, and with its surety of voice and stunning
originality, it moves beyond the parochial Troubles novel. Where
``Breakfast on Pluto'' succeeds is where others have failed -- by
underlining the vast contradictions inherent in the Irish conflict,
of brutality and kindness, horror and gaiety, conviction and
apathy. With a sassy narrator clad in an ice-cream-pink mohair
sweater, humming the tunes of Barry White as he sashays into a
London disco-pub on the verge of exploding, it is a mosaic of
sound, color and spirit. The underlying grief resonates deeply and
personally, transforming what could be a literary trifle into an
obsessive gift, from a man who may be one of Ireland's finest
living writers.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Weaver's book, ``Unzipped,'' about contemporary mating
and dating, will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
