<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no easy task to hold a reader's attention when a novel's
outcome is obvious from the very first page. But Susan Isaacs has
such a knack for entertaining her reader with the details of
American pop culture -- from brand names and television shows to
the most fashionable neuroses -- that it's easy to be distracted
from the predictability of her plot. In her eighth novel, RED,
WHITE AND BLUE (HarperCollins, $25), Isaacs has taken on a
formidable project: to write a multigenerational family drama that
is also a romantic comedy and a murder mystery and a serious
consideration of weighty issues like anti-Semitism and assimilation
-- all without losing her sense of humor or her eye for the
entertaining detour. At the center of the novel are Charlie Blair,
an F.B.I. agent from Wyoming, and Lauren Miller, a reporter for a
Long Island newspaper called The Jewish News. It is clear from the
start that Charlie and Lauren are lovers-to-be; they are also
distant cousins, several generations removed. The story of their
common ancestry, which reads like a tale of ``city mouse-country
mouse'' ad-libbed by a Jewish grandmother, makes up the first half
of the novel. It begins in the late 19th century with the arrival
of Lauren and Charlie's great-great-grandparents on a ship in New
York harbor and follows the divergent paths of the family's two
halves in Wyoming and New York -- all the way up to the present. In
the novel's second half, Lauren and Charlie are at last brought
together after a series of it-could-only-happen-in-a-novel
coincidences surrounding their investigation of Wrath, an
anti-Semitic, white supremacist hate group in Wyoming. Never mind
the preposterousness of this subplot. ``Red, White and Blue'' is
nothing if not a delightful diversion. _ NORA KRUG
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A NEW AND GLORIOUS LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Novellas.
</P>
<P>
   By Michelle Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Mellon University,
</P>
<P>
   paper, $15.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Herman's trio of novellas features artists or academics
trying to arrive at the truest direction in which to take their
lives. The heroine of the bittersweet, somewhat schematic
``Auslander'' is a translator who is introduced to a brilliant
Romanian poet, only to be pulled into a self-destructive tragedy
involving the mysterious author and her deliberately unpublished
work. Herman's strongest work occurs in the title novella, in which
a composer and a poet discover true love at an artists' colony.
Watching them struggle to understand and manage the bond that grows
between them is an unexpectedly moving experience. In addition,
Herman's use of her love story's setting (drawing particularly on
the strained friendliness between artists who are also competitors)
is shrewd and amusing. In her less successful final selection,
``Hope Among Men,'' she cuts loose with some humorous and teasing
post-modern effects, only to wind up steering dangerously close to
cuteness. _ PATRICK GILES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NAMAKO
</P>
<P>
   Sea Cucumber.
</P>
<P>
   By Linda Watanabe McFerrin.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee House Press, paper, $14.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be horrible to be so strange that nobody knows what
you really are,'' observes 10-year-old Ellen, examining a preserved
sea cucumber in her biology classroom. With her protagonist's
perception of this strange plantlike animal, Linda Watanabe
McFerrin aims for an emblematic suggestion of what it's like to be
on the cusp of adolescence. Unfortunately, McFerrin's brief,
occasionally exquisite debut is often as imprecise as its titular
metaphor and as awkward as its young narrator. ``Namako: Sea
Cucumber'' follows Ellen, her father, her mother (who is half
Japanese) and her three siblings as they transplant themselves from
the United States to Japan in an attempt to hold their family
together. ``I was shocked by the order, the absence of clutter and
the silence,'' Ellen notes on their first night in a stately Tokyo
hotel. ``We children were loud without saying a word.'' What ensues
is a series of episodes at once overstuffed and attenuated.
McFerrin touches on so many bold thematic contrasts -- childhood
versus adulthood, America versus Japan, spirituality versus
sensuality, violence versus serenity -- with such a gently
equivocal prose style that ``Namako'' is as slippery to grasp as
its namesake. McFerrin is clearly ambitious, attempting to blend
the powerful mythological approach of a Maxine Hong Kingston with
the earthy realism of a Dorothy Allison. It is generally too much
for this small book to bear. _ JIM GLADSTONE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A HISTORY OF SILENCE
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Neil.
</P>
<P>
   Nan A. Talese/Doubleday, $23. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At times, Barbara Neil's fourth novel has the feel of a
tantalizing Gothic mystery instead of a carefully calibrated foray
into the destructiveness of repression -- and these are the times
when the story springs to life. Robbie and her sister, Laura, are
bound by a vague but insistent belief that they were sexually
abused in their early childhood. Their mother, Esther, seems to
have been aware of the abuse but did nothing to stop it. The three
share an unbreakable closeness, but only Robbie, a physiotherapist,
seems anxious to bring her memories out in the open. Frustrated,
she leaves her London home for an estate in Louisiana, where she
has been hired to work with Raoul Patout, a charming elderly stroke
victim. Eventually, Laura and Esther are drawn into Robbie's new
life in America, but the three never confront their past, and
that's what makes ``A History of Silence'' so frustrating. Neil has
an eye for detail, but her narrative builds toward a devastating
revelation that never comes: the only resolution offered is that
there's no possible resolution. _ STEPHANIE ZACHAREK
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE VAMPIRE ARMAND
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $26.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the latest volume of her Vampire Chronicles, Anne Rice offers
an absorbing account of another all-too-human ghoul, this one
struggling to reconcile vampirism with devotion to Christ. She
first sketched out his story in ``Interview With the Vampire'' and
``The Vampire Lestat,'' but here she colors it in, using a vibrant
palette suitable to its initial 16th-century Italian setting. As a
boy, Armand is kidnapped, sold into slavery and taken to the
Venetian palazzo of the vampire Marius, under whom he happily
studies history, painting and law. Later, Marius initiates Armand
into the family of the undead and together they practice a sort of
vigilante vampirism, preying only on ``evil people.''
Unfortunately, their beneficence and worldly humanism invite the
wrath of a more traditional and diabolical Satanic vampire coven,
which destroys Marius and forces Armand to join it. A perfunctory
second section relates Armand's perspective on events that will
already be familiar to Rice devotees, culminating in his modern-day
viewing of a relic imprinted with the image of Christ's face.
Caught up in mystical transport, Armand is exposed to the sunlight,
and only the intercession of a wealthy young orphan and her
scampish companion saves him from obliteration. A grateful Armand
promptly adopts the two and journeys with them to New Orleans,
where he attempts to feed on Lestat, comatose after his own
mystical encounter with Christ. But, of course, the end of this
uneven but enjoyable story is surely only the prelude to another.
Stay tuned. _ MICHAEL PORTER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: MICHAEL PORTER) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GATES OF EDEN
</P>
<P>
   Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Ethan Coen.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Weisbach/Morrow, $24. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Coen and his brother, Joel, have made some of the more
interesting movies of the last two decades: ``Blood Simple,''
``Raising Arizona,'' ``Barton Fink'' and ``Fargo.'' Ethan Coen
writes and Joel Coen directs. And while Ethan Coen isn't quite as
stylish with language as his brother is with a camera, he does have
a distinctive voice and an offbeat worldview, both of which come
through with varying degrees of success in his first collection of
stories. ``Have You Ever Been to Electric Ladyland'' is a brilliant
monologue by a record executive trying to figure out who had a
motive to castrate his dog. But ``Johnnie Ga-Botz,'' composed of
nothing but dialogue and stage directions, is the sort of exercise
that talented, undisciplined creative writing students pound out at
3 A.M. The title story is a good example of what the Coen brothers
are known for: a leap into an off-kilter yet fully imagined world
in which a bureaucrat with the California Department of Weights and
Measures thinks and acts like a hard-boiled detective. All of these
stories take place in Coen Brothers Land, a parallel universe
similar to our own -- except it's weirder, funnier and better
edited. _ MARK LINDQUIST
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
