<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     12-16 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The French archeologist Jean-Yves Empereur worked at the
excavation of Alexandria, the Egyptian city founded by Alexander
the Great in 331 B.C., for more than 25 years, as he details in the
lavishly illustrated ALEXANDRIA REDISCOVERED (Braziller, $60). In
spite of the somewhat lackluster telling, Empereur's stories about
the excavations are fascinating, particularly those about the
underwater dig of Fort Qait Bey, a find that uncovered details
about the Pharos lighthouse, one of the seven wonders of the
ancient world. Empereur does excel in illuminating the difficulties
of uncovering a lost city that industrialization continually
encroaches upon. With limited financial means and tough physical
conditions, Empereur writes, ``the Alexandrian experience can also
be wearisome: one has to confront various obstacles, such as the
hostility of the developers who have quite other interests at heart
than the enhancement of their cultural heritage.'' Today, for
instance, only engravings and old maps indicate where Cleopatra's
Needles, now located in London and in Central Park, once stood in
Alexandria. ``People lost no time in erecting buildings in their
place,'' Empereur writes. ``Do the guests of the Hotel Metropole
realize, I wonder, that they are sleeping on the spot where almost
two millennia ago the monumental entrance markers of the Caesareum
stood?'' _ SANDRA MARDENFELD
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUTSIDER, INSIDER
</P>
<P>
   An Unlikely Success Story.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Heiskell with Ralph Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Marian-Darien Press, $22.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heiskell has had a fascinating life: a nomadic childhood
in Europe, three marriages (one to Madeleine Carroll, the actress,
and later to Marian Sulzberger Dryfoos, sister of Arthur Ochs
Sulzberger, then the publisher of The New York Times) and a career
at Time Inc., where he began as a wholly unqualified medical editor
at the fledgling Life magazine in 1937 and ended up running the
company from 1960 to 1980 as chairman and then chief executive
officer. ``Outsider, Insider'' has plenty to engage anyone
interested in the machinations of a major media company, but mostly
the book is a witty and charming look at what goes into making
magazines work -- and what makes them fail. During his tenure at
Life, Heiskell was involved in the creation of the magazine's major
stories, from the German occupation of France to the sinking of the
Andrea Doria. He also recounts with great wit his dealings with the
titans of the day who published their memoirs in Life. Winston
Churchill, for example, was an extraordinary writer but knew how to
run up an expense account, and the Duke of Windsor was ``a world
class nonwriter'' whose ``effective attention span was about two
minutes.'' As the originator of the idea for the extraordinarily
successful People magazine, Heiskell cannot contain his relish
recounting the stories of various staggeringly expensive magazine
start-ups and failures after his retirement (like TV Cable Week and
Picture Week). And that, finally, may be the charm of this book: a
corporate warrior with such frankness is a rare bird indeed. _
JUDITH NEWMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD LIFE
</P>
<P>
   By Tony Bennett with Will Friedwald.
</P>
<P>
   Pocket Books, $25. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Life has been good to one Anthony Dominick Benedetto, born 72
years ago in Queens and better known as Tony Bennett. The son of a
grocer and a seamstress, growing up during the Great Depression the
aspiring singer played hooky from the High School of Industrial
Arts to take in Frank Sinatra at the Paramount. ``I was one of the
original Sinatra groupies,'' Bennett writes. ``He communicated
precisely what he was feeling at any moment. He knocked down the
wall between performer and audience, inviting listeners inside his
mind.'' After serving under Patton in early 1945 and helping to
liberate the Landsberg concentration camp near Dachau, Bennett
returned to Manhattan to soak up the percolating postwar bebop
scene on 52d Street. His break came in 1949 when he met Bob Hope,
who told him his real name was too long for the marquee and said,
``We'll call you Tony Bennett.'' He was also blessed in his choice
of material with a string of mellow, swinging hits, from ``Because
of You'' and ``Stranger in Paradise'' to his signature ``I Left My
Heart in San Francisco.'' His ``Rags to Riches'' was dusted off
memorably in the movie ``Goodfellas,'' and with the revival of all
things lounge, his amiably crumpled visage and dulcet voice have
crossed over with the MTV generation as icons of suavity. ``The
Good Life'' is not a tell-all memoir -- Bennett has a kind word for
almost everybody except a former manager -- and he stood for all
the right things. Written with the music critic Will Friedwald, the
book's tone is as breezy as an evening listening to Bennett
himself. _ ERIC P. NASH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE JEW STORE
</P>
<P>
   By Stella Suberman.
</P>
<P>
   Algonquin, $19.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the South during the 1920s, Stella Suberman recalls in her
family memoir, every small town had a ``Jew store,'' which sold dry
goods and odds and ends. In Concordia, Tenn., this was Bronson's
Low-Priced Store, owned and operated by Suberman's father, whom she
calls Aaron Bronson. (An author's note informs us that all names in
the book, including the name of the town, were changed.) A Russian
immigrant with a young family and ambition to become a salesman,
Bronson made his way south, searching for opportunity. Ultimately,
he built a life for himself, his wife and his three children in a
place where they were the only Jews. There was a lot to contend
with: the local big-shot, Tom Dillon, who had no use for Jews; the
ever-present threat of the Ku Klux Klan; the nagging question of
what to do about a bar mitzvah for 13-year-old Joey. But there were
also the kindnesses of the spinster Miss Brookie Simmons, the
excitement of the wild auction held to save the town during the
Depression and, after years of hard work, success, as Bronson's
modest store became a town fixture. Like the store, which is
practically a character in its own right, the people in ``The Jew
Store'' linger in the mind. Only the narrator herself, born halfway
through the story, fails to emerge as a developed character. But
when, in the end, she reflects on her return to her native town as
an adult, the reader may share her wish that the golden letters of
Bronson's Low-Priced Store were still gleaming on First Street. _
MARISA KANTOR STARK
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: MARISA KANTOR STARK) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LITHOGRAPHS OF JAMES McNEILL WHISTLER
</P>
<P>
   Harriet K. Stratis and Martha Tedeschi, general editors.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Institute of Chicago/The Arie and Ida Crown
Memorial/Hudson Hills Press, $395. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Among artists lithography was infra dig by the 1870's -- because
commercial illustrators had discovered it was a perfect printing
medium for glaring posters. So, naturally, Whistler, the
contrarian, turned to it. From 1887 to 1897, he made a large series
of subtle lithographs, most of which have fallen into obscurity
since then because they were so difficult to reproduce. For 10
years, seven curators and conservators assembled by the Art
Institute of Chicago have worked on a magnificent two-volume study,
the first a catalogue raisonne, the second containing Whistler's
correspondence and a number of technical studies. The recent
development of high-resolution digital photography allows brilliant
reproduction of all of Whistler's 179 lithographs -- including some
with color highlights suggesting he was thinking of pastels or
watercolors -- along with lithographic drawings never transferred
to stone. Several prints appear in various states, to let one see
the artist at work. This 992-page two-volume set also includes 173
letters between Whistler and his printer (a fine technical
archive); a chronology of exhibitions, printings and sales; a
complete survey of the papers he used and of their watermarks; a
concordance; essays on Whistler's methods; and more. There are 864
illustrations: color plates, halftones, duotones and tritones. The
accounts of the pictures, the introductions to other materials and
the essays are quite accessible, and the printing and production of
this formidable monument pay fitting tribute to the intellectual
labor it enshrines, as well as to Whistler. It is not too heavy to
lift, and, at 14 by 10 by 4 inches in its slipcase, it can be
carried home in any old shopping bag. _ D. J. R. BRUCKNER
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
