<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE STONE
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Persian Legend of the Magi.
</P>
<P>
   By Dianne Hofmeyr. Illustrated by Jude Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaged. New York: Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $16. (Ages 5 to 9)
 &UR; THE FOURTH WISE MAN
</P>
<P>
   Based on the story
</P>
<P>
   by Henry Van Dyke.
</P>
<P>
   Retold by Susan Summers.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated by Jackie Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaged. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Dial Books for Young Readers. $16.99. (Ages 5 to 9)
 &UR; CHILDREN'S BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BY EDES GILBERT
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THE story of the Magi, the Wise Men who followed the star to
Bethlehem, is a timeless, treasured tale whose message is never out
of date. In ``The Stone: A Persian Legend of the Magi,'' we are
given a version of that story as Marco Polo said it was given to
him in Persia on his way to the court of Kublai Khan in the 13th
century. ``In the ancient town of Saveh stood a tower . . .
encrusted with turquoise tiles and filled with strange
instruments'': such language helps evoke the mystery and the power
of the long journey of the tower's three inhabitants. That journey
ends not with their gifts to the child, but with his to them;
disappointing at first, it soon appears to be, as the Magus
Balthasar announces, ``a gift that will bring justice and healing
and peace into the world.'' And sharing the child's gift, the Magi
and many others set out on another journey, bearing it ``to all the
faraway places of the earth,'' a journey that is not over to this
day.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of ``The Stone'' is unmistakable and clear, and the
words of the author, Dianne Hofmeyr, a South African writer living
in London, lend themselves to reading aloud in cadences that are
more like music than preaching. The appealing illustrations by the
South African artist Jude Daly portray the people and the scenes
from a variety of perspectives and with a directness that is
consistent with the story's simple prose (but never so simple as to
detract from its essential spiritual quality and charm).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fourth Wise Man'' is a retelling by Susan Summers, a
British writer, of Henry Van Dyke's once well-known 1896 book,
first written as a sermon and intended for an older audience, about
a Zoroastrian called Artaban. In this attractive version, with
lovely if predictable illustrations by Jackie Morris, the story
shifts focus; from a statement that emphasizes the power of virtue
and hope, it has become a more pragmatic tale about a man on a
quest. In this version Artaban lacks some of the nobility of
character that the original tale endowed him with. The story is
thus to some extent transformed from a parable for adults and young
adults that teaches the values of faith, hope, love and integrity
into one that substitutes an attitude that sometimes bows to
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   On the journey to see the child Jesus, the fourth wise man,
Artaban, is late to join the others, who have left without him. As
he travels he has several presumably life-transforming experiences,
which are diminished here by the lack of a philosophical base -- or
perhaps by the dreadful history of the 20th century, in which
faith, hope, love and integrity sometimes availed less than Van
Dyke might have expected. Artaban visits a young woman and her baby
as the soldiers of Herod are ransacking a village and murdering its
infants. When the soldiers come to the woman's cottage looking for
another child to kill, Artaban tells their captain that he is alone
in the house: ``I will give you this jewel if you will leave me in
peace.'' Then he shows a gift he had meant for the child Jesus, a
ruby, ``glistening in his palm like a great drop of blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The story continues: ``The captain's eyes widened with greed and
he grabbed the jewel. 'March on!' he cried. As the soldiers left,
Artaban quietly prayed: 'God of Truth, forgive my lie. I have said
the thing that is not, to save the life of a child.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Van Dyke's book, the jewel is also offered and accepted but
only after Artaban ``stood in the doorway of the house. . . . His
face was as calm as though he were watching the stars, and in his
eyes there burned that steady radiance before which even the
half-tamed hunting leopard shrinks and the fierce bloodhound pauses
in his leap.'' It is his strength of character, not the jewel, that
saves the child.
</P>
<P>
   Of this new version, one might ask, ``Is it acceptable to lie in
certain circumstances?'' and ``What are those circumstances and
why?'' Such questions could be difficult to talk about with a young
child, and the picture-book presentation makes the book seem too
young for an older child who might find the questions
thought-provoking.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this is a romantic and important story,
weaving the faith of those who followed Zoroaster with the story of
the birth of Jesus. Artaban was a scholar of the stars, as were the
other Wise Men, Caspar, Melchior and Balthazar. All four were men
of faith and hope. Their mission to follow the star to see Jesus is
an unforgettable statement of the power of faith and hope that
grows from wisdom and knowledge. From Artaban, the fourth Wise Man,
we learn that although his heart's desire was denied him, his
mission was accomplished through that denial.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Edes Gilbert is an educational consultant in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
