<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BOOKSHELF-NYT     12-16 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BOOKSHELF-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOUNG MARY OF NAZARETH. By Marianna Mayer. Morrow. $16. (All
ages) This account of the girlhood of the Virgin Mary is drawn from
apocryphal and traditional sources, and the 24 color illustrations
include many well-known images from European art.
</P>
<P>
   JOY TO THE WORLD: Christmas Stories From Around the Globe. By
Saviour Pirotta. Illustrated by Sheila Moxley. HarperCollins.
$15.95. (All ages) Five sweet holiday stories from Syria, Malta,
Mexico, Ghana and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   THE ADVENTURES OF SNOWWOMAN. Retold and illustrated by Katya
Arnold. Based on a story by V. Suteev. Holiday House. $15.95. (Ages
5 to 9) A story by the Russian writer Vladimir Suteev has been
adapted so that in this version a group of children write a letter
to Santa and make a Snowwoman to deliver it. Her adventures in the
forest involve all sorts of animals, and of course there is a happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHRISTMAS DOLLS. By Candice Ransom. Illustrated by Moira
Fain. Walker. $15.95. (Ages 5 to 8) Claire's mother brings home a
box of broken dolls in early December and sets about repairing
them, transforming them into nice presents for other children.
Despite the fact that her father has left and she's gloomy, Claire
helps with the project and the Christmas spirit takes hold.
</P>
<P>
   CAROL OF THE BROWN KING: Nativity Poems by Langston Hughes.
Illustrated by Ashley Bryan. Jean Karl/Atheneum. $16. (All ages)
Six poems, five by Hughes and one from a Puerto Rican Christmas
card that he translated from the Spanish, have been appealingly
illustrated in glowing colors.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS IS COMING! By Claire Masurel. Illustrated by Marie H.
Henry. Chronicle. $14.95. (Ages 2 to 6) Juliette throws herself
into holiday preparations with the help of her faithful dolls and
stuffed dinosaur, but on Christmas Day it seems all the presents
are for her. No, wait, there's something for all to share as well.
Ebullient illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   A CALENDAR OF FESTIVALS. Retold by Cherry Gilchrist. Illustrated
by Helen Cann. Barefoot Books. $18.95. (Ages 4 and up) Here's a set
of eight stories that will take you around the world through the
year, from the Jewish Purim in the spring to the Hindu story of
Holi, from the Celtic Halloween to a Russian New Year story about
Father Frost.
</P>
<P>
   THE ANGEL TREE. By Helena Clare Pittman. Illustrated by Jo Ellen
McAllister Stammen. Dial. $15.99. (Ages 5 to 9) Cyrus McCafferty,
the richest man in Bordenville, lived alone, and invited all the
children on the Friday after Thanksgiving to decorate a huge spruce
tree. He was already old when Jake was little. The Christmas after
he left town, he sent Jake a special present.
</P>
<P>
   SILENT NIGHT: The Song and Its Story. By Margaret Hodges.
Illustrated by Tim Ladwig. Eerdmans. $15. (All ages) The text in
this account of how Franz Gruber, the part-time organist, and
Father Joseph Mohr, the young priest, happened to compose a
charming carol for the parishioners in the Austrian village of
Oberndorf in 1818 doesn't say that mice got into the organ works;
but the crucial illustration shows a small rodent scampering away
from the choir. The story of an enduring success is gracefully
told.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
