<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2980 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDREN-BRIE     12-16 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDREN-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: FOR CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a December evening President Theodore Roosevelt chases his
six children through an obstacle course of overturned chairs and
scattered pillows in the family quarters of the White House. After
the giggling dies down, someone asks when they will get their
Christmas tree. ``It's not good to cut down trees for mere
decoration. . . . We must save our trees for the future,'' the
President and conservationist explains.
</P>
<P>
   In this mostly true story, Roosevelt's two youngest boys, Archie
and Quentin, decide to smuggle in a small evergreen anyway. With
the help of an aunt who leaves the little tree outside, they hoist
it up to their bedroom, using some knotted sheets, and hide it in
their closet. Gary Hines, a former forest ranger and author of the
exciting ``Flying Firefighters,'' knows how to spin a tale for the
very young. A CHRISTMAS TREE IN THE WHITE HOUSE (Holt, $15.95; ages
5 to 9) has just the right amount of suspense as the story unfolds
and the tree is, of course, discovered. When Roosevelt marches the
boys over to the home of his chief forester, Gifford Pinchot, the
expert provides a plot twist -- and a happy ending -- with a lesson
on nature.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Wallner's illustrations seem static at first, with
figures as carefully arranged as the Victorian furniture, until you
notice such sweet details as little red hearts near the mouths of
the boys as they blow good-night kisses to their mother. This small
story shines up the image of the White House by portraying one of
its most popular occupants as the loving father and dedicated
leader that he was. In a note, Hines explains that the Christmas
tree really was hidden in the closet, and the children were sent to
see Pinchot, but he has contracted the events. He also reports that
Roosevelt was responsible for protecting millions of acres of
forested land. _ MARGARET MOORMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NORTH BY NIGHT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Story of the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   By Katherine Ayres.
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte, $15.95. (Ages 10 and up) BRIGHT FREEDOM'S SONG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Story of the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   By Gloria Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Whistle/
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt Brace, $16. (Ages 8 to 12) THE LAST SAFE HOUSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Story of the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Greenwood.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated by Heather Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Kids Can Press, $16.95. (Ages 8 to 12) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These three books have more in common than their subtitles. Each
tells the story of a plucky white girl who, having been raised to
trek the moral high ground by abolitionist parents, risks her life,
reputation or standing in the community to help slaves escape to
freedom on the underground railroad. Nice idea. But since a search
for ``underground railroad'' in the children's section of
Amazon.com turns up more than 50 titles, why now? And why do all
three books have the same plot?
</P>
<P>
   A little detective work: If you know a school-age girl with
grandparents willing to spend $75 or so (and, trust me, that's just
the beginning) on a toy, you can probably find the answer by
opening that child's bedroom door and looking at her American Girl
doll. The brainchildren of Pleasant T. Rowland, the American Girl
dolls, which now number six, come in white, black or Hispanic,
colonial to modern. Each doll, representing her period of American
history, comes (for a price) with clothes, cunning accessories and
books. You can put on plays with your doll; you can make art
projects she might have made; you can read historically vetted and
hence parent-pleasing novels about her. And there's more, much
more.
</P>
<P>
   It's an industry, all based on the premise, as expressed on the
back of the books, that some things about growing up have changed,
while others, like families, friendships and feelings, haven't
changed at all. These are the important things that American girls
will always share. Also a nice idea. But seeing all of history as
an excuse to connect the experiences of girls over time is a
formula, even (in the case of the Pleasant Company) a business
plan. It's not a template for children's fiction, as these three
books, which seem to follow the Pleasant Company formula, might
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Ayres's ``North by Night,'' while treacly, is the
standout in this crowd, largely because Ayres's heroine, conceived
more in the tradition of Jacqueline Susann than Louisa May Alcott,
has adventures (and the emotions that go with them) worthy of an
episode of ``Dawson's Creek.'' There's a baby named Hope born to a
dying slave girl; a boyfriend named Jeremiah Strong who, though a
Quaker, knows how to kiss; a neighbor widow who's only pretending
her husband is dead. What a page turner! It even made me snuffle
once or twice.
</P>
<P>
   No such guilty pleasures rescue ``Bright Freedom's Song,'' which
seems to have been inspired not by the desire to spin a narrative
but by the urge to make a point: Gloria Houston believes, though
she admits in a preface she can find no proof, that there was a
connection between antislavery activities in the southern
Appalachian Mountains and the previous indentureships of many of
the earliest settlers. And so our young girl's Pa, who had come
over from the auld country, the land of the Scots, as an indentured
servant, now helps others escape the brutality he knew too well.
What happens when Pa gets the fever? Guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Safe House'' is more a textbook and study guide than
a story. Its premise is that Canadians have not got their share of
underground railroad thanks. Well, O.K., I'm sorry. And I hope that
teachers putting together underground railroad curriculums will
refer to this book. But I don't think too many children are going
to be turning to it for pleasure reading.
</P>
<P>
   Learning about history from fiction can be thrilling --
successful examples are too numerous and obvious to mention -- but
only if the characters who inhabit the events are more than dolls.
That's where the fun comes in. And that's what's missing here. _
SUSAN BOLOTIN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIRE!
</P>
<P>
   My Parents' Story.
</P>
<P>
   By Jessie Haas.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwillow, $15. (Ages 8 to 12) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Early one spring morning in Vermont an 8-year-old coughed
herself awake and ended up saving her family. Patty Trevorrow
awakened her mother, who realized that the house was on fire and
sprang into action, waking up all the relatives and boarders who
were vacationing at the farm in East Dover, which belonged to
Patty's uncle, Earl Yeaw. While the adults were able to save some
of their things and most of the animals, they could not save the
house. Fifty years later, Patty's daughter, the author Jessie Haas,
tells this true tale in ``Fire! My Parents' Story.'' ``We were
brought up on stories about the farm,'' Haas writes of herself and
her brother and sister. ``But the big story was the Fire.'' The
event is seen through Patty's eyes, which accounts for much of its
charm. The 1948 setting makes this a history book, yet it is the
relatively near past; in part because of the family photographs, it
will feel more real to most children than the faraway 1800's of the
``Little House'' series and ``Little Women.'' ``Fire!'' is a plain,
well-told tale by the author of more than a dozen children's books
(most of them about horses), who imaginatively captures the facts
and fears of being in a fire. ``Everything is terrible,'' she
notes, ``but not as terrible as it might be, and it's also a little
exciting.'' Romance came out of this particular fire as well:
Patty, who was carried out of the burning house by 18-year-old
Bobby Haas, a vacationer at the farm, was carried by him across the
threshold of their marital home, another farm, 10 years later.
Jessie Haas also reports that both her grandparents and her parents
became volunteer firefighters. The enduring truth is that life goes
on. ``What happens next? Does everything come to an end?'' Haas
writes. ``No.'' A lesson for us all. _ ANDREA HIGBIE
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
