<HEADER>
A2981 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WATCHING-NYTS     12-16 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WATCHING-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE WOMAN WATCHING
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Paola Capriolo. Translated by Liz Heron.
</P>
<P>
   214 pp. St. Paul: Serpent's Tail/Consortium Book Sales and
Distribution. Paper, $13.99.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; STAGE BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   BY PETER HAINSWORTH
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Paola Capriolo is one of the few Italian novelists whose
imagination looks north -- to landscapes and townscapes of mists
and gloom that are not quite real and to psychological and
philosophical mysteries that are always moving toward resolution
but never quite get there. All this is romantically Germanic -- in
some books overtly Kafkaesque, in others more like the early Thomas
Mann. At the same time Capriolo never lets us forget she is an
ironic post-modernist, which means she can keep up the deeply
rooted Italian tradition of holding unnamable menaces at a
distance. Her narratives proceed with calm, if perhaps a
neurotically preserved one. Her prose is as abstracted from realism
as it is from emotional violence, carefully and elegantly
constructing the surfaces that, it grants, could fracture at any
moment if this were anything but literature. At times the absurdity
of the whole project -- of crazed emotions, of philosophizing, of
reading and writing -- comes comically through, only for the humor
to vanish again.
</P>
<P>
   Capriolo has completed six novels since ``La Grande Eulalia,'' a
collection of stories published in 1988, when she was in her
mid-20's. They are surprisingly varied, though they tend to play
with similar ingredients. Over all the melange has steadily become
more and more refined, but it has not always turned out as
satisfyingly as it does in ``The Woman Watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening pages offer a deliberately unfocused version of the
real world. The setting is an unnamed provincial town, which just
might be in northern Italy; the time, one guesses, the 1920's or
thereabouts; the plot simple, or simply incredible. The principal
figures are brought into being before our eyes as fictional
versions of people who existed but may have been quite different in
reality -- Vulpius and Dora, two young actors in the municipal
theater company, he hyper-self-aware in a Pirandellian way and able
to transform himself into any character he is required to play, she
unreflectively and cheerfully herself and hence an indifferent
actress.
</P>
<P>
   What was apparently a happy love affair, at least for Dora,
begins to go wrong. In the course of a performance of a dramatic
version of ``Don Giovanni'' Vulpius notices a mysterious spectator,
the ``woman watching'' of the title. He never meets her, but after
a few exchanges of looks he begins to realize that the art of
acting is ultimately not for the audience or even for the actors,
but for itself.
</P>
<P>
   From this point on, normal performance and normal life gradually
become secondary. Vulpius gets Dora to perform at night to an empty
theater, in an eerily addictive ritual that is ultimately fatal.
Dora finds herself the unhappy plaything of forces outside her
control, not least the author, who disingenuously claims to be
obliged to kill her off. But Vulpius, egoist though he is, is also
the devotee of a sacred cult. He is made calmly to meet his end in
a final act of theater as funeral, quite alone apart from the
imagined gaze of the woman spectator who triggered the process in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Can Capriolo be serious? In 1996, shortly after this novel was
published, she wrote a study of the esthetic thought of the German
poet Gottfried Benn (``L'Assoluto Artificiale''), which was very
serious indeed about his particular version of art for art's sake.
It emphasized the way in which his theory reinstituted the timeless
and the sacred through dedicated artificial play and created the
only area of meaningfulness that was allowed to post-modern man. In
her fiction the clash between worn-out humanism or normality and
the austere demands of the Bennian creed takes on several meanings.
The journey to superior purity is an absurd journey to death, which
inevitably involves cruelty and pathos if it is really to be
undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   ALL the same, this is not an admonitory fable. The dangers of
art are part of what art is. Both as novelist and essayist Capriolo
has no doubt about the validity of fictional ironies and
artificialities. In this novel she achieves a new lucidity in her
juxtaposition of mirroring looks and in her playing of construction
and deconstruction against each other. As for the reader, he or she
is implicitly invited to join the author and her mysterious
watching woman, to take pleasure in the spectacle and to cast on it
the sort of glittering gaze that was cast by Yeats's Chinese sages
on all the tragic scene before them.
</P>
<P>
   Some Italian critics have judged Capriolo's style bookish. But
the bookishness is an integral part of her conception of
literature, and always carried lightly. It is probably impossible
to transfer that aware but easy elegance into English. Liz Heron's
version is highly readable, though her phrasing and intonation
often have an Italianate air. But perhaps that is an added pleasure
and, depending on which way you look at it, both natural and
unnatural. Capriolo should approve.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hainsworth is a professor of Italian at Oxford University.
He is editing, with David Robey, the Oxford Companion to Italian
Literature.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
