<HEADER>
A2996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE-SUITS-TEX     12-16 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-SUITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE'S PREPARATIONS FOR SERVICE FROM DALLAS SEEM STALLED BY
SUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED and MAX B. BAKER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The long, costly legal battle over expanded
service at Dallas' Love Field is making it tough for Legend
Airlines to get its business off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Legend President Allan McArtor, who wants to offer long-haul
service from Love, says the company is not facing a cash crunch.
</P>
<P>
   But a Legend source who requested anonymity said the company has
been carefully conserving its cash since October, when a state
judge issued an initial ruling against the long-haul service from
Love.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little, if any, construction progress over the
past two months on the airline's private six-gate terminal at Love.
And plans to start training pilots in January have been put on
hold, according to a recruiting consultant and pilots who have
applied to the airline.
</P>
<P>
   In government filings, the airline has said that much of its
financing is contingent on clearing the legal hurdles and getting
final authorization to serve Love, neither of which is expected
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The airline denies reports that construction of its terminal and
parking garage has been halted. It said it no longer wants to talk
about pilot hiring or training schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are where we choose to be in the terminal construction,''
McArtor said. ``We don't intend to be denied our authority to fly
out of Love Field. ... Everyone wants to pull us up by our roots to
see why we are not blooming now.''
</P>
<P>
   Legend originally wanted to launch service at Love Field in the
third quarter of 1997. But it has had to push back the start-up
date several times because of the political and legal wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   In documents filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission
and the Transportation Department, Legend has said it expects to
raise at least $32 million in start-up investment.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has ``enough commitments for money, but most of that is
contingent on Legend getting all this cleared up and getting the
final certification to fly,'' the Legend source said.
</P>
<P>
   Without additional capital, the source estimated, the airline
has enough cash to last another year at the current rate of
spending, or perhaps longer if some staff members are dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The legal fight began in October 1997, when Fort Worth sued
Legend, the city of Dallas and others to enforce its rights under
its 1968 contract with Dallas to build Dallas/Fort Worth Airport.
The 1968 deal precludes the kind of long-haul service from Love
Field that Legend proposes.
</P>
<P>
   The legal fight _ which has included trips into three federal
courts, the Texas appellate courts and the Texas Supreme Court,
plus several Transportation Department proceedings _ has been
costly to all the parties.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Fort Worth City Council has authorized spending
$950,000 on legal fees. The Dallas City Council has approved
spending up to $1.5 million, and the D/FW board has authorized up
to $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   The legal expenses of the private parties in the case, including
Legend and American Airlines, are not known but are believed to be
equal to or greater than the cities' legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   And the legal wrangling is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Legend is expected to appeal the October ruling by state
District Judge Bob McCoy of Fort Worth that blocked long-haul
service at Love Field.
</P>
<P>
   In court this week, McCoy agreed that a dispute over attorneys'
fees could be split into a separate lawsuit. He had previously
approved severing Fort Worth's original lawsuit from cross-claims
made by the D/FW Airport board against Continental, Continental
Express and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   A federal case is also pending, and the Transportation
Department is expected to issue a ruling soon on the same issue. No
matter which side that ruling favors, the losing side can be
expected to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling has apparently stalled Legend's hiring. As
recently as late October, prospective pilots said they were being
told by Legend officials that the company expected to start its
training in January.
</P>
<P>
   But Air Inc., an Atlanta firm that helps pilots looking for
jobs, reports that Legend is telling candidates only that it hopes
to start a class sometime in the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   At the terminal, meanwhile, a foundation has been poured, as has
the concrete floor of what will be the passenger concourse, or
second floor. But little work has been done at the site since late
October.
</P>
<P>
   The Legend source estimated that between $3 million and $4
million has been spent on the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of spending the additional $8 million to $10 million
it will take to complete the terminal, money that Legend apparently
has on hand, Legend will probably use that money ``to keep the
legal fight going a year or more,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
