<HEADER>
A2998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-HNS &LR;      12-16 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS NEED A GARGANTUAN BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For interested bystanders who wish to send any tokens of
appreciation or esteem (hint, hint), the address is Giants Stadium,
East Rutherford, N.J., 07073.
</P>
<P>
   Cards from the 1972 Miami Dolphins would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of champagne would be nicer.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the New York Giants need any help to get on a good
buzz. Their shocking 20-16 victory against the Denver Broncos was
legally intoxicating. The 1998 highlight film will have game
footage after all. The Giants have a bounce in their walk, smiles
on their faces, songs in their hearts. They look in the mirror, and
they see handsome devils. They look around, and their significant
others are more ravishing than ever.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when a dead-end team gets the satisfaction
of dragging the high and mighty to its level. They can talk until
they're Big Blue in their face about how the only thing that truly
matters to them is defending their Super Bowl championship. They
lost their chance to stamp themselves as truly special Sunday when
the answer to John Elway's dial-a-prayer pass into the end zone on
the final play was no.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's perfect. Nobody but the '72 Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team will be remembered for this game,'' Giants
coach Jim Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel's hurry to put an epitaph on his '98 team is
understandable. The sooner the season is buried, the better for the
Giants. They will be home after the holidays, unwelcome to attend
the playoffs. Though the Giants play in the National Football
League's equivalent of the 98-pound weakling division, the best
they can finish is 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   They went 10-5-1 last year. One interpretation is that they're
taking a couple steps backward before they go boldly into the next
millennium. Another interpretation is that they have no idea where
the hell they're going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had something to prove,'' said Giants safety Percy
Ellworth, who batted down the pass in the end zone that sent the
Broncos thudding to 13-1. ``We think when we come to play, nobody
can march up and down the field against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what? The Giants had something to prove all season.
They won the NFC East last season with the help of a schedule that
made a baby's bottom look like sandpaper. This was the Giants'
chance to see how they measure up against the class of the NFL.
Playing the sort of first-place schedule that separates the men
from the boys, the Giants quickly took on the look of a team that
needed its mommy.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants didn't define themselves by driving 84 yards for the
winning touchdown against Denver. The Giants defined themselves by
the body of work that made them 5-8 (1-5 outside the NFC East)
entering Sunday. Too often, their bodies were dead on arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget the bookend 31-7 defeats against Dallas and San
Francisco in front of the Monday Night Football cameras. Or the
37-3 November thrashing by Green Bay in the Meadowlands. Or the
21-14 defeat against a dispirited Washington team that had lost its
first seven games. Or the eyesore of a 23-3 defeat against Tampa
Bay, which limited the Giants to 135 yards of total offense. Or the
dreary performances on both sides of the ball (233 yards gained,
414 allowed) in a 20-17 defeat at Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   If the Giants had played with the purpose and passion they
showed against Denver all season, they wouldn't be where they are
today. They sure wouldn't be looking up at Dallas and Arizona in
the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always look back and say, `Gosh, if we had won this
game or that game,''' Fassel said. ``But you can kill yourself
looking back. You have to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. The Giants need to move on, before they convince
themselves that one shining moment against a live, breathing team
truly makes a season. The harsh light of the standings reveals the
Giants to be closer to Philadelphia than Denver both in geography
and accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are 28th out of 30 teams in total offense. They're
28th in passing, 27th in pass-efficiency rating, 27th in scoring.
The defense that masquerades as a source of pride is 20th in yards
allowed, 18th in points allowed. The Giants have allowed 51 points
more than they've scored. They've allowed 801 more yards than
they've gained. The season-ending knee injury of cornerback Jason
Sehorn didn't do that much damage. Worse for the Giants is that
they are no closer to finding a quarterback than they were the day
they pushed Phil Simms out the door. In 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the rush of seeing Kent Graham do an Elway imitation
impair the judgment. It was only an imitation. If the answer is
Kent Graham or Danny Kanell, rest assured that the question is not:
Who led the Giants to their third Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Kanell are the sort of quarterbacks who are just good
enough to find work in the NFL _ as long as no heavy lifting of a
team is involved. And they aren't in the habit of bursting into
tears during games. At least, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is the current quarterback in favor because of three
victories in four starts. His passing rating: 65.4. Kanell's: 67.3.
Dave Brown had a 71.1 rating last year, and the Giants couldn't
wait to push him out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Giants will have the good luck to have Syracuse's
Donovan McNabb fall to their spot in the next draft. Maybe the
Giants would have the good sense to take him at that point. Until
the blessed day when the Giants find a quarterback who is part of
the solution instead the problem, meaningful victories will be few
and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Still, cards would be nice. Champagne would be nicer. A victory
buzz can only last so long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
