r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     12-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET YOUR VOICE BE HEARD IN D.C.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I keep hearing that the polls don't mean anything, that Gallup
and other polling organizations rig the results to create the
illusion of widespread support for their political agenda _
whatever that may be.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the anti-polling comments have been focused on all those
polls estimating that opposition to the impeachment of President
Clinton has been hovering somewhere in the range of 65 to 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pollster ever calls to ask my opinion,'' the poll critics
say. ``They never call anybody I know.''
</P>
<P>
   I've never had much use for polls myself, but it does seem that
they're getting more accurate all the time. Besides, I know a lot
of people who oppose impeachment; the anti-impeachment numbers in
the polls make perfect sense to me.
</P>
<P>
   It also made sense that polls taken at the end of the House
Judiciary Committee's impeachment proceedings showed that support
for impeachment had increased. Those anti-impeachment numbers in
the upper 60s suddenly dropped to 60 or thereabouts, suggesting
that the steady drumbeat of pro-impeachment rhetoric had taken its
toll.
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural that when people hear something over and over
again, some will begin to believe it. The Judiciary Committee's 21
Republicans said it over and over, hour after hour, day after day:
President Clinton should be impeached and removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Like those TV commercials that pound at our brain until we
finally rush to the store and buy a certain brand of breakfast
cereal, the ceaseless pitch for impeachment could be expected to
change some minds. The surprise might be that a solid 60 percent of
the American people still were opposed by the time the Judiciary
Committee approved the last of four articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I know what you're thinking. Do I intend to make a point
here, or just keep jabbering?
</P>
<P>
   The point is this: After Sunday's column in which I urged
readers to contact their representatives in Congress and register
their views on impeachment, I received a number of phone calls from
people wanting to know which representatives to contact and how to
reach them.
</P>
<P>
   Among callers who stated an opinion on impeachment, pro or con,
six out of ten opposed impeachment. In other words, my completely
serendipitous, totally unscientific survey produced the same result
as the latest national polls: 60 percent of respondents said
Clinton should not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe those folks in Congress don't want to take the pollsters'
word for it, but they surely can't ignore my voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding. I'm well aware that the folks in Congress couldn't
care less about my voice mail. In fact, I suspect that they
resolutely ignore their own voice mail if it tells them something
that they don't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the point of Sunday's column was to encourage
people who oppose impeachment to make their opinion known to
Congress in the wake of news reports last week indicating that the
people who will decide Clinton's fate in the House of
Representatives were hearing mostly from pro-impeachment
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't suggesting that citizens who favor impeachment
shouldn't be heard. It just seemed to me that one side was being
disproportionately vocal, perhaps creating a distorted sense of the
national mood when those elected to the people's House very much
need to know what the people were thinking.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't contacted your representative, you still have
time to do so before the House votes on the articles of impeachment
recommended by the Judiciary Committee. If a majority of House
members vote for impeachment, the future of Clinton's presidency
will be in the hands of the Senate, where a trial will be held and
a two-thirds vote for conviction would result in the president's
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   This impeachment stuff is a big deal, folks. If you don't care
about it, you should.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
