 &HT;    COST OF A PRESIDENTIAL BID: $2,500 AN HOUR THROUGHOUT 1999
 &HT;    750&AMP;add. With CAMPAIGN-DATA. For release Saturday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    Eds: This story remains good for use through the New Year's
holiday.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Any presidential candidate who wants to win a major
party's nomination in 2000 will have to raise at least $22 million
in 1999, campaign finance experts say.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republican or Democratic hopeful who starts New Year's
Day, that comes to more than $2,500 an hour, 24 hours a day, seven
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising that much doesn't mean you're going to win, but it
means you have a chance,'' said political scientist Herbert
Alexander, who has published book-length studies of the financing
of each presidential election since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some scholars have come to regard fund-raising in the
pre-election year as the invisible primary,'' agreed John Green,
director of the University of Akron's Bliss School of Applied
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate who raised the most early money has captured his
party's nomination in every presidential election since 1976, when
reporting of pre-primary finances was first required.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard reality that will drive next year's quest for money
is that candidates will be so busy campaigning during the heart of
the 2000 primary season that they simply won't have much time to
raise funds.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 states may hold their caucuses or primaries on or
before March 11, 2000. If they do, candidates will have to appeal
to three-fourths of the nation's voters by that date.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous election years, candidates won't be able to
concentrate solely on the Iowa caucuses or the New Hampshire
primary for the first two months. They'll have to buy lots of ads
or make expensive campaign trips to attract news coverage in huge
states such as California, Florida and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you do well in Iowa or New Hampshire, you'll have only
a week or two before New York and California,'' Alexander said.
``You can't possibly raise big bucks in that short a time, so
you'll need money in the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander set the realistic minimum to be raised in 1999 by ``a
serious contender'' at $25 million. The $22 million estimate came
from accountant Stan Huckaby, whose Virginia-based firm has kept
the books for hundreds of Republican campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Only one Democrat and two Republicans definitely could raise
that much in 1999, said political scientist Paul Herrnson(cq) of
the University of Maryland. The Democrat is Vice President Al Gore
of Tennessee. The Republicans are Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and
publisher Malcolm ``Steve'' Forbes of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly Al Gore has a national network of people he can call
on, and the same is true of George W. (Bush), who will inherit the
Bush dynasty'' from his father, former President George H.W. Bush,
Herrnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has spent the last two years honing his fund-raising
ability and is rich enough to use his own money if he comes up
short, Herrnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other hopefuls believe they would have a chance if they
raise at least $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can be viable with $15 million to $20 million,
(if) you husband your resources and don't spend them on straw polls
and other distractions in 1999,'' said Ed Gillespie, communications
director for the leadership PAC of Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio. ``If
John runs, we'd hope to have $12 million on hand on Jan. 1, 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans whose records indicate they might raise that
much include conservative activist Gary Bauer of Virginia, former
Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, former Vice President Dan Quayle
of Arizona, and Sens. John McCain of Arizona and John Ashcroft of
Missouri. All have raised at least $3 million for their own
campaigns or their personal political organizations in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats with a solid national fund-raising reputation include
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri and Sen. John Kerry
of Massachusetts, who met the $3 million threshold in the past two
years, as well as two others who raised that much in the past. The
two are former Sens. Bill Bradley of New Jersey and Paul Wellstone
of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're outspent four to one, you're cooked,'' Wellstone's
campaign manager, Dan Lucas, said. ``But if you're only outspent
two to one, you're in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   All those calculations include only ``hard'' money, which under
federal rules can be raised from individuals giving no more than
$1,000 apiece, plus federal funds to match the first $250 from any
of those donors.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcement of campaign finance laws has become so lax and
haphazard that Green said he can't even guess at how much
unregulated ``soft'' money will be raised for indirect help to some
of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing fast and loose with the rules will be easier than ever
in 2000,'' Green predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of financing their political travels during 1998 solely
through the small hard-money contributions raised by their
federally regulated committees, at least six hopefuls also formed
state committees or taxable corporations to help out. The federal
committees could accept only non-corporate gifts of $5,000 or less,
but the other organizations could accept soft money from any source
in any amount. Some may use these unregulated organizations to
finance activities in 1999 as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soft money's been useful before,'' Green said. Democrat
``Walter Mondale spent a lot early in 1984, but then Gary Hart came
out of nowhere in mid-spring when Mondale was almost out of money.
So labor unions (spending an estimated $5 million) bankrolled
Mondale delegates in various states.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said, ``I just see the creative use of soft money in 2000
as being like 1984 or 1996, but squared or cubed.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
