   US-IRAQ (Washington) _ U.S. officials build a case for a
military attack as another showdown with Iraqi leader Saddam
Hussein looms over weapons inspections. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SOLOMON (Washington) _ Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., the
outgoing chairman of the House Rules Committee, accuses President
Clinton of manufacturing a new confrontation with Iraq in order to
delay an impeachment vote in the House. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   GONZALEZ-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
is ``saddened'' that his last act of a 37-year career in the House
will be voting on impeachment. It ``was never intended to coerce
private moral standards,'' he says, stressing he opposes removing
President Clinton from office. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   GILMAN-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., one
of the few remaining House members uncommitted on the impeachment
issue, spends time at cafes and other meeting places in his upstate
New York district sounding out the views of his constituents. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SHAYS-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Republican moderate Rep.
Christopher Shays of Connecticut, who remains undecided on whether
to impeach the president, meets with him this afternoon. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   BOEHLERT-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y.,
a previously uncommitted moderate, announces he will vote for
impeachment of President Clinton. ``The president had an obligation
to tell the truth under oath,'' Boehlert says. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
