<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SLIP BACK INTO '50S-ERA SLEEPWEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jammies and matching robes just like Kitten,
Princess and Shortcake wore.
</P>
<P>
   Saucy baby dolls like Rizzo had in ``Grease.''
</P>
<P>
   Peignoirs with movie-star glamour.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget those plaid Lanz nighties that Grandma always
gave us.
</P>
<P>
   Jeepers, it's the '50s all over again, and we're playing records
at a pajama party in ``Pleasantville.'' Only this is real life, not
Nick at Nite.
</P>
<P>
   Wait. Maybe all those black-and-white sitcoms like ``Leave It to
Beaver,'' ``Father Knows Best'' and ``I Love Lucy'' are affecting
our sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles fashion consultant and author Patty Fox says movies
and TV have always influenced what we wear, and right now we're
stuck in the '50s. ``Young women have been watching all these old
TV shows, and it's all new to them. We've already had the glasses
(cat's-eye frames), the twinsets ... now it's flannel pajamas and
its sexy sister, the marabou-trimmed baby doll,'' Fox explains.
</P>
<P>
   The baby doll (a short nightie with matching panties) is
starting to show up in numerous department stores, but its
headquarters is Frederick's of Hollywood. According to Frederick's
spokeswoman Ellen Appel, the flirty baby doll in sheer nylon,
trimmed with fluffy marabou feathers, lace or sequins were inspired
by the comedy ``Austin Powers.''
</P>
<P>
   And the 20th anniversary of ``Grease'' helped fuel the fire.
</P>
<P>
   But TV's ``Ally McBeal'' got women of all ages to rethink
old-fashioned pajamas. Says Fox: ``Ally McBeal is a great
character. She's vulnerable yet appealing, and her look is fresh.
She's the Audrey Hepburn of the '90s. And as Audrey once said,
she's not as innocent as her doe eyes suggested.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, lingerie sales are up as high as 20 percent from last
year, reports Women's Wear Daily. And the NPD Group American
Shoppers Panel report for retailers also notes gains, suggesting
that women have tired of the athletic-inspired sleepwear and
oversized T-shirts they've worn for so long.
</P>
<P>
   At Robinsons-May stores, sales are consistent with national
trends. Says company spokeswoman Milinda Martin: ``Playful novelty
print pajamas are doing exceptionally well with Generation ``I was
at our holiday party and silent auction last week and was amazed at
how many grown women were bidding on a pair of those new `Ally
McBeal' pajamas from Bloomingdale's.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they know Santa won't be bringing them. ``Men tend to buy
overtly sexy lingerie, not flannel,'' Martin says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
