<SLUG> BC-FOX-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FANTASTIC MR. FOX': GREAT CHILDREN'S BOOK, MEDIOCRE OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The world is littered with great children's books
that failed to make the transition into great operas. Now Roald
Dahl's ``Fantastic Mr. Fox'' is joining the list, thanks to a work
commissioned from the composer Tobias Picker and presented by the
Los Angeles Opera. I just hope all those fifth graders in Tuesday
night's audience will accept a reassurance. Opera can be thrilling
and terrifying. You can hear things you never thought possible.
It's not always a matter of being vaguely polite (or not) to the
adults who took you along.
</P>
<P>
   The original story is strong, and it works. Like much of Dahl's
writing, it has an engaging coarseness: it reeks of greasy chicken
dishes and freshly dug soil. These smells do not go forward into
Picker's score, which is thoroughly nondescript. He rises
reasonably to the occasion for the ditty that the four fox cubs
sing about the three farmers who are the fox family's enemies, but
every other ball he drops. In an opera whose main characters are
nocturnal animals, and whose action unfolds after dark, the night
sounds are disappointingly tame. Worse, foxes, hedgehogs, rats and
humans all sound much the same. The music is woefully
undercharacterized.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, there is not much help from the libretto, by Donald
Sturrock, who is also responsible for the lame direction. The text
is wordy and sentimental. It misses all the opportunities it
creates. The mechanical digger with the soul of an artist, for
instance, could have been a funny and real operatic character, but
here she just brings one smile in the middle of the pervasive
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Picker gives her tuba and trombones, with more than a suggestion
of Wagner's Fafner, but otherwise his music deals in small change.
A couple of times it provides atmospheric, if rhythmically flaccid,
writing for a children's chorus of tree spirits. There is, rather
oddly, a good bit of showy if ungainly counterpoint. Nothing seizes
the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the animal costumes, after designs by Gerald Scarfe, are
delightful, especially those for the mole, badger and porcupine.
Philip Hill gives the fox cubs neat animal movements. There are
also some wastefully good performances, notably from Gerald Finley
in the title role and from Jamie Offenbach as Farmer Bean. Apart
from anything else, these two are the only members of the cast who
get the words across; they are also both lusty singers, and
Finley's lyrical baritone is good to hear even in indifferent
music.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ash conducts. The run ends on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3155 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XMAS-LIGHTS-ART-TEX     12-16 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMAS-LIGHTS-ART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART CRITIC SEES THE LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being an art critic is a lot easier than being a mommy, I'm
thinking as I drive the boys around to look at Christmas
decorations. Trickier still, I'm presently blending both roles,
trying to entertain the boys while applying professional criteria
to light displays.
</P>
<P>
   What I quickly discover is that their appreciation of holiday
lights depends on what they manage to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, look at those red lights over there, guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which lights, Mommy?''
</P>
<P>
   Or:
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were some interesting lights, Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh. I didn't notice them.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the boys like things they see _ and I see things
I like. Which is kind of the way it is when I look at art.
</P>
<P>
   But, this being the holiday season, I'm perhaps even more
willing than usual to stretch my definition of art (and good art,
at that) to include any number of Christmas decorations _ as
site-specific installations or folk art or whatever. About the only
things I won't accept are decorations that make homes look like
upscale boutiques, or installations that include those ``chasing''
lights (which make me dizzy).
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, eclecticism is the rule.
</P>
<P>
   There's a plain colonial-style house _ dark red brick,
white-painted trim, little if any shrubbery _ that looks as lovely
during the daytime as it does after dark. This is because it
doesn't rely extensively on lights. The residents have used boughs
and wreaths of greenery, in addition to lighting so simple that
it's almost stark. The green boughs interact beautifully with the
crisp geometry of the house. At night, the lights add to, but don't
overpower, the general effect. If the Puritans did much decorating
for Christmas, it would have been like this.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics might sniff and say this house is in excessively good
taste. But I don't think that's the issue. The owners' choice of
house and perfectly suited decoration reflect personal aesthetic
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for an informally designed, vaguely ranch-style
house with an informal but well-informed display of lights. There
are precisely placed miniature lights along the eaves, as well as
lights wrapped around the trunks of several trees. With one
exception, the trees are wrapped in single colors. The exceptional
tree is wrapped in multicolored lights, recapitulating each of the
other color themes.
</P>
<P>
   There is just enough contrast between the fine, straight lines
of light along the roof and the thick, organic sculptural forms
created by the wrapped trees. Just enough to let us know that,
informal as the arrangement is, it doesn't lack thought.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a big, white house with neo-classical overtones but
no real architectural integrity. Still, it's obviously comfortable
being what it is.
</P>
<P>
   And so are the lights and lighting fixtures decorating it. You
cannot beat this house for robust exuberance. It has conical
``trees'' made entirely of lights. Santa and his sleigh (with eight
tiny, wire reindeer) about to take off from the side yard. Live
oaks wrapped with lights. Lights everywhere. If that austere
colonial house is the Vermeer of holiday decoration, this is the
Leroy Neiman. Another example of aesthetic integrity, of choice of
decoration mirroring choice of house.
</P>
<P>
   But there are countless examples of totally incongruous holiday
decorations _ and that's where critical objectivity falters.
Because these are houses where the decorations are so piled on that
they take over the house, where the fantasy element of lights and
statues eclipses the reality of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Those are displays where heartfelt, personal enthusiasm rushes
in.
</P>
<P>
   While looking at lights in north Fort Worth the other night, I
see a house with lights along the eaves, lights draped from the
fence, with a blue-lighted star at the apex of the roof and a
rotund plastic Santa (illuminated from within) on the tiny roof.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks farther, I see a house with a few strands of
lights, randomly draped, and the word ``Jesus'' spelled out in
miniature white lights carefully affixed to the chain-link fence.
``Bravo,'' I think to myself.
</P>
<P>
   From a critical standpoint, I suppose I'm choosing content over
form. This is a nearly artless arrangement, and here I am homing in
on the message.
</P>
<P>
   But the next day, when I return to locate the house, I realize
what a seamless fusion of form and content this truly is. That's
because, in daylight, I can barely make out the word on the fence.
How fitting, I think, that the Light of the World is visible only
in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   I drive a little farther, and that's when I find the decorations
that I still can't understand, critically or personally.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny house has seen better days. But its yard is filled with
brightly painted decorations as well as everyday household stuff,
mud and what looks like rubbish. There is so much going on I don't
even see the Nativity display at first. Each of the figures looks
as though it has been hand-cut from plywood, then given a coat of
white paint. The details of each, including facial features, were
drawn on by hand.
</P>
<P>
   What would it look like by night, I wonder. So I go back with
the boys. If I hadn't rather carefully figured out the location by
daylight, though, I never would have found it. There are no lights,
just the ghostly Nativity and glimmers of candy canes placed in
neat rows.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if it weren't for a couple of wooden trusses stacked
out front, I'd overlook it entirely. But I see it and don't know
what to think. So I stop the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it, Mommy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure, Jack. It's sort of like decorations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, I think, maybe it's sort of like art.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
