<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3156 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BOOKSHELF-2TAK     12-16 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOOKSHELF-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL BOOKS HELP FILL HOLIDAY WISH LISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
and SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for that last-minute holiday gift for the traveler on
your shopping list?
</P>
<P>
   Give them the world: an atlas.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Eartha World Travelog'' (DeLoreme, $19.95) is especially
appealing. This large-format atlas showcases 192 countries and uses
satellite imaging to convey geographical features as well as cities
and borders. The maps are augmented with clever and well-researched
charts that offer historical and insightful information.
</P>
<P>
   Once the traveler has chosen a vacation destination, he or she
will want to know when to go. And whether to take an umbrella or
overcoat. Fodor's ``World Weather Guide'' (Random House, $17.95),
compiled by E. A. Pearce and C. G. Smith, offers charts with
climate breakdowns for major cities in more than 200 countries
organized in an A to Z format. A glossary of weather-related terms
is included. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Here are some other new or updated titles worth considering:
</P>
<P>
   Near the beginning of Bill Bryson's wonderful ``A Walk in the
Woods'' (Broadway Books, $25), the author is reunited with old
buddy Stephen Katz, now seriously out-of-shape, and you realize
than their quest to hike the 2,100-mile Appalachian Trail will be
anything but routine. ``He (Katz) indicated his bag on the carousel
_ a green army surplus duffel _ and let me pick it up,'' writes
Bryson. ``It weighed at least 75 pounds. He saw my look of wonder.
`Snickers,''' he explained. ``Lots and lots of Snickers.'' Laughs
abound throughout this 276-page book, but Bryson also captures the
beauty and wonder of the region's forests and mountains. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ Paris's cafes and bistros are at the heart of that romantic
city's personality and appeal. New York Daily News restaurant
critic Daniel Young focuses on ``rendezvous and recipes'' in ``The
Paris Cafe Cookbook'' (William Morrow, $24). Young infuses both
insight and wit into essays on 50 ``people-percolating
properties.'' Among dozens of recipes, he tells how to re-create
the Clown Bar's mussels and zucchini soup, Cafe Very's salmon with
coconut milk, Le Cafe Marly's tomato and goat cheese cake and Cafe
Cannibal's bricks (paper-thin sheets of pastry) with raisins,
cucumbers and onions. This hard-cover volume is a keeper. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ At the time of his death on July 4, 1997, longtime CBS ``On
the Road'' correspondent Charles Kuralt was working on a series of
vignettes collectively called ``An American Moment.'' They have now
been edited and organized by Peter Freundlich, Kuralt's friend and
collaborator, to make up ``Charles Kuralt's American Moments''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $22). Kuralt had a knack for introducing us to
one-of-a-kind people and places, and here we meet hex sign painter
Johnny Claypoole, broom maker Bob Funke, doll restorer Irving Chais
and 10-year old ``Trombone Shorty.'' Kuralt covers American
dreamers, shrines, heirlooms and much more; it's not heavy reading,
but spend just five minutes with this book and chances are you'll
be touched. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; A city has never been more thoughtfully photographed than in
``Timeless New York'' (Universe, $19.95). Paul Coughlin's
sepia-toned images offer a sentimental perspective on such
well-known landmarks as Trinity Church, Chinatown and Central Park.
The intimacy and the romance of the country's largest city is
captured in photographs such as one of lovers kissing in Greenwich
Village. Complementing the photos are the author's concise but
illuminative text and a thoughtful selection of quotes by some of
the city's most famous admirers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Karen Foulk of Sugar Land, a surburb of Houston, has written
two guides geared to families: ``147 Fun Things to do in Houston''
($12.95) and ``101 Fun Things to do on the Texas Coast'' ($13.95).
Both are published by Into Fun Company Publications. The guides
offer helpful information such as opening hours, fees and contact
numbers for scores of appealing attractions.
</P>
<P>
   _ For a not-so-subtle nudge toward an idyllic escape for two,
consider ``Bed &AMP; Champagne: World's Top Romantic Holidays'' (Boru
Publishing, $14.95), Bradley S. O'Leary's newly updated edition of
his 1997 volume. O'Leary assesses such diverse gems as Madewood
Plantation, a Greek Revival Mansion overlooking Bayou Lafourche
halfway between New Orleans and Baton Rouge, La.; Poppies Samui's
two-dozen beachside cottages in Koh Samui, Thailand; and the
elegant Turnberry Hotel in Scotland. Included are 201 destinations
from 40 states, the District of Columbia and 38 foreign countries.
You won't find photographs in this soft-cover publication, but each
destination report is preceded by verses of romantic poetry.
</P>
<P>
   _ We're enchanted with Abrams Publishers' ``Art of the State''
series. Its four new titles _ Vermont, Arizona, New York and
Louisiana _ are filled with tasty cultural tidbits such as images
of people, architecture and folk art. The tiny tomes ($12.95 each)
pay tribute to the state's history, literature and musical
traditions. Also, each guide is well served with lists of native
sons and daughters, attractions and events.
</P>
<P>
   _ Golfing continues to grow as a popular vacation activity, and
several books point to the best resorts and public courses. Among
them: the second edition of ``Golf Resorts: Where to Play in the
USA, Canada, Mexico, Costa Rica and the Caribbean'' (Hunter Travel
Guides, $16.95) by Jim and Barbara Nicol; and the ``Econoguide Golf
Resorts and Courses USA `98-'99'' (Contemporary Publishing, $16.95)
by Corey Sandler. Sandler's volume is accompanied by more than
$1,000 worth of discount coupons. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Bookshelves are crammed with consumer-tip books, and many
offer helpful advice that may apply to your individual needs. Among
comprehensive guides, it's hard to go wrong with the new second
edition of ``Insider Travel Secrets You're Not Supposed to Know''
(Best Fares, $19.95). Tom Parsons, editor of Best Fares Discount
Magazine, covers almost all aspects of the travel industry in this
447-page volume. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; For the coffee table: Celebrating a quarter-century of
publishing, Lonely Planet has produced its first large-format
illustrated book, ``Chasing Rickshaws'' (Lonely Planet
Publications, $24.95). Text is by Tony Wheeler, the well-respected
firm's founder, with 238 color photographs by Richard I'Anson. The
two men journey throughout Asia to explore the fascinating
development and variety of the rickshaw, born in Japan in the 1880s
and still utilized _ along with the cycle-rickshaw _ as an
important form of transportation. Emphasis is not only on distinct
designs but on fascinating people _ rickshaw pullers, riders,
manufacturers, artists _ whose roles are beautifully captured in
words and photos.
</P>
<P>
   _ Photojournalist Bill Bachman spent more than two years
exploring the Australian Outback, and his 256-page hard-cover
``Australian Colors'' (Amphoto Art, $35), with additional text by
Tim Winton, provides extraordinary images of the people and
landscape that make that continent's interior so distinct. The text
is no mere afterthought; it blends history, culture and humor in
helping readers gain insight into life in the Outback.
</P>
<P>
   _ Treasured artworks, gourmet cuisine and one of the world's
most fascinating regions share the focus in ``Matisse: A Way of
Life in the South of France'' (Rizzoli International Publications,
$40), another deluxe hard-cover volume. Gilles Plazy's text and
Jean-Bernard Naudin`s photographs help readers understand why life
along the French Riviera captivated and inspired artist Henri
Matisse early in this century. Matisse's paintings are juxtaposed
with the actual settings depicted in them. Matisse also was greatly
influenced by the region's foods, and Coco Jobard contributes 60
recipes _ among them eggplant caviar, pastilla with almonds and
pigeons and roasted pineapple with cinnamon _ that reflect the
Provencal and Russian specialties popular when the artist lived in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small but significant: If you need a stocking-stuffer for your
world traveler, go for the Berlitz pocket guides. These full-color
guides pack a lot of information into a tiny package. In addition
to attractions and history, the books offer detailed maps, helpful
translations and tips on shopping and dining. The series covers
more than 100 destinations; the two newest titles are Munich,
Germany, and Edinburgh, Scotland. Both are priced at $8.95.
</P>
<P>
   _ Show a loved one how much you care with the terrific ``Safety
and Security for Women Who Travel'' (Travelers' Tales, $12.95).
Authors Sheila Swan and Peter Laufer share what they call the
triple-A's of travel safety: attitude, awareness and attention. The
book covers topics ranging from how to spot a scam artist to coping
with your fears in a foreign place. Its anecdotes remind us of the
Jewish proverb: No matter what happens, travel gives you a story to
tell.
</P>
<P>
   _ No kid stuff here: In ``The Grown Up's Guide to Running Away
from Home'' (Ten Speed Press, $11.95), Roseanne Knorr suggests ways
to turn the dream of living abroad into a reality. The emphasis is
on practical tips: how to choose a destination, handle finances,
obtain health information, find house-sitters and pack and dress
for months away from home. Knorr encourages the hesitant: ``As you
hoist your backpack (well, OK, roll-on luggage), just tell the kids
who look on enviously that, after all these years, it's your turn
for adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   _ For the history buff on your gift list, look at
``Archaeological Mexico'' (Moon, $19.95). Author Andrew Coe has
written this first-edition guide that encourages archaeological
adventures to some of Mexico's more obscure and inaccessible ruins.
Comprehensive historical and archaeological information is
supplemented with practical travel tips. Coe also is anxious to
separate fact from the folklore that has surrounded Mayan culture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another new Moon title is ``Colonial Mexico'' ($18.95) by
Chicki and Oz Mallan. It's subtitle says it all: ``A Traveler's
Guide to Distinctive Lodging, Dining and Shopping in Historic
Districts and Artisans' Communities Throughout Mexico.'' Whew.
</P>
<P>
   _ An oldie but goodie is Rick Steves' ``Mona Winks'' (John Muir,
$19.95) and an updated fourth edition is just hitting bookshelves.
Written by Steves and Gene Openshaw, the irreverent, fun-to-read
guide steers visitors through Europe's top museums, including the
British Museum and the Prado. Intimated by the Louvre? You won't be
after reading ``Mona Winks.'' The 1999 edition of Steves' ``Europe
Through the Back Door'' (John Muir, $19.95), invaluable for
independent travelers, is also new on bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Author Lynn Cline has taken the guesswork out of planning a
tete-a-tete in Santa Fe. ``Romantic Days and Nights in Santa Fe''
(Globe Pequot, $15.95) offers 36 enticing and detailed itineraries.
Each getaway is themed. Among the options are ``A Spiritual
Soujourn,'' ``A Hiker's Paradise,'' and ``A Southwestern
Honeymoon.'' Travelers will appreciate Cline's inclusion of
practical information such as prices, Web sites and directions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also in Globe Pequot's ``Romantic Days and Nights'' series:
Atlanta, Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles, New York City, New Orleans,
San Francisco, Seattle and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
