<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, Dec. 17. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Confident they have the votes to impeach
President Clinton, House Republicans debated whether to go ahead
with the scheduled debate and vote on Thursday despite the growing
crisis over Iraq. By John M. Broder and Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With a timeline graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Analysis: How did we get here from
the post-election sense that impeachment was a non-starter? By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WHIP (Washington) _ When Majority House Whip Tom DeLay
was a kid, his parents used to wake him up early on Christmas
morning so he could help them finish assembling the other
children's toys. ``I read the instructions,'' he said. ``I've
always been a rules person.'' That affinity for the rules, the
small print, the Bible and the Constitution, he says, is the key to
why he's leading the House drive to impeach the president. By
Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REACTION (Washington) _ Members of Congress are bitterly
divided over President Clinton's decision to press a confrontation
with Iraq. While most still support an aggressive stance against
Saddam Hussein, Republicans began questioning the timing. Rep.
Gerald B.H. Solomon essentially accused Clinton of playing with the
lives of American servicemen in order to postpone the impeachment
vote. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Iraq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ American warships in the Persian Gulf
and B-52s nearby are poised to launch a punishing barrage of cruise
missiles against military targets in Iraq, prompting the House to
consider postponing its plan to begin debate on four articles of
impeachment against President Clinton. With graphic and photos,
including photo of naval activity, taken recently. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECT (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu essentially called for new elections Wednesday night,
seizing the offensive as he faced the increasing and humiliating
likelihood that his government would be toppled by the Parliament
on Monday. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMB (New York) _ New indictments are expected Wednesday
afternoon in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Tanzania. By
Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLONE (Seoul, South Korea) _ South Korean scientists said
Wednesday that they had cloned a human cell from an infertile
woman, creating an embryo that theoretically could have grown into
a physical replica of the woman. But they said that because of the
legal and ethical implications of their work, they stopped the
experiment and did not try to breed a human clone. By Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
