A3226 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GONZALEZ-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-16 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONZALEZ-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRING TEXAS DEMOCRAT CONDEMNS IMPEACHMENT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A veteran House Democrat who called for the ouster
of two Republican presidents said Wednesday he was saddened that
the last act of his 37-year career in Congress will be voting on
the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez of San Antonio said impeachment should
not be used by Congress to ``coerce private moral standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we start impeaching presidents for moral acts, it just
becomes a bottomless hole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, 82, will be one of 40 House lawmakers leaving office
when the 105th Congress adjourns at the end of this year. First
elected in 1961, he is retiring due to health problems.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed in August to defend Clinton from impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider this one of the most important votes ever,''
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at stake here is the coequality of the branches of
government and the stability that that has given us through
history. Once that is gone, there is no end to the possible
reoccurrences and imbalance of government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzalez name has been synonymous with impeachment. He
called for President Ronald Reagan's ouster twice, when U.S. forces
carried out a rescue invasion in Grenada and when the Iran-contra
scandal came to light.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush's military strike against Iraq in the Gulf
War also drew Gonzalez's ire and an impeachment resolution that
lacked support from the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were actually distorting the constitutional process in
the War Powers Act. In other words, my contention was that only
Congress could declare war, and unless the president receives
congressional approval, he would be declaring an unconstitutional
war,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton, Gonzalez accused the Republican leadership in the
House of engaging in a partisan ploy to overturn the president's
election in 1992 and re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation is to get control of the executive branch. The
people haven't given them that. They haven't been elected to that,
and they want that by hook or by crook,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   When the House convenes, it will debate impeachment charges that
Clinton committed perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of
power in connection with the cover-up of his affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a 228-207 majority in the House where a
majority vote in favor of one or more articles of impeachment would
trigger a Senate trial. If convicted by a two-thirds majority in
the Senate, Clinton would automatically be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   The dean of the Texas congressional delegation, Gonzalez called
the impeachment vote unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saddens me very much to return for this,'' Gonzalez added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me the Congress is acting beyond its
constitutional authority. As much as I defend against executive
encroachment, I'm also sensitive about legislative branch excess,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we go into that swamp, there is no getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez will cast his ballots alongside the other 29 House
members from Texas in what was expected to be an all-but-party-line
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Only Democratic Rep. Ralph Hall has announced his intention to
join Republicans and vote to impeach.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Stenholm, a conservative Democrat who often votes
with the Republicans on social issues, was still undecided
Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
