<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEHLERT-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-16 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEHLERT-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEHLERT SAYS HE WILL VOTE TO IMPEACH CLINTON FOR PERJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Sherwood Boehlert announced Wednesday that he
will vote to impeach President Clinton on at least charge _ perjury
before a federal grand jury _ but will wait until hearing the House
debate before making up his mind on three other accusations against
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert, a moderate New York Republican, said he believes
Clinton gave perjured testimony before the federal grand jury on
Aug. 17 about his sexual relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he did not tell the truth and this is about truth and
law,'' Boehlert told a news conference, adding: ``It's something I
have arrived at after thoughtful deliberation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the charge of perjury before a federal grand
jury, the president also is accused of perjury in the Paula Jones
civil lawsuit, obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said Clinton has tried ``repeatedly to game the
judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the origins of this case, whatever the motives of his
questioners, the president had an obligation _ a legal and
constitutional obligation _ to tell the truth under oath,''
Boehlert said.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said deciding whether to vote for impeachment is the
most difficult decision he has made in his 16 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 10 days I have had sleepless nights,'' he said in
an interview. ``My wife reports that my sense of humor is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert compared Clinton to former President Richard Nixon who
resigned in the aftermath of the Watergate scandal as the House was
about to impeach him in August 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a rare moment of personal insight, Richard Nixon concluded
that he had destroyed himself by hating his enemies back,'' he
said. ``I am afraid that President Clinton fell into the same, all
too human, trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blinded by his contempt for people who he thought were out to
get him, the president forgot his larger obligations to his office,
the Constitution and to the American people. He let his personal
feelings interfere with fulfilling his Constitutional
obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said none of the members of the Republican
congressional leadership have tried to sway his decision, which he
made after consulting judges and academics.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he was elected to a ninth term in his upstate New
York district by winning 80 percent of the vote. Two years earlier,
Clinton won only 46 percent of the vote in the district.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said he has received over 2,500 calls since Friday,
with the callers evenly split on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert insisted impeachment ``is not a partisan issue. It is a
serious, sober, heart-rending debate on the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vote of conscience _ my conscience is
nonnegotiable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said the House had very few options _ to vote yes or no
on impeachment, but the Senate has ``different options and a broad
array of possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am doing is sending this matter to the Senate, which
has a lot more flexibility than we do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert said he ``was enamored of'' a proposal by former
Massachusetts Gov. William F. Weld, a Republican support of the
president. Weld has proposed that Clinton be reprimanded and pay a
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Weld's proposal ``deserves the most careful consideration''
Boehlert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
