<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TECHNO-BOOKS-3TAK     12-16 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TECHNO-BOOKS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE USERS' RIGHTS (HAH!)  
 WELCOME TO LAMBDA MOO 
TO THE MONITOR BORN 
THE AUTISTIC SOCIETY 
MODERN TIME TRAVEL
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `BAD SOFTWARE'
</P>
<P>
   By Cem Kaner and David Pels (Wiley Computer Publishing, $29.99).
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows what it's like to spend $199 on a piece of
software that promises to change your life and delivers nothing but
headaches. ``Bad Software'' by Cem Kaner and David Pels is a
combative, encyclopedic rundown of the many ways in which
commercial software can waste our time, raise our stress levels and
generally wreck our spirits.
</P>
<P>
   But the book is less emboldening than it might seem. ``You Don't
Have to Put Up With This'' is the title of the book's first
section. Unfortunately, when it comes to bad software, you do. As
the authors concede, software might be difficult to install, and
still more difficult to use, but if it performs its job as
advertised, a consumer has little recourse.
</P>
<P>
   The authors merely reinforce this point by noting the high
volume of computer-related complaints received each year by the
Better Business Bureau. As anyone who has complained to the bureau
can tell you, lodging a complaint there is more often than not a
futile exercise motivated by desperation.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting chapter in ``Bad Software'' is the one on
consumers' legal rights. Kaner is a practicing lawyer and an expert
in legal issues surrounding software. It's fascinating, for
instance, to learn the difference between implied warranties and
express ones. But the information seems academic. ``If you have
been cheated, the law is on your side,'' the authors wrote. But
software makers seldom actually cheat their customers so much as
frustrate them.
</P>
<P>
   As the authors point out, refunds are difficult to get, and the
quest for one can require hours of testy telephone exchanges with
salespeople and their supervisors. Eventually, the authors boil
their message down to this: If you hate a program you are not
legally entitled to a refund if the program does what the publisher
said it would do.
</P>
<P>
   There is always small claims court, the authors tell us. But
trying to get a small claims court judge to understand the fine
points of software could turn into an experience that makes the
shouting matches with salespeople seem appealing.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to know that someone is out there standing up for the
consumer. Still, $29.99 seems a lot to pay for a topic that could
be covered in a five-page pamphlet instead of a 365-page book. The
authors' Web site (www.badsoftware.com) goes a long way toward
offering just such succinct advice. It's a welcome addition to the
Web, where most software guides are written from the perspective of
the companies, who seldom put themselves in the consumer's shoes,
perhaps because they don't have the time. They're too busy cranking
out bad software.
</P>
<P>
   _ KATIE HAFNER
</P>
<P>
   And Now, Back to Real Life
</P>
<P>
   `MY TINY LIFE: CRIME AND PASSION IN A VIRTUAL WORLD'
</P>
<P>
   By Julian Dibbell (Henry Holt and Co., due out in January,
$14.95).
</P>
<P>
   You can understand how things got so confusing for Julian
Dibbell, author of ``My Tiny Life.'' In real life, he was living
with his flesh-and-blood girlfriend in his New York flat. In
virtual reality, he _ actually, his online persona, Dr. Bombay _
had the serious hots for a fellow cybercitizen, and the pair were
having a passionate online affair that he calls tinysex. In the
end, of course, Dibbell was forced to make a choice. ``Two lives
was more than I could handle at the time,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Dibbell's story takes place in Lambda Moo, a virtual community
known as Multiple-User Dimension, Object Oriented. This virtual
world, called Moo for short, is rich with landscapes, meeting
places and fantastic images, with one crucial catch: There are no
graphics, just vivid textual descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Lamda Moo, thousands from around the world,
interact by typing conversations to one another. They create
personas, as Dibbell created Dr. Bombay, describing him as ``a
walking optical illusion, oscillating randomly between the sitcom's
plump pseudo-scholarly fop and the image of a lean old streetwise
back-alley medic.''
</P>
<P>
   The author's online tryst is just a piece of the story. A good
portion of Dibbell's book is devoted to exploring the nascent
social and political structure of Lamda Moo. The debates therein
harks back to the formation of any society struggling to be
democratic and create a rule of law. Who is in charge? What
constitutes harassment of another person? What authority determines
who can ``build'' new architecture?
</P>
<P>
   It may sound absurd that the author was able to become so
immersed in a world decorated only by text and populated by
inhabitants scattered around the world he would never actually see
or touch. But become immersed he did. The 324-page exploration of
Lamda Moo seems self-indulgent at first, but it eventually draws
the reader to the characters, their world and the worthy questions
the book provokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can anybody spend such time and energy in such a place and not
be in the throes of a miserable, soul-wasting addiction?'' Dibbell
asks. His own answer falls somewhere between no and perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
