<HEADER>
A3331 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TECHNO-BOOKS-2NDT     12-16 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TECHNO-BOOKS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and perhaps.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Outsmarting Ourselves: How Computers Can Fail Children
</P>
<P>
   `FAILURE TO CONNECT: HOW COMPUTERS AFFECT OUR CHILDREN'S MINDS _
FOR BETTER AND WORSE'
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Healy, Ph.D. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
</P>
<P>
   When you see a child in front of a computer monitor, engaged in
the fun or the challenge of a math game or a drawing program, there
is much more going on than meets the eye. For this book, Jane
Healy, an educational psychologist and educator for more than 35
years, spent two years and hundreds of hours talking to and
observing kids, their parents, teachers and school administrators.
She concluded that what you don't see is dangerous to children.
</P>
<P>
   With a federal initiative to wire all schools for computers by
2000 and the increasingly loud public debate over the allocation of
educational funds, this book provides an excellent look at what is
happening already in schools _ from well-endowed private academies
to poorer urban schools.
</P>
<P>
   The book is broad-ranging in its consideration, from a
discussion of surveys on the educational benefits of computer
access to an analysis of the various critical stages of early
childhood development and a prognosis of what children will need to
succeed in the technological future.
</P>
<P>
   The author has a knack for knowing when to pull back from
clinical psychological terminology to keep the book accessible to
the general reader. For parents of computer-using children of any
age, there are various lists of guidelines scattered throughout.
They include advice for Internet use and choosing and using
so-called educational software aimed at children (most of which,
Healy says, is designed by people who have little if any knowledge
of child development or educational philosophy).
</P>
<P>
   The discussion of the damage that computer use can have on young
learners _ especially preschoolers, the latest target of a software
marketing explosion _ is especially interesting. ``Starting
children on computers too early,'' Healy says, ``is far worse than
starting them too late.'' Her anecdotes, drawn from hours spent
with ``cybertots'' and ``digi-kids'' in school and at home,
illustrate the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the 4-year-old girl who spends up to four hours a day on
a home computer, to the delight of her parents. (``Wait till you
see how she handles these programs!'' her mother said). She plays
with some ``interactive problem-solving'' software in a game
format, racing a car around an animated landscape and picking up
items along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you pick up the rope?'' the author asked her. ``'Cause
you're s'posed to,'' was the response. The child had learned only
the tricks of someone else's invention. At early ages, Healy says,
problem-solving skills and lessons in cause and effect come from
play with toys like blocks and puzzles. In these activities, she
writes, ``the child is laying the groundwork to be either an
internally motivated or a weak learner.''
</P>
<P>
   In another example, eight third-graders were writing and
illustrating their own stories on a software program. They moved
around graphics and icons, fooled around with music, typed in
different sizes and fonts but did virtually no writing. ``Isn't it
wonderful what this technology can do!'' the teacher said. Not only
were the students not learning much useful, but their attention
spans were surely not being aided by all the multimedia
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Healy concludes, among other things, that the number of
computers a school has matters less than how well the school has
incorporated computers into the curriculum. Healy warns against
letting the new wave of school-based technology coordinators have
the upper hand over more experienced educators with less
technological expertise.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when more bombastic critics of the computerization of
education are making themselves widely heard, ``Failure to
Connect,'' by a self-described ``techno-pusher turned critic,'' is
a revealing study with useful practical applications.
</P>
<P>
   _ SANDY BYERS HARVIN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
