<SLUG> BC-CIR-TECHNO-BOOKS-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: practical applications. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE DE-VOICING OF SOCIETY: WHY WE DON'T TALK TO EACH OTHER
ANYMORE'
</P>
<P>
   By John L. Locke (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
</P>
<P>
   With billions of e-mail messages being sent every day, millions
of words spilling across the Web, instant messaging, pagers,
beepers and, of course, television and radio, it's hard to imagine
that anything worth saying is being left unsaid.
</P>
<P>
   But in a new book, John L. Locke, a linguist at the University
of Sheffield, argues that modern technology is robbing people of
the inclination to speak meaningfully to one another: ``Our social
voices are slipping away, leaving people in social isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   Humans, Locke writes, began speaking tens of thousands of years
ago, but vocal expression among our ancestors began hundreds of
thousands of years earlier, in the form of the facial displays and
chattering that accompanied social rituals like grooming.
</P>
<P>
   Locke argues that language is still broadly dualistic,
comprising its form (the structure and content of what we say) and
its function, that is, the way that talking, through inflections,
gestures and eye movements, creates social relationships. He calls
that ``the fundamentally nonlinguistic nature of talking'' or
``intimate talking.'' Village gossip and a baby's cooing are
examples. Neither offers much information, but both establish
important relationships with neighbors or parents.
</P>
<P>
   Locke argues that new technologies like e-mail and telephone
answering machines have increased the amount of functional
information we encounter in a day but lack the capacity for
intimate talking. The result, he says, is that we now live in an
``autistic society'' that is at home with computers but
uncomfortable with human intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of what Locke writes about social disconnection will be
familiar to readers of Robert Putnam, and it will make emotional
sense to anyone exhausted after a day of pages, phone calls, e-mail
messages and talk radio. But his book trips on a couple of
assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that new forms of communication always displace
earlier ones, rather than creating new opportunities for
conversation. But even Locke provides examples that undercut his
own argument. A Finnish student he quotes on the popularity of
mobile phones in Scandinavia says: ``We've never been much good at
talking to each other face to face. All that's happened is we've
found our ideal way of communication _ at arm's length.''
</P>
<P>
   Locke also assumes that a lack of intimacy is always a bad
thing. Take e-mail, which Locke calls an ``emotionally parched''
form of communication. He's right, of course: E-mail does strip
away the intimacy of face-to-face conversation. But it also strips
away some of the fear, guilt, anger and self-consciousness, which
is one reason that e-mail has become so successful. Co-workers who
otherwise loathe one another can still be productive through
e-mail. Children can carry on (relatively) guilt-free relationships
with parents. Narrowing the emotional range of conversation can
sometimes increase the value of what is being said.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, some social relationships _ the kind supported by
intimate talking _ aren't worth maintaining. Fifty years ago, my
father's working-class London accent would have all but precluded
him from attending Oxford or Cambridge. Today, as a university
administrator, he now regularly exchanges e-mail with his
counterparts at those institutions. I know which world he'd rather
be living in.
</P>
<P>
   _ BRUCE HEADLAM
</P>
<P>
   A Road Map for the Future
</P>
<P>
   `TIPS FOR TIME TRAVELERS: VISIONARY INSIGHTS INTO NEW
TECHNOLOGY, LIFE, AND THE FUTURE ON THE EDGE OF TECHNOLOGY'
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Cochrane (McGraw-Hill, $20).
</P>
<P>
   The future, especially one likely to be strongly shaped by
higher and more baffling technologies, gives rise to apprehension
for many and, for some, downright terror. Yet everyone is, in
effect, a time traveler, plunging into the unknown one day at a
time, moving seamlessly from today to tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Cochrane, a futurist, clearly understands that. Since we
are all embarked on the journey anyway, Cochrane offers in his new
book an easy-to-read map for roads that are beginning to be paved
by current technologies and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Anything but stuffy, ``Tips for Time Travelers'' is a collection
of 108 pithy, well-reasoned and often entertaining essays. None are
longer than two pages. And the quotations, from Walt Disney to
Oscar Wilde, that open each essay are priceless.
</P>
<P>
   Cochrane, who is in charge of research for British
Telecommunications, writes with charm and bite that with all the
high technology available today, he still finds himself stuck in
sluggish lines when he wants to get services or make purchases. The
problem, he says, is the bottleneck created by the dozens of
identification cards we are all saddled with. Wouldn't it be much
better if all that information was stored on a sliver of silicon
and slipped beneath the skin? Unflinchingly, Cochrane says yes.
</P>
<P>
   Cochrane, who began his lifelong fascination with technology
when he was bedridden with a childhood illness at the age of 11,
often reveals his insights coiled in arguments that seem to lean
toward the counterintuitive.
</P>
<P>
   He dismisses high-definition television as nothing more than a
sharper picture. He dreams of a new way to evoke and interact with
images and sounds in a manner as superior to today's televisions
and personal computers as television was to the telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he says improved telecommunications is not going to
stop people from needing and wanting to travel, as some predict.
</P>
<P>
   But his enthusiasm for high technology does not blind him to
some of its disturbing implications. He notes, for instance, that
advancements in telecommunications have melted the traditional
barriers between work and play. ``Work never stops,'' he writes.
``Home life is no longer sacrosanct.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
</TEXT>
