<HEADLINE>
CAMELOT: THE REALM ON LINE
</HEADLINE>
  EDS: Internet addresses at bottom of article.  
(dal) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   King Arthur, in legend the greatest king of Britain's Dark Ages,
has had a lot heaped on his Round Table. However thinly supported
by fact, his story is a wellspring of British pride, a medieval
justification of the monarchy and an epic of Christian symbolism.
It is also an inspiration for just about every video and computer
pastime featuring swords and sorcery.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the world of Arthur on the Internet can
resemble a battle royal, with a whole castleful of serious sites
bravely trying to organize 1,500 years of logic, literature and
popular culture while under siege by cultists, hoaxers, gamesters
and the Monty Pythonized.
</P>
<P>
   If ye be worthy, it would be well to make the Camelot Project of
the University of Rochester your first stop. It has an index for
each lord and lady of Arthur's realm and such symbols as the Siege
Perilous and Excalibur. It is a doorway to huge chunks of
literature _ Middle English to pre-Raphaelite and modern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often tell my students that Arthur is everywhere,'' Alan
Lupack, who teaches the Arthurian tradition at the university and
is curator of the Robbins Library of medieval studies there, wrote
via e-mail. He and his wife, Barbara Tepa Lupack, designed the
Camelot Project as a database of Arthurian texts, images,
bibliographies and basics.
</P>
<P>
   He said that what a publisher would find too costly _ say,
``Historia Brittonum'' by Nennius, the eighth-century Welsh scribe
who set down an account of Arthur's battles 300 years earlier _
occupies only a tiny amount of disk space. The site has hundreds of
texts from scores of authors, from Anonymous to Yeats.
</P>
<P>
   A different main site, the Quest, is maintained by Caliburn, the
University of Idaho's Arthurian Legend Society. It is gorgeously
illustrated, both in its Arthurian Art Gallery and in the texts,
many of which are presented like illuminated manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   Arthurian Resources, a site by Thomas Green of Exeter College at
Oxford, focuses on Welsh literature and is a vast compendium of
Arthur scholarship. It includes his own essays and recent research,
including a current archeology project at Tintagel Castle in
Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
   Although so much is murky in Arthur's realm, John J. Doherty,
compiler of the site Arthurian Resources on the Internet, said
there was no question which Arthurian character is the most
popular: Merlin. ``For some reason, the enchanter actually seems to
engender more interest than Arthur,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You can subscribe to the online or print version of Arthuriana,
the quarterly journal of the International Arthurian Society's
North American branch. Arthuriana maintains a discussion group of
about 1,100 subscribers. ``A recurrent subject is the nature of the
Arthurian women, especially Guenevere and Morgan,'' Professor
Bonnie Wheeler of Southern Methodist University, the editor of
Arthuriana, wrote via e-mail. ``Are they related to fertility
cults, to Celtic goddesses (or gods)? How does their sexual nature
in the Arthurian stories function in the society of Camelot?''
</P>
<P>
   And her opinion about Arthur's existence? ``It is a question to
which there is no definitive answer (except that a sixth-century
British warrior would not have lived in a stone castle),'' she
wrote, ``but people from all walks of life care intensely about the
answer. I've never heard anyone worry about whether Alexander the
Great and Charlemagne were real (who cares?), but a lot of people
want or need a `real' King Arthur.''
</P>
<P>
   CAMELOT PROJECT:
</P>
<P>
   www.lib.rochester.edu/camelot/cphome.stm
</P>
<P>
   THE QUEST:
</P>
<P>
   www.uidaho.edu/student_orgs/arthurian_legend/welcome.html
</P>
<P>
   ARTHURIAN RESOURCES:
www.users.globalnet.co.uk/(tilde)tomgreen/Arthuriana.htm
</P>
<P>
   ARTHURIAN RESOURCES ON THE INTERNET:
</P>
<P>
   jan.ucc.nau.edu/(tilde)jjd23/arthur/
</P>
<P>
   ARTHURIANA:
</P>
<P>
   dc.smu.edu/Arthuriana/
</P>
</TEXT>
