<HEADLINE>
CANCEL THE RED ALERT, IT'S JUST RUDOLPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Uh, Dad, Can I Borrow The Key to the Modem?
</P>
<P>
   While parents continue to buy filtering software for their home
computers, a Dallas entrepreneur has invented a decidedly
lower-tech solution for parents to restrict their children's
surfing. His Netprotector is a lock designed to shut off access to
the modem with the turn of a key.
</P>
<P>
   The lock is connected to a wire that is attached to the modem
card. When the parent turns the key, the rest of the computer
works, but the modem goes mute, said the entrepreneur, Douglas
Horn, president of Dallas-based EZ Solve
(www.companylisting.com/us/national/netprotector), based in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Horn said he was all in favor of parental supervision of
Internet use, but the trouble was that parents had to leave the
house sometimes. ``When parents aren't home, they don't want kids
looking at dirty pictures or wasting time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company promotes the $14.95 lock-and-key device as well
suited to the low-tech skills of many parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``NetProtector is not a software product that computer-savvy
kids can `hack' or that requires users to remember passwords,'' a
company release states.
</P>
<P>
   Next up: a guard dog that barks whenever a child calls up a URL
for the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor Mill Churns Overtime About New Apple Portable
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer has been officially tight-lipped about rumors it
will soon release a new portable computer along the lines of its
translucent bluegreen iMac.
</P>
<P>
   While the company has said it plans one, Steve Jobs, Apple's
interim chief executive, said pointedly last week that no such
portable would be unveiled in January at the MacWorld trade show in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, the story is something else entirely. Internet
sites devoted to following Apple _ and there are some that do so
passionately _ are filled with veritable spec sheets on the new
computer.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely thought that the new machine will be out in the
first quarter of next year, also will have a translucent shell
(perhaps green or even orange), a 300 megahertz or faster
processor, cost less than $1,500, and, like the iMac itself, have
limited expansion capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Among hot topics of debate in the rumor mill is whether the new
computer will qualify as a full-fledged laptop or be more of a
personal digital assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been leaked is that it's more of a cross between a
laptop and a Palm Pilot or Newton,'' said Stan Flack, publisher of
the MacCentral site, www.maccentral.com.
</P>
<P>
   An Apple spokeswoman, Natalie Welch, said the company had little
to say about any new ``consumer portable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people looking at iMac thinking we'll mimic
the industrial design,'' she said. ``At this point, that is just
rumor and speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the source of all the unofficial information? The
keepers of several sites that follow Apple say company sources tend
to loosen their lips when they want to start a consumer buzz for a
new product.
</P>
<P>
   Pumping Up A Palm Pilot By Adding a Real Keyboard
</P>
<P>
   The latest accessory for the handheld Palm Pilot will require
more than one palm to use, and carry.
</P>
<P>
   The accessory is a full-sized keyboard, which includes a docking
station in the center into which the Palm can be plugged. Once the
Palm is plugged in, users of the Go Type! keyboardcan type away on
the Palm as if sitting at an actual laptop, PC or other computer of
self-respecting size.
</P>
<P>
   Made by LandWare, Inc. in Oradell, N.J., the $79.95 keyboard
began shipping to Comp USA and other retailers this week, said
Larry Reich, vice president for marketing for LandWare. Reich said
the keyboard required no batteries or cables, and runs off of the
Palm's own battery supply. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Furby or Just a Facsimile? Some On-Line Goods Are Bad &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On-line buyers beware: a new survey concludes that many Web
sites are hawking counterfeit luxury wares like imitation Gucci
handbags, facsimiles of Furbie, and virtually real Rolexes.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, compiled by Cyveillance, a New York company that
tracks corporate counterfeiters on the Net, found that 10 percent
to 20 percent of sites selling Gucci, Coach, Rolex Beanie Babies
and other big-name stuff, were not selling the real product
advertised. Cyveillance's chairman and chief executive, Brandy
Thomas, compared the problem to buying a watch from a street corner
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is, you see someone selling something in front
of Macy's, you suspect something may be wrong,'' he said. ``On the
Internet, you look at a site, you may not be able to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   He said consumers should look for sites to betray fraudulent
products by including words like ``replica,'' or that suggest
something is in the ``style'' or ``like'' a well-known product. He
said if a deal seems too good to be true, than it's probably time
to move on to a new URL. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trivial in Name Only: 80s Game Coming to the Web  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trivia question: What popular board game has found a new home on
the Internet? Hint: It made its debut in 1982, enjoyed huge sales,
and frequently caused players to bemoan the names of forgotten
state capitals, curse categories like ``Arts &AMP; Entertainment'' and
``People &AMP; Places,'' and sometimes to yank out their own hair
trying to remember some detail from high school science.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that game known as Trivial Pursuit is coming to the Web.
Sony Online Entertainment said it had reached an agreement with
Hasbro Interactive to next year publish an online version on the
Sony game page.
</P>
<P>
   The game's appearance on the Sony site begs a different
question, namely, what is Sony, a movie house/entertainment
company/consumer electronics maker, doing in the online game
business? In an effort to promote its brand name, the Sony site,
www.station.sony.com, offers numerous free games, including online
Jeopardy! and Wheel of Fortune.
</P>
</TEXT>
