<SLUG> BC-VINOLY-DESIGN-ART-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN BY A THOROUGHLY MODERN MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The modernist interior, conceived in midcentury to
exalt the everyday, the mass-produced and the fuss-free, has in
1998 become merely au courant. Plywood stacking chairs and tubular
steel chairs, designed for utility, now peer from the pages of
glossy magazines like so many blase models with nothing to do but
pose.
</P>
<P>
   The high-style status of modernism is putting the once proudly
democratic design movement at odds with young people who just want
to live with it. Lucas Michael, 33, and Roman Vinoly, 28, are
brothers who grew up with modernism. They cut their baby teeth on
the nubby boucle of a Florence Knoll sofa and learned to walk in a
home that was the first in Buenos Aires to bring exposed concrete
indoors, built by their father, Rafael Vinoly, a committed
modernist architect whose career, though begun in Argentina, took
off in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   How to live unpretentiously with vintage objects that are
suddenly objets hit home for the brothers when they started to
renovate their own apartments in downtown Manhattan. What to do?
Hire the designer of one of the modern restaurants du jour? Yes, if
she also happens to be your mother.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Vinoly has been working professionally as an interior
designer for only a few years, but the distinctive look that she
gave Lot 61, a lofty, clubby nightspot and tapas bar in Chelsea,
has brought her to the fore among designers working the industrial
look. Her approach might best be described as tossed-off chic. At
Lot 61, the muscular red rubber armchairs, the restaurant's
signature, were reclaimed by Ms. Vinoly from a mental institution.
</P>
<P>
   For the apartments belonging to two of her sons (there's a
third, but his girlfriend is an architect, so, as Ms. Vinoly said,
``that one I couldn't touch''), the designer drew on the classic
silhouettes of some modern furniture designs _ a testament to
beauty in brevity _ and revived an old standby: the built-in wall
unit. Ms. Vinoly, 59, whose open, pixieish grin belies the
austerity of her downtown-black outfits, managed to reinvigorate
this sturdy motif and show its moods, from avant-garde to placid
but always ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a way that challenges today's curatorial approach, she
helped her sons fill the rooms with the cozy ephemera of daily
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned from my mom that there was nothing wrong with being
different,'' said Michael, a son from her first marriage. In his
East Village apartment, the wall unit is industrial metal, right
out of a hardware storeroom; the perforated-steel-sheet cabinet
doors look as fashionable as his photography monographs. (Similar
wall units show up in the private dining room at Lot 61.) But at
the Gramercy Park home of Vinoly, the shelves are classical _ maple
veneer over plywood. ``It's not really like storage,'' he said.
``It's a piece of furniture I plug into.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael, a photographer, prides himself on having inherited his
mother's eye and her modern tastes. Still, he wasn't interested in
a home awaiting its magazine close-up. ``He's always been way ahead
of the times,'' she said. She noted that he wore clothes with
artistic tears ``way before the Japanese style was in.'' She added,
``I'd say to him, `How can you come in here looking like that?' and
two years later, I'd be buying the same thing at Issey Miyake.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Ms. Vinoly's idea to renovate his apartment. ``I couldn't
stand the way his place looked, like he was still living in a
college dorm,'' she said. ``Besides, I wanted to try out something
tough and modern but not really minimal.'' Maternal instinct
struggled with professional drive. ``He was the perfect guinea
pig.''
</P>
<P>
   In Michael's 700-square-foot pre-World War II apartment with
East Village views of some of the city's earliest public housing,
nothing is minimal except the size. A small living room with an
adjacent galley kitchen leads to a smaller bedroom overlooking the
street. The metal storage unit that hugs the wall between the
living room and the bedroom establishes a steel-gray backdrop
against which Michael's furnishings are arranged. There is some
jostling among the smoky plastic 1956 Eero Saarinen tulip chair,
the Plexiglas side table, the low, Italian-leather sofa and the
1928 tubular-steel armchair by Le Corbusier, Pierre Jeanneret and
Charlotte Perriand, which Ms. Vinoly found at a flea market.
</P>
<P>
   The crowding is welcome, even artful, with orange construction
lamps slung by extension cords on the shelves _ a touch that
Michael suggested and that his mother at first disliked but later
declared to be in sync with her son's more baroque taste. ``We're a
family that really cares about the way things look,'' Ms. Vinoly
said. ``But I do not believe in doing things for visual effect.
Houses should feel like an extension of a personality.''
</P>
<P>
   In a startling confession from a modernist, Ms. Vinoly said that
she still owns an inlaid vase she bought when she was 12. She did
not, however, urge her son to display his own creepy keepsake, a
monk's skull from Tibet. Daily life still leaves its mark on the
design, framed by a small pass-through between the kitchen and the
living room. When piled with the colorful 1940s and '50s bowls and
platters that Michael has collected, a Florence Knoll dining table
takes on the saturated intensity of a Flemish still life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of untidiness, of things accumulated, is what
makes a house,'' Ms. Vinoly said. ``Otherwise it has no feeling, no
sense of history. So many American houses look like chain hotels.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For the bedroom, Ms. Vinoly, who consulted her son on purchases
(he said: ``My budget was tight _ if I said no, she bought it for
me herself''), surprised him with a '60s Goodform orange metal
filing credenza and tossed a purple fur coverlet lined in a
Burberry plaid on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Vinoly's one-bedroom place on Gramercy Park is, at 550
square feet, even smaller than his brother's apartment. Ms. Vinoly
said that Roman, her youngest son, wanted something more
traditional. As a youngster, his favorite book was Jack Finney's
``Time and Again,'' a 1970 novel about a man who travels back to
Victorian-era New York and lives in a Gramercy Park rooming house.
The trick, then, was to convey period coziness with midcentury
furnishings. ``I knew my mother would make it serene,'' said
Vinoly, 28, a recent graduate of film school. ``Her homes have
always been safe havens. Probably she learned how to make things
feel permanent because we moved around a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   His renovation was more a construction project than a decorating
job. The built-ins were not just esthetic, but to contain Vinoly's
film-editing equipment, CD player and piano _ ``so I don't have to
deal with my mother saying no one should have to look at this
mess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vinoly approached the apartment as if it were a boat. (Dad,
the architect, weighed in and suggested that the ceiling be lowered
to just over eight feet to enhance the slightly cloistered
feeling.) In a combined living-dining room and open kitchen, a
small dining table unfolds to seat 10 people. Monumental-size
furniture, Ms. Vinoly contends, actually helps make a room feel
larger.
</P>
<P>
   An open kitchen area is just barely demarcated by a
stainless-steel-top bar. Across from it is a 24-foot wall of
slab-thick wood shelves that appear to radiate from the corner
where Vinoly has his desk. ``Now I can just sit at my desk with the
remotes and control everything,'' Vinoly said. ``The room's a
perfect little ergonomic gem.''
</P>
<P>
   It was selecting a desk chair that went to the heart of their
esthetic differences. She chose a '30s dentist chair on castors
that could have starred in Fritz Lang's ``Metropolis.'' ``It was
fun _ it was everything,'' she said. He wanted something that
worked.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to the bathroom, between the living room and the
bedroom, Ms. Vinoly more fully indulged the romantic side of
modern. She swept all the plumbing to one side and hid it behind
shoji-like sliding doors, creating a hallway between the two rooms.
The walls are lined with inexpensive ceramic tiles that look like
stone. ``I thought they looked kind of cheesy in the samples,''
Vinoly said. Mother won that round, and her son still can't believe
how good they look.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a family that believes in being a little original,''
Ms. Vinoly said. ``My children get ahead of me, but somehow I catch
up, maybe a little faster than most mothers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
