<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN' BOOKS: WHERE'S PETER RABBIT? '
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They left out Peter Rabbit! In arguably the most stylish
children's book of this season of books for the young, ``The 20th
Century Children's Book Treasury,'' an anthology of ``celebrated
picture books and stories to read aloud,'' there's no ``Tale of
Peter Rabbit.'' Which is rather like not having a Faulkner novel on
the list of the 20th century's best books in English.
</P>
<P>
   While others are stuffing stockings, book publishers use
Christmas, Hanukkah and Kwanzaa to cram young heads with what they
hope will become the reading habit. Unlike an adult book, a
children's book's success is measured not only by first sales but
by how often the child returns to it; the more tattered the pages,
the better. Is it a book to be enjoyed by a child while sitting on
a lap? A terrific lap book is a measure in children's publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprisingly, this has been a luminous season for
children's books, most of which haven't been selling too well
recently. So this omission of the great bunny may be the only tiny,
shadowy blip on an otherwise blissful season. There are now three
children's books on The New York Times' hardcover fiction
best-seller list. ``The Treasury'' collection of 44 of the
century's most memorable examples is dawdling just beneath the
list, with about 400,000 copies in print and most of those shipped.
</P>
<P>
   Selling children's books is as much about grandparents and aunts
and uncles (they are the most likely buyers of the higher-priced
books) and teachers as about parents; at least that's the
inferential evidence that publishers work on. Nancy Pines, who is
the publisher of two young-readers divisions for Pocket Books, says
the upturn in sales for children's books means ``the baby boomers
are having babies, and the grandparents are giving stuff to their
grandkids that the parents are reluctant to pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents are important in literacy in yet another way, as
sort of a metaphorical bindery between then and now. Kristina
Peterson, president of the Random House Children's Media Group,
said the ideal was to publish books ``that grandparents loved as
children and gave to their children, who in turn loved them and
gave to their children.''
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of the treasury, Alfred A. Knopf, tried to bag
this ideal in one book, and Janet Schulman, who made the selections
and edited them, said she was ``very torn'' about keeping the
renowned rabbit out of the garden, so to speak, but the tale
``would have taken up too many pages'' of the 308-page book, of
which only two of the selections were slightly abridged, she said,
``even if we condensed the size of the illustrations.'' Anyhow, she
added, ``I'm not worried about Peter Rabbit not being around in the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Beatrix Potter's 1902 classic didn't make it into this
exquisite book, which the publisher hopes will become a collector's
item, the treasury does chronicle the doings of another bunny as
well those of cats, dogs, cows, elephants, bears, toads, ducklings
and about a million fish. And, oh, yes, it includes ``The Story of
Ferdinand'' by Munro Leaf, illustrated by Robert Lawson.
</P>
<P>
   Priced at $40 _ though it's often discounted, as are most
popular books _ it might still be too steep for even the most
doting grandparents. But this was an expensive book to produce
because Knopf had to pay other publishers for the right to reprint
most of the stories and illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Katz, president and publisher of HarperCollins Children's
Books, said that when buying a children's manuscript, ``you are
always thinking about: `Is there a message? One that kids will
really like. Is it fresh, how many times will the kid ask to have
the book read again?''' Having said that, Ms. Katz published this
season's most popular piece of children's literature so far, Jamie
Lee Curtis' ``Today I Feel Silly and Other Moods That Make My
Day,'' a book that many critics said had a title so precisely
accurate that it would not make many school libraries. The other
books on the fiction best-seller list are ``The Night Before
Christmas'' (Putnam) by Clement Moore and ``Harry Potter and the
Sorcerer's Stone'' (Scholastic) by J.K. Rowling, certainly closer
to belles lettres than Ms. Curtis' work.
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins also published the successful and library-popular
``If You Give a Pig a Pancake'' in April as part of what one could
call its ``feed an animal'' series, having previously produced ``If
You Give a Moose a Muffin'' and ``If You Give a Mouse a Cookie,''
an extraordinarily successful sequence written by Laura Numeroff
and illustrated by Felicia Bond.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, some children's books that not only get
beyond animals and feeling silly but also give some edge to the
learning process. The author of one such book is Elizabeth Levy,
who has written about 70 books and has three publishers:
HarperCollins, Scholastic and Hyperion.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Ms. Levy's ``My Life as a Fifth-Grade Comedian'' was
published by HarperCollins to critical acclaim, and this year
Harper Trophy published the paperback version, which is in the
stores for the season. The book is about a boy who is having
trouble in school because he has a sarcastic father and is
therefore sarcastic himself, and so is not too popular and has to
learn the hard way what's truly funny and what's not. ``I love my
connection with children,'' Ms. Levy said. ``I speak to kids a lot,
and I want them to learn something from my books.'' Generally they
do, the critics agree.
</P>
</TEXT>
