<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SUICIDE-ART-2TAKE     12-16 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SUICIDE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS NOW HELPING TO SCREEN FOR TROUBLED TEEN-AGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RITA BEAMISH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a school office cubicle, beneath walls plastered with
hot-line lists, philosophical poems and a poster of a sunflower,
two people sit on hard plastic chairs, a slight 14-year-old girl
shyly pouring out her innermost demons to an earnest young man
she's only just met.
</P>
<P>
   The girl fingers a delicate crucifix around her neck and jiggles
a foot shod in a platform shoe beneath bell-bottom jeans. Her
bashfulness, her bad dreams, her thoughts of suicide _ all are duly
recorded, her small voice barely audible as the interviewer, Jason
Greenburg, methodically asks about anxiety, fears, depression and
phobias.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a third presence here in the basement of Christopher
Columbus High School in the Bronx that commands much of her
attention: the real director of this interview, Greenburg's sleek
laptop computer. Offering only an occasional beep and blink of its
screen, the laptop serves up question after question. Each is based
on information the girl provides as the interview proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Greenburg, a doctoral candidate in psychology, reads the
questions aloud as they pop onto the screen, then records the
girl's yes or no answers.
</P>
<P>
   The interview is part of an exercise designed to prevent suicide
among teen-agers. The girl and some 200 other students at the
school, all of whose names are kept confidential, are undergoing a
computer analysis of their mental health.
</P>
<P>
   The computer program, a project of researchers at Columbia
University College of Physicians and Surgeons, is designed to sniff
out deep-rooted psychiatric troubles that might otherwise go
unnoticed in teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all intents and purposes, it seems to do it just as well as
a psychiatrist,'' said Dr. David Shaffer, director of child and
adolescent psychiatry at Columbia and a principal developer of the
computerized interview.
</P>
<P>
   Shaffer contends that the computer-guided interview is so
specific it can pick up psychiatric problems that psychologists and
counselors might miss.
</P>
<P>
   Other mental health professionals, however, express some
reservations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can compare a computer to an individual
trying to do a diagnosis,'' said Dr. James Masterson, who heads the
Masterson Institute for Psychoanalytic Psychotherapy in Manhattan.
``It's not just the symptoms, it's the patients' affect when
they're talking about it, which I don't think a computer can pick
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaded with 3,000 standardized questions and follow-up
questions, the program offers diagnoses not just for suicidal
tendencies but for more than 30 other psychiatric ailments,
including mood and anxiety disorders, substance abuse problems,
schizophrenia and eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   If a person says he has considered suicide, the
computer-administered test finds out when and by what method. If
the person answers negatively, the questions proceed to other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Touted by Shaffer's team as a time-saver for clinicians _ a
trained layperson can administer it, and a new, self-administered
version using headphones has also been developed _ the disk with
the questions has spread to clinic and school settings as far away
as South Africa and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Some 70 groups are using the program worldwide, Shaffer said.
The Justice Department plans to implement it at some juvenile
facilities. Wall Street magnates are providing philanthropic
backing. And institutions like Boys Town have made it a routine
part of their services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about the way the disk is constructed that
yields better information from kids than other formats,'' said
Patrick Friman, director of clinical services and research at Boys
Town.
</P>
<P>
   The computer interview, administered upon admission to Boys
Town, a 550-student center in Nebraska, has been good at picking up
cases involving two or more conditions, common in Boys Town youth
but difficult to diagnose, Friman said.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely anticipated version of the test is the audio
version, which uses headphones to bypass literacy demands or the
need for a person to read the questions, said Dr. Chris Lucas, a
member of Shaffer's team. It will make its debut at two schools in
New York early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia program is rooted in research showing that suicidal
proclivities increase as teen-agers move into young adulthood,
Lucas said. Though rare, suicide is the second most common cause of
death among teen-agers, after auto accidents. Nationally, some
2,000 youths between the ages of 15 and 19 take their lives each
year. Seventeen did so in New York City in 1996, the most recent
year for which the city has data.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years alone, 110 public high school juniors and
seniors in New York attempted suicide on school property, according
to school board data.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``What you really want to screen for are clusters of risk which
kids may carry,'' said Eve Moscicki, a suicide expert at the
preventive interventions unit of the National Institute for Mental
Health. ``Suicide doesn't just strike people out of the blue. It's
always embedded in deep troubles. It can be very profound
depression that's accompanied by hopelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   At Columbus High on this fall day, the printer spits out
diagnoses one after another as students go through their
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The monotonous questions ricochet around the cubicles. Do you
get stomach aches in the morning before school? Have you had
uncontrollable attacks of feeling afraid or strange? Do thoughts
come to your mind that you can't get rid of? In the last year, was
there a time when you thought seriously about killing yourself?
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers say they hear voices. They're withdrawn. They've
wanted to die. Some have tried to kill themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Those flagged by the computer then talk to a psychologist, who
makes a diagnosis. Out of the first five dozen interviewed,
identified by a preliminary questionnaire as being the most
troubled, the psychologist referred half for professional help.
Their parents were offered clinical help through Columbia, a
service financed by a foundation grant.
</P>
<P>
   One petite girl who said she had previously attempted suicide
emerged from her interview in tears. She wanted help but didn't
want her parents to know about her depression. Kathleen Cigich, the
screening coordinator, calmed her down, agreed not to divulge her
suicide attempt and, with a Spanish-speaking interpreter, later won
the parents' support for therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia team will visit three other Bronx high schools by
the end of the school year, screening about 200 students at each.
</P>
<P>
   The principal of Columbus High, Gerald Garfin, who has a student
body of 3,500, said he had jumped at the chance when the
coordinator of the screening program, Leslie Craft, had offered its
services to Bronx principals. ``If this helps one kid see himself
or herself through a crisis, that's all I care about,'' Garfin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is receptive. The parents of one Columbus High
student found to be at high risk refused to enroll her in therapy.
The girl, apparently under pressure from her parents, recanted the
responses that had concerned the Columbia team. ``Is she OK?''
Garfin said. ``I'll never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer screening is based on the Diagnostic Interview
Schedule for Children, which began as a lengthy, standardized
questionnaire on paper and was financed by a federal mental health
grant 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Can the computer replace the psychiatrist? ``At the moment, we
really don't want to say that this can replace the clinician,''
Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mina Dulcan, head of child psychiatry for Children's
Memorial Hospital in Chicago, said that whatever its limitations,
the computer test could identify teen-agers in need of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the computer may sometimes be too prone to suspect a
problem, as in the case of Greenburg's 14-year-old subject. She was
tagged as agoraphobic, but a psychologist who then spoke with her
found that she did not need professional help. On the other hand,
research has found that the computer rarely gives a clean bill of
health to anyone who is severely troubled.
</P>
<P>
   William Ruane, an investment adviser who heads the Sequoia Fund,
has become an important benefactor of the diagnostic project. He
has donated some $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come is a telephone version of the interview. And
despite the cautionary views of some clinicians, Shaffer hopes to
see the interactive interview go on line one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you can train people to find out what's wrong with
themselves in a sophisticated way, the better off you are,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
