<HEADLINE>
REP. GILMAN, UNCOMMITTED ON IMPEACHMENT, LISTENS TO CONSTITUENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., who is uncommitted on
whether to impeach President Clinton, did what he often does before
momentous votes: He sounded out the constituents of his district,
which stretches from Westchester County to the Catskill Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, 76, a Republican moderate who is chairs the House
International Relations Committee, started early Wednesday from his
home in Greenville, N.Y. and hit diners and a bus station packed
with New York City-bound commuters to hear how he should vote.
</P>
<P>
   He is a self-styled ``Rockefeller'' Republican in the tradition
of Nelson Rockefeller, New York governor from 1959 to 1973 and U.S.
vice president from 1974 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Gilman say the 25-year House veteran ultimately
will vote his conscience. ``Ben is a very independent-minded person
and he may not make up his mind until the last minute,'' said John
Hicks, GOP chairman in Orange County, N.Y. ``He's not premature in
his judgment in most cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks and other local Republican leaders are counseling a
pro-impeachment vote. But Gilman is also getting opposing advice. A
bus of 50 or more local anti-impeachment Democrats and some
Republicans is scheduled to descend on Washington Thursday to lobby
the congressman in his Capitol Hill office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message to Ben Gilman is: You're in Congress for 25 years.
You don't have to be bullied by the (Republican) leadership,'' said
Paul Adler, Democratic chairman in Rockland County, who is
organizing the bus trip.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment vote is shaping up at a dicey time, now that
U.S. warplanes have launched air strikes on Iraq over its refusal
to grant U.N. inspectors full access to suspected
weapons-production sites.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman is sensitive to the impact of impeachment on America's
image and interests overseas and to the perception among some
Republican House leaders that reality might be imitating the recent
movie ``Wag the Dog,'' a farce in which image-meisters conjure up a
war to deflect public attention from a White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But neither consideration will have any bearing on Gilman's
impeachment vote, said a senior aide, who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman's Washington office has logged 2,000 impeachment-related
calls since Monday, according to his press secretary, Andrew
Zarutskie. The callers have been split about 50-50 on impeachment,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman followed the tally Wednesday by stopping at his district
offices in Middletown and Monsey, N.Y. to talk on the phone with
his Washington staffers and review what constituents have told
them.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman's 20th congressional district runs from Westchester
through Rockland and Orange Counties into Sullivan County, home of
a dwindling number of Catskill Mountain ``borscht belt'' resorts as
well as the site of the legendary 1969 Woodstock music festival.
</P>
<P>
   It is a region in transition from hamlets of farm homes and
summer cottages to bedroom communities sprawling outward from New
York City. Many newcomers are Democrats who are altering the
politics of the traditionally Republican-leaning district. Voter
registration is now 2-1 Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Reda, GOP chairman in Rockland County, said he assumes
Gilman is ``getting pressure from Democrats.'' Reda said that last
week the county Republican organization's executive committee
approved a resolution supporting impeachment and forwarded it to
Gilman.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Gilman has not returned his phone calls, Reda said.
``I'd like to think he'd come around'' to favoring impeachment,
Reda said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
