<HEADLINE>
HOME REPAIR COLUMN: MAKING THE RIGHT CHOICES WHEN BUYING LUMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Homeowners who do their own home repairs need to buy lumber at
the local lumber yard. Do-it-yourselfers, however, are often
confused by the terms used to classify wood and they are unsure
what to look for when picking out boards.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they know that a common wall stud is called a two
by four _ meaning it is two inches thick by four inches wide _ but
careful measurement shows that it is not that wide nor that thick.
Actually the stud is cut to a full two inches by four inches at the
saw mill, but then it is dressed (planed) and dried. This reduces
the thickness and width by 1/2 inch. The 2 by 4 specification is
the nominal size, that is the size by name only. The actual size is
the final dimension of the dressed piece.
</P>
<P>
   Wood sold in nominal sizes is called dimensional lumber. Most
lumber yards stock dimensional lumber in seven standard sizes: 2 by
2, 2 by 4, 2 by 6, 2 by 8, 2 by 10, 2 by 12, 4 by 4. The
accompanying diagram shows how the actual size differs from the
nominal size. It is important to keep in mind that the length of
the board is always actual size. If, for example, you buy a 2 by 4
that is 10 feet long, it will actually be 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have determined the size of the lumber that you need,
you can proceed to pick out the best boards. Obviously, you want
pieces that are relatively flawless, but almost all the boards will
have some imperfections. The trick then is to choose boards with
defects that you can work around so they will not affect your
project.
</P>
<P>
   With dimensional lumber there are two categories of flaws: those
that distort the shape of the board, and those that compromise the
strength of the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Crooks, bows, cupping and twists are defects that affect the
shape, and therefore the straightness, of the board. Before buying
any board, sight down the edge to see how straight it is. Boards
with crooks, bows, or twists are still usable provided the
deformity is not too extreme. Do not, however, use them in corners
or around door or window openings.
</P>
<P>
   A crook is a curve along the edge of the board. You can use
pieces with a slight crook for framing, provided the bow on all the
boards faces out the same way. A bow is a longitudinal curve along
the face of the board. Studs with a bow of less than a 1/2 inch are
acceptable for walls because you can usually push them straight
when you install the wallboard.
</P>
<P>
   Cupping, or ``warp,'' is a dished effect created by the edges
curving up from the center. Avoid using cupped boards for decking
because they create an uneven surface. If you must use a cupped
piece as a floor or deck board, position it with the rounded center
up and the curved edges down.
</P>
<P>
   A twist is spiral distortion along the length of the board with
the ends no longer in line. Boards with a slight twist, less than
20 degrees, can be used in framing because the twist can be
straightened and then held in place with nails.
</P>
<P>
   Knots, splits, shakes and wanes are defects in the wood fibers
and they can compromise the strength of the board. Knots are the
circular plugs that result from a branch growing off the trunk.
Small, tight knots in the center of a board are tolerable, but
large, loose knots near the edges can weaken the board.
</P>
<P>
   Splits are cracks that run through the length of the board.
Short splits usually develop near the end of the board as the wood
dries out. If the board is long enough, you can cut these away.
Avoid using any board for framing if it has long splits extending
into the center area.
</P>
<P>
   Shakes look like cracks, but they are actually hollows between
the growth rings. A few short shakes here and there are not a
problem, but avoid using any board for joists or rafters if it has
shakes running more than half its length.
</P>
<P>
   A wane is a length of bark that adheres to the edge of the
board. Wanes are more like surface blemishes rather that structural
defects so they are generally not a problem. They do, however,
reduce the nailing surface on the edge of the board. This can be a
problem if you need to attach wallboard to the stud.
</P>
<P>
   If you are able to buy boards that are reasonably straight, it
doesn't mean that they will remain that way. They can warp or twist
if stored improperly. Stack the boards in an unheated environment,
like a garage or shed, but not out of doors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
