<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Dec. 17, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weather pattern across North America will continue to shift
Thursday as an enlarging area of frigid air over Alaska and western
Canada begins to effect more of the continent. While dry conditions
will prevail, colder air crossing the Great Lakes will finally
induce more widespread snow showers and squalls.
</P>
<P>
   The snow drought across the interior Northeast will end as low
pressure developing in southern New England spreads light to
moderate snow from the northern Catskills to the White Mountains.
Patches of rain will dampen southeast New England. A strengthening
flow from the northwest will contribute to numerous snow showers
from Michigan to central New York. Some sections will receive their
first measurable snow of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Middle Atlantic and Southeast States will stay dry, but turn
brisk and cooler. A large high pressure system crested over the
central Rockies will influence the weather over much of the West
and Plains. Gusty winds from the west will descend the east slopes
of the Rockies causing the air to become much warmer. Record
maximums are expected from eastern Montana to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   An intensifying disturbance near Regina in southern Canada will
push the milder air in the western Plains over a very cold air mass
in the Middle West. The result will be light snow, mainly around
the Red River of the North. An extremely cold air mass will be
poised along the border with Canada, but it should not surge
southward until Friday. The Southwest will notice more high clouds,
but it will remain warm.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Unnatural Snow
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, an unnatural snow dusted the ground in an
industrial valley south of Charleston, W.Va. It had been a clear,
calm December night. The ground cooled rapidly below freezing as
radiation was lost to space, but at 3,000 feet aloft the
temperature held nearly steady. The layer of warmth above the
chilling ground acted as a lid that trapped tiny particles and
moisture which was belching from smokestacks in the valley. The
pollution particles acted as sites that collected moisture and ice
crystals began to grow in the air. Eventually, a fine snow fell
forcing crews to salt the roads.
</P>
</TEXT>
