<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: MASTERPIECE GETS NEW HOME; TANGLEWOOD NEWS; TOP
HOLIDAY SONGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Great Britain, Israel, Italy)   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lost for 320 years and rediscovered in Britain in 1995, Nicolas
Poussin's 1626 masterpiece, ``The Destruction and Sack of the
Temple of Jerusalem,'' is headed for a new home: the Israel Museum
in Jerusalem. The museum announced the acquisition Wednesday,
saying it was made possible by a grant from Yad Hanadiv, the
Rothschild Foundation in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The painting will be at the Palazzo delle Esposizioni in Rome
through March before going to the National Gallery in London.
Commissioned in 1625 by Cardinal Francesco Barberini, the painting
eventually vanished, before emerging in 1995 from the estate of
Ernest Onians, a British collector. It will be installed in the
Israel Museum in May.
</P>
<P>
   Calendar Check
</P>
<P>
   For those who dream of summer at the advent of winter, here is
news of coming events at Tanglewood in Lenox, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 season of the Tanglewood Music Center, Tanglewood's
training academy, will feature a residency, from July 27 through
Aug. 8, by Claudio Abbado and the Gustav Mahler Youth Orchestra. At
the Leonard Bernstein Memorial Concert on July 27, the Mahler
Orchestra and Seiji Ozawa's Boston Symphony Orchestra will join in
a performance of Bartok's ``Miraculous Mandarin'' and Strauss'
``Don Quixote,'' with the cellist Yo-Yo Ma and the violist Yuri
Bashmet as guest soloists.
</P>
<P>
   The Music Center's season will also include a fully staged
production of Puccini's ``Gianni Schicchi,'' led by Robert Spano in
his first summer in charge of the center's conducting program. The
composer and conductor Tan Dun will direct the center's 1999
Festival of Contemporary Music.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Quiz
</P>
<P>
   What are the top holiday season songs? According to Marilyn
Bergman, president and chairman of ASCAP, the American Society of
Composers, Authors and Publishers, the most performed songs are led
by ``White Christmas,'' by Irving Berlin. Next in order are ``Santa
Claus Is Comin' to Town,'' by J. Fred Coots and Haven Gillespie;
``The Christmas Song (Chestnuts Roasting on an Open Fire),'' by Mel
Torme and Robert Wells; ``Winter Wonderland,'' by Felix Bernard and
Richard Smith, and ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer,'' by Johnny
Marks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top 25, ``Santa Claus Is Comin' to Town'' and ``Winter
Wonderland'' are the oldest, dating from 1934. The most recorded
song is ``White Christmas,'' with more than 500 versions in dozens
of languages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
