<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BABSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID L. BABSON, 87; `REAL PIONEER IN EQUITY INVESTING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David L. Babson, an influential investment counselor once
described in Forbes magazine as ``a prophet with honor. . . and
profits,'' died Monday in his home in Lyndeborough, N.H. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Babson was the founder of David L. Babson &AMP; Co., an
investment counseling firm that was handling about $3 billion in
private investments when he retired in 1978. He was known for his
yankee work ethic as well as his remarkable record of
prognostications.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, when President Kennedy banned any rise in steel prices,
and glamour stocks such as IBM and Xerox lost value in the market,
Mr. Babson told his followers they were in the middle of a major
buying opportunity. . . and he was right. In February 1968, in the
midst of a conglomerate craze, he put out a warning that the end of
the bull market was in sight. . . and he was right. When the market
bottomed out in May 1970, he saw a historic chance to purchase
quality stocks at rock-bottom prices. . . and he was right again.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Brad Perry, who succeeded Mr. Babson as president of
David L. Babson &AMP; Co., described him as a ``real pioneer in equity
investing who really developed the modern concept of growth stock
investing.'' He explained that prior to Mr. Babson's innovations,
most people invested in stocks for their dividends and were
primarily concerned with the preservation of capital, not with
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 1, 1974, issue of Forbes magazine decribed Mr. Babson
as a ``prophet with honor. . . and profits.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Gloucester, Mass., he grew up on the family dairy
farm and delivered milk as a boy. In a profile published in the
September 1973 issue of Money magazine, he recalled hurrying home
from Harvard College one summer elated over some particularly good
grades. Spotting his father digging in the vegetable garden, he
trotted out to him and reported the good news. His father, a
veterinarian as well as a dairyman, listened with approval, then he
said, ``That's fine, son, but you've been home 10 minutes now, and
you still don't have your overalls on.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Harvard in 1932, he went to work for his
cousin, Roger W. Babson, at Babson Reports, where he became a vice
president and director when he was 26 years old. He founded David
L. Babson &AMP; Co. in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Babson worked in the radiation laboratory at Massachusetts
Institute of Technology during World War II while operating his
investment firm on nights and weekends.
</P>
<P>
   A practical, unassuming man, he was known to wear khakis and
hunting boots to the office, and commuted to work in an
unpretentious Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said, ``He had all the good characteristics of a Yankee.
He was sensible, hard working, forthright, and frugal.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a town meeting member in Wellesley, Mass. for more than
40 years and the chairman of the town's veterans housing authority
and its board of public works. He was a member of the finance
committees of the New Hampshire Charitable trust and Monadnock
Hospital in Peterborough, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves a son, David L. Jr. of Ossipee, N.H.; two daughters,
Susan Babson Young of Sheffield, Mass. and Katherine L. Jr. of
Wellesley; six grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
