<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-MUSEUM-567-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A OP CURATOR IS LEAVING THE WHITNEY FOR SOHO POST
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lisa Phillips, the curator of contemporary art at the
Whitney Museum of American Art, is leaving the institution after 23
years to become director of the New Museum of Contemporary Art in
SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips is the fourth top curator to resign from the
Whitney since Maxwell L. Anderson took over the museum as director
in September. The museum's associate director for public programs,
Constance Wolf, announced her departure from the Whitney earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the curators resigned after their positions were
diminished in a staff reorganization, but Anderson said Ms.
Phillips' move took him by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspected that at some point Lisa would find a new challenge
irresistible,'' he said. ``It made my decision to put her at the
helm of contemporary art justified. My first question was could her
mind be changed, and she said no, that this has been something she
had hoped for for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of unfilled curators' jobs ``gives me an amazing
amount of latitude to think about the future of the Whitney,''
Anderson added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips will succeed Marcia Tucker, the New Museum's
founding director. During her years at the Whitney, Ms. Phillips
organized such broad thematic exhibitions as ``Beat Culture and the
New America: 1950-1965'' and ``Image World: Art and Media
Culture.'' She also was involved in every Biennial exhibition from
1985 to 1993. In 1997 she was the Biennial's curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity,'' said Ms. Phillips. ``The New
Museum has tremendous integrity in its commitment to contemporary
art, which is something I want to explore and expand on.
Contemporary art and culture is my principal love.'' She said she
had begun her discussions with the New Museum months before
Anderson's arrival, and described the new job as ``a perfect fit.''
</P>
<P>
   With her appointment, a bit of New York museum history comes
full circle. Before Ms. Tucker founded the new museum in 1977, she
worked at the Whitney as curator of contemporary art, resigning
shortly after the arrival of Thomas N. Armstrong 3d.
</P>
<P>
   At the time she said she left partly because she found the
museum too focused on the mainstream and unresponsive to new
developments in contemporary art. The mainstream has tended to be
Ms. Phillips' specialty with the organization of survey shows of
mid-career artists like Cindy Sherman, Richard Prince and Terry
Winters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the New Museum has moved closer to the mainstream.
What began as a tiny institution in an office on Hudson Street
founded to promote innovative, cutting edge art has grown
significantly. In the process it has moved several times, from
Hudson Street to space at the Graduate Center of the New School for
Social Research to its current site on Broadway in SoHo in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In March it unveiled a renovated and expanded building that is
now 33,000 square feet with more than double the previous program
space and a new bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Saul Dennison, president of the New Museum's board, said of Ms.
Phillips, ``She really has a feeling for contemporary art, likes
artists, knows artists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
