   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-AIRSTRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton ordered
airstrikes against Saddam Hussein Wednesday. The strikes were
expected to target the weapons stockpiles, strategic military
facilities and the communications systems through which Baghdad
controls the country. Coming on the eve of a Congressional
impeachment vote against Clinton, the precarious timing of the
attack was not lost on Congressional critics _ damaging chances for
bipartisan support. However, observers noted that the situation
follows months of conflict between Clinton and Saddam. White House
officials said the attack would likely continue on Thursday and
perhaps longer. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   US-IRAQ _ WASHINGTON _ The question: Is this wagging the dog? An
attack late Wednesday on Iraq caps off a year of living dangerously
for President Clinton and Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein, who have
been locked for the past 12 months in a perilous game of
brinkmanship that has framed one of Clinton's most enduring foreign
policy dilemmas. The high stakes drama is being played out against
the background of an unseemly sex and deception scandal at the
White House, prompting Republican Congressional critics to charge
Clinton with trumping up a military strike to divert public
attention from his personal travails. ANALYSIS. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   US-MILITARY _ WASHINGTON _ A Pentagon-oriented nuts and bolts
look at the possible strike. Developing. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service).
</P>
