<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABUSE-DEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY'S DEATH OPENS KANSAS AGENCY TO CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COUNCIL GROVE, Kan. _ When Timmy Post's grandmother saw marks of
a beating on the toddler this fall, she called the Kansas
Department of Social and Rehabilitation Services.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers examined Timmy on Sept. 23 and photographed his
bruises. They concluded that Scotty Adam, 24, the boyfriend of
Timmy's mother, had physically abused the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Social and Rehabilitation Services officials say Adam cried and
showed remorse when they showed him the photographs, and he
promised to stop the abuse. Social workers then had Adam sign a
pledge that he would never harm the boy again.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine days later, Timmy was dead. Adam is accused of
killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Timmy's death has unleashed a torrent of criticism against the
state welfare agency over its methods of determining when children
stay in homes, its communications with law-enforcement officials _
even its processes for checking the backgrounds of its social
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials say child welfare workers did their best to
protect Timmy, but the state will re-examine a policy that aims to
keep children and parents together whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who treated Timmy at Wesley Medical Center in Wichita
said the 16-month-old had been shaken so hard that his brain had
swelled and his retinas had hemorrhaged. He had also been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys say Adam is not guilty in Timmy's death. On
Dec. 2, a Morris County judge ruled that there was sufficient
evidence to try Adam on charges of felony first-degree murder and
child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, we shouldn't have believed Mr. Adam,'' said
Roberta Sue McKenna, an attorney with the agency's legal
department.
</P>
<P>
   State officials generally don't discuss details of child welfare
investigations. But because of criticism from legislators and child
advocates, McKenna agreed to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   The ``family safety plan'' Adam signed is designed to keep
families intact and children in their homes, she said. But the
department will soon explore whether that policy is flawed and
needs to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say social workers, based on the earlier abuse, should
have removed either Adam _ or Timmy and his two sisters _ from the
house where they all lived with the children's mother in Council
Grove.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Sept. 23 abuse, Frederick Ramirez, the social
worker assigned to Timmy's family, had written a letter to the
Morris County attorney, asking that a ``child in need of care''
petition be filed to give the local court jurisdiction over the
children.
</P>
<P>
   That Sept. 3 letter, a copy of which was obtained by /{The
Kansas City Star/}, cited an apparent ``alcohol problem'' in the
home and said Adam was recovering from an alcohol-related car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez wrote that Timmy's mother, Jessica McAuley Post, was
spending so much time helping Adam recover that she was putting her
children's needs second. He also wrote that Timmy's mother had not
cooperated with his suggestion that Adam reside elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there have been no reports of abuse or neglect
received at this office, the alcohol//drug behavior does concern
me,'' Ramirez wrote in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   With others at the agency, Ramirez later investigated the Sept.
23 abuse. He was the one who confronted Adam with the photos and
told him to sign the family safety plan.
</P>
<P>
   Agency spokesman John Garlinger said it was Ramirez's
recommendation to resolve the abuse investigation that way, but
other people in the agency were consulted. Investigators at the
agency, he said, never make such decisions on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez left the state agency after Timmy died and could not be
reached for comment. His Topeka phone number has been disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Post and everyone else who testified at the preliminary hearing
are under a gag order not to discuss the case.  &LR; brk:Past conviction
 &LR; tx:Critics say that in trying to protect Timmy, social workers
should have looked deeper into Adam's background. Then they might
have learned that Adam had been convicted in the stabbing death of
a Kansas State University student and had spent three years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should not have been an effort to keep this family
together,'' said Rene Netherton, a Topeka lawyer and frequent
critic of the state agency.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege that Timmy suffered fatal injuries Oct. 21,
after his mother went out to mow yards and left the children in
Adam's care.
</P>
<P>
   Timmy died the next day in the Wichita hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At a preliminary hearing earlier this month, Adam's attorneys
tried to show that Timmy's death could have been caused by falls
that took place several days earlier. But doctors said the injuries
occurred that day, probably within hours of Timmy's arrival at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A KBI investigator testified that Adam told him he had treated
Timmy roughly that day and and had thrown him like a ``sack of
potatoes'' into a crib.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Phyllis Gilmore of Johnson County said Timmy's death
exposed flaws in the Social and Rehabilitation Services system.
</P>
<P>
   If an abused child is put back in the home, ``social workers
need to be held accountable for that decision,'' said Gilmore, who
has taken an interest in the child-welfare system. ``As long as we
allow them to hide within the `system,' the tragedies will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Arnold, executive director of Best Interest of the Child
Inc., an Overland Park-based advocacy group seeking reform of
Social and Rehabilitation Services, said statistics show that in 50
percent of fatal abuse cases, the child had been removed from the
home and returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making someone sign a promise they won't beat a child is not
enough,'' Arnold said. ``We can't put these kids back in there
based on a written promise and say, `Gee, I hope this works.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Brunk, executive director of Kansas Action for
Children, said tragedies such as Timmy's sometimes lead advocates
to jump to conclusions that there are deep flaws in the
child-welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what I know about the case, I'm not sure I wouldn't
have done the same thing as the social worker at that time,'' Brunk
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brunk acknowledges that the state agency could be faulted
for not doing more to protect Timmy.
</P>
<P>
   Adam was convicted in 1993 of second-degree murder in the
K-State student's stabbing death. The conviction was later
overturned on a technicality, and a jury convicted him of the
lesser charge of involuntary manslaughter in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An agency spokesman said child-welfare investigators do not
routinely look at the criminal record of everyone involved with the
child when investigating abuse cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do a KBI (Kansas Bureau of Investigation) check on
every boyfriend who lives in a house,'' said Garlinger.
</P>
<P>
   And whenever possible, he said, children are kept in homes with
their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming that children are safe _ and that is job one for this
agency _ there is no doubt in our minds that a child's home is the
best place for a child to be,'' Garlinger said. ``The state is a
poor parent. ''  &LR; brk:Calls usually correct  &LR; tx:Social workers make
judgment calls every day about what is in the best interest of a
child, Garlinger said. Those decisions are often criticized _ they
took the child too quickly...they left the the child in the home
too long.
</P>
<P>
   But the correct call is made most of the time, Garlinger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that means anything right now because Timmy Post is
dead,'' Garlinger said.
</P>
<P>
   But Timmy is dead, he said, because he was abused _ not because
of lack of effort by social workers.
</P>
<P>
   The agency initially tried to deflect some of the criticism by
pointing out that Morris County Attorney Matt Oleen had declined to
file the ``child in need of care'' petition, which could have
removed Timmy from the home.
</P>
<P>
   Oleen said he had declined because the Sept. 3 letter said there
had been no reports of abuse or neglect.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna said that a follow-up report was sent to Oleen after the
confirmed abuse on Sept. 23 and that a copy of the report is in the
case file. That report, obtained by /{The Star/}, says Adam
admitted the abuse. It made no recommendation that the children be
removed.
</P>
<P>
   But Garlinger said Tuesday that the agency could not confirm
that the report was received by Oleen's office in Council Grove.
Oleen said he never received the report, and voiced frustration
that he was not made aware of the additional information.
</P>
<P>
   Social and Rehabilitation Services officials now have backed off
from any criticism of Oleen.
</P>
<P>
   Netherton thinks the agency is making excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once SRS gets involved in a child-abuse case, they have the
obligation to see that that child is protected,'' Netherton said.
``If those social workers had learned the facts about Mr. Adam,
they should have removed those children from that home.''
</P>
<P>
   Netherton is also highly critical of the agency for having had
Ramirez working as a social worker.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez was convicted in May of domestic battery in an incident
involving his wife. A judge sentenced him to six months in jail but
suspended the sentence and placed Ramirez on 12 months' probation
and ordered him to attend anger-control counseling sessions.
</P>
<P>
   He was also found guilty in 1997 of assaulting a law enforcement
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez had been with the agency four years when he left. Agency
officials said he was an excellent employee and was not fired.
</P>
<P>
   Garlinger at first said it was against agency policy for a
social worker with such a background to remain with the agency. He
said later, however, that Ramirez had informed supervisors about
his troubles and that the disclosure enabled him to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has no policy that would prohibit a person with
Ramirez's convictions from keeping his job, Garlinger said.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna said: ``Clearly, reasonable people could suggest that
his (Ramirez) judgment was impaired. It's reasonable to question
how much his personal life affected his work.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore said agency supervisors made the wrong decision in
allowing Ramirez to continue in his job.
</P>
<P>
   Adam is in the Morris County Jail awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Timmy's sisters, ages 2 and 3, were put in foster care after
Timmy's death.
</P>
</TEXT>
