<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S SURVIVAL SKILLS FACE EXTREMELY HARSH TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Apologies haven't worked, legal arguments haven't
worked, managing diplomacy on the global stage hasn't worked.
</P>
<P>
   His bottomless pool of personal charisma might as well be empty,
and his high-flying public approval ratings are proving to be cold
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   For Bill Clinton, the political walls are closing in. By the
weekend, short of a dramatic and successful political Hail Mary, he
will be only the second president in more than 200 years to face an
impeachment vote in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Why has a president who has constantly rewritten the book on
political survival been unable to save himself when it matters
most?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a terrible bind,'' said Will Marshall, an official
with the centrist Democratic Leadership Council, a longtime Clinton
supporter. ``He wants to express contrition, but he can't simply
admit to a felony that then gives everybody a reason to vote for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got him over this barrel, and they are exploiting that
to the fullest. He can't give them what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCurry, Clinton's former press secretary and spokesman
throughout much of this year's scandal, agreed that the constraints
of his legal situation have tripped up his usual surefootedness.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the president has been able to charm votes from
reluctant congressmen and turn Republican strengths into Democratic
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   But this scandal ``is not conducive to that type of political
smooze,'' McCurry said. ``It is a world of fine lines and tortured
phrases. It sort of negates his ability to find a common
vocabulary. It is frustrating. In his mind, he has always separated
the personal from the performance of his official duties. In this
matter, all of that has been woven together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself is a complex patchwork. He went from a rural
backwater to the halls of Yale and Oxford, from the statehouse of a
small Southern state to the White House. With his ``aw shucks''
over-the-fence-manner, he has an ability to make everyone in a
crowd feel as if he is speaking directly to them. Wrapped in his
slight Arkansas twang, words disarm and ingratiate, and set people
at ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the bean fields and the river bottoms, and when I
came into town, I felt like I was home,'' he told an outdoor rally
in Cairo, Ill. one evening during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, he was discussing the intricacies of welfare
reform with a receptive roomful of corporate titans and Wall Street
investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for someone whose verbal gifts and political acumen is
praised by friends and enemies alike, Clinton has seemed
``peculiarly tone-deaf'' in this scandal, according to former aide
George Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always seems to say exactly the wrong thing,''
Stephanopoulos said on ABC Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   It began last January. With the scandal less than 2 weeks old,
when he had chance to take his hits early and move on, he
completely denied his affair with Monica Lewinsky. His face red,
his finger wagging, the president said in a news clip that will
forever haunt him, ``I want you to listen to me. I'm going to say
this again. I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky. These allegations are false.''
</P>
<P>
   But his nationally televised apology in August, seven months
later, following several hours of grand jury testimony, didn't
satisfy his critics. He sounded petulant, they said. Neither did a
second, more expansive speech a few weeks later while he was on
vacation, nor a third attempt at the annual White House prayer
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   His latest effort came last Friday just minutes before the House
Judiciary Committee approved its first article of impeachment
against him for allegedly lying before the grand jury about his
relationship with the former White House intern. Looking chastened
and weary, the president said, ``I am profoundly sorry for all that
I have done wrong in words and deed. I should never have misled the
country, the Congress, my friends or my family. Quite simply, I
gave in to my shame.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city where words are dissected and scrutinized like a
laboratory rat, that didn't measure up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you were a kid chasing a flashlight,'' said
Kiki Moore, a Democratic consultant and former Clinton campaign
aide. ``You don't have any control and there's no rationale to
predict where it's going to go next. The man said he said he was
sorry. What's he supposed to do?''
</P>
<P>
   But for all of his apologies, opponents question his sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, he really is not sorry for anything that he
did,'' said former Republican congressman Robert Walker, a close
adviser to outgoing House Speaker Newt Gingrich. ``It can be said
he's sorry for getting caught. The fact is he doesn't believe what
most of the rest of the political establishment on Capitol Hill has
come to believe: that he lied and committed perjury. Until the Hill
hears something where he acknowledges the wrong that he's done,
until he does have some remorse, the situation is going to be very
difficult to come up with a message that works.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker hit the core of Clinton's dilemma. Though he's satisfied
the public _ one White House aide even argued that the president's
rhetorical and political skills were as strong as ever, evidenced
by the public's decision long ago to side with him _ he never
struck the proper chord with the audience that truly counted, the
capital's political class. Indeed, events over the past week have
borne that out.
</P>
<P>
   Polls continue to show that the public opposes impeachment and
supports censure. But the Judiciary Committee approved articles of
impeachment anyway _ on a partisan basis _ and the House Republican
leadership so far is refusing to allow censure as an option when
the issue comes to the House floor Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton now faces a dwindling pool of Republicans in Congress
who might buck their leadership's strong behind-the-scenes efforts
to encourage them to vote according to party dictates. Few
Republicans, and not a lot of Democrats either, trust the White
House because of past instances where they felt they were
politically burned or betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   And long-time friends and supporters also feel a sense of
frustration at the president's _ and their own _ inability to make
a breakthrough because, in the end, his predicament is of his own
making.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee member Gary LaPaille, a supporter
since 1990 who named his second son after the president, said, ``At
the beginning, we kind of felt, `God, why did you do something like
this? Your record was great, the economy was great, you were
charismatic. Why did you let your guard down?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now they're left to hope that Bill Clinton's strong imperative
toward political survival, which has trumped any number of personal
and philosophical roadblocks, will somehow, even at this late date,
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should follow his own instincts and his own
conscience,'' Democratic Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, a
longtime ally, said Tuesday outside the White House. ``This is an
unprecedented moment. But this president been through an awful lot
in his life and he seems to always find reserves of strength. So he
is going to be tested in the next few days. This is a serious
moment, and potentially a destructive moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
