<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3411 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-IMPEACHMENT-HNS &LR;      12-16 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS ATTACK ON IRAQ ON EVE OF IMPEACHMENT VOTE  
 URGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Will be updated with Clinton speech, House GOP plans)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton ordered U.S. missiles and
warplanes to strike Iraq Wednesday, triggering Republican
suspicions that the timing of the attack was designed to force the
House to postpone a vote on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Live televised coverage from Baghdad showed anti-aircraft
batteries firing into the night sky over the Iraqi capital at 12:29
a.m. Iraqi time _ 4:49 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton launched Operation Desert Fox
in response to a report from chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard
Butler that Iraq had resumed cat-and-mouse efforts to hide
components of chemical and biological weapons and the missiles to
deliver them against U.S. allies such as Israel and oil-rich Arab
nations in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. offensive was the third attack on Iraq during the
Clinton presidency. A total of 24,100 U.S. military personnel were
in the region as well as the aircraft carrier USS Enterprise and 22
other U.S. warships. Eight of the vessels are armed with 300
Tomahawk cruise missiles capable of delivering 1,000-pound warheads
against targets with pinpoint accuracy. A second aircraft carrier,
the USS Carl Vinson, is due to arrive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said more than 200 combat aircraft also were
available, including 15 Cold War-era B-52 bombers capable of firing
air-launched cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said that a pattern of
Iraqi defiance dating back to the end of the 43-day Persian Gulf
War in 1991 triggered U.S. military operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout these many long years, Iraq has managed to block,
impede, delay, and frustrate efforts to implement that resolution,
right down to today,'' Rubin said. ``There is no end in sight for
this pattern of obfuscation, obstruction and outright violation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials insisted that U.S. military
action was not related to the president's impeachment struggle with
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The House had planned to vote Thursday on four articles of
impeachment and, though predictions on the outcome were scarce,
many uncommitted Republican House members were announcing plans to
vote for impeachment. House Republicans met late Wednesday to
determine the schedule for the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing here is generated by Iraq's failure to comply,''
Rubin insisted to reporters at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart also rejected
suggestions that Clinton was using military action to distract
attention from the impeachment fight. ``The president of the United
States makes national security decisions based on the best
interests of the United States of America,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., questioned the
timing of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the timing and the policy are subject to question,'' Lott
said. ``While I have been assured by administration officials that
there is no connection with the impeachment process in the House of
Representatives, I cannot support this military action in the
Persian Gulf at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   House Rules Committee Chairman Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., accused
Clinton of ordering the attack to delay or even thwart impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to do this at this time is just outrageous,'' Solomon
said. ``He should have delayed this. It would not have been
political the way it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said he supported a House leadership decision to delay
an impeachment vote amid combat operations. ``We should not be
handling the impeachment while the bombing is going on _ and that's
exactly the reason (Clinton is) doing it.'' Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., said she too feared that Clinton
might be ordering military action to stall impeachment. As Fowler
put it: ``I think this president is shameless in what he would do
to stay in office. He will use our military and he will use our
foreign policy to remain president.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee and a former Navy combat pilot during the Vietnam War,
said decisive action by Clinton would rally public support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there will be those who will question his motives
and timing,'' McCain said, adding: ``I think he will receive
significant support because it's pretty obvious that Saddam Hussein
is neither complying nor cooperating.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton continued efforts to urge Republican
moderates in the House to censure him rather than vote impeachment
for his cover-up of a sexual dalliance with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met privately at the White House with Rep. Amo Houghton,
R-N.Y., author of a White House-backed resolution of censure that
included a $500,000 fine. Clinton postponed a planned private
meeting with Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., another moderate
Republican who had told his constituents at a town meeting in
Norwalk, Conn., on Tuesday evening that Clinton's conduct fell
short of impeachable offenses. However, the Shays meeting was
postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the president remained ``committed to finding some
bipartisan compromise that allows us to put this issue behind us
short of impeachment,'' adding: ``We continue to try to reach out
across party lines to find a bipartisan solution or compromise to
put this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del., an ally of Clinton's from their
days as governors, worked to persuade the House GOP leadership to
permit House consideration of his proposal to censure and impose a
$2 million fine on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at this late date, there are compelling reasons to pursue
a different course with a better solution for our nation,'' Castle
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton worked behind the scenes, he left public lobbying
on his behalf to Vice President Gore, who still enjoys strong ties
with lawmakers on Capitol Hill after representing Tennessee in the
House and Senate for 16 years before joining Clinton on the
Democratic ticket in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and other Clinton administration officials have been
pressing the Republican House leadership to permit House
consideration of a resolution of censure. The vice president told a
group of business leaders at the White House that there was ``still
time for Democrats and Republicans to come together and embrace a
bipartisan compromise to seek a resolution that is both quick and
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing unspecified dangers from ``excessive partisanship,'' Gore
said the best outcome to the impeachment quandary would be a deal
that ``transcends partisanship and puts in the top priority-place
what's best for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., a member of the House Judiciary
Committee who voted for three of the four articles of impeachment,
said that it was ``too late'' for Clinton to reverse expected
impeachment by the House.
</P>
</TEXT>
