<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISDOM LIFTS OUR DAILY LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keeping up is Job 1 for a columnist whose work is
issue-oriented. Keeping up means lots of reading. The reward of
lots of reading is finding nuggets of thought worth pondering.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred some years back that the best of these are worth
sharing, and the holiday season is a good time to do so. Harried
readers not only need light fare, but many also find themselves in
a reflective mood at this time of year. So, for your reading and
thinking pleasure, here are my candidates for the best quotes of
1998:
</P>
<P>
   Once you start thinking about retirement, you've already
retired. (Charles J. Carlsen, president, Johnson County, Kan.,
Community College)
</P>
<P>
   The new basic resource, information, differs radically from all
other commodities in that it does not stand under the scarcity
theorem, (but) under the abundance theorem. If I sell a thing...I
no longer have (it). If I impart information I still have it and
can sell it again and again...This will force us (to) radically
revise basic economic theory. (Management guru Peter Drucker)
</P>
<P>
   Income inequality is not a problem, but a natural consequence of
a free society. Nevertheless, judging capitalism by the standards
of communism is a favorite pastime of economists. The process
allows them to denigrate capitalism for not doing what (communism)
was supposed to do, but didn't. (Paul Craig Roberts)
</P>
<P>
   As Asia tries to grow out of its depression, it must encourage
consumer spending...Henry Ford paid his workers more so they could
buy his tin lizzies; if Indonesia wants a car industry, it will
have to do the same thing. (Walter Russell Mead)
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of day care often say it is essential for women's
equality in the work force...(However,) it is fathers who are
(often) the biggest fans of day care: They like the extra income
their wives can bring in...It is mothers who usually feel the sting
of guilt. (Andrew Peyton Thomas, lawyer and author)
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken was not immortal. He was just the best of ourselves.
(Joe Posnanski, /{Kansas City Star/} sports columnist)
</P>
<P>
   People keep telling me I could have made $8 million or $10
million a year as a free agent, but I make more money than I will
ever need. (Curt Schilling, Philadelphia Phillies pitching ace)
</P>
<P>
   It's not the money. (Various overpaid professional athletes)
</P>
<P>
   In choosing this path, I fear that the president has undercut
the efforts of millions of American parents who are naturally
trying to instill in our children the value of honesty. (Sen.
Joseph I. Lieberman, Democrat of Connecticut)
</P>
<P>
   There are no German and American companies. There are only
successful and unsuccessful companies. (Thomas Middelhoff, chairman
of Germany's Bertelsmann AG, which this year acquired Random House
Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   Ribbons are getting to be as popular as the corporate logos that
adorn everything from automobiles to underwear. In a world of empty
gestures, it is one more way to make the wearers feel good or feel
connected or feel they are doing something useful, when they
probably are not. (Nicholas von Hoffman, /{New York Observer/}
columnist)
</P>
<P>
   I don't think many people really save a lot of time by moving
faster from one point to the next...You have to take advantage of
time, not speed. (Chuck Yeager, first pilot to fly faster than the
speed of sound)
</P>
</TEXT>
