<HEADER>
A3415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETRONIO-DANCE-REVIEW     12-16 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETRONIO-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING (SORT OF) IN DANTE'S FOOTSTEPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Stephen Petronio Company took dancegoers on a
fascinating trip to hell on Tuesday night at the Joyce Theater. But
it should have provided a road map for the journey.
</P>
<P>
   The expedition, which lasted about an hour, was part of the New
York premiere of Stephen Petronio's ``Not Garden.'' It soon became
evident that if anything about this work was meant to refer to a
garden, that garden was not Eden. If pronounced aloud, the title
sounds especially appropriate for Petronio's knotted choreography.
</P>
<P>
   A program note explained that a slide projection showing Hebrew
letters was an inscription referring to immortality derived from
cabala. That proved good to know. Audiences might have found
another piece of information even more helpful.
</P>
<P>
   News releases stated that Petronio was inspired in part by
Dante's ``Inferno.'' Yet there was no reference to this in the
Playbill. ``Not Garden'' does not interpret Dante's poem literally.
Nevertheless, it is tied to it just closely enough as to warrant a
program note.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the ``Inferno,'' Dante says that in the
middle of his life he found himself lost in a dark wood. Petronio,
42, opened ``Not Garden'' with a solo in which he became a
modern-day Dante fumbling about the stage in a puzzled manner. The
accompaniment was a recording of the ``Ave Maria'' Gounod composed
on a theme by Bach, performed by the soprano Diamanda Galas and the
organist David Jett.
</P>
<P>
   The aria gave way to restless percussion music by David Linton
and the tortures of the infernal realms were evoked in choreography
for Kristen Borg, Steven Fetherhuff, Ori Flomin, Philip Gardner,
Ashleigh Leite, Jessica Meeker, Jenifer Weaver, Todd Williams and
Petronio. The dance was plotless. Yet, like Dante, Petronio
assigned specific people to hell, in this case by means of slide
projections naming famous 20th-century figures. It was an odd
assortment of villains, ranging from Hitler and Saddam Hussein to
Freud, Calvin Klein and Madonna. And when a slide listed ``Every
President'' among them, one wondered if Petronio might be guilty of
excessive spleen.
</P>
<P>
   It was more stimulating to forget the slides in this production
designed by Tal Yarden and Patricia Fox and to focus on the
choreography. Dancers turned relentlessly or rushed to and fro,
repeating movements over and over. No matter what they did, they
seemed fated. Just as Dante's doomed souls are eternally locked in
torment, so the dancers suggested that they were condemned to
perform their actions forever.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the second half of the two-part work Linton's score was
replaced by meditative music by Sheila Chandra. The choreographic
tone also changed. Petronio danced a calm duet with Ms. Borg, who
has been a member of his company for 15 years and who will leave it
at the end of this season. Standing side by side, they performed
unhurried steps in unison. Although they did not touch, they gave
the impression that a mystical bond united them. Other dancers
bounded joyously, perhaps as a reminder that Dante created more
than an ``Inferno.'' He also wrote a ``Purgatorio'' and a
``Paradiso.'' And the serene way in which ``Not Garden'' concluded
implied that Petronio thinks that paradise may not be hopelessly
lost.
</P>
<P>
   His production continues through Sunday night at the Joyce
Theater, 175 Eighth Ave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
