<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-BLUES17-COX     12-16 0242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BLUES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLUES
 &HT;    Taj Mahal set a box of many vibes
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now a seasoned, walking compendium of blues styles, the man who
calls himself Taj Mahal once was a young acolyte in the church of
the holy jelly roll. He's part of a generation of performers who
came of age in the 1960s, sponging up the influence and folkwise
wiles of blues legends and unknowns enjoying a latter-day
spotlight. The singer and guitarist is a torchbearer whose surplus
of personality and exceptionally canny taste has made him an
entertainer with a personal stamp of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play to please elitists,'' he declares in the notes
accompanying this 3-CD, career-spanning box set. ``I had my
father's bebop attitude.'' Which simply means the guitarist and
vocalist has never been concerned with passing fashion. His work,
handsomely collected, comes across as that of a one-man diaspora,
equally at home raising hell in the Texas Panhandle, catching the
breeze in the West Indies, reworking classic reggae tunes with
distinctive guitar picking, strutting with a tuba choir, going up
to country or slopping around the Chicago Southside.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Progress &AMP; In Motion: 1965-1998''
</P>
<P>
   Taj Mahal.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia/Legacy.
</P>
<P>
   54 tracks (3 CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: They don't call him Senor Blues for nothing
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
