NYT-12-16-98 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS17-COX     12-16 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of recent releases
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Richard L. Eldredge and Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Bethlehem''
</P>
<P>
   Brian McKnight. Motown. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   This probably would have been fine if it were just Brian
McKnight oozing his way over the expected Christmas songs. What
makes it exceptional is the company he keeps. Which proves that a
honeyed way with a verse must be in the genes, as the McKnight
Family Choir opens with a stirring ``Hail Mary,'' followed by pop
quartet Boyz II Men's more sensual reworking of the tune McKnight
penned for them, ``Let It Snow.'' Even beyond the vocals, simply
having a guest appearance from Mrs. Nat ``King'' Cole, who talks
about her 15 Christmases with her late, legendary husband, does as
much to set the emotional tone of this record as the many well-done
originals McKnight also offers.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Shades of Bey''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Bey. Evidence. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Longtime jazz pianist and vocalist Andy Bey refuses to be pinned
down musically. And ``Shades of Bey,'' his second solo date, might
be the sleeper holiday gift for the jazz aficionado in your life as
a result. Bey, who's logged time behind the microphone with drum
wizard Max Roach and Count Basie bandleader Frank Foster,
seamlessly floats from a heart-stopping ballad like ``Pretty Girl''
to the uptempo improvisations of Thelonious Monk's ``Straight, No
Chaser.'' Strings and an acoustic guitar, meanwhile, add lushness
to the proceedings on ``River Man.'' Bey's voice is reminiscent of
Joe Williams, with maybe a touch more elasticity. Seek this one
out.
</P>
<P>
   SHOW TUNES
</P>
<P>
   ``Way Back to Paradise''
</P>
<P>
   Audra McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Nonesuch. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Few adjectives can aptly describe the instrument that is Audra
McDonald's voice. It soars, condemns, caresses, cajoles, all with
such honesty that you absolutely must listen. McDonald, a Broadway
star at age 28, follows her heart on this debut album. Instead of
reinterpreting standards as convention might dictate, she takes on
the songs of young composers. Her ``Way Back to Paradise,'' written
for an update of ``Medea,'' is a gumbo of opera, spirituals and the
syncopation native to New Orleans, where the new show is set. ``You
Don't Know This Man,'' from Alfred Uhry's ``Parade,'' is an
impassioned wife's angry defense of her jailed husband. There may
or may not be a Stephen Sondheim in this bunch of composers, but
one thing is certain: Their songs will never sound better.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Richard L. Eldredge and Kathy Janich write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
