</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MILITARY-1217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. MILITARY FORCES WERE ALREADY DEPLOYED
 &HT;    With US-AIRSTRIKES-1217.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In contrast to the U.S.-Iraqi standoff six weeks
ago, the current crisis over United Nations weapons inspections
found U.S. military forces already in place.
</P>
<P>
   The troops, planes and ships sent to the Persian Gulf region in
mid-November were still deployed Wednesday morning (EST), when
President Clinton says he decided to order an attack on Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman described the forces deployed against Iraq
as:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  24,100 armed troops from all four branches of the U.S.
military.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  22 ships, of which 15 are combatant vessels and seven are
support ships. The combatant ships include the U.S.S. Enterprise, a
nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, and eight smaller ships, which
were armed with Tomahawk cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  201 aircraft, including land-based planes, 50 strike aircraft
on the Enterprise and an undisclosed number of helicopters on the
Marine Corps' helicopter assault ship, the U.S.S. Belleau Wood,
which was deployed to the Gulf from its base in Sasebo, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft also include 15 B-52 bombers based in the Indian
Ocean island of Diego Garcia. The B-52s carry air-launch cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Pentagon said aircraft poised to strike Iraq
included 24 Air Force F-16s and 12 F-15s and 12 F-117 Stealth
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 24,000 U.S. troops in the Persian Gulf represented
a slightly larger contingent than the 21,500 troops deployed in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had said the November breakdown of troops was Navy,
12,000; Army, 4,900; Air Force 2,400 and Marine Corps, 2,200. It
was not clear before the air strikes Wednesday evening which
services provided the additional 2,600 troops now in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Enterprise had been scheduled to replace the U.S.S.
Eisenhower as part of a normal rotation of U.S. carriers
permanently cruising the Persian Gulf. U.S. Defense Department
officials had said last month that the Eisenhower might remain in
the Gulf, along with the Enterprise for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was not clear earlier Wednesday whether the
Eisenhower had been withdrawn _ or if it had, where it is now.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
