<HEADER>
A3460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOTES17-COX     12-16 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thriller takes novelist Kay in a new direction
 &HT;    By Don O' Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One thing readers of Terry Kay have come to expect is
the unexpected. Kay, a former Atlantan who lives in Athens(Ga.),
never covers the same literary territory twice. When publishers
urged him to cash in on the success of ``To Dance With the White
Dog'' with a similar Southern family novel, Kay abandoned the South
altogether to write about a midlife romance in New York's Catskills
in ``Shadow Song.'' After that, he tackled the intricacies of race
relations in Georgia's pre-civil rights era in ``The Runaway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I get bored writing in the same voice,'' Kay says. ``If I
could find a genre I really like, I might stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   With his new book, ``The Kidnapping of Aaron Greene'' (Morrow,
$25), Kay veers off into the adventure-thriller field. Set in
Atlanta, the story focuses on a young bank mail clerk who is
kidnapped and held for an $11 million ransom. All tape-recorded
messages from the kidnappers are delivered to Atlanta Journal
reporter Cody Yates. And, inexplicably, the voice on the tapes is
his.
</P>
<P>
   The key point of the novel, Kay says, is that the kidnap victim
is an ordinary person.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time or another, everyone has felt like nobody,'' Kay
says. ``Suddenly there's a nobody who gets into the news and all
the other nobodies respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay began writing the story when he worked as a film and theater
critic for The Atlanta Journal nearly 30 years ago. ``It started as
a concept for a screenplay, but I never did anything with it. I did
have a great experience with the actor Richard Harris, though. He
was in town one night and I told him about the story and he said it
was a great idea. A couple of years later, I saw him when he came
back to Atlanta and he introduced me to his new wife and, without
any prompting from me, told her about my story. To me, that was a
fine compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kay is working on three other novels and waiting for
final word on Hallmark Hall of Fame's plans for ``The Runaway,''
which is tentatively scheduled for filming next summer.
</P>
<P>
   NOT ENOUGH CHARM: If you can't get picked for Oprah's Book Club,
winning the National Book Award apparently is the next best thing.
Since garnering the top fiction award Nov. 18, Alice McDermott's
``Charming Billy'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $22) has been flying
off the shelves. The novel about a group of Irish-Americans who
gather after Billy Lynch's funeral to recall his wrecked life has
sold more than 80,000 copies in hardcover, and many stores are out.
``It's been selling like crazy,'' says Bonnie Welch of Wordsworth
Booksellers in Decatur, ``but we could sell a lot more if we could
get copies. We've had it on back order for two weeks.'' For readers
who can wait, the paperback edition is to be published in January.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR FAVORITES: If you wonder what books some famous authors
loved this year, check out Amazon.com's Web site. Eighteen authors,
including Alice Hoffman, Elmore Leonard and Sara Paretsky, talk
about the books they most admired in 1998. Leonard raves about
Andre Dubus' collection of essays, ``Meditations From a Movable
Chair,'' and Barbara Kingsolver's ``The Poisonwood Bible.'' He also
recommends ``Into Thin Air'' by Jon Krakauer and ``The Perfect
Storm'' by Sebastian Junger. Hoffman, author of ``Practical
Magic,'' praises ``Final Vinyl Days,'' Jill McCorkle's book of
short stories. And mystery writer Paretsky says she loved Rose
Tremain's ``The Way I Found Her,'' Arthur Golden's ``Memoirs of a
Geisha'' and McDermott's ``Charming Billy.'' But, she says, ``The
book that stands out most vividly for me is Joseph Skibell's `A
Blessing on the Moon.' I read it three times.''
</P>
<P>
   GREEN PASTURES: Better late than never. Effie Leland Wilder was
85 years old when Peachtree Publishers released her first book,
``Out to Pasture, But Not Over the Hill'' (Peachtree Publishers,
$14.95). The novel about adventures in a nursing home is now in its
eighth printing, and two other Wilder novels, ``Over What Hill''
(Peachtree, $14.95) and ``Older But Wilder'' (Peachtree, $14.95)
have gone into multiple printings, for a total of 320,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Quinlin, president of Peachtree Publishers, is
overwhelmed by the response. ``Of course we loved the stories and
believed that a significant portion of the reading population _ the
over-60 set _ would enjoy these novels. But, to be honest, even we
would never have predicted just how popular her books would be.''
Now 89, Wilder spends her time writing and answering fan mail at
the Presbyterian Home in Summerville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O' Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
