<HEADLINE>
MEGGETT, PARCELLS TEAM UP _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ They had stayed in touch throughout the
season. Bill Parcells never forgot his favorite kick returner, and
Dave Meggett never forgot his favorite coach. They are friends.
They chatted a lot. Now, again, they also are boss and employee.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells-Meggett, Part III, was unveiled Wednesday when the
former Giant and Patriot showed up and donned the green of the New
York Jets. Meggett has not played a down this season while
recovering from foot surgery, but he told Parcells he thought he
could help. That was enough for the Jets coach, who needed exactly
what Meggett provides after returner Leon Johnson went down for the
season with a serious rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was sealed Sunday night in a phone call, which went
thusly, according to both men.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells: ``Tell me where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Meggett: ``I can help you right now if you need me.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells: ``That's all I need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets worked out Meggett, 32, Tuesday and signed him for the
rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him for about two minutes and I knew he was OK,''
Parcells said. ``I think David will be a quality replacement. He
can do all the things that Leon can do. And he knows our system.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knows about half the team. Pepper Johnson and Jumbo
Elliott were teammates when the Giants won Super Bowl XXV on Jan.
27, 1991. His locker is adjacent to former New England teammate
Curtis Martin, who praised Meggett for his ``versatility and
leadership. He's a great guy, and I'm glad he's here.'' Keith
Byars, also a former Patriot teammate, sits on the other side of
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have Dave,'' Byars said. ``He knows what it's all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expressed concern about Meggett's off-field activities.
In February, he was charged with assault and robbery stemming from
an incident with a prostitute in Toronto. The assault charge was
dismissed. He also has been taken to court on several paternity
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Toronto situation, Parcells said, ``I talked to
him the day after, and he told me it was a setup. David has always
been up front and truthful with me. He's never lied to me. I've
never had a single problem with him over discipline. He's never
late. He never missed a practice. He's tough as nails.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto incident did, however, help prompt the Patriots to
release Meggett in May. At the time, he was recovering from surgery
on his left foot, which he injured in the Patriots' playoff loss to
the Steelers. While working out this fall, he was taking five
classes at Towson State University, his alma mater, and had a final
exam in sports management scheduled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take an incomplete,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meggett said he basically relaxed this past season, waiting for
his foot to heal. He cracked, ``I feel kind of good. I didn't have
to do the work to get us here. But I enjoy the pressure of a
playoff atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about leaving New England, Meggett was vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' he said. ``I never questioned
it. I think it was a business decision. I don't understand what
kind of personal situation it might have been. Those people didn't
know me. But I'm not going to cry about it or make a big stink.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Parcells, who does know Meggett. The Jets coach is
looking at a huge game Saturday in Buffalo and thinks Meggett will
be able to play. Then there is the season finale against the
Patriots, followed by the playoffs. Meggett Time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be presumptuous,'' Parcells said, ``but this
guy is a money player. When the money is on the line, this guy
shows up. Always has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
