<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESSMAN: CLINTON PONDERED 'WAG THE DOG' PERCEPTION
 &HT;    With US-AIRSTRIKES-1217.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton flew back from the Middle East
Tuesday night, he agonized over the political implications of
bombing Iraq in the face of an impeachment debate in the U.S. House
of Representatives, according to a participant in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., who flew back on Air Force One with
Clinton, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and a
congressional delegation, said Clinton discussed the matter after
it was raised by Rep. Rick Lazio, D-N.Y. Lazio could not be reached
Wednesday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one used the term 'Wag the Dog' ... (but) there was obvious
concern,'' that military action in the face of a possible
impeachment would be viewed as a cynical effort to dodge
impeachment, Hastings said. The movie ``Wag the Dog'' earlier this
year was about a fictitious president who launched a bogus war to
divert attention from a sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he told Clinton: ``You have to do what you have to
do as if there were no impeachment. He said he felt that is what he
must do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he was confident Clinton did not order the
military strike to delay impeachment. If anything, he said the
threat of impeachment forced Clinton to prove he could act to
protect the United States' interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many things have to be taken into account,'' Hastings
said. ``The Joint Chiefs of Staff are not crazy. If it were not
absolutely necessary to do this, they would have told him. The CIA
is not crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he was convinced the strike was the result of
military and national security advice that had nothing to do with
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment can wait, it ain't going nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
