<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-LIFE-NYT &LR;      12-16 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-LIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POP LIFE: THE INDUSTRY VS. WEB PIRATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill, Mass., Wis.)  (dal) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chief executives at the major labels, heads of
technology companies and the Recording Industry Association of
America met to announce their Secure Digital Music Initiative on
Tuesday in Manhattan. They said that in the next year they hoped to
agree on a standard to deliver music to consumers on the Internet
through a system that would prevent piracy and insure that music
copyright holders were paid.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was, in some ways, a public relations move for
the music industry to look technology-friendly after a series of
lawsuits intended to stop pirate music activity on the Internet,
announcements criticizing manufacturers of CD players capable of
recording music and attempts to block the sale of the Diamond Rio,
a tiny portable stereo that plays some types of Internet music
files.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the announcement is that the tiny sliver of
music fans buying songs and albums to download on their computer
seems likely to grow significantly once record labels support a
uniform, easy-to-use Internet standard and make more music
available.
</P>
<P>
   But in the record labels' slowness to adopt a standard and in
their debilitating worries about how to protect copyright holders
from Internet piracy and keep downloaded songs from being heard by
anyone except the user who paid for them, there are a few
fundamental fallacies at work in their logic.
</P>
<P>
   The industry fears that Internet digital song-compression
formats like the widely used MP3, which has no built-in security
system, combined with CD players with the capability of recording
music turn potential consumers into audio pirates. While there may
be some truth to their worries, it is likely that even without
protective devices, the music market won't be significantly hurt.
The fear is predicated on the belief that the majority of consumers
care so much about having music in a digital format that an analog
copy won't suffice.
</P>
<P>
   At present, all a music fan has to do to copy any CD or song on
the Internet is to attach a cassette deck to his computer and hit
the record button. Even before music was digital, the ability of
cassette decks (and reel-to-reel recorders before them) to make
unlimited copies of vinyl albums and tapes didn't seem to hurt the
business.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there's a funny little quirk to the new Philips
dual-tray CD recorder, the compact disk equivalent of a
tape-to-tape cassette deck for copying recordings. Like all such
digital music recording technology, it is equipped with the
mandatory Serial Copy Management System, which prevents consumers
from making digital recordings of any copied disks. But when users
try to copy such a disk, a message appears asking the user if he
would like to make an analog copy. For most music fans, the
analog-digital distinction is moot as long as they can hear the
music in some way.
</P>
<P>
   The second assumption is that free access to music for consumers
is going to cut into the profits of artists and record labels. The
industry fears the music fan who is able to make unlimited digital
copies. But what the industry does not take into account is that
the music fan is a fan, and free music on the Internet may well
send him into record stores to buy more music as he discovers new
acts or buy the actual CDs of songs he has downloaded. I receive
thousands of free CDs in the mail _ more than any Internet addict
has time to download _ and I still spend thousands of dollars in
record stores each year. Free music hasn't kept me out of stores;
it has made me more eager to explore newer acts, fringe genres and
the historical precedents of the music I like.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of the record business in the first years of the CDs
popularity because of consumers replacing their vinyl records
should have proved to record labels that people will buy the same
albums again and that they like to have the official version in the
popular format. If albums can be bought digitally as well, they may
even have fans paying all over again for a favorite CD or
collection of songs. At the news conference, no speaker was able to
provide concrete proof that Internet piracy was affecting sales. In
the meantime, a technological research company, Forrester in
Cambridge, Mass., has already determined that the number of disks
now being digitally downloaded on the Internet is not financially
meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   The other mistake the industry seems to be on the verge of
making is that representatives at the conference said they wanted
to sell downloadable albums for the same price as those bought in
stores, despite the fact that they will be saving money in raw
materials and shipping. After all, this is an industry that would
still like to see the cost of CD's rise to more than $20, more
comparable to prices in England and Japan. Cheap music on the
Internet, they say, will stabilize or even lower CD prices. But
even if record labels gave the music away, they could still make
more money. The Internet will allow them to find new sources of
revenue in inserting advertisements into downloadable music,
selling their databases of customers who have bought certain albums
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we are still far from a digital distribution
takeover. Consumers don't have the room on their hard drives to
download enough CDs, and Web sites aren't built to handle the
volume of downloads that could occur the day a major hit goes on
sale. Instead of focusing on security and taking preventive
measures, the music business should be stimulating the market by
looking into improving (instead of limiting) technology, teaching
consumers how to use the Internet to download music and offering a
bigger and better selection of available music. There will always
be a way around any anti-piracy solution, just as there will always
be a way to steal CDs from record stores that have security
systems.
</P>
<P>
   LOOSE NOTES
</P>
<P>
   When he released his album ``Imagination'' last spring, the
reclusive former Beach Boy BRIAN WILSON did not think he would be
able to perform the music. A trial concert, filmed for a PBS
special with a limited audience last May in his hometown, Lake
Charles, Ill., found him tense and nervous. But by the end of the
concert, he was in top form and soon decided to embark on his first
solo tour. It begins on Feb. 14 in Milwaukee and ends on March 10
in Chicago, stopping at the Beacon Theater in Manhattan on Feb. 24
and 25. Wilson is to be supported by Joe Thomas, who produced the
album, and possibly by the Wondermints, an up-and-coming band of
Los Angeles retro-pop savants.
</P>
<P>
   The movie action hero STEVEN SEAGAL has signed a five-album,
seven-year recording contract with Outwest, a multimedia recording
company based in Los Angeles. His first album is due in 1999,
followed by a tour. Though the names of his films may sound like
Metallica albums _ ``Out for Justice,'' ``Above the Law,'' ``Fire
Down Below'' _ his music, a spokesman for Outwest said, will be
Southern rock.
</P>
</TEXT>
