<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAL-ATLANTA17-COX     12-16 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAL-ATLANTA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Japan Airlines to Atlanta: Sayanora in March
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Japan Airlines is ditching Atlanta-Tokyo flights in
March, leaving hometown giant Delta Air Lines with a lock on
nonstop service to Asia's top destination.
</P>
<P>
   JAL, which has flown the route for 13 years, cited Asia's
economic troubles and Delta's addition of daily nonstop flights
last June, more than doubling seat capacity on the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Declining traffic demand and the competitive situation at
Atlanta have had a negative impact on the gateway's profitability,
and JAL has made the decision to utilize its resources elsewhere,''
JAL said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time it ends Atlanta service, JAL on March 15 will
add service between Tokyo and Dallas-Fort Worth. The new route will
enable JAL to offer domestic connections on Dallas-based American
Airlines, with which it has a new marketing alliance.
</P>
<P>
   JAL's moves are not a surprise. When Delta started its nonstop
Tokyo flights, JAL officials conceded they would probably face a
decision on whether to continue the service.
</P>
<P>
   The American alliance also made it likely JAL would reconfigure
routes to capitalize on ties between the two, which include joint
seat sales and operational cost-savings at each other's hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Evilsizor, a JAL marketing official in Atlanta, said the
carrier's average Atlanta-Tokyo load factors have dropped to 58
percent, down from about 78 percent last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt in June we might lose 10 (percent) to 12 percent when
Delta started, but as the Asia situation dragged on we saw the
numbers go lower,'' Evilsizor said.
</P>
<P>
   JAL's Atlanta service helped foster a spurt of Japanese
investment in Georgia and the Southeast when it began in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't foresee a big impact from this, but JAL's service was
always a selling point to Japanese companies, so we'll see,'' said
Yoko Kagawa, executive director of the Japanese Chamber of Commerce
in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of convenience, there's no effect because Delta's
there,'' she said. ``Psychologically, it's a little bit of a
blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Evilsizor said JAL hopes to retain many customers in the
Southeast with special deals for those who fly to Dallas or Chicago
to board its nonstops. Evilsizor also noted that JAL will offer
five weekly cargo flights in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta previously flew to Tokyo via Portland, Ore., but added
nonstop service from Atlanta in the wake of a liberalized
U.S.-Japan air treaty. Delta spokesman Bill Berry said the flights
are selling well but added the carrier has no plans to add more in
light of the uncertain economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers seeking more alternatives also can fly American,
United or Northwest airlines via their U.S. hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
