A3537 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SOLOMON-HNS &LR;      12-16 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOLOMON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. SOLOMON SAYS CLINTON TIMED ATTACK TO DELAY IMPEACHMENT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Gerald B. H. Solomon, R-N.Y., on Wednesday
called President Clinton's decision to attack Iraq ``outrageous''
and accused him of launching air strikes on that nation in order to
delay an impeachment vote in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, who is retiring at the end of the year, is chairman of
the House Rules Committee and an outspoken critic of Clinton. He
said White House officials were ``doing everything they can to
postpone this vote on impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to do this at this unbelievable time is just
outrageous,'' Solomon said, asserting there was no pressing
military need to attack Iraq on the eve of the scheduled start of
House debate on impeachment. Aides to Republican House leaders said
a postponement of the debate was likely.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon reflected Republican skepticism over the timing of the
air strikes and Clinton's motives for ordering them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never underestimate a desperate president,'' he said. ``This
time he means business. What option is left for getting impeachment
off the front page and maybe even postponed? And how else to
explain the sudden appearance of a backbone that has been invisible
up to now?''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon added, ``If he (had) delayed this until Monday or
Tuesday, it would still be outrageous but would not be as political
as it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   When Iraqi President Saddam Hussein surrendered after the 1991
Persian Gulf War, he agreed to relinquish nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons to U.N. inspectors. But the inspectors have
repeatedly cited the Iraqi regime for failure to reveal the extent
of its illegal weapons programs and for stockpiling weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the attack a day after Richard Butler, the
U.N.'s chief weapons inspector, reported that Iraq was not
cooperating with his team.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said Clinton could have ordered attacks against Iraq
many times since February after confrontations with the regime over
weapons violations, but chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why now?'' Solomon asked.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., also raised
questions Wednesday about the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the timing and the policy are subject to question,'' Lott
said. ``While I have been assured by administration officials that
there is no connection with the impeachment process in the House of
Representatives, I cannot support this military action in the
Persian Gulf at this time,'' Lott added.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., a member of the House National
Security Committee, said, ``I think this president is shameless in
what he would do to stay in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart, responding to the criticism,
said, ``The president of the United States makes national security
decisions based on the recommendations of his national security
advisers and on the best interests of the people of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., called Solomon's comments
``outrageous,'' and added that the New York congressman ``has spent
a career making outrageous comments.'' Gejdenson said the attack on
Iraq was justified and that ``as an ex-Marine, Solomon should know
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Republicans challenged the timing of the attack on Iraq.
Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
said, ``Saddam Hussein has left the United States with no choice
but to strike Iraq, and I believe most Americans will support the
decision by our defense leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
