<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3577 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      12-16 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOLAK GETS THE NOD AGAINST 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Three quarterbacks who started the season as
backups were named to the Pro Bowl Wednesday. Randall Cunningham
(Vikings), Doug Flutie (Bills), and Vinny Testaverde (Jets) didn't
have realistic hopes of playing much when they joined their
respective teams, but injury situations thrust them into starting
roles and all three came up huge.
</P>
<P>
   So huge they are now MVP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Zolak finds himself in a similar spot, but his assignment
is temporary. His job is to produce immediately and keep the
Patriots' playoff hopes alive while Drew Bledsoe nurses his broken
right index finger.
</P>
<P>
   There is virtually no room for error for Zolak, named by coach
Pete Carroll Wednesday as the starter for Sunday's game against the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll kept his two backups guessing until Tuesday night when
he told Zolak of his decision, but it really wasn't a decision at
all. Carroll acknowledged he just wanted to make sure Tupa was
prepared to be the backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got that message across,'' said Tupa. ``I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no break-in period for Zolak. After three years of
basically sitting and watching, he must get off the bench and
perform at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie had a nine-year absence from the NFL, but he spent eight
of those years as a standout in the Canadian Football League.
Testaverde was an All-Pro with the Baltimore Ravens two years ago,
and Cunningham, who was out of football for a spell, still played
more the past three years than Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   If Zolak, an unrestricted free agent, performs heroically, he
could earn himself a sizable pay raise in the open market. If he
doesn't, he may be looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   The onus is not only on Zolak but also on offensive coordinator
Ernie Zampese, who must put the substitute quarterback in position
to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go heavy on things in the playbook that Scott
can do and shorten up the things we think he can't do,'' siad
Zampese. ``We'll go with his strength. He's a big, strong
quarterback who has a lot of experience in the league. He's got a
strong arm, and there's no question that this is a tough situation
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zampese agrees that backup quarterbacks must be able to step
in and win right away in today's NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``Scott will have some things to
overcome, mainly that we don't have Terry Glenn and we're injured
in the fullback spot. But these are things Drew would have had to
overcome also.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampese has coached Dan Fouts, Troy Aikman, Jim Everett, and
Bledsoe, but he remembers some of his backups _ Mark Herrmann, Ed
Luther, Jason Garrett, and Rodney Peete.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak could easily go to the head of that class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to stay within himself,'' said Zampese. ``He has to be
told that he doesn't have to win the game himself. He needs to let
other guys make plays for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who appeared at a brief press conference with his
finger exposed and the infamous pin sticking out from the top, said
he will do what Zolak has tried do for him _ serve as a supportive
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's streak of 58 straight regular-season games, tops among
AFC quarterbacks, is ending, but he hopes he will heal sufficiently
to play in the regular-season finale against the Jets Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess Zolak's talents, Bledsoe said, ``Scott's
accurate. He does a good job of throwing the deep ball. I look for
us to throw the ball upfield. He does a good job of going through
progressions and makes the right reads. When he's forced to, he can
do a good job running the game. I feel he'll go in and give us a
very good chance to win the game this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to help Scott as much as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak said this will be the most significant start of his
career. He started some games in 1992 and 1995, but this is a
late-season game with playoff implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about it,'' he said. ``I've been looking to be in
a meaningful game all my life. We can still win the division. With
all we've been through, guys have stepped up. I need to pick up
where he left off. I can't do the things Drew does, but I have to
move the sticks and let the guys run and make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak said he's going to watch the game films from '92 and ``get
the goose bumps back. I've been doing a lot of throwing to these
guys, so it won't be a situation of cold turkey. I think the
receivers are excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing he'll be the guy ``makes me more focused, and I look
forward to it even more. I'm kind of itchy about it. I wish the
game was tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of his teammates are glad the game is Sunday. They'll have
more time to get used to Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not changing anything,'' said Zolak. ``I'm me. Drew's
Drew. He does things his way. I do things my way. If somebody makes
a play, I'll get excited for him. I just want to get in there and
get some points early, not only for my confidence but for the
team's confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak is not lacking for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge for any backup,'' said San Francisco's Steve
Young, who for years was Joe Montana's backup. ``There's no secret
to it. Staying prepared week in and week out is key. Getting the
flow of the game when you haven't been in is. It's like driving
around in a Volkswagen and then getting into a Ferrari. The hard
part is that everything is new.''
</P>
<P>
   49ers coach Steve Mariucci was noncommittal about how the change
will affect his team's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the world of Drew Bledsoe,'' said Mariucci. ``It's
unfortunate he broke that finger. He's had a heck of a year. Scott
is a guy who's been in the league eight years, he's not a a rookie,
so we have to treat him as we would Drew Bledsoe. We know we have
to play a physical game and stop the running game and Ben Coates.
We have to win a game on the road. That starts with defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the 49ers' defense will be gunning for Zolak, just as
the Rams did last Sunday when Bledsoe went briefly to the locker
room for repairs. They decked him after a lineman missed a blocking
assignment, and Ray Agnew throttled Zolak, sacking him and forcing
a fumble on the quarterback's first play.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the things he'll have to overcome, but Zolak is ready
for the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I've worked and paid my dues,'' he said, ``and I feel I
deserve this chance and I'm excited about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
