<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-IRAQ-1217-COX     12-16 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-1217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: AIRSTRIKES FINAL STEP IN YEAR-LONG CLINTON, SADDAM
DANCE
 &HT;    With US-AIRSTRIKES-1217.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wednesday's attack on Iraq capped off a year of
brinksmanship between President Clinton and Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein over Iraq's production of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this year -- last February and again in November --
Clinton has ordered dozens of warships, scores of attack aircraft
and thousands of U.S. troops to the Persian Gulf region in
preparation for strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Iraq managed to slip the noose by offering
last-minute diplomatic concessions, only to later break its promise
to allow United Nations inspectors full access to its alleged
weapons manufacturing and stockpiling facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks ago, though, when Clinton first ordered an attack,
then called it off less than an hour before cruise missiles and
bombs were scheduled to begin hitting Iraq, he warned that this
time promises alone would not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam would be held accountable, Clinton warned, and airstrikes
could take place, without warning, if Saddam went back on his word
again.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Richard Butler, head of the United Nations Special
Commission, or UNSCOM, responsible for inspecting Iraq's weapons
programs, submitted a report to the United Nations in New York
alleging a pattern of continuing Iraqi attempts to impede
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had learned the substance of Butler's report
Tuesday night, while traveling back to Washington from the Middle
East aboard Air Force One, convened a meeting of his national
security team at 7:30 a.m. Wednesday -- just seven hours after
returning to the White House -- to approve Wednesday's attack
without warning, without diplomacy, without giving Saddam the
chance to make one more promise that few believe would be kept.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was the continuing impediments Saddam threw up
against the UNSCOM inspectors on the ground in Iraq that convinced
Clinton's security advisers that there was little point in giving
Saddam another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Since agreeing on November 15 and 16 to cooperate fully with the
UNSCOM teams, ''Iraq has tried to create new safe havens, they've
cleaned out sites before UNSCOM has arrived, they've interfered
with photography, they've interfered and put at risk (UNSCOM)
helicopters,'' said State Department spokesman James Rubin. ''And
there is no end in sight for this pattern of obfuscation,
obstruction and outright violation.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest act in the long-running U.S.-Iraq drama unfolded on
the eve of a scheduled debate in the House of Representatives over
whether to impeach Clinton on any of four charges stemming from the
Monica Lewinsky sex-and-deception scandal.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted some of the president's critics, at home and
abroad, to charge Clinton with trumping up a military crisis to
divert public attention from his personal travails, a charge the
administration rejects.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wags will continue to talk about whatever it is we do,''
Rubin told reporters at the regular daily State Department briefing
on Wednesday. ''The timing here is generated by Iraq's failure to
comply.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's most enduring national security headaches, the
problems with Iraq are those he inherited when he took office in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the terms of his surrender to U.S.-led coalition
forces at the end of the Persian Gulf War in 1991, Saddam agreed to
destroy any chemical, biological and nuclear weapons in his arsenal
and to dismantle any facilities involved in producing such arms.
</P>
<P>
   He further agreed to allow United Nations inspections teams,
structured as UNSCOM, to verify that he did as he promised.
</P>
<P>
   Compliance, though, has rarely been anything other than spotty.
The result is that UNSCOM has not yet been able to verify that Iraq
no longer has, or is building, weapons capable of killing thousands
of people in a single strike with lethal chemicals or deadly germs.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the U.S. intelligence community, moreover, have
testified in recent weeks that Iraq has the capability to build a
nuclear weapon within as little as two years, unless its
proliferation program is curbed.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago last month, Iraq threatened to shoot down the U.S.
warplanes that routinely fly over Iraqi airspace, under U.N.
auspices, in part to provide support to UNSCOM inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, Iraq blocked UNSCOM teams from inspecting
suspected weapons sites, then expelled UNSCOM completely, forcing a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's response was to deploy a massive military force and
wage a weeks-long campaign to win public support, in this country
and abroad, for contemplated strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Under threat of those strikes, Saddam backed down and, in
February, promised U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan that he would
cooperate with UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   By August, though, compliance was again thrown into doubt,
though briefly, and in October, Saddam, yet again, challenged
inspectors to the point that they concluded they could no longer
perform their tasks.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted the November Gulf build-up. On November 15,
Clinton ordered a massive attack on Iraq, only to call it off with
bombers only 20 minutes or less from releasing cruise missiles and
bombs against their targets, after Saddam sent a letter, which he
modified through the night and into the morning of November 16,
vowing compliance.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the White House said its plan was to conduct
increasingly aggressive inspections in Iraq to test Saddam's word.
</P>
<P>
   By early Wednesday, the White House verdict was in: ''Iraq has
failed that test,'' said Rubin. ''Iraq has not changed its stripes
and it does not intend to comply.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
