<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3581 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BROWN-LADN     12-16 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BROWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN BECOMES PATIENT OF JOBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the Dodgers rolled out their $105 million man for the
media Tuesday, Kevin Brown went to visit Dr. Frank Jobe, who is to
the human arm what Michael DeBakey is the human heart.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had no reason to question Brown's ticker. Their new
ace pitcher has proven to have the kind of pump, as well as other
key body parts, that separates one from your generic starting
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   But arms are so fragile, especially those asked to hit 90 miles
per hour on the speed gun, throw 220 or more innings a year, and
last for seven seasons, a veritable eternity in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe knows best, because he's rebuilt a few hundred over the
years. So for assurance and insurance, the Dodgers put Brown's
33-year-old right arm in the hands of the arm doc.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe's report: Kevin Brown has a clean elbow and a clean
shoulder. Brown's right arm is the epitome of health. ``Dr. Jobe
said we got a bargain,'' said Dodgers' general manager Kevin
Malone. ``He should pitch for 10 more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Great. So now would be a good time to renegotiate, right?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone on hand chuckled at the notion of a $105 million
bargain and a warranty on a body part. But the Dodgers and Brown
are dead serious about two of these matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will take Dr. Jobe's report and some more of Rupert
Murdoch's money and buy some disability insurance on their
seven-year investment. Baseball people are already hooting at the
Dodgers giving a pitcher a seven-year contract; it would be double
jeopardy to have Brown's arm blow and not be covered.
</P>
<P>
   And Brown truly he believes he will pitch another 10 years. As
far as he's concerned, he can pitch as long as Nolan Ryan, who
didn't holster his gun until he was 46.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at every year as an opportunity to get better,''
said Brown. ``I'm never satisfied. I'm always looking to be better
and find a way to stay strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stay away from any freak accident, like falling down
a doorstep, I can be competitive for a long time. I'd like to be
like Nolan and pitch until I'm 46. I obviously don't look that far
ahead, but I believe in my heart of hearts that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus thought in baseball is that pitchers are poor
risks when it comes to multiyear deals. They only pitch every five
days as it is, and a torn rotator can end a career quicker than any
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   It will shock you not at all to learn that Scott Boras, Brown's
agent, doesn't agree. His research says a 33-year-old position
player is more likely to spend time on the disabled list than a
33-year-old pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   His client has never had any arm problems, and the last three
years of his career are comparable to those of Ryan, Steve Carlton,
Tom Seaver, Don Sutton and Gaylord Perry at the same age. And every
member of that group pitched into his 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the elite group of pitchers,'' Boras said, ``Kevin and Greg
Maddux are the only two who have not had any arm problems. When you
look at the general shortage of pitching, it supports the value of
someone like Kevin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team the Padres took to the World Series this year is
basically the same team they had in 1997, with the exception of
Kevin. He's durable, he wins, and he's getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's rich. Having landed his client a contract, Boras
doesn't need a Greek chorus for support. But he's dead-on in his
comparisons. Assuming Brown doesn't have a piano fall on his head,
he could be part of the Dodger rotation in 2005, when he's 40.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, a Hall of Famer, was 21-6 for the Padres in 1978 at the
age of 40. He would win 47 more games over the next five seasons
before finally accepting his AARP card. It's debatable whether his
career was spit-aided, but the numbers seem to hold water.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, a Hall of Famer, won 16 games at the age of 30 in 1975,
and 15 at the age of 40 in 1984. The ex-Dodger won 108 of his 324
games after turning 35.
</P>
<P>
   Seaver, a Hall of Famer, was 14-2 for the Reds in 1981 at the
age of 36. That was considered a fluke until he bounced back with
16 wins in 1985 at the age of 40, and 15 more in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton, a Hall of Famer, was 23-11 in 1982 at the age of 38. He
won 15 games a year later, and 13 when he was 40. He would pitch
until he was 43.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens has bounced back from a career pause to win a pair
of Cy Youngs after reaching 35. Dennis Eckersley, who just retired,
made more than 600 appearances after turning 30. And we all know
Fernando Valenzuela pitched into his 60s. (Lo siento, amigo.)
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who will be elected to the Hall of Fame next year, won 19
games in 1977 at the age of 30. Two years later, Angels' G.M.
Buzzie Bavasi balked at Ryan's contract demands. Ryan would move on
and pitch for another 14 seasons, throw three more no-hitters, and
win 71 games in his 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will settle for half that.
</P>
<P>
   A decade and several world titles from now, maybe everyone will
gather at the ceremony where Brown's jersey and Jobe's scalpel are
retired, and we'll giggle about how $105 million seemed like such a
large number back in '98.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
