<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' HISTORY OF FREE AGENTS A BUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Dodgers had considered their free agent history this
shopping season, they wouldn't have signed Devon White, much less
the $105 million man, Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have had little success in the free-agent market.
The signing of Kirk Gibson in 1988 produced a World Series, but
many people forget he played only 179 games the next two seasons
and left the team before the conclusion of the 1990 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to pin the past on them,'' said Dodgers
president Bob Graziano. ``We're dealing with different guys at a
different time, and the decision-making process has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse at Dodger free agent lore, or gore:
</P>
<P>
   Terry Forster:
</P>
<P>
   The first major free-agent acquisition, the reliever spent five
years with the team and played in the 1978 and 1981 World Series.
He had 22 saves in 1978, but made only 47 appearances the next
three seasons because of injuries. He's best remembered for giving
up the pennant-losing home run to Joe Morgan in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Goltz and Don Stanhouse:
</P>
<P>
   Two disastrous 1980 signings. A 20-game winner for the Twins in
1978, Goltz was 9-18 in two seasons here before being traded in
1982. Stanhouse was an all-star closer for the Orioles in 1979, but
made just 21 appearances for the Dodgers in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Class of '88:
</P>
<P>
   Despite modest numbers (.290, 25 home runs, 76 RBI), Gibson was
named N.L. MVP for leading the Dodgers to an improbable World
Series championship. The other '88 free agent signee, Mike Davis,
hit .196.
</P>
<P>
   He is best remembered for earning a two-out walk in the ninth
inning of Game 1 from Dennis Eckersley, giving Gibson the chance to
be a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry:
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers signed Strawberry from the Mets and he hit 28 homers
and drove in 99 runs in 1991. But he was hurt most of the next two
seasons, and a lapse in his drug rehab led to his departure. Brett
Butler, also signed in 1991, was probably the Dodgers' most
successful free agent, although he didn't win a postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Others of note:
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gott (1990) pitched for five seasons and had 25 saves in
1993. Hubie Brooks (1990) lasted one year. Kevin Gross (1991)
pitched a no-hitter but was 40-43 record in four seasons. Cory
Snyder (1993) hit around .250 in two seasons. Todd Worrell (1993)
saved 111 games between 1995 and 1997, but he ended '97 with a 5.28
ERA and the ire of most fans. Greg Gagne (1996) was a very slight
improvement on Jose Offerman at shortstop. Todd Zeile (1996) hit 30
homers in 1997. Jose Vizcaino (1997) was hurt at mid-season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
