<HEADLINE>
NASA OFFICIALS STRESS SAFETY TO WORKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid excitement over the success of its first international
space station assembly mission, top NASA officials have urged
thousands of workers involved in the U.S.-led project to guard
against becoming complacent over safety.
</P>
<P>
   New cautionary notes were sounded soon after the space shuttle
Endeavour touched down late Tuesday at NASA's Kennedy Space Center
in Florida. The shuttle's six-member crew joined the first two
modules of the orbital outpost during a 12-day flight.
</P>
<P>
   Full assembly will require six years, at least 35 more space
shuttle missions and more than 160 spacewalks by U.S. and Russian
astronauts. Space agency officials characterized Endeavour's flight
as one of the 17-year-old shuttle program's most difficult but one
of the less complicated for station construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not project forward that everything is going to be
easy,'' warned NASA administrator Dan Goldin as he greeted the
Endeavour crew. ``This is tough stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Holloway, NASA's shuttle program manager, said, ``Although
(the Endeavour mission) appeared easy, I can assure you it took a
lot of hard work, preparation and attention to detail to make sure
it operated the way it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway disclosed a memo circulated before Endeavour's Dec. 4
launching in which he urged workers to ``take stock'' of their
safety commitments based on what he characterized as three recent
``close calls'' for shuttles and other highly visible incidents in
commercial aerospace, such as the May 1996 crash of a ValuJet
airliner in the Florida Everglades that killed 110 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shuttle is a robust system and fundamentally very safe.
The people make it safe,'' Holloway said. ``I wanted to remind the
work force it is their responsibility and our responsibility. That
includes the decisions I make every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The incidents he cited include the previously disclosed loss of
the drag chute door on the shuttle Discovery as it launched Oct. 29
with a crew that included 77-year-old U.S. Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio.
The 11-pound aluminum door fell from the tail where a braking
parachute is housed for the shuttle's landing. The panel struck an
engine nozzle as it fell away.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences could have been catastrophic had the panel
struck and punctured enough of the 1,082 lines that circulate
explosive hydrogen through the three nozzles for cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said the cause of that incident still is under
investigation but appears to involve several factors. Those include
an unusually rough rocket engine ignition and an inadequate design
of the door hinges. In combination they permitted the vibrations to
shake the door off.
</P>
<P>
   The parachute was not used on Endeavour's mission and a redesign
effort for the door is under way.
</P>
<P>
   A second incident involved Discovery's June 2 launching to the
Russian Mir space station. Early in Discovery's ascent, a rocket
engine pressure sensor was rendered inactive by a small piece of
test equipment that had been inadvertently left inside a narrow
hydrogen line during ground operations.
</P>
<P>
   A backup sensor furnished reliable pressure readings to shuttle
flight computers.
</P>
<P>
   But had the disruption occurred later in flight, the computers
might have shut down the engine prematurely, triggering a launch
abort, Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   The initial incident he cited was also previously disclosed and
involved unmanned shuttle activity. On Nov. 11, 1997, the shuttle
Atlantis left Kennedy bolted atop a jumbo jet for a round of
modifications and inspections at Boeing Co. facilities in Palmdale,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Later, it was discovered that some of the large washers that
distribute the forces of the 150,000-pound shuttle on the fastening
bolts had not been installed. In a worst case, Atlantis could have
separated from the jumbo jet in mid-air.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
