<HEADLINE>
JOHN HANCOCK TO PURSUE ACQUISITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Hancock-Unit)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dormant in recent years as a buyer of financial
services firms, John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. is
reactivating the acquisitive streak it displayed earlier this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, among the nation's top 15 life insurers, said Wednesday
it would seek to buy smaller financial companies next year as it
prepares to go public. After raising cash in a planned initial
public offering in early 2000, Hancock intends to spend billions of
dollars more acquiring additional financial firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking for is to grow the asset management piece
of the business right now,'' Hancock chief financial officer Thomas
Mallory said. ``There's the possibility for more acquisitions in
1999, and after demutualization, the size of the acquisitions will
become much larger.''
</P>
<P>
   A company statement said Hancock would concentrate on smaller
mergers and acquisitions before converting from a mutual company,
owned by its policyholders, to a publicly owned company, a process
known as demutualization. Once publicly traded, the statement said,
Hancock would seek deals worth several billions of dollars to
expand products and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock is part of a larger trend among insurers seeking to cast
off the mutual form of ownership in favor of going public and
gaining access to capital markets to finance acquisitions.
Insurance companies are particularly keen to acquire more assets in
the retail fund, variable annuities, and pension businesses as well
as broaden the channels through which they sell products.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory said estimates Hancock could raise $10 billion to $14
billion in an initial public offering were ``a little high,''
adding that if market conditions were not right, the company could,
under special conditions agreed with regulators, delay issuing
stock until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock bought a host of smaller mutual fund firms between 1991
and 1994, building up its John Hancock Funds unit. Then it fell
quiet, selling off its Tucker Anthony Inc. and Sutro &AMP; Co.
brokerage and investment units in 1996 in much-criticized deals.
Hancock officials declined to comment on new acquisition targets,
but one fund industry source said the company was eyeing Nicholas
Applegate Capital Management of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry observers have wondered if Hancock would
eventually sell itself to a bank, possibly BankBoston Corp. or
Fleet Financial Group Inc. But Salomon Smith Barney analyst Colin
Devine said Hancock was behaving like a company that intended to
remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've actually decided that banks are in our
future _ that would appear very long term,'' Mallory said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its new expansion effort, Hancock appointed senior
vice president and former treasurer John Farady to head up a new
strategic acquisitions unit. Gregory Winn, a vice president, was
named treasurer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
