<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forbes questions Lockheed plant's future
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Newt Gingrich's departure as speaker of the House may
be a blessing to Lockheed Martin, since it will remove the last
protector of Lockheed's giant _ but costly _ suburban Atlanta
assembly plant, Forbes (Dec. 28) says. Now, Forbes contends,
Lockheed Martin Chairman Vance Coffman will be able to apply the
cost-cutting knife even to the World War II-vintage aircraft plant
that employs 9,600 _ a plant Forbes calls ``an albatross'' for
Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forbes, the company's third-quarter financial
report lists a writedown of $350 million to $400 million for the
first quarter of 1999, ``mostly to cover cost overruns on the
latest update of the C-130 Hercules, which is built in Marietta.''
Forbes suggests this may be ``a first installment'' on the cost of
closing the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes says the plant is also in trouble developing the Air
Force F-22 stealth fighter, a joint $40 billion program with
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Blackwell, president of Lockheed Martin's aeronautics
divison, rejects the idea of closing the Marietta plant, because it
would be too costly to do so, although he is closing 40 smaller
factory units in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts keep coming
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 forecast sweepstakes continue with magazines offering
their best bets for the year ahead.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (January) is out with
its annual forecast issue, which concludes ``there is more promise
than peril'' for investors in the year ahead. As for the ``Year
2000'' problem _ when computers will be confused by a year ending
in double zeros _ Kiplinger's says ``most things will still work.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual Investor (January) says the outlook for stocks ``is
as uncertain as it's been in awhile,'' which is why the magazine
suggests investors spread their risk. The magazine recommends
stocks in five groups: corporate titans (Time Warner), turnaround
plays (Motorola), on the move (Gulfstream Aerospace), special
situations (Monsanto) and bargain bin (Ford Motor).
</P>
<P>
   More consumer delights
</P>
<P>
   Glorious TV pictures, portable phones that operate anywhere,
artificial skin for treating disease, and Viagra, Pfizer's
impotence pill, are among the best new products of 1998, Business
Week (Dec. 21) reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be they lightweight computers, clever toys or medical marvels,
the products touch every part of our daily lives,'' says the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Gillette's triple-bladed razor, Yamaha's silent
violin that the musician hears via headphones, and without
disturbing the neighbors, and, of course, Furby, Tiger Electronics'
gremlin-like doll.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Success (January) offers readers a ``guide to the 21st
century,'' complete with advice on raising capital, hiring and
tapping new markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barron's (Dec. 14) looks at the best and worst of new stock
offerings in 1998, noting that IPOs _ initial public offerings _
looked dead in the water about five months ago only to come roaring
back, powered by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
