<HEADER>
A3595 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUCKER-NICARAGUA17-CO     12-16 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUCKER-NICARAGUA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martinez on mission of conscience
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dennis Martinez went home to Nicaragua in fine style
last month, traveling with Tipper Gore and six members of Congress.
``There I was on Air Force Two, like a dream,'' Martinez says. But
all the while, traveling to the hurricane-ravaged nation, he felt
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking: `Why do I, a kid from Nicaragua, have all that
I have?' '' he says. ``I've always felt proud about what I've done
in my life. But now I felt so bad to know I sit in my (Miami)
house, with whatever luxury I can have, eating and drinking
whatever I want, when so many people in my (homeland) suffer
without food or medicine or a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt ashamed of myself in a way. The more I think about it,
the more down I get. And the more I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Dennis Martinez, the winningest Latin American pitcher in
baseball history, a big leaguer for 21 seasons and a Brave in '98,
was in Atlanta on Wednesday, starting an effort to raise $100,000
here for Nicaraguans suffering from the devastation of Hurricane
Mitch. The idea is that Martinez, in conjunction with Turner
Broadcasting and WSB-TV's ``Family 2 Family'' project, can raise
enough money to buy a planeload of medical supplies. And then the
Hawks' team plane, underutilized these days, will fly the items to
Nicaragua on Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he returned from his trip on Air Force Two, Martinez
began a campaign to collect food, medicine and clothing in Miami,
and he talked a business executive into providing a plane to take
the goods to Nicaragua a few weeks later. For Martinez, so popular
in his homeland that he often is mentioned as a possible
presidential candidate there, it was another painful trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted the supplies, but they were more interested in
the boxes,'' he says, sadly. ``They said they could use the boxes,
which were large, to make a shelter over their children. Or turn
them into sleeping mats for the kids. That's how bad it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch killed 11,000 people, left millions homeless and
did billions of dollars of damage in Central America. Doing what he
can, Martinez will have another planeload of supplies ready to
leave Miami for Nicaragua soon. And among other things, he has
written letters to every major-league player and general manager,
asking for assistance. ``It hurt me _ I couldn't believe it'' _
when two teams wrote back saying they couldn't help, Martinez says.
He also was disappointed by the initial response from players, but
he says they have come around, and ``now, almost every day, one or
two checks arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   As he discussed Hurricane Mitch's devastation over lunch
Wednesday at a CNN Center restaurant, Martinez spotted Ted Turner
across the way. He chased him down and hugged him. Back at the
table, the 43-year-old pitcher said he hasn't decided whether he
wants to play baseball in '99. If he plays, he'd prefer to play
here, but the Braves haven't approached him. The Cleveland Indians
expressed interest, but he put them off until January. ``Right now,
my mind is not on baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tim(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   For information on how to join Martinez's efforts to help
Hurricane Mitch victims in Nicaragua, call 404-222-2972, extension
MITCH, beginning Friday.
</P>
