<HEADLINE>
HARVARD INVESTMENT EXECUTIVES' COMPENSATION UP 55 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of excellence keeps going up at Harvard Management Co.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation at the investment arm of Harvard University jumped
55 percent for the top six executives in the last fiscal year.
Jonathon Jacobson, the perennial top earner, became the first to
pass the $10 million mark. Two other managers fell just shy of $10
million each.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson, who left Harvard Management in July to start his own
private investment fund, made $10.2 million for the fiscal year
ended in June, up from $7.6 million the year before. Jacobson's
equity portfolios produced an extraordinary annualized return of
42.7 percent over the last three years. He declined to comment on
his compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, five Harvard money managers and the firm's
president, Jack Meyer, made $45.4 million, up from $29.2 million
the year earlier. The 1998 compensation is nearly four times the
$11.6 million that the top six executives were paid two years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   As it has in the past, Harvard Management defended the pay
levels, which have been controversial in some quarters because they
dwarf what top academics at the university receive. It said the
compensation reflected the value the managers had added to the
school's $13 billion endowment.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Harvard Management reported a total return for
fiscal 1998 of 20.5 percent, or 2.6 percentage points ahead of the
typical large institutional fund. Over five years, Harvard showed
an annualized return of 19.6 percent compared with 14.8 percent for
similar funds. Harvard estimates its outperformance provided the
university with an extra $2.7 billion over that five years.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most money management firms, Harvard is required to
report on compensation in the tax returns it files as a nonprofit.
Most of the compensation for money managers is tied to performance
rather than salaries, and factors in performance over three years,
Harvard says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an extraordinary three-year period and that is
what you are seeing in the bonuses,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Jacobson, the other top earners at Harvard
Management were: David Mittelman, a fixed-income manager, $9.8
million; Phillip Gross, equities, $9.7 million; Robert Atchinson,
equities, $7.9 million; Maurice Samuels, $6 million; and Meyer, the
president, $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lieberman, managing director of the Orion Group, a
mutual fund executive search firm in Princeton, N.J., said it was
not unusual to see a top mutual fund manager making $3 million to
$5 million. The $10 million paid by Harvard is unusual, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten million does not put them in a class by themselves, but in
the mutual fund business as opposed to the hedge fund business it
puts them on the high end,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 1927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN     12-16 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUG BOOK PROVIDES FOOD FOR THOUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Rich Martin  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everyone's looking for the perfect diet. Well,
here's one that will do the trick. Guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy. You need lots of protein, a little fat and some bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Try a Three Bee Salad for lunch. How about Cockroach a la King?
</P>
<P>
   David George Gordon has opened a new front in the anti-fat war
with ``The Eat-A-Bug Cookbook'' (Ten Speed Press; $12.95). And he
makes as good a case as can be made for eating insects.
</P>
<P>
   Livestock are a ``tremendous waste of the planet's resources,''
while chickens and pigs cause pollution. All those animals create
methane gas, which leads to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also points out in the 102 pages that we are eating bugs
whether we know it or not. The Food and Drug Administration lists
permissible amounts of insects in various foods. You may want to
put that sandwich down before reading this, but two or three
fruit-fly maggots are allowed in 200 grams of tomato juice and 34
fruit-fly eggs are permitted in a cup of raisins.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are finicky about eating insects, though he points out
how we don't mind scarfing down huge amounts of fat. On the other
hand, Colombians eat roasted ants in movie theaters and insects are
common fare in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Gordon is a good advocate. But I'm bugging out of this
menu. Our rating: (2 stars) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Yellowstone, like Yosemite and the Grand Canyon, can provide a
microcosm of the country's natural history. Paul Schullery, in
``Searching for Yellowstone'' (Houghton Mifflin Co.; $25), serves
up tidbits that provide penetrating insights into issues of
conservation and development _ inside and outside the famous
national park.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the 338-page book centers on the debate over Yellowstone
wildlife, which may be the park's biggest draw despite the geysers.
There are too many elk, or maybe there aren't. The philosophy used
to be that predators were bad and must be eradicated; now grizzly
bears and wolves are seen as enhancing the park.
</P>
<P>
   The book attempts to show how environmental views have changed
since Yellowstone inaugurated the National Park System in 1872.
Since World War II, Schullery points out, the emphasis has been on
the appreciation of nature on its own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Another major issue has been the preservation of species, with
Yellowstone the testing ground. Protecting single species has given
way to the prevailing view now of preserving habitat. Introducing
non-native species is no longer seen as a good practice.
</P>
<P>
   Schullery, a historian, outdoors writer and longtime Yellowstone
employee, is refreshingly free of agenda. He wonders how
Yellowstone could have avoided becoming such a popular park and
refuses to give in to environmental doomsaying _ one of the less
attractive aspects of the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Other enlightening parts of the book focus on the U.S. Army's
administration of the park in the 19th century and the prominent
role of railroad interests in early development. Our rating: (3
stars) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __Reading Robert Mohle's Southern California kayaking book makes
one want to get out there. That it stokes the flames of desire for
adventures may be the best possible recommendation for a guidebook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adventure Kayaking: Trips From Big Sur to San Diego''
(Wilderness Press; $15.95), includes 52 well-organized trips,
including nine in the Channel Islands and several others in Los
Angeles, Ventura, Orange, Santa Barbara, San Luis Obispo and
Monterey counties, as well as on the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   Each section includes topographic maps and voluminous data on
how to get to the location, recommended skill levels, camping,
water hazards and lengths of the trips. An introduction provides
some of the basics necessary before undertaking such journeys.
There is a decent appendix and plenty of description of personal
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   One can quibble about the 277-page work. It seems strange there
is only one Ventura County outing. And the photos, while decent,
would have been much better in color.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the organization, introduction and overall quality make this
a more-than-adequate guidebook. Our rating: (2{ stars)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
