<HEADLINE>
HUNT IS SACRED _ AT LEAST TO THE HUNTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``The Sacred Hunt II'' (Marty Stouffer Prods.;
$24.95) successfully argues the virtues of hunting but too often
engages in overkill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunt,'' by Randall L. Eaton, with music by 50-year-old rocker
Ted Nugent, states the case for the defense: The sport provides
what men lack and what they desperately need _ a connection to the
land. Further, the video shows the mythic aspects, especially
American Indian views of hunting, as a male initiation rite and the
respect paid to the quarry.
</P>
<P>
   The activity, its proponents say, provides a unique relationship
to the land and to our past as hunters. But that sounds arrogant,
since hiking, fishing and many other outdoor activities could be
touted as having many of the same benefits. And to say that killing
an animal affords some kind of religious experience is going too
far.
</P>
<P>
   But the hour-long video achieves its goal of portraying the
honorable form of hunting _ when the animal should be used and
eaten, not simply thrown away, and it observes the cycles of life
and death.
</P>
<P>
   The sumptuous photography itself is enough to recommend this
work, even after the argument (repeated in solemn tones) becomes
tiresome and starts to sound a lot like propaganda. Our rating: (2{
stars)
</P>
</TEXT>
