<SLUG> BC-MISSING-REPORTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY OF AMERICAN JOURNALIST FOUND IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _20The body of an American journalist missing in the
rugged mountains of western Mexico was found Wednesday by Mexican
soldiers, a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip True, the Mexico City-based correspondent for the San
Antonio Express-News, apparently fell to his death in the Sierra
Madre range's Chapalagana Canyon, on the border between the states
of Nayarit and Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
   True's body was recovered by an army helicopter and flown to the
city of Tepic, said an official at the American consulate in
Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   True, 50, was last seen on Dec. 4 in Jalisco. He had embarked on
a solo hiking trip Nov. 29 to a sparsely populated area of the
Sierra Madres to photograph and report on the Huichol Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all mourn the loss of a colleague and an outstanding
journalist,'' said Larry Walker, publisher and chief executive of
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Jesus Reyes Heroles, Mexico's ambassador to the
United States, said federal and state officials had few details
about the death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corresponding authorities are going to put all their
efforts and attention to this matter,'' Reyes said, expressing his
``deepest regrets for this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a story proposal made in March, True said he wanted to write
about the Indians because, in contrast to the Maya Indians of
Mexico's highlands, the Huicholes ``have retained a certain joy in
their life. This kind of joy gives them a certain integrity in
their being that allows them to welcome in strangers, something the
Maya are usually loathe to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A latecomer to journalism, True was hanging wallpaper until his
late 30s, said John MacCormack, a San Antonio Express-News
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by the time he was 50, he was the correspondent in Mexico
for a major Texas newspaper,'' MacCormack said. ``His dream came
true.''
</P>
<P>
   True's colleagues in the Mexico City press corps were stunned by
news of his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us correspondents _ and it's a very small community _ this
is a very sad day,'' said Paul de la Garza of the Chicago Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Eaton, bureau chief for the Dallas Morning News, said:
``This just breaks all of us up. This is not one of our great
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton recalled True as ``someone who really loved Mexico, and he
would go after stories with gusto.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sam Dillon of the New York Times: ``He was a good
reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   Born on June 18, 1948, in San Fernando, Calif., True graduated
from the University of California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be a teacher, but the school district wouldn't
hire him unless he cut his long hair,'' said his sister, Bonnie
Biggs, of Reno, Nev. ``Philip said his hair had nothing to do with
his teaching ability so he didn't cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   True moved to New York, where he worked on the docks and later
as a maritime union representative.
</P>
<P>
   He later made his way to the Texas-Mexico border and was hired
at the Brownsville (Texas) Herald.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the staff of the Express-News in 1992, and became the
newspaper's first border correspondent. He remained at the border
bureau in Laredo until January 1996, when he took over the Mexico
City bureau.
</P>
<P>
   As a newspaper reporter for the Express-News, True covered the
Zapatista uprising in Chiapas, opposition leader Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas' unsuccessful quest for the presidency in Mexico, the
massacre of Indian peasants in Guerrero, and Pope John Paul II's
historic trip to Cuba in January.
</P>
<P>
   He was still in Laredo when the Zapatista rebels launched a
brief uprising on Jan. 1, 1994, in the southern state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   True departed immediately for Chiapas and covered the rebellion
that ended 12 days later when then-President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari declared a cease-fire. Later that same year, True reported
on a meeting supporters held with ``Subcommander Marcos,'' the
Zapatista leader.
</P>
<P>
   His last major article for the newspaper was on the Sierra Gorda
Biosphere Reserve in Queretaro, Mexico, an environmental project
that has drawn international support and interest.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Marta, who is five months' pregnant
with their first child; his sister, Bonnie Biggs; and two nieces.
</P>
<P>
   A family member said True's body would be cremated in Mexico
City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
