<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMAN-CLONE17-COX     12-16 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMAN-CLONE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientists find Korean researchers' human clone claim suspect
 &HT;    By Diane Lore and Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ South Korean researchers said Wednesday they cloned a
human embryo through a breakthrough experiment - prompting other
scientists to question the accuracy of the claim and the Asian
team's medical ethics.
</P>
<P>
   The research team, headed by Kim Sung-ho and Lee Bo-yon of
Kyunghee University Hospital in Seoul, said they produced the
embryo using an unfertilized egg and a cell taken from the body of
a woman in her 30s. The embryo was aborted after it had divided
into four cells because of ethical and legal reasons, according to
the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But other cloning experts said Wednesday they were suspicious of
the claim and appalled at the attempt. No scientific papers had
been presented on the work and the team had not submitted their
results for peer review before making the announcement at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any information that suggests that they've
actually accomplished this,'' said Steven Stice, a world-class
cloning expert at the University of Georgia. ``And to say you have
four cells is a far cry from saying you have succeeded at cloning
humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Stice, formerly of Massachusetts, was the first in the world to
produce cloned calves that were also products of transgenics, the
science of altering and adding genes.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Roslin Institute near Edinburgh, Scotland, who
produced the first cloned mammal, Dolly the sheep, were also
puzzled by the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little in the reports to suggest that their work is
part of a substantial program of research,'' said Harry Griffin,
assistant director of the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Caplan, professor and director of the Center of Bioethics
at the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia, emphatically
disparaged the Koreans for what he called their ``cowboying their
way to headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First, science by press conference in an area like cloning is
very suspect,'' Caplan said. ``I believe that's a highly
inappropriate way to announce anything about cloning. If it is
true, it is an unethical, outrageous thing to have done, simply
because it would only be done for curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Caplan reiterated his earlier prediction that the first
human clone would be produced by foreign scientists. Many
scientists have agreed that human cloning is within the realm of
possibility, but say they will not pursue research in that field
because of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Caplan emphasized that for every successful animal cloning,
there have been dozens _ in some cases, hundreds _ of dismal
failures resulting in grotesque malformations that are horrifying
in animals and would be tragic in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even know yet if Dolly and the other animal clones
are healthy,'' Caplan said. ``Making people for curiosity when you
can harm them is the height of irresponsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the experiment, Lee said he used the same
technique used by Teruhiko Wakayama of the University of Tokyo, who
produced 50 cloned mice from several different adult animals in
July while at the University of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean experiment involved replacing the nucleus of the
donated egg cell with the nucleus of an ordinary body cell. The
scientists induced the egg to divide as if it were fertilized,
before the experiment was ended Friday. The embryo, if brought to
maturity, would have been genetically identical to the donor of the
body cell, they claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Wednesday it probably is possible to clone humans
through the technique, but that it is morally reprehensible to
attempt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that any of all of us could do (human
cloning),'' said Corey Goodman, professor of neurobiology and
genetics at the University of California-Berkeley. ``If you can do
it for mice and cattle, you can do it for humans. This is not a
question of can we do it but should we do it? And I thought that
had argument had already been settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman speculated that the South Korean researchers were
conducting human-cloning experiments because it has been banned in
many other countries, setting the stage for publicity in a country
that had not outlawed such experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Virginia Papaioannou, a professor of genetics and
development at Columbia University in New York, also said she
believes the science is possible, but that the ethical cost in
experimenting with humans is too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most responsible scientists have accepted that any technique
needs to be worked out very carefully in model animals and systems
before it could be applied to humans,'' Papaioannou said.
</P>
<P>
   And Stice, who's been successful at cloning, said there is still
a high failure rate with the procedure. It is indeed not difficult
to clone in the early stages. However, Stice said cloning experts
have found problems typically arise after embryos have developed
between 100 and 200 cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting beyond that is tough,'' he said. ``So there's no
indication that getting a four-cell embryo means you could get an
offspring.''
</P>
<P>
   Stice points out that one of the most difficult parts is getting
the embryos to thrive and implant properly. Stice's technique still
results in eight of 10 cloned embryos dying. And of those
implanted, only 20 percent survive. And that's considerably better
than the rate at the Roslin Institute. To get Dolly, the cloned
sheep, the institute made more than 250 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hilton Kort of Reproductive Biology Associates in Atlanta, a
leading infertility clinic, said four-celled embryos do have a
chance at successful implantation _ if the cells are healthy and
the development rate is on track. Typically, an embryo reaches the
four-cell stage roughly two days after the egg is fertilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see some embryos at 72 hours that are four cells,'' Kort
said. ``That's clearly not normal. Those embryos have a much lower
likelihood of implantation.''
</P>
<P>
   RBA waits to implant embryos in a woman's uterus until they are
between 6 and 12 cells, Kort said. RBA also has started implanting
embryos at a later stage of development, when they have divided
into hundreds of cells.
</P>
<P>
   News of the Korean experiment drew protests from local
environmental groups, and the South Korean parliament is
considerig legislation that would prohibit gene reassembling
experiments ``which infringe upon the dignity of human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the research team had no intention of creating a
complete human clone, but hoped the technology could lead to the
production of replicated organs for transplant. Lee said the
research team would not attempt to take the cloning experiment
further until there was a social, legal and moral consensus to
support it.
</P>
<P>
   Stice said he has not heard of Lee or his team, nor had others
in the tightly-knit cloning world community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid it might be just a ploy to raise public awareness
for their cause,'' he said. ``This is extremely unfortunate and I'm
totally against what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Patricia Guthrie contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
