<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SHOPPING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online shopping clicks in
 &HT;    By Frances Katz and Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This holiday season, it's not the crowds at the mall,
it's the crowds in front of the computer that shoppers must contend
with.
</P>
<P>
   The Web has emerged in 1998 as the year of the online shopper,
with millions of shoppers heading to the keyboard to buy most
everything they'd normally buy at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, America Online, the nation's largest online
service, said 750,000 first-time buyers logged on to do a little
holiday shopping. AOL said consumers snapped up everything from
toys to computer software. The company said the average shopper is
buying online twice every week, averaging $54 per order, more than
48 percent more than last year. Top categories for AOL users were
toys, children and baby items, apparel, books and music, and
electronics and video.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the apparel merchants, the Gap, J. Crew, Lands
End, Levi's, Eddie Bauer,'' says AOL's Vice President of E-commerce
Wendy Brown, ``it's literally as a good a selection as malls get. A
lot of people in America don't have access to these stores _ or not
all in one place as you have here. You're really seeing the
traditional things, but merchants have been able to use the space
to promote certain items.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of online shopping sales are as extravagant as
Amazon.com's stock price rise. A recent report by the Boston
Consulting Group and Internet retail trade group Shop.org says 1998
online sales will exceed $13 billion. Research firm Jupiter
Communications is half that optimistic, projecting $5.8 billion in
online revenue this year. But Jupiter predicts that by 2002, online
sales will hit $40.6 billion _ or equivalent to the current annual
revenue of Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday sales alone this year will reach $2.35 billion,
according to Dataquest Inc., a unit of research firm Gartner Group
Inc. Still, that's less than 1 percent of projected holiday retail
sales of $490 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix, the Web-based measurement service, reported this
week that online shopping sites show major growth across all gift
categories. In the week following Thanksgiving, Dec. 4 -10, Media
Metrix says online shopping increased 80 percent from the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix Senior Vice President Bob Ivins, who heads the
company's' e-commerce initiatives, said the week-to-week growth
patterns suggest that ``shoppers are motivated to use a mouse and a
modem rather than fight crowds in malls or on Main Street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go into one of the large bookstores and have to go
through what seems like a million books, then the Internet is a
feasible alternative for looking something up,'' said Beth
VanStory, vice president of Office Depot's online venture. Office
Depot took that theory, combined with its Internet-suitable
products, and launched a Web page in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, many of our customers don't shop for office
products for enjoyment. It's a chore, and the Internet makes it
easier,'' VanStory said. The site is generating sales equal to two
superstores, and VanStory expects that to increase 350 percent next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Office Depot sees the Web page as another channel of
distribution rather than a replacement for its sprawling
warehouse-style stores. But the company does expect online shopping
to impact its catalog business, VanStory said.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers to online shopping headed straight for the online
outposts of their favorite department stores, with department store
Web sites reporting a 137 percent increase in traffic over the
pre-Thanksgiving period.
</P>
<P>
   Reflect shopping lists
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix's most popular sites mirror the AOL users shopping
lists: book, music and movie sites such as Amazon.com, Barnes and
Noble, CDNow, Reel.com and others. Media Metrix reported 5.5
million visitors to those sites, followed by toys, apparel and
department store Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester analyst James McQuivey says one reason for the jump in
online shopping this quarter is that there are more things for
consumers to buy. ``Now everything you can think of is online,
including a Soviet satellite from online auctioneer eBay, although
nobody bid on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuivey used the satellite example to illustrate how many
products and retailers are online this holiday season who weren't
as recently as six months ago. ``There is more product online and
the people who were already shopping online reacted by spending
more because they had a comfort level and doubled the amount they
were spending. Then they went and told their friends, saying, 'You
should do this; this is the greatest thing since sliced bread,' and
then you have all these newbies coming online to shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had projected just over 2 million U.S. households would
shop online this quarter,'' McQuivey said, ``so AOL's numbers
indicate we are on track or maybe even conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds simple on its face to say there are more sites and
there are more people, but the reality is that there are so many
choices now that consumers are more likely than before to find an
online retailer they feel comfortable with.'' McQuivey also said
that the shopping boom is also partly due to online retailers
becoming more savvy in their use of Internet technology. ``They
explain privacy policies and made the ordering process faster. All
these little tweaks here and there mean more people are buying
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
