<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUITCAKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOU HEARD THE ONE ABOUT FRUITCAKE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CRAVEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Fruitcake.
</P>
<P>
   There, we said it. Go ahead and giggle. That it's the only
material denser than a neutron star. That it should be an element
on the Periodic Table of Culinary Crap. That U.N. inspectors were
alarmed that Iraq had obtained advanced fruitcake technology.
</P>
<P>
   Knock knock. Who's there? Fruitcake. Go away or we'll call the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment, and the jokes, aren't new. The baked confection
gets less respect than the tobacco industry. Its name is a slang
(and politically incorrect) term for the mentally challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Through all this, the fruitcake lives. No, it thrives. Its gooey
goodness continues to spread holiday cheer throughout the
hemispheres, and not just because it travels so well.
</P>
<P>
   Fruitcake inspires the kind of passion rarely associated with
fruit-based goods. Do you find such emotional Internet sites
devoted to the pros and cons of the raspberry Danish? Raisin bread?
Apple Betty?
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, cut into. Feel the surface give just slightly before
the knife slides in. Once inside, the knife meets just a slight
resistance before its dense treasures are revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Mmmm, pineapple. Cherries. Raisins. Walnuts. Dates. Pecans.
Those green chunks you can't quite identify but know are bursting
with fruity-nutty flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Few people participate in the annual ``Bring a Fruitcake to Work
Day'' (sponsored by the fictitious National Council of Fruitcakes).
But those who do say that, after their offerings receive the
popularly enforced snubs, the cake disappears bit by bit. Computer
techs report a higher incidence of ``foreign and very sticky
matter'' wedged between keys.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of fruit in cake is not lost on the good people
of Corsicana, Texas. If not for that simple combination of
ingredients, Corsicana might be known as ``The Gateway to Angus''
instead of ``The Fruitcake Capital of the World.'' Well, no one
really calls Corsicana that, at least to its face, but it is home
to Collin Street Bakery, where more than 33,000 fruitcakes roll off
the line each day during the holiday rush. That would be enough to
feed all residents of Corsicana each day, as long as they held
themselves to 1.3 fruitcakes each (and far above the U.S.
government's recommended daily fruitcake allowance).
</P>
<P>
   The bakery ships to 196 countries and is one of the few firms in
the world to be honored by the New York Gourmet Society as well as
the Texas Historical Commission. OK, maybe it's the only company
with those two plaques.
</P>
<P>
   (Warning, mandatory pun ahead.) Think people are nuts to like
fruitcake? The Collin Street Bakery makes a lot of dough. More than
$30 million a year in fruit, nuts and decorative tins.
</P>
<P>
   No one sends his favorite aunt a basket of holiday jelly
doughnuts. You can't order a lovely Santa tin of bear claws on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Fruitcakes are where you least suspect them. Like monasteries.
At least the monastery belonging to the Monks of Holy Cross Abbey
in Virginia's Shenandoah Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to prayer, solitude and communion with God, the
monks bake a mean fruitcake, one so good they unconditionally
guarantee it. Sales of the Monastery Fruitcake are the monks' chief
means of support. As ye bake, so shall ye reap. Be fruitcakeful and
multiply.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the monks' Web site (www. &QL; 
olworld.com/olworld/mall/mall &QL; 
(underscore)us/c(underscore)flower/ &QL; 
m(underscore)fruitcake/aboutcak.html) and learn not only of
Monastery Fruitcakes but of the demands of abbey life.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find such philosophical insights at www.pecanlogs.com.
In fact, you won't even find www.pecanlogs.com. Not even the star
of truck-stop snacks can compete with fruitcakes' popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Which came first, the fruits or the nuts? The holiday treat's
history is shrouded in baking mystery.
</P>
<P>
   It first was known for its mystical powers of healing . . . no,
wait, that refers to TV evangelists, not the kind of fruitcakes
we're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   First mention of the foodstuff apparently goes back to Roman
times, when it included ingredients such as pine nuts and raisins.
A century or so later (a mere decade in fruitcake years), Europeans
added spices, honey and preserved fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The cake traveled well, lasting weeks. Soldiers who didn't
consume it used it as impenetrable shields . . . hey, was that
another fruitcake joke? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
