<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECT-2NDTAKE-     12-16 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JERUSALEM: be heeded. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Netanyahu called the conditions ``the necessary principles for
the state of Israel to ensure its future.'' He said he would bring
them before his cabinet on Sunday. The principles are likely to be
approved by the cabinet but not in a subsequent vote e in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the necessary majority is not found to support these
articles, we will initiate early elections to get from the people
the mandate necessary to secure real peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Israeli campaign season opened, two years before
Netanyahu's term expires.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, the Labor Party leader, called for elections to be held
in the late spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' he said, ``the government has reached the
end of its road.''
</P>
<P>
   While Netanyahu was speaking, Barak already was dining with his
campaign consultants: James Carville, a former strategist for
Clinton, and Stanley Greenberg and Robert Shrum. Carville, a
Louisiana native who spent his first few days ever in Israel this
week, was referring to Barak as ``the candidate'' hours before
Netanyahu's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it was too early to describe strategy, Carville
nonetheless pounced on Netanyahu's ``lack of record'' and his
assessment that the Likud coalition ``is held hostage to small
extreme groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has been represented by another American political
consultant, Arthur Finkelstein, who formerly worked for Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Tichon, the speaker of the parliament, said earlier
Wednesday that in the no-confidence decision, Netanyahu's fate was
likely to hinge on a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Sharon was witheringly critical of his Likud
audience for failing to stand behind the prime minister when it
became evident he could fall. He evinced obvious distaste for the
political jockeying for votes that has consumed him in the last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you the problem started from within,'' he said.
``Attacks from the outside we could have withstood if we stood
together. But we're crumbling from within.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found ourselves in a situation in which it is
impossible to continue,'' he added. ``We cannot conduct a constant
chase after this or that member of parliament or minister.''
</P>
<P>
   The discordant and unsupportive rumblings within the Cabinet
have most plagued Netanyahu. His government began disintegrating
after he signed the land-for-security peace plan in October,
alienating the right, which elected him largely because he opposed
territorial compromise. Many felt betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   But it was when he start losing his top ministers that the
discomfort set in.
</P>
<P>
   The first blow came Tuesday when Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman,
a professional appointee and once a personal friend of Netanyahu's,
said he would resign, partly in frustration with the prime
minister's political manipulation of the budget process. Then came
news of Mordechai's intentions, leaving the impression that
Netanyahu's ministers were jumping ship.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai has been the staunchest supporter of the peace effort
within the cabinet, and he is reportedly alarmed that Netanyahu has
suspended carrying out the peace plan. During a cabinet meeting on
Wednesday, he warned that the Palestinian territories could erupt
in violent frustration.
</P>
<P>
   After the Cabinet confirmed there would be no troop pullback,
the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, termed the decision ``a
dangerous violation'' of the peace accord. One senior Palestinian
negotiator issued what sounded like a barely veiled threat that the
government could stand back and let the people take to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu's decision is a clear message that he wants to stop
the political process, and a public call to violence and a renewed
confrontation,'' Hassan Asfour said, referring obliquely to the
unrest in the West Bank that the Palestinian Authority had
suppressed during Clinton's visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
