<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-LEGAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL AND U.N. RESOLUTIONS CITED AS JUSTIFICATION FOR
ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The legal justification for Wednesday's bombing of
Iraq by U.S. forces is contained in congressional and U.N.
resolutions dating back to the 1991 Gulf War, government officials
and scholars of international law said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The most important element was the resolution adopted by the
United Nations to end the Gulf War in February 1991, which was
cited on Wednesday by James Rubin, the State Department spokesman.
That resolution provided for a cease-fire and established a system
under which Iraq would demolish any weapons of mass destruction and
allow unrestricted inspections by a U.N. commission of suspected
weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the legal authority to launch a military strike,
Rubin told reporters: ``I think one need go no further than talk to
the subject of the cease-fire resolution, Resolution 687, which set
forth the conditions for a cease-fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Iraq has thwarted the weapons inspections required by
the cease-fire resolution, Rubin said, the United Nations may then
fall back on the earlier resolution that authorized military force
and began the Gulf War, the start of which President George Bush
announced to the nation on Jan. 16, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Ruth Wedgewood of Yale Law School argued in the
current issue of the American Journal of International Law that the
cease-fire resolution was conditioned on Iraq's acceptance of
inspections of suspected weapons sites. By blocking the inspectors,
she said, the cease-fire resolution was automatically suspended.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, she also said that the United States was not
required to go back to the United Nations for additional
permission. She added that the bombing of Iraq in January 1993 by
forces from the United States, Britain and France reinforced the
notion that such nations may act by themselves to enforce U.N.
resolutions. That bombing occurred after Baghdad prevented weapons
inspectors from using the Habbaniyah airfield, effectively
preventing short-notice inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Ratner, a lawyer with the Center for Constitutional
Rights in New York, said on Wednesday that he believed that the
United States had no legal right to conduct the military operation
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner, who brought an unsuccessful lawsuit in 1990 trying to
block the Gulf War, said that after the cease-fire was in place,
all authorization to bomb Iraq ended.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United Nations would have to first formally declare
that there has been ``a material breach'' of the cease-fire before
it could fall back on the resolutions authorizing military force.
To do otherwise, he argued, would allow ``any nation in the world
to decide unilaterally that Iraq has breached its promise to abide
by the cease-fire resolution and bomb Baghdad.''
</P>
<P>
   A second legal issue is whether Clinton may authorize military
force on his own without congressional authorization. The
Constitution vests Congress with the sole power to declare war. Yet
according to various experts' tallies, presidents have dispatched
forces abroad between 130 and 200 times since the founding of the
Republic, even though Congress has explicitly declared war on only
five occasions: the War of 1812, the Mexican War, the
Spanish-American War and the two world wars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have argued that a resolution passed by
Congress on the eve of the 1991 Persian Gulf War provides the
justification for the president to act unilaterally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
