<HEADER>
A3658 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      12-16 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESET BY IMPEACHMENT, BUT TOTALLY IN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The American attack on Iraq, the growing
congressional support for impeachment, and the postponement of the
House vote on President Clinton's fate provide a window into what
power the president retains, what he has lost and how the country
has been altered in the last tumultuous week.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary set of events has shattered a decades-old
tradition that, until Wednesday, restrained opposition leaders from
questioning the political motives behind a president's national
security decisions, even as it fractured a century-old assumption
about how drastically an impeachment threat would weaken an
American president.
</P>
<P>
   By ordering a military strike at the time of his gravest
political peril, the president simultaneously signaled his hold on
power and underlined the brittleness of his position.
</P>
<P>
   And by questioning ``both the timing and the policy,'' as Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott did moments before Operation Desert Fox
began Wednesday night, the president's opponents shook the
bipartisan consensus that has traditionally accompanied the
beginning of American military involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with every precedent broken and every assumption shattered,
Clinton might be edging closer to destroying the ultimate political
assumption: That impeachment would shatter his effectiveness as a
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The military strikes were a joint undertaking of American and
British forces, and Prime Minister Tony Blair pointedly made a
televised statement first, almost certainly an effort to remove
political considerations from public perceptions. But even before
the explosions were visible above the Baghdad skyline, the
bipartisan consensus was endangered in Washington by a series of
remarks suggesting the president had ordered the air assault to
forestall impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never underestimate a desperate president,'' said
Representative Gerald B.H. Solomon, the New York Republican who
heads the House Rules Committee. GOP Representative Robert Barr of
Georgia added: ``For this sort of thing to seem to come to a head
on the eve of an impeachment vote is highly suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the president's actions demonstrated the remarkable
ability to carry on by a man who delivered the State of the Union
Message amid the wildfire of the Monica S. Lewinsky affair, ordered
air strikes against Sudan and Afghanistan amid the furor over his
grand-jury testimony, and pressed the Israelis and Palestinians to
embrace peace as the impeachment storm gathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``In areas where he has the ability to act unilaterally, like
bombing Iraq, he can still act,'' said Joseph Cooper, a political
scientist at Johns Hopkins University. ``But where he needs to make
compromises and elicit cooperation, it might not be so clear.''
</P>
<P>
   A Wall Street Journal/NBC News poll taken after the House
Judiciary Committee reported out its impeachment resolutions but
before the military action began in Iraq found that seven out of 10
Americans believe Clinton can still be an effective president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable he can carry on in the face of what is
colliding or collapsing around him,'' said Senator Jeff Bingaman, a
New Mexico Democrat who is a member of the Armed Services
Committee. ``He'll probably be able to do that if he's impeached.
He can continue doing what he's doing _ and keep on keeping on.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, the common American premise was that
impeachment was the surpassing stigma of American politics, an act
of discipline and disgrace that marked a president for historical
shame and exposed him to expulsion in a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, who in the past six years has upended so many of
the governing assumptions of politics, could be on the verge of
toppling traditional views of impeachment as well.
</P>
<P>
   Though the House Judiciary Committee has approved four
impeachment articles and the White House has failed to rally the
moderate Republicans who hold the balance of power in the
impeachment struggle, the House itself has not yet voted. Indeed,
it is possible that a major military action against Iraq could
change the political landscape in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the widespread assumption, in the White House and on Capitol
Hill, that Clinton's critics have sufficient votes to impeach the
president is being accompanied by the growing notion that the
president's policies and strategies might not be altered by
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been business as usual all year,'' said Senator Edward M.
Kennedy. ``Impeachment may not have any influence whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the clearest sign of the potential irrelevance of
impeachment came from a leading Republican, Representative E. Clay
Shaw Jr., who has worked with Clinton on welfare overhaul and who
is preparing to negotiate with the president on ways to shore up
the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-paragraph statement Shaw issued from his Fort
Lauderdale office before leaving for Washington for the expected
House vote, the Florida lawmaker, declared that he would vote to
impeach the president. His statement devoted two paragraphs to the
president's conduct, declaring there is a ``strong case against the
president on several of the impeachment resolutions'' and then
added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to be working closely with the president in my role as
chairman of the Social Security subcommittee of the Committee on
Ways and Means. It is my hope to reform Social Security with the
help and cooperation of Clinton as we did in welfare reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
