<HEADLINE>
PARTY GOES ON IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As the United States bombed Iraq Wednesday night, the
nerve center of its closest ally partied.
</P>
<P>
   As bombs rained down on Baghdad, the annual British Foreign
Office Christmas party was in full swing. Revelers sipped white
wine from France, red wine from South Africa and Foster's lager
from Australia. The diplomats and analysts who had to return to
their computer terminals for an all-nighter settled for orange
juice.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred journalists and diplomats mingled as the bombs
dropped, remarking on the incandescent beauty of the Locarno Room
off King Charles Street where the event was held.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was where the empire held court, when we ruled India,''
said George Jones, political editor of The Daily Telegraph, staring
up at the magnificent, pastel cathedral ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   While the right-wing press, including the Telegraph, has
disparaged the relationship between British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and President Clinton, portraying London as a Washington
lapdog, Jones does not dismiss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's serious, as I think the relationship between (British
Foreign Secretary) Robin Cook and (US Secretary of State) Madeleine
Albright is very close and very good,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The opulence of the Locarno Room, however, seemed to unnerve
more than one celebrant. Many of the people who attended the party
commented on the irony of what they described as London fiddling
while Baghdad burned.
</P>
<P>
   As he entered the room, Cook seemed a bit disarmed. In a brief
interview less than two hours before the attack, Cook seemed as
much at ease as he was nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the bombing would take place, Cook raised his
omni-arched eyebrows and said, ``I can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Cook was more interested in the fate of President
Clinton, asking an American newspaper reporter to explain the
timetable of the impeachment hearings should the bombing go ahead.
Advised that those hearings would likely be put off a week, Cook
asked, ``Really?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever seen or heard of ``Wag the Dog,'' the movie
that uses as its premise a president bombing a defenseless country
to divert attention from his indiscretion with a woman not his
wife, Cook shook his head and said, ``No. I've never seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics of the Blair administration say that Cook's
responses illustrate exactly what is wrong with the government,
that it is clueless to the realities of the Beltway, and that it
takes direction from Washington without question.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Office officials, however, are quick to rebut those
allegations, even if they are not as quick to supply their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff that we're in the pocket of Washington is so much
tripe,'' says a British official, barely hiding his contempt for
the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when the White House lined up its bombers, the only
indisputable ally was Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a microphone to the 200 to 300 journalists and
diplomats who had crowded into the Locarno Room for free booze,
food and advice, Cook said he had spent the last year accruing 177
hours in airplanes, visiting 29 countries, circumventing the globe
2 1/2 times, unable to claim frequent-flyer miles because they were
deemed unethical by some faceless bureaucrat.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Cook rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to take New Year's off,'' the foreign minister
informed those who dog him, ``and I will drink a toast to you _ one
by one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
