<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3669 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-IMPEACHMENT-1STL     12-16 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-IMPEACHMENT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS ATTACK ON IRAQ; HOUSE DELAYS IMPEACHMENT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Updates with Clinton address; House delays on vote.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton ordered sweeping air attacks on
Iraq Wednesday, prompting House Republican leaders to delay the
start of impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The president told a nationally televised audience that he
launched ``Operation Desert Fox'' on the eve of a scheduled House
impeachment vote to preserve the element of surprise and to avoid
initiating the campaign during the month-long Muslim holiday of
Ramadan that begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans leaders, anxious to avoid any political
fallout over voting on impeachment against the commander-in-chief
while U.S. military forces were in action, later postponed the
impeachment debate that had been scheduled to start Thursday. They
said the debate would be delayed for several days, possibly until
the beginning of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision on Iraqi military action came amid a growing
wave of House members declared their intention to vote for his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., questioned the
timing of Clinton's military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the timing and the policy are subject to question,'' Lott
said, adding that he had ``been assured by administration officials
that there is no connection with the impeachment process in the
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., complained: ``Is there anybody
who doesn't question whether the president has political motives?
It's time for this president to step down.''
</P>
<P>
   In his televised remarks, Clinton defended the timing of his
decision and said it was in response to a report from chief U.N.
weapons inspector Richard Butler that Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein had resumed cat-and-mouse efforts to hide components of
chemical and biological weapons and the missiles to deliver them
against U.S. allies such as Israel and oil-rich Arab nations in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The president said his national security team, including Defense
Secretary William Cohen, a former Republican senator from Maine,
unanimously endorsed the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had delayed for even a matter of days ... we would have
given Saddam more time to disperse his forces and protect his
weapons,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president referred only briefly to the impeachment struggle
that imperils his presidency, saying Hussein ``may have thought
that the serious debate currently before the House of
Representatives would distract Americans or weaken our resolve to
face him down.'' Not so, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   House Rules Committee Chairman Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., accused
Clinton of ordering the attack to delay or even thwart impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to do this at this time is just outrageous,'' Solomon
said. ``He should have delayed this. It would not have been
political the way it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., said she too feared that Clinton
might be ordering military action to stall impeachment. As Fowler
put it: ``I think this president is shameless in what he would do
to stay in office. He will use our military and he will use our
foreign policy to remain president.''
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger said the
impeachment struggle did not play any part in Clinton's decision to
order the attacks that had been suspended at the last minute in the
most recent showdown with Baghdad in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Chiefs of Staff, concerned that Saddam would disperse
his forces, advised the president that ``tactical surprise was
extremely important,'' requiring the United States to ``act as
swiftly as was militarily possible,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart rejected suggestions
that Clinton was using military action to distract attention from
the impeachment fight. ``The president of the United States makes
national security decisions based on the best interests of the
United States of America,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee and a former Navy combat pilot during the Vietnam War,
said decisive action by Clinton would rally public support, adding:
``Obviously, there will be those who will question his motives and
timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton continued efforts to urge Republican
moderates in the House to censure him rather than vote impeachment
for his cover-up of a sexual dalliance with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He met privately at the White House with Rep. Amo Houghton,
R-N.Y., author of a White House-backed resolution of censure that
included a $500,000 fine. Clinton postponed a planned private
meeting with Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., another moderate
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the president remained ``committed to finding some
bipartisan compromise that allows us to put this issue behind us
short of impeachment,'' adding: ``We continue to try to reach out
across party lines to find a bipartisan solution or compromise to
put this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore told a group of business leaders at the
White House that there was ``still time for Democrats and
Republicans to come together and embrace a bipartisan compromise to
seek a resolution that is both quick and fair.'' Gore still enjoys
strong ties with lawmakers on Capitol Hill after representing
Tennessee in the House and Senate for 16 years before joining
Clinton on the Democratic ticket in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. offensive was the third attack on Iraq during the
Clinton presidency. A total of 24,100 U.S. military personnel were
in the region as well as the aircraft carrier USS Enterprise and 22
other U.S. warships. Eight of the vessels are armed with 300
Tomahawk cruise missiles capable of delivering 1,000-pound warheads
against targets with pinpoint accuracy. A second aircraft carrier,
the USS Carl Vinson, is due to arrive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said more than 200 combat aircraft also were
available, including 15 Cold War-era B-52 bombers capable of firing
air-launched cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has ordered U.S. military attacks on Iraq twice before.
</P>
<P>
   During his re-election drive in 1996, Clinton ordered a
44-cruise missile strike against Iraqi military and command posts
in southern Iraq to retaliate against Iraqi troop movements against
Kurds in northern Iraq in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In June, 1993, Clinton ordered a 23-cruise missile attack
against Iraq's intelligence headquarters in Baghdad in retaliation
for an Iraqi plot to assassinate former President George Bush
during the ex-president's visit to Kuwait in April 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
