<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIPP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS EXPECTED TO RAISE QUESTIONS ABOUT TRIPP'S ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee
originally had hoped to use impeachment hearings to show that
President Clinton was set up by political enemies who colluded with
lawyers for Paula Jones and with lawyers from the office of Kenneth
Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Although the evidence is at best ambiguous, President Clinton's
lawyers and defenders contend that his pursuers set a perjury trap
that ensnared him in the scandal that threatens his presidency, and
the Democrats wanted the motives of his pursuers to be weighed in
judging the fairness of the case against him.
</P>
<P>
   But they were largely unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the judiciary committee, decided
against calling witnesses who played an early and pivotal role in
exposing the President's affair with Monica Lewinsky, the former
White House intern. Several Democrats on the judiciary committee
said they had wanted to call as witnesses Linda Tripp, Ms.
Lewinsky's former confidante; Lucianne Goldberg, a New York
literary agent, and a group of conservative lawyers with ties to
the Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate conducts an impeachment trial, it is almost
certain that Democrats will again try to raise questions about the
chain of events in late 1997 and early 1998 that led Mrs. Tripp,
who taped her conversations with Ms. Lewinsky, to the Jones lawyers
and then to Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a pattern to put attention on the prosecutors and
deflect attention away from the facts,'' said Charles Bakaly, a
spokesman for Starr's office. ``We have flatly said there was no
conspiracy or coordination between us and the Jones lawyers. It
just didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some new evidence about this early period emerged from the
hearings, although there are still many more questions than
answers. Late last week, the Judiciary Committee released a new
batch of documents, including a 29-page letter from Starr and
transcripts of taped conversations between Mrs. Tripp and Ms.
Goldberg. These documents shed more light on Mrs. Tripp's early
dealings with the Jones lawyers and with Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's letter, sent to Hyde and Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., on
Dec. 11, confirms that Mrs. Tripp's lawyer, James Moody, supplied
an early and crucial piece of evidence to Starr _ Ms. Lewinsky's
affidavit in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   In the affidavit, which Starr said his office received
anonymously by fax on Jan. 15, Ms. Lewinsky denied having a sexual
relationship with the president. The affidavit, which Ms. Lewinsky
later admitted was false, was a catalyst for Starr to seek
permission from the Justice Department to expand his Whitewater
investigation into the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   The president's defenders had earlier contended that Starr got
the affidavit, which Ms. Lewinsky's lawyer had not yet filed in
court, from the Jones camp. Moody, who was acquainted with lawyers
who had written briefs for Mrs. Jones, said in an interview this
week that he is ``99 percent sure'' that he obtained the affidavit
from the Jones lawyers. He said it was his idea to give the
affidavit to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   How and when Mrs. Tripp first contacted Starr's office has also
been much debated. In his letter to the judiciary committee, Starr
said he had not discussed the Jones sexual misconduct case against
President Clinton with Richard Porter, who was once Starr's law
partner at Kirkland &AMP; Ellis. Porter is friendly with several
lawyers who worked on the Jones case. Porter also had discussions
with Ms. Goldberg about how Mrs. Tripp might contact Starr's
office. On Jan. 8, one of Starr's prosecutors learned of Mrs. Tripp
from Jerome Marcus, another conservative lawyer with whom Ms.
Goldberg had talked.
</P>
<P>
   Months earlier, Mrs. Tripp and Ms. Goldberg first discussed the
possibility of tipping off the Jones team about the president's
affair with Ms. Lewinsky, according to a transcript of a
conversation the two women had in September 1997.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
