<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIPP-2NDTAKE     12-16 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIPP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: September 1997. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Is there any way,'' Ms. Goldberg asks, ``to have her be, uh,
shall we say, reached by the Paula Jones people?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp responds that Ms. Lewinsky, whose name she had not
yet disclosed to Ms. Goldberg, has no desire to go public or hurt
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp testified before the grand jury that fear compelled
her to tape her conversations with Ms. Lewinsky. She told the grand
jury that she was worried that the president's allies might try to
destroy her and that Ms. Lewinsky was pushing her to lie in the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tripp-Goldberg transcripts released by the judiciary
committee reveal another motive. Mrs. Tripp talked with her friend
about using her knowledge of the president's affair to help get a
book deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate is extremely good for this kind of information,``
Ms. Goldberg tells Mrs. Tripp. Mrs. Tripp responds that she would
have have ``no quarrel'' with taking some information to the
tabloids, in an effort to stimulate public interest. ``If it gets
out,'' Mrs. Tripp says, ``it gets it out quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goldberg tells Mrs. Tripp she must be ready to turn on her
friend, emphasizing ``you've got to really rat, and you've got to
tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp agrees. ``This would have been a great time for a
tape,'' she tells Ms. Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   By November, Mrs. Tripp was taping her conversations with Ms.
Lewinsky and talking to the Jones lawyers. On Jan. 16, the day she
helped Starr's investigators lure Ms. Lewinsky to the Ritz-Carlton
Hotel, Mrs. Tripp also briefed the Jones team about the
Lewinsky-Clinton relationship. Starr has said he knew nothing about
Mrs. Tripp's appointment with the Jones lawyers, and in his letter
he said no one from his office drove Mrs. Tripp to the appointment.
Starr acknowledged on the ABC News program ``20/20'' that he should
have kept better tabs on Mrs. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, in his deposition in the Jones case, Clinton was
asked detailed questions about Ms. Lewinsky, including questions
about the gifts they had exchanged and whether they had had
specific forms of sexual relations. His misleading answers to those
questions are at the heart of the impeachment articles facing him
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Moody downplayed the importance of the meeting
between Mrs. Tripp and the Jones lawyers on the eve of the
president's deposition, saying he arranged the briefing so that
Mrs. Tripp would not have to testify in the case. ``I did not tell
Starr's office,'' he said. ``It didn't seem appropriate for me to
tell them.'' He also emphasized that the Jones lawyers already knew
a lot about Ms. Lewinsky, including information about the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp, a Pentagon employee who is working at her job from
home, has been watching the impeachment proceedings in seclusion.
Her current lawyer, Anthony Zaccagnini, said in an interview, ``She
is not invested in impeachment. She has never said, `I hope he is
impeached.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
