<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WHIP-ART-700&AMP;     12-16 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WHIP-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAY FINDS LITTLE NEED OF THE HAMMER IN IMPEACHMENT DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-INTEL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-TRIPP, IMPEACH-HILLARY, IMPEACH-NY.)  (ART ADV: Photo is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(nk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Tom DeLay was a boy, his parents would wake
him early on Christmas mornings so he could help them finish
assembling the other children's toys. ``I read the instructions,''
he said. ``I've always been a rules person.''
</P>
<P>
   That affinity for the rules, the small print, the Bible and the
Constitution, says DeLay, the House majority whip, is the key to
why he is leading the drive to impeach President Clinton, although
he hastens to add that he isn't ``driving anything, just showing
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is why he has never doubted throughout the impeachment
battle that he is right. ``Believe me, I take no pleasure in
this,'' he said in an interview at his office. ``But it's
absolutely clear to me.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has been the House Republican leadership's point man on
impeachment for months, having kept the issue alive while other
Republicans pulled back. Fighting on procedure, he has blocked
efforts to make censure an option. And in filling a leadership void
that has opened between the speakerships of Newt Gingrich and Bob
Livingston, he has been ``the de facto speaker,'' in the words of
one senior Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, with more House Republicans announcing that they
would vote to impeach, the president's press secretary, Joe
Lockhart, said: ``Given the results, whatever he's saying it must
be awfully effective. Whatever power he has over members, he's
certainly proved to be a persuasive fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats also feel that DeLay, known as ``the Hammer'' for
his aggressive whipping of GOP members, shows excellent potential
as a replacement for Gingrich as the Republican they most love to
hate.
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay does not seem to mind very much. And if most of the
public does not agree with him on impeachment, that, too, is fine.
He figures that everybody who says the Republicans will suffer as a
result of the push toward impeachment is probably a Democrat;
leadership on the issue, he says, will solidify the party, if
anything.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has repeatedly and heatedly spoken of the president's
dishonesty, recently boiling it down to this: ``I don't believe a
word he says.'' And that, friends say, is at the heart of what
really bothers him about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A number of friends interviewed about DeLay mentioned his
honesty first. Clinton has said he thinks that both Anita Hill and
Clarence Thomas were telling the truth as they remembered it. Such
a notion is so different from DeLay's own much more static sense of
what is real and true, friends say, as to be an affront to him.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay says he tries to keep his personal feelings about the
president separate from the impeachment issue. But he allows:
``That's hard to do. I've seen what goes on, and I've been lied to.
Lies, stonewalling. What's happening now is the culmination of this
man's whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   He can remember the day he says Clinton first lied to him: Nov.
19, 1995. Not more than 15 minutes after congressional Republicans
agreed to end the partial government shutdown that had resulted
from a budget stalemate, the president went back on his word, DeLay
says, breaking an accord the two sides had just negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason Clinton should be impeached, DeLay said, is to
uphold the law and the Constitution, a tiny copy of which he has
carried in his pocket for almost 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, DeLay is not working the phones this week. He
is not calling in chits, mobilizing his 64 deputy and assistant
whips or orchestrating indirect communication through his staff. In
fact, he shows no evidence of whipping this one at all.
</P>
<P>
   He does not have to, fellow House Republicans say, because he
has made himself clear without resorting to arm-twisting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very effective at getting votes for the Republicans
through TV appearances or through what Tom calls intelligence
gathering,'' said Rep. Peter King, a New York Republican against
impeachment. ``Everybody knows his reputation of being the Hammer,
and it may help him so much he doesn't have to do anything. People
will still think he could make sure you don't get as much money
from lobbyists or longtime Republican contributors.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although DeLay, a former exterminator from Sugar Land, Texas, is
best known for applying blunt force, he is far more fluent in the
subtler political arts than his critics acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   His admirers say he is the best whip in a generation, because he
is able to tailor his sales pitches, making it his business to
understand each member's psyche and paying close attention to
vulnerabilities and motivations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows everyone's idiosyncrasies, quirks and buttons that
can be pushed,'' said Rep. Henry Bonilla, a fellow Texas
Republican. ``Someone will walk to the door in a meeting,'' Bonilla
said, and while no one else is paying much attention, DeLay will
note, `` `That guy needs a cigarette.' He's extremely wired to
everyone's personal needs.''
</P>
<P>
   His own motivations, friends say, are pretty straightforward: He
got into politics as a small-business owner frustrated by big
government. And always, he has been ambitious for both himself and
his hard-line conservative ideology.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, born in the border town of Laredo, Texas, grew up in
Venezuela, where his father was an oil drilling contractor. While
in grade school, he decided that he was a Republican at heart, much
to the surprise of his Democratic parents.
</P>
<P>
   He studied chemistry at the University of Houston because his
father wanted him to be a doctor, but ended up buying a
pest-control business. Soon the red tape was bothering him more
than the bugs. About that time he suffered his only electoral
defeat, in a race for treasurer of the Texas Pest Control
Association, to a competitor he still refers to as ``my nemesis.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, after reading a how-to book on campaigns, he ran for
the Texas Legislature and became the first Republican ever elected
from Fort Bend County. He was elected to Congress in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   A born-again Christian and ally of the religious right, he spent
much of the last year fighting losing battles like the drive to end
financing of the National Endowment for the Arts. And on a personal
level, he said, ``it's been a horrible year,'' between the upheaval
in the Republican leadership and, particularly, the shootings this
summer in which two Capitol police officers, one of whom worked in
DeLay's own office, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   With all that, though, he says his faith keeps him from worrying
too much about what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy,'' he said, and pointed to a wooden plaque in his
office.
</P>
<P>
   It reads, ``This could be the day,'' in reference to the end of
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
