<HEADLINE>
MUSLIMS EXPRESS RESENTMENT AT ATTACK NEAR RAMADAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait _ With Ramadan, the Muslim month of mercy,
just days away, early Arab reaction to the American-led air strikes
on Iraq included flashes of the kind of resentment that President
Clinton said he had hoped to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had launched the attack early Thursday morning
here in part because, to have waited until Ramadan began would have
been ``profoundly offensive to the Arab world.'' Still, some people
interviewed at random here and in Cairo, Egypt, said they found the
timing of the attack offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramadan is a great month,'' said Khaled Abdulkarim, a
40-year-old Qatari visitor to Kuwait. ``It should have been a time
to bring the Muslims and the Arabs closer together, not tear them
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is bad timing,'' said Mohsen Abdel Salam, a
35-year-old physician in Cairo. ``As a Muslim, it fuels my anger
against America and its policy towards us as Arabs and Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in ordinary times, the attitudes of Arab governments and
people about American strikes against Iraq often seem conflicted.
</P>
<P>
   And on the cusp of Ramadan, several experts said a sense of Arab
solidarity with the Iraqi people could spill over into animosity or
perhaps even terrorist strikes against the United States if what
President Clinton called ``unintended Iraqi casualties'' of the air
strikes include large numbers of Iraqi civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Arab leaders and ordinary people say the religious and cultural
ties they feel with ordinary Iraqis have made them deeply
uncomfortable with military action.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, Kuwait _ with its vivid memories of Iraqi
occupation in 1990 and 1991 _ has been a hawkish exception.
</P>
<P>
   As the news spread early this morning that an attack the United
States has threatened for so long had begun, car horns around the
city could be heard honking in celebration. But the attack began at
1 a.m. in Kuwait, and governments around the Arab world did not
volunteer any immediate reaction.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear, for example, whether Saudi Arabia would permit
the U.S. war planes based on its soil to take part in attacks on
Iraq, something the Saudi government has said in the past it would
oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramadan-related pall over the military action had been
anticipated, diplomats said, and researchers in Washington and
London have spent weeks seeking precedents that might soothe the
expected Arab complaints.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the prophet Mohammed and his army battled in Mecca
during Ramadan against those they regarded as infidels. And Arab
armies have often chosen to disregard the holiday, most notably
with the simultaneous Egyptian and Syrian attacks on Israel that
began the 1973 war.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, Muslims are taught that war during Ramadan is
unacceptable except in self-defense, a view that was repeated time
and again here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Saddam was hoping the holiday would protect him,
because he knows that Muslims don't want a war during Ramadan,''
said Mohammed Saleh, 30, a Kuwaiti customs officer. ``I don't want
a war during Ramadan either.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past six weeks, a diplomatic drive by U.S. officials has
succeeding in persuading eight Arab governments _ Egypt, Syria,
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and five other countries in the Persian Gulf _
to put new distance between themselves and the Baghdad government.
</P>
<P>
   But with Ramadan now at hand, Kuwaiti-based diplomats suggested
that the United States and Britain might best avert complaints if
the attack is wrapped up before the holy month begins over the
weekend. (The exact timing depends on the sighting of the new
moon.)
</P>
<P>
   In briefings in Washington, U.S. officials would not say
specifically when they expected the attacks to end. Defense
Secretary William Cohen said that he ``wouldn't want to set any
time frame'' and that the attacks would continue ``until such time
as we accomplish our set goals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
