<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME RELIEF WORKERS STILL IN BAGHDAD
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In the hours before the U.S. and British
military strike began Wednesday, all international arms inspectors
were hurriedly evacuated from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But 133 relief workers remained behind at the United Nations'
Baghdad headquarters on the orders of Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's decision, based in part on fears of the risks involved
in evacuating dozens of people over a long desert road to Jordan by
night, caused concern among some officials, who feared for their
colleagues' safety in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   About 73 U.N. relief workers were able to leave Iraq, most for
scheduled holiday breaks that some of them had moved forward to get
out of the country sooner than planned.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining foreigners working for the organization and for
its agencies were sent to the U.N. headquarters at the Canal Hotel,
a former hotel school on the edge of Baghdad, to sleep in their
offices.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the U.N. Special Commission, the inspectors who
have been disarming Iraq and whose headquarters are also in the
Canal Hotel, said Wednesday night that the commission was in touch
with relief workers in the building and that there had been no
problems in the early hours of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Another 232 relief workers are in the Kurdish areas of northern
Iraq. They remain on duty, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
