<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-FUGITIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FUGITIVE ZIMBABWEAN LEADER SURRENDERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Zimbabwe's former president, the
Rev. Canaan Banana, who fled Zimbabwe just before his conviction on
sodomy and sexual assault charges last month, turned himself in to
authorities there Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Banana, 62, who had been in hiding in Botswana and South Africa,
arrived at the High Court in the capital, Harare, in a Mercedes. He
was dressed, as usual, in a Mao-cut suit and walked with a cane.
</P>
<P>
   Through his lawyer, he told the judge he had not fled the
country to escape justice, but to discuss politics with other
African leaders. The court ordered him placed under house arrest in
his mansion in the Harare suburbs. He is due to be sentenced soon
and could face up to 22 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In a short discussion with reporters on the courthouse steps,
Banana said ``political assassins'' were ``carrying out a plot
against me.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 26, Banana was convicted of 11 counts of sodomy,
attempted sodomy and indecent assault, all stemming from incidents
with young male bodyguards, gardeners and cooks assigned to him
when he was president from 1980 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The charges grew out of the 1995 murder trial of a police
inspector, Jefta Dube, who killed a colleague; Dube said the man
had taunted him, calling him ``Banana's wife.''
</P>
</TEXT>
