<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHBASE17-COX     12-16 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 BASE17-COX &HT;    ANTI-IMPEACHMENT FORCES CAUGHT FLAT-FOOTED
 &HT;    EDS: Story has been reskedded for Thursday's publication.
 &HT;    510 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a postponed but still-looming vote in the
House of Representatives, stunned Democrats are puzzling over the
revival of an impeachment effort they thought they'd snuffed out.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the outnumbered pro-impeachment forces had steadily
gained momentum. But where were the labor unions and the rest of
President Clinton's political base? Where were the Wall Street
financiers and business leaders to warn against the uncertainty?
</P>
<P>
   Despite a last-minute flurry of activity from Democratic allies,
many of Clinton's champions were barely visible for the past five
weeks, as momentum gained for impeachment in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was almost disbelief that this was actually going to get
to this level,'' said Naomi Walker, spokeswoman for the AFL-CIO.
The labor organization had suspended its stop-impeachment efforts
after the Nov. 3 elections in which Republicans unexpectedly lost
seats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought (Republicans) had heard what they said in
November'' and would give up on impeaching Clinton, Walker said.
The unions have hurriedly reassembled a lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street and in corporate America, the silence has been
deafening.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, a former Wall Street investment
banker, has made no apparent attempt to whip up concerns about the
economic effects of an impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the underlying economy, which is in the long run
what drives markets ... I think the most likely scenario is still
to look forward to solid growth and low inflation,'' he said
Wednesday, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have business leaders expressed a general concern about
instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is a business issue,'' said Frank Coleman,
spokesman for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. He said his members,
instead of viewing it as an economic question, are asking, ``Do we
really want to do this?'' and ``Don't we want to draw the line
somewhere?''
</P>
<P>
   The president's admitted misconduct also has been a factor. It
has sapped some of the enthusiasm from defenders, according to
longtime Clinton ally, Will Marshall, president of the Progressive
Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plenty of people have rallied behind the president and
defended him over the course of the last year,'' Marshall said.
``And many of them felt burned when he, in the end, was forced to
admit what had happened'' in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said ``most people think he acted deplorably,'' and he
added many Democrats have therefore shifted their focus from
Clinton himself to defending ``the results of a democratic
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has had the steady backing of African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson has called a prayer vigil at the U.S.
Capitol for Thursday, the day the impeachment date was originally
scheduled to begin. But even Jackson has not been highly visible in
the Clinton defense in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, our presence will have made a statement,'' Jackson
said in calling for the 11th-hour vigil. ``If we lose the vote, at
least we were witnesses to this action.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
