<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREAN SCIENTISTS SAY THEY CLONED A HUMAN CELL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ South Korean scientists said Wednesday that
they had cloned a human cell from an infertile woman, creating a
four-cell embryo that theoretically could have grown into a
genetically identical replica of the woman. But they said that
because of the legal and ethical implications of their work, they
stopped the experiment and did not try to create a human clone.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, at a major hospital here, are believed to be the
first to publicly claim that they taken steps to clone a human
being. Their research has not been confirmed or reviewed by other
scientists, but experts in the United States said that although
they did not know of the scientists' work, the requisite techniques
had been demonstrated in animals and that there was no theoretical
reason they could not be applied to people.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean researchers said they let the embryo reach only
four cells before halting the experiment and did not take the
critical step of implanting the embryo in a woman, so there is no
guarantee that it would have developed into a fetus. Still, the
research shows how quickly cloning, dismissed as science fiction a
decade ago, has crossed into uncharted ethical territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need some genetic proof that this really happened,'' said
Dr. Alan DeCherney, chairman of the obstetrics and gynecology
department at University of California, Los Angeles. But what is
``interesting,'' he said, is ``if they're trying it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Scotland, researchers at the institute that produced the
first clone, Dolly the sheep, also expressed skepticism about the
Korean claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``By stopping the experiment when they did, the Korean
researchers are unable to provide any evidence that the transferred
nucleus had been successfully `reprogrammed,''' said Harry Griffin,
assistant director of the Roslin Institute in Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In the experiment, conducted by a three-person research team at
the Kyunghee University Hospital in Seoul, scientists at an
infertility clinic said they cultivated a human embryo by using an
unfertilized egg and an ordinary, or somatic, cell donated by a
woman in her 30s. They used a technique similar to the one used by
researchers at the University of Hawaii who announced in July that
they had cloned mice.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean government restricts the cloning of humans, though it
does not ban it outright. There is a significant amount of cloning
experimentation in South Korea, and some experts say that it is
about as advanced as that in Japan, where scientists recently
cloned eight calves from a single adult cow.
</P>
<P>
   Yukio Tsunoda, a scientist at Kinki University who led the
recent cloning of the eight calves in Japan, said that he had
little information on the research work by the Korean team. But he
said that since cloning of animals could be done, he did not see
any scientific reason why cloning humans could not. Moreover, he
said it is possible that human cloning to the same stage reached by
the Korean team may have been done secretly in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than admiration, however, the work in Korea inspired
outrage and was immediately denounced by lawmakers and civics
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We oppose the cloning of human cells,'' said Jung Myoung-hee,
director of Green Korea United, a group concerned with ethics in
biology and environmental pollution. ``This is not an advancement
for medical technology and now we have to be prepared to accept
international criticism. The result of this experiment is not
something Koreans should be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason other countries have not developed this
technology is because they feared the ethical repercussions, not
because they lacked the technology,'' Jung said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhee Shang-hi, a legislator, along with 35 other lawmakers
introduced a proposal in Parliament last month that would strictly
limit experimentation on areas that ``may damage the integrity of
human life,'' according to a statement released by Rhee's office.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sung-bo, who supervised the research team, said he was very
aware of the ethical issues surrounding his experiment. He added
that while he was worried that such concerns could sometimes stand
in the way of medical advances, his team had no plans to disregard
ethical standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of developing our technology while
disobeying the rule of ethics,'' said Kim by telephone. ``But if
conditions are ripe and if we can reach a point of agreement with
medical experts around the world, we are willing to continue our
experiment within limited boundaries, but not involving the
implantation of an egg into a uterus.''
</P>
<P>
   Implantation was the key step that the team did not take. If
they had taken the embryo and implanted it in the woman's uterus,
they said, it perhaps would have developed as a fetus and been born
regularly, but they chose not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The team said it plans to publish its results, but did not have
a timetable. Kim said that the team had not videotaped the work,
but that members planned to include photographs in their
description of the work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think they wanted to experiment on the early stage of human
embryo growth, which is potentially a technology of making
clones,'' said Shohei Yonemoto, senior researcher at Mitsubishi
Kasei Institute of Life Sciences in Japan. He noted that even if
the embryo had been implanted, the success rate of in-vitro
fertilization is only about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's colleague in cloning the human cell, Lee Bo-yon, said
Wednesday that ``cloning humans was not so high-tech.'' He also
stressed, however, that the experiment was not related to solving
infertility problems for patients at the clinic, and that
participants had received permission from the donor to use three of
her eggs for experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the team cultured six eggs on two different
occasions from two different women. But only one developed into an
embryo. In the successful round, Lee said that on Dec. 8 he took an
egg from a woman and removed its nucleus, which contains its
genetic material. In its place, he put the nucleus from a somatic
cell, which is a typical cell from the body. By Dec. 10, the cell
had divided into four cells, a stage at which it could have been
implanted.
</P>
<P>
   Though it may appear relatively simple, the experiment could be
looked upon in the future as a milestone. ``It might be said that
this experiment was a trigger,'' said Yonemoto, at Mitsubishi. ``It
showed proof that human cloning is possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
