<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn charges America to revive public service
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Retiring U.S. Senator John Glenn on Wednesday
challenged a standing-room-only crowd crammed into the Ohio House
chambers to rekindle respect for public service.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a rare joint session of the Ohio House and Senate
gathered to hear him, Glenn praised the representatives and
senators for entering public life. He said the public now thinks
little of politicians and that too many people are cynical about
the value of public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is vital that everyone be willing to devote at least some
of their talents and a portion of their time to solving the many
pressing problems that plague our communities, our country and our
world,'' Glenn said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn received standing ovations and applause throughout his
visit Wednesday in Columbus as he was featured in a downtown parade
and in his speech to the Legislature. He and his wife, Annie, are
traveling throughout the state this week taking part in events
marking the conclusion of his 24-year Senate career and his
November mission aboard the space shuttle. He will finish attending
public events this weekend in his hometown of New Concord.
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Bob Taft praised Glenn for bringing honor to all
Ohioans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a man who came from a small town but held big dreams,''
Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   The parade brought out crowds of downtown workers and
schoolchildren to line several blocks to cheer Glenn. Children who
were too young to remember even Glenn's failed presidential bid
from 1984 clamored to get a front-row seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all want to meet him and get his autograph,'' said Chance
Leslie, who was shepherding four Cub Scouts through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is scheduled to visit the Dayton area at 4 p.m. today at
Carillon Park to return a portion of the Wright brothers' first
powered aircraft he took with him aboard the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Glenn said, the country has had no traumatic
events such as those in the past that forced people to care about
their society. The Depression and the wars that followed showed
people the need for being active in society. Today, Glenn said,
young people want no part of politics or serving the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to convince them, young people in particular, that our
democracy has no room for the cynicism and apathy that we find
toward politics and government in our society,'' Glenn said.
</P>
<P>
   After he leaves the Senate, he will be an adjunct professor at
Ohio State University helping establish the John Glenn Institute
for Public Service and Public Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn also stressed the message that his shuttle flight has sent
to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nation needs our efforts and our wisdom every bit as much
as we need that of our younger citizens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He joked that his age, 77, was overplayed during his shuttle
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no truth to the rumor that NASA refused to
schedule a space walk for me because they were afraid I'd wander
off someplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
