<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3735 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NATIONAL-REPORT-T     12-16 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NATIONAL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURROUNDED BY SUCCESS, VOLS ARE COMING UP SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The football team is celebrating a wondrous 12-0 season and
preparing to play for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The women's basketball team is coming off its third consecutive
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   So, what the heck's going on with Tennssee's men's basketball
team? The Volunteers were ranked No. 9 in The Associated Press
preseason poll, but they are on the ``early-season disappointment''
list, along with Xavier, Temple, and Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations probably got to us a little bit,'' sophomore
point guard Tony Harris said. ``We figured teams were going to lay
down to us because we have the No. 9 ranking by our name. We
haven't been in the upper echelon \Rbefore\S. Now that we've got a
taste of how NCAA basketball is going to be, we know what to
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers finished 20-9 last season under first-year coach
Jerry Green and made the NCAA Tournament. They returned all five
starters, added top recruit Vincent Yarbrough and welcomed the
return of frontcourt force Charles Hathaway, who missed most of
last season with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   But projecting teams' success in preseason is an inexact science
(and calling it a science gives too much credit to the people
making the predictions). However, it made sense to figure the
Volunteers would be one of this season's top teams. Didn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably everyone was looking at the way we were playing the
last eight or 10 games of last year and saying, `You've got a good
freshman coming in and a good post coming back, and you should be
good,' '' Green said. ``The problem is, we're not playing as well
as we were. Expectations are good on paper, but you've got to play
the game. We have a few people not playing as well as \Rthey did
last year\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Green didn't name names. But senior guard Brandon Wharton, in
particular, is struggling. He's averaging 9.3 points while shooting
30 percent from the field and 19 percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is 6-3 and unranked. The Volunteers' three losses have
come against Arizona, Miami (Ohio) and St. Joseph's. All three of
the losses came on the road, which makes Saturday's game at 5-0
South Florida another potential pothole.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have as good a basketball team in terms of personnel as
there is in the country,'' South Florida coach Seth Greenberg said.
``They're one of the top 10 most talented teams, without a doubt.''
IN THE LANE CALHOUN: IT WAS PITT-IFUL
</P>
<P>
   There was more to Connecticut's great escape at Pittsburgh on
Saturday. The top-ranked Huskies scored five points in the final 10
seconds for their 70-69 victory. And that just stirred UConn's
emotions all the more.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun has filed a protest with the Big
East Conference regarding conditions at Fitzgerald Field House,
which is undergoing renovations. Calhoun claims there was no heat
in his team's locker room and that he and his players were pelted
with objects and racial slurs during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut sophomore point guard Khalid El-Amin hit the winning
shot, then appeared to showboat when he jumped on the scorer's
table to taunt the Pitt student section. El-Amin was upset with
comments about his weight, his Muslim religion and his fathering a
second child that was born this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it out of a lot of frustration from the crowd,'' El-Amin
said. ``From them yelling things and throwing stuff. Emotion was
running high.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitt athletic director Steve Pederson disputes Calhoun's claims
about a frigid locker room and said he has not been able to confirm
Connecticut's claims of fan misconduct.
NOT IN GREEN BAY ANYMORE
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin, which held on to beat Texas on Tuesday night, is
ranked No. 23 in this week's Associated Press poll. For Badgers
coach Dick Bennett, it's the first time in 14 seasons he's had a
team ranked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the best team I've coached,'' said Bennett, who
coached at Wisconsin-Green Bay and Wisconsin-Stevens Point before
coming to Madison. ``I've had a number of teams I felt were
stronger than this one, but they just weren't ranked. They don't
rank you if you're in Green Bay in basketball, no matter how good
you are.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-1 Badgers have won eight in a row, with road victories
against Rhode Island and Temple in addition to their defeat of the
Longhorns. Wisconsin's only loss came to New Mexico State in the
Top of the World Classic last month.
AN AUBURN MAN
</P>
<P>
   Computer programmer and sports nut Jeff Sagarin got a lot of
attention during the football season. He was the man who crunched
the Bowl Championship Series strength-of-schedule numbers, and his
computer ratings were one of three used by the BCS.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sagarin's basketball rankings _ which first brought him to
the attention of the sporting public _ are causing a stir. His No.
1 team in this week's rankings isn't Connecticut or Duke or
Kentucky. It's Auburn, which is 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't watch that much basketball,'' Sagarin said. ``I
haven't seen Auburn play, but from doing this over the years, I bet
they are a very good team to have such a good rating after nine
games.''
STUDENT OF THE GAME
</P>
<P>
   Arizona reserve guard Josh Pastner is scheduled to graduate
Saturday and then fly to Las Vegas to join the Wildcats for their
game against Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Pastner, a walk-on from Kingwood High, near Houston, completed
his degree requirements in family studies in just 2 1/2years. He
wants to become a coach, and he zipped through school so he could
``show prospective employers that he is able to accomplish whatever
he set his mind to.''
FREE THROWS QUOTABLE
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State junior point guard Mateen Cleaves, on his
early-season struggles that have been a factor in the Spartans' 6-3
start:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing Mateen Cleaves basketball right now. My game
is going to come in time, and when it does, we're going to be an
awfully tough team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Lute Olson on his team's No. 8 ranking in The
Associated Press poll:
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, in my opinion, we're not in the top 40. To rate us
in the Top 10 is an absolute joke. We're not anywhere close to
that. From the tapes I've seen, I think we're fifth in the
Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana coach Bob Knight, ever the comic when it comes to his
friends in the media, discussing reporters' academic credentials
when asked about the Hoosiers' weeklong break for finals:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think you ever had to take a final in journalism, did
you? You just had to spell your name and they passed you. I just
wanted to throw that out about finals for those of you who are
unfamiliar with them.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Coppin State, better known as America's Guest, is again playing
a difficult nonconference schedule. The Eagles ``stopped by'' their
home facility Saturday and Monday for Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference games. That was after playing _ and losing _ their first
seven games on the road. Coppin State plays at Kansas State on
Monday, the first of five more road games. Coppin's next home game
is Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   When George Washington played DePaul on Dec. 6, St. John's coach
Mike Jarvis showed up to watch the team he used to coach. When his
successor, former Texas coach Tom Penders, was ejected with just
over nine minutes remaining, a fan yelled, ``Mike Jarvis, come on
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
