<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY WOULD BE GLAD TO SEE CLINTON RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the Resignation.com website, you can chat about
the president's future, read Richard Nixon's resignation speech,
order ``Gore 1998'' T-shirts for $16 apiece, and enter a contest by
predicting the date and time of Bill Clinton's self-imposed
departure from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner,'' said Arianna Huffington, the conservative
commentator and resignation advocate who set up the website in
September, ``gets a free trip to wherever Clinton decides to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Games aside, the idea of President Clinton resigning is no joke.
This week, senior House Republicans, including majority whip Tom
DeLay and Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, have called on
the president to step down and spare the nation what they say could
be a protracted and paralyzing Senate trial in the wake of a House
vote to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could really be heroic if he did that,'' Hyde said Sunday
on ``Face the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, traveling in Israel at the time, immediately rejected
the suggestion. He said he had ``no intention'' of resigning and,
in fact, the notion had not even crossed his mind. But surveys show
that it is on Americans' minds. In a Washington Post poll conducted
over the weekend, 58 percent of respondents said they believed the
president should resign if the House voted to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls this week have showed weaker public support for
resignation, though in all of them, a majority of Americans
register their fear that putting the president on trial in the
Senate would be bad for the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great gift for the nation if the president gave
it a Monica-free 1999,'' said Huffington, who has collected more
than 100,000 names on a resignation petition on her website, which
she said has been ``phenomenally busy'' this week.
</P>
<P>
   Huffington said Wednesday's presidential order of US airstrikes
on Iraq, challenged by Republicans as timed to thwart impeachment,
is an example of why Clinton has to do the ``selfless thing'' and
resign. ``We live in too dangerous an international environment to
have decisions of the commander in chief second-guessed,''
Huffington said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for the president's resignation began in January, after
his extramarital affair with former White House intern Monica S.
Lewinsky became public, and they intensified in newspaper
editorials and political circles after he testified before
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's grand jury, and then gave a
much criticized speech to the nation in August.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats see a strategic calculation by Republicans in
raising the volume on resignation now. To woo wavering moderates,
Hyde and other Republicans on the Judiciary Committee downplayed
the House's role in removing the president from office. Now that a
vote in favor of one or more articles of impeachment appears within
reach, House leaders are pressing the president to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a coup d'etat by impeachment,'' said former
Massachusetts governor Michael Dukakis. ``Republicans have been
gunning for this guy, and it drives them crazy that he not only is
president, but that he remains very popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing Clinton should do is resign,'' Dukakis said.
``It's preposterous, just like the charge the president committed
an impeachable offense is preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who would sit in judgment of the
president in a Senate trial, agrees. ``It's absolutely imperative
that he resist this call and that he remain in office,'' Kennedy
said. ``It's enormously important from a constitutional point of
view and because of the nature of the charges against him.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, President Nixon resigned before the full House voted on
articles of impeachment. In 1868, Andrew Johnson, the only
president impeached by the House, fought against the odds and for
his job, and was acquitted after a Senate trial by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a historical perspective, it is possible to fight it out
and change your legacy,'' said Allan Lichtman, a history professor
at American University. ``History may record a process that was
vicious, partisan, and mean-spirited, and Clinton could emerge not
as a disgraced president but as a comeback kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Senator Alan Simpson, a Wyoming Republican, sat through
what he said were two ``numbing'' Senate trials of federal judges
who were impeached. Simpson said a Clinton trial could take months
and prevent the Senate from accomplishing anything else. Yet he
doesn't expect that to carry much weight with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who has followed this tragic story knows that this
man is constitutionally incapable of resigning,'' said Simpson, who
now directs the Institute of Politics at Harvard's Kennedy School
of Government. ``They could put him on the rack, they could begin
the tortures of Salem on him, but they should know there is
something in the extraordinarily complex DNA of Bill Clinton that
won't let him resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson recalled it was Republican Senator Barry Goldwater who
visited Nixon and told him that for the good of the country, he had
to quit. Simpson does not believe any Democratic senator has that
kind of relationship or leverage with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is brilliant and remarkable, but his whole pattern is
never to put his state or his country above himself,'' Simpson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reich, Clinton's former Labor secretary and now a
professor at Brandeis University, said a significant difference
between Nixon and Clinton is that Nixon had been abandoned not only
by his party but also by the American people. Clinton's approval
rating hasn't wavered in months; it is above 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a terrible precedent for the president to be
hounded out of office when a majority of the public supports what
he is doing,'' said Reich, noting he ``doesn't believe for a
moment'' Clinton will step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in tight spots before, and this is definitely his
hardest challenge,'' Reich said. ``But few mortals have managed
like he to wiggle out of or escape more difficult straitjackets.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has argued against impeachment by warning that a
Senate trial would cause turmoil. Nevertheless, several senators
have suggested the Constitution requires them to carry through with
a trial and not cut a censure deal with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``All bets are off if this goes to the Senate,'' said pollster
John Zogby, who is tracking public opinion on impeachment. ``I
don't think time is on the president's side. The more people want
this whole thing to go away, the closer we get to reaching the
unthinkable _ that Clinton won't finish his term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
