<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAIN-MALADY-BOS &LR;      12-16 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-MALADY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATAL BRAIN MALADY NOT `MAD COW DISEASE,' OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Massachusetts woman who died recently of a brain
malady called Creutzfeld-Jakob disease had the classic form of the
disorder normally seen in North America and not the European
variant popularly known as ``mad cow disease,'' state health
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The family of the deceased patient, a Taunton woman in her
seventies, had asked health officials whether her case might
represent the first case of mad cow disease on this side of the
Atlantic. But officials said the case fits the pattern of classic
Creutzfeld-Jakob disease, or CJD, which results in six to eight
deaths a year in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alfred DeMaria, the state's chief of communicable diseases,
said classic CJD is readily distinguishable from the variant linked
in Britain and France to ingestion of beef from animals with a
similar disorder called bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variant form of CJD has more gradual onset of symptoms, it
involves people under the age of 50, and its course unfolds over a
period of 12 to 14 months rather than the six to eight months of
classic CJD,'' DeMaria said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Classic CJD begins with movement disorders and symptoms of
dementia, such as memory loss and confusion, which worsen rapidly.
The European variant initially causes psychiatric and behavioral
abnormalities with gradual onset.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 30 cases of the European variant have been reported,
most in Britain. Their emergence led to wholesale
government-ordered slaughter of cattle and export restrictions on
British beef to curtail any possible spread.
</P>
<P>
   Classic CJD arises spontaneously in individual patients due to a
mutant protein which builds up in the brain, causing sponge-like
holes in the brain. It is not transmitted from one person to
another except in unusual circumstances, such as from contamination
of surgical instruments used in brain or eye surgery. Some patients
contracted the disease from injections of growth hormone derived
from human pituitary glands, but that form of the hormone has been
supplanted by a genetically engineered drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been monitoring CJD back to 1990, and have found no
trend in terms of age or rate of disease that would be of any
concern,'' DeMaria added.
</P>
<P>
   The US Centers for Disease Control has alerted states to watch
for any cases that might suggest the appearance of variant CJD on
this continent, but so far none have emerged, DeMaria said.
</P>
<P>
   Two research groups since the 1980s have documented CJD among
individuals in Texas and Kentucky who ate squirrel meat, including
brains. Unlike cattle, however, squirrels are not known to suffer a
brain equivalent to human CJD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
