<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA-BOS &LR;      12-16 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ ATTACK SHIFTS COVERAGE   OFF IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A nation anticipating, or resigned to, an
additional burst of impeachment stories Wednesday instead saw TV
screens awash with reports about the US military strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   For viewers, the sudden switch in focus may have evoked memories
of Jan. 22, the day the White House sex scandal broke. Amid much
advance ballyhoo, major network news anchors had gathered in Cuba
to cover the pope's unprecedented visit, but when the scandal
broke, the anchors quickly redeployed to Washington. That began a
year of unrelenting media focus on the Monica Lewinsky case that
Wednesday gave way to the reality of combat.
</P>
<P>
   For TV and newspaper reporters already scrambling to keep up
with the fast-moving story of a possible presidential impeachment,
the military action meant a swift change in plans. ``We're on a
dual track now, covering both,'' said NBC News reporter Gwen Ifill.
``The reporters are just trying to keep all the balls in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Many out-of-town reporters and camera crews had arrived here to
cover the House impeachment debate, but found themselves reporting
instead about the military action to their viewers back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's two stories, and reporters have double-duty,'' said
Keith Plummer, chief photographer for Hearst-Argyll Television, as
he unloaded cameras from the back of a van outside the Capitol.
``There's just so much going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer set up extra cameras at sites near the House and Senate
sides of the Capitol, gathering live-shots for the evening news
packages of local newscasts in the Hearst-Argyll chain. NBC Senate
producer Roberta Hornig, who makes daily calls to congressional
leaders and key members to gauge the prospects for impeachment,
Wednesday expanded her must-call list to include members of the
Foreign Relations and Intelligence committees. To each member of
Congress she reached, she asked questions about impeachment and the
hostilities in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two stories now,'' said Hornig. ``You have to cover
them both, and see how they relate.''
</P>
<P>
   A news conference held by Senator John F. Kerry illustrated the
new duality. Kerry announced his support for the Clinton
administration's decision to use force in Iraq, but reporters also
peppered him with questions on whether the military action was
related to the threat of impeachment hanging over President
Clinton's head, and whether Kerry believes there might be 67 votes
in the Senate to convict Clinton if the House votes to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike during the beginning of the Gulf War in 1991, CNN was not
the only network in Baghdad Wednesday. CNN military affairs
reporter Jamie McIntyre reported details of the military strike
Wednesday at 5:02 p.m., shortly before it occurred. A spokeswoman
Wednesday night indicated the network did so only after concluding
it would not jeopardize the mission. ``We have a policy of total
prohibition against going on the air with anything that could
jeopardize people's lives,'' said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   If the public is weary of the impeachment saga, as poll after
poll suggests, the same is true of some reporters on Capitol Hill
who came to work Wednesday expecting to see at least the beginning
of the end of the story that has dominated their work lives all
year.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted a twinge of sympathy from one Capitol Hill staff
member as she watched reporters scurrying around. ``You work and
work and work, and you think the story is going to come to some
resolution, but it just goes on and on,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
