<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS SUPPORTS ATTACK, BUT TIMING DIVIDES REPUBLICANS
</HEADLINE>
   (htv) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress were bitterly divided
Wednesday night over the timing of the air strikes against Iraq,
and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott fiercely attacked President
Clinton's policy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting with House Republicans, Rep. Bob Livingston of
Louisiana, the speaker-designate, called on Republicans and
Democrats ``to support our troops now that they're deployed.'' But
clearly skeptical of the timing of the attack, Livingston said,
``we'll leave that to the best judgment of the American people.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is on the Armed Services
Committee, said if Clinton acts decisively, he will win public
support.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there will be those who will question his motives
and timing,'' said McCain. ``He will receive significant support
because it's pretty obvious that Saddam Hussein is neither
complying nor cooperating'' with international arms inspectors.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in an extraordinary rebuke of the president's foreign
policy, Lott, stood virtually alone in opposing the air assault on
suspected Iraqi chemical, nuclear and biological weapons sites,
arguing that the attacks were ineffective. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot support this military action in the Persian Gulf at
this time,'' Lott said in a statement, infuriating the White House.
``Both the timing and the policy are subject to question.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For months, Lott has criticized the administration for failing
to take more aggressive steps to topple Saddam. Under pressure from
Congress, Clinton enacted the Iraq Liberation Act in October, which
earmarked $8 million to support Iraqi political opposition. But in
a letter to Clinton on Wednesday, Lott and five other Senate
Republicans said only $58,000 of that money has been spent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I will support serious and sustained action but will oppose
action that does not accomplish our larger strategic goal,'' Lott
said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But even as Lott raised objections, House Republicans were
planning to vote Thursday on a resolution of support for the troops
in the Persian Gulf.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The core of the debate among Republicans, who were suddenly
chastened by the spectacle of impeaching the commander-in-chief
while he launched one of the biggest military strikes since the
1991 Persian Gulf War, was over the timing and motivations behind
the aerial bombardment that began on Wednesday night.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious they're trying to do everything they can to
postpone the vote in order to get as much leverage as they can,''
said Rep. Gerald Solomon of New York, a former marine who is
chairman of the House Rules Committee, said on CNN. ``For him to do
this at this unbelievable time is just outrageous.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, who is retiring this year, issued a press release
entitled, ``Bombs Away _ Save Impeachment for Another Day?''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler of Florida, the fifth-ranking Republican and
a member of the House National Security Committee, said: ``I'm very
suspicious of the timing.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans accused the president of bombing rogue nations
or terrorists when he was in political binds in the past. The last
time the United States launched air strikes, said Rep. Spencer
Bachus of Alabama, they ``destroyed a drug store in the Sudan and
two camels in Afghanistan.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham of South Carolina put it bluntly: ``The
trust level is low.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But several other Republicans, many of whom are vocal critics of
the White House, set aside partisan differences, and defended the
president.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He has our full support as long as he's president to take any
action he deems necessary,'' said Rep. John Mica of Florida. ``I
don't think they conflict at all.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sherwood Boehlert of New York, who announced Wednesday that
he would vote for impeachment, said: ``I really do believe that in
sensitive foreign policy issues, partisanship does stop at the
water's edge.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Edward Porter of Illinois, another moderate
Republican, echoed similar sentiments: ``The president is the
president. I respect the office and I respect the judgments that
have to be made in regards to Iraq and the situation there.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats quickly threw their support to the president. Rep.
Dick Gephardt of Missouri and Sen. Thomas Daschle of South Dakota,
the House and Senate Democratic leaders, said in a joint statement:
``The president has made the correct decision to undertake military
action against Iraq at this time. Any delay would have given Saddam
Hussein time to reconstitute his arsenal of weapons of mass
destruction and undermine support for our efforts.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., a decorated Vietnam veteran, said
Wednesday that no one should question the ``legitimacy'' of
Clinton's decision to bomb Iraq. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that every reasonable member of the United
States Congress and reasonable people of this country will
understand the legitimacy of this moment. And no one will question
that once again, once too many times, it is Hussein who has
precipitated this confrontation and no one else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein is responsible for the coincidence,'' said
Kerry. ``Saddam Hussein is responsible for the timing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, criticized Lott for violating
an unwritten rule of backing a president's foreign policy decision
once U.S. troops are in action.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed and surprised,'' said Biden. ``Senator Lott
doesn't do foreign policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 2104EST &QL; 
