<SLUG> BC-POLAROID-CUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAROID CONFIRMS WARNINGS OF WEAK PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polaroid Corp. Wednesday provided yet another quarterly snapshot
of bleak images: nearly 700 jobs cuts, $90 million in one-time
charges, the loss of Serafino ``Sandy'' Posa, its top marketing
executive, and indications of lower revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Investor reaction was instant as Polaroid shares reached a
52-week low of 17 7/16, before closing at 18 1/4, down 5/8. That's
more than 30 points below its 1998 high of nearly 50 in January and
less than half the 40 a share that the Cambridge, Mass. photography
company commanded three years ago when it recruited Gary T.
DiCamillo as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts shrugged off the latest moves, noting that in
October the company warned that fourth-quarter results would be
worse than those for the third quarter. The company's also said
Wednesday that it had won a two-year extension on a $350 million
credit line, which analysts said would help it buy time to
stimulate sales while reducing inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important news, at least locally, was that
Polaroid would cut its work force again. The elimination of 600 to
700 jobs, or up to 7.6 percent of its payroll, is expected to take
12 to 18 months. It follows January's announcement of a reduction
of 1,800 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The combined cuts will leave the pioneer of instant photography
with about 9,000 employees at the end of this year _ down more than
3,000 from 12,000 five years ago and significantly below the 21,000
employees Polaroid had in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early going, DiCamillo was taking decisive action and
doing the right kinds of things at a seemily rapid pace,'' said
Michael W. Ellmann, vice president of research at Schroder &AMP; Co.
``But at this juncture whether the company difficulties are due to
DiCamillo dropping the ball or if the structural challenges facing
Polaroid are essentially overwhelming is still not clear,''
</P>
<P>
   The company blamed the collapse of the Russian market for part
of the write-down, as well as lackluster overseas sales, which
account for about half its revenue, and the need to further reduce
dealer inventories. But most Wall Street analysts said the heart of
the company's problems was the lack of significant new consumer
products for this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Ellmann and other analysts maintain that DiCamillo is under
pressure to show improved results in 1999. So far, only one
promising new camera product for the consumer market, a disposable
instant camera, is being test marketed in Atlanta with plans to be
sold nationwide early next year. It will be the first of 20 new
products Polaroid plans to introduce next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's announcement puts Polaroid on a more solid footing to
enter 1999 poised for profitable growth,'' said DiCamillo, who has
recruited a senior management team from other consumer products
companies to sell the new cameras and film.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, one key player, Sandy Posa, Polaroid's senior
vice president for worldwide marketing and new product development,
abruptly resigned, citing ``personal reasons.'' His departure
surprised Polaroid observers since DiCamillo picked him just three
months ago to run all marketing ahead of Carole J. Uhrich, a
32-year veteran of Polaroid. She returned to running manufacturing
and logistics as part of a corporate reorganization that merged the
consumer and commerical imaging divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The change in management prompted B. Alex Henderson, a
Prudential Securities analyst who has been critical of the company,
to question whether Polaroid has difficulties getting new products
ready for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Posa, 44, a former senior vice president of business development
at Kraft Foods North America, was replaced by Jerry Noonan, 39, who
came to Polaroid two years ago to manage consumer products from
Nabsico Biscuit Co., where he was senior vice president of
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts have been critical of DiCamillo's tenure
because the company has largely developed product extensions or
repackaging of existing consumer products. Newer products are aimed
at niche markets, such as a low-cost thin flashlight that uses the
same batteries as its instant film packs and a line of high-priced
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   And while the company has revamped its bread-and-butter instant
film line and expanded into digital photo printers, several new
products, such as a digital camera, called PhotoMax, have had
difficulty competing against similar filmless equipment from
Eastman Kodak and Japanese camera makers.
</P>
<P>
   If digital cameras pose a major challenge, Polaroid faces an
even bigger competitive threat in what it knows best. Barely 6 1/2
weeks ago Fuji Photo Film Co., the world's second largest
photography company, said it was considering selling instant film
and cameras in the United States. Fuji's reason for entering the
instant film market: Some of Polaroid's key patents are expiring.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid will take fourth-quarter charges of $50 million for the
job cuts and $40 million to write off Russian assets. The company
said the Russian assets include receivables, inventories, fixed
assets and prepaid expenses. In addition, the company expects to
take a pretax gain of about $22 million in the quarter from the
sale of some buildings in Cambridge for $27 million, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid expects the moves to save it $20 million to $30 million
in the next two years, offsetting a similar increase in interest
costs from the new loan, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
