 By BRENDAN M. CASE, with JOACHIM BAMRUD and DOUGLASS STINSON 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ In Mexico, NAFTA stands for change. Five years
after it took effect, NAFTA has become the leading impetus for the
far-reaching transformations sweeping the world of Mexican
business. Open markets and competition have obliged executives to
rethink their companies, pushing them to face up to the challenge
of free trade. And, during the economic crisis of 1995, NAFTA threw
a life-line to hundreds of Mexican companies, even as unfettered
foreign competition helped push weaker firms out of business.
 &HT;    The North American Free Trade Agreement has given a turbo boost
to commerce between Mexico and the United States, and turned Canada
into Mexico's second-largest trade partner, with interregional
trade growing at double-digit rates and causing huge traffic jams
at border highway crossings and rail yards. ``NAFTA constitutes one
of Mexico's greatest competitive advantages,'' says Luis Rubio, a
noted economist who is director of Mexico's Center for Development.
``It is an exceptional tool for the development of the Mexican
economy, attracting much foreign investment that translates into
jobs, technology transfer, indirect export opportunities through
supply chains, and training for workers and executives. In
addition, it generates secure access to the U.S. market.''
 &HT;    The effects on companies in the United States and Canada have
been positive as well, though more modest in scope. In many ways,
the trade accord simply ratified and codified trends in
manufacturing sectors such as textiles and automotive trades. But
for companies in other industries, and for smaller companies that
had not previously considered exporting, NAFTA has provided a
window of opportunity to increase sales and rationalize costs.
While the macroeconomic effect on the two larger countries has been
minimal, for companies that have directly benefited from the new
markets, NAFTA is exciting and successful.
 &HT;    Indeed, on a company-by-company level, some patterns are
emerging as to how NAFTA is affecting the way companies do business
in North America. The last five years have seen a major increase in
cross-border joint ventures and foreign direct investment,
especially in Mexico. Relocation of labor-intensive manufacturing
processes to Mexico _ not only from Canada and the United States,
but from Central America, the Caribbean region and even as far away
as Asia _ has occurred, especially in automotive, electronic and
textile work, the three leading trade segments under NAFTA. ``NAFTA
has made it possible for manufacturing companies to make decisions
based purely on manufacturing costs,'' says Chris Padilla, director
of international trade relations for U.S. imaging company Eastman
Kodak, which recently announced that it hopes to save US$1 billion
over two years by shifting production of its X-ray film processors
to Mexico, to add to assembly operations of one-use cameras and
printed circuit boards. Film production, a capital-intense process,
has been centralized at one U.S. plant for all North American
sales.
 &HT;    Any Mexican consumer with money to buy U.S. imports profits from
low tariffs. But most Mexicans, many of whom have seen their
purchasing power decline just as free trade rose in influence, are
not celebrating NAFTA. To millions of Mexicans, direct benefits
from the accord have been scarce.
 &HT;    Even from a corporate viewpoint, the benefits of open borders
are concentrated in several hundred world-class large companies and
a limited number of smaller ones with the pluck, luck and know-how
to crack export markets.
 &HT;    Mexico's overall exports have doubled since 1994, from US$60
billion annually to an expected $120 billion for 1998. Exports to
the U.S. have grown to nearly $100 billion, making Mexico the third
largest supplier of goods and services to the U.S. market after
Canada and Japan. With U.S. exports to Mexico at about the same
level, Mexico is the second-largest market in the world for U.S.
products.
 &HT;    Big Mexican companies have been clear winners. Grupo Alfa, a
$3.9 billion conglomerate, exports a quarter of its sales. Grupo
Desc and San Luis Corporaci have become major autoparts suppliers
to the U.S. market. Grupo Industrial Bimbo, a breadmaker, and Isaac
Saba, a textile magnate, both made multimillion-dollar acquisitions
in the United States in their respective fields during 1998.
 &HT;    Most small companies that make up the backbone of Mexico's
employment, if not its production, have been left out of the party,
lacking the resources to mount the market research and seek foreign
buyers, or _ due to diverse factors _ simply fail to compete in
global markets. Take Alejandro Hernandez, a metal stamper in Mexico
City. Back in the early 1990s, he was one of thousands who believed
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's pledge that free trade would
vault Mexico out of chronic poverty. So he took action, borrowing
about $90,000 in bank loans. With the money, he opened a small
metal-stamping shop to supply large industrial companies. But
Hernandez's dream turned sour. ``The competition was tough, really
tough. Little by little, we just couldn't keep up, even before the
peso devaluation,'' says Hernandez, who closed the shop in 1995 and
released 35 employees. ``Once the crisis struck, our interest
payments doubled and there was nothing to do but close. The loans
were too expensive and the market was too difficult. Our mistake
was believing the line that only by investing would we develop.''
Economists say that NAFTA is just one of many factors _ the Tequila
Crisis and the relentless pace of globalization among others _ that
have affected Mexico. Nonetheless, countless others found
themselves in similar situations, and as their companies turned
into the losers of free trade, they blamed NAFTA. Some free-trade
critics blamed the Mexican government's liberalization policies for
undermining the country's industrial base and paving the way for a
severe crisis. But others see things a bit differently. ``I think
NAFTA saved the Mexican economy during the crisis,'' says Alberto
Covarrubias, the director general of Walmi Transformer, a
450-employee company in the northern city of Saltillo that exports
air filters for automobile engines and specialty applications. ``I
don't know what the country would look like now without NAFTA.''
 &HT;    Walmi Transformer is one of an elite group of small and
medium-sized companies who saw free trade as inevitable and decided
to do something about it. The company once served the domestic
market from a plant in Lermo, an industrial town in central Mexico.
But several years before NAFTA was signed, Walmi executives decided
their future was in exports, so they moved to Saltillo, a day's
drive from the Texas border. And they launched a massive makeover
of the company's production techniques, management methods and
sales practices. ``It's a long process and you have to involve all
your people,'' says Covarrubias. ``But now, the companies that
transformed themselves can take advantage of all these changes,
while the companies that believed that things would never really
change are paying the price.''
 &HT;    Today, Walmi sells air filters to several automakers and the
auto aftermarket, as well as specialty filters to companies like
Ingersoll Rand. It won Mexico's National Export Prize in 1997 for
its market performance in the United States and Canada, and
recently signed a contract with a German company after attending a
trade fair in Hamburg. Covarrubias even closed the company's
warehouse in Laredo, Texas, realizing that with NAFTA, regular
bureaucratic delays at customs were a thing of the past.
 &HT;    A few large companies were able to turn operations geared to the
domestic market into export production in a short time: Goodyear de
Mexico and most automakers did so by 1995. But Walmi is typical of
smaller companies that needed several years to do it.
 &HT;    Techtube de Mexico, an independent, cutting-edge steel company
in Mexico City with 150 employees, was founded in 1990, and started
to export in 1995. But that was two years after it first decided to
buy several million dollars' worth of capital equipment from
specialized suppliers in France, Italy and Germany to produce the
technology to make top-grade stainless-steel pipes and joints.
``NAFTA was a detonator for our entire investment, because we saw a
big opportunity to export to the United States and we were able to
recalculate our return on investment because of the treaty,'' says
Sergio Espinoza, the company's export manager. ``We wanted to
compete against the big guys. You find out what you know, and you
learn faster.''
 &HT;    Today, Techtube sells about half its production in Mexico,
supplying tons of steel pipes for beer giant Grupo Modelo's new
plant in Zacatecas, and other large companies. It exports the other
half to the United States and Canada, and to the rest of Latin
America.
 &HT;    NAFTA has also attracted foreign firms interested not just in
serving the Mexican market, but also in using Mexico as an export
platform to the United States. Mexico received $12 billion in
foreign direct investment in 1997, more than any Latin American
country after Brazil, which is still in the process of selling off
huge state-owned companies.
 &HT;    Mexico overtook China as the single-largest supplier of textiles
to the United States in 1998, spearheaded by foreign firms'
maquiladora assembly-for-export plants. U.S. automobile maker
General Motors and Bombardier, the Canadian transportation and
finance giant, have joined forces to assemble locomotives in
Mexico. Major parts will be shipped from GM plants in the United
States to Bombardier's Mexico facility for assembly and then sold
throughout Latin America. GM's Delphi parts subsidiary is already
the largest private employer in Mexico, with over 27,000 workers.
``We believe that Mexico will continue to get stronger and
stronger,'' says Tom Glaser, an executive at U.S. trucking firm
Contract Freighters, Inc. ``More U.S. manufacturing plants will
relocate there and more parts and components will need to be hauled
from the U.S.''
 &HT;    Sara Lee, the giant U.S. apparel company, while not adding new
plant capacity to its existing Mexico operations, has seen a shift
in production as duty free goods under NAFTA reduce overall costs.
``We have not been as dependent on the Far East for our sourcing
needs,'' says Sara Lee spokeswoman Peggy Carter, who added that
Mexican plants have increased their competitiveness under NAFTA.
 &HT;    Textiles are a prime example of how the complementary aspects of
Mexico's economy with those of Canada and the United States fit
together and benefit companies' bottom lines and their ability to
compete in other markets. Before the trade accord took effect,
Quaker Fabric Corp., a U.S. textile company with $200 million in
annual sales, was unsuccessful in gaining a license to import its
products into Mexico. But since NAFTA, the company has opened
offices in Mexico City and Guadalajara, while 150 of the company's
2,300 U.S.-based workers owe their jobs to the new export revenue
stream.
 &HT;    ``What you are finding is a natural partnership,'' says Quaker
Fabric CEO Larry Liebenow. ``More sophisticated products like yarns
and upholstery, are being made in the United States.
Apparel-cutting and sewing is moving to Mexico. For years that is a
business that has moved out of the United States. But with NAFTA,
apparel is moving to Mexico from Asia, and that is important
because Mexican apparel makers buy a lot of U.S. fabric as raw
materials.''
 &HT;    In addition to NAFTA and Mexico's location, Canadian companies
have been drawn to set up manufacturing operations in Mexico due to
a highly qualified and productive workforce, says Andres Darvasi,
president of the Canadian Chamber of Commerce in Mexico and
director of marketing and sales for the Mexico operations of
Bombardier.
 &HT;    At the same time, NAFTA has helped increase awareness in Canada
for the opportunities in Mexico, he says.
 &HT;    ``NAFTA has brought considerable benefits to Canadian
companies,'' adds Katherine Funtek, commercial secretary at the
Canadian Embassy in Mexico. ``Among the many positive aspects are
better access to the Mexican market, particularly in areas that
were previously highly protected, including automotive parts,
transportation equipment and services, natural gas [and textiles.''
 &HT;    Other benefits include the creation of effective trade dispute
settlement mechanisms and greater transparency in, and access to,
government procurement, she says. And, Canada's economy itself has
also benefited by the increased competitiveness, according to
Funtek. As a result of all this NAFTA-spurred change, foreign
investment from U.S. and Canadian companies far outstrips funds
coming from other parts of the world and is growing in importance.
Indeed, the perceived stability that a multilateral treaty provides
has persuaded companies to divert investment from other traditional
manufacturing centers to Mexico.
 &HT;    And companies expect to leverage their Mexican investment far
beyond the NAFTA region. The Mexican plants of automakers like
General Motors, Ford and Chrysler (all from the United States),
Nissan (Japan) and Volkswagen (Germany) have increased their
presence, and in 1997, shipped nearly a million vehicles around the
world. Samsung (Korea), Sony (Japan) and other electronics firms
have turned Tijuana into the world capital of television
production. ``NAFTA is fueling all this growth,'' says Horacio
Ojeda, the director of business planning at the fibers department
of the Mexico operations of U.S.-based energy and chemicals company
DuPont. ``But it's broader than that. We also want to export to
Europe, Latin America and Asia.''
 &HT;    Other indirect effects from NAFTA are still being played out.
Demand for top-quality real estate is rising in Mexico City, in
large part from foreign firms looking for expanded space. And with
industrial companies flocking here, law firms, accountants,
consultants and other service companies are racing to compete for
new business. Behind the success, though, skeptics worry that
Mexico is not doing enough to take advantage of NAFTA. After all,
its competitive advantage of privileged access to the U.S. market
will disappear if the U.S. signs similar trade agreements _ such as
the Free Trade Area of the Americas _ in the future with other
developing countries in Latin America or elsewhere. ``In practice,
we're leaving the country's development to the initiative of each
individual,'' says Rubio, the economist. ``There's nothing wrong
with that, but it's insufficient. The fact is that those who reap
the rewards of NAFTA are a small portion of Mexicans.'' Mexico
still needs to make internal improvements to cement its
competitiveness, particularly in education and financial services.
To consolidate Mexico's advantage and spread the gains among larger
segments of the population, says Rubio, Mexico must address these
pressing weaknesses.
 &HT;    Public and private sector officials are already seeking ways to
upgrade labor-intensive industries. True, Mexico needed and needs
the low-tech jobs, but as the trade accord enters into its second
five-year period, they hope to raise wages and earnings by
producing more complex products. NAFTA has already made U.S.-Mexico
commerce into one of the world's fastest-growing trade zones,
speeding trends that were already underway in the 1980s. But in
Mexico, NAFTA means change, and the ongoing change of NAFTA is best
thought of as evolution.
 &HT;     
