<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS TIMING OF ATTACK ON IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton declared Wednesday night that the
timing of Wednesday's attack on Baghdad was determined by Iraq's
flouting of UN weapons inspectors and the coming of the holy month
of Ramadan _ not by impeachment hearings at home.
</P>
<P>
   After a surrealistic day that included calling out troops and
plotting strategy to avoid impeachment, Clinton defended the strike
against Iraq while briefly alluding to his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein and the other enemies of peace may have thought
that the serious debate currently before the House of
Representatives would distract Americans or weaken our resolve to
face him down,'' the president said on the eve of a scheduled House
impeachment vote. ``But once more, the United States has proven
that although we are never eager to use force, when we must act in
America's vital interests, we will do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 15-minute speech came about an hour after the strike
started _ and after Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott issued a
statement questioning the timing.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Clinton's national security team said they had been
preparing for the strike for a month and unanimously recommended
the strike Wednesday. In separate remarks, Defense Secretary
William Cohen, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger, and chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff General Hugh Shelton said the president's domestic troubles
never entered into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am prepared to place 30 years of public service on the line
to say the only factor that was imnportant in this decision is what
is in America's national security interest,'' said Cohen, a former
Republican senator from Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The move to attack Iraq was in the works from Nov. 15 and a
tentative decision was made Tuesday night, when Clinton, Albright
and Berger, flying back from Israel, received a scathing report
from the UN weapons inspections chief about Iraq's efforts to
thwart inspections. In a conference call from the plane with Vice
President Al Gore, CIA chief George Tenet and other officials in
Washington, the president discussed the need for an attack, Berger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Late that night, he said, Cohen called Republican leaders to
tell them that an attack was likely, and Clinton called Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One landed outside Washington at 1 a.m. Wednesday, and
by 3 a.m., Berger was briefing UN Secretary General Kofi Annan on
the president's preliminary decision to attack Baghdad. At 7 a.m.,
top US national security officials gathered in the White House
Situation Room while the Democrats and Republicans in Congress
prepared for afternoon party caucuses to discuss impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   After the morning meeting, Clinton met with his chief of staff,
John Podesta, to discuss impeachment and stopped by the regular
senior staff meeting to give his aides a pep talk. The president
admonished his aides to ``concentrate on the jobs we were sent here
to do (and) that ultimately the American people get it right, and
he believes that they will,'' according to White House press
secretary Joseph Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also met with Representative Amo Houghton of New York,
who is among a small group of Republican lawmakers who have said
they will vote no on impeachment. To work on his speech, the
president canceled an afternoon session with Representative
Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican who had opposed
impeachment but started wavering in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and the White House had the nervous air of
households biding time while waiting for a storm to approach. At 1
pm, Albright and two aides, Elaine Shocus and Wendy Sherman, sat in
the middle of the State Department cafeteria, looking studiously
casual. Albright ate a piece of carrot cake and made small talk
with a couple of reporters who passed by.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, spokesmen for the White House, the State
Department and the Pentagon gave carefully choreographed remarks
about Hussein's violation. Other officials dropped broad hints that
an attack was imminent, and even joked about a long night ahead
with pizza dinners at the office.
</P>
<P>
   The first high-level remarks about the bombing came not from an
American, but from British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who set the
stage for his friend Clinton. Speaking in London, Blair denounced
Saddam Hussein as a ``a serial breaker of promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of a report by Richard Butler, the chief of the United
Nations weapons inspection team, Blair said, ``It is damning, it is
a catalogue of destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair, not Clinton, disclosed the Pentagon's name of the strike:
``Operation Desert Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton defended his timing, saying, ``The
situation presents a clear and present danger to the stability of
the Persian Gulf and the safety of people everywhere. The
international community gave Saddam one last chance to resume
cooperation with the weapons inspectors. Saddam has failed to seize
the chance. And so we had to act and to act now.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said the end of inspections would allow Iraq to
rebuild chemical, biological and nuclear weapons programs ``in
months, not years.''
</P>
<P>
   The president added, ``We acted  &UR; today &LR;  because in the judgment
of my military advisers, a swift response would provide the most
surprise and the least opportunity for Saddam to prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security advisers said that the die was cast
for an attack in mid-November when the president pulled back on a
US missile strike, but vowed swift and decisive action if Hussein
broke his promise to cooperate with weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``A failure to take action under those circumstances, I think,
would in fact impair our national security intersts for some time
to come,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   General Shelton said, ``We started planning, as we do in our
business, for the worst case. And we started looking at what the
windows of opportunity might be available.'' The exact timing, he
said, was driven by Butler's report and for the purpose of
achieving a tactical surprise.
</P>
<P>
   One official said Clinton and his advisers felt that the White
House should take advantage of good feeling in the Arab world
following Clinton's four-day trip to Israel, Gaza and the West
Bank. The White House felt that Clinton gave an uplifting speech in
Gaza, winning points with Arab countries by speaking emphatically
about Palestinians' frustrations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States felt justified in the attack
because of a statement made last month by eight Arab nations _
including Egypt, Syria and Saudi Arabia _ that rebuffed Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   This year, like last year, Ramadan was a consideration. The
monthlong holy period starts when a new moon is spotted over Saudi
Arabia, probably Friday or Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to initiate military action during Ramadan would be
profoundly offensive to the Muslim world and therefore would damage
our relations with Arab countries and the progress we have made in
the Middle East. That is something we wanted very much much to
avoid, without giving Iraq a month's head start to prepare for
potential action against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such explanations failed to convince several critics in
Congress. ``Never underestimate a desperate president,'' said
Representative Gerald B.H. Solomon, a New York Republican and
former Marine. ``The American people ought to be as outraged as I
am about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who has led the
impeachment drive, called the timing ``highly suspicious.'' And
Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, noted
``cynicism'' about the timing.
</P>
<P>
   Those words echoed comments made by Representative Tom Delay,
the House majority whip, who said Clinton could not be trusted,
even when announcing the start of an attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm suggesting that the president of the United States cannot
be believed, and I think it's reflective in his foreign policy...
Saddam Hussein knows it, and that's why he jerks his chain all the
time,'' Delay said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CNN soon after the first missiles were launched,
former Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleberger said the timing
``smells to high heaven.'' Stepping up the criticism,
Representative Porter Goss, a Florida Republican who heads the
House Intelligence Committee, said he had arrived in Washington to
be ``totally blindsided'' by news reports that an attack was
already under way.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials all day vigorously defended Clinton's
timing on the military action, calling merely coincidental that
Butler's report would come just two days before the House was set
to vote on impeaching the president. But they firmly denied that
the president's decision-making was influenced by the upcoming
vote, which was delayed Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
