</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IMPEACHMENT DEBATE PLANS KNOCKED ASKEW BY IRAQ RAID
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans on Wednesday night delayed not
only impeachment proceedings against President Clinton, but also
final decisions on the procedure for conducting their historic
floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   While House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri insisted
that any impeachment debate should be postponed until military
hostilities with Iraq have ``completely ended,'' Speaker-designate
Bob Livingston of Louisiana said the historic debate would begin
``within the near future,'' possibly as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When it convenes Thursday for what was expected to be the first
impeachment debate in 130 years, the House instead will approve a
resolution supporting the U.S. military forces the president
ordered into battle against Iraq on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Such a resolution could give both parties a somber forum for
airing their views. Some Republicans may repeat their suspicions
that the president ordered air strikes to derail the impeachment
proceedings, and Democrats may argue that the impeachment effort
should be shelved until the conflict with Iraq is over.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the House does begin the impeachment debate, much of
what happens will follow carefully scripted parliamentary
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are simple, however. And while it appears unlikely
that Clinton can avoid becoming only the second president in
history to be impeached, the rules offer Clinton's allies plenty of
opportunities to defeat or to delay the four articles of
impeachment to be debated.
</P>
<P>
   The four articles of impeachment approved by the Judiciary
Committee came to the House bundled as one ``highly privileged''
resolution. The Republican leaders chose such parliamentary
packaging in order to make it more difficult for Democrats to
present censure as an alternative to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Privileged resolutions are not subject to amendments. They
require an up-or-down vote, normally after only one hour of debate.
In view of the gravity of impeachment, though, it was expected that
the Republicans and Democrats would agree to expand this limit.
</P>
<P>
   But even the length of debate has been a matter of contention
between the two parties. Democrats want 36 hours of
around-the-clock debate, enough for all 435 members to speak five
minutes each _ the procedure used for the Persian Gulf war debate.
Republicans have offered six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats could delay a final vote on impeachment well beyond
any time limit set by the Republicans, however, by making motions
to adjourn or to kill the resolution, which would require
time-consuming votes.
</P>
<P>
   But first, they are expected to make a final attempt to get a
censure resolution to the floor of the House over the steadfast
objections of the Republican leaders. It probably will happen this
way:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Democrat, probably Gephardt, will ask to be recognized by
the presiding officer, Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill. Gephardt will then
move that the privileged resolution containing the impeachment
articles be sent back to the Judiciary Committee with instructions
to replace it with a resolution of censure.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Republican will then challenge Gephardt's motion on the
grounds that censure is not germane to impeachment and is,
therefore, in violation of House rules. It will then fall to the
House parliamentarian, Charles Johnson, who is not affiliated with
either party, to rule on the motion.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Johnson rules that the motion is not germane, the
Democrats' last-ditch effort to avert Clinton's impeachment is
probably over. His ruling could be appealed by the Democrats and
overturned by a majority vote of the House, but in the past 60
years, the ruling of the House parliamentarian has been overturned
only four times.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans prevail on censure, the House would then
begin debate on the impeachment resolution. Each party would name a
floor manager to keep track of their debate time. At the end of the
debate, the vote would be taken. A simple majority of at least 218
of the 435 House members would send the matter to the Senate for
trial.
</P>
<P>
   A final matter would be another privileged resolution to appoint
``managers'' who would handle the Senate trial, and to determine
what authority the managers have, such as subpoena power.
</P>
<P>
   If the impeachment vote is delayed until the new Congress takes
office in January, another resolution appointing managers will have
to be considered by the new Congress. Since the Republican majority
shrinks by five seats in the new Congress, Democrats will have a
chance to resurrect their motion to recommit the impeachment
resolution to the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
