<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU GOES ON THE OFFENSIVE IN CALLING FOR EARLY ELECTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu endorsed
early elections Wednesday in a bid to escape the prospect that he
would lose a crucial vote of no confidence next week in the
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's bold move put him on the offensive against his
political foes. It also effectively put the U.S.-brokered Wye River
peace agreement, which mandates more transfers of West Bank land to
the Palestinians, on hold for an election campaign that could last
several months.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials were angered by the move. ``He had to
choose between maintaining himself as the prime minister,
maintaining his coalition or maintaining the peace process,''
Palestinian senior negotiator Saeb Erekat told Reuters.
``Unfortunately, he chose to sacrifice the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite frantic back-room negotiations, it appeared that
Netanyahu was having difficulty mustering the 61 votes needed in
the 120-seat Parliament both to defeat the no-confidence motion and
to kill an opposition bill for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition Labor Party officials said they had enough votes to
win either motion.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu presented what he called principals for peace, which
included past demands. Palestinians, he said, must renounce
aspirations for statehood and a capital in east Jerusalem. They
must also accept the prisoners Israel releases, stop inciting
violence against Israelis, seize all illegal weapons in
Palestinian-controlled areas and reduce the ranks of the
Palestinian police force.
</P>
<P>
   Any politician who accepted these principles, he said, was
welcome to join his government.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that by setting out a list of principles likely to
please right-wing members of his government, Netanyahu may be able
to keep his disintegrating coalition together for the no-confidence
vote. Those members have threatened to withdraw support if
Netanyahu complies with the Wye River accord and transfers more
West Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say now from the start, if there isn't the necessary
majority to support these principles, I will call for early
elections in order to get from the people the necessary mandate to
achieve a real peace,'' Netanyahu said. ``We are walking this road
with deep conviction that there is no other way to reach peace with
security and reciprocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak, leader of the opposition Labor Party, which had been
supporting Netanyahu on votes crucial to furthering peacemaking
with the Palestinians, said his party had no plans to join
Netanyahu's government in a unity coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of a (coalition) can be created with a government
that gives in to extremists, ruins the economy and ruins the
society?'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said that he would present the list of principles to
his coalition Sunday and to the Parliament on Monday, the day on
which the motion of no-confidence was expected to be debated.
</P>
<P>
   His problems worsened Wednesday when his finance minister,
Yaakov Neeman, resigned. Neeman said the ruling coalition had
ceased functioning, ``the public coffers are no longer guarded, and
every legislator, faction or party acts as if they are his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at least three members of Netanyahu's own Likud Party _
former Science Minister Benny Begin, former Finance Minister Dan
Meridor and Michael Kleiner, who heads a extra-parliamentary group
called the Land of Israel Front _ said they favored holding early
elections. And the leadership of a centrist coalition party, the
Third Way, said its members were also likely to vote for new
elections.
</P>
<P>
   By calling for new elections, Netanyahu can avoid an appearance
of weakness, analysts said. Moreover, he, not his political foes,
would be able to decide the date for the elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way, he's setting the time, he's in control,'' said
Reuven Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's Hebrew University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quicker he calls for elections, the more he catches them
off guard,`` Hazan said. ``He doesn't want to look like elections
were thrust upon him at a time that was quite uncomfortable for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Netanyahu can make a deal with Labor, together they can
choose the election date, possibly as early as the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, by setting out principles for peacemaking with the
Palestinians, he might be able to pull disgruntled right-wingers
back into the fold. And, if elections do take place, he has set out
a platform of ``tough peacemaking'' that could appeal to the
political center, the analysts said. And, he shifts blame for the
failure of the peace agreement to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by going to new elections, Netanyahu is taking a risk. The
latest opinion polls suggest Netanyahu is trailing Barak by 44
percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Against another politician, former army chief of staff Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak, Netanyahu trailed 52 percent to 35 percent
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
