<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hunter sees no quick fix for NBA
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Union chief Billy Hunter on Wednesday dismissed any
chance of a resolution of the NBA labor situation by Christmas and
suggested Feb. 1 as a start for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're gonna (negotiate next), it will be between Christmas
and New Year's,'' Hunter said in a telephone conference call with
the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Sarcasm dripping, Hunter said he was not ``overly concerned''
about reaching an agreement that will end the NBA lockout and
provide for a ``42, 44 to 50, 55-game season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at (NBA commissioner David Stern), and he will be the
one who will decide when we get a deal. Obviously, his timeline
isn't affected by getting a deal before Christmas, not if he's
going to Aspen, Colo.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern is scheduled to leave on a skiing vacation Friday, but the
league pointed out that he will be in telephone contact and can
return to New York in a matter of few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, however, refused to take issue with a Tuesday Associated
Press story that said a resolution could be achieved with about 24
hours of hard bargaining. ``We're prepared to compromise. I think
that can be done in a few days. First, they have to come to the
table with that mind-set.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter listed five points as most contentious: restoration of
the middle class in salaries, increase in minimum salaries,
percentage of basketball-related income, duration of rookie
contracts and details of an escrow clause.
</P>
<P>
   He said he already has made substantial concessions in agreeing
to limits on contracts for players in their first six seasons in
the league and on high-end salaries but said they had not been
enough to satisfy the league.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter also said that the NBA had demanded preconditions for an
agreement and that he would not go along with such a demand. He
also asserted that he is the one who makes the call that starts
each negotiating session and that now he will wait for the league
to call.
</P>
<P>
   Stern disputed that assertion, stating that he initiated last
week's two negotiating sessions.
</P>
<P>
   On a related topic, Hunter disagreed with a news magazine report
that indicated racial tensions have contributed to the impasse.
``It's all about dollars, hard economics,'' Hunter said. ``If
things don't go right or tempers flare, the first reaction is it
has to be racial.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks' Steve Smith agreed. ``This is a financial issue,''
Smith said, ``and nothing more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
