<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duties shuffled with Reeves out
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons' first practice without coach Dan Reeves
looked pretty much like any other, except that he was nowhere to be
found.
</P>
<P>
   But while he recovers in Piedmont Hospital from Monday's bypass
surgery, there were subtle differences at team headquarters in
Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant head coach/defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, serving
as interim head coach, conducted the morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
   And when trainer Ron Medlin and team physician Andrew Bishop got
a second opinion from orthopedist James Andrews on the condition of
linebacker Cornelius Bennett's sprained left knee, the news was
relayed first to Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, where Reeves normally wears the headset at practice and
radios plays to quarterback Chris Chandler, on Wednesday backup
quarterback Steve DeBerg was on the headset.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan for Sunday's game at Detroit (5-9) was to have
quarterbacks coach Jack Burns continue calling plays from the
coaches' box, with running backs coach George Sefcik relaying them
via radio headset to Chandler. Reeves normally calls in plays after
getting them from Burns. Sometimes, Reeves changes them.
</P>
<P>
   It appears now that DeBerg will be involved in that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit different not seeing Dan out there and not
hearing his input,'' Chandler said. ``But I feel good working with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said, ``We may put Steve on the headset sometimes to
communicate with Chris because we all work together so much in
meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks will continue calling defenses from the coaches' box, and
will talk to several people on the sideline via radio Sunday,
including general manager Harold Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than watch from the press box, Richardson, who has 12
years of college coaching and nine years of pro coaching experience
(New Orleans and Denver), will be Brooks' connection with game
officials. He'll also instruct Falcon captains what to do when they
have decisions to make regarding penalties _ after Brooks makes the
command decision and relays it to Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep everybody's role as close to normal as
possible,'' Brooks said. ``I'll have Harold Richardson on the phone
with me ... so we can keep defensive and offensive coaches doing
what they were doing before.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves update
</P>
<P>
   Reeves continues to improve, and still looks to get out of the
hospital Friday. He might be involved in a limited role in
game-planning for the Dec. 27 home game against the Miami Dolphins.
He's trying to get involved before that, but his wife, Pam, has
other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Reeves appears to be doing very well,'' Brooks said.
``He called in this morning, and he was up walking (Monday). I
think he wanted to get the offensive gameplan. He said he might get
out (today) or Friday, but I imagine they're trying to tie him to
his bed right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Special teams coach Joe DeCamillis, Reeves' son-in-law, said his
wife, Reeves' daughter Dana, said Reeves is trying to work from his
hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made the comment (Tuesday) that he said yesterday morning
that he was already worried about who I was going to replace
(injured) Bob Christian with on the punt team,'' said DeCamillis.
</P>
<P>
   Answer man
</P>
<P>
   DeCamillis said Christian will be replaced as the up back on the
punting team by either cornerback Ronnie Bradford or linebacker
Craig Sauer. That player calls the blocking schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett report
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's trip to the Alabama Sports Medicine Clinic in his
hometown of Birmingham revealed nothing more than the MRI showed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The left knee he sprained Sunday at New Orleans has small tears
to the anterior cruciate ligament but probably not enough to
prevent him from playing. He also has some bone bruises in the
joint.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who is tied with middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle for
the team lead with 105 tackles, was not at practice Wednesday, but
stands a very good chance of practicing today, when he will test
the knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some fluid taken off the knee (Tuesday),'' Brooks said.
``The knee is stable; it's not loose. It's not clear how much of
the damage is new, and how much is old. He went ahead and played
after the injury (Sunday) ... and played very well. We anticipate
him playing.'' If he doesn't play, rookie Keith Brooking, the
team's first-round draft choice, will start.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl follow up
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the five Falcons named to the Feb. 7 Pro Bowl in
Honolulu, and first alternates in left tackle Bob Whitfield and
defensive end Chuck Smith, here are the other Falcon alternates:
Second alternates _ wide receiver Terance Mathis and kicker Morten
Andersen; third alternates _ Bennett, Christian, tight end O.J.
Santiago; fourth alternate _ defensive tackle Travis Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket talk
</P>
<P>
   Playoff tickets will go on sale to the general public at 9 a.m.
Saturday. They can be purchased at Ticketmaster outlets, or through
Ticketmaster by phone (404-249-6400), or at the Georgia Dome ticket
office. There will be about 27,000 available for a home game Jan. 2
or 3, or Jan. 9 or 10.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl regular
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle is the fifth Falcon to be picked for five or more Pro
Bowls, joining defensive end Claude Humphrey and center Jeff Van
Note (six each), and linebacker Tommy Nobis and tackle Mike Kenn
(five each).
</P>
<P>
   Big numbers
</P>
<P>
   Mathis and wide receiver Tony Martin (59 catches, 1,034 yards,
five touchdowns) lead all NFL receiving tandems with 2,119 yards.
That's ahead of Minnesota's Randy Moss and Cris Carter, who total
2,115.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Lester Archambeau did not practice Wednesday as he
rested his broken thumb, but he likely will practice today and is
sure to play Sunday. ... On the final Sunday of the regular season,
the Fox network's Terry Bradshaw will give out his ``Terry Awards,_
and running back Jamal Anderson will be honored for best dance _
``The Dirty Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
