<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-REGULATIONS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State environmental commissioners propose new air pollution
regulations
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Cleaner-burning and more expensive gasoline
would be required in Austin, San Antonio and the eastern half of
the state under air pollution rules the state's environmental
agency is likely to propose today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud to be a clean city, but we're coming up very close
to the limits,'' Austin City Council Member Gus Garcia told
commissioners for the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Austin and San Antonio are running just under the federal
standard for ozone, a gaseous pollutant formed from tailpipe
emissions and from vapors released during refueling.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals would require reduced levels of sulfur and vapor
pressure in gasoline sold in 110 counties. The vapor pressure
requirement would go into effect in May 2000 and the sulfur rule in
May 2003. Austin and San Antonio requested that the sulfur rule to
go into effect three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline with lower vapor pressure and lower sulfur would cost
two to four cents more at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio Mayor Howard Peak said San Antonio wants to preserve
its status as the largest clean-air city in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry wants to market cleaner-burning gasoline but
does not favor a piecemeal approach with different formulas and
deadlines for various localities, said Cindy Morphew, vice
president of environmental affairs for the Texas Oil and Gas
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry McBee, chairman of the conservation commission, said
Austin and San Antonio should have the option of moving as quickly
as possible. Complying with the ozone standard will be a tall order
for both cities even with cleaner gasoline, he said. Growing
populations, urban sprawl, industrial emissions and pollution
blowing in from other areas all are factors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the effort is worthwhile not only for public health
reasons but also because cities in violation of the ozone standard
must undertake various burdensome clean-up measures, McBee said.
These include new regulations governing dry cleaners, painting
shops and other small businesses, as well as tough new restrictions
on industrial expansion. For example, a factory that wanted to
expand would have to ensure that emissions after the expansion were
lower than emissions before the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental and consumer groups support cleaner-burning
gasoline. But some activists and three cities in East Texas urged
the conservation commission to ban the use of an additive, called
MTBE, to produce cleaner fuels. Some studies have found MTBE
contamination in drinking-water supplies. Jim Mathews, a lawyer
representing the cities of Tyler, Longview and Marshall, noted that
Maine is moving to end the use of the additive after traces were
found in 15 percent of its water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's proposal is expected to be silent on MTBE.
McBee said he would not support a ban on the additive because there
is great uncertainty on whether it poses a health threat.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners initially voted Wednesday to propose the rules
on vapor pressure and sulfur but later rescinded that action to
fine tune an amendment by Commissioner Ralph Marquez. The amendment
would split the rules into two parts, one dealing with vapor
pressure and the other dealing with sulfur.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners are expected to issue the proposal at a work
session today, said Andy Saenz, a spokesman for the agency.
Hearings will be held on the proposal, and public comments will be
accepted through Feb. 1. Final rules are expected to be adopted
later next year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
