<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US, BRITAIN UNLEASH MISSILES ON RECALCITRANT IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States and Britain struck Baghdad at
about 1 a.m. local time with a barrage of cruise missiles to punish
Iraq for blocking UN Nations weapons inspectors seeking to rid Iraq
of its most lethal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The military attack, by far the largest strike against Iraq
during the Clinton presidency, came as congressional leaders agreed
to postpone a vote on impeachment scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised address to the nation from the White House,
President Clinton said he had ordered a ``strong, sustained series
of air strikes against Iraq'' to ``degrade'' its capacity to
rebuild its nuclear, chemical and biological arsenals and to
destroy its capacity to threaten its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Warning that the operation could kill innocent Iraqis, Clinton
said he had exhausted all diplomatic options before making the
decision to use military force to punish Baghdad for not meeting is
obligations to scrap its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs of action must be weighed against the price of
inaction. If Saddam defies the world, and we failed to respond, we
will face a far greater threat in the future,'' Clinton said. ``The
hard fact is that so long as Saddam remains in power, he threatens
the well-being of his people, the peace of his region, the security
of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement carried Wednesday night by the official Iraqi
news agency, an unharmed Iraqi President Saddam Hussein defiantly
called on Iraq's armed forces and people to fight a U.S. and
British air assault. ``Our great people and our brave armed
forces...resist and fight them. Fight the enemies of God, the Arab
nation and humanity. God willing, you will be the victors.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Pentagon briefing, Secretary of Defense William Cohen
described a three-pronged attack against Iraq which includes: US
Navy aircraft flying from the decks of the U.S.S. Enterprise; US
Air Force and Royal Air Force aircraft flying from land bases; and
cruise missiles launched from Navy ships and B-52 bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the military operation, dubbed Operation Desert Fox,
would continue until the United States had accomplished the goals
set by the president. He said he had decided to strengthen the
American military presence in the region in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the military assault included 36 combat aircraft,
including fighters, bombers and F-117 Stealth aircraft. He added
that there were already enough forces in the region to start an
attack without a further buildup.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began about five p.m. Wednesday afternoon, New York
time, as the UN Security Council was debating the fate of Iraq.
Council members emerged from the meeting to watch a CNN screen
showing the night sky above downtown Baghdad studded with explosive
light as Iraqi anti-aircraft guns fired at incoming American
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The military action prompted a strong reaction from Iraq's
allies on the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no excuse or pretext to use force against
Iraq,'' Chinese ambassador Qin Huasun said as the council suspended
its closed door consultation. The action ``poses a threat to
international peace as well as regional security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for the United Nations and for the world,''
added UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, who undertook a number of
diplomatic efforts to secure Iraq's cooperation. ``My hopes are
with the people of Iraq and with the 307 united nations
humanitarian workers who remain in the country and with all others
whose lives are in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the United Nations would be on hand to respond to the
humanitarian and diplomatic aid needed to heal the damage from the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Britain's Prime Minister Tony Blair said the joint
US-British military action would hit military targets dearest to
Saddam Hussin. ``We have no option but to act,'' Blair said
Wednesday evening. ``We are taking every possible care to avoid
civilian casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   The President's top aides sought to portray the action as
necessary step to averting a more costly war with Baghdad in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Advisor Sandy Berger said that the president
acted with the unanimous backing of his national security advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have absolutely no doubt this is the right decision, this
is the right time,'' Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
   US and British officials said the United States decided to act
now to avoid offending its allies in the Arab world by beginning a
military strike during the Muslim holy month of Ramadan, which
begins Thursday evening and lasts for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had delayed for even a matter of days from Chairman
Butler's report, we would have given Saddam more time to disperse
his forces and protect his weapons,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to maximize our ability to strike quickly,
without any further warning,'' Cohen said. ``From a security point
of view, we decided that we had enough in place and could carry out
this operation with minimal notice and with minimal compromise of
the surprise element.''
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts estimated that the United States has 22 ships
in the theater of operations, including the lone US aircraft
carrier in the region, the Enterprise. The sea force will be joined
on Friday by another aircraft carrier, the Carl Vinson, and its
accompanying battle group, Cohen said. Additional ground troops are
also heading to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give General Zinni additional flexibility'' and
``increase the intensity and tempo of our strike operation if
necessary,'' said General Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen declined to provide any specific numbers about the force,
but independent military analysts said they believed the United
States had 25,000 troops and 220 planes in the region and available
for a protracted attack.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the President made his decision after
receiving a damning report from Richard Butler, the chairman of the
UN Special Commission (UNSCOM) tasked with ridding Iraq of its most
deadly arms, on Iraq's failure to cooperate with the United Nations
team.
</P>
<P>
   The UN chief said Wednesday that Iraq has long engaged in a
systematic pattern of obstruction that has thwarted the UN's
ability to give Iraq a clean bill of health. ``From the inception
of the Commission's work in Iraq, in 1991, Iraq's cooperation has
been limited,'' Butler wrote in his 10-page report that served as a
green light for US military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that UNSCOM has been ineffective for some time,''
said Berger at a briefing Wednesday night. `It can stay in Baghdad,
but it's a sham. To have a Potemkin UNSCOM in Iraq doesn't make
much sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad agreed to scrap all of its long-range missile and
nuclear, chemical and biological capabilities as part of a 1991
cease fire agreement ending the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM has already destroyed thousands of chemical and
biological warheads. But it continues to suspect that Baghdad still
possesses deadly nerve agents and missiles capable of striking
Israel or Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Since the United States called off a bombing raid on Nov 14,
Butler accused Iraq of routinely obstructing the inspectors. He
charged Baghdad of blocking at least three inspections by the
United Nations, refusing to hand over documents on its weapons
program, prohibiting photographs of warheads and harassing UN
inspectors, among other violations.
</P>
<P>
   Butler's highly critical report elicited charges from Russia
that the UN chief was looking for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Russian UN Ambassador Sergei Lavrov called the Butler report
``outrageous'' and urged him to resign. During an emergency council
meeting, Lavrov said, ``If Butler thinks he cannot work in Iraq, he
should start looking for another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's anger stemmed in part from Butler's decision to
withdraw more than 140 UN weapons inspectors from Iraq without
consulting Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   US ambassador Peter Burleigh warned Annan, Butler, and Benon
Sevan, the chief of the UN humanitarian aid workers, late Tuesday
night that the United States was urging non-essential American
diplomatic personnel to leave the region. And he urged them to
``consider prudent measures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no time,'' Butler said Wednesday. ``The Secretary
General was consulted, I talked to him and he agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's aides disputed Butler's claim. A senior UN official
said, ``The Secretary General was informed not consulted,'' on
Butler's decision to withdraw the UN inspectors. He added that
Annan would have preferred that the inspectors remain.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi UN Ambassador Nizar Hamdoon concluded Wednesday afternoon:
``We have done everything in our capacity. There is nothing else we
can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
