<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-TV-NYT &LR;      12-16 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ AND IMPEACHMENT STAR IN A STRANGE TV PAS DE DEUX 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IRAQ-U.S., IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-ASSESS, IRAQ-LEGAL,
IRAQ-U.N., IRAQ-INSPECT, IRAQ-KUWAIT, IRAQ-VOICES, IRAQ-ALLIES,
IRAQ-REACT) (mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In late afternoon, eerie green-tinted pictures of Baghdad began
to appear on the television screen. Suddenly warning sirens were
heard, and viewers of CNN and MSNBC learned along with the Iraqi
people that an attack was probably imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Soon there was a booming noise and anti-aircraft fire flashed
like green Roman candles through the sky. Though the words
``Nightscope Image'' on screen explained the green color that
enhanced the glow of lights, the commonplace ``Live'' was the word
that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   This was an attack television had been anticipating all day. Its
drama came not from any element of surprise, but because, from the
safety of home and with the guilty intimacy of a voyeur, viewers
could watch the attack almost step by step.
</P>
<P>
   From early morning, the cable news channel had a split
personality, leaping back and forth between the impeachment debate
that had been planned for Thursday in the House of Representatives
and the probability of an attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Among other cultural lessons, the day demonstrated how swiftly
``wag the dog'' has entered the language as a shorthand phrase for
a war staged to distract attention from a sex scandal. (NBC even
briefly showed a clip of the film ``Wag the Dog.'') The issues were
so intertwined that even President Clinton could not avoid a
reference to his domestic crisis in his televised address, carried
by all the networks, about why he had ordered the missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   From early morning, the cable channels had continued to chart
what everyone described as congressional ``momentum'' in favor of
impeachment. But the account was sharing attention with what was
happening at the Pentagon. In early afternoon reporters were saying
that Republicans and Democrats would probably agree to postpone the
House vote if an attack were to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The sirens from Baghdad soon after 4:15 changed everything. It
was the cue for the networks to join the cable stations,
positioning themselves to be there when the missiles hit. The
methodical way the process unfolded before our eyes added a
chilling note that was both intensely real in its content and
bizarrely surreal because it arrived in a neat television package,
a drama to outdo ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching along with us, even the network anchors were at first
uncertain of what was happening. On CBS, Dan Rather said, ``We
don't know'' if an attack had already started. It was ``possibly
under way,'' Peter Jennings said on ABC. And on NBC Tom Brokaw
said, ``The attack is under way in Baghdad,'' though it turned out
he was watching Iraqi anti-aircraft fire, not American missiles.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for the actual missiles to hit, word came that the
attack had been approved. Standing in front of the White House,
David Bloom of NBC was not exaggerating when he said ``you will
see'' the missiles soon.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Baghdad scenes were familiar from the Persian
Gulf war, Wednesday's media lead-up to the event signaled how
thoroughly viewers have become accustomed to watching every step of
the news unfold. When Brokaw said, ``We know some targets have
already been hit outside our ability to see them'' (outside the
city), that came as a shock in the midst of such saturation
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   When the missiles did hit and what looked like great plumes of
green smoke filled the screen, viewers could flip around networks
searching for the greatest action as if this were a real-life video
game. And as the attacks continued, so did the political crisis.
Sometimes sound and pictures were mismatched to cover both
happenings at once. As Brokaw talked to two Democratic members of
the House Judiciary Committee, their voices ran over pictures from
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton spoke from the Oval Office in early evening, the
bags under his eyes and the atmosphere of a dual crisis informed
the speech, even when he was explaining his decision on Iraq. He
showed no emotion when he said America would not be distracted by
what he called ``the serious debate currently before the House of
Representatives'' (never using the word ``impeachment''). Only at
the end was there a touch of the lofty rhetoric and emotion that
usually serves him best.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a new century we'll have a remarkable opportunity to shape
a future more peaceful than the past, but only if we stand strong
against the enemies of peace.'' The message about standing strong
was, of course, addressed to the national audience following his
impeachment crisis as well as to Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Well into prime time, the two events continued to merge. ABC
signed off after its evening news, only to break in for a brief
news conference in which Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., the newly
selected speaker of the House, confirmed that the impeachment vote
would be delayed. Later in the evening, ABC and CBS offered special
hourlong reports. NBC stayed on continuously from late afternoon
until 9. Against those increasingly familiar green-tinted images,
they monitored how many Republicans supported the president on Iraq
and how many thought he was wagging a dog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3840 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SAFIRE-COLUMN     12-16 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ON IMPEACHMENT EVE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Has Bill Clinton at long last had a change of heart
about Saddam Hussein? Or is his sudden hawkishness _ on the eve of
Impeachment Day _ a trick to buy time, delay the vote on spurious
national security grounds and play for a break in the House?
</P>
<P>
   A mark of the degree of distrust in the president's word,
developed over years of listening to evasions, half-truths and
outright lies, is the fury of frustrated Republicans on the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night they heard him invoke ``the fear of force''
against the dictator who for years has had no reason to fear
Clinton force. ``The cost of action,'' he intoned, ``must be
weighed against the price of inaction.'' So true _ just as it was
true in the spring, when he chose inaction with the U.N.'s Kofi
Annan, and true recently when he flinched at the last minute and
gave Saddam a cheap victory by recalling an air strike.
</P>
<P>
   But then we have to ask ourselves: Would any U.S. president,
even in political extremis, stoop to risking lives to cling to
power? Holding summit meetings to affect public opinion is par for
the course, but launching hundreds of cruise missiles will cost
lives and invite retaliation. No matter what I think of Bill
Clinton's motives and methods, I cannot bring myself to think that.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming only patriotic motives, then, what do we make of
``Desert Fox,'' the first American military operation named after a
Nazi-era German general? What is its mission, and how long will it
last?
</P>
<P>
   One clue comes from the reason given for the attack at
impeachment time. The president tells us that it would have been a
mistake to ``initiate'' it during Ramadan, Islam's holy month. That
starts on Saturday. Unless it is deemed not ``profoundly
offensive'' to continue bombing during Ramadan, that limits the
attack to a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heavy rhetoric and the televised sight and sound,
the timorous mission has not changed. With off-again-on-again
bombing, Clinton still hopes to ``contain'' Saddam, to persuade him
to re-admit inspectors, to finance indigenous rebellion, to plead
with the United Nations to maintain sanctions. It is a strategy of
half-measures.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a lucky hit, a few days _ or even weeks _ of bombs will
not eliminate the Iraqi dictator's threat to every civilized
country. Air power may temporarily ``degrade'' but not knock out
his capacity to produce germ and poison-gas weapons, nor will bombs
destroy the well-dispersed Republican Guard. Even as we annoy him
from above, he will produce a weapon of mass destruction somewhere
down below. And then he will tell us to stop or else.
</P>
<P>
   Only the credible threat of another invasion of Iraq is likely
to stimulate a successful coup. No such unpopular gulf buildup will
be in the works during the Clinton administration. That can has
been kicked to the next president.
</P>
<P>
   Now to the impact of the Impeachment-Eve Desert Foxiness on
Clinton's personal fortunes. The last-ditch, fallback argument of
his defenders is that House action would ``paralyze the country.''
That has just been demolished by Clinton's acceptance of Saddam's
invitation to bomb his people into Arab martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the national-paralysis bogeyman can be found in
these punitive air strikes. The House, with a bow to seemliness,
will delay an impeachment decision for a bit. Then, as Clinton
declares a famous victory in the war process (following his getting
things ``back on track'' in the peace process) the House will
coolly proceed with the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   We are in a period of half-measures. The military half-measure
Clinton is taking in Iraq is unlikely to depose Saddam, which is a
bad thing. But the political half-measure Congress is taking in
Washington _ with the House impeaching and the Senate chastising
but not removing Clinton _ is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   In so conducting our foreign and domestic affairs, we show the
world that the United States is able to exert military power abroad
while calling to account the abuse of executive power at home. Up
to a point, we can chew up a dictator and chew out a president at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Clinton with pure motives in doing too little, too late.
Credit Congress with equally patriotic motives in doing just enough
and on time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
