<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL ABOUT CASH, NOT COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The players were angry. The labor dispute had gone on
longer than anyone had believed possible, and some were taking it
personally. There was a feeling among them that the owners, who
were locking them out, did not necessarily have the highest opinion
of their ability to hang together and that they were being
dismissed as just a bunch of dumb jocks.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? The National Basketball Association and its
players association today? Yes and no. This was also the situation
at this time of the year in the National Hockey League _ four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario: The players had been seeking to make an
agreement with management, management was, essentially, giving them
the back of their hand. They were getting no satisfaction and felt
they were getting even less respect. And at the All-Star Game, the
best players in the league had decided they would boycott the game
unless they received a little more of both of the above. They did _
an hour before the game _ and so played it. That was in the
National Basketball Association in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been several strikes and lockouts in major
league baseball in the last three decades. ``What I see being done
and said in the labor dispute in the NBA ,'' said Donald Fehr,
executive director of baseball's players association, ``is
fundamentally no different from our experiences. If you change the
names, from, say the Bulls and Knicks and Ewing and Mourning, to
the Yankees and Dodgers and Keith Hernandez and David Cone, you
have virtually the same story.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a difference with the NBA today and the other
situations cited. The players in the NBA are 85 percent black, 15
percent white. The National Hockey League is less than 1 percent
black. Baseball is 18 percent black. And in 1964, the NBA was just
the reverse of the present, 85 percent white, 15 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   And with the preponderance of black players in the NBA has come
a sense that the all-white ownership of the 29 teams is treating
them, as Karl Malone said, ``like children.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The league has cast us as dumb and stupid and
uninformed.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jayson Williams of the Nets said, ``For some guys it's hard
not to think about race.''
</P>
<P>
   If the season were canceled, he continued, ``You'll have to look
under the carpet and ask why.''
</P>
<P>
   Has there been even a single overt racist comment or tactic that
the players can put their fingers on? The answer is no, though the
owners have not been quick to defend players who have been
portrayed in the press as lavish spenders _ black men as lavish
spenders, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for the players to play the race card without factual
evidence is very disappointing,'' said Bob Cousy, the Hall of Fame
guard and first president of the players association in the early
1950s. ``Sure, it's a racist planet, and being black in America is
no shrimp cocktail, but in this case, it's not justified. The
league has been ahead of most of the rest of the country in race
relations. No, this is purely a bottom-line issue.''
</P>
<P>
   There are substantial reasons for some of the black players'
racial perceptions in this case. It is an understandable _ if not
anticipated _ historical reaction for them, growing up black in
America. And despite the current diversity in the league, the
league did have a history of quota systems, both on the court and
on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' said Richard Hurd, a labor relations professor at
Cornell University, ``maybe Billy Hunter, the executive director of
the players association, is using it to keep the union solid. It
may not be such a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the labor dispute itself, Paul Weiler, Harvard professor
of labor relations, said it follows in the tradition of labor
disputes in sports and beyond. ``It's a complex question about how
to divide revenues of $2 billion,'' he said. ``But I think it will
be resolved and there will be a season.''
</P>
<P>
   David Falk, agent for such star players as Ewing and Michael
Jordan, believes the season won't be canceled _ ``too much money
involved on both sides,'' he said. He sees a settlement by Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Weiler recalled that the 1994 hockey lockout was settled on Jan.
13. ``And they went on to have a decent season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the NBA All-Stars threatened to strike in 1964, Tom
Heinsohn was the president of a players association. ``Relations
between players and management were about the same then as now _
tense,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   And the issue was the same. It was not about race. It was about
money.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
