<HEADLINE>
NFL PLAYOFF PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BUZINSKI  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the talk in Washington this week revolves around the
impending impeachment of President Clinton by the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censure him,'' say the president's defenders. ``Throw him
out,'' say his critics. But here's a better idea:
</P>
<P>
   Force Bill Clinton and Henry Hyde to stand before the Congress
and explain the NFL's procedures to determine playoff teams. First
one that figures out how New Orleans and Seattle can play for the
Super Bowl wins.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, here are the NFL playoff possibilities with
two weeks to go:
</P>
<P>
   NFC
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (12-2):
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have clinched a playoff spot. They will win the
division and have a first-round bye by defeating Detroit this week.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco (11-3):
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have clinched a playoff spot. They will clinch the
division and have a first-round bye by winning its last two games
and if Atlanta loses to Detroit this week (based on best record vs.
Common opponents).
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (6-8):
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the Saints will win a playoff spot with two
wins (against Arizona and Buffalo) and one Tampa Bay loss (based on
head-to-head wins over Arizona and Tampa).
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (4-10)
</P>
<P>
   and Carolina (2-12)
</P>
<P>
   were eliminated before the end of Daylight Savings Time.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (13-1):
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have clinched the Central Division and a first-round
bye. They will clinch home field advantage through the NFC playoffs
this week with either a win and Atlanta beats Detroit by less than
68 points, or an Atlanta loss.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (9-5):
</P>
<P>
   The Packers will clinch a playoff berth with one win or one loss
by either Tampa Bay or Arizona. The only way for the Packers to not
make the playoffs would be to lose twice while Arizona and Tampa
each win twice. The Packers will almost certainly be the NFC's
fifth seed and have to play a wild card game at San Francisco or
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (7-7):
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers will clinch a playoff berth with two wins and one
Arizona loss or two Green Bay losses. It is also mathematically
possible for Tampa to qualify at 8-8, but it would take up more
space than the Starr referral.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (5-9)
</P>
<P>
   and Chicago (3-11)
</P>
<P>
   were eliminated before the season premiere of the `X-Files.`
</P>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (8-6)
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will clinch the NFC East with one win or one Arizona
loss. The only way for the Cowboys to miss the playoffs is to lose
twice while Tampa Bay beats Washington this week (based on a worst
record vs. Common opponents with Tampa).
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (7-7)
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will clinch their first playoff berth since moving
to the desert in 1988 with two wins, or a win this week coupled
with one Tampa Bay loss and one loss or tie by the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   New York (6-8):
</P>
<P>
   The Giants will clinch a playoff berth with two wins, two Tampa
Bay losses, plus one loss each by Arizona and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Washington (5-9)
</P>
<P>
   and Philadelphia (3-11)
</P>
<P>
   were eliminated when Mark McGwire had only 40 homers.
</P>
<P>
   AFC
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   Denver (13-1):
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have clinched home field advantage throughout the
AFC playoffs. Wish they were all this easy.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (7-7):
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders will make the playoffs with two wins, plus two
losses each by Tennessee and New England and one loss by
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (7-7):
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks will make the playoffs with two wins, plus two
losses by New England and one loss each by Tennessee, Pittsburgh
and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (6-8)
</P>
<P>
   and San Diego (5-9)
</P>
<P>
   were eliminated when Newt Gingrich was still relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (10-4):
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars will clinch the Central Division title with one win
or tie, or one Tennessee loss or tie. The Jaguars also clinch a
playoff spot with either a Miami loss or a New England loss or tie.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (8-6):
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers will win the division with two wins and two
Jacksonville losses (based on better division record than the
Jaguars). The Oilers will clinch a playoff spot with two wins, plus
one loss by either New England or Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (7-7):
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers will make the playoffs with two wins, plus two
losses each by New England and Tennessee. There might be a scenario
where the Steelers could wind up in a 9-7 tie with five teams and
still qualify, but my calculator only goes to 178 decimal places.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (5-9)
</P>
<P>
   and Cincinnati (2-12)
</P>
<P>
   were eliminated when the American flag had only 48 stars.
</P>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   New York (10-4):
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have clinched a playoff spot and will win the division
title with a win over either Buffalo or New England. The Jets will
clinch a first-round bye with two wins, or one win and one
Jacksonville loss.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (9-5):
</P>
<P>
   The Bills will win the division with two wins, two New York
losses and one Miami loss. The Bills will clinch a playoff spot
with a win, or a Tennessee loss as long as the Bills lose to the
Jets by less than 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (9-5):
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins will win the division with two wins, plus two New
York losses and one Buffalo loss. The Dolphins will clinch a
playoff berth with a win against Denver and any one of the
following occurring: a New England loss or tie; a Tennessee loss or
tie; or a Buffalo loss by more than 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   New England (8-6):
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will clinch a playoff berth with a win and a
Tennessee loss. The Patriots can also win the division, but sending
a man to Mars is less complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (3-11)
</P>
<P>
   was eliminated when the only Manning playing quarterback was
Archie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
