<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-NY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON COULD NOT COUNT ON ALL HIS ALLIES IN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-INTEL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-WHIP, IMPEACH-TRIPP, IMPEACH-HILLARY.) (dal) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the House of Representatives votes to impeach
President Clinton, as seems almost certain, three of the six
Democratic Senators from New York, New Jersey and Connecticut say
they would probably vote to acquit him after a trial before the
Senate next year. The other three would not say how they might
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The three who would forecast their votes, Sens. Robert
Torricelli and Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey, and Senator-elect
Charles Schumer of New York, said that they did not think that
Clinton had committed impeachable offenses. But all three said they
thought Clinton's actions in the Monica Lewinsky affair were
reprehensible and deserving of some lesser punishment, like
censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his personal conduct, while ugly, is not an
impeachable offense,'' Lautenberg said in an interview this week.
``But I think people across the country would find it almost
impossible to understand that there wasn't something there that
demanded a reprimand. So I would consider that as a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York region's other three senators, Christopher Dodd and
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New
York, said they felt their roles as potential jurors obligated them
to avoid taking positions on impeachment or removal until a Senate
trial was over.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan's chief of staff, Tony Bullock, said: ``The senator has
been very careful to not make any public comments on this matter,
in light of the possibility that it may come over to our side. He
views his role as a juror. He takes that role very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Removing a president from office requires 67 votes in the
Senate, where the Republicans hold a 55-45 majority. That means the
president's adversaries would need to convince 12 Democrats to vote
for conviction while preventing any defections from the Republican
side to force Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Both Moynihan and Lieberman might be considered possible votes
against Clinton. Lieberman, once considered one of Clinton's
strongest Senate allies, sharply rebuked the president in a Senate
speech in September, calling Clinton's actions ``immoral.'' But he
has also advocated censure, calling it ``a collective statement by
Congress that while Mr. Clinton's conduct may not be reason enough
to remove him, it calls for rebuke.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, who will retire at the end of his fourth term in 2000,
has often clashed with the Clinton administration. He also rose to
applaud Lieberman after his September speech, saying that Clinton's
apologies were ``not adequate.'' Later, in a television interview,
Moynihan said that perjury might be an impeachable offense. But he
has expressed an openness to considering censure.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, who has been a strong ally of Clinton, did not return
repeated phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who has served nine terms in the House, was one of the
first and most outspoken defenders of Clinton in Congress. He voted
against impeachment in the House Judiciary Committee, and says he
will vote against it in on the House floor and again in the Senate.
He says he thinks a Senate trial will prevent Congress from dealing
with more important issues.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, who was just appointed as chairman to the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, asserted that the impeachment was
being driven by right-wing groups, calling it a ``constitutionally
sanctioned coup.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said that at some point, Senate leaders might
encourage Clinton and congressional leaders to begin negotiations
to settle the case with some penalty short of removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the judge will say, `Come into my chambers _ why
don't we work this out?''' Lieberman said. ``But it's way early for
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
