<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHRISTMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: HAVE YOURSELF A TACKY LITTLE CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editorial Notebook)  
 By VERYLYN KLINKENBORG (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know a house where Santa Claus was hung by his heels from a
beam every Christmas. I know the house because my family lived in
it. One December my brother stuck a stuffed Santa upside down
overhead in the living room, just to get it out of the way, and
because it happened once it became tradition and was made to happen
again and again, until my parents moved to a house without a
living-room beam.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas has that agglutinative quality. Things stick to it
like a half-eaten candy cane in a coat pocket and never let go.
That is why nothing feels more festive to some people than the
sight of Santa riding his electric-razor sleigh in the old TV
commercial. It reminds them of childhood Christmases long, long
ago, which is one of the very things Christmas is supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas also brings out the jaybird in nearly everybody _ that
instinctive love of bright shiny objects. In some families it just
doesn't feel like Christmas until they screw the aluminum tree
together and plug in the color wheel and the room fills with sparks
of light in the primary tints. There is no accounting for tastes,
it is said, but at Christmas there is almost no taste to account
for. This has become a big, wide, sloppy holiday, and if you are
going to try too hard it should be in the general direction of
tacky. It looks less ironic.
</P>
<P>
   I blame the whole thing on the Clauses. When Madison Avenue went
shopping for a holiday shill, it faced a choice: a cozy, childless
elderly couple with a strong manufacturing and distribution base or
a homeless carpenter and his pregnant virgin bride. Santa lives in
a land that is wee, and every year the world, at least that portion
with charge cards, gets wee with him.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday came to a fork in the road years ago, and the
beacon it ended up following turned out to be Rudolph's nose. We
wanted a smaller God _ omnipresent, omniscient but not so scary or
paradoxical _ and now Santa has the job for one month a year in
certain parts of town. Naughty and nice _ the wee ethics of
Christmas _ is Santa's bailiwick, not good and evil, which is just
how we seem to like it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 2156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
