<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-VOICES-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYNICISM OVER MOTIVE, SUPPORT FOR ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., Ill., Calif., Colo., N.J., Nev., Pa., N.Y.,
Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also IRAQ-U.S., IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-ASSESS, IRAQ-LEGAL,
IRAQ-U.N., IRAQ-TV, IRAQ-INSPECT, IRAQ-KUWAIT, IRAQ-ALLIES,
IRAQ-REACT) (jw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If President Clinton was trying to divert attention from his
personal problems by bombing Iraq on Wednesday, he succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of talking about his probable impeachment by the House
of Representatives, instead of discussing his sex life and debating
whether lying is a high crime or misdemeanor, Americans had turned
their attention to questioning the president's motives in launching
air strikes, finding the timing more than a little coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wag the Dog, I say, Wag the Dog,'' said Andrew Kaye, a New
York lawyer, as he led his three children to see ``Grimm Tales'' at
the New Victory Theater in Times Square. ``It is linkage, political
linkage, because this is an elective event. You can wait a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The cynics were everywhere: A seventh-grader Christmas shopping
in Hartford, Conn., switched into a fake falsetto and called
Clinton ``desperate.'' A San Francisco industrial designer used the
words ``ludicrous,'' ``pathetic'' and ``shameful'' in one breath. A
commuter in the Chicago loop said she questioned the president's
character ``more today than yesterday.'' And at Kennedy
International Airport, a Brazilian tourist wondered why he didn't
wait until tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they weren't connected,'' said Bill Bonebreak, 39, a
Denver photographer. ``It's like having one child who screams
louder than the other, and the louder one will get the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lizondo, a 29-year-old architect hurrying to catch a bus
from Denver to his home in Boulder, Colo., was one of the few who
said he believed the timing was coincidental. ``But I'm sure Bill's
happy about it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they made the inevitable comparisons to the Hollywood
movie in which an American president fakes a war to keep the focus
off of his extramarital extracurriculars, most of those interviewed
in the moments after the bombs fell Wednesday said they supported
Clinton's decision. If he benefited politically from the timing, so
what? It was long past time to get serious with Saddam Hussein,
person after person on the streets of cities across the country
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Republicans and others who are eager for Clinton's
ouster were among the strongest backers of the decision to launch
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, the timing is poor,'' said John Cable, 37, a
financial adviser who lives in Bloomfield, N.J., and joined the
throng watching President Clinton's address to the nation on the
Jumbotron in Times Square. ``But I thought we were way overdue. I
thought we were going to do it the last time, and should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get criticized either way,'' Cable said. ``If he
doesn't act, people will get him for that. If he does act, people
will question his timing.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the growing criticism of Clinton, as the bombs fell
Wednesday he placed himself opposite perhaps the least popular
person in America. Saddam Hussein is the enemy Americans love to
hate, and while some expressed concerned about the impact of the
air strikes on Iraqi civilians and American soldiers, people could
not find harsh enough words for what they hoped happened to the
Iraqi leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man's getting what he deserves,'' said Jerry Gilbert, 35,
a contractor who was heading home to the San Fernando Valley after
finishing cementing a stairway on a building near Wilshire
Boulevard in Los Angeles. ``I feel he's capable of way more
destruction than people want to believe. I think we have to do what
we have to do to keep him in check.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Halligan, an accountant from Berkeley, Calif., only quibbled
with the tactics. Why risk a military action, he asked, suggesting
outright assassination instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we just get the CIA to go whack Saddam?'' Halligan
said. ``That would be the smart way to conserve money and lives.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Kmart in Urbana, Ill., John Gallimore of Las Vegas was
gung-ho: ``I say, `Go get him, Frosty.' He's pushed everybody too
many times. We should have got him the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Flesher, a Philadelphia car salesman, called Saddam ``a
Hitler'' with whom one can't negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad they can't drop a bomb right on him,'' said Rosie
Moon, 67, as she headed home to the Bronx from her job in midtown
Manhattan. ``He has played possum with us for too long. He deserves
what he's getting. He's a wicked man.''
</P>
<P>
   Some even blamed any suspicious timing not on Clinton, but on
Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no choice because if he didn't do anything right now
they would look at it as a very weak response and blame the
impeachment,'' said Dana Burrell, a student who lives in Oakland.
``I think Saddam did this to exactly coincide politically with the
impeachment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Few quibbled with the denouncements of the Iraqi leader, but
many were worried about the fate of his people. About 50 antiwar
protesters rallied in Times Square, chanting, ``Money for jobs, not
for war, stop the bombing now,'' while others complained that
another round of air strikes would only increase the poverty and
devastation in Iraqi cities and towns, not disable its government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anyone to fight,'' said Elizabeth Aguilar, 33, a
receptionist in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to kill a lot of people again,'' worried Helen
Alexandri, 42, a seamstress at Maxene Dry Cleaners on the Upper
West Side of Manhattan. ``We have to get Hussein. But I'm very
sorry for the people over there, the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sepin of Chicago said he was firmly opposed to the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we do is punish the Iraqi people and we don't gain
anything from it,'' said Sepin, 61. ``I don't have any solution,
but I don't think bombing is the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   In a week that has been filled with banner headlines over
impeachment even as department-store ads blare reminders about the
dwindling number of shopping days until Christmas, many of those
interviewed were in overload. Too much to do, too much news, too
little time.
</P>
<P>
   At every corner in Times Square, necks were craned, chins lifted
toward the Jumbotron, where white letters marched across the screen
transcribing Clinton's somber speech. As they stopped to watch,
people wondered if the president was resigning. Only when the CNN
graphics of little green specks crossing the sky took over the
screen did they understand that, suddenly, the subject had been
switched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about impeachment, all about impeachment,'' chanted
Ozzie Wiley, a large man in sunglasses and a black knit NYC ski
hat, as others silently watched the closed-captioned address. ``Put
two and two together. You've got to go out with a big bang. He's
going to pick off some human life before you go.''
</P>
<P>
   Commuters with briefcases, tourists with shopping bags and
messengers with dollies all stood still as Clinton, and then
Secretary of Defense William Cohen, and then Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright filled the massive screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird, with all the other stuff that's going on in the
country,'' said Jeanne Dzienciol, an architect who was on her way
to her company Christmas party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is mixed up,'' said Joseph Rozgonyi, 58, a painter
and poet who emigrated from Hungary and now lives near Times
Square. ``Maybe the bombing is related to other problems. I don't
know if it's based on sufficient evidence. How can you find out
what is the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   An impromptu salon broke out in the median of Broadway, as
socialists from the protest confronted military veterans in debates
about foreign policy. A woman from Cologne, Germany, feared for her
safety as she traveled home Thursday. A woman from the United Arab
Emirates feared for her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's bombing everyone, left, right and center,''
complained the woman, Nada Hamad, 21, who is in New York on a
three-week vacation but heading home soon for Ramadan. ``He's
talking about everyone in other countries going along with him.
That's because they can't say no to him. He's been bombing
everyone. What's to stop them from bombing them, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Most people hoped that this attack, finally, would end the
years-long threat Saddam has posed in the Middle East. And even if
Clinton managed to boost morale and score some political points,
they said, he was unlikely to permanently take the minds of the
country _ or of the Congress _ off the scandal that has dominated
the past year of his presidency. The House may have postponed its
impeachment vote, but it will remain on the agenda once this crisis
passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a snowball rolling downhill, you can't stop it
now,'' said Sharon Quiller, 46, a financial analyst in Chicago.
``He can try to bomb the whole world, it's not going to stop now.
It's got a life of its own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
