<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-AIRSTRIKES-1217-1S     12-16 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-AIRSTRIKES-1217-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: adds 12th, 13th grafs to updates with statement from Saddam
 &HT;    U.S. LAUNCHES AIR STRIKES AGAINST IRAQ
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1217, US-MILITARY-1217-1STLD,
CLINTON-WAGTHEDOG-1217-1STLD.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. and British forces launched massive air
strikes on Iraqi military and communications sites late Wednesday,
as President Clinton said patience had run out on Baghdad's secret
efforts to build chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''Iraq has abused its final chance,'' Clinton said in a
televised Oval Office address announcing the strikes, as U.S. B-52
bombers, F-16 fighters and warships at sea loosed more than 100
cruise missiles on Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq responded with sporadic anti-aircraft fire, but as of late
Wednesday U.S. officials reported no American casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the operation, dubbed ''Desert Fox,'' would consist
of ''a strong, sustained series of air strikes,'' expected to
continue day and night at least until the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to diminish Iraq's weapons production capability and
to strike hard at the heart of the Iraqi military, the backbone of
President Saddam Hussein's two-decade grip on power in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   In response, House Republicans postponed debate that was
scheduled to begin Thursday on whether to impeach Clinton on
charges stemming from the Monica Lewinsky sex-and-deception
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials denied any link between the two events,
and Clinton said the controversy has not divided the nation on
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was not a factor in the president's decision,'' White
House National Security Adviser Samuel E. ``Sandy'' Berger told
reporters. ''This is an action taken by the president solely on the
basis of his best judgment of what is in the national security
interest of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Girding Americans against the images of civilian deaths, Clinton
cautioned that ''there will be unintended Iraqi casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar strikes that were planned but not executed against Iraq
last month could have killed several thousand Iraqi civilians,
according to Pentagon estimates, and Berger said the strikes that
began Wednesday night would be ''no less than what we had
contemplated in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Without referring to specific estimates on such deaths, Clinton
said, ''We must be prepared for these realities.''
</P>
<P>
   Saddam told the Iraqi people that several targets had been hit,
and he accused the United States and Britain of cowardice for
striking with long-range missiles instead of assuming the higher
risks of close-range bombing strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fight the enemies of God, enemies of the nation, enemies of
humanity,'' Saddam implored his countrymen in a statement carried
by the official Iraqi News Agency, the Associated Press reported
from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's strikes were another step in eight years of U.S.
efforts to contain Iraq's military ambitions. The attack capped a
year-long standoff between the Clinton administration and Saddam
over the issue of Iraq's efforts to build and hide weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''Saddam Hussein must not be allowed to threaten his neighbors,
or the world, with nuclear weapons, poison gas or biological
weapons,'' Clinton said. ''Other countries possess weapons of mass
destruction . . . with Saddam, there is one big difference: he has
used them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ''left unchecked, Saddam Hussein will use these
terrible weapons again.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Iraq's weapons, Clinton made clear that the military
might that props up Saddam's regime is also being targeted, in the
hope of weakening his ability to retain control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hard fact is that so long as Saddam remains in power he
threatens the well-being of his people, the peace of his region,
the security of the world,'' Clinton said. ''The best way to end
that threat once and for all is with a new Iraqi government.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of his surrender to U.S.-led coalition forces
following the Persian Gulf War in 1991, Saddam agreed to dismantle
his weapons of mass destruction program and to permit U.N.
inspectors to verify his compliance with that promise.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this year -- in February and again in November -- Clinton
has arrayed massive force against Iraq and threatened air strikes
after Saddam so impeded U.N. inspections teams that they were
unable to effectively do their work.
</P>
<P>
   After the latest showdown, on November 15 and 16, Saddam
promised to cooperate fully with the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, he's continued to obstruct them, according
to a report filed Wednesday with the United Nations by Richard
Butler, chief of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), charged with
overseeing the inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ''In short, the inspectors are saying that, even if they could
stay in Iraq, their work would be a sham,'' Clinton said. ''Instead
of the inspectors disarming Saddam, Saddam has disarmed the
inspectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq disputed that assessment, saying Clinton was determined to
strike Iraq and was trumping up a crisis to justify it.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the last three weeks, there has been about 300
visits,'' by UNSCOM inspectors, Iraq's ambassador to the United
Nations, Nizar Hamdoon, told reporters in New York. ''Iraq has done
its best to try to meet the obligations and try to satisfy both
UNSCOM and the
</P>
<P>
   IAEA,'' referring to the International Atomic Energy Agency, the
U.N. arm that has been inspecting Iraq's alleged efforts to acquire
nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said it was important to strike quickly in the face of
the UNSCOM report, to prevent Iraq from taking evasive and
defensive measures, as it has in the past, to mitigate the effects
of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   While stopping short of condemning the attacks, U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan expressed frustration and grief over them. He
stressed Iraq's humanitarian needs and made no mention of Saddam's
record of UNSCOM impedance.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a sad day for the United Nations, and for the world,''
he told reporters at U.N. headquarters in New York. ''My thoughts
tonight are with the people of Iraq and with the 307 United Nations
humanitarian workers who remain in the country and all others whose
lives are in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the United
States had the support, in the U.N. Security Council and in the
international community at large, it needed to conduct the strikes,
and she dismissed the suggestion that the attack had been launched
with unnecessary haste.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States did no go looking for this fight,'' Albright
told reporters. ''We have explored and exhausted every diplomatic
option.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
