</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MILITARY-1217-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: updates with Penatgon briefings, quotes throughout
 &HT;    MILITARY FORCES WERE ALREADY DEPLOYED
 &HT;    With US-AIRSTRIKES-1217-1STLD.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concern about Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's
ability to ``threaten his neighbors'' with chemical and biological
weapons was the underlying cause of America's decision to attack
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen promised that the Tomahawk
cruise missiles that rained their 2,000-pound warheads down on Iraq
early Thursday (Iraq time) was the first of what would be a
``serious and sustained'' assault.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also referred to concerns about the possibility that
Hussein could develop and use nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Cohen nor Army Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, would say specifically how long they
expected the military action the Pentagon had designated
``Operation: Desert Fox'' to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective of the attack is to go after those chemical,
biological or weapons of mass destruction sites,'' Cohen said at a
Pentagon briefing, ``and to prevent him from being able to deliver,
to the best of our ability, the chemical or biological or nuclear
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The military hardware deployed to carry out that mission was
impressive:
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a carrier task force made up of the U.S.S.
Enterprise, two guided missile cruisers, two guided missile
destroyers and missile-armed attack submarine, the United States
had 16 other ships in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Over 200 aircraft, ranging from B-52s based at the Indian Ocean
island of Diego Garcia to helicopters aboard the Marine helicopter
assault ship U.S.S. Belleau Wood were arrayed against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   A second carrier task force, assembled around the U.S.S. Carl
Vinson was en route to the Persian Gulf from bases in the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Asia ``Crisis Response Force'' also included Air
Force F-15s , F-16s and F-117 stealth fighters.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 24,100 troops from all four branches of the service
also were in the area, Defense Department spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen acknowledged that striking Iraq's facilities for
manufacturing chemical and biological would be complicated by the
fact that the plants may be hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   But both he and Shelton predicted that before the United States
has finished its attack the Iraqi leaders ability to use such
weapons will be ``degraded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very carefully selected those things that are very
closely associated with the things that he uses to transport, the
things he uses to protect, the things he uses to guard his
facilities, as well as delivery facilities and some production
capabilities,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not be more specific about the targets of the first
wave of U.S. attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said military planners have been working on details of
the assault since mid-November when most of the U.S. forces were
originally deployed to the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cohen and Shelton refused to say even which weapons
systems were used in the first attacks, Greg Seigle, a weapons
analyst with Jane's Information Group, said Tomahawk cruise
missiles are designed for just such a use.
</P>
<P>
   Accurate, dependable and capable of carrying any of several
different kinds of warheads, the Tomahawk could be launched from
most of the ships in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   It is also likely, Seigle said, that Tomahawks launched against
Iraq Wednesday at 5 p.m. Washington time (early in the morning in
Baghdad), carried a new 2,000-pound ``BLU 116'' warhead that
reportedly has twice the penetrating capability of its
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   After one or two cruise missile attacks, the typical strategy in
an action like that ordered against Iraq by President Clinton would
be to attack with a ``wide array'' of manned aircraft, Seigle said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``you could keep hitting him with the Tomahawk.
It's so accurate, there's no reason to stop using it if you don't
want to.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
