<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IMPEACH-3, 12-16 -- As
President Clinton announces strikes on Baghdad on Wednesday, Robert
Livingston, the Speaker-elect, emphasizes support for American
troops. Other Republicans voiced suspicions. (Keith Myers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IRAQ-VOICES, 12-16 --
Passers-by in Times Square pause to watch Wednesday as the air
strikes in Baghdad unfold live on the large screen. If President
Clinton was trying to divert attention from his personal problems
by bombing Iraq, he succeeded. Instead of talking about his
probable impeachment, Americans turned their attention to
questioning the president's motives in launching air strikes.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- FBN-JETS, 12-16 --
David Meggett, the newest member of the New York Jets, picks up
equipment at his locker during a workout in Hempstead on Wednesday.
Meggett says that, despite 11 months away from football, he is
ready to play Saturday against the Buffalo Bills. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNITED NATIONS-- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IRAQ-U.N., 12-16 --
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan delivers a statement to reporters
after it is announced that U.S. and British forces had conducted
military strikes against Iraq on Wednesday. In the hours before the
strike began, some 133 relief workers remained behind at the United
Nations' Baghdad headquarters on Annan's orders. (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IMPEACH-WHIP, 12-16 --
Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip and chief
legislative strategist behind the drive to impeach President
Clinton, arriving Wednesday for the meeting of the Republican
caucus. ``Believe me, I take no pleasure in this,'' he says. ``But
it's absolutely clear to me.'' (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IMPEACH-TRIPP, 12-16 --
Linda Tripp reads her statement to reporters after her final
appearence before independent counsel Kenneth Starr and the grand
jury in July. If the Senate conducts an impeachment trial, the
Democrats will likely try again to raise questions about the chain
of events that led Tripp, who taped her conversations with Monica
Lewinsky, to Starr's office. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IRAQ-U.S.-6, 12-16 --
According to U.S. officials, B-52 bombers, similar to the one shown
here, were used in Wednesday's bombing of targets in Iraq.
President Clinton ordered air strikes against Iraq for flouting
U.N. mandates to account for weapons of mass destruction.
(Boeing/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IMPEACH-2, 12-16 --
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch listens to a live
broadcast of President Clinton announcing U.S. military action
against Iraq on Wednesday. On the eve of an impeachment vote before
the House of Representatives, President Clinton ordered air strikes
against Iraq for flouting U.N. mandates to account for weapons of
mass destruction. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) ABOARD THE USS ENTERPRISE -- Dec. 16, 1998 --
IRAQ-U.S.-5, 12-16 -- On the flight deck of the USS Enterprise in
the Persian Gulf on Wednesday, aviation ordnancemen wheel a cart
carrying two 500 pound laser guided bombs to be attached to an F/A
18 ``Hornet.'' The U.S. and Britain launched a series of air
strikes against Iraq on Wednesday, claiming retaliation for Iraq's
refusal to cooperate with U.N. weapons inspectors. (Photographer's
Mate 1st Class Todd Cichonowicz/New York Times Photo)
