   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 12-16
-- Homeowners who do their own home repairs need to buy lumber at
the local lumber yard. Do-it-yourselfers, however, are often
confused by the terms used to classify wood and they are unsure
what to look for when picking out boards. (Edward R. Lipinski/New
York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- PETRONIO-DANCE-REVIEW,
12-16 -- Locked in torment: Members of the Stephen Petronio Dance
Company in ``Not Garden,'' at the Joyce Theater. It soon becomes
evident that if anything about this work is meant to refer to a
garden, that garden is not Eden. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) FLORENCE, Italy -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- ITALY-UFFIZI-2,
12-16 -- A worker in the Uffizi Gallery applying finishing touches
to one of the statues damaged in a 1993 bombing attributed to the
Mafia. This week, Italy completed a major renovation of the Uffizi.
It is the most recent - and stunning - example of how Italy is
seeking to renovate its 760 state museums and monuments and
introduce contemporary forms of merchandising at the most important
ones. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) FLORENCE, Italy -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- ITALY-UFFIZI-1,
12-16 -- A worker applying gold leaf to a railing at the Uffizi.
This week, Italy unveiled what it calls the New Uffizi, a major
renovation that in addition to repairing damaged rooms, added more
than 20,000 square feet of museum space, including a new annex for
a collection of 144 artworks that have never been shown before.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ABOARD USS ENTERPRISE -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IRAQ-U.S.-4,
12-16 -- An F/A-18 ``Hornet'' begins its take off run off the
flight deck of the USS Enterprise as the aircraft carrier patrolled
the Persian Gulf earlier this month. The carrier heads an armada of
warships which could be called into action in the event of a
military strike against Iraq. U.N. weapons experts pulled out of
Baghdad on Wednesday as Iraq braced for U.S. and British air
strikes. (Photographer's Mate 1st Class Nicholas D. Sherrouse/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LEXINGTON, Mass. -- Dec. 16, 1998 --
RAYTHEON-BURNHAM-BOS, 12-16 -- Daniel Burnham, chief executive of
Raytheon Co. Burnham, who took over in July, is just the fifth
leader in Raytheon's 76-year history, and the first outsider
brought in to take its helm. Burnham, 52, a midwesterner with an
MBA and a penchant for fast cars, intends to decentralize
decision-makin and reduce the company's bureaucracy. (Frank
O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TEWKSBURY, Mass. -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- STARTUP-AGAIN-BOS,
12-16 -- Desh Despande, left, and Dan Smith were leaders of Cascade
Communications Corp., a telecommunications equipment maker that was
sold in 1997 for $3.7 billion, leaving them to split more than $150
million in Ascend stock. In February - barely seven months out of
Cascade - Deshpande launched another telecommunications start-up,
Sycamore Networks Inc., and recruited Smith as president and chief
executive. (Tom Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) OFF THE COAST OF VIRGINIA -- Dec. 16, 1998 --
IRAQ-U.S.-3, 12-16 -- The aircraft carrier USS Enterprise prepares
for flight operations off the coast of Virginia before being
deployed to the Persian Gulf. The carrier, currently in the
northern Gulf region, heads an armada of warships which could be
called into action in the event of a military strike against Iraq.
U.N. weapons experts pulled out of Baghdad on Wednesday as Iraq
braced for U.S. and British air strikes. (Lt. Steve Davis/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IMPEACH, 12-16 -- Two
people who were part of a group with People for The American Way
stand outside of House Speaker-elect Bob Livingston's office on
Wednesday as a guard looks on at left. The group's representatives
had brought boxes of petitions calling against the impeachment of
President Clinton. Livingston, seen at center, declined to meet
with them. The House is expected to hold a vote on the articles of
impeachment on Thursday. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- CIR-SUICIDE, 12-16 -- Ted
Greenberg, a program coordinator, interviews a student at Roosevelt
High School in the Bronx. The interview is part of an exercise
designed to prevent suicide among teen-agers. (G. Paul Burnett/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IRAQ-U.S.-2, 12-16 -- UN
weapons experts pulled out Wednesday from Baghdad as Iraq braced
for U.S. and British air strikes following a report that Baghdad
had failed to cooperate fully with the arms inspectors. Any attack
by the U.S. would involve the use of Cruise Missiles, like the one
shown in this undated photo. (Boeing/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LAS VEGAS -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- CIR-GAMBLE-2, 12-16 -- A
couple reacts to some winnings at a slot machine in Palace Station.
Computers are augmenting the glitter of gambling machines with
high-end graphics such as these in the Las Vegas casino. (Eduardo
Citrinblum/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LAS VEGAS -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- CIR-GAMBLE, 12-16 -- A
computer network links 700 Megabucks slot machines in Nevada, like
this one at the Palace Station Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas. A
central computer puts some of the money gambled at each machine
into the jackpot, which can be won at any Megabucks machine.
(Eduardo Citrinblum/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. -- Dec. 15, 1998 --
DEE-DAVIS-ANNIVERSARY, 12-15 -- Ruby Dee and Ossie Davis at their
home just outside of New York City. In November the couple
published a joint memoir, ``With Ossie and Ruby: In This Life
Together,'' an assessment of their lives together spanning the 50
years they have been married. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ABOARD USS ENTERPRISE -- Dec. 16, 1998 -- IRAQ-U.S.,
12-16 -- An F/A-18 ``Hornet'' is positioned for take off by the
flight deck crew of the USS Enterprise in the Persian Gulf earlier
this month. UN weapons experts pulled out Wednesday from Baghdad as
Iraq braced for U.S. and British air strikes following a report
that Baghdad had failed to cooperate fully with the arms
inspectors. (Photographer's Mate Airman Jason D. Malcom/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
