<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-H     12-16 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS AGREE TO DELAY IMPEACHMENT VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hours before a constitutional showdown with the
White House, House Republicans agreed late Wednesday to postpone a
vote on whether to impeach President Clinton as he launched a
military attack against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The House's presidential impeachment debate, only the second in
U.S. history, was set to begin Thursday and had been expected to
end with a vote along party lines to put the president on trial in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Although House action on impeachment was put off, a move that
angered several conservative Republicans who have pushed to end
Clinton's presidency, lawmakers plan to convene anyway to consider
a resolution of support for U.S. military forces.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker-elect Bob Livingston declined to question Clinton's
motivation for launching the missile attack on the eve of the
impeachment debate, but the New Orleans Republican warned that it
would not be put off indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to ask that all members, Republican and Democrat,
remain available to the call of the chair for further action,
possibly Friday, possibly Saturday, but within the near future,''
Livingston told reporters as he emerged from a two-hour,
closed-door meeting of House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   While the attack on Iraq delayed the start of the debate, it was
not expected to change the outcome. Before the missile launch
Wednesday, more moderate Republicans, a segment of the GOP the
White House had hoped would side with Clinton, announced their
support for at least one of the four articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The articles, recommended last week in a series of party-line
votes by the House Judiciary Committee, accuse the president of
perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of power in trying to
hide his affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of even one article of impeachment will send the
president's case to the Senate for trial, a process experts say
could last several months.
</P>
<P>
   Republican moderates announcing their decision to vote against
the president were Reps. Brian Bilbray of California, Sherwood
Boehlert of New York, Jim Leach of Iowa and Bob Ney of Ohio. Also
announcing plans to support impeachment were Jay Kim of California,
Mike Pappas of New Jersey, Billy Tauzin of Louisiana and John
Porter, an Illinois moderate who said he could no longer oppose
impeachment, a position he staked out earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the impression that the president considers himself
above the law,'' Porter said. ``If there are no consequences for
the president's conduct, our commitment to truth and the rule of
law is undermined.''
</P>
<P>
   As word spread that Clinton had ordered military action and then
that House leaders were planning to postpone the impeachment
debate, some Republicans responded with fury and questioned whether
the attack was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart dismissed suggestions
that Clinton was trying to escape House action with a blend of
military and political chicanery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States makes national security
decisions based on the best interest of the United States, based on
the recommendations of his national security advisers and in the
best interest of the people of the United States,'' Lockhart told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cynicism is at an all-time high,'' said Rep. Curt Weldon,
a Pennsylvania Republican. ``This is the `anything to keep my job'
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Clinton critic Rep. Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who
filed a presidential impeachment resolution in late 1997 well
before the Lewinsky affair began dominating the news, called the
timing of the Iraq attack ``highly suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Paul of Texas called the bombing a ``despicable'' act
that in itself was an impeachable offense. ``How many American
soldiers and innocent Iraqi children will die so that this
president can hide from justice?'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del., said he had all but given up on
convincing Livingston, Richard Armey, R-Texas, and other party
leaders to allow a vote on an impeachment alternative, a harshly
worded censure resolution that, if endorsed by the president, would
impose a $2 million fine. If House leaders stick by their plans to
not allow a vote on censure, Castle said he is undecided whether he
will vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said there were no plans for any dramatic overtures by
the president to fend off an impeachment vote by the House. At the
same time, Lockhart said, White House officials are continuing to
seek a compromise short of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton never met as planned Wednesday with Rep. Christopher
Shays, a Connecticut Republican who once opposed impeachment but is
now wavering. He did meet with Rep. Amo Houghton, a New York
Republican who has announced he is against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
