<DOCNO> NYT19981216.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-MILITARY-1STLD-W     12-16 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQI ATTACK LARGEST SINCE THE GULF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT, UN inspection program is 7 years
old, sted 8; trims redundant material from 6th graf, The United
State ...; tightens elsewhere.)  
(See also IRAQ-U.S., IRAQ-ASSESS, IRAQ-LEGAL, IRAQ-U.N., IRAQ-TV,
IRAQ-INSPECT, IRAQ-KUWAIT, IRAQ-VOICES, IRAQ-ALLIES, IRAQ-REACT)
(nk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The military strike against Iraq ordered by
President Clinton on Wednesday was by far the largest and most
punishing since the 1991 Gulf War and was intended to cripple
Iraq's ability to make chemical, biological and nuclear weapons,
according to senior administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   They said the joint U.S.-British attack, which is expected to
last at least until this weekend, began with a wave of more than
200 Tomahawk cruise missiles, most of them launched against
facilities believed to be used by the Iraqis for the manufacture or
storage of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Other missiles, they said, were targeted against compounds of
buildings used by Iraqi intelligence agencies and by the elite
military unit known as the Republican Guard. Initial reports
Wednesday night suggested that one of President Saddam Hussein's
marble-draped palaces in central Baghdad had also been hit, and
that ambulances were rushing to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   While senior U.S. officials insisted that the air strikes would
significantly hamper Iraq's programs to make poison gas and nuclear
weapons, they readily acknowledged that the weapons programs would
continue and perhaps accelerate, and that the air strikes could
mean the end of the 7-year-old U.N. weapons inspection program in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Without the inspection program, they said, the Clinton
administration would have only a limited ability to monitor Iraq's
program to manufacture weapons of mass destruction _ and to prevent
Iraq from threatening its neighbors with poison gas.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, they said, will likely be forced to leave a
large military force in the region for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already acknowledged that a military strike like the
one launched Wednesday would sound the death knell for the weapons
inspections that have been carried out in Iraq by the U.N. Special
Commission, or UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   When he called off air strikes on Iraq last month, Clinton said
then that he had made the decision in part because he believed such
an attack ``would mean the end of UNSCOM'' and ``we would then have
no oversight, no insight, no involvement in what is going on in
Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After this, it's hard to imagine that Saddam will ever allow
the inspectors back in,'' said one U.S. official. ``So what is our
policy? What do we do in a post-UNSCOM world? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to provide full details on the weapons fired
against Iraq and the number of U.S. warplanes and ships that joined
in the mission, administration officials said Wednesday's attack
was several times larger than any strike launched against Iraq
since the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``The others were pinpricks by comparison,'' one official said.
`'It's smaller than the war but much bigger than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1993, the United States fired 23 cruise missiles at
Iraqi intelligence headquarters in Baghdad in retaliation for an
alleged plot to assassinate former President Bush. In September
1996, 27 cruise missiles were launched against military targets in
southern Iraq in retaliation for the movement of Iraqi troops
against Kurds in northern Iraq.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   U.S. officials said that they have had target lists for the
attack ready since last month, when the United States initially
planned to launch air strikes against Iraq over its refusal to
allow unfettered weapons inspections by UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   The target list, they said, included a variety of factories,
warehouses and military compounds identified by the U.N. inspectors
as potential sites for the manufacture or stockpiling of chemical
and biological weapons, some of them in Baghdad or on the outskirts
of the Iraqi capital.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department officials, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said Wednesday's attack was similar in most respects to
the attack that was planned for last month, when the United States
and Britain were prepared to launch a first strike of nearly 300
cruise missiles from eight warships in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   They said the cruise missile attack that began Wednesday night
in Baghdad was followed by an intensive bombing campaign by F-14
and F-18 fighters launched from the aircraft carrier Enterprise,
which is now in the gulf. They said that several B-52 bombers
stationed on Diego Garcia, the British-controlled island in the
Indian Ocean, were expected to join in subsequent attacks this
week.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Defense Department, there are 24,100 U.S.
troops in the Gulf region; 22 warships, eight of them armed with
Tomahawk cruise missiles; and 201 military aircraft. The aircraft
carrier Carl Vinson is expected to join the Enterprise in the gulf
on Saturday, along with six other warships able to fire cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen announced Wednesday that he had
ordered an additional 80 to 90 aircraft, including about a dozen
F-117 ``stealth'' fighter jets, to travel to the region to join in
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has maintained a small but powerful force in the region
since last January, when Iraq's standoff over U.N. weapons
inspections first brought the threat of military action. The
British force in the region includes 12 Tornado fighter-bombers
stationed in Kuwait, six reconnaissance jets in Saudi Arabia and a
frigate in the gulf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 2218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
