<SLUG> BC-TURBODYNE-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURBODYNE SUES SHORT SELLER OVER TECHNOLOGICAL FRAUD CLAIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Turbodyne Technologies said it is suing a
well-known short seller for bad-mouthing the company, contributing
to a stock decline of 74 percent since July.
</P>
<P>
   The company filed a lawsuit against Manuel P. Asensio and his
New York firm, Asensio &AMP; Co., in Los Angeles County Superior Court.
The six-count complaint charges Asensio with fraud, defamation and
other violations for claiming that Turbodyne did not possess any
valuable technology or the patents for it.
</P>
<P>
   Turbodyne, based in suburban Woodland Hills, is seeking $60
million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Asensio is a well-known short seller -- someone who profits from
a declining stock. In a short sale, an investor borrows shares from
a broker and immediately sells them with the intention of buying
shares to pay back the broker later when the stock price drops. The
short seller profits from the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Turbodyne has short sales of 1.96 million shares, with 41.3
million shares outstanding. Its stock closed Wednesday at $4.375,
up 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In an Aug. 4 report, Asensio &AMP; Co. said that ``no manufacturer
has ever incorporated a single Turbodyne product in a new engine or
vehicle. . . . Despite raising and spending over $55 million in
equity capital, Turbodyne has failed to create any new products.''
</P>
<P>
   Asensio contends that Turbodyne's technology, incorporated into
its Turbopac and Dynacharger products and expected to improve fuel
efficiency and minimize pollution, is merely an
``electric-motor-driven supercharger.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Asensio described his company's research on
Turbodyne as ``complete, correct and accurate.'' He said Turbodyne
has been making claims about its technology for years but that it
hasn't been reflected in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fraudulent company that got caught,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Turbodyne argued that its ``breakthrough technology'' is
protected by more than 30 granted and pending patents worldwide. It
is certified by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and is
being installed in buses nationwide, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is true that Turbodyne's annual sales of $39 million
come from another part of its business -- engine components and
cast-aluminum wheels.
</P>
<P>
   An expected surge in Russian sales for the new technology
disappeared when that country lapsed into an economic crisis, said
Brett Hendrickson, an analyst at B. Riley &AMP; Co. in West Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The company had expected a positive cash flow in the fourth
quarter, but that will be pushed back now because of the situation
in Russia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the nine months ended Sept. 30, Turbodyne lost $12 million,
or 35 cents per diluted share, on sales of $29.8 million. In 1997,
the company lost $13.2 million, or 50 cents per share, on revenues
of $39 million.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
