<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Y2K Software Has Problems of Its Own  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For something that boils down to just two digits, the Year 2000
problem certainly has created a thorny dilemma for business and
governments around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It also presents risks to consumers, who may find that their
personal computers won't be able to handle the fact that ``00''
could just as easily be 1900 as 2000. And many software programs _
including Windows 98 _ could have problems when the big ball comes
down in Times Square next year on December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Where there is danger there also is opportunity, however. In
this case, it's the opportunity for software companies to make
money selling programs that fix Y2K problems in PCs. A flurry of
such programs has hit the market in recent months, and more are
sure to follow as the deadly deadline approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K programs check your hardware and software for Year 2000
compliance. They're also designed to fix many of the problems they
encounter, including changing two-digit date fields to four digits
in database and spreadsheet files.
</P>
<P>
   In most newer PCs, Y2K software probably can fix the system's
bios and clock so that they can handle the new millennium. The bios
is the built-in software that tests your system at startup and
makes sure the software can work with the hardware. If your PC was
made before 1997, however, you may have to upgrade the bios.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the two front-runners in the race for your
Year 2000 dollars are Symantec and Network Associates _ the same
companies that have made a killing scaring the hell out of people
about computer viruses and getting them to buy anti-virus programs.
Symantec sells Norton 2000 for $50, and Network Associates sells
the McAfee 2000 Toolbox for $30. Another popular Y2K program is Fix
2000, which goes for $50, from Intelliquis.
</P>
<P>
   I tested all three of those programs on a Compaq Presario loaded
with Windows 98, Microsoft Office 97, Microsoft Money, Microsoft
Front Page, WinFax Pro, America Online, Netscape Communicator,
Paint Shop Pro, Zip-It and a bunch of other stuff I can't remember.
</P>
<P>
   All three Y2K busters gave my system a passing grade in the
hardware department. But they came up with different conclusions
when it came to software.
</P>
<P>
   Norton 2000 told me that Windows 98 and WinFax Pro were known to
have Year 2000 issues (ironic, because WinFax is made by Symantec).
</P>
<P>
   McAfee's 2000 Toolbox found only one problem application _
Microsoft Money.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fix 2000, I've got problems with half a dozen
programs, including Netscape, Front Page and Adobe Acrobat Reader.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, this didn't exactly fill me with confidence.
But it did give me some insight into the horrendous difficulties
presented by the Year 2000. If my little PC is so difficult to
diagnose, think of the magnitude of the problem facing Citibank or
the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Which Y2K program did the best job? You got me. I suspect that
to ferret out all the potential problems, you'd have to run all of
them _ and perhaps a few others as well.
</P>
<P>
   Among the three programs, Norton 2000 has the best presentation.
In addition to listing applications with known Y2K problems, it
tells you which programs on your PC are questionable when it comes
to Year 2000 compliance, and which applications are claimed to be
compliant by their manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Norton 2000 also calculates the severity of each problem, so you
can identify the ones likely to torpedo your software.
</P>
<P>
   With both Norton 2000 and McAfee 2000 Toolbox, you can get the
latest update for the program anytime for free over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I have a better idea. Hold off on buying a Y2K program for now.
You've got until the end of next year to deal with it, and in the
meantime, why worry. Besides, maybe the programs will be better by
then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
