<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-tailers now offering gifts you can custom-design  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Many children tearing open their presents in the next week will
find something that makes them feel special. But a few may be
surprised by a gift that really has their name on it.
</P>
<P>
   It might be ``A Bug's Life'' T-shirt emblazoned with Johnny or
Jane's name, his or her favorite character from the film and a few
special words.
</P>
<P>
   Or a CD labeled ``Jane's CD'' with a selection of her favorite
Christmas or Hanukkah songs. Or a Barbie doll designed to look just
like her.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody likes to be seen as an individual. But in the world of
mass retailing, that's been largely impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Internet. Unlike any other mass medium, the Internet
offers merchants the ability to communicate individually with their
customers. A growing number of sites now offer personalization
features that enable customers to set preferences for what they'd
like to buy or how they'd like the site to look.
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of companies such as Disney and Mattel have taken
personalization a step further by allowing shoppers to
custom-design gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing more than taking the technology of the Internet
and putting it into the hands of the computer user,'' said Russell
Gillam, vice president for electronic commerce at the Buena Vista
Internet Group. He is responsible for both Disney.com and ESPN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Disney added ``Design Online'' to its  &LR; www.disney.com  &LR; site in
February and changes the gift selection seasonally. Although it is
too late to order a custom-designed gift for Christmas, the site
offers gifts for birthdays, holidays and other events decorated
with the smiling faces of such familiar characters as Winnie the
Pooh, Mickey and Minnie Mouse, and Flik and Atta from ``A Bug's
Life.'' Besides the characters, gift-givers can put a name or
personal message (or sometimes both) on a mug, T-shirt, watch,
picture frame, baby's romper and lots of other items.
Custom-designing adds a few dollars to the cost of the item _ an
$18 T-shirt, for instance, is $24 when you personalize it.
</P>
<P>
   Although he isn't providing specifics, Gillam said ``Design
Online'' has been a big hit. The company also is offering
personalized sports jerseys at &LR;  www.espn.com. &LR;  For an extra $30-$50
(depending on the product) shoppers can put the name and number of
their favorite player, a friend or relative or even themselves on
the back of the shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people on the Web are looking for things like this.
You can't manipulate things this way in a retail store or
catalog,'' he said. ``It's something only the Web can bring.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``mass customization'' can provide merchants with lots of
advantages, said Julia Pickar, an analyst at Zona Research in
Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of mass customization is that the customer
perceives greater value in the personalization for obvious reasons
_ they are getting exactly what they want. But the cost of
providing these products doesn't increase for each variation,''
Pickar said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the customization is self-service and doesn't
require the e-retailer to interact with each person or take the
time to record each complicated order, said Ken Cassar, an analyst
in Jupiter Communication's digital commerce group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a boon to merchants, but for customers, self-service
often can mean no service. The process isn't always easy, and the
flexibility is limited to whatever choices the merchant allows.
Finding out when an order will be delivered or whether a company
can ship in time for a holiday or event requires an e-mail or phone
call. The same goes for any questions that shoppers may have about
an item. And don't even think about changing an order _ names had
better be spelled right the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, online customization can be an easy and relatively
inexpensive way to find a unique gift. Among those singing its
praises are some of the music sites. At CDnow ( &LR; www.cdnow.com &LR; ) and
Music Boulevard ( &LR; www.musicblvd.com &LR; ) and a number of smaller
sites, customers can pick the holiday songs they want to hear and
burn them onto a CD. CDnow has Hanukkah and Christmas songs. Music
Boulevard offers only Christmas tunes. Both sites can take orders
for Christmas delivery as late as Monday (with overnight shipping).
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a lot less economical to do without the
Internet. You wouldn't have as great a reach,'' said Ted Hooban,
digital media director at CDnow.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Washington, Pa., company is selling customized holiday
CDs until December 31 and is working to add other song titles to
its ``burn-your-own'' repertoire. That involves negotiating
licensing deals with record companies, which have been reluctant to
issue licenses for individual songs because of concerns that
customers then won't buy albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``People send us e-mail and say they really like the holiday
thing and want more,'' Hooban said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Barbie dolls can get a personal touch. At Mattel's
 &LR; www.barbie.com &LR;  site, girls can design their own ``friend of
Barbie'' for $39.95. With a few clicks, they can pick the doll's
skin color, eye color, hair color and style.
</P>
<P>
   But customization will go only so far, and you can't always get
what you want. The dolls apparently must adhere to certain Barbie
beauty standards. There are no curly or kinky-haired dolls, no
plump ones and none of them wear glasses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
