<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 More Rivalry May Come to Phone Market  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Californians could inch a few steps closer toward true local
competition for telephone and high-speed data services if state
regulators approve several proposals today.
</P>
<P>
   The California Public Utilities Commission is expected to tell
Pacific Bell that it must give competitors access to the phone
company's telephone network and set cheaper rates for that access.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The commission also is expected to approve a road map
outlining steps Pac Bell must take to open the local telephone
market to competition, which it must do before the PUC will allow
it to enter the lucrative long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Since the passage of the 1996 Telecommunications Act, competing
phone companies have struggled to gain market share in California.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the companies, such as MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T, and
consumer groups have blamed Pac Bell, saying the Baby Bell has
created barriers to competition by denying affordable access to its
local phone network.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors need to connect to parts of Pac Bell's telephone
network in order to offer service because it is the only existing
infrastructure that serves most Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have been fighting with Pac Bell for the right to put
their equipment in its central offices in order to connect with Pac
Bell's network.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell has allowed some competitors in, but has often claimed
that there is no space in its central offices for all the
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC is expected to approve an order that would force Pac
Bell to prove the lack of space each time it denies a company's
request to house equipment. The proposed decision calls for an
independent, third-party inspection to verify whether there truly
is no space.
</P>
<P>
   ``For consumers, this means that every time the phone company
contends there is no space, competitors and consumers won't be
forced to take Pac Bell's word on it,'' said Dhruv Khanna, vice
president of Covad Communications. ``This is a breakthrough and it
means the first step toward true local competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Covad, a San Jose company which offers high-speed data services
such as digital subscriber lines, has been fighting Pac Bell about
the issue for more than a year. It has gotten permission to locate
its equipment in several Pac Bell offices, but is still not in
every office it wants access to.
</P>
<P>
   Khanna said he hopes the PUC's decision will change that.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mashek, a spokesman for Pac Bell, said the company supports
the proposed decision and welcomes third-party inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reasonable way to ensure that competitors have space in
our locations,'' Mashek said.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are also hopeful the commission will approve a
proposal that could lower what competitors have to pay to connect
to Pac Bell's network.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, a competitor must buy an ``unbundled network
element'' or a piece of Pac Bell's telephone network if it wants to
sell phone service in the state. Pac Bell has been charging some
competitors about $440 for each customer the competitor signs to
its network _ a charge the companies say is prohibitively
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   It's forced most companies to abandon their quest to serve
residential customers and focus instead on the lucrative business
customer market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the pricing isn't right, there will never be competition in
the residential market,'' said Barbara Gibson, a spokeswoman for
MCI. ``Pac Bell's rates (for competitor access to its network) are
the highest in the nation by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathi Oram, a spokeswoman for AT&AMP;T, said the commission's
proposed decision would make it easier for the phone giant to offer
local service to residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PACBELL1 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The decisions being made are certainly going to help us take a
step forward,'' she said. ``It puts the prices closer to cost,
which is where they should have been to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   The PUC is expected to vote on a pricing formula and is expected
to set actual prices next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Oram said the commission's expected rejection of Pac Bell's
long-distance application also will help speed competition.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a judge with the PUC recommended Pac Bell's
application to offer long-distance service be denied because it has
failed to open up the local market to competition. The decision
also outlined what steps the company needs to take to gain entry
into the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to approve the judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PACBELL1 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
