</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PUC Set To Vote on Rules for Pac Bell  &HT;       
 By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The state Public Utilities Commission is scheduled to vote today on
a new set of minimum standards intended to boost the quality of
Pacific Bell phone service.
</P>
<P>
   The vote comes in the wake of a six-month investigation by state
regulators into complaints about substandard service _ including
missed appointments, shoddy repairs and a shortage of lines _ in
Pacific Bell's huge territory that spans 52 of the state's 58
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the new standards would force Pacific Bell
to install new phones within three days of when they are ordered.
Customers would get refunds for extended delays.
</P>
<P>
   The move is an attempt to get Pacific Bell to channel money to
where it can do the most good _ upgrading equipment and adding
personnel who can provide better service.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the rules don't go far enough. Instead of tough
standards backed by stiff penalties, they say the proposed rules
rely on small refunds and the ``competitive market'' to motivate
Pacific Bell to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because there's the potential for competition, doesn't
mean we should accept a degradation in the quality of service that
has been provided to us for a hundred years,'' said Elena Schmid,
director of the PUC's Office of Ratepayer Advocates. ``The PUC has
a duty to see that ratepayers get the service they're entitled
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say the standards are weak because they apply
solely to incumbent carriers like Pacific Bell and General Tele
phone of California, not to the 600-plus other telephone companies
doing business in California.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Pacific Bell says the proposed standards are the
result of slipshod investigative work by the PUC. For one thing,
the PUC refused to hold public hearings. And it failed to collect
comprehensive complaint data, either from its own staff or the
phone company.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC's own statistics were inadmissible because flaws in the
way complaints are recorded resulted in some over counting. The
problem still has not been corrected.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC launched the investigation into phone service quality on
June 18 in response to an increasing number of complaints from
customers who were frustrated with delays in getting new phone
lines put in and getting phones repaired. By law, the PUC must
provide ``high-quality telecommunications service to all
Californians.''
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, the proposed order reflects the PUC's
ambivalence about regulating utilities in deregulated industries.
For much of this decade, the PUC watched passively as Pacific Bell
cut nearly one-third of its workforce and reduced capital
investments in the basic phone network by hundreds of millions of
dollars, when adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The insufficient spending resulted in a chronic shortage of
phone lines, increases in broken lines and long delays in reaching
people who could help.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC was warned repeatedly in the past five years that
Pacific Bell service had deteriorated. But it adopted a hands-off
posture, trusting the marketplace to make Pacific Bell improve
service.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in July 1997, the chiefs of the PUC's
telecommunications and consumer services divisions gave the
five-member commission a memorandum that detailed substandard
service during a 20-month period ending in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The memo, which was updated in January, compared Pacific Bell's
performance with industry standards developed by the National
Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners, some state
standards and the phone company's own internal goals.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, it found:
</P>
<P>
   _ Repair work was abysmal. NARUC said states should require 90
percent of work orders be completed within 24 hours. Pacific Bell's
goal was 60 percent. Its average performance was 40.6 percent.
California had no standard, and the proposed rules simply grant
small daily refunds if repairs take too long.
</P>
<P>
   _ Installation performance was substandard. NARUC said states
should require 90 percent of installations be completed within
three days. Pac Bell's average was 75.9 percent within three days.
</P>
<P>
   Its internal target was 80 percent within one day when the July
1997 memo was prepared. By the time it was revised in January, the
phone company had reduced its internal objective to 80 percent
within five days.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of knocking heads at Pac Bell over these performance
problems, the commission preferred to tweak the market structure
that it believed had failed consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the five PUC members, all Republicans, trusted
competitive markets to police service quality, even though Pac Bell
faces no meaningful competition for the dial tone service it
provides to 25 million of the state's 32 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   PUC Commissioner Jessie Knight Jr. defended the commission's
approach. ``It's not necessarily Pac Bell I would fault but the
whole monopoly system that's been used to provide service,'' he
said. ``I blame the regulatory scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications Inc. of Texas acknowledged it inherited a
system punctuated with problems when it took control of Pacific
Bell last year. ``We knew something had to be done,'' said Ed
Mueller, former chief of Southwestern Bell who has headed Pacific
Bell for a year.
</P>
<P>
   SBC dramatically stepped up spending and hiring, but the weight
of past neglect, combined with explosive demand for new lines for
fax machines and Internet browsing, made the game of catchup
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   When the commission meets today, it will consider a hastily
written order that was written with input from only a handful of
telephone utilities and consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   Why the haste? The terms of two of the PUC's five commissioners
expire at the end of the year. That means there is a push to get
work out the door. ``It's hard to set a standard that covers the
whole waterfront,'' said Greg Conlon, the lead commissioner on the
case. ``In the short run, I just wanted to fix the problems we know
we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some provisions of the proposed order:
</P>
<P>
   _ It requires that 90 percent of phone installations be
completed within three days of when service is ordered, but only
``when sufficient existing plant (equipment) is available.''
</P>
<P>
   The order gives utilities who claim they don't have sufficient
equipment a huge loophole.
</P>
<P>
   _ It refunds installation fees to customers when commitments are
not met. But the utilities are given a ``grace period'' that can
extend as long as 11 days after the order is placed, even when
there is no capacity problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ It grants refunds to customers who cannot get broken phones
fixed fast enough. The refunds, though, only begin three days after
the phone has broken. The daily credit, 37.5 cents for most
residential customers, is barely enough to cover one pay-phone
call.
</P>
<P>
   Although consumer advocates believe the rules fall short of what
Californians deserve, they say they will take any improvements they
can get, especially since they are the first contemplated by the
PUC since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rare to get sweeping decisions that do everything
you want,'' said Schmid. ``We can build on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft decision does strengthen a requirement that Pac Bell
answer 80 percent of all complaint calls within 20 seconds _ one of
California's few standards.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the phone company does not count calls that get busy
signals. The proposed order says such calls should fall under the
20-second rule.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell's Mueller said most of its system problems have
been fixed. ``I really feel we're where we need to be,'' he said.
The company is spending $800 million this year improving the
``local loop'' to increase calling capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say there is no regulatory system, including the
proposed set of standards, to prevent backsliding in the future.
``The only thing that can prevent a recurrence is a commission
interested in exercising its authority,'' said Regina Costa, a
telecommunications analyst for the Utility Reform Network in San
Francisco, a nonprofit advocacy group. ``That's something this
commission is loath to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about Pacific Bell began rising shortly after the PUC
changed the way the company is compensated for the service it
provides for nearly 18 million access lines in California.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called New Regulatory Framework, adopted in 1989, ended
the practice of reimbursing the utility for its investments
dollar-for-dollar. Instead, the utility was given a big pot of
money and allowed to decide, pretty much on its own, how to spend
it.
</P>
<P>
   This new process was supposed to encourage Pacific Bell to
become more efficient, but it also allowed the company to pass
savings along to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   When the new rate-making system began, the phone company had
61,500 employees. By 1996, it had 42,500 workers. Currently, it has
53,000.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell's Mueller said California does not need new
standards. He downplays fears that service could deteriorate again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to stumble, someone will drive a Mack truck through
us,'' he said. ``No company could allow that to happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
