<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BofA Forms S.F. Unit for Electronic Payments  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BankAmerica Corp. has set up a group based in San Francisco to
develop the bank's electronic payments strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina bank, which bought San Francisco's
BankAmerica in September and took its name, appointed Chris
Callero, a 27-year veteran of the old BofA, to head the unit.
</P>
<P>
   The new group will chart the bank's course as it rolls out
next-generation electronic payments technologies, such as the
presentation of bills to consumers by computer or interactive
television.
</P>
<P>
   Callero's organization is a planning group that will work with
the business units that will use the new technologies. Those
include commercial businesses, such as corporate cash management,
and consumer banking businesses, such as card services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to build the integrated strategy for the company``
in electronic commerce, Callero said.
</P>
<P>
   Callero said he's still hiring staff for the unit. ``We will be
small and mighty. There is not going to be a whole lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, banks are shifting from checks to electronic
payment systems to cut costs and keep customers. Both the old BofA
and NationsBank _ the two banks that combined to form the new BofA
_ have invested hundreds of millions in digital payments
technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
