<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Fix A PC After An Outage  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I was using my computer when the lights went out in San
Francisco last week. The power went out, came back on after a
second, then went out again. When power was finally restored, I got
back on the computer and found there were some problems that I'm
not sure I can fix.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some of the keys on the keyboard are sporadically not
responding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Four of the icons on the Windows desktop have changed to small
numbered Windows icons that don't show exactly what they do.
</P>
<P>
   _ When typing in Word, I see flashes of the red and green
underlines throughout the page.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scanning light in my scanner is on all the time. So I had
to unplug it.
</P>
<P>
   Do I need to get a repairman, or is this something I can fix
myself? I have a service agreement with Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  OK, here's what you do. Open the computer case,
scoop out the innards and use it as a planter box. Just kidding.
Since you have the service agreement, I'd get on the phone to
Gateway. But if you want to have a go at it yourself, here are a
few things you can try.
</P>
<P>
   First, run the ScanDisk program, which you'll find in the System
Tools folder inside the Accessories folder in the Windows Programs
menu. ScanDisk will check your hard drive for errors, and fix
anything minor (assuming ScanDisk itself hasn't been damaged).
</P>
<P>
   After running ScanDisk, restart the PC. If you still have
problems (and you probably will), reinstall Windows, Word and any
other damaged applications. Also reinstall the driver for your
scanner. If, after doing all this, you've still got trouble, it
probably means the power surge frazzled something in the computer's
circuit system. And for that, you'll need a technician.
</P>
<P>
   Too Good to Be True
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me if the Internet service provider AtBigger.net
has gone under? They offered lifetime service for $60, and I signed
up. But now all access numbers are busy constantly and their
customer service numbers have been disconnected. Also, is there
another ISP that offers lifetime service for even a little more
money?
</P>
<P>
   A: AtBigger.net is a classic example of the adage, if something
seems too good to be true, it probably is. The San Jose company
couldn't survive with its pricing scheme, even though it amassed
some 40,0000 customers. It was acquired in October by Brigadoon, a
Seattle-based ISP which also is having financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Brigadoon reported on its Web site
( &LR; www.brigadoon.com &LR; ) that all access to AtBigger.net had been shut
down. It said it is working to restore service, but didn't say how
long that might take. You can try phoning them at (206) 652-9365
(they're in Seattle), or by sending e-mail to  &LR; admin(AT &LR; 
 &LR; SIGN)brigadoon.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   As for other ISPs, I don't know of any in Northern California
that offer lifetime service. It certainly doesn't appear to be a
profitable way to run a business. However, many ISPs will give you
service for as little as $8 a month if you sign up for a year in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Printing Problem
</P>
<P>
   Q: In printing a document in Microsoft Word, is there a way to
make the ``current page'' the default rather than ``All?''
Sometimes I want to print on both sides of the paper. But Word
won't let me pause while printing so I can reverse the paper and
thus do it in one operation.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't change the default, but there is a way to work
around it. In the Print window, type in just the odd numbered pages
_ 1,3,5 etc. When the printing job is finished, turn the printed
pages around and print on the back using the even numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Tower or Desktop
</P>
<P>
   Q: What advantages does a tower PC have over a desktop model?
And which would you recommend?
</P>
<P>
   A: Full-sized towers generally have more room inside than
desktops for adding things like video and sound cards and extra
hard drives. But the trend is toward minitowers, which don't offer
any advantages. If you plan to add components, look for a big tower
such as the Hewlett-Packard Pavilion series, which is designed for
easy expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Operationally, there's no difference between a tower and a
desktop. It comes down to whether you want the computer on the desk
or on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  If your computer crashes, or you get a new one, you're going to
have to re-enter information that's necessary to log onto your ISP
and any other online accounts that you have, including banking and
customized Web pages. So do yourself a favor and write down all
your user IDs, passwords, log-on phone numbers and DNS numbers and
keep them somewhere safe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
