A4071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      12-16 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQI ATTACK FAILS TO UNITE LAWMAKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For most of the year Monica Lewinsky and Saddam
Hussein have competed for Americans' attention.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the two dramas collided when President Clinton
approved U.S. airstrikes against Iraq just a day before the House
was to open debate on impeaching the commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   The events did little to unite members of both parties _ as
military actions traditionally do _ but rather inflamed poisonous
partisanship that has infected the nation's capital during the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   And while the military action forced congressional Republicans
to delay the impeachment vote, few believe it is likely to affect
the outcome, which appears to be tilting against the president.
</P>
<P>
   However, some observers said the attack will give the president
a few precious days to try and halt the momentum growing against
him.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, it allows Clinton to bolster his image at a time
when Republicans are harshly condemning his ethics and questioning
his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the airstrikes spread among House members as they were
walking into their respective party meetings to map out strategy
for the impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans were unable to contain their anger, voicing
suspicions that the attack was politically timed to distract the
nation from the president's domestic woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a liar, and he can't be trusted,'' shouted Rep. Dana
Rohrbacher, R-Calif., as he walked into a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A number said it only reinforced their belief that the president
should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspicions some people have about the president's motives
in this attack is a powerful argument for impeachment,'' said House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``After months of lies the
president has given millions of people around the world reason to
doubt that he has sent Americans into battle for the right
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, said that ``today's events have
reinforced the need for President Clinton to resign or be removed
from office.''
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual move, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss, issued a press release just moments before the bombing
saying he opposed the military action.
</P>
<P>
   Others rushed to the television cameras to condemn the
president's motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that he is doing it for political reasons, and I
and others are outraged,'' Rep. Gerald Solomon, an outspoken
Republican from New York, told Cable News Network.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks triggered an immediate backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, was hissed by many of his
colleagues when he interrupted a briefing by Defense Department
officials to ask if there was any reason the impeachment hearing
couldn't continue during the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused their colleagues of breaking with tradition by
engaging in partisan attacks on the president when troops were
engaged in military action abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, called Republican criticism ``rather
crass'' and a ``cheap shot.'' He noted that members of Congress
still supported President Reagan when he took military action
during the Iran-Contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stop the world while all this is going on,'' Bentsen
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, also called Republicans
``irresponsible'' for questioning the military action, saying such
divisiveness would only embolden Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas, said that Saddam may have been
trying to take advantage of perceived U.S. weakness because of the
impeachment fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit on our hands because we are going through this
constitutional crisis,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most political observers said there is little question that the
military strike will enhance the embattled president's standing
with the voters in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drop a bomb and your ratings go up 10 points,'' said Larry
Sabato, political science professor at the University of Virginia,
who believes that the president factored in political
considerations in deciding to launch the attack the day before the
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   He noted this is the second time the president has taken
military action when he was in trouble. In August, Clinton sent
cruise missiles into Afghanistan and the Sudan days after he
admitted to an improper relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the events were likened to the movie ``Wag the
Dog,'' where a president embroiled in a sex scandal concocts a fake
war to distract the voters.
</P>
<P>
   University of Pennsylvania political science professor Mark
Rozell said that Republicans are unlikely to back away from
impeachment even if the president gets a short-term popularity
boost.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Clinton currently enjoys high approval ratings but
that has has not stopped GOP lawmakers from pursuing impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bottom line is the Republicans will do what they
have planned on doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are aware of the public relations problem of pushing
the impeachment vote into Christmas week, when Americans might view
such action as unseemly.
</P>
<P>
   They are also alarmed at the prospect that prolonged military
action could force the impeachment debate into next year. That
could jeopardize any impeachment effort because the Republicans
will lose five seats from their majority.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
