<SLUG> BC-NY-JFK-THEFT-RING-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRPORT THEFT RING IS BROKEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Law enforcement officials Wednesday shut down a major
theft ring that stole millions of dollars in merchandise from
warehouses around Kennedy International Airport, moving against a
crime that officials say saddles customers with incalculable hidden
costs on many everyday purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Officials recovered more than $5 million in stolen items that
ranged from specialized items like airplane data recorders and
designer Italian suits to more common purchases like Disney wall
clocks, bottles of aspirin and anti-smoking kits.
</P>
<P>
   They said, however, that the $5 million in goods was probably
only a small percentage of the total losses from cargo theft in and
around the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year investigation involved city, state and federal
officials and resulted in the indictment of 56 people, including
warehouse owners, teamster shop stewards and owners of stores
across the city that sold the stolen goods.
</P>
<P>
   As the announcement was being made, as many as 300 law
enforcement officials were rounding up the suspects, 43 of whom
were in custody by last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Queens district attorney, Richard A. Brown, said that
``virtually everything and anything that moves through J.F.K.'' was
included in the ring's inventory. He said breaking up the ring was
crucial for ``protecting one of New York's most valuable economic
resources, the airport, but also the consuming public.''
</P>
<P>
   The airport's $100-billion-a-year air cargo industry, which has
made it the fourth busiest cargo airport in the world, has long
been a target of theft and corruption operations that for years had
been controlled by organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that at least two of the people arrested
Wednesday had ties to the Lucchese and Gambino crime families, but
added that organized crime no longer had exclusive rights to air
cargo theft, as most of those arrested were warehouse workers or
otherwise legitimate business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Caron, a detective with the police of the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey, said that cargo theft had
become so routine at airports across the country that many
companies regularly shipped far more items than a retailer ordered
because they expected a certain amount to be stolen. He said that
the computer industry in particular had become a very popular
target.
</P>
<P>
   The record of recovered stolen goods read like an exhaustive
holiday shopping list. There were hundreds of name-brand laptop
computers, 11,000 Remington electric shavers valued at $1.8
million, boxes of Kodak cameras and 10,000 rolls of Kodak film;
crates of Hugo Boss and Estee Lauder perfume, racks of designer
suits, loads of Calvin Klein and Ralph Lauren shirts and sweaters,
cases of Versace sunglasses and $242,000 worth of cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they first learned of the ring in the summer of
1996 when BAX Global, a shipping concern with a warehouse at
Kennedy Airport, discovered two employees stealing laptop
computers. The company assisted in the investigation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials said that information from the workers at BAX led them
to Lewis Luxenberg, 54, who apparently brokered the sale of
millions of dollars in stolen goods from his home in Sheepshead
Bay, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that workers and owners would contact Luxenberg
whenever they stole items that were being shipped through their
warehouses and that Luxembourg in turn would find shop owners in
Manhattan, Brooklyn and Staten Island who were willing to sell the
items.
</P>
<P>
   The two people indicted in the ring who officials said were
connected to organized crime are Louis Tranese, whom the district
attorney's office Wednesday called an associate of the Lucchese
crime family known as Old Man Louie, and Frank Daviano, who the
officials said was connected to the Gambino crime family and is
known as Frankie Suits. Tranese was accused of supplying Luxenberg
with the stolen goods, while Daviano was charged with selling
stolen items on the black market.
</P>
</TEXT>
