<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 MEMORIES OF JUDICIARY COMMITTEES PAST  
 DESPERATELY SEEKING THE FISTS OF ALI  
 STORY WITH PICTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may sound like an unusual variation on the old
where-were-you-when question, but for those who worked in the
administration of Richard Nixon, it is not. What do you remember
about July 1974, the last time the House Judiciary Committee voted
on articles of impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   Diane Sawyer _ then a White House aide, now a correspondent for
ABC News _ said through a spokeswoman that she ``would love to
talk, but not in the middle of the storm.'' Charles Colson _ now a
syndicated radio personality _ recalled his testimony before the
Judiciary Committee as he called for President Clinton's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As for memories of the moment when the House Judiciary Committee
voted the first of three articles of impeachment against Nixon, ``I
was having a white wine spritzer,'' said Frank Gannon, a special
assistant to the president. Nixon and his closest aides were in
California, he said, and he was in Washington, having a drink with
his landlady, Kay Halle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of suspended animation and devastating
action because there was very little happening for those of us in
Washington,'' he said. ``Suspended animation, but with the feeling
that these enormous tides were surging under you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali's Bronze Fists Have Disappeared
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it floated away like a butterfly. Its disappearance is
stinging like a bee.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-pound bronze casting of Muhammad Ali's fists disappeared
from a foundry in Beacon, N.Y., that did the casting for the Korean
War memorial in Washington and for several sculptures by the artist
Roy Lichtenstein. Reproductions of the fists were to have been sold
through catalogs and galleries for $4,195.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the foundry, Peter Homestead, told The Associated
Press that he had not given up hope that the fists had merely been
misplaced, not stolen. Cast in June, they were not reported missing
until last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Walley, president of Virtual Presence Recreations, which
ordered the fists cast, also voiced a hope that they would turn up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not support the theory of this being some kind of inside
job,'' he said. He added that the foundry was supposed to make 100
copies and that 30 had been finished.
</P>
<P>
   Caricature Tale
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This story started in 1991, when the Broadway
producer Stewart Lane took his daughter, Eliana, to Sardi's for
dinner for her sixth birthday. The watercolors on the walls above
the banquettes captured her attention. Row after row of famous
faces. Actors. Mayors. Governors. And lots of prominent teeth, some
real, some removable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you up there?'' she asked Lane, who is an owner and a
manager of the Palace Theater.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to wing it. ``I looked around and I saw the one of
David Merrick, and because I have a mustache and dark hair, I said,
`That's me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she believed him, maybe she did not.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Lane has produced ``The Will Rogers Follies,'' which
won a Tony Award for best musical.
</P>
<P>
   He has set up a Web site with an address, www.mrbroadway.com,
that is anything but modest.
</P>
<P>
   And recently, Lane's picture was hung at Sardi's, and Eliana had
another birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Lane pointed proudly to himself, but Eliana was not buying. She
announced that she liked the Merrick portrait better. ``She said he
had darker hair, and more of it,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not all. The other day Lane went to Sardi's for
lunch. One of the restaurant's owners, Max Klimavicius, switched
the pictures before he arrived, putting the one of Lane under that
of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The one of Merrick went on the opposite
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Lane looked flummoxed until another customer clued him in to the
practical joke.
</P>
</TEXT>
