<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS MISSILE ATTACK AGAINST IRAQ 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton unleashed a massive military
airstrike against Iraq on Wednesday, hitting targets in Baghdad and
other parts of the country in an effort to cripple chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   Long-range Tomahawk cruise missiles fired from American ships in
the Persian Gulf and U.S. and British warplanes also struck several
military sites.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's surprise decision to launch the military action,
dubbed ``Desert Fox,'' sparked angry Republican charges that he was
putting U.S. military personnel in harm's way to stave off the
House vote on impeachment that had been scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In an address from the Oval Office, Clinton said he ordered ``a
strong, sustained series of airstrikes against Iraq,'' because of
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein's continued defiance of United Nations
orders to allow unrestricted inspections of suspected weapons
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein must not be allowed to threaten his neighbors
or the world with nuclear weapons, poison gas or biological
weapons,'' the president said, describing the military action as
vital to America's national interests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's action came less than a day after the United Nations
was presented with what he called a ``profoundly disturbing''
report from its chief weapons inspector, Richard Butler, outlining
Saddam's repeated violations of an agreement that was reached Nov.
15. The agreement narrowly postponed a U.S. military strike then.
Clinton warned Saddam at the time that if he violated the November
agreement, military action would come ``without delay, diplomacy or
warning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had delayed for even a matter of days ... we would have
given Saddam more time to disperse his forces and protect his
weapons,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he acted on the eve of the scheduled impeachment vote
``because, in the judgment of my military advisers, a swift
response would provide the most surprise and the least opportunity
for Saddam to prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Fires broke out in Baghdad in the wake of the initial attack,
which began about 5 p.m. EST. Anti-aircraft fire lit the night sky
there as missiles fell from planes launched from the aircraft
carrier USS Enterprise in the Persian Gulf and land bases in the
region. The missile attacks continued intermittently through the
night, with some missiles hitting near one of Saddam's palaces.
U.S. officials said ground forces were not involved in the action.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam issued a statement to the Iraqi people in the midst of
the attack, saying the country was under assault by ``wicked
people.'' He urged citizens to take to the streets to fight ``the
enemies of God, enemies of the nation, enemies of humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said there would be no immediate information
on targets hit, or more importantly, on casualties. Military
officials would say only that more than 200 U.S. and British
aircraft were involved in the initial attacks, including 15 B-52
bombers that were deployed to the region last month with 400 cruise
missiles and bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen. Hugh Shelton said that
another 36 combat aircraft are on their way to the region,
including B-117 Stealth fighters. He said there also are 24,100
U.S. military personnel aboard 22 ships and on land bases in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed that he wanted to act before the Muslim holy
month of Ramadan begins this weekend because he feared that using
force during that time would be ``profoundly offensive'' to the
Arab world and damage U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
   The president's decision caused an angry eruption among
Republican lawmakers on Capitol Hill, who were anticipating a vote
Thursday on impeaching Clinton for lying about his affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. But instead of voting to
remove him from office, incoming House Speaker Bob Livingston,
R-La., said the impeachment debate would be postponed and that
members instead would vote on a bipartisan resolution in support of
U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said he and a few other congressional leaders were
first told by administration officials about two days ago that an
attack might occur this week. Still, several GOP members denounced
Clinton's action, accusing him of putting U.S. military personnel
in danger in an attempt to derail the Republican-led impeachment
movement against him.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss, issued a statement
saying, ``I cannot support this military action in the Persian Gulf
at this time. Both the timing and the policy are subject to
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Republican Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas questioned the
timing, but said he would support U.S. forces. But he did not
endorse the policy, as his Texas GOP colleague Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a long time coming,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the window was small (because of the Ramadan holy
month), and I don't think that waiting a month would have been a
good thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also got support from former President Bush, who led the
allied war against Iraq seven years ago. Bush issued a statement
saying that ``as long as one American military airman, seaman, or
soldier is in harm's way, I will fully support this action.''
</P>
<P>
   In his address to the nation, Clinton alluded to the controversy
surrounding the timing of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein and the other enemies of peace may have thought
that the serious debate currently before the House of
Representatives would distract Americans, weaken our resolve to
face them down,'' Clinton said.``But once more the United States
has proven that although we are never eager to use force, when we
must act in America's vital interests we will do so.''
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing for reporters at the Pentagon, Defense Secretary
William Cohen, a former Republican senator, called on lawmakers not
to allow the impeachment to blunt their support for what he
insisted was a matter of national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am prepared to place 30 years of public service on the line
to say the only factor that was important in this decision was what
was in the American people's best interests,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   While not aimed at getting Saddam, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said the military strikes would likely increase pressure
within Iraq for Saddam's removal. In the meantime, she said the
United States would step up its efforts to work with Iraqi
opposition groups determined to overthrow Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave the final order to begin the attack only hours
after his return from a Middle East trip.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the White House late Tuesday night, he was
briefed more fully on Butler's report and called a meeting of his
national advisers for Wednesday morning. The final decision on
military action was made in that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to the nation, Clinton said the missile strikes
are designed to ``degrade Saddam's capacity to develop and deliver
weapons of mass destruction and to degrade his ability to threaten
his neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Saddam defies the world and we fail to respond, we will
face a far greater threat in the future. ... Mark my words,''
Clinton said, ``he will develop weapons of mass destruction, he
will deploy them and he will use them.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton spoke to the nation, the Security Council met at
the U.N. to discuss the president's decision and to hear from
Iraq's ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for the United Nations and the world,'' said
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened cannot be reversed,'' he said, calling on
U.N. officials to get behind humanitarian relief efforts in Iraq
and to begin ``healing diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
