<SLUG> BC-BEEF-INDICTMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INDICTS PRODUCER OF CONTAMINATED BEEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Ill., Neb., Ky. ,  Colo., Mo.)  
(nk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A federal grand jury has indicted a beef company and
two employees, charging them with providing false information in
connection with the contamination of hamburgers produced at a
Nebraska beef plant last year.
</P>
<P>
   The hamburgers, which are believed to have sickened 16 people in
Colorado and Kentucky in August 1997, prompted the recall of 25
million pounds of ground beef, the largest meat recall in U.S.
history.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the U.S. attorney in Omaha, Thomas Monaghan,
announced the indictments of the company, Hudson Foods, and two
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, which merged with Tyson Foods in January, operated the
Columbus, Neb., plant that produced the hamburgers. The indicted
employees are Brent Wolke, who managed the Hudson plant, and
Michael Gregory, who was director of customer relations and quality
control for Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen hamburger patties produced at the plant were linked to an
outbreak of E. coli O157:H7, bacteria that can cause serious kidney
problems and other symptoms and may be deadly, especially in
children, the elderly and those with vulnerable immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says Wolke, Gregory and the company falsely told
investigators from the U.S. Department of Agriculture that the
company had traced the infected beef to a single lot of hamburgers.
By pinpointing the outbreak to a single lot, the company limited
the scope of the national recall to only three days of beef
production, the indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   But, Monaghan's office said, the grand jury determined that the
meat produced on those three days had not been sent to Colorado,
where the majority of the illnesses occurred. The indictment
charges that the company and the two employees learned that the
beef had not been shipped to Colorado, but still told investigators
that the single lot of beef was linked to the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also says it was impossible to identify the
specific day or production run tied to the E. coli outbreak because
Hudson Foods had a practice of using leftover ground beef from one
production run in later production runs, sometimes freezing the
leftover meat for months before it was ultimately made into burger
patties. The grand jury found that Hudson did not accurately track
the use of leftover ground beef in subsequent production runs.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the two employees could face up to five years in
prison and fines of up to $250,000, while Hudson Foods could be
fined up to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Wolke, Peter Romatowski of Washington, said the
charges were fales. ``We look forward to the opportunity to prove
that in court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolke is still the manager of the plant, which was closed after
the outbreak but was bought by IBP and reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory's lawyer, J.R. Hobbs of Kansas City, Mo., could not be
reached Wednesday night. Gregory now works for Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson Foods said in a statement: ``The company has no basis to
believe that any mistakes that might have been made in the handling
of the recall amount to actionable offenses. Hudson believes it
cooperated fully with the government during the recall period and
withheld no information.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson's former chairman, James T. Hudson, issued a separate
statement defending his company's honesty and criticizing the
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overreaction of the USDA in Washington in this incident
destroyed my company's good name,'' Hudson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
