<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-D'AMATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO'S NEXT JOB: MEDIATING HOLOCAUST VICTIMS' SUIT AGAINST
BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sen. Alfonse D'Amato has decided to begin his life
after government on familiar terrain: He has accepted a job
mediating a federal lawsuit brought against German and Austrian
banks by Holocaust survivors, whose cause he has relentlessly
championed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term appointment by a federal judge in Manhattan,
which was disclosed Wednesday, caught the participants in the
lawsuit by surprise, and quickly generated debate over whether
D'Amato's vigorous advocacy on behalf of Holocaust victims might
complicate the negotiations that he would oversee.
</P>
<P>
   Because the job is not full time, D'Amato, who lost his bid for
a fourth term last month, is still considered likely to take a
position with a prominent law firm and to venture into the media
world, perhaps becoming the host of a radio talk show like his
friend Edward Koch, the former mayor.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the plaintiffs in the class-action lawsuit, Edward
Fagan, applauded the choice of D'Amato, saying that the banks
should be ``terrified'' of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``D'Amato is a street fighter with not only gut instincts, but
with a very good history and a lot of knowledge to back it up,''
Fagan said. ``He is not going to buy a lot of the regular mumbo
jumbo and all the other things that the banks are going to try and
throw at the court.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Fagan said he believed that D'Amato would be
fair.
</P>
<P>
   One of the German banks, Dresdner Bank, declined to comment on
the lawsuit, which alleges that the banks trafficked in gold that
the Nazis stole from European Jews during World War II. A
spokeswoman for another bank, Deutsche Bank, referred calls to the
bank's headquarters in Frankfurt, where there was no answer
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The German banks have asked the judge to dismiss the suit, which
was filed last June, on the grounds that Germany had already paid
extensive reparations for its wartime actions.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald McKelvey, a spokesman for two Austrian banks named in the
suit, Bank Austria and Creditanstalt, said D'Amato was ``eminently
qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no conflict as far as we are concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case, Shirley Wohl Kram of U.S. district court,
is no stranger to D'Amato, who is to be paid $350 an hour. He
recommended her for the post to President Reagan in 1982, who
formally selected her. The judge declined to comment on D'Amato's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The judge asked D'Amato, whose title is Special Master, to
supervise talks between the two sides in an attempt to get them to
settle before trial.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's spokesman, Harvey Valentine, said questions about his
impartiality in the matter or his ties to the judge were misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senator demonstrated his commitment to fairness in the
pursuit of justice during the Senate Banking hearings in the Swiss
bank inquiry,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment is an unusual turn in D'Amato's work on behalf
of Holocaust victims and survivors. Throughout his last term, he
repeatedly came to their aid, holding hearings in the Senate and
criticizing what he said was the unwillingness of some Swiss and
German institutions to make amends for their actions during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, D'Amato often promoted these efforts in an
attempt to reach out to Jewish voters, who have historically leaned
more toward Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank acknowledged earlier this year that it had dealt
in Nazi gold during the war, saying that it ``regrets most deeply
injustices that occurred.'' It declined then to say whether its
wartime officials knew that some of the gold might have been from
Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   Two experts on legal ethics said they saw nothing improper in
Judge Kram's decision to give work to a senator who helped her get
appointed. They noted that D'Amato recommended many people for
federal judgeships in his 18 years in office and that it would not
be practical for him to recuse himself from dealings with all of
them.
</P>
<P>
   One expert, Professor Stephen Gillers of New York University Law
School, said that if the judge had asked D'Amato to draw
conclusions about the case and make recommendations, then such a
role might present a conflict. But Gillers said that because the
job was limited to mediating, it was not troubling. If the banks do
not like a proposed settlement, they can reject it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other expert, Professor Steven Lubet of Northwestern School
of Law, noted that the justice system was based upon the idea that
judges and others handling disputes would set aside their personal
views. But he added that, ``Even assuming that Senator D'Amato
could be achingly fair, you could understand why the defendants
might prefer to have somebody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
