<HEADER>
A4143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLIONAIRE-BODY-400&AMP;     12-16 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-BODY-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS ASSERT CASE CAN BE PRESSED WITHOUT BODY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., Del., Calif.)   (Eds: Sidebar to MILLIONAIRE-DISAPPEAR) 
(jw) 
 By LAURA MANSNERUS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The examples are few, but the law was clear for the
prosecutors who secured the indictment of Sante and Kenneth Kimes:
A homicide case can proceed without a body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old common-law rule,'' said Steven Zeidman, a
professor at the New York University School of Law. ``The body
isn't necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying rationale,'' he said, ``is that you're not
entitled to an acquittal because you were especially good at
getting rid of the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Schreiber, a deputy district attorney in Brooklyn, had to
put that reasoning to the test when he prosecuted a homicide case
last year in which the body of the victim, an 8-year-old girl, was
never found. ``The bottom line is you don't need the corpus,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in that case, involving the killing of Justina Morales in
1995, Schreiber won a conviction for manslaughter, not murder, as
he had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, a jury in 1989 convicted a Connecticut man, Richard
Crafts, of murdering his wife, whose body was never recovered,
after hearing evidence that he had put the body parts through a
wood chipper. And in a highly publicized case now on trial in
Delaware, Thomas Capano, the defendant, was charged with murder
after a 17-month search for the body of a former girlfriend yielded
nothing but the cooler that witnesses said he used to dump it at
sea.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has long been reluctance to prosecute homicides on
the basis of a confession alone, or on circumstantial evidence
alone, Zeidman said, and for years some states required the body
for an indictment to be handed up, though these laws have all been
repealed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a 1957 prosecution in California that paved the way for
allowing a murder case to be brought without the body of a victim.
The defendant, Leonard Ewing Scott, was convicted of killing his
wife, Evelyn, though no physical trace of her was ever found. Her
body was believed to have been buried in the supports of the San
Diego freeway. Although he was convicted, the jury rejected the
death penalty in favor of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen cases around the nation have been successfully
prosecuted since then. But Zeidman said that in these instances,
``my guess is that you'll see some kind of admission or
confession.'' He added: ``They don't have that from the Kimeses. I
think the Kimes case is going to push this to the limit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his prosecution in Brooklyn, Schreiber pointed out, ``our
case was not entirely circumstantial.'' First, he said, the child's
stepfather had acknowledged her death and acknowledged striking
her, though he maintained that it was accidental. In addition, he
noted that prosecutors were able to obtain the testimony of the
girl's mother.
</P>
<P>
   And it is that kind of account, from witnesses to a homicide, if
not from the defendant, that the Manhattan prosecutors lack in
their account of how Irene Silverman disappeared from her East Side
town house this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not found any physical evidence that Mrs.
Silverman was harmed. Such evidence was critical in the Connecticut
case, which included traces of bone, a fingernail and hair samples
recovered from the victim, Helle Crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even with such direct evidence, Schreiber said,
without a body ``you can't corroborate statements because without a
coroner you can't confirm the account of death; in the absence of
medical testimony, it's more difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
