<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SULLIVAN     12-16 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SULLIVAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALLING GRIDIRON PATRIOTS AS A RAGGED, PROUD BAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the New England Patriots left Boston for Foxboro, Mass., 27
years ago, it was a treat for the team to have any home at all. The
Patriots, a charter team in the maverick American Football League,
were pigskin nomads from 1960 to 1970, when they roamed the Boston
area playing home games in other teams' homes: Harvard, Boston
College, Boston University and Fenway Park of the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1970, the president of Harvard wrote my dad a note, saying,
`Billy, you finally made it to Harvard,''' said Chuck Sullivan, one
of the six children of William H. Sullivan Jr., the Patriots'
original owner who died last February.
</P>
<P>
   So the team was happy to have a stadium of its own, even one it
had to pay $7.1 million to build.
</P>
<P>
   Now the team will be on the move again, 85 miles away to
Hartford. By 2001 at the earliest, the Patriots will move into a
$375 million downtown stadium with 150 luxury suites and 5,000 club
seats, thanks to a generous package approved Tuesday night by the
Connecticut legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Although he described the terms as awesome, Sullivan, an
investment banker and a former executive vice president of the
team, said: ``My dad wouldn't have let the taxpayers of
Massachusetts or Connecticut build a stadium for him. He felt the
taxpayers shouldn't foot the bill for a private business.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Sullivan was a raconteur, former sports publicity agent,
newspaperman, printing salesman and oil company executive from
Lowell, Mass. He acquired the eighth and final team in the new AFL
in 1959 with $8,300 of his own money and the rest of the $25,000
franchise fee from his brother, father-in-law and others.
</P>
<P>
   Those were arduous days for the AFL, which had to convince
players it was serious and endure the scorn of the National
Football League. There were wealthy owners, like oil man Lamar
Hunt, owner of the Dallas Texans (which became the Kansas City
Chiefs), and those who were just getting by, like Harry Wismer, a
former radio sportscaster who owned the New York Titans (now the
Jets). They were the days of five-figure salaries and grass fields,
a time when cities were not competing to lure teams with
taxpayer-built stadiums filled with luxury boxes and club seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game we were playing the Titans, in either 1960 or 1961,''
Chuck Sullivan recalled. ``Harry couldn't meet his payroll, and we
were not financially strong either. But my father wouldn't let
anybody who was involved in the game not be paid. So he paid both
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Sullivan's Patriots were an up-and-down team, losing more
than winning under nine coaches. But there were stars, like
quarterbacks Babe Parilli and Jim Plunkett and place-kicker Gino
Cappelletti. After a 5-9 start in 1960, the team fired its coach
early in the next season and posted a 9-4-1 record. The Patriots
made it to the 1963 AFL championship game, but were trounced,
51-10, by the San Diego Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan still owned the team when Coach Raymond Berry took the
team to Super Bowl XX in 1986, but the Patriots were trampled by
the Chicago Bears, 46-10. In the late 1980s, the team entered a
period of instability. In 1988, the NFL had to advance $4 million
for the team to meet its payroll. The Patriots put the stadium into
bankruptcy to prevent its being auctioned.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Sullivan sold the team for $85 million to Victor Kiam
and Fran Murray. Kiam bought out Murray and sold the team to James
Orthwein for $106 million in 1992. Orthwein sold it to Robert K.
Kraft for $158 million. Kraft had bought the stadium for $25
million six years before.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Billy Sullivan filed an antitrust suit against the
NFL in federal court in 1991, charging that the league conspired to
keep him from selling 49 percent of the team when he needed to
raise money to pay his debts. Five years later, he settled for
$11.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, under Coach Bill Parcells, the Patriots made it back to
the Super Bowl, but lost again, 35-21, to the Green Bay Packers.
Shortly after, Parcells bolted to the Jets, enraging Kraft, who was
awarded four draft picks by the NFL as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Sullivan thought about his father this week while reading
about the perks Hartford offered the team: a free stadium, no rent,
a $13 million revenue guarantee if luxury boxes and club seats
don't sell out, and $15 million for a training center.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Tuesday what he would make of his old team's going to
Hartford, he said: ``If you ask the season-ticket holders who were
with us in 1960, and who are still there, I'll bet 10 out of 10
don't want to go to Hartford. Dad's focus was not on the luxury box
holder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-16-98 2325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
