<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      12-16 1546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK ON BAGHDAD GIVES CLINTON REPRIEVE ON IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Startled and angry House Republicans gave President
Clinton a reprieve Wednesday night from certain impeachment as the
United States and Britain launched a military attack on Saddam
Hussein's Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders, confronted with the assault on the eve of an
impeachment debate that had been set for Thursday, abruptly
postponed the proceedings, deferring what Clinton's friends and
foes all but agreed would be his inevitable impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than debate Clinton's impeachment fate Thursday, the
House will vote on a resolution to support US forces involved in
the strike on Iraq. House Republicans said the impeachment
proceedings would be delayed until after the military action but
probably to no later than early next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reserve the right in the next few days to complete the
business that brought us here in the last few hours,'' said the
House speaker-designate, Representative Robert L. Livingston,
referring to the impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning confluence of events, Clinton ordered the military
strike as a final wave of moderate Republicans appeared to seal the
president's fate by announcing they no longer consider him fit to
govern in the face of four impeachment charges stemming from his
sexual affair with the former White House intern, Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The timing triggered anger among many Republican lawmakers,
despite the administration's insistence that Clinton's impeachment
crisis had no effect on the military foray.
</P>
<P>
   ``This president is shameless in what he will do to maintain his
presidency,'' said Representative Tillie Fowler of Florida, vice
chairwoman of the House Republican conference. ``He will use our
military, our foreign policy, whatever it takes to stay in
office.''
</P>
<P>
   While other GOP members called for Clinton's resignation, the
House majority leader, Richard K. Armey, said, ``After months of
lies, the president has given millions of people around the world
reason to doubt that he has sent Americans into battle for the
right reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders vehemently defended the strike as a vital
response to Saddam Hussein's latest provocation in refusing to
comply with United Nations resolutions that Iraq dismantle its
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein should make no mistake that despite domestic
political differences in the United States, the American people and
Congress stand firmly behind the defense of our nation's vital
interests,'' the Democratic leaders of the House and Senate,
Richard A. Gephardt and Thomas A. Daschle, said in a joint
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, denounced the attack,
saying, ``Both the timing and the policy are subject to question.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Republican lawmakers cautioned against criticizing the
military action while US troops are carrying out Clinton's order.
Livingston said the resolution Thursday will ``say that we are
united ... in the belief that Saddam Hussein must be contained and
that his use of weapons of mass destruction must be curtailed, and
in the belief that our troops should come home safely after the
completion of their effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in an address to the nation, made only a brief
reference to his military order intersecting with the imeachment
inquiry. In announcing the assault, Clinton said: ``Saddam Hussein
and the other enemies of peace may have thought that the serious
debate currently before the House of Representatives would distract
Americans or weaken our resolve to face them down.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day that verged on the bizarre even by Washington
standards, the business on Capitol Hill gradually shifted from
completing final preparations for the first House impeachment vote
in 130 years to monitoring televised images of anti-aircraft fire
lighting the sky over Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, lawmakers who had planned to gather in the House
chamber Thursday for an unprecedented lame-duck impeachment session
convened instead for a closed-door briefing on the military action
by Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is nuts,'' said Representative E. Clay Shaw
Jr., a Florida Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, few of the signs were promising for Clinton.
For every conservative Republican who blasted the timing of the
military attack, there was a moderate GOP lawmaker who was vowing
to vote for Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``While history remembers that George Washington could not tell
a lie, it now appears that history may well remember Bill Clinton
for his inability to tell the truth,'' said Representative Jerry
Lewis, a California Republican, in announcing he will vote for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen other GOP moderates joined Lewis in turning
against Clinton, leaving the president little mathematical chance,
if any, of surviving the vote to send his case to the Senate for a
trial, according to lawmakers on both sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe the vote is going to be the same whether it
is cast Thursday, Friday, Saturday or Sunday,'' said Representative
Edward J. Markey, a Malden Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston remained adamant in refusing to allow the House to
vote on an alternative resolution of the crisis short of
impeachment, such as a censure. Some of Clinton's allies said the
leadership's resistance to the censure plan has helped drive
moderate Republicans to vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Even Democrats who had believed Clinton would not be impeached
were close to conceding his defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrong,'' said Representative Barney Frank, a Newton
Democrat. ``The right wing is determined to do it, and I
underestimated their control over the Republican moderates. It
means the total collapse of moderate Republicanism.''
</P>
<P>
   The only good news for the White House, scant as it was, emerged
from an unusual source. Representative Jay Kim, a California
Republican who is wearing an electronic bracelet as part of his
sentence for pleading guilty to accepting illegal campaign
donations, said he is leaning against voting to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Iraq enflamed hostilities among House factions
that already were bitterly divided over the impeachment issue. The
frayed relations were evident last night as House members huddled
in closed-door party caucuses to develop strategy for the
impeachment proceedings and late-breaking military attack.
</P>
<P>
   Told that the impeachment debate might be delayed until
Christmas week, several Democrats accused conservative Republicans
of trying to oust Clinton at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we do it during Mass?'' said Representative David R.
Obey, a Wisconsin Democrat. ``Then we can have a national
crucifixion.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans said they were increasingly losing tolerance
and respect for Clinton, even as US pilots were in the air over
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never underestimate a desperate president,'' said
Representative Gerald B.H. Solomon, a New York Republican. ``This
time he means business. What option is left for getting impeachment
off the front page and maybe even postponed? It's about the lowest
thing I can think of any president doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Dana Rohrabacher, a California Republican, called
Clinton ``a shameless liar,'' and joined other GOP members in
calling on him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats said Clinton would come under fire no matter
which course he pursued, particularly on Iraq. ``If he did nothing,
the same Republicans who are complaining about him would be jumping
down his throat, saying, `See, he's not acting like the president
of the United States,''' said Representative James P. McGovern, a
Worcester Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans also opposed delaying the impeachment debate.
``To postpone it is like giving satisfaction to Saddam,'' said
Representative Bill McCollum, a Florida Republican. ``It's like
yielding to terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said of the anti-Clinton Republicans: ``Their hatred for
him is just bubbling over in every direction. It has gotten out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy struck a similar chord. ``This is a
classic absue of power, a subversion of the Constitution of the
United States, carried on by extremists in the Republican Party,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with Vice President Al Gore appealing to Congress
to ``turn away from the bitter partisanship'' and reject Clinton's
impeachment. But there was little sign last night of either side
bridging the gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements abounded, including a dispute over how long the
impeachment debate should last. Gephardt called for a 36-hour,
around-the-clock debate that would permit every member to speak for
five minutes, as lawmakers had been given to debate the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP leaders said they want to limit the debate to six to
eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Clinton's focus on the military action
prompted him to postpone a meeting Wednesday with Representative
Christopher Shays, a Republican from Connecticut who had initially
opposed impeachment but has wavered in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Zitner of the Globe staff and Globe correspondent Louise
D. Palmer contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
