<SLUG> BC-CHILES-FUNERAL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILES SALUTED FOR HIS TIES TO THE PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group c.1998 N.Y. Times News
Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ With Vice President Al Gore and scores of
other dignitaries in attendance, Gov. Lawton Chiles was remembered
at his funeral Wednesday as a leader who never forgot the common
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawton loved his fellow citizens in the state,'' said former
Sen. Sam Nunn, a Democrat from Georgia, who once worked beside
Chiles in the Senate. ``No other senator or governor had such a
remarkable bond with his constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout a 100-minute service at Faith Presbyterian Church
here in the state capital, the life and 40-year public career of
Chiles, who died of heart failure on Saturday at the age of 68, was
recalled by officials, friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Although about half the church's 850 seats were open to the
public, the pews were packed with dignitaries, including the vice
president, seven current or former senators, half a dozen members
of the House, the governors of five other states, four former
governors of Florida, the Florida Cabinet and most of the
160-member state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   A common thread in the eulogies was Chiles' ability to relate to
ordinary citizens. Many said it began with his 1,000-mile campaign
walk across the state in 1970, a trek that helped turn a
little-known Democratic state legislator into a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles served 18 years in the Senate before retiring in 1989,
then came out of retirement to run for governor in 1990. He was
within 23 days of completing his second and final four-year term
when he died. He was succeeded by Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay, who will
be governor until Jeb Bush, who defeated MacKay in the election
last month, is inaugurated on Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   (This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
