<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Timing inspires cynicism or belief in coincidence
 &HT;    By Bob Dart
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen rushed to the
Capitol on Wednesday night to explain the military mission against
Iraq after Republican leaders openly questioned whether President
Clinton had launched the attacks to delay his presidency's day of
reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   Many GOP members of both the House and Senate voiced suspicion
about Clinton's decision to attack on the eve of a scheduled debate
and possible vote on his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never underestimate a desperate president,'' said Rep. Gerald
Solomon (R-N.Y.), the retiring chairman of the House Rules
Committee. ``They're doing everything they can to avoid
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, a former Marine, said the American people should be
``outraged'' and charged that Clinton launched the attack for
``political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly rather suspicious timing,'' said Rep. Tillie
Fowler (R-Fla.), of the House GOP leadership team. ``I think the
president is shameless in what he would do to stay in office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot support this military action in the Persian Gulf at
this time, ``said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.).
``Both the timing and the policy are in question.''
</P>
<P>
   The skepticism was extraordinary in that such missions almost
always receive bipartisan backing, at least while the attack is
actually taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP critics took care to declare their support for American
military forces. Speaker-designate Bob Livingston (R-La.) said the
House would convene today to pass a resolution of bipartisan
backing of the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to the matter of timing, we just would leave that to the
best judgment of the American people,'' said Livingston. ``We
support the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that he doesn't ``blame anyone for being a
little cynical'' about the timing, Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) said,
``Regardless of any cynicism anybody has, we ought to get behind
the president at this particular time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, a former Republican senator from Maine, was questioned at
a Pentagon briefing before his trip to Capitol Hill about the
suspicions of his former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that every member of Congress and every member of this
country will have to make his or her own judgment based upon the
facts,'' he said. ``I am prepared to place 30 years of public
service on the line to say the only factor that was important in
this decision is what is in the American people's best interest.
There were no other factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic congressional leaders defended the mission and
predicted that most members from both parties would end up
supporting the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake about it: The American people and the American
Congress will stand behind our troops and stand behind our
president as we go into these next few days,'' said House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time for our country to be united, even though we
are divided on other matters,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle (D-S.D.). ``We need to stand united, Republicans and
Democrats alike, in ensuring that our troops are completely
successful in the dangerous mission that they are undertaking
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton was flying back from Israel on Tuesday, ``there
was obvious concern'' aboard Air Force One that military action
would be viewed as a cynical effort to dodge impeachment, said Rep.
Alcee Hastings (D-Fla.), himself a subject of impeachment as a
federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said the president agonized over the political
implications of his decision after they were raised by Rep. Rick
Lazio (R-N.Y.), a member of the congressional delegation who met
with Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he told Clinton: ``You have to do what you have to
do as if there were no impeachment. He said he felt that is what he
must do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, as a federal judge, was impeached by the House and
convicted by the Senate in 1989 of soliciting a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how the air strike against Iraq would be
perceived also was discussed Wednesday aboard Air Force Two as Vice
President Al Gore returned to Washington from Gov. Lawton Chiles'
funeral in Florida, said Rep. Mark Foley (R-Fla.).
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president made note that people would second-guess
this decision,'' Foley said. Gore would not comment on the timing
of the strike. Foley said, but ``merely made the comment that there
would be cynics among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats said the timing of the attack was awkward, but
was forced by the Iraqi leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not contrived, and it has nothing to do with
impeachment,'' said Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.). ``I think that the
reason I wanted to make this statement today is that I think
Americans need to really understand the gravity and legitimacy of
what is happening with Saddam Hussein,'' Iraq's president.
</P>
<P>
   And some Republicans said the bombing is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein has thwarted the will of the international
community for far too long,'' said Sen. Sam Brownback (R-Kan.).
``The U.S. must have the will to bring this to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   The military action was an unexpected event in a long day of
anticipation as House members returned from recess and thought they
would be debating, and possibly voting, on impeachment of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Bureau reporter Larry Lipman contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
