<HEADER>
A4172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GOPCAUCUS17-C     12-16 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOPCAUCUS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baghdad bombs a `surreal' event for those in impeachment
trenches
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As House Republicans crowded into a windowless room
in the basement of the U.S. Capitol, David Schippers sat quietly
underneath a potted fern just outside the door.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders had called the chief investigative counsel of
the House Judiciary Committee to brief members about the
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But just minutes before the meeting started, bombs started
falling in Iraq at the request of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, impeachment went to the back burner behind bombs and
Schippers was ordered outside with the rest of staff.
</P>
<P>
   So here he sat, legs dangling from his perch like a 10-year-old
boy's, waiting for the lawmakers inside to make a decision: would
they green-light the vote on impeachment scheduled for today or
would they postpone in light of the air raids on Iraq?
</P>
<P>
   The salty Chicagoan, known for his penchant for poetry and love
of the Democratic Party, appeared weary of the constant news coming
through he hallways of the Capitol. Weary of trying to read the
political tea leaves, longing for the black and white of the court
room.
</P>
<P>
   And now this. Another delay.
</P>
<P>
   This time over bombs. ``Surreal would be a good word to express
how I feel,'' Schippers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What comes to mind as I sit here? I wish I was in Chicago,''
said Schippers. ``I wish I was home.''
</P>
<P>
   Every year, his 10 children and 25 grandchildren gather at his
home just outside Chicago to celebrate the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   It is Schippers' tradition to gather the children by his feet
and regale them with stories.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the vote on impeachment has been indefinitely delayed,
it is questionable whether he will make it home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to tell them that there might not be a Christmas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Given all of the political machinations of the four-month
impeachment inquiry, Schippers has less than a stellar appetitie
for the wily ways of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He's enjoyed the people, but has little respect for the
political process _ the way loyalty is a rare commodity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out here long enough that nothing surprises me,'' he
said. But about the bombs flying on the eve of the impeachment
vote? ``I wouldn't believe this if it were fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members had the same disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Many mentioned the same surreal feeling that Schippers had as
they filed into the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   They had all been called back to vote on impeachment but they
suddenly found themselves coping with combat with Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Many questioned the timing of the attack, suspecting that
Clinton bombed Iraq in a desperate effort to save his political
life.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon (R-N.Y.) is one who believes that.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a briefing by Secretary of Defense William Cohen in
the House chambers, Solomon said he ``didn't feel any better about
the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   As he rushed to leave the Capitol, Solomon noted that the
information Clinton used to make his decision to bomb Iraq was
delivered to Congress and the White House back in September by a
former U.N. inspector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't we bomb 90 days ago, 60 days ago, 30 days ago?''
Asked a visibly upset Solomon. ``They're trying to divert
attention, no one can convince me otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   During the session with Cohen, House Majority Whip Tom Delay
(R-Texas) asked about the timing, expressing disbelief that it was
merely coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Following the session, Cohen said he had a productive exchange
with doubting members. Every question was answered.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the meeting, Speaker-designate Rep. Bob
Livingston walked out of the Capitol with a solemn face.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the session with Cohen had changed minds among
Republicans about the timing of the bombing, Livingston looked out
from the gaggle of aides surrounding him and said quietly, ``These
are tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
